INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'correlation between maternal and fetal plasma levels of glucose and free\rfatty acids .                                                           \r  correlation coefficients have been determined between the levels of   \rglucose and ffa in maternal and fetal plasma collected at delivery .    \rsignificant correlations were obtained between the maternal and fetal   \rglucose levels and the maternal and fetal ffa levels . from the size of \rthe correlation coefficients and the slopes of regression lines it      \rappears that the fetal plasma glucose level at delivery is very strongly\rdependent upon the maternal level whereas the fetal ffa level at        \rdelivery is only slightly dependent upon the maternal level .           \r'),
 (2,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes of the nucleic acid and phospholipid levels of the livers in the\rcourse of fetal and postnatal development .                             \r  we have followed the evolution of dna, rna and pl in the livers of rat\rfoeti removed between the fifteenth and the twenty-first day of         \rgestation and of young rats newly-born or at weaning . we can observe   \rthe following facts..                                                   \r  1. dna concentration is 1100 ug p on the 15th day, it decreases from  \rthe 19th day until it reaches a value of 280 ug 5 days after weaning .  \r  2. rna concentration is 1400 ug p on the 15th day and decreases to 820\rduring the same period .                                                \r  3. pl concentration is low on the 15th day and during foetal life (700\rug) and increases abruptly at birth .                                   \r  4. the ratios rna cyto/dna and pl cyto/dna increase regularly from the\r18th day of foetal life .                                               \r  5. nuclear rna and pl contents are very high throughout the           \rdevelopment .                                                           \r  6. these results enable us to characterize three stages in the        \rdevelopment of the rat liver.. - from the 15th day to the 18th day of   \rfoetal life.. stage of growth through hyperplasia without hypertrophy,  \r  - from the 19th day of foetal life to the 3rd day of post-natal life,.\rstage of cellular reorganisation,                                       \r  - after the 3rd day of post-natal life.. stage of growth through      \rhyperplasia and hypertrophy .                                           \r'),
 (3,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'surfactant in fetal lamb tracheal fluid .                               \r  lambs delivered by cesarean section with intact fetal circulation have\ra fluid filling the trachea . analysis revealed that this fluid         \rcontained material high in surface activity in lambs delivered near     \rterm, but less surface activity in premature lambs .                    \r  administration of 10 per cent oxygen to the ewe for 1 hour prior to   \rdelivery did not alter the surfactant properties of the fetal tracheal  \rfluid .                                                                 \r  two analyses of the fetal tracheal fluid revealed it to contain 146   \rand 198 mg. of lipid per 100 ml., 30 to 40 per cent of which was        \rphospholipid, part of the active component of surfactant .              \r  the investigations reported here offer a model for further research   \rinto possible intrauterine factors in the pathogenesis of hyaline       \rmembrane disease .                                                      \r'),
 (4,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'placental and cord blood lipids.. comparison in a set of double ovum    \rtwins, a stillborn and a live-born .                                    \r  1. determinations of phospholipid, total and free cholesterol,        \rtriglyceride and nefa have been made on placental tissue and cord blood \rin a set of double ovum twins, one stillborn and one live-born .        \r  2. similarities occurred in all fractions studied except the cord     \rblood triglyceride and nefa levels .                                    \r  3. the serum of the stillborn infant contained one-third as much      \rtriglyceride and 21/2 times as much nefa as did the live-born infant .  \r  4. the phospholipid content and the total lipid content of the        \rstillbirth placenta were the highest studied in this laboratory which   \rincludes determinations on 26 live births .                             \r  5. the suggestion is made that increased lipoprotein lipase activity  \rin the cord blood may accompany intrauterine fetal death .              \r'),
 (5,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'free fatty acid concentration in maternal plasma and fetal body fat     \rcontent .                                                               \r  subcutaneous injection of 200 u.s.p. units of heparin into female     \rsprague-dawley rats produced large and sustained elevations of plasma   \rfree fatty acids but no significant change in blood glucose . a group of\rpregnant rats received such injections of heparin 3 times daily         \rthroughout pregnancy . the fetuses from mothers of this group, at 191/2 \rand 211/2 days of gestation, had significantly more body fat than the   \rfetuses from uninjected mothers . the hypothesis is presented that the  \rmaternal free fatty acid concentration in part determines fetal fat     \raccumulation . it is proposed that the body composition changes noted in\rbabies of mothers with diabetes might thus be ascribed to abnormally    \rhigh maternal plasma free fatty acid concentrations .                   \r'),
 (6,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the concentration of non-esterified fatty acids in maternal and fetal   \rplasma in intact, alloxan-diabetic and x-ray-irradiated rats .          \r  determinations of the non-esterified fatty acids in the plasma of     \rpregnant rats showed that there do not exist any increases in the       \rconcentrations depending on pregnancy during the period from the 20th - \r22nd day of pregnancy . in the fetal plasma the concentrations of       \rnon-esterified fatty acids only amounted to 40 - 50 per cent of the     \rmaternal values .                                                       \r  with alloxan diabetes produced 2 days prior to the test the           \rconcentration in the maternal plasma increased three- to fivefold, while\rat the same time a significant rise was absent in fetal plasma with     \rslightly increased average values .                                     \r  whole-body x-ray exposures (dose.. 400r, dose output.. 40r/min) of    \rnon-pregnant female and of pregnant rats beginning on the 17th day of   \rpregnancy did not result in any changes of the concentration of         \rnon-esterified fatty acids immediately after irradiation .              \r'),
 (7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lipid metabolism in toxemia and normal pregnancy .                      \r  the amount and fatty acid composition of total lipid extract from     \rserum were examined in normal pregnant women in the first, second, and  \rthird trimesters, and early postpartum period, and in patients with mild\rand severe preeclampsia and with essential hypertension . placentas at  \rterm were also examined for total lipid and its fatty acid composition .\rin the normal women, total serum lipid increased during pregnancy . the \rrise was less pronounced in those with preeclampsia or hypertension .   \rserum palmitate was mildly but significantly elevated in preeclampsia . \rtotal lipid and arachidonic acid were elevated in the placentas of      \rpreeclamptic women . the findings are compared with those obtained from \ranimals developing eclampsia on an experimental basis .                 \r'),
 (8,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'essential fatty acids and acids with trans-configuration in the         \rsubcutaneous and visceral fat of the newborn .                          \r  we made an investigation of the subcutaneous and visceral fat in the  \rnewborn . we estimated the contents of linolic and linolenic acid and of\racids with trans-configuration spectrophotometrically .                 \r  we were able to show the penetration of these acids through the       \rplacental barrier . the essential fatty acid contents of fat in the     \rnewborn is low . in immature ones about 7-14 g, there is a rising trend.\r'),
 (9,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acetoacetate formation by livers from human fetuses aged 8-17 weeks .   \r  slices and homogenates from livers of human fetuses aged 8-17 weeks   \rhave a low rate of acetoacetate formation which can be raised by        \raddition of acetate or octanoate to the incubation medium . it was not  \rpossible to demonstrate acetoacetate formation by isolated liver        \rmitochondria from 17-week-old fetuses, probably because mitochondria are\rinjured during isolation .                                              \r'),
 (10,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes in blood glucose and non-esterified fatty acids in the foetal   \rand newborn lamb after injection of adrenaline .                        \r  changes in blood glucose and non-esterified fatty acids after         \rintravenous adrenaline were measured in foetal, newborn and adult sheep \rin the foetus and immediately after birth there was very little       \rincrease in either blood glucose or non-esterified fatty acids after    \radrenaline . the response of blood glucose to adrenaline had reached    \radult levels at twenty-four hours of age . the response of non-esterifi-\red fatty acids to adrenaline increased gradually over the first week .  \r'),
 (11,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electron-microscopic observatations on transference of fat through the  \rhuman placenta .                                                        \r  from the results of our previous and present studied on the           \rtransportation of fat through the human placenta by means of electron   \rmicroscopy, we obtained the following conclusions .                     \r  1) neutral fat can permeate through the human placenta without        \rdissociation .                                                          \r  2) almost all processes of fat permeation seem to be due to the       \rbiological activity . pinocytosis is most representative, but the       \rauthors newly found several facts such as dissolution-like change in the\rbasement membrane and transport via the stroma cell . the authors       \rbelieve that these results will bring a clue to explain the mechanism of\rbiological transportation of materials through the placenta .           \r'),
 (12,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the content of phosphatides, triglycerides and cholesterol in placentas,\rmaternal, fetal and new-born liver of the white rat .                   \r  thin-layer-chromatographic examinations in the maternal rat liver     \rshowed different rise of the triglycerides and a significant increase of\rthe esterified cholesterol, however, no striking changes in the content \rof free cholesterol and lipid phosphorus with the fractions examined    \r(lecithin, colamine cephalin, sphingomyelin and lysolecithin) .         \r  as compared to the liver of adult rats, the fetal liver contains a    \rlittle less than 50 per cent lipid phosphorus . the difference is       \rconditioned by the concentrations of lecithin, and colamine cephalin .  \ron the 19th day the content of triglycerides is lower than in the mother\rrat . referred to the dry weight, there results a decrease of all       \rphosphatide fractions, as well as of the free cholesterol and a slight  \rrise of the triglycerides from the 19th to the 22nd day .               \r  the rise of the phosphatide concentrations to the values of adult rats\roccurs immediately after birth under the influence of milk food, which, \rmoreover, leads to a considerable increase of the triglyceride values . \rphospholipid- and triglyceride concentrations of the placenta correspond\rto those of the fetal liver . solely the content of free cholesterol is \rhigher at the end of pregnancy . the content of triglyceride drops      \rtowards the 22nd day .                                                  \r'),
 (13,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'analysis of mammalian lens proteins by electrophoresis .                \r  lens proteins of different mammalian species were analyzed by         \rtwo-dimensional starch gel electrophoresis . the number of fractions    \rdetected by this means varied from 11-20 . a-crystallin was resolved    \rinto two to three components, b-crystallin into 5-11, and y-crystallin  \rinto three to five components . this technique provides a sensitive     \rmethod for the fractionation of lens proteins and for analyzing species \rdifferences .                                                           \r'),
 (14,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an autoradiographic study on cell migration in the eye lens epithelium  \rfrom normal and alloxan diabetic rats .                                 \r  lenses from normal and alloxan diabetic rats with and without cataract\rwere investigated by autoradiography 4 hours, 4 days and 8 days after an\rintraperitoneal injection of h3-thymidine (0.4 uc/g body weight) . the  \rrats were made diabetic 8 days prior to the injection of thymidine at an\rage of 4 weeks . the position of labelled nuclei of the lens epithelium \rwas noted and their grain numbers counted . the diabetic rats had a     \rlower frequency of labelled nuclei than the controls but after 4 hours  \rtheir grain counts were equal . frequency diagrams of labelled nuclei   \rare given for each of the three experimental periods . a predominant    \rpeak appears after 4 hours at a distance of 30-60 cells in front of the \rbeginning of the nuclear arc . a successive shift towards this area was \robserved for the longer experimental periods . the shift of the peaks   \rwas more restricted in the diabetic animals . this result may best be   \rinterpreted as an effect of an increased time of cell generation .      \r  as an appendix a histotechnique for the eye lens is given in          \rcollaboration with mrs. gertraude moewis .                              \r'),
 (15,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lens development.. the differentiation of embryonic chick lens          \repithelial cells in vitro and in vivo .                                 \r  the behavior of lens epithelial cells from six-day chick embryos was  \rstudied in three different experimental situations.. (a) explantation   \rinto several different fluid culture media, (b) explantation followed by\rreimplantation into lensectomized embryonic eyes, and (c) explantation  \rfollowed by reimplantation into the embryonic coelomic cavity .         \rspecimens were examined histologically, and the total volume of the lens\rmaterial of each specimen was determined from the planimetry of serial  \rsections . the results were interpreted as follows..                    \r  1. with a small amount of protein supplement in the culture medium,   \rembryonic lens epithelial cells are capable of a limited amount of      \rindependent cytodifferentiation . without protein supplement they fail  \rto undergo any fiber formation .                                        \r  2. when returned to the eye environment, cultured epithelial explants \rwill respond with a resumption of growth, with further cellular         \rdifferentiation, and with at least some of the morphogenetic changes    \rnecessary to form a lens . the embryonic coelom will not support these  \rresponses .                                                             \r  3. the initiation of the formation of lens fibers is not sufficient   \rfor their complete autonomous maturation .                              \r  4. the internal architecture of the developing lens is not the only   \rdeterminant of its overall shape .                                      \r'),
 (16,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of active chronic hepatitis and lupoid hepatitis with         \r6-mercaptopurine and azothioprine .                                     \r  6-mercaptopurine or azothioprine (\'imuran\') was used successfully in 3\rpatients with active chronic hepatitis and 2 with lupoid hepatitis, for \rperiods up to 1 year . these drugs allowed modification and even        \rabolition of discomforting corticosteroid regimes . their action in     \rchronic hepatitis may be analogous to their anti-immune action in       \rsuppressing homograft rejection .                                       \r'),
 (17,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of collagen diseases with cytostatics .                       \r  22 patients with collagen diseases and 3 patients with other          \rimmunological diseases were treated with the cytostatic antimetabolites \r(\'purinethol\') 6-mercaptopurine and (\'imuran\') azathioprine for an      \raverage period of four months (range one to eleven months) . improvement\rwas obtained in 17 patients,. and, in 20 out of 22 patients who had been\ron long-term glucocorticoid medication, the steroid therapy could be    \rpermanently discontinued . serious complications occurred, in the form  \rof two deaths from pancytopenia and sepsis . the treatment requires     \rcareful supervision of the patients, and should only be instituted, on  \rstrict indications, when the alternative is long-term glucocorticoid    \rmedication .                                                            \r'),
 (18,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bilateral popliteal cysts in a patient with rheumatoid arthritis .      \r  a case of bilateral popliteal cysts and multiple joint subluxations in\ra patient with rheumatoid arthritis on corticosteroid medication for    \rmany years is reported . the effect of long-term corticosteroid therapy \ron all periarticular connective tissue structure and the relationship of\rarticular disease and popliteal knee cysts to this therapy have been    \rdiscussed .                                                             \r'),
 (19,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'systemic lupus erythematosus and renal transplantation.. report of two  \rcases .                                                                 \r  two cases of systemic lupus erythematosus along with terminal uremia  \rsecondary to lupus nephritis are presented . both patients were treated \rwith renal hemodialysis and transplantation . certain mechanical,       \rinfectious, and immunologic problems were responsible for their death . \rthere was no evidence of resurgence of lupus erythematosus in either    \rpatient, and the transplanted kidneys did not show evidence of lupus    \rnephritis . renal transplantation should be considered as a last resort \rin treatment of patients with terminal lupus nephritis .                \r'),
 (20,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'arteritis and localised periosteal new bone formation .                 \r  1. three patients with localised periosteal new bone formation        \rassociated with periosteal arteritis and other evidence of systemic     \rlupus erythematosus are described .                                     \r  2. systemic steroid therapy was valuable in the management of this    \rcondition .                                                             \r'),
 (21,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fine structure of subtilis phage sp-50 .                                \r  some structural details and anomalous forms of subtilis phage sp-50   \rare described .                                                         \r'),
 (22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'genetic transcription during morphogenesis .                            \r  messenger rna\'s from bacillus subtilis undergoing sporulation,        \rgermination, or step-down transition have been characterized and        \rcompared . hybrid competition experiments indicate that these messengers\rare derived from distinct genetic loci . the results are consistent with\rthe hypothesis that differential transcription of the genome occurs     \rduring morphogenesis . the data also complement previously observed     \rchanges in morphology and enzymatic activity in sporulating bacteria .  \r'),
 (23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal amyloidosis a clinicopathological study .                         \r  the clinical and histopathological data from 40 cases of renal        \ramyloidosis diagnosed by percutaneous renal biopsy are presented .      \r  twenty-two cases were labelled as \'secondary\' amyloidosis, as definite\raetiological factors responsible for renal amyloidosis could be         \rdiscovered . the predisposing disease states leading to amyloid deposits\rin the kidney in the order of frequency were fibrocaseous pulmonary     \rtuberculosis, bronchiectasis, lung abscess, and ileocaecal tuberculosis \rfive cases were labelled as suspected \'primary\' amyloidosis as a      \rdefinite evidence of the predisposing disease could not be obtained     \ralthough the skiagram of chest revealed minimal healed foci . no cause  \rcould be determined in thirteen cases, which were, therefore, labelled  \ras \'primary\' amyloidosis .                                              \r  albuminuria was a constant feature in all the cases and 32 cases      \rpresented as nephrotic syndrome . the rest of the cases presented with  \rhypertension or renal failure in addition to albuminuria .              \r  the ancillary procedure, viz., congo-red test, gingival and liver     \rbiopsies proved to be of limited value in the diagnosis of renal        \ramyloidosis .                                                           \r  the importance of percutaneous renal biopsy as a diagnostic tool has  \rbeen emphasised .                                                       \r'),
 (24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'idiopathic autoimmune hemolytic anemia and idiopathic thrombocytopenic  \rpurpura associated with diffuse hypergammaglobulinemia, amyloidosis,    \rhypoalbuminemia and plasmacytosis .                                     \r  a case is reported of a sixty-nine year old woman with severe,        \ridiopathic, autoimmune hemolytic anemia which was initially controlled  \rby splenectomy . a relapse associated with the development of severe,   \rautoimmune, thrombocytopenic purpura failed to respond to large doses of\rprednisone, but was controlled to a variable degree with imuran .       \r  associated features included diffuse hypergammaglobulinemia, excessive\rgamma-u proteins in the urine, idiopathic hypoalbuminemia with a greatly\rreduced total exchangeable albumin pool, amyloidosis in the spleen and  \rother organs, and diffuse plasmacytosis of the bone marrow, lymph nodes,\rand thoracic and peritoneal fat . these features and their              \rinterrelationships are discussed . there was no deficiency in the       \rsynthesis of specific neutralizing antibodies against viruses,          \rindicating that a qualitative immune deficiency did not exist .         \r  the frequency of occurrence of thrombocytopenic purpura in such a case\ris discussed, as is the prognosis . the mechanism of action of          \rantimetabolites in inducing a remission in autoimmune hemolytic anemia, \ras well as the etiology of the disease, is reviewed .                   \r'),
 (25,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'corticosteroid therapy of amyloid nephrotic syndrome .                  \r  the results of treatment with prolonged adrenal corticosteroids in 26 \radults with amyloid nephrotic syndrome are presented . eight subjects   \rwere observed in this series, and 18 additional cases were summarized   \rfrom the literature . twenty-two of the patients were male and four were\rfemale . the diagnosis was established by renal biopsy in 19 instances  \rand by autopsy in the others, with 18 patients considered to have       \rprimary amyloidosis and 8, secondary amyloidosis .                      \r  the majority of the subjects died in renal failure with an average    \rsurvival after onset of the disease of 17.6 months . the renal disease  \rwas indistinguishable from that seen in other forms of the nephrotic    \rsyndrome, with the possible exceptions of (a) a high incidence of       \rpurpuric skin lesions, (b) a low or negligible incidence of hypertension\r(at times actual hypotension was prominent), and (c) a rapid and        \rinexorable progression of azotemia despite persistence of the clinical  \rand biochemical characteristics of the nephrotic syndrome . amyloidosis \rwas found by percutaneous renal biopsy in 12 per cent of 83 adults with \rthe nephotic syndrome .                                                 \r  corticosteroids did not appear to affect the progress of the disease  \rand were neither beneficial nor detrimental . in view of the high       \rincidence of deleterious side effects of prolonged corticosteroid       \rtherapy and the availability of potent diuretic agents which may be     \rhelpful in relieving edema in this disorder, it is felt that            \rcorticosteroids are contraindicated in the treatment of amyloid         \rnephrotic syndrome .                                                    \r'),
 (26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal amyloidosis.. a biopsy study .                                    \r  the relationship of the amount of amyloid deposition in the kidney to \rthe clinical picture is reviewed in 14 cases of renal amyloidosis       \rdiagnosed by renal biopsy . the large percentage of patients who had the\rnephrotic syndrome (11 patients) probably reflects the criteria for     \rrenal biopsy at this institution . the etiology of the amyloid          \rdeposition did not seem to be clearly correlated with either the amount \rof amyloid deposition in the kidney or the severity of the clinical     \rrenal disease . all patients had deposits in the glomerulus, and the    \rheavier the deposition the severer the renal disease . of 7 patients who\rhad biopsy of the bone marrow, all had abnormal types or numbers of     \rplasma cells . the age range in primary amyloidosis appeared to be about\rthe same as that in amyloidosis secondary to myeloma . amyloidosis      \rshould be suspected in patients with proteinuria, the nephrotic         \rsyndrome, or renal failure .                                            \r'),
 (27,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'amyloid goitre a case report .                                          \r  a case of amyloid goitre in an indian female, aged 27 years, occurring\ras a sequelae to pulmonary tuberculosis, is reported .                  \r'),
 (28,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'amyloid.. starch gel electrophoretic analysis of some proteins extracted\rfrom amyloid .                                                          \r  proteins extracted by strong urea from washed tissue of patients with \ramyloidosis secondary to several diseases or associated with familial   \rmediterranean fever have common major electrophoretic components . in   \rhearts of primary amyloidosis one component in common with the secondary\ramyloid may be present . however, primary amyloid is much more difficult\rto dissolve and does not regularly give the components observed when the\rsecondary amyloid is extracted . the big question remains as to what    \rconstituent or constituents comprise the fibrils now known to be a part \rof amyloid .                                                            \r'),
 (29,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'selectivity of protein excretion in patients with the nephrotic syndrome.\r  with a gel diffusion precipitin technique and commercially prepared   \rantisera, urine/plasma ratios of specific proteins were determined .    \rindividual protein clearances, expressed as a percentage of transferrin \rclearance, were plotted as ordinates against respective molecular       \rweights on a log-log graph . a straight line was evident graphically,   \rits constants were estimated by the method of least squares, and the    \rslope, expressed as , was determined . the slope of the line may be said\rto express the degree of glomerular selectivity to protein excretion .  \rsixty-five determinations were performed in 48 patients . 45 satisfying \rthe usual criteria of the nephrotic syndrome .                          \r  1) those patients with primary renal disease and the nephrotic        \rsyndrome who displayed high selectivity types of proteinuria ( greater  \rthan the average for the group + 1 sd) usually respond initially to     \rsteroid therapy, regardless of the acute or subacute glomerular changes \robserved on renal biopsy .                                              \r  2) those patients with chronic renal disease and the nephrotic        \rsyndrome display an average and frequently a low selectivity type of    \rproteinuria .                                                           \r  3) there appears to be no characteristic type of selectivity for a    \rgiven pathologic group of patients with the nephrotic syndrome .        \r  4) the degree of selective protein excretion is not related to the    \rtotal daily amount of protein being excreted at any one time and remains\rfairly constant despite fluctuation in the amount of protein being      \rexcreted .                                                              \r  5) there is a slight correlation of borderline significance between   \rthe degree of selective protein excretion and the duration of the       \rdisease, and the initial para-aminohippuric acid clearance .            \r  6) a statistically significant correlation exists between the initial \rblood urea nitrogen or inulin clearance and the selectivity type of     \rprotein excretion . those patients who were not azotemic and had        \rinitially near-normal inulin clearances had an average selectivity type \ror better .                                                             \r  7) it is suggested that if the adult patient is initially azotemic and\rhas a grossly abnormal inulin clearance, response to therapy is         \runlikely, whereas if the blood urea nitrogen is normal and the inulin   \rclearance is near normal, response to therapy cannot be predicted with  \rany degree of accuracy . further studies of adult patients with the     \rnephrotic syndrome are required to substantiate this premise .          \r'),
 (30,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some aspects of haemostasis after open-heart surgery .                  \r  synopsis in two groups of patients undergoing extracorporeal          \rcirculation with hypothermia, changes were found in the coagulation     \rmechanism which were probably due to the dosage of polybrene            \radministered .                                                          \r  the role of heparin and polybrene and the concept of activation of the\rcoagulation mechanism in the production of bleeding after perfusion are \rdiscussed .                                                             \r'),
 (31,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a case of interventricular septal defect with dextrocardia and situs    \rinversus treated by surgery .                                           \r  a case of interventricular septal defect associated with situs        \rinversus and dextrocardia in twenty year old male patient was presented \ralong with discussion on three types of dextrocardial complexes and with\remphasis on the rarity of occurrence of the intracardiac anomalies in   \rtrue /mirror-image/ dextrocardia with total situs inversus . a comment  \rwas also made on kartagener\'s syndrome which was excluded by appropriate\rradiographic procedures in this case .                                  \r  the closure of the interventricular septal defect with extracorporeal \rcirculation was successfully performed under moderate hypothermia .     \r'),
 (32,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'excretion patterns of urinary metabolites of estradiol-4-c14 in         \rpostmenopausal women with benign and malignant disease of the breast .  \r  a study of the excretion patterns of the urinary metabolites of       \restradiol-4-c1j administered to a group of 43 postmenopausal women, 38  \rwith advanced mammary carcinoma prior to endocrine therapy and 5 with   \rbenign mammary dysplasia, is reported . a chromatographic method was    \remployed for the determination of estradiol, estrone, and estriol and   \rother estrogen metabolites . the urinary excretion pattern is defined by\r(a) the extent of excretion of isotope in each of 3 successive 24-hr.   \rcollection periods, (b) the percentage of the urinary radiometabolites  \renzymatically hydrolyzed, (c) the relative concentration of the several \rmetabolites in the hydrolyzed fraction . wide subject-to-subject        \rvariations were found . the metabolites other than estradiol, estrone,  \rand estriol comprised a large portion of the total estrogens excreted . \ra significantly lower amount of estradiol was noted in the group of     \rwomen with mammary carcinoma as compared to the amount found in the     \rgroup of women with benign mammary dysplasia, suggesting that the former\rgroup metabolizes more rapidly the administered estradiol . although the\rexcretion patterns of patients who failed to respond to estrogen        \rtreatment (nonresponders) differed the greatest from the patterns       \rassociated with benign disease, distinctive patterns of the urinary     \rexcretion of isotopic estrogens which allowed a statistically           \rsignificant or clinically useful separation between responders and      \rnonresponders to subsequent estrogen therapy were not discovered .      \r'),
 (33,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the localizing significance of limited simultaneous visual form         \rperception .                                                            \r  a patient presenting with an isolated /spelling dyslexia/ and         \rimpairment in picture interpretation (simultanagnosia) was shown by     \rtachistoscopic studies to have a pathological limitation of simultaneous\rform perception . at autopsy a localized lesion was found within the    \rinferior part of the left occipital lobe .                              \r  these findings are discussed in relation to the problem of the        \rdisorder of function underlying /agnosic alexia/ .                      \r'),
 (34,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'visual anosognosia in cortical blindness anton\'s symptom .              \r  denial of blindness in a case of bilateral hemianopia is presented to \racquaint ophthalmologists with this symptom which is well-known to      \rneurologists but is rarely seen by opthalmologists .                    \r'),
 (35,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the development of social attachments in infancy .                      \r  this report is devoted to the formation and development of social     \rattachments in infancy . it is suggested that the core of the attachment\rfunction is represented by the tendency of the young to seek the        \rproximity of certain other members of the species and that the most     \rsuitable operational definition may be found in the behavior of the     \rindividual when deprived of such proximity .                            \r  the study takes the form of a longitudinal follow-up, in which 60     \rinfants were investigated at four-weekly intervals from the early weeks \ron up to the end of the first year and again at 18 months of age . with \rthe use of an attachment scale, based on seven everyday separation      \rsituations, the following three main parameters were explored.. the age \rat onset of specific attachments, the intensity of such attachments, and\rthe number of objects to whom attachments are formed . a measure of     \rfear-of-strangers was also included .                                   \r  results indicate that the age at onset of specific attachments is     \rgenerally to be found in the third quarter of the first year, but that  \rthis is preceded by a phase of indiscriminate attachment behavior,. that\rthe intensity of specific attachment increases most in the first month  \rfollowing onset and that thereafter fluctuations occur in individual    \rcases which make long-term prediction difficult,. and that multiplicity \rof objects can be found in some instances at the very beginning of the  \rspecific attachment phase, becoming the rule in most of the remaining   \rcases very soon thereafter . correlations between the attachment        \rvariables, as well as with the fear-of-strangers measure, are presented,\rand an examination is also made of the conditions eliciting protest at  \rproximity loss, of the manner in which protest is expressed, and of the \rconditions necessary to terminate protest .                             \r  individual differences with regard to the three main parameters were  \rexplored in a subgroup of 36 infants . a number of variables were       \rexamined in relation to these individual differences, and suggestions   \rmade regarding the conditions which affect the manifestation of the     \rattachment function .                                                   \r  the data are discussed in relation to four themes which emerged from  \rthe findings.. the nature of the attachment function, its developmental \rorigins, its developmental trends, and the influence of the social      \rsetting .                                                               \r'),
 (36,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'separation anxiety as a cause of early emotional problems in children . \r  in summary, three cases of disturbed behavior in children have been   \rdiscussed, with particular emphasis on disturbances in feeding,         \rsleeping, and motility . some of the hypotheses have been presented of  \rwhy such behavior should develop,. the significance of attachment       \rbehavior and separation anxiety in infants has been particularly        \rstressed . difficulties in mothering care are threatening to the child\'s\rsense of security and lead to greater experience of separation anxiety, \rwhich may then be reflected in various disturbances or alterations in   \rhis behavior . this experience of separation anxiety is the result of   \rearly life experience, may reach pathologic proportions, and may account\rfor many later problems in children and adults .                        \r'),
 (37,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the production of malignant tumours by nickel in the rat .              \r  powdered metallic nickel when injected intramuscularly into rats      \rproduced tumours of striated muscle origin, most of which were very well\rdifferentiated .                                                        \r'),
 (38,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of nickel carcinogenesis fractionations of nickel in            \rultracentrifugal supernatants of lung and liver by means of dextran gel \rchromatography .                                                        \r  chromatographic fractionations have been performed on the             \rultracentrifugal supernatants of homogenates of rat lung and liver by   \rthe use of columns of dextran gel (sephadex g-100) . a major proportion \rof nickel in these tissue supernatants has been demonstrated to be      \rfirmly bound to macromolecular constituents . following acute and       \rchronic inhalation of carcinogenic levels of nickel carbonyl, the       \rpredominant increases in the concentrations of nickel have been observed\rin the macromolecular fractions . these findings are consistent with the\rprevious demonstration of nickel in purified preparations of ribonucleic\racids (rna) from several rat tissues, and with the observation of       \rincreased concentrations of nickel in high-molecular weight rna from    \rlung and liver following the inhalation of nickel carbonyl .            \r'),
 (39,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a study of the inhibitory effect of ethylenediaminetetra-acetic acid on \rthe thrombin-fibrinogen reaction .                                      \r  1. ethylenediaminetetra-acetic acid reversibly inhibits the           \rthrombin-fibrinogen reaction by means of a time-dependent diminution in \rfibrinogen reactivity .                                                 \r  2. this alteration of fibrinogen is due to some property of the edta  \rmolecule in an unchelated form, and is not due to the removal of trace  \rmetal ions .                                                            \r  3. possible explanations for this phenomenon are discussed .          \r'),
 (40,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'intradermal test using cobalt chloride .                                \r  selected groups of patients with cobalt allergy and nickel allergy as \rwell as normal controls were tested intradermally with cobalt chloride  \rin the dilutions 10 to 10 . reactions of the wheal and flare type appear\rduring the first hours and make the 24-hour reading misleading . the    \rpapular response to cobalt chloride 10, when read 48 to 96 hours after  \rthe injection, appears to be a reliable test for cobalt allergy .       \rpatients with combined nickel-cobalt allergy were excluded from the     \rstudy, and the question of group reactions is not discussed . nickel    \rallergics give a somewhat stronger reaction than controls to the        \rslightly impure cobalt chloride . it would be preferable if the degree  \rof purity of the cobalt chloride were ten times greater .               \r'),
 (41,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'measurements of nickel in biological materials by atomic absorption     \rspectrometry .                                                          \r  an atomic absorption procedure has been developed which facilitates   \rquantitative measurements of nickel in biological materials, including  \rurine, ribonucleic acids (rna), and serum proteins .                    \r  the sensitivity of detection of nickel by the atomic absorption       \rspectrometer (0.10 p.p.m.) was insufficient to permit direct            \rmeasurements of nickel in normal urine . therefore, it was necessary to \remploy a dimethylglyoxime extraction procedure to concentrate the       \rnickel, prior to atomic absorption spectrometry .                       \r  the coefficients of variation of measurements of nickel in urine and  \rhuman b- globulins were 6.3 and 5.9 per cent, respectively . the        \rrecovery of nickel added to urine averaged 96 per cent, with a range    \rfrom 94 to 97, and the recovery of nickel added to human b-globulin     \raveraged 101 per cent, with a range from 96 to 104 .                    \r  the mean concentration of nickel in 24-hr. collections of urine from  \r17 normal subjects was 1.8 ug. per 100 ml. (s.d. = 0.8), with a range   \rfrom 0.4 to 3.1 . the mean urinary excretion of nickel was 19.8 ug. per \r24 hr. (s.d. = 10.0), with a range from 7.2 to 37.6 .                   \r  the mean concentration of nickel in 5 preparations of ribonucleic     \racids from ultracentrifugal supernatants of homogenates of rat lung was \r48 ug. of ni per gm. of rna, with a range from 34 to 64 . the mean      \rconcentration of nickel in 5 preparations of rna from ultracentrifugal  \rsupernatants of homogenates of rat liver was 29 ug. of ni per gm. of    \rrna, with a range from 21 to 39 .                                       \r  measurements of nickel were performed upon fractions of human serum   \rproteins, prepared by continuous-flow electrophoresis, and by           \rcold-ethanol precipitation . the highest concentrations of nickel were  \rfound in preparations of serum b-globulins .                            \r'),
 (42,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'properties of activity of 5\'-nucleotidase in human serum, and           \rapplications in diagnosis .                                             \r  the influence of mg , ni , and l-histidine on purified preparations of\rbone and intestinal alkaline phosphatases and 5\'-nucleotidase, and on   \rvarious mixtures of these enzymes has been studied . the extent to which\rthese findings can be utilized in the quantitative assay of             \r5\'-nucleotidase in serum has been evaluated . results are presented on  \rthe possible utilization of l-histodine in the simultaneous evaluation  \rof serum alkaline phosphatase and 5\'-nucleotidase activity .            \r'),
 (43,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some 2-iminoselenazolidin-4-ones and related compounds .                \r  a series of 2-iminoselenazolidin-4-ones, selenazolidine-2,4-diones and\rsome 2-alkylidenehydrazones have been synthesised . wide-range screening\rfor biological activity failed to reveal any compounds of promise .     \r'),
 (44,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the influence of methemoglobinemia on the lethality of some toxic       \ranions, 1. azide .                                                      \r  the time course and extent of the methemoglobinemia induced by        \rintraperitoneal sodium nitrite and p-aminopropiophenone (papp) have been\rcharacterized in female mice . the peak methemoglobin formation (34 ) is\rachieved in about 40 minutes . comparable levels from papp (15 mg/kg)   \rare achieved more quickly (between 5 and 10 minutes) but decline more   \rrapidly to normal . both nitrite- and papp-induced methemoglobinemia    \rafford a significant degree of protection against poisoning by sodium   \razide when administered in an appropriate time sequence . it was not    \rpossible under the same circumstances to protect mice against death from\rfluoride, cyanate, thiocyanate, selenate, or borate, although some      \rprolongation of survival time was seen after fluoride . the formation of\rthe azide-methemoglobin complex has been demonstrated within intact     \rmouse red blood cells, and small amounts of the complex were identified \rin vivo in an antidotal situation . we think it important that the      \rprotective action of methemoglobinemia has been demonstrated to date    \ronly against established inhibitors of cytochrome oxidase .             \r'),
 (45,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'selenium as a trace element .                                           \r  an account is given of the discovery of selenium by berzelius and gahn\rthe toxic behaviour of large selenium quantities in soils upon        \rvegetation, animals, and man is surveyed . a review is also given of the\rrole of trace amounts of selenium in the prevention of myopathies in    \ranimals . finally, some recent theories on the importance of retinal    \rselenium to vision are mentioned .                                      \r'),
 (46,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'toxicity of inorganic selenium salts to chick embryos .                 \r  the effects of selenite and selenate treatment by air cell injection  \ron mortality and growth of 14-day chick embryos during a 64-68 hour     \rperiod were studied . the ld for selenite-se was about 0.5 ppm, based on\rweight of the egg contents, and that for selenate-se about 1.8-2.0 ppm .\rgrowth depression was evident from these treatments, but other gross    \reffects were not prominent . the treatment of embryos with selenite and \rsulfate together caused a greater mortality than treatment with selenite\ralone .                                                                 \r'),
 (47,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lesions of the islets of langerhans during injections of sodium selenite\radministered intravenously .                                            \r  sodium selenite was administered intravenously in rabbits and in dogs \r  repeated injections can lead to the development of a diabetic syndrome\rin the rabbit .                                                         \r  the histological examination of the pancreas in the poisoned animals  \r(dogs and rabbits) has shown the existence of lesions of the islets of  \rlangerhans, mostly of the b cells which lose their granules partly or   \rcompletely .                                                            \r  these changes seem analogous to the ones produced by alloxan,. these  \rtwo poisons act at first by inactivating the sh groups, which leads to a\rdeficiency to which the b cells are very sensitive .                    \r'),
 (48,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'toxicity of sulfur-35, selenium, and tellurium to avian embryos .       \r  continuous internal irradiation of chick embryos with sulfur-35       \radministered on the 4th or 8th day of incubation produced abnormalities \rsimilar to those observed in selenium toxicosis of avian embryos . the  \rhighest level of sulfur-35 (1600 uc) injected into eggs containing 4-day\rembryos produced morphological abnormalities more severe than those     \rproduced by the same level of radiosulfur administered to 8-day embryos,\ror by any level of stable selenium tolerated . selenium at levels       \rgreater than 30 ug killed all the embryos within 24 hours after         \rinjection . nearly 20 times more tellurium than selenium was required to\rkill all the embryos within 24 hours.. no abnormalities were observed in\rthe tellurium-injected embryos .                                        \r'),
 (49,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of selenium on the upper respiratory passages .              \r  results are reported of examination of workers exposed to selenium,   \rwith special reference to chronic changes in the respiratory passages . \rthe findings are the same as reported in the literature . we emphasize  \rthe occurrence of teleangiectasias on the uvula and on the posterior    \rpalatinal arcs and on the epiglotis . we describe the occurrence of the \rfirst poisoning with selenium xyde in this country . the poisoning      \rhealed within a few days under symptomatic treatment . the patient had  \rhowever to be transferred into another shop owing to frequent symptoms  \rdue to toxic effect of selenium . we report also on secondary findings  \rin examination of chronic changes and we emphasize particularly the     \rfinding of profesional selenium external otitis .                       \r'),
 (50,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the influence of small selenite doses upon the toxic fatty degeneration \rof the liver .                                                          \r  sodium selenite (10 ug/kg) manifests a lipotropic effect after        \rtoxication of the rat by tetrachlorocarbon . this effect is absent when \rthe selenite dose is increased to 50 ug/kg . the level of the total     \rlipides of the liver after ethionine toxication is not significantly    \rinfluenced by 10 ug selenite/kg . it is increased by 50 ug selenite/kg. \r'),
 (51,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'selenium-caused tumours .                                               \r  in 10 out of 23 heterozygous rats administered 10 mg na seo per 1 kg  \rfood (containing 12 protein) and surviving for 18 months, cancer of the \rliver (with metastases in the lungs) along with sarcoma and adenoma was \rrecorded . in another series of the yet incompleted experiment the      \ranimals were fed higher quantities of protein and selenium . toward     \r14-19 months in three of them sarcoma was noted.. in two sarcoma of the \rlymphatic nodes, and in one- of the mediastinum .                       \r  it is suggested that the changes caused by selenium compounds are to  \rsome extent due to their antagonistic relationship with methionine .    \r'),
 (52,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'blood and bone marrow damage caused by drugs .                          \r  drug side effects on blood and bone marrow are briefly reviewed . they\rembrace a wide variety of symptoms and pathogenetic mechanisms, and in  \rrecent years study of these effects has made important contributions to \rour knowledge of the immunology, biochemistry and metabolism of the     \rblood cells .                                                           \r'),
 (53,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypothermia.. physiologic effects and clinical application .            \r  a survey of the background, physiologic effects, indications,         \rtechnique and complications of hypothermia is presented . the           \rapplication of this technique is straightforward and safe when used at  \rthe proper levels with the proper indications .                         \r'),
 (54,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ehrlich ascites tumor cells agglutination.. the interference exerted by \repsilonaminocaproic acid (eac) and its acetyl derivative (eaca) .       \r  the activity of epsilon-aminocaproic acid (eac) and of its acetyl     \rderivative (eaca) was studied on antigen-antibody reactions, membrane   \rantigens and immune globulins .                                         \r  in vitro eac and eaca do not affect immune globulins, but they do     \ralter the membrane antigens of ehrlich ascites tumor cells and inhibit  \rthe agglutination reaction induced by a specific antiserum . inhibition \ris only partially due to the antigenic alteration observed, and it      \rrepresents more prominently a direct interference at the level of the   \rantigen-antibody reaction .                                             \r  the membrane antigen alternations induced by the drugs and by nitrogen\rmustard were compared, taking into account their toxicity.. eac and eaca\rwere found to be much more active and more specific than nitrogen       \rmustard .                                                               \r'),
 (55,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'study on the behavior of tumor tissue in diffusion chambers against     \rpenetrating host cells in tumor-resistant rats .                        \r  tumour cells in diffusion chambers, which were implanted in           \rtumour-resistant rats, were only destroyed by penetrating immunized host\rcells when membrane filters of large pore size were used, whereas with  \rfilters of small pore size the tumour cells survived and remained       \rvirulent .                                                              \r'),
 (56,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'current status of hypothermia .                                         \r  moderate hypothermia has been recommended for many and varied         \rconditions . today its value is being questioned in the light of        \rcontrolled groups of patients . at the moment its use is justified in   \rcertain cardiac and other operations where circulation may be           \rinterrupted for short periods.. in general surgical procedures where    \rmassive, sudden blood loss may be anticipated.. in neurosurgical        \roperations where a /relaxed/ brain is required.. following acute hypoxia\rsuch as seen in cardiac arrest.. and perhaps in the therapy of acute    \rsepticemic shock .                                                      \r  profound hypothermia in association with extracorporeal circulation   \rrests on shakier premises, but can be of value in major cardiac         \roperations where asystole is required and in certain neurosurgical      \rprocedures where complete interruption of circulation is indicated .    \r  there is a great hazard in the development of inadvertent or          \runrecognized hypothermia in the anesthetized patient . monitoring of    \rbody temperature is an important feature of the care of the patient in  \rthe operating theater and in the recovery room .                        \r'),
 (57,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hyperglycemic coronary perfusion.. effect of hypothermia on myocardial  \rfunction during cardiopulmonary bypass .                                \r  in a series of 84 animal experiments hyperglycemic perfusion of the   \rheart gave significant protection to the anoxic heart . this protection \rwas evaluated by ventricular function and contractile force studies and \rwas observed after aortic occlusion at 37, 28 and 10 degrees c .        \r  metabolic data revealed a considerable myocardial glucose uptake,     \rhigher coronary ph, higher po and lower pco in the glucose-perfused     \rgroups as compared to controls .                                        \r  a hypothesis for the protective effect may be an alteration in        \rmetabolic pathway and support of the myocardial enzyme systems          \rassociated with high glucose concentration and utilization .            \r'),
 (58,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'specific carcinoembryonic antigens of the human digestive system .      \r  a wide variety of human adult and fetal tissues were studied by       \rimmunodiffusion techniques in agar gel to determine whether they        \rcontained the tumor-specific antigen(s) previously found in colonic     \rcancers . in the adult tissues it was demonstrated that identical       \rantigens were present in all tested specimens of malignant tumors of the\rentodermally derived epithelium of the gastro-intestinal tract and      \rpancreas, but were absent from all other tested adult tissues . the     \rcommon antigenic constituents, therefore, represent system-specific     \rcancer antigens of the human digestive system . system-specific cancer  \rantigens have not previously been demonstrated in humans .              \r  experiments with fetal tissues demonstrated that identical antigens   \rwere also present in fetal gut, liver, and pancreas between 2 and 6     \rmonths of gestation . these components were named /carcinoembryonic/    \rantigens of the human digestive system . on the basis of the present    \rfindings and the recent work regarding control of the expression of     \rgenetic potentialities in various genetic potentialities in various     \rtypes of cells, it was concluded that the carcinoembryonic antigens     \rrepresent cellular constituents which are repressed during the course of\rdifferentiation of the normal digestive system epithelium and reappear  \rin the corresponding malignant cells by a process of                    \rderepressive-dedifferentiation .                                        \r'),
 (59,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the course of influenza virus infection in mice.. organ tissues of      \rinfected mice tested by electron microscope .                           \r  using the electron microscope the presence of inclusions could be     \rshown in the lungs and liver of mice infected with the pr 8 strain . the\rinclusions contained particles of size and shape closely resembling the \rmost frequently seen forms of influenza virus . the presence of         \rinclusions in liver tissue might perhaps speak for the possibility of   \rvirus multiplication in this organ .                                    \r'),
 (60,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparative bone marrow study using two aspiration needles and two      \rbiopsy sites .                                                          \r  bone marrow aspiration is now widely used in the diagnosis of         \rhematologic diseases and many conditions not primarily affecting the    \rblood system . a number of techniques have been devised by which a      \rsuitable specimen of marrow can be obtained with relatively little      \rdiscomfort to the patient . the two needle sets described in this paper \rhave been found to be equally reliable in obtaining bone marrow for     \rmicroscopic study and diagnosis . comparative studies of bone marrow    \raspirated simultaneously from the iliac crest and the sternum in 26     \rpatients show no significant difference . however, there were four      \rinstances of dry tap at the iliac site . this fact, in addition to the  \robservation that less discomfort was experienced by the patient when the\rsternum was used, might indicate that the sternal area is a more        \rreliable and efficient site for obtaining bone marrow .                 \r  it was also observed during this study that patients experienced less \rdiscomfort when the university of illinois needle was used . the major  \robjection to the use of this needle is the inability to obtain a bone   \rcore for biopsy .                                                       \r'),
 (61,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cell populations in the bone marrow of the normal guinea-pig .          \r  quantitative data have been obtained for cell-populations in the bone \rmarrow of the normal 400g guinea-pig based on a study of 25 animals .   \rthere was good agreement between two independent groups of observations \rand an average of 1880000 nucleated cells per c. mm. was found . of this\rtotal, 27 were lymphocytes, 31 granulocyte precursors and 26 nucleated  \rerythrocyte precursors . whole body populations have been computed and  \rthe implications of the findings discussed .                            \r'),
 (62,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pneumocystis carinii pneumonia.. case studies with electron microscopy .\r  this paper deals with the clinicopathologic findings in 2 patients    \rwith pneumocystis carinii pneumonia . the first example was in a        \r51/2-month-old white female infant without an underlying disease . the  \rsecond occurred, in association with cytomegalic inclusion disease of   \rthe lungs, in a 46-year-old white woman who had received steroid        \rtherapy, cytotoxic agents, and irradiation to the thorax for hodgkin\'s  \rdisease . an electron microscope was used for the study of the          \rmorphology of the organisms in tissue removed at autopsy .              \r'),
 (63,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of dehydroepiandrosterone on the dehydroxycorticosteroids in \rthe plasms in various stages of breast cancer and mastopathy .          \r  the depressing effect of dehydroepiandrosterone on plasma             \rcorticosteroids is, on an average, shortened in advanced breast cancer  \r(stage iv) . the lowest corticosteroid values have been found with the  \rthree groups of patients 6 hours after infusion of                      \rdehydroepiandrosterone phosphate . the effect of dehydroepiandrosterone \rbeing, still provable after 12 hours with the group suffering from      \rmastopathy, the breast cancer group of stage iv had at this time already\rreached the level of the initial values . the breast cancer group of    \rstage iv had at this time already reached the level of the initial      \rvalues . the breast cancer group of stage i/ii behaved intermediately . \rthe less lasting effect of dehydroepiandrosterone is attributed to its  \raccelerated transformation in advanced breast cancer .                  \r'),
 (64,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the meaning of ph at low temperatures during extra-corporeal circulation\r  a review of the temperature gradients occurring during profound       \rhypothermia is made in regard to acid base changes in general, and to ph\rreadings in particular . it is concluded that terms such as \'body\',     \r\'mean\', \'average\' and \'core\' temperature should be discarded and that   \rwhen a temperature is quoted it should be referred to the site at which \rit was measured .                                                       \r  the main circumstances in which blood ph is measured at a temperature \rdifferent from that at which the blood is equilibrated with respiratory \rgases are reviewed by describing the changes which occur during         \rtonometry experiments . in this way fundamental changes can be          \runderstood before considering the more complicated sequences of events  \rtaking place in the living body .                                       \r  the alterations that occur in the concentrations of protein and       \rbicarbonate ion when whole blood is cooled are reviewed, together with  \rtheir influence on \'correction factors\' . the reasons why these factors \rshould not be applied to blood when the living body is undergoing       \rhypothermia involving the use of an extra-corporeal circulation are     \rdiscussed .                                                             \r  examples of the numerical values for blood ph during the two main     \rmethods for producing profound hypothermia, one using autogenous lung   \rperfusion and the other a pump-oxygenator are given, with reference to  \rthe influence of pco2 upon these values .                               \r  the existing methods of acid-base measurement appear to be            \rsufficiently accurate to reflect the metabolic component during profound\rhypothermia .                                                           \r'),
 (65,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'induced tumour resistance in rats .                                     \r  the human sarcoma hs has been grown in weanling rats treated with     \rcortisone . this growth was modified by prior injection of various      \rtissue antigens . active /immunity/ was produced by using human placenta\ror embryonic tissue as antigen, and similar results were obtained using \rsuspensions of rapidly growing human tumours .                          \r  the response to other human tissues varied.. foetal muscle and spleen \rwere active, whereas adult plasma was inactive except from some patients\rwith extensive malignant disease .                                      \r  passive protection was produced by using certain human sera at the    \rtime of challenging with hs . sera from five women who aborted showed   \rthis characteristic . where the pregnancy continued to term,            \rantisubstances were not found,. and they were present in the puerperium \rin only two out of fifty cases .                                        \r  further groups of rats were given rat embryonic tissues as antigen,   \rand the tumour challenge was then made with walker tumour,. the results \rwere variable .                                                         \r  with a benzpyrene-induced tumour in a pure line of /wag/ rat the      \reffect was not obtained except in isolated cases .                      \r  in experiments in mice, using as challenge an irondextran induced     \rmouse sarcoma, prior injection with embryonic mouse liver or placenta   \rincreased the resistance to the growth of the tumour, but the tumour has\rnot as yet been produced in a pure-line mouse . on the other hand mouse \rexperiments, using as challenge the crocker tumour, proved negative .   \r  it is suggested that immune reactions may play a part in causing some \rabortions .                                                             \r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (66,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'urinary steroid estimations in the prediction of response to            \radrenalectomy or hypophysectomy .                                       \r  a clinical trial has been carried out to test the use of the          \rdiscriminant in assessing the suitability of patients with advanced     \rbreast cancer for hypophysectomy or adrenalectomy .                     \r  patients with positive discriminants submitted to hypophysectomy have \ra much better prognosis than patients with negative discriminants       \rsubmitted to adrenalectomy .                                            \r  patients selected for adrenalectomy because of negative discriminants \rhave a significantly worse response to the operation than patients      \rselected by random sample .                                             \r  patients selected for hypophysectomy because of positive discriminants\rtend to have a better response to the operation than do patients        \rselected by random sample, but the difference is not significant .      \r  adrenalectomy is not recommended for patients with negative           \rdiscriminants .                                                         \r'),
 (67,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'primary epidermoid cancer of the lung.. ultrastructural study .         \r  the early epidermoidic epithelioma of the human lung are initiated by \rthe proliferation of body cells whose structure is analogical to that of\rthe medium cells and/or the modificated basal cells of the normal       \rbronchial wall .                                                        \r  the presence of desmosomes and tonofibrils in the cells of the stratum\rgerminativum of the bronchial epithelium and in the cells derived from  \rit, allows us a better understanding of the malpighian metaplasis of    \rthis wall and gives account of the epidermoidic evolution of the        \rbronchial epithelioma .                                                 \r  certain nuclear and cytoplasmic modifications suggest the possibility \rof a causal virus .                                                     \r'),
 (68,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'biosynthesis of glycoproteins i. incorporation of glucosamine- c into   \rliver and plasma proteins of the rat .                                  \r  it has been shown that glucosamine-1- c administered intravenously to \rfed rats is rapidly removed from the blood stream and appears first as  \rtrichloroacetic acid-soluble derivatives in the tissues . this is       \rfollowed by a conversion to macromolecules . at least 80 of the         \radministered compound can be recovered in tissues . the liver is by far \rthe most active organ in accumulating glucosamine . this is rapidly     \rconverted to protein-bound components of the liver particulate fraction \r(microsomes and mitochondria) and is then released to the plasma without\rappreciable accumulation in the soluble proteins of the liver . it is   \rconcluded that the glucosamine is transferred to the peptide chains of  \rglycoproteins at some stage before these proteins are released from the \rliver particulate fraction .                                            \r'),
 (69,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acute experimental pneumococcal (type i) pneumonia in the mouse.. the   \rmigration of leucocytes from the pulmonary capillaries into the alveolar\rspaces as revealed by the electron microscope .                         \r  in this preliminary study of experimental pneumococcal pulmonary      \rpneumonia in the mouse the leucocytes were observed to pass from the    \rcapillaries into the interstitial tissue and eventually into the        \ralveolar spaces through the intercellular junctions of the endothelial  \rand epithelial cell membranes .                                         \r'),
 (70,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a light and electron microscope study of developing respiratory tissue  \rin the rat .                                                            \r  1. light microscopic observations on the development of the rat lung  \rhave shown the presence of glandular, canalicular and alveolar stages . \r  2. these same three stages can be identified by electron microscopy   \rand all may be present in different parts of the lung at one time, e.g. \rat 40 and 45 mm. c.r. length .                                          \r  3. in the glandular stage, the lung tissue itself has an immature     \rappearance by light microscopy and by electron microscopy individual    \rcells also are immature in respect of organelles . glycogen is present  \rin immature cells .                                                     \r  4. during the canalicular stage, lung tissue becomes more vascular .  \r  5. throughout all stages of development, the \'duct\' or \'air\' spaces   \rare always lined by a continuous and complete epithelium, and blood     \rvessels by a complete endothelium .                                     \r  6. lamellated inclusion bodies are present in epithelial (endodermal) \rcells at an early stage of development .                                \r  7. micropinocytotic vesicles are present in large numbers in both     \repithelial and endothelial cytoplasm and it is suggested that in the    \rfoetus they may indicate absorption of amniotic fluid from alveolar     \rspaces .                                                                \r  8. the mechanism of alveolar distension is discussed and its nature   \rremains uncertain .                                                     \r  9. respiratory tissue of the rat is not fully differentiated at birth \rand the importance of this fact in human infants is discussed .         \r  10. the adult blood-air barrier, consisting of epithelium, zona       \rdiffusa and endothelium, varies in thickness .                          \r  this project was performed whilst both of us were in receipt of grants\rfrom the medical research council of canada, for which gratitude is     \rexpressed . our gratitude is also expressed to miss sylvia smith for    \rtyping the manuscript .                                                 \r'),
 (71,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the pathogenesis of viral influenzal pneumonia in mice .                \r  the pathogenesis of influenzal pneumonia in mice was studied by       \relectron microscopy . mice were inoculated with 1.5 ld of pr8 influenza \rvirus and killed at varying intervals after inoculation . observations  \rby light microscopy were correlated with those by electron microscopy in\rorder to evaluate the lesions produced .                                \r  at the periphery, the earliest lesions were focal areas of edema of   \ralveolar lining cells, the capillary endothelium and the interposed     \rbasement membrane . this caused an appreciable thickening of the        \rblood-air pathway . hypertrophy, degeneration and desquamation of the   \ralveolar lining and proliferation of alveolar macrophages resulted in   \rcomplete consolidation, which was progressive up to 1 week after        \rinfection .                                                             \r  the central areas of the lung were affected somewhat differently . at \r3 days after infection, the nonciliated bronchiolar cells showed        \rconsiderable hyperplasia of endoplasmic reticulum and apical cytoplasmic\redema . viral particles matured at the lumen surface of these cells and \rwere then released into the bronchiolar lumen . the bronchiolar cells,  \rboth ciliated and nonciliated, underwent degeneration and sloughed into \rthe bronchiolar lumen . the regenerating epithelium was stratified, and \rthe surface cells were elongated and flattened . the peribronchiolar    \rinterstitial tissue gradually became totally infiltrated by cells,      \rmostly of the mononuclear type .                                        \r'),
 (72,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on aging with horse crystalline lens gel as a contribution to   \rbiomorphosis of the mammalian crystalline lens .                        \r  the effects of biomorphosis -dash the continuous material change in   \rthe chemical composition of the organs and tissues -dash are studied on \rthe horse crystalline lens in respect of its amino acid content subject \rto substantial variations in the course of life . it is shown by        \relectrophoretic and paperchromatographic methods that the qualitative   \rcomposition of horse crystalline lenses remains quite the same, but that\rwithin the individual age stages there occur quantitative variations    \rbetween the individual amino acids .                                    \r'),
 (73,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the role of alveolar inclusion bodies in the developing lung .          \r  the developing alveolar epithelium of man and rat contains            \rcharacteristic inclusion bodies which are heterogeneous structures but  \rbasically consist of a system of membranous profiles and a limiting     \rmembrane of the unit type .                                             \r  inclusion bodies appear to result from focal cytoplasmic degradation  \rwhich occurs in the rapidly changing cuboidal alveolar epithelium . some\rinclusion bodies in the developing rat lung are similar to the so-called\r/lamellar transformed mitochondria./ however, evidence is presented     \rsuggesting that alteration of all cytoplasmic membranes may be involved \rin the process of inclusion body formation . certain images associated  \rwith the golgi complex are interpreted as early forms of inclusion      \rbodies . there is also evidence that inclusion bodies enlarge by        \raccretion of membranes which finally are extruded into the alveolar     \rspace . inclusion bodies are formed and /secreted/ in greater number    \rlate in fetal life and in early infancy, i.e., at the time when the     \rcuboidal alveolar epithelium is differentiating to the mature flattened \rtype . the latter contains no inclusion bodies .                        \r  on the basis of the morphologic characteristics of the inclusion      \rbodies and the distribution of the acid phosphatase reaction, it is     \rconcluded that inclusion bodies are lysosomal structures active during  \rremodeling of the developing alveolar epithelium .                      \r  the possible interrelationship of inclusion bodies and pulmonary      \rsurfactant is discussed .                                               \r'),
 (74,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'retinal detachment, cataract, keratoconus as ocular symptom complex in  \rendogenous eczema .                                                     \r  with reference to personal observations the authors describe the      \rovular changes encountered in endogenous eczema . besides the cataract  \rwhich has been known to occur already for a long time, retinal          \rdetachment, keratoconus and keratoconjunctivitis do still belong to the \rsymptom complex .                                                       \r'),
 (75,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'postural changes in blood distribution and its relation to the change in\rcardiac output .                                                        \r  (1) cardiac output and the blood content indices of the several parts \rof the body were measured in 18 subjects including patients with various\rdiseases using external radioisotope counting techniques . changes in   \rthese 2 parameters induced by standing were compared with each other .  \r  (2) average changes in blood distribution produced by standing were as\rfollows . decrease in blood content in the /lung/ (-25 ) and in the     \r/heart/ (-26 ) and increase in the /thigh/ (+56 ) were statistically    \rsignificant . no significant change was revealed in the /head/, /palm/, \r/liver/ and /abdomen/ .                                                 \r  (3) cardiac output and stroke volume decreased by standing in most of \rthe cases . recent data were added to those reported previously and were\rtreated statistically . average decrease in cardiac output was -13 in 6 \rcontrol cases, -35 in 16 cases with neurocirculatory asthenia and -35 in\r10 cases with hyperthyroidism . the difference was significant between  \rcontrol and neurocirculatory asthenia . standing induced a substantial  \rincrease in cardiac output in a case of idiopathic nodal rhythm,        \ralthough there remains a doubt whether it is the ordinary response in   \rthis disease .                                                          \r  (4) significant linear correlation was revealed between per cent      \rchange of blood content in the /thigh/ or in the /lung/ and that of     \rcardiac output or stroke volume induced by standing . minimal blood     \rshift was observed when the latter was extreme, and vice versa . this   \rimplies as follows.. reactivity of the heart might be influenced by     \rposture, and transmural pressure of veins and or capillaries is probably\radjusted, as in arterioles, to compensate for changes in cardiac output \r'),
 (76,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparative studies of the glycogen content of heart, liver and brain   \rbefore and after iodine treatment and under conditions of asphyxia .    \r  blood sugar level and glycogen concentration in the heart, brain and  \rliver of rabbits after treatment with inorganic iodine, depot insulin,  \riodine and insulin combined, hostacortine and hostacortine and iodine   \rcombined are being examined . a control group remains untreated . in a  \rsecond test series the glycogen determination under asphyxia (the       \rtrachea is being pinched off for three minutes) is repeated .           \r  contrary to the brain the glycogen content of the heart muscle is not \rdependent upon the blood sugar level . after iodine treatment a lowering\rof the blood sugar becomes noticeable, but also an increase in heart    \rglycogen . the liver glycogen shows greater variations . the levels     \rachieved in these test series therefore show no significant differences \rduring asphyxia there is a significant lowering of glycogen in all    \rthree organs . preliminary treatment with iodine succeeds in stopping   \rthe lowering of glycogen in the heart muscle and the brain . the        \rpossible causes for this phenomenon are being discussed .               \r'),
 (77,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'altered immunologic activity in sarcoidosis .                           \r  studies in 16 patients with sarcoidosis revealed evidence of          \rimmunologic alterations other than impaired delayed hypersensitivity .  \rtransient impairment of the response of lymphocytes cultured from       \rpatients with sarcoidosis to phytohemagglutinin stimulation was found to\rparallel the clinical severity of the disease . the hemolytic activity  \rof serum complement was increased . a disproportionate increase in serum\riga was found characteristic of the hyperglobulinemia of sarcoidosis .  \rthese observations indicate that an altered immune response may be      \rimportant in the pathogenesis of sarcoidosis . a simple hypothesis as to\rthe specific kind of interaction of infectious agent and immunity which \rmight result in the immunologic alterations observed is formulated and  \rpresented .                                                             \r'),
 (78,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electron microscopy of cytoplasmic inclusions within /macrophages/ of   \rhuman tissue .                                                          \r  the fine structure of inclusions found within the cytoplasm of        \rmacrophages of human lung, spleen, skin, lymph node, and rectum has been\rdescribed .                                                             \r  the inclusions appear as concentric or whorled lamellae arranged      \raround a core . each lamella is constructed of discrete, parallel       \rfilaments . the inclusions do not resemble currently described viruses  \ror virus-like particles, nor do they resemble asbestos bodies or other  \rknown atmospheric pollutants or ingestants .                            \r  there is some resemblance to lipid phase systems as well as mast cell \rgranules,. possibly the inclusions represent partial intracellular      \rdigestion of phagocytized tissue membranes or ingested mast cell        \rgranules, respectively . differences and similarities exist between the \rinclusion bodies of macrophages and the granules of mast cells . such   \rvariations could be due to alterations in mast cell granule morphology  \rbefore or after macrophage ingestion .                                  \r  cytologic distinctions between macrophages laden with mast cell       \rgranules and mast cells proper, remains obscure and requires additional \rexperimental evidence for clear electron microscopic differentiation of \rthese two cell types .                                                  \r  the exact nature of these highly structured bodies remains speculative\r'),
 (79,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'histological research on the lens in condition of hypoxia, changes in   \rthe mitotic activity of the epithelium .                                \r  the effect of hypoxia on the mitotic activity of the cells of the lens\repithelium was studied in 24 rats of the same strain and weight . the   \rhypoxia was obtained in the decompression chamber .                     \r  the results show that the mitotic activity of the lens epithelium is  \rdepressed at any of the examined altitudes (6.500, 8.000, 9.500 m),. in \rparticular, a marked reduction in the number of the prophases and an    \raccumulation in metaphase was observed .                                \r  the results were examined from the statistical standpoint and         \rdiscussed .                                                             \r'),
 (80,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'rate of change of carbon dioxide tension in arterial blood, jugular     \rvenous blood and cisternal cerebrospinal fluid on carbon dioxide        \radministration .                                                        \r  1. the rate of change of p in arterial blood and cisternal c.s.f., was\rmeasured following 5 percent co administration in eight anaesthetized   \rpatients undergoing routine air encephalography . ventilation was       \rmaintained constant throughout the procedure by a respirator . in three \rof the experiments the rate of change of p in the jugular venous blood  \rwas also measured .                                                     \r  2. the rise in p varied between 25.7 and 14.8 mm hg . the final       \rsamples of blood and c.s.f. were taken 20-25 min after the start of co  \radministration in five experiments . at this time the mean rise in p was\r65.9 (maximum range 68.1-61.6 percent) of the rise in p . in the        \rremaining three experiments the final samples were taken at 15 min when \rthe rises in p were 53.2, 39.4 and 38.1 percent of the arterial change .\r  3. the increases in p were 57.5, 76.2 and 76.1 percent of those in the\rarterial blood . the changes in p in the c.s.f. were smaller than in the\rjugular venous blood in all three experiments . in two of the           \rexperiments the final samples were taken 15 min after the start of co   \radministration when the increases of p in the c.s.f. were 68.5 percent  \rand 50 percent of those in jugular venous blood . in one experiment     \rwhere the final samples were taken at 20 min the increase in p was 89   \rpercent of the rise in p .                                              \r  4. there was a delay, following the start of co administration, in the\rrise of p in jugular venous blood and in the c.s.f . this delay was     \rabout 1 min in the jugular venous blood but in the c.s.f. it varied from\r1.6 to 4.2 min (mean 2.3) .                                             \r  5. the rise of p in blood and c.s.f. was exponential . the rise in p  \rin all experiments consisted of a fast component with time constants    \rwhich varied between 0.2 and 0.9 min (mean 0.5) and a slow component    \rwith time constants varying between 6.7 and 14.7 (mean 11.6) .          \r  the rise in p and p consisted of only one component . the time        \rconstants for the changes in jugular venous blood were 2.1, 3.8 and 4.3 \rmin, whilst in the c.s.f. they varied between 6.7 and 14.7 (mean 11.6) .\r  6. it is probable that about 40 percent of the increase in ventilation\rfollowing co administration is due to stimulation of an area in the     \rantero-lateral surface of the medulla sensitive to changes in ph or p   \r(mitchell et al. 1963) . this area is superficial and ventilation is    \raffected by changes in the p of the overlying c.s.f . it can be         \rpredicted from our experiments that the rise in p on co administration  \rwill take some 30 min to be complete . this may explain the slow rise in\rventilation on co breathing when compared with the rate of rise of      \rarterial and jugular venous p .                                         \r'),
 (81,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on the compound lipids from x-ray irradiated animal, ii.        \rbiological and biochemical properties of the compound lipids in the     \rx-ray irradiated rabbit organs .                                        \r  for the purpose to clarify the causes of x-ray disturbances a series  \rof experiments have been conducted on biological and biochemical        \rproperties of compound lipids extracted from normal and x-ray irradiated\rrabbit organs with a special reference to the p -labeled compound lipids\ruptake, inhibitory action to l cell proliferation and uncoupling of     \roxidative phosphorylation, and the following results have been obtained \r  the compound lipids (lysophosphatide rich fraction) isolated from the \rx-ray irradiated rabbit organ have been found to possess a strong       \rhemolytic action and also an action to inhibit the cell proliferation as\rwell as to accelerate the respiration of the mitochondria in the rabbit \rliver and spleen . it has also been proven that they act as to induce a \rmarked swelling of mitochondria, to impede the formation of high energy \rphosphate as well as to act as an uncoupler of oxidative phosphorylation\rin vivo . in the test to see the uptake of p -labeled compound lipids by\rvarious organs, a marked uptake has been observed in spleen, bone       \rmarrow, and liver of both irradiated and non-irradiated groups .        \rfurther, the uptake of p -labeled compound lipids in the rabbits given  \rintravenous injections of compound lipid fraction for 30 consecutive    \rdays previously has been found to be greatest in pancreas followed by   \rbone marrow, spleen, liver in the order mentioned in male group, whereas\rit is greatest in spleen, followed by liver and bone marrow in the      \rfemale group .                                                          \r  with these results the discussion was conducted concerning the        \rrelation between the lipid metabolism and x-ray disturbances .          \r'),
 (82,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cesium-131 uptake and distribution in the human heart.. an analysis of  \rcardiac scans in 104 patients .                                         \r  when properly used, cesium-131 is a satisfactory agent for the study  \rof cardiac morphology by photoscanning, which we believe is a useful    \radjunctive diagnostic procedure in patients for whom the results of     \rother methods of evaluation are at variance with the clinical symptoms  \rof cardiac disease . the studies reported here suggest that perhaps     \rinfarction of a subclinical type, size, or location may occur earlier   \rthan has been previously thought and that the damage it leaves may not  \rbe detectable by any means other than autopsy or a technique such as    \rscanning . we have not yet been able to measure the actual concentration\rof cesium-131 in the heart at autopsy so that the cold and cool areas   \rcould be examined by histologic sections .                              \r'),
 (83,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'oxygen consumption of paralysed men exposed to cold .                   \r  1. oxygen consumption and carbon dioxide output were measured when    \rhuman subjects were cooled for 80-210 min . two subjects were normal,   \rone had been almost completely paralysed below the neck by              \rpoliomyelitis, and two were unconscious as a result of intracranial     \rdamage and were observed with and without paralysing doses of muscle    \rrelaxants (d-tubocurarine and gallamine) .                              \r  2. when normal subjects and unconscious subjects receiving no drugs   \rwere cooled, oxygen consumption and carbon dioxide output rose .        \r  3. when subjects paralysed by disease or drugs were cooled, oxygen    \rconsumption and carbon dioxide output were not increased .              \r  4. these observations are consistent with the view that in man the    \rincrease in metabolism on cooling for periods up to 31/2 hr occurs      \rsolely in skeletal muscle .                                             \r'),
 (84,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'heparin levels during and after hypothermic perfusion .                 \r  1. perfusion-temperature influences the rate of heparin-loss during   \rextracorporeal circulation, and therefore, the requirement of           \rre-heparinization .                                                     \r  2. heparin half-lives of approximately 13/4 hours and 21/2 hours were \rcalculated during perfusions conducted at average temperatures of 31.5  \rand 22.6 c. respectively .                                              \r  3. the rate of heparin-loss during extracorporeal circulation is      \rinconstant in an individual, and variable between individuals, so that  \rexact neutralization requires an accurate estimation of the heparin     \rconcentration present at the end of perfusion .                         \r  4. the protamine titration test provides a crude but simple and       \rsatisfactory means of monitoring free-heparin levels .                  \r  5. complete neutralization of heparin is an important factor in       \rminimizing postoperative blood losses .                                 \r  6. protamine is a less efficient neutralizing agent than polybrene at \rthe same dosage level . it may be most effective in divided dosage .    \r  7. /rebound/ was detected in 5 of 45 cases studied, although in only  \rone instance was it of a degree likely to be significant .              \r  8. significant prolongation of the clotting-time resulting from excess\rneutralizing agent, was not evident in this study .                     \r'),
 (85,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'platelet sequestration in man . i. methods .                            \r  current methods of labeling platelets with chromium using             \rethylenediamine tetraacetate (edta) as an anticoagulant were found to   \rcause rapid hepatic sequestration of nearly all the transfused platelets\rabout 50 returned to the circulation but then were partially destroyed\rin the spleen . less than one-third survived . evidence is presented    \rwhich indicates that edta is injurious to platelets .                   \r  when an acid-citrate medium that buffered plasma at ph 6.5 was used as\ran anticoagulant, 36 to 85 of the labeled platelets survived (average,  \r62 ), and marked temporary sequestration did not occur . studies in     \rthrombocytopenic persons showed that circulating platelet cr activity   \rmeasures the true survival of such transfused platelets .               \r  the survival and sequestration of platelets were studied in normal    \rsubjects . the survival data support the concept that platelets die     \rchiefly by a process of senescence . external scintillation scanning of \rthe various organs suggests that normally the majority of platelets is  \rdestroyed in the liver .                                                \r'),
 (86,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acute leukemia associated with phenylbutazone treatment.. a review of   \rthe literature and report of a further case .                           \r  the possible toxic reactions to phenylbutazone have been listed, and a\rreview of the literature of haematological complications has shown that \r16 deaths attributable to agranulocytosis, aplastic anaemia and         \rthrombocytopenia have been recorded . the association between leukaemia \rand phenylbutazone first suggested by bean (1960) has been amplified by \rfurther reports, which have been reviewed .                             \r  a further case history has been presented . of the 15 patients with   \racute leukaemia in which the association has been recorded, there were  \rother possible leukaemogenic factors in three, and in a further three   \rthe drug had been given for only a short time before the leukaemia was  \rdiagnosed . however, in the remaining nine, the histories are such that \rthe phenylbutazone ingestion may have been associated with the          \rdevelopment of the leukaemia . further studies, which should include    \rmatched controls, are indicated, and will be required before a definite \ropinion can be given as to any causal relationship between the drug and \rthe disease .                                                           \r'),
 (87,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'absorbed radiation dose and excretion of cesium-131 in humans .         \r  data relating to the effective half-life, absorbed dose of radiation, \rand excretion rates of cesium-131 have been presented . cesium-131 is an\rexcellent material for cardiac scanning, since a very low amount of     \rradiation is absorbed -dash a dose of the order of one twentieth that   \rreceived in diagnostic x-ray studies of the gastrointestinal tract .    \rabsorption of radiation can be reduced further by the administration of \ra thiazide type of diuretic and, probably, by catharsis after the scan .\r'),
 (88,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radiocardiography.. principles and methods .                            \r  the aa show the importance of radiocardiography, as a method to       \revaluate the cardiac output, the ventricular volumes and the pulmonary  \rblood volume .                                                          \r  in this first paper, they are particulary concerned with some         \rtechnical aspects, which are very important to collect data .           \r  the position of the collimator on the precordium, the injection of    \risotopes through a catheter, just behind the ventricle near the         \rtricuspid valve, the selection of ratemeter constants the velocity of   \rpaper on the recorder and the way to read the area of the curve, were   \rspecially discussed .                                                   \r  finally, they present the formula used to calculate cardiac output,   \rventricular volumes and pulmonary blood volumes .                       \r'),
 (89,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'reaction of the adrenal cortex during controlled experimental           \rhypothermia .                                                           \r  the stress reaction caused by hypothermia was studied in rabbits      \rsubjected to controlled hypothermia by immersion in an icebath . some of\rthe animals were re-warmed . to anesthetize the animals, pentobarbitone \rsodium (nembutal) was given intraperitoneally, and, in some cases,      \rfollowed by ether anesthesia . further, the stress reaction produced by \rpentobarbitone alone was studied in five animals, and that of ether     \ranesthesia alone in three . no anesthesia was given to the three rabbits\rplaced in the refrigerator . the variation in distribution and amount of\radrenocortical lipids served as an indicator for evaluation of the      \rstress reaction .                                                       \r  in all the hypothermia tests there occurred changes in the            \rdistribution and amount of cortical lipids, denoting a stress reaction  \rbrought about by hypothermia . in rabbits, the barbiturate did not seem \rto inhibit the stress reaction . this may be attributed partly to the   \rtest animal, as such and partly to the fact that shivering of some      \rextent always occurred during the hypothermia experiments .             \r'),
 (90,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'use of a cross-circulation technique in studying respiratory responses  \rto co .                                                                 \r  the effect of hypercapnia and hypocapnia on ventilation was           \rinvestigated in cross-circulated dogs in which the recipient dog\'s head \rand neck regions were perfused by blood from a donor dog . hypercapnia  \rof the donor dog was produced by administering co -o -n gas mixtures in \rthe inspired air . hypocapnia was produced by hyperventilating the donor\rdog with the aid of a respiratory pump . when the donor dog was         \rhyperventilated, the ventilation of the recipient was maintained at or  \rjust below its resting level and it was independent of the arterial pco \rof the donor . the donor dog was apneic when the artificial             \rhyperventilation was suspended and this response was not abolished by   \rvagotomy . bilateral vagotomy caused an increase in ventilation in the  \rrecipient when its head was perfused by hypocapnic blood . bilateral    \rremoval of the carotid receptors did not influence the response to co   \rqualitatively although there was some reduction in the ventilation of   \rthe recipient to cephalic hypercapnia . the ventilation of the recipient\rdog was best correlated to the ph and pco of its cerebrospinal fluid in \rboth hypercapnic and hypocapnic states .                                \r'),
 (91,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'action of phytohaemagglutinin in vitro on the lymphocytes of chronic    \rlymphoid leukaemia .                                                    \r  the in vitro action of phytohaemagglutinin has been the subjects of a \rcomparative investigation of the lymphocytes of 13 normal subjects and  \rof 15 cases of chronic lymphatic leukaemia .                            \r  in both groups there is cellular change shown by the appearance of    \rlarge basophil nucleolated cells showing mitotic activity .             \r  in all the cases of lymphatic leukaemia the percentage of cells       \rundergoing such change is lower than in normal subjects, and the        \rtransformation occurs more slowly .                                     \r  the two phenomena are more striking the higher the initial            \rleucocytosis .                                                          \r  these results suggest, in chronic lymphatic leukaemia, the cells      \raffected by the transformation are residual normal lymphoid elements .  \rleukaemic lymphoid cells appear to be incapable of this transformation .\r'),
 (92,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'demonstration of ventricular aneurysms by radioisotope scanning .       \r  radioisotope scanning of the cardiac blood pool after the intravenous \rinjection of i -labeled iodipamide was carried out in 14 patients with  \rventricular aneurysm . in 4, the aneurysm could be demonstrated on      \rneither the anteroposterior chest roentgenogram nor the scan . in 5, the\raneurysm was apparent on the radiograph, but the blood pool did not     \renter the area, suggesting a thrombus within the aneurysm . in 5, the   \raneurysm was detectable on the film and was also seen to be filled with \rradioactivity on the scan . presumably these findings showed that a     \rthrombus had not yet formed . blood pool radioisotope scanning appears  \rto be another tool in the diagnosis of ventricular aneurysm, useful also\rin demonstrating in some patients the presence or absence of an         \rintraluminal clot within the aneurysm .                                 \r'),
 (93,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'propagation of lactic dehydrogenase-elevating virus in cell culture .   \r  primary cultures of adult mouse lung, spleen, and liver and of mouse  \rembryo support the multiplication of the lactic dehydrogenase-elevating \rvirus . such cultures produced virus continuously until they had been   \rsubcultured 2-3 times . this corresponded to 20 weeks in the case of    \rlung and spleen and to 2-3 weeks with cultures of embryo . viral        \rmultiplication was not accompanied by cytologic alterations in the cells\ror by changes in their rate of synthesis of nucleic acids or protein .  \rinfection did not cause detectable changes in either the production of  \rldh or in its release from cells .                                      \r'),
 (94,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'transformation of bovine cells in vitro after inoculation of simian     \rvirus 40 or its nucleic acid .                                          \r  cells of bovine embryonic lung tissue in culture were inoculated with \rsimian virus 40 (sv 40) or a phenol extract of a high titer suspension  \rof sv 40 . both the virus and the nucleic acid preparation induced      \rproliferative morphological changes characteristic for sv 40            \rtransformation . non-infected control cultures and cultures which were  \rinoculated with a preparation of nucleic acid exposed to dnase and      \rmaintained under the same conditions as infected cultures showed a      \rregular fibroblastic growth .                                           \r  cell lines of rapidly growing transformed cells have been obtained .  \rmost attempts to isolate virus from the transformed cells were negative,\rbut minute amounts of virus were recovered from occasional passages .   \r'),
 (95,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'rapid transformation of human fibroblast cultures by simian virus 40 .  \r  the risk of systemic embolism is assessed in a group of 754 patients  \rwith chronic rheumatic heart disease followed over a period of 5,833    \rpatient-years .                                                         \r  the incidence of embolism was 1.5 per patient-year for the whole group\rit was seven times higher in atrial fibrillation than in sinus rhythm \rwhen the duration of atrial fibrillation was known, it was found that \rone-third of the emboli occurred within one month and two-thirds within \r12 months after the onset of atrial fibrillation . the incidence of     \rembolic recurrences was 8 per patient-year, irrespective of the nature  \rof the cardiac rhythm, but 66 of the recurrences took place within 12   \rmonths of the initial embolic episode .                                 \r  mitral valvotomy did not eliminate the danger of embolism . it is     \rquestionable whether it reduced its incidence .                         \r  anticoagulant treatment reduced the incidence of embolic recurrences .\r'),
 (96,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the tissue reaction to hyperbaric oxygen .                              \r  hyperbaric oxygen damages tissues exposed in vitro, but their         \rsensitivity varies . if exposure is limited some tissues may recover .  \rthe effect appears to depend on oxygen tension rather than raised       \rpressure per se . the tissue reaction may be involved in the clinical   \rapplication of hyperbaric oxygen .                                      \r'),
 (97,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'attitudinal factors in congenital heart disease .                       \r  this study considers the behavioral implications of congenital heart  \rdisease for the pediatric patient, his siblings, and his parents . the  \reffects of a disease on the child, on his siblings, and on his parents  \rand the interplay among these individuals are explored . the impact of  \rthe physician\'s diagnosis is illustrated by the induced significant     \rchanges in family attitudes, which are not necessarily related to       \rdisease severity or child incapacity .                                  \r  poorer adjustment and anxiety in the cardiac child related more highly\rto maternal anxiety and pampering than to his degree of incapacity .    \rmaternal protectiveness and pampering were significantly greater in the \rcardiac than in the normal group and were highest in the cyanotic group \rthe best predictor of maternal protectiveness was maternal anxiety,   \rand it was found that the addition of other variables such as incapacity\rand child dependence failed to improve prediction substantially .       \rmaternal anxiety seemed related to the presence rather than to the      \rseverity of the heart condition .                                       \r'),
 (98,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maternal anxiety during pregnancy and adequacy of mother and child      \radjustment eight months following childbirth .                          \r  fifty pregnant women were administered a battery of psychological     \rtests . on the basis of scores obtained from the manifest anxiety scale,\rthese pregnant women were dichotomized into a /high anxiety/ group and a\r/low anxiety/ group . eight months following childbirth, the mothers and\rchildren were seen for a psychological assessment . it was found that   \rthe women in the /high anxious/ group evidenced significantly more      \rnegative childrearing attitudes . that is, the /high anxious/ mothers   \robtained significantly higher scores on the hostility and control       \rfactors measured by the pari . on the basis of the examiner\'s ratings of\rthe mother\'s personality traits, it was found that the women who were   \rhighly anxious during pregnancy received much less favorable personality\rratings at the time of the 8-month assessment . moreover, there was a   \rsignificant difference in the proportions of mothers in the two groups  \rwho received a favorable rating from the examiner on the basis of his   \robservation of the mother-child interaction during the session . in     \rstudying the children of these mothers, it was found that the children  \rof the /low anxious/ mothers received a significantly higher            \rdevelopmental quotient on the infant mental scale . in keeping with this\rfinding, they also obtained a higher developmental quotient on the motor\rscale, although on this aspect of the intellectual assessment the       \rdifference was not statistically significant . also, the children from  \rthe /low anxious/ mothers tended to receive a score indicative of a more\rfavorable general emotional tone than did the offspring of the /high    \ranxious/ mothers . this difference between the two groups of children   \rwas not statistically significant . in general, the findings were       \rconsistent with the predictions that the children who were being reared \rby women who had been highly anxious during pregnancy would fare less   \rwell on tests of intellectual development and indices of emotional      \radjustment . the findings also were in keeping with the prediction that \rthe highly anxious women during pregnancy would evidence less desirable \rparental attitudes during their child\'s early development and that they \rwould present a less favorable personality picture at a time            \rapproximately 8 months following pregnancy .                            \r'),
 (99,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maternal separation in the rhesus monkey .                              \r  the present study involved separation of eight monkey mother-infant   \rpairs for a period of two weeks and measurement of the behavior of the  \rinfants before, during and after reunion with their mothers, and of the \rmothers before and after reunion . all infants showed emotional         \rdisturbance in response to separation and drastic decreases in play and \rother complex social behaviors while separated .                        \r  it is clear that infant-mother separation produces emotional          \rdisturbance in both human and macaque infants and that the patterns of  \rresponses following separation are similar in both species . the results\robtained in studies of monkey infant-mother separation indicate that    \rsheer physical separation is the crucial aspect of maternal separation  \rfor monkeys . undoubtedly other factors associated with separation from \rthe mother are vitally important for human children, and may account in \rpart for the absence or rarity of the detachment stage (as seen in human\rresponse pattern) in separated monkey infants . the overall results show\rconsiderable similarity in the responses of human children and infant   \rmonkeys to separation from the mother .                                 \r'),
 (100,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the ophthalmologist\'s role in the management of dyslexia .              \r  dyslexia is a clinical entity characterized by subnormal reading      \rability in a person of average or above average intelligence .          \r  it is a disease which has different causes in different children . the\rcauses include brain damage in the /language area,/ hereditary          \rpredisposition and such ophthalmic factors as hyperopia, muscle         \rimbalance, aniseikonia or visual immaturity . emotional disturbances,   \reducational immaturity and cerebral dominance may also play some role in\rthe etiology of this condition .                                        \r  the universal symptom is poor reading ability . however, these cases  \rfrequently have other associated symptoms such as poor writing,         \rdifficulty in reading and writing numbers, inability to read or write   \rmusical notes and disorientation for left and right . many of these     \rpatients develop personality maladjustments . visual fields often reveal\ra hemianopia .                                                          \r  in any group of poor readers, a large percentage will have ocular,    \rneurologic, psychiatric or psychologic abnormalities and/or a strong    \rhereditary tendency . the degree to which reading can be learned depends\rupon the ability of the individual to adjust to the psycho-physiologic  \rneeds that are present at the time he reaches /reading age/ in school . \rif compensating abilities are present, and if the child\'s reaction is a \rfavorable one, he may read well in spite of unfavorable factors,. if    \rnot, he may become a /poor reader/ . these children should be recognized\rin their first year of school .                                         \r  a complete medical work-up should be managed by an ophthalmologist . a\rcomplete ophthalmic examination should first be performed and all       \rpossible visual anomalies should be corrected . the ophthalmologist may \rwant a psychometric evaluation, a neurologic opinion to determine the   \rrole of organic brain damage, psychiatric consultation for evaluation of\remotional disturbances, pediatric consultation for evaluation of the    \rstatus of the general health and/or consultation by an otolaryngologist \rto determine the patient\'s hearing ability . with all the necessary     \rinformation at hand, the ophthalmologist will be able to recommend      \rcorrective medical therapy and to advise the parents and teachers about \ravailable remedial reading aids .                                       \r  the prognosis is good for most patients since they are of average or  \rabove average intelligence,. nearly all cases can be helped .           \r'),
 (101,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'unusual course of internal carotid artery accompanied by bitemporal     \rhemianopia .                                                            \r  a case is reported with bitemporal relative hemianopia, craniotomy    \rshowing internal carotid arteries to have an unusual course,            \rcorresponding to the carotid siphon, with resultant change in shape of  \rthe optic nerves .                                                      \r  abnormalities of the carotid siphons could not be detected on         \rreviewing the carotid angiograms . evaluation of the optic nerve\'s      \rrelationship, as can be measured on the pneumograms, indicated that the \roptic nerves in this case were exposed to compression from the abnormal \rarteries .                                                              \r'),
 (102,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'frontal lobes and vision .                                              \r  the influence of the frontal lobe on vision is discussed based on the \rpresentation of a rather unusual case . after the operation of a right  \rfrontal brain abscess, which never had led to papilledema, there was a  \rpronounced diminution of the visual capacities of the patient,.         \rgradually these disturbances regressed to the point of return of full   \rvisual acuity,. but there remained a hemianopic field defect . this and \rpsychological defects in the sense of a partial visual agnosia (which   \rlatter are also regressing very well) prompted a discussion of those    \rneuroanatomical and neurophysiological observations pertinent to the    \rfindings in this patient . the many data on the fronto-occipital        \rconnections in subhuman primates point to the role of the frontal lobe  \r(area 8) in the development of visual disturbances in the sense of a    \rtemporary hemianopia with partial visual agnosia and some intellectual  \rdeficits . contrary to a single observation in an anthropoid ape, our   \rcase would seem to indicate that the aforementioned combination of      \rsymptoms may originate in the frontal lobe,. and we hope it will prompt \rother long-term follow-up studies of similar patients . the continued   \robservation of this patient and perhaps of others will give a           \rpossibility to gain insight into the role of the frontal lobe in vision,\ras has been assumed for animals .                                       \r'),
 (103,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'physiologic bitemporal hemianopsia in pregnancy .                       \r  a severe case of bitemporal hemianopsia occurring late in pregnancy is\rpresented . the patient illustrated a typical rapidly progressive course\rand rapid recovery with complete return of visual fields and visual     \racuity after delivery was accomplished . the presumed pathologic        \rphysiology of this entity is briefly reviewed .                         \r'),
 (104,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evoked response in visual disorders .                                   \r  1. erg and ver have been recorded from eyelid and lateral occipital   \relectrodes in response to diffuse stroboscopic stimulation . in 45      \rnormal subjects ver was found to be composed of an early triphasic      \rpotential arising from the occipital region . wave i was present in 67  \rpercent of subjects, wave ii in 97 percent, and wave iii in 100 percent \rlater waves were inconstant and contained components from the vertex  \rreference . no overall asymmetry in ver from right to left was found in \rnormal subjects, although average asymmetry with smaller side compared  \rto larger was 19 percent 12.5 . on monocular stimulation the            \rcontralateral ver was regularly larger than the ipsilateral reflecting  \rpredominant retinal representation of the temporal field .              \r  2. a statistically determined criterion of 50 percent depression in   \rwave ii successfully identifies most patients with hemianopic defects   \rinvolving the central 10 percent of visual field on tangent screen      \rcampimetry .                                                            \r  latency asymmetry of six msec. or more and grossly asymmetrical       \raberrant wave forms are seen in some patients with diffuse cerebral     \rdisease and hemianopic defects .                                        \r  3. severe or diffuse retinal disease is associated with alteration or \rloss of erg and ver on stimulation of the involved eye .                \r  4. optic nerve disease is indicated by bilateral loss or suppression  \rof ver on stimulation of the involved eye . erg is normal .             \r  5. bilateral prechiasmal involvement is associated with complete      \rsuppression of ver . if only waves i and ii are lost, disease is        \rprobably, but not conclusively, demonstrated .                          \r  6. involvement of nasal retinal fibres is indicated by reversal of the\rnormal contralateral preponderance of ver on monocular stimulation .    \rthese changes are observed in chiasmal disease .                        \r  7. retrogeniculate blindness is associated with loss of early ver and \rpreservation of late response . nonspecific projections are felt to     \rcontribute to the late cortical response to photic stimulation .        \r'),
 (105,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'optokinetic nystagmus and occipital lesions .                           \r  six cases are presented to invalidate the rule that horizontally      \rsymmetric optokinetic responses indicate a vascular etiology in patients\rwith occipital lobe type hemianopias . the converse of this rule is, in \rour experience, still a valuable observation . that is, asymmetry of    \rhorizontal optokinetic responses accompanying an occipital type field   \rdefect is a strong indication of a mass lesion . optokinetic nystagmus  \rmay be helpful, therefore, as corroborative evidence in diagnosing      \roccipital lobe tumor but not in ruling it out .                         \r'),
 (106,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'anaphylactoid shock induced by oral penicillin and resulting in         \rgerstmann\'s syndrome .                                                  \r  an anaphylactoid reaction to oral penicillin in a 46-year-old woman is\rdescribed.. after hours of unconsciousness and weeks of confusion she   \rwas left with a residual gerstmann\'s syndrome . these reactions are less\rrare than is generally supposed . symptomatology, treatment, diagnosis, \rand mechanism are discussed, and some of the relevant literature is     \rbriefly reviewed .                                                      \r'),
 (107,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'disturbances of the verbal body image.. a particular syndrome of sensory\raphasia .                                                               \r  1. the pto syndrome of the dominant hemisphere varies according to the\rextent and depth of the lesion in the angular and supramarginal areas . \rthe mildest clinical syndrome consists of a vague contralateral sensory \rimpairment associated with dyscalculia, dysgraphia, dyslexia and        \rdifficulty in naming . a more extensive lesion is needed to cause the   \rwide variety of classical signs described in parietal lobe disease,     \ramong them being gerstmann\'s syndrome, which is usually found in        \rassociation with other manifestations of parietal loss (case 1) . an    \reven more extensive corticosubcortical lesion in the area leads to      \rcomplete disintegration of naming and understanding of speech (cases 3, \r4 and 5) .                                                              \r  2. attention is drawn to the difficulties arising from lack of        \rdifferentiation between the concrete gnostic body image and the abstract\rverbal body image in investigation of these patients . the aphasic      \rsyndrome should be differentiated from disturbances of gnosis by        \rapplication of separate, non-verbal methods of testing to elicit the    \rimpairment of the gnostic body image . the latter may be well           \rcompensated for and it is apparently unimpaired in the presence of an   \raphasic syndrome limited to the verbal body image .                     \r  3. disturbances of speech in pto lesions if investigated along        \rquantitative scales of impairment of repetition, understanding and      \rnaming, show a regular interrelation . nomination is the most affected, \runderstanding is less affected . repetition is the best preserved       \rfunction (cases 1-4) . the same interrelation of these functions is     \rfound with regard to the verbal body image . however, understanding and \rnaming of parts of the body show far greater disintegration than        \runderstanding and naming of any other categories of words (all cases    \rpresented here) . if the aphasic syndrome is subsiding, finger aphasia  \rwith some other minor disturbances of verbal body image associated with \racalculia may persist (case 1) . thus gerstmann\'s /finger agnosia/ may  \rrepresent a partial impairment of the verbal body image and be limited  \rto finger aphasia .                                                     \r  4. it is assumed that the verbal body image differs from other        \rcategories of verbal symbols owing to the mainly proprioceptive,        \rvestibular and tactile experience forming its specific physiologic      \rbackground . telereceptive experience is of minor importance in the     \rinitial development of the understanding of words defining the body     \rimage .                                                                 \r  in the patients described here, the selectively worse aphasic         \rimpairment of the verbal body image, as compared with other categories  \rof words, seem to confirm this assumption .                             \r'),
 (108,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chromosomal patterns in cancer patients during treatment .              \r  radiation damages the chromosomes of human cells, and through         \rshort-term cultures of white blood cells some of this damage can be     \rassessed . patients with cancer were selected for this study because of \rthe large portions of the blood-forming tissues irradiated in the course\rof treatment . chromosomal damage may be quantitative with variations   \rfrom the normal number of 46, or qualitative, thereby showing structural\raberrations . counting the chromosomes in cells from cultures grown     \rprior to therapy and at intervals during treatment enables us to        \rdetermine the variation .                                               \r  stained preparations examined microscopically allow us to recognize   \rthese abnormalities which are apparent before, during, and after        \rradiotherapy . the damage appears to be largely random in the           \rchromosomes affected in the different cancers, and the specific         \raberrations differ from cell to cell . however, there does seem to be   \rsome correlation between the appearance of persistent aberrant          \rchromosomes and their frequency . while the peak incidence or /plateau/ \rmay remain unchanged, the frequency may change .                        \r'),
 (109,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a few interesting neurologic manifestations of migraine .               \r  migraine is a complex vascular phenomenon presumably of genetic origin\rwhich, through changes induced by either vasoconstriction or            \rvasodilitation, can produce interference with the neurologic system and \rresult in many bizarre and alarming clinical pictures . a few examples  \rof the more interesting neurologic manifestations have been shown .     \r'),
 (110,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'visual neglect .                                                        \r  clinical trainees in nursing and in psychology from boston college and\rsimmons college, boston, mass., collected data and observed patients    \runder the direction of the authors in a pilot program designed to       \rmeasure visual spatial neglect and to develop rehabilitative material . \rthese measurements and exercises might also be used by nurses in their  \rcare of those patients who have had cerebral vascular accidents .       \r  the diversity of daily activities in which the patient becomes        \rinvolved during his hospitalization should provide some indication of   \rthe extent to which the compensatory visual neglect therapeutics have   \rbeen effective . more formal estimates can be obtained by               \rre-administering the battery of visual neglect tests at periodic        \rintervals . nursing personnel adopting a program of therapeutics such as\rthis must bear in mind that patients suffering cerebral insult are      \rusually less adaptive than their nonbrain-injured peers . they develop  \rnew habit patterns slowly and regression often will follow apparent     \rfixation at a more adaptive level of response habituation(11) . however,\rexperimental inquiry has shown that the dimension of behavioral         \rdifference between the brain-injured adults and normal adults is one of \rdegree rather than kind -dash a difference that skilled nursing can     \roften reduce(12) .                                                      \r'),
 (111,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'respiratory changes after open-heart surgery .                          \r  patients who undergo cardiac surgery with extracorporeal circulation  \rdevelop significant alveolar-arterial oxygen tension differences and    \rvenous admixture in the early post-operative period . up to 50 of this  \rabnormality is due to anatomical right to left shunting through the     \rlungs.. the remainder is most likely to be due to ventilation-perfusion \rinequality . the changes appear to be completely reversible . the       \rcardiopulmonary bypass procedure may be responsible for initiating the  \runderlying pathology, since changes of this magnitude were not found in \rcardiothoracic surgery patients in whom this technique was not required \r'),
 (112,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cardiac malformations associated with ventricular septal defect .       \r  in this study, 46 necropsy-proved cases of ventricular septal defect  \rassociated with another anomaly but not part of a recognized complex    \rwere selected .                                                         \r  the associated anomalies were classified as (1) obstructive or        \rpositional anomalies of the great vessels, (2) anomalies responsible for\radditional shunts, (3) anomalies causing intraventricular obstruction   \rand (4) aortic valvular insufficiency .                                 \r  clinical findings were often those of the ventricular septal defect,  \rand the findings related to the associated lesion were frequently       \robscure . even with special studies, including cardiac catheterization  \rand angiocardiography, there was often failure to arrive at a complete  \rdiagnosis . the findings which led to an erroneous or incomplete        \rdiagnosis have been presented . when a complete diagnosis was made      \rpreoperatively, the procedures leading to it have been outlined . while \rthe diagnostic approach varies with the malformations which may coexist \rwith ventricular septal defect, it was observed that aortography and    \rselective left ventricular angiocardiography were most commonly helpful \rin identifying occult malformations associated with ventricular septal  \rdefect . it is therefore recommended that complete studies, including   \rleft-sided cardiac catheterization with left ventricular                \rangiocardiography and aortography, should be considered in all cases in \rwhich the clinical, electrocardiographic, and right-sided cardiac       \rcatheterization studies are not entirely typical for isolated           \rventricular septal defect .                                             \r'),
 (113,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'anatomic types of single or common ventricle in man morphologic and     \rgeometric aspects of 60 necropsied cases .                              \r  in 60 necropsied cases of single or common ventricle in man, four     \rmajor unrelated ventricular malformations were found.. (1) absence of   \rthe right ventricular sinus, in 47 cases (78 percent), designated type  \ra,. (2) absence of the left ventricular sinus, in 3 cases (5 percent),  \rtype b,. (3) absence or rudimentary development of the ventricular      \rseptum, in 4 cases (7 percent), type c,. and (4) absence of both        \rventricular sinuses and of the ventricular septum, in 6 cases (10       \rpercent), type d .                                                      \r  three types of relationship between the great arteries were present.. \ra normal (solitus) interrelationship, in 9 cases (15 percent),          \rdesignated type 1,. d-transposition, the transposed aortic valve lying  \rto the right (dextro, or d), relative to the transposed pulmonary valve,\rin 25 cases (42 percent), type ii,. and l-transposition, the transposed \raortic valve lying to the left (levo or l), relative to the transposed  \rpulmonary valve, in 26 cases (43 percent), type iii . in none was the   \rinversus interrelationship, type iv, displayed .                        \r  three types of visceral and atrial situs were found.. solitus, or     \rnormal, in 50 cases (83 percent),. inversus, an exact apparent mirror   \rimage of normal, in 2 cases (3 percent),. and heterotaxy, the uncertain \rvisceral and atrial situs associated with asplenia, in 8 cases (13      \rpercent) .                                                              \r  the 60 cases were classified segmentally, according to the anatomy of \rthe three cardiac segments.. the great arteries, the ventricular        \rsinuses, and the atria .                                                \r  the classic single ventricle with a rudimentary outlet chamber was    \rfound morphologically to be a large left ventricle with a right         \rventricular infundibulum, the sinus of the right ventricle being absent \r(type a) .                                                              \r  the myocardium of the right ventricular infundibulum, of the right    \rventricular sinus, and of the left ventricular sinus was identified by  \rthe distinctive gross morphologic characteristics of each .             \r  the planes of the atrial and ventricular septa, and the relationships \rbetween the great arteries at the semilunar valves, were measured as    \rprojections upon the horizontal plane, relative to the anteroposterior  \rline .                                                                  \r  an approach to cardiac anatomy is presented which is segmental,       \rmorphologic and geometric . this approach has angiocardiographic,       \relectrocardiographic and embryologic applications .                     \r'),
 (114,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital heart disease in the adult .                                 \r  events in the natural course of 310 adult patients with proved        \rsignificant congenital cardiac anomalies have been reviewed to determine\rincidence, longevity, complications and cause of death .                \r  atrial septal defect and patent ductus arteriosus were the most       \rfrequently encountered lesions and comprised over one third of the      \rentire series . ventricular septal defect and pulmonic stenosis made up \ralmost a quarter of the group . twenty-two instances of the eisenmenger \rsyndrome secondary to a variety of shunting lesions are included .      \r  bacterial endocarditis, sudden death and cardiac decompensation were  \rthe greatest threats to these patients . symptoms were minimal until the\rappearance of heart failure, which was the most common cause of death,  \respecially with older patients . sudden death occurred most often in    \rpatients with ventricular septal defect .                               \r  although the clinical features are usually characteristic of a        \rcongenital malformation, young adults with acyanotic congenital heart   \rdisease are often misdiagnosed as rheumatic,. and in older patients,    \rpresenting manifestations are frequently attributed to arteriosclerotic \rheart disease . at times an associated acquired cardiovascular disorder \rmay alter the basic syndrome .                                          \r  three quarters of the patients survive and continue under observation \rthe ability of many to live active, productive lives and to withstand \rstress, surgery, both cardiac and non-cardiac, and pregnancy was        \rimpressive . further observation of the patient with congenital heart   \rdisease but without surgical intervention is essential for accurate     \revaluation of the long term efficacy of cardiac surgery .               \r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (115,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a study of ventricular septal defect associated with aortic             \rinsufficiency .                                                         \r  clinical, electrocardiographic, radiographic, and hemodynamic findings\rin 12 children with the combination of a ventricular septal defect and  \raortic insufficiency are presented . the left-to-right shunt was        \rdetermined to be small or moderate in all, and significant aortic       \rinsufficiency was documented by aortography in 11 patients . clinical   \rindication of aortic insufficiency as manifested by an aortic diastolic \rmurmur first appeared at an average age of 6 years in 7 patients, with  \rconcomitant widening of the pulse pressure in 4 . progressive left      \rventricular hypertrophy was noted electrocardiographically, with        \rprogressive cardiac hypertrophy and aortic dilatation on x-ray          \rexamination in 2 patients . progression of the hemodynamic disability   \rdoes not appear to be common in childhood, however .                    \r'),
 (116,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ventricular septal defect and aortic regurgitation clinical, hemodynamic\rand surgical considerations .                                           \r  the clinical, hemodynamic, angiographic and anatomic findings in      \rfifteen patients with ventricular septal defect complicated by aortic   \rregurgitation are presented . in this combination of malformations the  \raortic regurgitation is acquired and results from prolapse of an aortic \rvalve leaflet into the septal defect . the strategic location of the    \rseptal defect in relation to the aortic leaflets appears to be more     \rimportant to the development of this complication than the size of the  \rdefect or the magnitude of the shunt through it . the onset of aortic   \rregurgitation occurs during early childhood and, once present, tends to \rbecome more severe . careful observation of patients with these defects \ris indicated following the appearance of aortic regurgitation since     \rrapid progression to severe left ventricular failure is not uncommon .  \rventricular septal defect and aortic regurgitation must be distinguished\rfrom other cardiovascular abnormalities producing a wide pulse pressure \rwith a continuous or to-and-fro murmur . cardiac catheterization and    \rthoracic aortography are the diagnostic procedures most helpful in this \rdifferentiation . the operative treatment of ventricular septal defect  \rand aortic regurgitation is reviewed and, on the basis of the present   \rand previously reported results, suggested plans for surgical management\rare presented .                                                         \r'),
 (117,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'current techniques in the surgical approach to aortic and mitral        \rvalvular disease .                                                      \r  1. the aortic and mitral valves can be operated upon successfully and \rtotally replaced with a prosthetic device of the ball-valve type with   \rgood long-term results . seventy-four cases are reported .              \r  2. in aortic valvular disease the outcome in the immediate            \rpostoperative period is influenced primarily by the presence of calcific\raortic stenosis as well as the presence or absence of disease in the    \rcoronary arteries .                                                     \r  3. we have significantly decreased the appearance of a low-output     \rsyndrome postoperatively in patients who are suffering from severe      \rmitral disease by leaving the papillary muscle-chordae tendineae-mural  \rleaflet relationship intact . we feel this adds strength to each        \rcontraction .                                                           \r  4. there have been no late deaths in the follow-up period to date     \r(thirty months) in any patient with replacement of aortic or mitral     \rvalves with the ball-valve prosthesis .                                 \r'),
 (118,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of aortic regurgitation on left ventricular performance direct  \rdeterminations of aortic blood flow before and after valve replacement .\r  the volume of regurgitant blood flow and its effects on the           \rperformance of the left ventricle were assessed at operation in 14      \rpatients with varying degrees of aortic regurgitation . instantaneous   \rforward and regurgitant flows in the ascending aorta were measured with \ra sine-wave electromagnetic flowmeter simultaneously with left          \rventricular and aortic pressures . in eight patients who had aortic     \rregurgitation without associated stenosis, 63 to 75 percent of the total\rforward stroke volume regurgitated during the succeeding diastole . the \rcalculated regurgitant orifice areas ranged from 0.13 to 0.44 cm /m .   \rafter replacement of the aortic valve with a starr-edwards prosthesis,  \rthe absence of regurgitant flow was proved in every patient, and the    \rrecords of aortic blood flow closely resembled those seen in patients   \rwith normal aortic valves . net forward blood flow increased by an      \raverage of 60 percent, total left ventricular stroke volume fell 42     \rpercent, and the mean aortic pressure rose 29 percent . the pressure    \rwork of the left ventricle was elevated preoperatively in five of the   \reight patients (average 89 g-m stroke/m ) and fell significantly to an  \raverage of 34 g-m stroke m after valve replacement . kinetic ventricular\rwork was high in seven of the eight patients and comprised 10 percent of\rtotal work before replacement but only 4.8 percent afterward .          \r  similar observations were made in five patients with aortic stenosis  \rand associated aortic regurgitation, ranging in severity from 24 to 72  \rpercent of total forward stroke volume . in four patients in whom the   \rvalve was replaced, no residual regurgitation was present afterward, and\rnet forward flow rose an average of 49 percent . kinetic left           \rventricular work was extremely high in every patient and averaged 26    \rpercent of total work preoperatively and 13 percent after valve         \rreplacement . in this group, pressure work was variable both before and \rafter operation .                                                       \r  the studies described provide definitive information concerning the   \reffects of aortic valve disease on left ventricular performance in man  \rand document the favorable changes in flow, pressure, and left          \rventricular work which immediately follow aortic valve replacement .    \r'),
 (119,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the absorption and hepatic uptake of orally ingested radioactive vitamin\rb in hepato-splenic bilharziasis .                                      \r  the absorbed plasma radioactivity and hepatic uptake of orally        \ringested vitamin b tagged with co were measured in 52 subjects, 26      \rnormals and 26 suffering from bilharziasis .                            \r  the results of the present work indicate that the absorption and      \rhepatic uptake of this vitamin are within normal limits in hepatosplenic\rbilharziasis irrespective of the stage of the disease, the size of the  \rorgans affected and the presence or absence of associated peripheral    \rneuritis .                                                              \r'),
 (120,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'early effects of digitalis on central hemodynamics in normal subjects . \r  the intravenous administration of lanatoside c in 7 normal subjects   \rhad the following effects..                                             \r  1. an early significant reduction of heart rate .                     \r  2. a significant transient reduction of cardiac output .              \r  3. a significant increase of the stroke volume initially accompanied  \rby a significant rise of the end-diastolic volume with unchanged        \rsystolic rate of emptying . the increase of end-diastolic volume seems  \rto be related to the lengthening of the diastolic filling period . later\ron, the systolic emptying rate increases, and the ventricular volumes   \rdecrease, suggesting an inotropic effect of the drug .                  \r  4. a significant increase of pulmonary blood volume, parallel to the  \rincrease of the stroke volume, suggestive of a passive relation between \rthe two variables .                                                     \r'),
 (121,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'measurement of pericardial fluid correlated with the i -cholografin and \rihsa heart scan .                                                       \r  in 23 patients undergoing open-heart surgery in whom the pericardial  \rcontents were accurately measured, and in 11 additional patients        \rexamined at autopsy or by pericardiocentesis, isotopic photoscans of the\rheart were made and the results were correlated .                       \r  the most accurate means of diagnosis of pericardial effusion was found\rto be the ratio of the maximum transverse cardiac diameters on scan and \rroentgenogram . in patients with less than 100 cc of pericardial fluid  \rthis ratio was greater than 0.80, and it was less than this in cases of \reffusion of 200 cc or more .                                            \r  measurement of the difference of these diameters, and visible         \rseparation of the cardiac blood pool from the pulmonary vasculature and \rliver aided in the diagnosis .                                          \r  pericardial effusions of 200-300 cc or greater can be detected by     \risotopic photoscanning . although cardiac dilatation and/or hypertrophy \rdecrease the sensitivity of the technique somewhat, a definite diagnosis\rof pericardial effusion can be made even when cardiomegaly exists .     \r'),
 (122,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'aneurysm of the membranous septum .                                     \r  1. aneurysms of the membranous septum are relatively rare lesions     \rpresumably developing on a congenital basis . these aneurysms originate \rin the left ventricle immediately beneath the aortic valve and bulge    \rinto the right ventricle, the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve or  \rinto the right atrium .                                                 \r  2. many of these aneurysms do not produce symptoms . others may cause \rright ventricular outflow tract obstruction or may rupture and result in\ra septal defect . the resulting shunt will be from the left ventricle   \rinto the right atrium or ventricle .                                    \r  3. an aneurysm of the membranous septum may be an isolated abnormality\ror be associated with other congenital cardiac defects, particularly    \raortic valvular insufficiency . membranous septal aneurysms may be the  \rsite of bacterial endocarditis or thrombus formation .                  \r  4. aneurysms resembling those arising from the membranous septum may  \roccur as part of the complex of deformities produced by an endocardial  \rcushion defect . however, the angiographic features diagnostic of a     \rcushion defect can still be recognized .                                \r  5. the presence of a septal aneurysm can be established only by       \rangiocardiography . the diagnostic features as seen on the left         \rventricular angiocardiogram are presented .                             \r'),
 (123,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'distribution of transfused tritiated cytidine-labeled leukocytes and red\rcells in the bone marrow of normal and irradiated rat .                 \r  in normal rats and after total body irradiation with 550 r of x-rays, \rthe fate in the bone marrow of labeled nucleated and red cells of       \rtransfused peripheral blood was observed autoradiographically .         \r  labeled nucleated cells, most of which were lymphocyte-like cells,    \rreadily migrated into the marrow parenchyma in normal animals (2 cells/ \r1,000 parenchymal cells/hr.) . following irradiation to at least 27-51  \rhr., this migration appeared to be relatively increased . beyond this   \rtime, parenchymal areas were more difficult to be defined as such .     \r  labeled red cells were rarely observed to enter parenchyma despite the\rpresence of nonlabeled erythrocytes within the parenchymal structure    \rafter irradiation .                                                     \r  the vascular bed following irradiation increased greatly as the       \rparenchyma diminished to a minimum of less than 10 percent control at 75\rhr . despite these changes in the architecture of the marrow, the       \raverage density of labeled cells per area of marrow corresponded to     \rvalues expected on the assumption of a free-flowing circulation . the   \rtechnique used at present did not allow us to distinguish, at all times,\rbetween a free-flowing circulation through intact sinusoids or through  \rareas in which the sinusoidal wall, as such, was destroyed .            \r'),
 (124,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'factors limiting survival after circulatory occlusion under hypothermia \rand hyperbaric oxygenation .                                            \r  thirty minutes of circulatory occlusion with mild hypothermia and     \rhyperbaric oxygen ventilation resulted in a mortality of 83.3 percent in\ranimals . when coronary perfusion from a reservoir was added, the       \rmortality rate was 22 percent . ventricular fibrillation was much more  \reasily reversed after coronary perfusion . there was no evidence of     \rbrain damage in survivors which leads to the conclusion that the brain  \rtolerates circulatory arrest better than the heart under these          \rconditions .                                                            \r'),
 (125,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of hypothermia on circulatory reflexes in the human .        \r  total circulatory occlusion and release result in hemodynamic         \rphenomena which provide an index of integrity of some cardiovascular    \rreflexes . these include carotid sinus and aortic baroceptors,          \rarteriolar vasomotor tone, and venomotor reactivity .                   \r  baroceptor depression appears at a more moderate level of cooling than\rdoes the sympathetic, vasomotor, depression . below 28 degrees c. both  \rare significantly depressed, although probably not totally abolished .  \r  the level of 28 degrees c. is a critical physiological level and may  \rrepresent an important limit in the clinical use of hypothermia .       \r'),
 (126,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies in perfusion hypothermia with special reference to /deep        \rhypothermia/ and circulatory arrest .                                   \r  1. perfusion hypothermia produces large temperature gradients within  \rthe body since organs are cooled roughly in proportion to their basal   \rblood flows . the difference between the coldest and the warmest portion\rof the body after 30 minutes of perfusion exceeds 25 c .                \r  2. the average body temperature, which provides a proper measure of   \rtotal body cooling, may be calculated from the arteriovenous temperature\rdifference and the extracorporeal flow rate .                           \r  3. true /deep/ hypothermia is not obtainable by reasonable periods of \rperfusion alone .                                                       \r  4. an important rise of core temperatures occurs during circulatory   \rarrest in hypothermia because of relatively high average body           \rtemperature .                                                           \r  5. high average body temperatures lead to continuing production of    \rlactic acid in muscle tissue, whereas low core temperatures impair      \rlactic acid metabolism . thus metabolic acidosis is progressive in      \rprolonged perfusion hypothermia, and is accentuated by total circulatory\rarrest . progressive acidosis may be minimized by uniform profound      \rcooling by combining external with perfusion hypothermia .              \r  6 diluents appear to have little effect on total body heat exchange   \rduring perfusion cooling .                                              \r  7. perfusion warming has a differentially greater effect on core      \rorgans . though these are readily brought to a normal range, much of the\ranimal may remain cold .                                                \r'),
 (127,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'application of the emission spectrograph to the analytical needs of the \rindustrial hygiene laboratory .                                         \r  examples of unique applications of the principles of emission         \rspectroscopy to industrial hygiene problems are provided . a discussion \rof qualitative, semiquantitative and quantitative methods of            \rspectrographic analysis is presented . these methods include            \rrepresentative applications which are made for the analysis of the      \rmetallic constituents of body tissues and fluids from human and animal  \rsubjects, industrial process materials, ores, and environmental dusts   \rand fumes . brief descriptions of sample preparation techniques required\rfor successful analyses are also presented .                            \r'),
 (128,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nickel carbonyl.. its detection and potential for formation .           \r  recent recommendations for control of nickel carbonyl exposures have  \rbeen considered in the design of a simple, sensitive field method for   \rsampling nickel carbonyl in air and process gases . the method involves \rcollection in dilute aqueous hcl, ph adjustment, nickel complex         \rdevelopment with alpha-furildioxime, and extraction with chloroform .   \rcolor intensity is compared visually (or for greater accuracy,          \rspectrophotometrically) with liquid standards . sensitivities on the    \rorder of 0.001 ppm are obtainable . a detailed development of the       \rthermodynamics associated with the formation of nickel carbonyl is also \rpresented to show the maximum concentrations of nickel carbonyl that may\rbe formed over a wide range of co concentrations, temperatures and      \rpressures .                                                             \r'),
 (129,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'polarographic determination of heavy metals in air samples .            \r  the polarograph possesses the required sensitivity and specificity to \rmake it the method of choice for analysis for a variety of heavy metals \rin air . two commercial polarographs are compared and both found        \radequate on the basis of analysis for lead . determinations may be made \rfor antimony, copper, lead, cadmium, chromium, nickel, cobalt,          \rmanganese, and others .                                                 \r'),
 (130,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the inorganic constituents of human teeth and bone examined by x-ray    \remission spectrography .                                                \r  x-ray emission spectrography has been applied to study of the         \relemental composition of human teeth, enamel, dentine and bone . the    \rmaterial consisted of eight crushed teeth, enamel and dentine powder    \rseparated from eighteen teeth, and four pieces of buccal cortical       \rmandibular bone . the teeth did not have fillings . the whole material  \rcontained nineteen elements, of which the main ones were calcium and    \rphosphorus . in all the samples of tooth material, there were found ca, \rp, cl, fe, zn, sr and k, and the bone also contained ni . the time      \rneeded for a semi-quantitative analysis compares very favourably with   \rthat needed for other methods .                                         \r'),
 (131,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a kinetic study of nickel(ii), complexes of sulfur-containing amino acid\r  the rate expression for the ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (edta)    \rligand exchange reaction with nickel(cysteine) is.. rate = k(complex) + \rkedta (complex)(edta) . this two-term rate expression is characteristic \rof square planar complexes and agrees with the square planar            \rconfiguration of ni(cysteine) reported on the basis of spectral studies \rthe edta-independent term of the rate expression is an acid-catalyzed \rterm and can be written k (h) (complex) . the value of kn is 2.5 x 10 m \rsec while the value of kedta is only on the order of 10 -10 m sec . the \redta reaction with ni(cysteine) methyl ester) is very similar to the    \rreaction with ni(cysteine) . when the sulfur-containing amino acid      \rligand contains a thiol ether, the kinetic differences are striking .   \r  ligand exchange reactions of edta, triethylenetetramine, and          \rdiethylenetriamine with nickel-methionine complexes are several orders  \rof magnitude faster and give products that are mixed-ligand complexes . \rthe results of this kinetic study of amino acid complexes containing    \rsulfhydryl and thiol ether sulfur groups support other studies at       \requilibrium which suggest sulfur coordination and square planar         \rcomplexes for the sulfhydryl groups and octahedral complexes with no    \rsulfur coordination for thiol ethers .                                  \r'),
 (132,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the action of metal ions on tobacco mosaic virus ribonucleic acid .     \r  added transition metal ions stabilize the secondary structure of      \rtobacco mosaic virus ribonucleic acid (tmv-rna) as evidenced by a       \rreduction in the absorbancy change of heated nucleic acid solutions . in\rspite of this stabilization of secondary structure, heating in the      \rpresence of metal ions results in the loss of biological activity due to\rthe hydrolysis of phosphodiester bonds . thus, all heavy metal ions of  \rthe iib and first-transition elements studied caused a rapid loss of    \rbiological activity of tmv-rna at ph 6.5 and 65 . calcium and magnesium \rions, while not affecting secondary structure at 65 and ph 8.5, caused a\rrapid loss of biological activity . at ph 5.8 and room temperature lead \rions catalyzed the hydrolysis of rna to i\'(3\')- mononucleotides,. on    \rlong standing, nucleosides were formed .                                \r'),
 (133,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chromium, lead, cadmium, nickel and titanium in mice.. effect on        \rmortality, tumors and tissue levels .                                   \r  about 700 mice were given throughout their lives 5 ppm cadmium, lead, \rchromium, nickel or titanium in drinking water while fed a diet         \rdeficient in cadmium and low in other metals . tissue concentrations    \rcomparable to those of man were observed . sex differences appeared .   \rmortality of females was unaffected . mortality of males on cadmium,    \rlead and nickel was increased compared with that of the chromium group, \rand of those on cadmium and lead compared with the controls . longevity \rof the oldest 10 of both sexes was less in lead and titanium groups, and\rof males in cadmium group, compared with controls . no metal was        \rcarcinogenic,. incidence of tumors in males on cadmium and lead, and in \rfemales given nickel was decreased . body weights at death were greater \rin titanium, chromium and lead groups . large increments of titanium,   \rmoderate increments of cadmium and nickel, and lesser increments of     \rchromium and lead were observed in 5 organs, compared with controls .   \rhigher concentrations of cadmium and titanium occurred in younger mice  \rand the other metals did not increase markedly in tissues with age . all\rmetals except chromium exhibited one or more signs of innate toxicity . \r'),
 (134,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'synergistic effects between antioxidants and selenium or vitamin e .    \r  several antioxidants when fed to chicks at relatively high levels in  \ran experimental diet were ineffective in preventing the exudates and    \rmortality from a combined deficiency of selenium and vitamin e . some of\rthe compounds were toxic, as evidenced by sudden death or subcutaneous  \rhemorrhages . when amounts of either selenite or a-tocopheryl acetate,  \rwhich individually had little or no effect on symptoms, were given with \rthe antioxidants signs of deficiency and mortality were prevented, and  \rtoxicity also was eliminated .                                          \r'),
 (135,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the expression of urine analysis results -dash  observations on the use \rof a specific gravity correction .                                      \r  urine analyses are very useful for measuring the extent of exposure to\rcertain toxic substances . the types of specimen obtainable from persons\remployed in industry, and the effect of concentration variations are    \rdiscussed . in expressing the results of analysis it is shown that a    \rconcentration correction is essential . the correction based on specific\rgravity is the easiest to apply . the mean specific gravity for persons \rresident in the u.k. has been found to be around 1.016, a figure        \rconsiderably lower than the mean of 1.024 used by many workers          \r(particularly in the u.s.a.) . the implications of this on the results  \rof urine analysis are indicated .                                       \r'),
 (136,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'activation and inactivation of p-hydroxyphenylpyruvate hydroxylase .    \r  1. p-hydroxyphenylpyruvate hydroxylase (ec 1.99.1.14) is reversibly   \rinactivated by dialysis, storage, purification involving ammonium       \rsulfate fractionation, and treatment with oxidizing agents . the        \rinactive enzyme is reactivated by various reducing agents .             \r  2. metal-chelating agents inhibited enzyme activity . 1,10-           \rphenanthroline and 4,7-diphenyl-1,10-phenanthroline (fe sensitive)      \rstrongly inhibited, but 2,9-dimethyl-1,10-phenanthroline (cu specific)  \rdid not . 1,10-phenanthroline-treated p-hydroxyphenylpyruvate hydroxyl- \rase was reactivated specifically by fe in the presence of a reducing    \ragent, indicating a role for fe in enzyme activity .                    \r  3. nonoxidative sulfhydryl reagents did not materially inhibit the    \renzyme activity under various conditions .                              \r'),
 (137,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'responses of b. subtilis (atcc 558) to streptomycin .                   \r  to observe in detail the influence of streptomycin on the growth of sm\rdependent type, the author chose b. subtilis (atcc 558) and made        \rexperiments on its responses to streptomycin, with special reference to \rthe relation of the sm concentration with spore formation of its sm     \rdependent type together with germination and outgrowth of the spores    \rformed . the results are as follows .                                   \r  1. among 18x10 cells of wild type of b. subtilis (atcc 558) about     \r3,200 cells of sm resistant and one cell of sm dependent are found as   \rits mutant .                                                            \r  2. b. substilis (atcc 558) shows normal growth at sm concentration    \rbelow 10 r/ml, but the growth declines rapidly between sm 10 r/ml-20 r/m\rl, and the growth stops entirely at sm concentration 20 r/ml .          \r  3. sm resistant type grows well between sm 0.1 r/ml-sm 2,000 r/ml, the\rgrowth declines rapidly at about sm 10,000 r/ml .                       \r  4. sm dependent type shows normal growth between sm 10,000 r/ml-20 r/m\rl, the growth get worth below sm 10 r/ml, and the cell shape elongates  \rseveral times, at sm below 1 r/ml each cell becomes filamentous form and\rhas several ten times length of normal cell, as if the cells have       \rstopped to divide at low sm concentration .                             \r  6. the germination and outgrowth of spores of the sm dependent type   \rslow down with decline of sm concentration, but the germinated spores   \rgrow in normal forms until sm concentration reaches 7.8 r/ml, then the  \rgermination becomes much slower, and the cells grow in filamentous forms\ror irregular forms . at extremely low sm concentration both germination \rand outgrowth nearly stop .                                             \r'),
 (138,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'phospholipids of the bovine, rabbit, and human lens .                   \r  the phospholipids of bovine, rabbit, and human lenses contain cephalin\rlecithin, and sphingomyelin but their distribution differs with each    \rspecies . there is suggestive evidence that there may also be           \rplasmalogen in the lens, but, if so, it represents a minor phospholipid \rcomponent . the fatty acid composition of each phospholipid differs in  \reach species, with most of the differences centering around 16..0,      \r18..1, and 24..1 .                                                      \r'),
 (139,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'surgical aspects of heart disease in pregnancy .                        \r  the ideal management of the pregnant woman with heart disease is      \rmedical, if feasible . the operative experience with mitral valvulotomy \rin pregnancy has expanded . this procedure is now indicated when        \rprogressive cardiac disability develops during the first or second      \rtrimester and when the proven dominant lesion is mitral stenosis . when \rother lesions are present, especially those requiring pump oxygenator   \rperfusion, the risk must be carefully measured . damage to the fetus may\rresult from reduced placental blood flow .                              \r'),
 (140,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'traumatic lesions of the optic chiasma.. a report of four cases .       \r  case histories of four patients who suffered severe head trauma       \rresulting in complete bitemporal hemianopia are presented . the optic   \rchiasm was visualized in only one patient . it was markedly swollen and \rdisintegrated . this appearance was consistent with multiple minute     \rtears of the crossed fibres in the median sagittal plane . other        \rtheories to explain the bitemporal field defect are discussed .         \r'),
 (141,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lung cancer.. an evolutionary approach .                                \r  lung cancer is presented as an example of somatic mutation . in       \rcontrast to previous theories the following are defined.. (a) the major \rgrowth controlling mechanism,. (b) the mutation found in cancer,. and   \r(c) the environmental changes in the lungs of patients who smoke        \rcigarettes which can select this mutant .                               \r'),
 (142,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effects of electrophoretically separated lens proteins on lens      \rregeneration in diemyctylus viridescens .                               \r  in the present study, lenses were removed from the eyes of adult      \ranesthetized newts, macerated in 0.03 m borate buffer at ph 8.6, and    \rseparated by starch gel electrophoresis . upon staining with amido black\r10-b, seven distinct staining areas appeared in the blocks . three bands\rmoved toward the anode, and three toward the cathode . in addition, a   \rseventh moiety represented by a smear of material moved toward the anode\rone millimeter times five tenths millimeter plugs were removed from   \reach of these areas and were placed into freshly lentectomized eyes .   \rplugs from most strongly positive and most weakly negative proteins     \rinhibited lens regeneration . in addition, plugs from the area          \rcontaining the weakly negative protein induced either lenses with       \raberrant polarity or double centered lenses with centers of opposed     \rpolarity . all other protein bands had no significant effect on         \rregeneration .                                                          \r  in addition to the above experiments, homogenates and                 \rproteinasedigested homogenates of lenses were injected into eyes        \rfollowing lentectomy . three 5-ul samples were injected in each case    \rover a six day period . injection of the plain homogenate stimulated    \rlens regeneration markedly, while the proteinase destroyed the          \rstimulatory activity .                                                  \r  theoretical considerations of the above data are discussed .          \r'),
 (143,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'enzymic synthesis of deoxyribonucleic acid xviii. the repair of         \rpartially single-stranded dna templates by dna polymerase .             \r  a partially single-stranded dna, prepared by limited digestion of each\rstrand with exonuclease iii, can be restored to its native, fully       \rdouble-stranded structure by escherichia coli dna polymerase . the rate \rof synthesis observed in the repair of such a partially degraded primer \rin the polymerase system is faster than that seen with a native dna .   \rthe newly synthesized dna is covalently attached to the primer . the    \rfully repaired dna resembles the original native dna as judged by its   \rappearance in electron micrographs, cscl density-gradient analysis,     \rdenaturability and genetic activity . dna synthesis which follows the   \rrepair phase produces a structure that is not covalently linked to the  \rprimer and resembles, in its nondenaturability, branched appearance, and\rlack of genetic activity, the product obtained with a native dna primer \r(schildkraut, richardson + kornberg, 1964) .                            \r'),
 (144,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on the mechanism of genetic recombination in transforming bacillus      \rsubtilis .                                                              \r  the molecular fate of transforming dna in competent bacillus subtilis \rhas been studied . the physical differentiation of transforming dna and \rthe genetic material of recipient bacteria was effected by employing the\risotopes n and p . competent bacteria labeled with n and p were allowed \rto incorporate n p-labeled transforming dna intracellularly . dna was   \risolated from these recipient cells and centrifuged in cesium chloride .\ranalysis of drop fractions collected at equilibrium showed the presence \rof radioactivity in a region of density corresponding to recipient dna .\rmaterial contribution from donor dna to the resident dna did not occur  \rwhen genetically inert bacillus cereus dna was substituted for          \rhomologous dna . it was concluded that radioactivity appearing in the   \runlabeled resident dna was not the result of degradation of input (     \rp)dna and subsequent incorporation by normal metabolic processes . since\rsingle-stranded dna of donor origin was not detected, nor was there     \revidence for the non-specific aggregation of donor and recipient dna, it\rwas concluded that the observed physical association of transforming and\rrecipient dna occurs as a result of genetic recombination in transformed\rb. subtilis .                                                           \r'),
 (145,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'physical and biological studies on transforming dna .                   \r  bacillus subtilis transforming dna prepared by the method described,  \rhas an average molecular weight of 11.6 million . the dna is            \rheterogeneous, as judged by chemical composition, thermo-spectral and   \rpyenographic properties . these properties have been used to fractionate\rsome of the biologically active molecules which show higher specific    \ractivities in transforming respective auxotrophs .                      \r'),
 (146,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparison of mutation and inactivation rates induced in bacteriophage  \rand transforming dna by various mutagens .                              \r  inactivation and mutation rates were measured for t4 phages and       \rbacillus subtilis transforming dna treated by low ph, nitrous acid, or  \rhydroxylamine at different temperatures . the frequency of mutants      \rincreased linearly with time for all three agents, whereas the logarithm\rof survival gave a linear plot only for nitrous acid and low ph . an    \rarrhenius plot showed the same slopes for both inactivation and mutation\rrates after treatment with low ph or nitrous acid,. for the latter agent\rthe slope remained unaltered even when the dna was treated in the       \rdenaturated state . in contrast, mutation rates obtained after the      \rexposure to hydroxylamine differed greatly for native or denatured dna, \rphage t4 being intermediate .                                           \r  treatment by low ph or nitrous acid interrupted the genetic linkage   \rbetween tryptophan and histidine, the interrupting hits being about 1/3 \ras frequent as lethal hits, independent of the temperature .            \r'),
 (147,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'autolysis of bacillus subtilis by glucose depletion .                   \r  in cultures in minimal medium, rapid lysis of cells of bacillus       \rsubtilis was observed as soon as the carbon source, e.g. glucose, had   \rbeen completely consumed . the cells died and ultraviolet-absorbing     \rmaterial was excreted in the medium . the results suggest that the cells\rlyse because of the presence of autolytic enzymes . in the presence of  \rglucose the damage to the cell wall caused by these enzymes is repaired \rimmediately .                                                           \r'),
 (148,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'plasma 17-hydroxycorticosteroids and 17-oxosteroids in patients with    \rbreast cancer and in normal women .                                     \r  (1) 17-hydroxycorticosteroids (17-ohcs) and 17-oxosteroids were       \rmeasured in the plasma of normal women, patients with early breast      \rcancer and in patients with advanced metastatic disease .               \r  (2) the mean plasma 17-ohcs level was found to be normal in the early \rstages of the disease but was raised in the advanced disease . in both  \rgroups of patients the variance was significantly greater than in normal\rwomen .                                                                 \r  (3) the mean plasma 17-oxosteroid level in both early and advanced    \rbreast cancer was not significantly different from the normal level but \rthe variance was increased .                                            \r  (4) there is a significant correlation between the plasma 17-ohcs and \r17-oxosteroids in normal women which was not found in the cancer        \rpatients .                                                              \r  (5) in patients with advanced breast cancer, the levels of plasma 17- \roxosteroids were significantly correlated with the amounts of 11-deoxy- \r17-oxosteroids found in the urine . there was no correlation between    \rplasma and urinary 17-ohcs .                                            \r  (6) the physiological significance of these findings is discussed .   \r'),
 (149,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hormone therapy in metastatic breast cancer.. clinical response and     \rurinary gonadotrophins .                                                \r  the total urinary gonadotrophin output of a group of post menopausal  \rwomen with metastatic breast carcinoma undergoing hormone therapy, which\rin every case initially consisted of treatment with diethylstilboestrol,\rdes (ca. 20 mg/d), has been studied for periods varying from seven      \rmonths to 31/2 years .                                                  \r  no correlation between gonadotrophin output and clinical response was \rfound, except that in all cases showing objective regression urinary    \rgonadotrophin remained low throughout the remission period . a low level\rof gonadotrophin output was not, however, necessarily indicative of a   \rgood clinical remission . following withdrawal of des, and independent  \rof the period of therapy, recovery to pre-treatment levels was the rule \rrather than the exception .                                             \r  a small group of patients maintained on a lower dose of des (3-5 mg/d)\rshowed the same degree of suppression of urinary output as those        \rreceiving 20 mg/d, and several of these exhibited objective remissions .\r  the study has emphasised the importance of site specificity in the    \rresponse to hormone therapy, and underlines the difficulties of relating\rthe clinical response of the patient as a whole to changes in hormonal  \renvironment .                                                           \r'),
 (150,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'plasma androgens in women i. normal and non-hirsute females,            \roophorectomized and adrenalectomized patients .                         \r  1. in a group of 20 normal non-hirsute females age 17 to 38, 18 non-  \rhirsute patients with varied genito-urinary disorders, 8 oophorectomized\rand or adrenalectomized patients plasma testosterone was measured by the\rmethod of finkelstein et al. (1961) . conjugated androsterone and       \rconjugated dhea were determined by a modified method of migeon + plager \r(1955) .                                                                \r  2. mean baseline values in normal females were .11 .06 ug/100 ml      \rtestosterone, 11.8 5.5 ug/100 ml conjugated androsterone, and 29.5 15.5 \rug/100 ml conjugated dhea . no significant response to hcg could be seen\rdexamethasone affected the conjugated dhea significantly, but did not \rseem to affect conjugated androsterone or testosterone .                \r  3. the non-hirsute patients showed essentially the same pattern . an  \reffect of dexamethasone on the levels of conjugated androsterone was    \rdemonstrated .                                                          \r  4. oophorectomized women had baseline values for the conjugates in the\rrange of normals . testosterone, however, was low with an average of    \r .016 ug/100 ml . in the adrenalectomized patients no androgens were     \rdetectable .                                                            \r'),
 (151,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'oophorectomy and cortisone treatment as a method of eliminating         \roestrogen production in patients with breast cancer .                   \r  the urinary excretion of oestrone, oestradiol-17b, oestriol, and 17-  \rhydroxycorticosteroids has been estimated in 55 premenopausal and 91    \rpostmenopausal women with breast cancer at various stages of the disease\rbefore therapy . the depletion of oestrogen excretion caused by         \roophorectomy combined with cortisone treatment was studied in the       \rpatients with metastasising breast tumours (32 premenopausal and 56     \rpostmenopausal subjects) .                                              \r  patients with disseminating breast cancer excreted significantly      \rlarger quantities of oestriol than healthy women of the same age,       \rwhether pre- or postmenopausal . the excretion of oestrone and          \roestradiol-17b was similar in cancer patients and healthy women of      \rcorresponding age .                                                     \r  oophorectomy reduced the oestrogen excretion not only in premenopausal\rsubjects but also in quite a number of postmenopausal patients,         \rparticularly in those who were still excreting significant amounts of   \roestrogens . this decrease in the oestrogen output was transient and was\rfollowed by a compensatory increase, possibly of adrenal origin .       \r  cortisone administered within a month after the oophorectomy at a     \rdosage of 50 mg per day rapidly depressed the secondary rise in the     \roestrogen output to a level of about 4 to 5 ug/24 h irrespective of the \rage of the patient . this excretion level was unchanged as long as      \rcortisone was given in an adequate dose, but increased rapidly when the \rcortisone treatment was discontinued .                                  \r  oophorectomy combined with adequate cortisone treatment seems to offer\ran alternative to the extensive surgical porcedures undertaken to       \reliminate oestrogen production in breast cancer patients .              \r'),
 (152,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some reactions of cytotoxic antibodies against previously unknown mouse \risoantigens .                                                           \r  the antiserum produced in c3h/he against c3h/st lymphosarcoma 6c3hed  \rcontains a mixture of at least two antibodies of different properties   \rand specificities . anti h-5a is a hemagglutinating antibody removed by \rabsorption with red cells and many tissues . anti v is a cytotoxin      \rreacting with c3h/st tissue and 6c3hed but not with red cells.          \r  the reciprocal antiserum c3h/st anti c3h/he sarcoma mc1m is more      \rcomplex . it contains the hemagglutinin anti h-6a and a variety of      \rcytotoxins . one appears to be specific for c3h/he tissues and the      \r   tumor mc1m . another reacts with antigens on the c3h/go carcinoma    \rbp8. two additional cytotoxins may also be present .                    \r  immunization between sublines of the same inbred strain can result in \rthe production of a variety of antibodies directed against unrelated    \rantigens present on even long transplanted cells . the significance of  \r'),
 (153,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on the value of thymectomy in adult mice as a means of potentiating the \rimmunosuppressive action of melphalan (l-phenylalanine mustard) .       \r  thymectomy has been found to be ineffective as a means of potentiating\rthe immunosuppressive action of melphalan in adult cba-p mice challenged\rwith a-strain mammary carcinoma transplants . this was true when the    \rthymectomy was performed 2 days, 4 weeks or 7 weeks prior to injection  \rof a single dose (15 mg/kg body weight) of melphalan, administered 24   \rhours prior to tumour transplantation, and also when thymectomy was     \rcombined with multiple doses of melphalan given before and after tumour \rtransplantation . these findings are discussed .                        \r'),
 (154,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on the kinetics of transplantation immunity .                   \r  using the parameter of the number of tumor cells necessary to produce \rs.c. tumors in allogeneic animals at varying intervals after antigenic  \rstimulation, immunity was found to be in force as early as 2 days after \rprimary antigenic stimulation . it reached a peak at 8-10 days and had  \rlargely subsided by the end of a month . this method was also applied to\rthe quantitative study of the onset, degree, and duration of immunity   \relicited by skin grafts . the results obtained with inocula of large    \rnumbers of tumor cells (10 percent) were comparable to those obtained   \rwith massive skin grafts .                                              \r  the differences in the degree of antigenic stimulation resulting from \rdifferent routes of inoculation were studied . it was found that the    \rintradermal (i.d.) route of inoculation resulted in a more intense      \rantigenic stimulation than the s.c. route . when both routes of         \rinoculation were used simultaneously the pattern of growth of the s.c.  \rtumor was influenced by the i.d. inoculation.. an i.d. inoculum given 24\ror 48 hr earlier caused marked suppression of growth of the s.c. tumor, \rwhile when an i.d. inoculation was preceded by an s.c. inoculation,     \ralthough there was an appreciable effect on the growth size, the growth \rcurves of the 2 tumors were always parallel .                           \r  there was no correlation between cytotoxic activity and the degree of \rimmunity in force at a given time .                                     \r'),
 (155,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evidence for an immunological reaction of the host directed against its \rown actively growing primary tumor .                                    \r  cells isolated from primary benzo(a)pyrene-induced fibrosarcomas in   \rrats of a pure line were tested for their ability to grow as autografts \rwhen injected back into the autochthonous host . the autograft did not  \rtake if the primary tumor had been removed but grew occasionally in     \ranimals in which the major part of the tumor was left . in every        \rinstance the sarcoma cells grew when injected into syngeneic recipients \rin these recipients the growth of the sarcoma cells was prevented or  \rretarded when they were mixed in vitro, prior to injection, with spleen \rcells from animals that had been immunized against the tumor .          \rautochthonous spleen cells taken from the animal with the tumor behaved \rin this test like those from immunized animals as long as the spleen was\rtaken 3 weeks after removal of the tumor . when the spleen and tumor    \rwere removed at the same time, however, autochthonous spleen cells did  \rnot behave like spleen cells from immunized animals and did not         \rinterfere with the growth of the tumor . the results of both the        \rautograft and spleen cell experiments suggest that rats react actively  \ragainst their own growing primary tumors, but that the tumor exhausts   \rthe supply of lymphocytes responsible for this reaction . after the     \rtumor is removed, the concentration of antitumor lymphocytes in the     \rspleen builds up and the animals can reject an autograft .-j nat cancer \rinst 36.. 29-35, 1966 .                                                 \r'),
 (156,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a comparison of the cytologic effects of leurosine methiodide and       \rvinblastine in tissue culture .                                         \r  comparison of the degree and duration of arrest of metaphases in      \rtissue culture cells by leurosine methiodide and vinblastine was made,. \rcolchicine and demecolcine were included for reference purposes . all   \rfour drugs produced a similar cytologic effect, but vinblastine was most\ractive and remained active for the longest period of time .             \r'),
 (157,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparison of central aortic and peripheral artery pressure curves .    \r  brachial artery and central aortic pressures were compared in 50      \rconsecutive patients subjected to retrograde left heart catheterization \rin order to re-emphasize the fact that the two pressures are not        \rnecessarily identical . in 43 cases the systemic systolic pressure peaks\rexceeded those in the central aorta while in seven these pressures were \requal . the average pressure difference was 22.6 mm. hg . the greatest  \rdifferences occurred in cases of aortic regurgitation and could be      \rextreme, the brachial artery systolic pressure exceeding that in the    \raorta by more than 100 mm. hg in some instances . the least differences \roccurred in cases of aortic stenosis but significant differences        \roccasionally existed, leading to erroneous estimation of valve orifice  \rsize if the systemic rather than the aortic systolic pressure was used .\r'),
 (158,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes in sphingosine and fatty acid components of the gangliosides in \rdeveloping rat and human brain .                                        \r  rat brain increases in weight after birth in three stages.. (i)       \rrapidly for the first 2 weeks, (ii) at a lower rate from 2 to 5 weeks,  \rand (iii) at a still lower rate from 5 weeks to 5 months . during the   \rsucceeding period, designated iv, it maintains constant weight up to 1  \ryear of age . brain ganglioside content increased linearly during i and \rii, more slowly during iii, and diminished during iv . the appearance of\rmeasurable amounts of brain sphingomyelin and cerebroside succeeded that\rof ganglioside .                                                        \r  ceramide with c -sphingosine and c fatty acid was found in a large    \rproportion of all three sphingolipids upon their first appearance in    \rmeasurable quantity . c fatty acid in cerebroside rapidly declined to a \rnegligible level, while in gangliosides and sphingomyelin it declined   \rslowly but remained the major fatty acid component .                    \r  cerebrosides and sphingomyelin contained c -sphingosine almost        \rexclusively at all stages of rat brain growth . gangliosides contained c\r-sphingosine almost exclusively at birth, but subsequently accumulated c\r-sphingosine until they had nearly equal quantities of each base type . \r  changes in human brain gangliosides resemble those in rat . in        \rtay-sachs disease, gangliosides have c -sphingosine predominantly, and a\rhigh content of c fatty acid .                                          \r'),
 (159,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of the generalized shwartzman reaction induced by diet vi.      \reffects of pregnancy on lipid composition of serum and tissues .        \r  pregnancy induced profound alterations in the lipid composition of    \rserum and tissues . (1) there is an elevation of total serum lipid,     \rphospholipid, triglyceride, free fatty acid and cholesterol,. (2) while \rthe total lipid of the liver and kidney are increased, that of the depot\rfat is decreased,. (3) palmitate and oleate are increased in serum and  \rliver,. (4) arachidonate and stearate are decreased in serum and liver,.\rand (5) placentas contain more stearate than the other organs of the    \rpregnant rat and also have a higher water content . the decrease in     \rdepot total fat,. elevation of serum, liver and kidney total fat,. and  \relevation of serum free fatty acids suggest that pregnancy induced      \rmobilization of depot fat . the increase in proportion of liver and     \rserum palmitate suggests that pregnancy induces increased lipogenesis   \rfrom the acetate pool . the appearance of an increased amount of        \rlong-chain fatty acids in the liver may be due to the increased intake  \rof dietary fat . the decrease in arachidonate and stearate in serum and \rliver suggests a relative decrease in mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis\r'),
 (160,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electron microscopy of the bovine lung.. the normal blood-air barrier . \r  lungs of 20 healthy, mature cattle were fixed in oso , embedded in a  \rpolyester resin, and studied via electron microscopy . the blood-air    \rbarrier was widely variable in thickness and consistency . there was a  \rcontinuous epithelial alveolar lining . the cytoplasm of some of the    \repithelial cells contained membrane-bound aggregates of granules which  \rmay be secretory structures . the epithelium rested on a basement       \rmembrane, which in turn was continuous with or rested on an adjacent    \rcapillary endothelial basement membrane, or continued into merging      \rconnective tissue . the capillary endothelium was not fenestrated,. it  \rwas a continuous cellular membrane . both the epithelium and endothelium\rcontained numerous caveolae and pinocytotic vesicles . cells of the     \ralveolar wall included fibroblasts, lymphocytes, macrophages, and an    \roccasional mast cell . very little elastin was observed .               \r'),
 (161,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a sensitive and specific fluorescence assay for tissue serotonin .      \r  a sensitive and specific method for the estimation of serotonin in    \rbiological materials is described . in this method, serotonin is reacted\rwith ninhydrin to form a product whose fluorescence is eight times more \rintense than the native fluorescence of serotonin in strong acid        \rsolution . with this method it is possible to measure serotonin in      \rorgans in which endogenous serotonin had not been previously detected   \rand to study the subcellular distribution of this amine in the rat      \rpineal and adrenal glands .                                             \r'),
 (162,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of ruminal insufflation on cerebral circulation and metabolism  \rin the goat .                                                           \r  the effects of nitrogen insufflation of the cannulated rumen were     \rstudied in 10 goats . parameters which were measured included cerebral  \rblood flow, mean carotid arterial pressure, pressure in the confluence  \rof sinuses, cerebrospinal fluid pressure, blood oxygen and carbon       \rdioxide contents, packed cell volume (pcv), and hemoglobin concentration\rvalues for cerebrovascular resistance and cerebral o utilization were \rcalculated .                                                            \r  increased ruminal pressure had little effect on cerebral blood flow   \rand cerebrovascular resistance . cerebral o utilization was decreased   \rwhen the intraruminal pressure was increased . this decrease was caused \rby a reduction in arterial o content and a consequent decrease in       \rcerebral arteriovenous o difference . mean arterial, venous sinus, and  \rcerebrospinal fluid pressures were increased as the intraruminal        \rpressure was increased . increases in pcv and hemoglobin concentration  \rwere not related to the elevated intraruminal pressure .                \r  central nervous system signs in goats with acute ruminal tympany may  \rbe caused by cerebral hypoxia . the nature of the hypertensive changes  \rassociated with increased ruminal pressure were demonstrated, but due to\rthe influence of multiple factors on fluid compartments, no conclusions \rcould be made about the mechanism of these pressure responses .         \rmechanical factors, however, may be involved .                          \r'),
 (163,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a comparison between inhaled dust and the dust recovered from human     \rlungs .                                                                 \r  experiments on the loss of dust particles during breathing indicate   \rtotal deposition in the respiratory tract,. subjection of the results to\rqualitative arguments may give information about alveolar deposition .  \rmeasurements of insoluble dust recovered post mortem from human lungs   \rgive the absolute retention of dust which was deposited in the alveoli  \rand subsequently shifted, probably to a large extent, to the lymphatic  \rvessels of the lungs .                                                  \r  experimental results for total deposition and absolute retention are  \rdiscussed in connection with the health risk due to inhaling insoluble  \rparticles, such as plutonium dioxide .                                  \r'),
 (164,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dual cation activation of bovine lens autolysis .                       \r  the autolytic activity of bovine lens extracts at 55 c. and ph 7.4 has\rbeen shown to be markedly influenced by the simultaneous presence of    \rmono- and divalent cations . of the cations tested, na at 2.5 to 5 mm . \rand mg at 5 to 10 mm. produce the best activation . the stimulation is  \rsynergistic . on the basis of results obtained here and in other        \rlaboratories, the suggestion is made that this combination of cations   \rmay be required for activation of the neutral proteinase of the lens .  \rin the presence of mg and average physiologic lenticular levels of both \rna and k , autolysis is suppressed to the basal level obtainable in the \rpresence of mg alone .                                                  \r'),
 (165,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nucleic acid metabolism in the lens iii. effect of x-radiation .        \r  a previous communication reported an increased in vivo incorporation  \rof p-32 into the albuminoid rna fraction of the rat lens 6 hours after  \rthe animal had been exposed to x-radiation (1,500 r) .                  \r  in the present study, the in vitro uptake of p-32 and c-14-adenine by \ralbuminoid, ribosomal, and soluble rna fractions of normal and x-       \rirradiated rat lenses was measured . the rna fractions were extracted by\rsodium dodecyl sulfate in 0.9 per cent nacl . the specific rna fractions\rwere also hydrolyzed, chromatographed (on paper), and the activity of   \rthe individual nucleotides (as well as the specific rna fractions) was  \rdetermined . an experiment was also performed in which the capsules were\rremoved (after the 3 hour incubation period) and the activities         \rdetermined in the nucleic acids extracted from the capsules and in the  \rthree rna fractions of the remaining lens matter .                      \r  the results of these experiments indicate that the incorporation of   \rp-32 and c-14-adenine into albuminoid rna was markedly stimulated 1 hour\rafter 1,500 r whole body radiation . there was no significant effect on \rribosomal or soluble fractions .                                        \r  the effect of formaldehyde and heating on x-irradiated albuminoid rna \rwas much less than on the albuminoid rna derived from control animals . \r'),
 (166,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes in dna, rna, and protein synthesis in the developing lens .     \r  lens cell dna, rna, and protein synthesis in the developing mouse eye \rwere studied with the use of tritium-labeled thymidine, uridine, and l- \rleucine and autoradiographic techniques . in the mouse embryonic lens,  \repithelial cells undergoing dna synthesis were found over the entire    \ranterior lens surface . from birth and until the eyes opened the        \rpercentage of epithelial cells undergoing dna synthesis rapidly         \rdecreased . later the percentage of epithelial cells undergoing dna     \rsynthesis was nearly constant as the germinative zone became localized  \rin the lens equator region . rna synthesis occurred in all nucleated    \rcells of the developing lens from the embryonic stage until the eyelids \ropened . with lens maturity the h uridine was incorporated into the rna \rof only the more superficial cells . a similar pattern of tritium       \rincorporation was seen with h l-leucine .                               \r'),
 (167,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'amino acid transport in the lens in relation to sugar cataracts .       \r  the steady state distribution of free amino acids between the lens and\raqueous humor is significantly reduced in diabetic rabbits and also in  \rrats fed rations containing high concentrations of xylose or galactose .\r  the reduction in the level of amino acids in the lens is apparently a \rdirect effect of the high concentration of sugars, but it is doubtful   \rwhether it is related to cataract formation .                           \r'),
 (168,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'visco-elastic properties of the lens .                                  \r  the dynamic visco-elastic properties of human, monkey and rabbit      \rlenses have been measured with a dynamic rheometer . the value for the  \rapparent elastic modulus (young modulus) of the lens was found to be 10 \r-10 dyne/cm in humans and 10 -10 dyne/cm in monkeys and rabbits . the   \rvalue for the loss tangent was 0.3-0.4 in the human lens and 0.3-0.6 in \rrabbit and monkey lenses .                                              \r  elastic moduli and loss tangents of the lenses showed poor dependence \ron temperature at 15 -55 c and on frequency of oscillation at 0.01-25 c/\rs . the lenses showed linear visco-elasticity when the amplitude of     \roscillation was below 0.02 mm, and they showed nonlinear visco-         \relasticity when the amplitude exceeded 0.03 mm .                        \r'),
 (169,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'carbonic anhydrase distribution in rabbit lens .                        \r  the distribution of carbonic anhydrase activity in the mature rabbit  \rlens was determined . the activities in nucleus, cortex, epithelium with\ranterior capsule, anterior capsule, and posterior capsule were,         \rrespectively, 2484 ( 256), 1571 ( 87), 545 ( 93), 159 ( 39) and 65 ( 49)\rmoles co /kg wet tissue wt per hr at 0 c . it was concluded, on the     \rbasis of the available evidence, that carbonic anhydrase cannot play a  \rprimary role in the cation transport system of the lens .               \r'),
 (170,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes in weight and adenosine triphosphate content in the lens of the \rxylose-fed rat .                                                        \r  xylitol and sorbitol accumulated in the lens of the xylose-fed rat two\rdays before loss of adenosine triphosphate, and cataractous changes,    \rwere apparent . the maximum degree of cataract occurred when the level  \rof the polyols was at its highest . regression of cataract was          \raccompanied by decrease in polyol concentration and restoration of the  \rlevel of atp . the lens of the xylose-fed rat did not usually increase  \rin weight .                                                             \r'),
 (171,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'identification of species-specific and organ-specific antigens in lens  \rproteins .                                                              \r  the species-specific and organ-specific antigens of lens were         \rinvestigated by gel diffusion and immunoelectrophoresis techniques . it \rwas found that rabbit antiserum to bovine lens showed cross reaction    \rwith other bovine tissues . these cross-reacting antigens were the b- - \rand y-crystallins . there were two major and a minor organ-specific     \rantigen in lens . both the major antigens had a mobility and were       \ridentified as the a-crystallin of lens .                                \r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (172,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an electron microscopic study of wolffian lens regeneration in the adult\rnewt .                                                                  \r  changes in the morphology of cells during the regenerative tissue     \rtransformation of the pigmented epithelium of the iris into lens in the \radult newt triturus viridescens were studied in ultrathin sections using\rthe electron microscope . in addition, quantitative analyses with       \relectron micrographs were performed . the cells of the normal iris are  \rcharacterized by an abundance of melanin granules, an extensive smooth--\rsurfaced endoplasmic reticulum, and irregular indentations of the       \rnuclear membrane . after lens removal, the first visible changes are    \rdetected in nuclei of the mediodorsal iris cells and involve an increase\rin the number of primary nucleoli . later, the nuclei enlarge and become\rspherical, and prominent nucleoli appear . these nucleoli can be        \rdistinguished from the normal nucleoli by the presence of the granular  \rcortex surrounding the fibrous core . the pigment granules seem to be   \rcompletely extruded into the intercellular spaces and subsequently taken\rup by leucocytes . the endoplasmic reticulum disintegrates gradually and\rfinally almost disappears . there is a significant increase of ribosomes\rin the cytoplasm . later, the cytoplasmic matrix also acquires fibrous  \relements (about 50 a wide) of low density, probably corresponding in    \rnature to the main components of a normal lens cell . these and other   \rchanges in the transforming cells are discussed .                       \r'),
 (173,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth of several human cell lines in newborn rats .                    \r  when injected intravenously into newborn rats, eight human            \rtissue-cultured cancer cell lines -dash h.ep. 2, detroit 6, j-111, rp   \r41, rp 212, adeno cx 1, ovary 2, and mac 21 -dash grew progressively in \rlung and other organs of more than 50 per cent of the animals and       \rcommonly caused death after 5-8 weeks . two other human cell lines -dash\rthe carcinoma h.ep. 1 and the presumably normal amnion b -dash grew less\rfrequently and rarely caused death or illness .                         \r'),
 (174,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the human tumor-egg host system iii. tumor-inhibitory properties of     \rtenuazonic acid .                                                       \r  the fermented broth of a culture of alternaria tenuis auct. inhibited \rthe growth of the human adenocarcinoma (h.ad. 1) in the embryonated egg \rwith the aid of studies in the egg-tumor system the active agent was  \risolated and identified as tenuazonic acid . tenuazonic acid was        \rproduced by a number of alternaria isolates and by an aspergillustamarii\rand a phoma sp . compared with tenuazonic acid, on a molar basis, about \r20 times as much hadacidin or 6-mercaptopurine, 2 times as much         \razaserine, but only 1/20 as much triethylenemelamine (tem) were required\rto achieve the same inhibition of h.ad. 1 tumor growth in the egg .     \rtenuazonic acid was more effective against h.ad. 1 than against another \rtransplantable human tumor, a-42 . tenuazonic acid, compared with       \rpuromycin, more specifically inhibited tumor growth in the egg-tumor    \rsystem .                                                                \r'),
 (175,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the occurrence of biologic crystals in tumor and nontumor cultures of   \rc3h/hej mice .                                                          \r  crystalline structures of various types have been found in primary    \rtissue cultures of neoplastic and non-neoplastic tissues from c3h/hej   \rmice . all of the cultures of mammary carcinoma tissue contained the    \rcrystals . the crystals were found in varying incidence in the cultures \rof several other tissues with the exception of those from the kidney . a\r\'dialysis compartment\' was not essential for the formation of the       \rcrystals . the development of the crystals was accelerated by a         \rmodification of the culture medium .                                    \r'),
 (176,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a comparison of the fine structure of cultured mac-21 and hela cell .   \r  the fine structure of a cultured mucoid adenocarcinoma cell of human  \rlung (mac-21) is described and compared with the fine structure of the  \rhela cell . the differences in fine structure between the two strains   \rare primarily quantitative . the mac-21 cell differed, however, in the  \rfollowing respects.. a spindle-shaped cell with larger nucleus and      \rincreased nuclear membrane invaginations, and considerably larger       \ramounts of perinuclear golgi apparatus . the cytoplasm contained areas  \rof low density, undefined by a limiting membrane, which are thought to  \rbe accumulations of mucin .                                             \r  the two cell strains contained numerous multivesicular bodies, some   \rwith lamellae in various stages of development, suggesting that these   \rorganelles may be involved in the formation of the lipide-rich,         \rmyelinated structures observed in both hela and mac-21 cells . the      \rnumber of myelinated bodies was found to be inversely proportional to   \rthe ph of the medium .                                                  \r'),
 (177,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of parathyroid and other human tumors and tissues on bone        \rresorption in tissue culture .                                          \r  mouse calvaria were grown in tissue culture in combination with single\ror multiple fragments of a variety of human tumors and glandular tissues\rto determine their capacity to enhance bone resorption . single         \rfragments of parathyroid adenoma tissue consistently enhanced resorption\rin both the frontal and the parietal bones . except for one squamous--  \rcell carcinoma of the lung which had some activity all other tissues    \rtested as single fragments had no enhancing effect . on the other hand, \rall human tissues enhanced resorption when multiple fragments were      \rplaced in a halo around the calvarium, suggesting the presence of lesser\ramounts of resorption-enhancing factors in other human tissues .        \r'),
 (178,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'limited growth period of human lung cell lines transformed by simian    \rvirus 40 .                                                              \r  summary--infection of human cell strains with simian virus 40 induced \rvirus replication and cell transformation with the changes in morphology\rand cytology described by previous investigators . although             \rtransformation greatly enhanced growth potentials of the strains, only 2\rof 23 transformed cultures appear to have attained autonomous growth.--j\rnat cancer inst 33.. 227-236, 1964 .                                    \r'),
 (179,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bacteriophages that lyse mycobacteria and corynebacteria, and show      \rcytopathogenic effect on tissue cultures of renal cells of cercopithecus\raethiops.. a preliminary communication .                                \r  bacteriophages isolated from sputum and resection specimens of pa-    \rtients suffering from carcinoma of the lung were found to lyse coryne-  \rbacteria and mycobacteria, and to produce a cytopathogenic effect on    \rcertain cells in tissue cultures . from the same and other patients with\rneoplastic disease, bacteria were isolated and described as coryne-my-  \rcobacteria because of bacteriological features they shared with both    \rspecies . these bacteria, which either were sensitive to mycobacterio-  \rphages and corynebacteriophages or were phage-immune lysogenic bacteria,\rcould be induced to produce lytic particles with phagolytic activity on \rcorynebacteria and mycobacteria and a cytopathogenic effect on hela     \rcells and on the renal cells of cercopithecus .                         \r'),
 (180,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'gel filtration of the soluble proteins from normal and cataractous human\rlenses .                                                                \r  the soluble proteins of normal and cataractous lenses were separated  \raccording to their molecular size on the polysaccharide gel sephadex    \rg-100 . in cataractous as well as in normal lenses 4 different compo-   \rnents were obtained . during the evolution of cataract there is a pre-  \rferential decrease of the low molecular weight proteins of the lens .   \rthese disappeared completely in mature and hypermature cataract . on the\rother hand, the proteins of high molecular weight (e.g., -crystallin)   \rare very resistant to the pathological process . the electrophoretic    \rpattern of the low molecular weight proteins in the normal lens revea-  \rled several fractions distributed over a large mobility area . after    \rimmunoelectrophoresis, 3 different precipitin lines were obtained .     \r'),
 (181,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the insoluble proteins of bovine crystalline lens .                     \r  the insoluble lens proteins, the albuminoids, of the adult bovine lens\rcortex can be rendered soluble by raising the ph of their washed        \rsuspension in 0.9 nacl to 10.5 and then reducing it again to ph 7.4 .   \rthe sedimentation constant of the dissolved protein is 10.8 s,. its     \rmolecular weight is estimated to be 360,000 12,000 . the amino acid     \rcomposition is approximately the same as that of the soluble -crysta-   \rllin fraction, a kinship which is also apparent from their immunochemi- \rcal properties . it is suggested that the initial insoluble protein is a\rmolecular aggregate of -crystallin, which is dissociated in alkaline    \rsolutions to molecules exhibiting a sedimentation constant of 10.8 s .  \r'),
 (182,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'glucose 6-phosphate dehydrogenase and 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase  \rin lens and blood of different species .                                \r  the activities of glucose 6-phosphate and 6-phosphogluconate dehydro- \rgenase were measured in the lens and erythrocytes of man and several    \rother species . there is a wide variation between individuals of the    \rsame species, but there seemed no correlation between the activity of   \reither enzyme in the lens and their activity in the erythrocytes of the \rsame species . there is a wide range of activity of both glucose 6-phos-\rphate dehydrogenase and 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase in the lens and\rin the blood of different species . several species had glucose 6-phos- \rphate dehydrogenase activity in erythrocytes below the level considered \r/deficient/ in man . the sorbitol content of the lens was not correla-  \rted with glucose 6-phosphate dehydrogenase activity .                   \r'),
 (183,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nucleic acid metabolism in the lens iii. effect of x-radiation .        \r  a previous communication reported an increased in vivo incorporation  \rof p-32 into the albuminoid rna fraction of the rat lens 6 hours after  \rthe animal had been exposed to x-radiation (1,500 r) .                  \r  in the present stody, the in vitro uptake of p-32 and c-14-adenine by \ralbuminoid, ribosomal, and soluble rna fractions of normal and          \rx-irradiated rat lenses was measured . the rna fractions were extracted \rby sodium dodecyl sulfate in 0.9 per cent nacl . the specific rna       \rfractions were also hydrolyzed, chromatographed (on paper), and the ac- \rtivity of the individual nucleotides (as well as the specific rna frac- \rtions) was determined . an experiment was also performed in which the   \rcapsules were removed (after the 3 hour incubation period) and the      \ractivities determined in the nucleic acids extracted from the capsules  \rand in the three rna fractions of the remaining lens matter .           \r  the results of these experiments indicate that the incorporation of   \rp-32 and c-14-adenine into albuminoid rna was markedly stimulated 1 hour\rafter 1,500 r whole body radiation . there was no significant effect on \rribosomal or soluble fractions .                                        \r  the effect of formaldehyde and heating on x-irradiated albuminoid rna \rwas much less than on the albuminoid rna derived from control animals . \r'),
 (184,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an investigation of mitotic control in the rabbit lens epithelium .     \r  a water soluble substance which inhibits mitosis in the rabbit lens   \repithelium has been found to be present in young and old rabbit lenses .\rit has a high molecular weight and is relatively stable at room tempera-\rture . the inhibitory factor is associated with the y-crystallin frac-  \rtion and exists throughout the young lens, although the activity in the \rnuclear region (on a wet weight basis) is less than half that of the    \rcortex and epithelium .                                                 \r'),
 (185,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the identification of lysosomal enzymes in bovine lens epithelium .     \r  biochemical studies are described for the isolation of lysosomes      \r(identified as such by the activities of their enzymes) in the cells of \rthe bovine lens epithelium . the various fractions assayed for lysosomal\renzymes showed contamination of mitochondrial and soluble cytoplasmic   \rmaterial in the two isolation procedures employed .                     \r'),
 (186,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'protein synthesis and polyribosomes in the calf lens .                  \r  a cell-free system capable of incorporating amino acid into protein   \rhas been isolated from calf lens . polyribosomes have been shown to be  \rpresent in the ribosomal fraction and to be responsible for most of the \rprotein-synthesizing capacity of this fraction . the polyribosomes have \rbeen examined by electron microscopy and appear to be composed of long  \rstrands of ribonucleic acid, ranging from 7,000 a to 20,000 a, and con- \rtaining a large number of ribosomes with an average diameter of about   \r140 a .                                                                 \r'),
 (187,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'measurement of oxygen tensions in cerebral tissues of rats exposed to   \rhigh pressures of oxygen .                                              \r  brain and cerebrospinal oxygen tensions have been measured in rats    \rbreathing air or in various high pressures of oxygen (ohp) . addition of\r5 percent co2 to the inspired oxygen raised cerebral oxygen tensions    \rwhen rats were exposed to 2 atm abs or above . inhibition of 75         \rhemoglobin saturation by para-aminopropriophenone lowered cerebral po in\rrats breathing air, but not in rats exposed to ohp . the rate of rise of\rcerebral po to a steady level after rapid compression was found to be   \rfaster than the rate of fall to a steady level following decompression .\raddition of co to the inspired gas mixture increased the rate of rise of\rcerebral po . the anesthetics urethane and pentobarbital sodium did not \raffect cerebral po in rats breathing air or oxygen at 4 atm . the       \rresults are discussed in relation to factors contributing to oxygen     \rpoisoning at high pressures .                                           \r'),
 (188,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'release of free fatty acids from adipose tissue obtained from newborn   \rinfants .                                                               \r  summary the role played by mobilization of free fatty acids (ffa) from\radipose tissue in producing the typically high serum ffa levels of human\rinfants has been studied . ffa concentrations in the serum and subcuta- \rneous adipose tissue from the gluteal region were determined during     \rpostnatal development . a maximum level was reached within 24 hr after  \rbirth, after which there was a gradual fall . in serum the ffa level at \rthe end of 12 months was still higher than that in adults, while the ffa\rlevel in adipose tissue was lower at 3 months than in adults .          \r  incubation of small pieces of adipose tissue in krebs-ringer phosphate\rbuffer containing 4 albumin led to release of ffa into the medium . this\rrelease could be suppressed by the addition of glucose (200 mg/100 ml)  \rfor tissue from all age groups except the youngest (0-15 hr after birth)\r'),
 (189,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'detection of pericardial effusion by radioisotope heart scanning .      \r  a marked difference between the cardiac silhouette on the six-foot    \rchest roentgenogram and the cardiac blood pool, determined by radioiso- \rtope scanning, has been shown to be consistent with pericardial effusion\rand/or thickening . it has also been observed that the cardiac blood    \rpool is separated from the liver margin by the interposition of peri-   \rcardial fluid and/or thickening . this separation was not demonstrated  \rin the presence of a normal pericardium . to appreciate these features, \r400 c. of radioiodinated human serum albumin and 50 c. of colloidal     \rradiogold were used for scanning . the former outlined the blood pool   \rand the latter demonstrated the position of the liver .                 \r'),
 (190,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on the mechanism of erythropoietin-induced differentiation iv. some     \rcharacteristics of erythropoietin action on hemoglobin synthesis in     \rmarrow cell culture .                                                   \r  some of the characteristics of the erythropoietin stimulation of hemo-\rglobin synthesis by rat marrow cells in culture have been studied . the \rrelationship between cell number and rate of hemoglobin synthesis at va-\rrious levels of erythropoietin is sigmoid rather than linear suggesting \ra cooperative action among the sensitive cells . the magnitude of the   \rerythropoietin effect on the cells increases with time of contact with  \rthe hormone,. at the time of one-half maximal effect there is no discer-\rnible loss of erythropoietin from the culture medium . a previously des-\rcribed lag time in the response to erythropoietin appears to be largely \rdue to the conditions of culture and disappears when the cells are pre--\rincubated for 9 h . replacement of a large fraction of the medium at    \r24-h intervals enabled the cells to continue hemoglobin synthesis for an\radditional 24 h .                                                       \r'),
 (191,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the occurrence of megakaryocytes in the peripheral blood of dogs .      \r  a study of megakaryocytes in buffy coat smears from 26 dogs revealed  \rthat no unusual characteristics were consistently associated with appea-\rrance of megakaryocytes in the peripheral blood .                       \r'),
 (192,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'moderate hypothermia in man.. haemodynamic and metabolic effects .      \r  studies were performed on four patients undergoing intracranial opera-\rtion during the induction and reversal of surface hypothermia to 30 c . \roxygen uptake decreased an average of 26 per cent from 34 to 30 c to a  \rmean value of 48 per cent of predicted basal uptake . at the same time, \rcardiac output decreased only 11.5 per cent, resulting in a consistent  \rrise in calculated mixed venous oxygen saturation from a mean of 76 to  \r81 per cent at 30 c . as a result of this and the effect of cooling on  \roxygen dissociation, the estimated tension of oxygen in mixed venous    \rblood remained virtually unchanged . when shivering was allowed to occur\rin two patients, oxygen uptake increased approximately 50 per cent      \rwithout any concomitant increase in cardiac output . observed right     \ratrial and svc oxygen saturations correlated well with calculated mixed \rvenous oxygen saturations with regard to direction and magnitude of     \rchange with change in temperature .                                     \r'),
 (193,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the spectrum of lupus nephritis .                                       \r  fifty cases of sle have been collected over a ten year period and the \rincidence and clinical picture of ln reviewed in the light of other     \rpublished data .                                                        \r  lupus nephritis, like sle, has a variable pattern of its own with a   \rwide spectrum of renal involvement -dash evaluation of therapy and      \rprognosis will have to be conducted against this background .           \r  lupus nephritis may present as a renal syndrome only, without any of  \rthe other manifestations of sle .                                       \r  renal involvement in sle is common, but this does not necessarily     \rindicate a poor short-term prognosis . in the peter bent brigham        \rhospital series a sustained raised blood pressure and the onset of renal\rinsufficiency influenced the prognosis adversely .                      \r'),
 (194,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparison of ultraviolet sensitivity of bacillus subtilis bacteriophage\rspo2 and its infectious dna .                                           \r  deoxyribonucleic acid extracted from a clear plaque mutant of the     \rtemperate phage, spo2, was infectious when incubated with competent     \rcultures of bacillus subtilis 168 m . the relationship between numbers  \rof infectious centers and dna concentration was linear .                \r  the sensitivity of the infectious dna to ultraviolet light was much   \rgreater than that of the free phage when b. subtilis 168 m was used as  \rhost . acriflavin, which inhibits host cell reactivation, increased the \rrate of ultraviolet inactivation of the free phage so that it approached\rthe inactivation rate of the phage dna . acriflavin had little effect on\rthe survival curves of the infectious dna .                             \r  non-host reactivating mutants (hcr ) of b. subtilis 168 m were        \risolated . the survival curves of spo2 phage were much steeper when the \rhcr mutant was used as a host than those obtained when the hcr parental \rstrain was used as a host .                                             \r  ultraviolet sensitivity of the phage dna was still greater than that  \rof the free phage even when b. subtilis hcr was used as host, but the   \rdifference in sensitivity was much less than the difference obtained    \rwith b. subtilis hcr as a host .                                        \r  possible explanations for the greater ultraviolet sensitivity of the  \rinfectious dna are discussed .                                          \r'),
 (195,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the isolation and morphology of some new bacteriophages specific for    \rbacillus and acetobacter species .                                      \r  the best natural habitat for bacteriophages is probably a semi-solid  \rmedium containing actively dividing host bacteria . such conditions are \rprovided for bacillus and acetobacter species in rotting grass and      \rapples, respectively . the bacillus phages found included one with a    \rlarge head and a contractile tail, and also a so-called killer particle,\rwhich had a 350 a head and a long contractile tail . this particle had  \rthe property of killing but not multiplying within a sensitive cell . a \rnew morphological type of virulent bacillus phage was also isolated,.   \rits head was oblong and the tail consisted of a short needle and a plate\rthe one acetobacter phage found resembled coliphage t3 but was of     \rparticular interest because of the prominence of the head capsomeres and\rthe three-pronged tail .                                                \r'),
 (196,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'characterization of bacillus subtilis bacteriophages .                  \r  brodetsky, anna m. (university of california, los angeles), and w. r. \rromig . characterization of bacillus subtilis bacteriophages . j.       \rbacteriol. 90..1655-1663. 1965.--a group of six phages, sp5, sp6, sp7,  \rsp8, sp9, and sp13, which use the marburg strain of bacillus subtilis as\rhost was characterized . these phages, referred to as group 1, were     \rexamined for the following properties.. host range, plaque morphology,  \rstability, adsorption kinetics, one-step growth characteristics, calcium\rrequirements, serum neutralization, thermal inactivation, and           \rinactivation by ultraviolet irradiation . five unrelated b. subtilis    \rphages, sp3, sp10, pbs1, sp alpha, and sp beta, were included in the    \rstudies . when first isolated, none of the group 1 phages was able to   \rreplicate efficiently on b. subtilis sb19, a mutant of the /transforming\r/ b. subtilis 168 . host range mutants capable of growth in sb19 were   \risolated for all of the group 1 phages except sp13, and are designated  \rthe /star/ phages (sp5 through sp9 ) . for characterization, sb19 was   \rused as host for the star phages, and another b. subtilis mutant, 168b, \rwas host for sp13 .                                                     \r'),
 (197,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'transduction in bacillus subtilis .                                     \r  (i) comparative examinations have shown that the temperate subtilis   \rphages can be divided into two groups . b. subtilis strain nrs 231 was  \ran adequate common host sensitive to all the examined temperate phages .\r  owing to certain technical advantages this strain was found suitable  \rfor the titration subtilis phages .                                     \r  (ii) some cultural differences have been revealed among substrains of \rb. subtilis 168 ind auxotrophs maintained in various laboratories .     \rcells in one of these cultures were partly capable and partly incapable \rof using ammonia . ammonia assimilation was transducible to ammonia     \rnegative bacteria .                                                     \r  (iii) after mitomycin c or ultraviolet ray induction the examined b.  \rsubtilis strains liberated /bacteriocin/-like principles . this finding \ris probably analogous to that of seaman et al. concerning pbsx defective\rphages . on the basis of bacteriocin production the examined strains    \rwere divided into two groups .                                          \r  (iv) several temperate phages isolated in our laboratory were         \rpresumably identical with phage pbs 1 . phage sp 10 differed from these \ragents both in antigenic structure and in host range .                  \r  (v) transduction by some lysates of pbs 1-type phages was observed at \rfrequencies of the order of 10 . considerably more and less effective   \rphage materials were yielded by some lysogenic transductants . thus     \rtransducing phages active in the order of 10 were prepared .            \r  (vi) transduction frequency, in addition to the properties of the     \rphage, was influenced by the physiological condition of bacteria .      \r  (vii) transduction of indole and histidine loci was studied by use of \rhis derivatives of strain 168 ind .                                     \r'),
 (198,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the carrier state of bacillus subtilis infected with the transducing    \rbacteriophage sp10 .                                                    \r  bacteriophage sp10 may infect bacillus subtilis to form a carrier     \rsystem . the infected bacteria give rise to infected organisms after six\ror more successive single-colony isolations . about 60 of the spores    \rderived from such an infected culture yield clones that produce phage,  \rand such spores retain their ability to produce phage even after        \rtreatment with antiserum and heating at 80 . four hours\' incubation of  \rcarrier spores in nutrient broth yields cultures having more than 10    \rinfective centers per bacterium . cultivation of infected organisms in  \rmedium containing sp10 antiserum leads to loss of phage and loss of     \rimmunity to phage infection . dna with a density characteristic of viral\rdna can be detected in infected bacteria . extracts of infected bacteria\rcontain a phage-induced deoxyribonuclease activity which attacks both   \rphage and bacterial dna in vitro . the phage-bacterial complex is       \rtherefore best described as a carrier state .                           \r  the dna of the phage and of b. subtilis are chemically different .    \renzymatically prepared complementary virus rna has no homology with     \rbacterial dna . the lack of homology of this transducing phage dna with \rthe dna of its host and the failure to form a truly lysogenic           \rrelationship reinforce previous conclusions that transducing bacterial  \rdna is incorporated into the sp10 virus particle without any            \rrecombination between viral and bacterial dna .                         \r'),
 (199,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'infectivity of dna isolated from bacillus subtilis bacteriophage, sp82 .\r  sp82, a newly isolated bacteriophage of bacillus subtilis, is         \rdescribed . sp82 is closely related to sp8, but differs from sp8 in the \rdensity of its denatured dna and in its plating effciency on b. subtilis\rstrain sb-1 .                                                           \r  dna isolated from this phage can be recovered in molecular weight     \requivalent to the amount contained in a single phage (approximately 130 \rx 10 daltons) . dna of this molecular weight, but not half pieces, is   \rinfective in competent b. subtilis . the response of plaque-forming     \rability to dna concentration suggests that four whole molecules are     \rrequired to initiate an infective center . recombination studies with   \rmixed dna\'s of two non-allelic temperature-sensitive mutants confirm the\rexistence of an obligatory co-operative infective process . a second    \rinfective procedure that utilizes extracted phage dna is described . in \rthis system, low concentrations of wild-type dna are exposed to the     \rcells . at these concentrations the multiple-event nature of phage dna  \rinfection precludes the formation of unaided plaques . however, by      \rsubsequently superinfecting the dna-infected cells with a               \rtemperature-sensitive mutant and plating under selective conditions,    \rgenetic rescue of the infecting dna is accomplished and detected .      \rinfective centers elicited by this /marker rescue/ phenomenon are       \rdirectly proportional to dna concentration . the time of attainment of  \rdnase resistance by phage dna infective centers that have irreversibly  \radsorbed dna can be measured . phage dna infective centers require at   \rleast 13 minutes to become totally dnase resistant . the reasons for the\rfailure of single phage dna molecules to carry out an infection are     \rdiscussed in terms of a specific breakage-reunion                       \r'),
 (200,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'psychology of children\'s dental treatment .                             \r  the communication deals with influences involved in the development of\rthe child\'s attitude to dental treatment . they are extrinsic           \r(educational etc.) and intrinsic (constitutional and hereditary) . their\runderstanding helps to determine the correct psychological policy for   \rthe management of the child in the surgery .                            \r  the aim of psychology applied in dentistry is to discover a mode of   \rtreatment procedure which would ensure that the child will not be       \rsubject to any psychic traumatization (psychophylaxis) . its second aim \ris the management of the so called difficult child and his treatment .  \r  to understand better the child\'s frame of mind during dental treatment\rthe situation in the surgery is dealt with step by step as the child    \rexperiences it through his senses and his psyche . beside the basic     \rsenses -dash hearing and seeing -dash others are also affected.. touch  \r(pressure sensation), smell and taste .                                 \r  children during dental treatment are nearly always in a state of      \rraised emotional tension and are susceptible to anxiety reactions .     \raccording to the degree of fear which they manifest children may be     \rclassed into categories of cooperating and difficult patients . the     \rpsychological procedure for the treatment of children of both groups is \rbased on the principles summarized in the section \'psychophylaxis in    \rdentistry\' . in difficult children it is often necessary to employ yet  \rother psychological measures-psychotherapy, suggestion etc . in         \rextremely exacting cases premedication helps sometimes to find contact  \rwith the child .                                                        \r  the experimental part of the work demonstrates the following findings \r 1. dental treatment consists of a series of interdependent           \rtraumatizing impulses . many of them appear only after a close analysis \rof the situation . 2. the adverse response similar to that elicited by  \rpain may be due also to sensory impressions with a negative emotional   \rbackground . 3. psychic traumatization of the child during dental       \rtreatment can be prevented by relatively simple psychological measures .\r'),
 (201,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'relation of emotional changes during pregnancy to obstetric             \rcomplications in unmarried primigravidas .                              \r  this study was designed to assess the psychological changes           \rexperienced by white unmarried primigravidas during pregnancy, the      \rrelationship between manifest anxiety and clinical factors such as labor\rtime and mean birth weight, and the personality differences between     \r/normal/ and /abnormal/ obstetric cases . the kent egy intelligence     \rscale, the taylor manifest anxiety scale, and the mmpi were administered\rto 160 obstetric patients at the beginning of the third trimester of    \rpregnancy, with the mmpi and taylor being readministered post partum .  \rreliable group personality changes observed from pre- to postdelivery   \rsupported the contention that pregnancy is a time of emotional upset .  \r  following delivery, each patient was classified as normal or abnormal \rdependent on the clinical course of parturition, delivery, and condition\rof the offspring . there were no significant differences between these  \rgroups with respect to age or intelligence . reliable differences were  \rfound, however, for manifest anxiety and total labor times . in         \raddition, a positive relationship was found between manifest anxiety and\rbirth weights . personality differences found at predelivery between the\rsubgroups were largely attributable to the abnormal group\'s greater     \rneuroticism, anxiety, and use of the ruminative ego defenses .          \r  post partum, the personality characteristics of the subgroups were    \rquite similar . both groups showed greater personality stability        \rfollowing delivery, with the most striking changes from predelivery     \rdemonstrable in the abnormal group . the magnitude of these changes were\rinterpreted as emotional lability and related to obstetric complications\rby activation of various physiological regulator systems .              \r'),
 (202,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stranger and separation anxiety in infancy .                            \r  anxiety responses to strangers and to separations from mother were    \rstudied longitudinally in 19 infants between the ages of three and 23   \rmonths by direct observations and by interviews with the mother .       \rbenjamin\'s hypotheses concerning the differentiation and immediate      \rdynamics of infantile stranger and separation anxiety were supported by \rthe findings . differences in onset, period of highest intensity,       \rtermination, and ratios in individuals were found between the two       \ranxieties . tests of the relationship between the two anxieties were    \rsupportive of deductive predictions made by benjamin . sex differences  \rin intensity of the two anxieties were found .                          \r'),
 (203,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mental retardation related to hypercalcaemia .                          \r  for more than 20 years a number of retarded children and adolescents  \rhave been observed who show points of striking similarity . we recognise\rin them a well-defined type that is clearly distinguishable from other  \rforms of mental deficiency . they are therefore described in detail .   \rsome of the children have had infantile hypercalcaemia but it is assumed\rthat other aetiological factors are also involved .                     \r  there is a characteristic facies and usually congenital heart disease \rordination is poor . there is a constant failure to thrive in infancy,\rwith episodes of vomiting, often with constipation . mentally the       \rchildren also show great similarities . their iq is about 40-50 but they\rshow outstanding loquacity and a great ability to establish interper-   \rsonal contacts . this stands against a background of insecurity and     \ranxiety .                                                               \r'),
 (204,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'psychological effects of circumcision .                                 \r  in order to evaluate the psychological effects of circumcision, a     \rsmall study was arranged in which twelve children, from average and low \rsocio-economic level, were given goodenough dam test, cat, rorschach and\rtwo sets of stories, prior to the operation and following it . the      \rresults of the tests showed that circumcision, performed around the     \rphallic stage is perceived by the child as an act of aggression and     \rcastration . it has detrimental effects on the child\'s functioning and  \radaptation, particularly on his ego strength . by weakening the         \rcontrolling and defensive mechanisms of the ego, and initiating         \rregression, it loosens the previously hidden fears, anxieties, and      \rinstinctual impulses, and renders a feeling of reality to them . what is\rexpressed following the operation is primitive, archaic, and            \runsocialized in character . as a defensive control and protection       \ragainst the surge of the instinctual forces coming from within and the  \rthreats coming from outside, the ego of the child seeks safety in total \rwithdrawal, thus isolates and insulates itself from disturbing stimuli .\r  the results of the study raised some questions concerning certain     \rpsychoanalytic formulations, for which further research was suggested . \rpossibilities for future research were also discussed .                 \r'),
 (205,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'changes in children\'s behavior after hospitalization some dimensions of \rresponse and their correlates .                                         \r  changes in 387 children\'s behavior following hospitalization were     \revaluated by means of a questionnaire sent to parents a week after      \rdischarge . factor analyses revealed that children\'s responses to       \rhospitalization and illness were of six types.. (i) general anxiety and \rregression, (ii) separation anxiety, (iii) anxiety about sleep, (iv)    \reating disturbance, (v) aggression toward authority, and (vi)           \rapathy-withdrawal . scores for these six factors (types of responses) as\rwell as a total score, were analyzed by univariate and, in most cases,  \rmultivariate analyses of variance . four variables -dash sex, prior     \rhospitalization, degree of pain experienced during hospitalization, and \rbirth order -dash were essentially unrelated to any type of response by \rany analysis . age, duration of hospitalization, and occupational status\rwere each significantly related to one or more types of responses .     \rcomparison of the mean factor and total scores for the full sample with \rthe levels indicative of no overall change indicated that the           \rcombination of illness and hospitalization is a psychologically         \rupsetting experience for children in general, resulting in increased    \rseparation anxiety, increased sleep anxiety, and increased aggression   \rtoward authority .                                                      \r'),
 (206,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'isozymes of lactic dehydrogenase.. sequential alterations during        \rdevelopment .                                                           \r  applications of isozymes in various biological contexts have been     \rreviewed . diagnosis of several disease states has been facilitated by  \rexamination of the serum isozyme pattern which has been shown to        \rcorrelate in some conditions with the isozyme pattern of pathologically \rinvolved tissues . physico-chemical studies of human ldh isozymes have  \rrevealed differences among isozymes in affinity for a given substrate . \rcomparative studies of ldh isozymes within the erythrocyte from various \rvertebrate species demonstrated a marked species variation in the number\rof ldh isozymes, in the distribution of total ldh activity among them,  \rand in their electrophoretic mobilities . during development of chick,  \rrabbit, and human tissues characteristic sequential alterations in the  \rldh isozyme pattern occurred and consisted for liver and muscle in loss \rof the most rapidly migrating anodal bands and increased activity in the\rcathodal bands and slower migrating anodal bands . in heart the reverse \rchanges were observed . if high enough ldh activities of early fetal    \rtissue extracts were applied to the gel the full complement of ldh      \risozymes was observed,. however, in lower concentrations the cathodal   \rbands, which in the starch gel disappear more rapidly on dilution than  \rdo the anodal bands, were not observed . a species-specific isozyme     \rpattern is obtained in long term culture of rabbit, chick, and human    \rcells . independently of the tissue of origin, there occurs in cells in \rculture a sequential series of isozyme alterations characterized by     \rdecreased intensity of rapidly migrating anodal bands . the shift toward\rprominence of cathodal isozymes during both fetal development and tissue\rculture can be explained by postulating the increased activity of the   \rgene producing one of the subunits of ldh with a concomitant decrease in\rthe activity of the gene producing the second subunit . practical       \rapplications of the study of isozymes in tissue culture were discussed .\r'),
 (207,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'establishment of a cell line in vitro from a case of human lung cancer .\r  1) one cell line has been established from the pneumonectomized       \rspecimen of a case with lung cancer, which was diagnosed as             \rundifferentiated cell carcinoma and partially adenocarcinoma by its     \rhistological findings and was characterized with intracytoplasmic fat   \rdroplets in them .                                                      \r  2) the morphological changes of the cells were repeated but they have \rbeen stabilized to their epithelial shapes after the 35th transfer . the\rcell atypy of the culture was remarkable . phagocytosis of the cell line\rhas not been observed . it was characterized that the intracytoplasmic  \rdroplets found in the original cancer cells have been maintained in the \rcultured cells, even in their mitotic stage, throughout the cultural    \rcourse .                                                                \r  3) concerning the chromosomal constitution diploid cells were only 15 \rper cent . the range of chromosome number did not show sharp peak,      \rforming two groups of near diploid and near tetraploid ranges .         \r  4) transplanting the cell to cheekpouches of golden hamsters, the     \rimplanted cells grew from the inoculum of 10 cells in conditioned animal\rbut did not show the invasiveness to neighbour tissue and metastasis to \rother organs .                                                          \r'),
 (208,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'factors influencing development of tumors in frogs .                    \r  (1) study of 75 spontaneous tumors of vermont frogs showed three      \rpathological grades of malignancy present.. aggressive renal            \radenocarcinoma in some 30 per cent, medium adenocarcinoma in 50 per     \rcent, and lower grade mixed with tumors of undetermined origin in the   \rremaining 20 per cent .                                                 \r  (2) correlation with parasite infections (trematodes) was demonstrable\rin only few cases in the kidney . hyperplasias and neoplasias grading   \rinto lung primary carcinoma have been found in the lung in r. pipiens . \rtemperatures below 15 c. protected animals from lung as well as kidney  \rdisease . higher temperatures disturbed the host-parasite relationships \rand led to higher incidence of malignancy . in the bullfrog, precancer  \rwas clearly associated with the worm attachment discs .                 \r  (3) other histological types of tumors in vermont frogs included      \rlymphosarcomas, liposarcoma, mesothelioma, epithelioma, and adrenal and \rcartilage tumors of uncertain malignancy .                              \r  (4) improved methods of obtaining tumor filtrates allowed greater     \rprobability of inducing malignancy with direct renal injection . in 106 \rfrogs 37 per cent developed histologically provable cancers in the      \rranges of three to seven months . twenty-six per cent showed some       \rpre-cancer response and 43 per cent were negative . within the series   \rreceiving filtrate from high malignancy donors one group yielded 100 per\rcent positive, the others 50 and 38 per cent, respectively .            \r  (5) among animals injected with /low/ malignancy filtrate, fewer      \rtumors resulted . some of these were clearly vesicular carcinomas and   \rcould be classed as lung tumors .                                       \r  (6) improved tissue culture methods allowed explants to live in liquid\rmedia under perforated cellophane up to one year . slower growth, aided \rby lower temperatures (16 c.) improved the microecology of cell types   \rand allowed detailed daily observations of each cell\'s intranuclear and \rintranucleolar physiology for extended time-lapse cine-photography .    \r  (7) mechanisms for malignant transformation are related to increased  \ractivity and production of nucleolar dna and rna . the infective dna    \rhypothesis is not classical virus theory, but it does offer detailed    \rsupport .                                                               \r'),
 (209,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mitotic lymphocytes in primary tissue cultures of normal and neoplastic \rhuman lung .                                                            \r  normal and tumor tissue explants from 33 resected human lungs were    \rstudied in vitro . lymphocyte mitoses were observed in tissue cultures  \rderived from 12 of the lungs . the ability of lymphocytes to undergo    \rmitotic division in human lung tissue culture has not been reported     \rpreviously . in the autologous systems used lymphocyte mitoses were much\rmore common in cellular outgrowths derived from non-neoplastic tissue   \rthan they were in the outgrowths derived from cancer-bearing explants . \rno differences were observed in the total number of nondividing         \rlymphocytes present in the non-neoplastic and neoplastic preparations . \rthe in ritro systems employed are promising tools for further           \rcontributions to an already well established clinicopathologic          \rrelationship between lymphocytes and cancer cells .                     \r  phase contrast and time-lapse cinephotomicrographic records were      \robtained of the mitotic process and special attention was paid to the   \rstructural details . certain findings were of particular interest,      \rnamely the formation of a dense chromatin ring during telophase, the    \rvariable occurrence of cytoplasmic bubbling, and the death of           \rlymphocytes during early metaphase (/exploding/ metaphase) . an         \relaboration and discussion of these findings have been presented .      \r'),
 (210,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on transformation of syrian hamster cells by simian virus 40    \r(sv40).. acquisition of oncogenicity by virus-exposed cells apparently  \runassociated with the viral genome .                                    \r  lines of syrian hamster lung and liver cells originally exposed as    \rprimary cultures to large doses of sv40 exhibited increased growth rate,\rhigh plating efficiency, morphological transformation, and, in some     \rinstances, oncogenic potential after unusually long intervals . in at   \rleast two lines acquisition of oncogenic potential occurred             \rindependently of morphological transformation . in none of a total of 11\rcell lines studied in detail was conclusive evidence for the presence of\rthe sv40 genome obtained .                                              \r'),
 (211,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'eye and kidney tissue reactions to heterologous anti-uveal antibodies . \r  the uvea, lens capsule and kidney glomerulus in the albino wistar rat \rhave a common antigenic component(s) . the uvea and lens capsule in the \rpigmented bovine eye also have a common antigenic component(s) . these  \rresults were demonstrated by the immunofluorescence technique . the     \rcommon antigenic sites in the uvea were assumed to be the basement      \rmembrane surrounding the vascular trees in the tissues . the possibility\rof the basement membrane participation as an antigenic source for       \rinducing sympathetic ophthalmia is discussed .                          \r'),
 (212,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experiments dealing with the role played by the aqueous humor and retina\rin lens regeneration of adult newts .                                   \r  1. these three groups of experiments involve approximately 140 eyes of\radult newts, triturus v. viridescens . they were devised to examine     \rwhat, if any, role the aqueous humor plays during lens regeneration from\rthe dorsal iris .                                                       \r  2. many daily injections of aqueous humor from normal eyes were made  \rin lentectomized eyes for as long as 96 days in some cases . as controls\rsome lensless eyes were daily injected with holtfreter\'s solution . in  \rothers aqueous humor was merely withdrawn .                             \r  3) procedures for the injection experiments are difficult to control .\rhowever, the most successful cases showed varying degrees of inhibition \rand retardation of lens regeneration .                                  \r  4. pairs of eyes were united at large adjacent wound openings to      \rprovide a common reservoir of aqueous humor bathing both lenses and     \rdorsal irises . in some cases the eyes were placed on the side of the   \rbody . in others more successful unions were made by fusing a           \rtransplanted eye to the right eye of a host .                           \r  5. approximately three months after operation one of two large lens   \rregenerates in a pair of perfectly fused eyes was removed . six weeks   \rlater a new large lens regenerate reappeared in most of the             \rlentectomized units in the presence of the intact lens of the other unit\r  6. there is a strong possibility that the more than normal amount of  \rneural retina present provided a more powerful retinal factor for lens  \rregeneration than the inhibiting influence of the intact lens in the    \renvironment .                                                           \r'),
 (213,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'correlation between the mast cells and histamine content of the eye in  \rcattle .                                                                \r  the authors have examined the mast cell content of the eyes of cattle \rand have established that most of the mast cells are contained in the   \rconjunctiva, the optic nerve and the ocular muscles,. fewer occur in the\rsclera and iris, and least in the ciliary body and choroid . cornea,    \rlens and retina do not contain mast cells . the histamine content of the\rocular tissues and their mast cell contents generally run parallel .    \rhowever, the cornea is exceptional in that its histamine does not occur \rin a bound state but in some form which is readily available to a mild  \rprocess of extraction (tyrode solution at 4 c) .                        \r'),
 (214,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies in sickle cell anemia xxi. clinico-pathological aspects of      \rneurological manifestations .                                           \r  neurologic manifestations are frequent in patients who have sickle    \rcell disease . these manifestations may be the earliest presenting signs\rand symptoms and they are so variable that the patient may be           \rerroneously diagnosed as having conditions such as meningitis,          \rpoliomyelitis, subdural hematoma, neoplasm, subarachnoid hemorrhage,    \rlead encephalitis, subacute bacterial endocarditis, and congenital      \rmalformations of the brain . furthermore, development of these          \rmanifestations cannot be predicted on the basis of the type of crisis   \rinvolved .                                                              \r  prognosis following neurological involvement is unpredictable, but    \rrecurrent episodes, together with abnormal electroencephalographic      \rreadings suggest a poor outcome . such patients die or are the victims  \rof rather severe neurological deficits .                                \r  neurological examination of these patients suggests diffuse           \rinvolvement of the cerebral hemispheres . examination of the            \rpathological material, however, often fails to reveal thromboses . the  \rstriking findings are infarcts in the white matter and perivascular     \rhemorrhages .                                                           \r  the thesis that the abnormal neurological findings in these patients  \rare actually due to sickle cell disease is supported by the fact that   \rall such symptoms appear in association with clinical circumstances     \rknown to induce sickling . these include surgery and anesthesia, fever  \rand infection .                                                         \r'),
 (215,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'attenuation curves of the human eye under normal and pathological       \rconditions .                                                            \r  a method is described which allows the determination of /attenuation  \rcurves/ of the human eye . those curves are obtained by plotting the    \rcritical depth of modulation (cmd) as a function of the critical fusion \rfrequency (cff) . routine experiments were carried out for a 2 test     \rfield showing a sinusoidal periodical variation of its luminance,       \rsurrounded by an extensive area with a luminance equal to the average   \rluminance of the test field . attenuation curves were obtained for      \rnormal observers under different experimental conditions and for a      \rnumber of patients . it is shown that this method affords us information\rwhich cannot be obtained by means of the classical methods for measuring\rthe cff .                                                               \r'),
 (216,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'central nervous system manifestations of periarteritis nodosa .         \r  in the 114 cases of pathologically proved periarteritis nodosa        \rreviewed, 53 patients (46 percent) had symptoms and signs of central    \rnervous system or cranial nerve involvement . thirty-nine patients had  \rboth cerebral manifestations and neuropathy, 38 had neuropathy alone,   \rand 14 had only cerebral symptoms and signs .                           \r  the most common cerebral manifestation was that of mental derangement,\rusually an organic psychosis or confusional state . headache,           \rconvulsions, blurred vision, vertigo, and sudden unilateral visual loss \rwere the most common symptoms referable to the central nervous system . \rthe most common abnormalities on examination were retinopathy,          \rhemiparesis, and signs of a brainstem lesion . there was no difference  \rin duration of life, after onset of disease, in those with and those    \rwithout central nervous system involvement .                            \r'),
 (217,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'see-saw nystagmus an unusual sign of lesions near the third ventricle . \r  a case of see-saw nystagmus in a child with craniopharyngioma and     \rbitemporal hemianopsia is described, and reference is made to previous  \rcase reports . the basis for this curious sign is not clear, but the    \rsite of the lesion must be considered to be in the region of the third  \rventricle, since bitemporal hemianopsia is a necessary part of the      \rsyndrome . the sign is not common but when present points to a lesion   \rnear the third ventricle .                                              \r'),
 (218,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'implications of gerstmann\'s syndrome .                                  \r  of 465 consecutive patients subjected to a standardized battery of    \rneuropsychological tests, 111 had one or more components of gerstmann\'s \rsyndrome . each of these 111 patients had some evidence of organic brain\rdysfunction in addition to gerstmann components . as the number of      \rgerstmann components increased, the responsible brain lesions tended to \rbe larger, more highly destructive of tissue, and to cause greater      \rneurological impairment . every patient with four gerstmann components  \rhad associated evidence of severe impairment of brain functions and the \rlesion or underlying disease was likely to compromise survival of the   \rpatient . the syndrome is not to be regarded as an autonomous entity,   \rbut merges with numerous other neurological deficits, notably dysphasia \rin agreement with benton, we find no justification for singling out   \rthe four gerstmann components as a separate syndrome, unless one is also\rprepared to recognize that any other arbitrary groups of concurrent     \rdeficits are also separate syndromes .                                  \r  in at least three of 23 patients with all four gerstmann components,  \rthe angular gyrus, as shown by necropsy examination, was not involved by\rthe lesion . however, the probability that the left hemisphere contained\ra lesion increased with the number of gerstmann components, and the     \rprobability of involvement of the left posterior parasylvian area also  \rincreased with the increase in the number of gerstmann components . with\rtwo, three, or four gerstmann components, the lesions were never        \rrestricted to the angular gyrus but tended to spread widely over the    \rparietal, temporal, and occipital lobes . as to localizing significance,\rgerstmann\'s syndrome has approximately the same degree of cogency as    \rdysphasia .                                                             \r'),
 (219,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'alterations of visual evoked response in the presence of homonymous     \rvisual defects .                                                        \r  the visual evoked response (ver) was studied by means of computer     \raveraging in 32 normal subjects, nineteen patients without visual       \rdisorder but with unilateral cerebral lesions, and 30 patients with     \rhomonymous visual field defects . an early negative-positive-negative   \rcomplex was recorded between laterally placed occipital electrodes and a\rvertex reference . latencies were prolonged in the hemianopic patients .\rsome amplitude asymmetries were noted in the brain-damaged controls but \rwere more pronounced in patients with visual defects . the recordings in\rthe hemianopic patients were differentiated from those in both control  \rgroups by the presence of aberrant wave forms (2 cases),. prolonged     \rlatencies (3 cases),. and amplitude depression of greater then 50 per   \rcent of the positive wave on the abnormal side (16 cases) . pathologic  \rverification was obtained in three patients and demonstrated a          \rcorrespondence between alterations in the ver and the presence of       \rlesions of the geniculocalcarine system .                               \r'),
 (220,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cerebro-vascular lesions and livedo reticularis .                       \r  extensive livedo reticularis has been observed in one man and five    \rwomen who have suffered from a series of cerebrovascular lesions . the  \rneurological disabilities have included aphasia, homonymous hemianopia  \rand hemiplegia but have been remarkable for the degree of recovery which\rhas occurred . it is presumed that the livedo which has been found in   \ronly one patient without neurological lesions is related to the         \rcerebrovascular incidents . investigations have failed to show any      \revidence of polyarteritis nodosa, disseminated lupus erythematosus and  \rthrombocythaemia and an arteritis of unrecognized type is suggested as  \rthe etiology .                                                          \r'),
 (221,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'seesaw nystagmus case report elucidating the mechanism .                \r  the eighth recorded case of see-saw nystagmus is reported . features  \rin this case are analyzed and evidence to suggest that this form of     \rnystagmus is ocular rather than central in origin is offered . see-saw, \rnystagmus, unlike true vertical nystagmus, is not of itself indicative  \rof a brain stem lesion .                                                \r'),
 (222,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'supratentorial paratransversal meningiomas .                            \r  the author describes 6 cases of supratentorial paratransversal        \rmeningioma . clinically, the development of these tumours is slow and   \rthe chief neurological signs are.. homonymous hemianopia, contralateral \rhemiparesis and speech disorders when the tumour is on the dominant side\rradiologically, carotid angiography permits identification of these   \rtumours easily . surgically, the tumours were removed completely and,   \ralthough in 2 cases the transverse sinus had to be resected, this caused\rno damage . one patient, who was operated on twice and whose            \rhistological specimen on the second occasion showed that the meningioma \rwas malignant, died seven months after the second operation . the other \rpatients are well and free of neurological deficits from 1 to 12 years  \rafter operation .                                                       \r'),
 (223,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'life span and lymphoma-incidence of mice injected at birth with spleen  \rcells across a weak histocompatibility locus .                          \r  newborn cogenic c h mice receiving injections across a weak (h-i h-i )\rhistocompatibility barrier exhibited life-shortening and a high         \rincidence of lymphomatous disease during mid-adult life . in control    \rexperiments (h-i h-i ) lymphomatous disease developed much later life . \rboth mouse strains when not given injections as new-borns manifest only \ra negligible incidence of lymphoma or leukemia . these findings are     \rvariably interpretable in terms of oncogenic virology, and of the       \rimmunologic theories of aging and cancer by analogy with transplantation\rdisease mechanisms .                                                    \r'),
 (224,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the heterogeneity of rheumatoid factors and the genetic control of      \rpolypeptide chains of globulin .                                        \r  (1) evidence is presented that most rf proteins are heterogeneous in  \rtheir antigenic composition although occasional ones are homogeneous and\rthus resemble the paraproteins .                                        \r  (2) studies pointing out some of the difficulties encountered with    \rcurrently available preparations of polypeptide chains in the genetic   \rmapping of globulin are described .                                     \r'),
 (225,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'progynon, a depot preparation with oestrogenic action, in the treatment \rof prostatic carcinoma .                                                \r  a derivative of a natural oestrogen -dash oestradiol undecylate,      \rprogynon-depot -dash was given in depot form by injection to a group of \rpatients with prostatic carcinoma . the study showed progynon-depot to  \rreduce the excretion of androgen metabolites in the urine . the results \rsuggest that the preparation reduced the testicular production of       \randrogens but probably not that of the adrenal glands . the depot effect\rand clinical action of the preparation are described briefly .          \r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (226,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'/urinary 17-ketosteroid excretion study in radiation induced menopause  \rin carcinoma breast./ .                                                 \r  (1) urinary 17-ketosteroid estimation results are given in 11 patients\rsubjected to radiotherapeutic sterilisation .                           \r  (2) a high dosage level was used in all these cases .                 \r  (3) results indicate some suppression of ovarian function within 2    \rweeks of sterilisation .                                                \r'),
 (227,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'prostatic cancer of a young person with primary hypogonadism .          \r  the prostatic carcinoma of a 34 years old man with primary            \rhypogonadism was presented . endocrine environment of relative          \restrogenic excess is suspected to have played the leading part in       \rpathogenesis of this case .                                             \r'),
 (228,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'urinary excretion of neutral 17-ketosteroids and pregnanediol by        \rpatients with prostatic cancer and benign prostatic hypertrophy .       \r  urinary neutral 17-ketosteroid fractions and pregnanediol excreted by \r21 patients with prostatic cancer, 17 patients with benign hypertrophy, \rand 59 clinically well subjects were assayed to determine whether       \rdifferences exist .                                                     \r  patients with prostatic cancer and those with benign hypertrophy      \rexcreted significantly less androsterone than the clinically well       \rsubjects . a disproportionately lower level of androsterone than        \retiocholanolone resulted in a significantly lower                       \randrosterone/etiocholanolone ratio in both groups .                     \r  the specificity of the findings is discussed . the lower levels of    \randrosterone excreted by patients with benign hypertrophy were          \rassociated with an extended period of hospitalization . patients        \rhospitalized less than 5 days excreted androsterone at levels not       \rsignificantly different from the clinically well subjects .             \r  lower levels of androsterone excreted by patients with prostatic      \rcancer were not explained by the presence of metastasis, the duration of\rhospitalization, loss of appetite, or other definable differences, when \reach was considered singly . the possible interrelationships of clinical\rdifferences prevent assigning lower excretion levels to the cancer state\ralone .                                                                 \r'),
 (229,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'i. urinary excretion of neutral 17-ketosteroids and pregnanediol by     \rpatients with breast cancer and benign breast disease .                 \r  urinary levels of neutral 17-ketosteroid fractions and pregnanediol   \rexcreted by 114 women, 56 premenopausal and 58 postmenopausal, were     \rdetermined . subjects studied were included in 4 premenopausal groups   \r(breast cancer 6, benign breast disease 18, sick control 8, well control\r24) and 3 postmenopausal groups (breast cancer 21, sick control 17, well\rcontrol 20) .                                                           \r  levels of androsterone and etiocholanolone excreted by premenopausal  \rpatients with breast cancer were significantly less than levels excreted\rby other premenopausal groups, and they did not differ significantly    \rfrom levels excreted by postmenopausal patients with breast cancer .    \r  disproportionately lower levels of the 11-desoxy-17-ketosteroids than \r11-oxy-17-ketosteroids excreted by premenopausal patients with cancer   \rresulted in significantly lower ratios than those found in other        \rpremenopausal groups . ratios associated with premenopausal patients    \rwith cancer did not differ significantly from those of postmenopausal   \rpatients with cancer .                                                  \r  lower levels of androsterone and etiocholanolone were not explained by\rdebilitation .                                                          \r'),
 (230,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the morphologic demonstration of an alveolar lining layer and its       \rrelationship to pulmonary surfactant .                                  \r  the presence of an alveolar lining layer was histologically           \rdemonstrated in animal lungs by ultraviolet microscopy . this layer     \rappeared as a thin fluorescent line at the air-tissue interface .       \r  the fluorescent lining layer could be abolished from lung sections by \rextraction with chloroform..methanol and was diminished by digestion    \rwith cl.welchii a-toxin lecithinase, suggesting that the structure was a\rlecithin-containing lipid . an alveolar lining structure was also       \ridentified by the use of phosphatide and polysaccharide stains,         \rsuggesting that the lipid was a phosphatide, but that a                 \rmucopolysaccharide component might also be present .                    \r  bilateral cervical vagotomy resulted in diminution or loss of the     \rfluorescent alveolar lines and abnormal surface tension properties of   \rlung extracts . this suggested that the presence of the fluorescent     \rmaterial was associated with the surface activity of the lung .         \r  alveolar lining structure could not be demonstrated by electron       \rmicroscopy, even with special staining techniques .                     \r'),
 (231,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experimental emphysema basis, review, and critique .                    \r  normal lung structure has been described as a rich capillary bed in a \rfinely partitioned airspace with unique surface-active effects .        \rmorphologic criteria of the lesions of human pulmonary emphysema include\revidence of destruction, residual vascular remnants, the absence of     \rsignificant amounts of fibrosis, and altered conducting airways without \ranatomic obstruction .                                                  \r  experimental studies relating to the pathogenesis of emphysema have   \rbeen reviewed and critically evaluated . stress has been placed on the  \rnecessity to control the biologic factors influencing the action of any \rspecific etiologic agent .                                              \r'),
 (232,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'alveolar lining cells and pulmonary reticuloendothelial system of the   \rrabbit .                                                                \r  complete freund\'s adjuvant was injected intravenously into rabbits and\rthe cellular response in the lungs was investigated . the population of \rcells within the alveolar spaces was contributed to by monocytes of the \rcirculation, mesenchymal cells of the alveolar walls and epithelial     \rlining cells of the alveoli . the abnormal epithelial lining during the \rproliferative phase was the result of an increase in size and number of \rthe cells that line the normal alveoli . as healing progressed, a       \rstructurally normal alveolar lining was found .                         \r'),
 (233,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'time course of changes in surface tension and morphology of alveolar    \repithelial cells in co2-induced hyaline membrane disease .              \r  atelectasis and hyaline membranes produced by exposure of guinea pigs \rto 15 percent co2 were found to be associated with disappearance of     \rlamellar bodies in the large alveolar lining cells (granular            \rpneumocytes) and an associated decrease in surfactant as indicated in   \rthe rise of minimal surface tension of the lungs . this process is      \rlimited to the uncompensated phase of respiratory acidosis and is       \rreversed during the compensatory phase . the parallel time course in    \rchanges of surface tension and alterations of lamellar bodies in the    \rgranular pneumocytes provides additional evidence for the identification\rof the latter as the cells responsible for the secretion of surfactant .\r'),
 (234,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cortisone and atypical pulmonary /epithelial/ hyperplasia further       \rstudies including electron microscopy, tissue culture, animal           \rtransplantation and long term observations .                            \r  previous work in rabbits showed that there was a proliferation of     \rcells within pulmonary alveoli following intratracheal injection of     \rnitric acid and that the proliferation was greatly enhanced by the      \radministration of cortisone to the animals .                            \r  electron microscopic observations indicated that these were           \rmorphologically large alveolar lining cells . tissue culture studies of \rdamaged and normal lung with and without cortisone showed no evidence   \rfor a direct effect of the drug on the proliferation of these cells .   \r  this observation, together with the knowledge that fibrosis was       \rdelayed in the cortisone treated animals, support the thesis that the   \rcortisone effect is an indirect one . transplantation of damaged lung   \rtissue to hamster cheek pouch failed to reveal evidence of growth .     \rwithin the period of observation (99 to 420 days) there was evidence    \rthat the proliferation subsided considerably and no neoplasms developed \r'),
 (235,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some observations on myelin-glial relationships and on the etiology of  \rthe cerebrospinal fluid exchange lesion .                               \r  the present paper presents cytological observations from developing   \rkitten spinal cord and from spinal cord white matter reacting to injury \rit also presents some recent experiments on the mechanism of etiology \rof the csf exchange lesion . drawing on these various sources, the      \rauthors propose specific functions for some of the cell types present in\rspinal cord white matter .                                              \r'),
 (236,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lactate and pyruvate in the brain of rats during hyperventilation .     \r  experiments on anesthetized and curarized rats under artificial       \rventilation show that during hyperventilation lactate and pyruvate are  \rmarkedly increased both in blood and in brain . the lactate/pyruvate    \rratio which remains in blood the same as in control conditions, is      \rsystematically decreased in brain . during hypoxia (ventilation with 7  \roxygen in nitrogen) lactate rises markedly in blood and in brain . the  \rlactate/pyruvate ratio which is strongly increased in blood shows a     \rsmall rise in brain . these observations could indicate that a different\rmechanism is responsible for the rise of lactate in brain during hypoxia\rand hyperventilation . the important augmentation of lactate in brain   \rduring hyperventilation can give an explanation for the delayed rise    \rwhich is seen in the lactate level in cerebrospinal fluid in these      \rconditions .                                                            \r'),
 (237,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cisternal fluid oxygen tension in man .                                 \r  using a beckman micro-oxygen-electrode we have studied the oxygen     \rtension simultaneously in the cisterna magna, the internal jugular vein \rand in arterial blood under various conditions . the results suggest    \rthat the cisternal oxygen tension to some degree reflects the average   \roxygen tension of the surrounding brain tissue and besides reflecting   \rthe available free oxygen to the brain it registrates changes of short  \rduration in the cerebral blood flow .                                   \r'),
 (238,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ventricular septal defect with prolapsed aortic valve and outflow tract \robstruction .                                                           \r  a case of ventricular septal defect combined with aortic valvular     \rlesion and infundibular pulmonic stenosis is described . the right      \rcoronary cusp of the aortic valve, protruding through the ventricular   \rseptal defect, was demonstrated by right ventricular angiocardiography  \ras a polyp-like mass in the right ventricular outflow tract . cardiac   \rcatheterization and angiocardiography showed progressive right          \rventricular outflow obstruction .                                       \r'),
 (239,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'functional adaptations of the right ventricular outflow tract in        \rcongenital heart disease .                                              \r  functional adaptations in the right ventricular outflow tract have    \rbeen discussed in relation to the development of acquired /pulmonary    \rstenosis/ .                                                             \r  it is concluded that physical forces as well as structural            \rabnormalities may greatly influence both the clinical picture and the   \rlife history of many patients with congenital heart lesions .           \r  the importance of further serial haemodynamic studies to provide a    \rfuller understanding of the natural course of many lesions is stressed, \rso that better advice about prognosis and the optimal time for surgical \rtreatment may be given .                                                \r'),
 (240,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mitral atresia associated with pulmonary venous anomalies .             \r  pulmonary venous anomalies were observed in 5 among 29 specimens with \rmitral atresia . in 4 of these 5 the anomalous pulmonary veins took the \rform of anomalous pulmonary venous connexion . in the remaining case the\rpulmonary venous anomaly was represented by cor triatriatum . in 3      \r(group i), mitral atresia and premature closure of the foramen ovale    \rcoexisted . the anomalous pulmonary venous connexions in this group     \rprovided collateral routes for the flow of pulmonary venous blood, and  \rcan be understood as developing en response to obstruction at the       \rforamen ovale when the mitral valve is atretic . in the remaining 2     \r(group ii) no such causative factor could be invoked . in one of the    \rlatter group total anomalous pulmonary venous connexion coexisted with a\rcommon atrium . in the other, cor triatriatum coexisted with a patent   \rforamen ovale .                                                         \r  pulmonary venous obstruction occurred in each of the 5 cases .        \r'),
 (241,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'basal metabolic rate after cardiovascular surgery .                     \r  the basal metabolic rate and respiratory equivalent of patients were  \rdetermined during 8 days of convalescence from cardiovascular surgical  \roperations performed with or without cardiopulmonary bypass . the       \rresults were compared in patients who had undergone operation for       \rdifferent diseases . metabolic rate in the majority of cases was        \rincreased but was commensurate with body temperature . some patients,   \rparticularly those requiring open operation on the aortic valve, had    \rraised metabolic rates which could not be explained solely by pyrexia . \r  all types of patients in this series had elevated respiratory         \requivalents which persisted throughout convalescence . these equivalents\rwere greater in patients treated with cardiopulmonary bypass than in    \rpatients treated without bypass .                                       \r'),
 (242,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'surgical treatment of ventricular septal defect .                       \r  the surgical technique of closure of ventricular septal defects in 80 \rcases (37 cases of isolated defects and 43 cases of tetralogy of fallot)\ris discussed in the light of the follow-up results . the use of a patch \rfor closure has reduced the incidence of recurrence to 4 percent, com-  \rpared with 18 percent when direct suture was performed . the incidence  \rof heart block also decreased from 15 percent, when direct suture was   \rused, to 4 percent with a patch . the transatrial approach is preferred \rfor isolated ventricular septal defects,. the ventricular approach is   \rpreferred for cases with tetralogy of fallot . in cases combined with   \raortic insufficiency only small defects are closed through the aorta .  \rlarger defects are closed in the usual way at a first stage operation,  \rand a total valve prosthesis is introduced at a second operation . there\rwas an operative mortality of 6 percent in isolated ventricular septal  \rdefects, compared with 27 percent in cyanotic patients with tetralogy of\rfallot .                                                                \r'),
 (243,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some hemodynamic observations in congenital heart disease with special  \rreference to pressure curves in ductus arteriosus .                     \r  hemodynamic observations in 100 congenital heart disease cases are    \rmade based on data in the department of pediatrics, kyoto university    \rbetween may 1961 and december 1963 . we have classified these 100 cases \raccording to the malformation from the hemodynamic view point . our     \rcases were classified into the following groups .                       \r  (1) ventricular septal defect                             35 cases    \r      small ventricular septal defect                       20          \r      moderate ventricular septal defect                     9          \r      marked ventricular septal defect                       4          \r      ventricular septal defect with pulmonary stenosis      2          \r  (2) patent ductus arteriosus                              21          \r  (3) atrial septal defect                                  19          \r      atrial septal defect                                  14          \r      atrial septal defect with pulmonary stenosis           5          \r  (4) pulmonary stenosis                                     5          \r  (5) tetralogy of fallot                                   14          \r  (6) aortic stenosis                                        3          \r  (7) aortic insufficiency                                   3          \r      aortic insufficiency with ventricular septal defect    2          \r      aortic insufficiency with pulmonary stenosis           1          \r  in sonre small ventricular septal defect, we tried the vasoactive     \rdrugs . phenylephrine was injected slowly into the right ventricle via  \rthe catheter, a rapid rise in femoral arterial pressure associated with \rbradycardia and intensiffication of the systolic murmur was observed .  \rafter the administration of amyl nitrite, a rapid fall in femoral       \rarterial pressure associated with tachycardia and softening of the sys- \rtolic murmur was observed .                                             \r  in patent ductus arteriosus, when the cardiac catheter is withdrawn   \rslowly from the aorta into the pulmonary artery, the outstanding        \rpressure curve is recorded in ductus arteriosus . the systolic pressure \rcurve in the ductus arteriosus is the same as the systolic pressure in  \rthe aorta and the diastolic pressure curve in the ductus arteriosus has \ra diastolic dip followed by a late diastolic pressure peak .            \r  in patent ductus arteriosus, when the cardiac catheter is withdrawn   \rfrom the left pulmonary artery to the right ventricle, the pressure     \rcurve reveals a considerable characteristic rise in pulmonary arterial  \rpressure which is regarded as an effect of the transmission of systemic \rpressure through the ductus arteriosus .                                \r'),
 (244,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a study on the direction of inscription of the vectorcardiographic      \rt-loop in left and right ventricular hypertrophy .                      \r  (1) frank lead vectorcardiogram was recorded in 30 normal persons and \rin 323 cases with hypertension and acquired and congenital heart disease\rthe t-loop was classified into 8 types according to the directions of \rinscription in 3 planar projections . frequently observed types were    \rexamined with the direction of the maximal t vector .                   \r  (2) in majority of normal cases, the t-loop was inscribed             \rcounterclockwise in horizontal and clockwise in sagittal planes .       \r  (3) in left ventricular hypertrophy, abnormal inscription of the      \rt-loop was observed with abnormal rightward and superior deviation of   \rits maximal vector and the t-loop oriented more than 120 in horizontal  \rplane was usually accompanied by abnormal inscription . percentage of   \rabnormal inscription was higher in cases with cardiac complaints .      \r  (4) in right ventricular hypertrophy, directional change of the t-loop\rwas relatively small but changes in inscription of it were common . the \rt-loop was always inscribed abnormally in cases with abnormal           \rinscription of the qrs-loop .                                           \r  (5) the concept of the polar vector was found to be valuable in       \rstudying the inscription and the direction of the t-loop . significance \rof changes in inscription of the t-loop was discussed .                 \r'),
 (245,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pulmonary vascular plexiform lesion pathogenetic studies .              \r  an attempt was made to test the theory that in pulmonary arterial     \rhypertension, the plexiform lesion is a jet lesion beyond points of     \rarterial stenosis resulting from nonspecific intimal thickening .       \r  in 39 subjects with such congenital communications as are associated  \rwith pulmonary arterial hypertension, the lungs were studied            \rhistologically . in each, there was an additional element of pulmonary  \rvenous obstruction . it is likely that in the absence of pulmonary      \rvenous obstruction, adult patients with only the congenital             \rcommunication would have developed plexiform lesions .                  \r  in the three adult patients in the study, no plexiform lesions were   \ridentified . among the 36 infants or children, one subject showed       \rplexiform lesions, a 53-day-old girl with mitral atresia, ventricular   \rseptal defect, and patent ductus arteriosus .                           \r  while the findings in the three adult subjects support the theory     \rregarding the genesis of plexiform lesions, the findings in the one     \rinfant with plexiform lesions appear to contradict it .                 \r'),
 (246,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal hemosiderosis (blue kidney) in patients with valvular heart       \rdisease .                                                               \r  anatomic evidence of intravascular hemolysis, i.e., renal             \rhemosiderosis, was found at necropsy in 4 of 132 patients who died of   \rsevere valvular heart disease . the aortic valve in each of these 4     \rpatients was heavily calcified, immobile, and portions of the calcific  \rdeposits were in direct contact with the blood . hemolysis in each      \rpatient was attributable to direct trauma to erythrocytes traversing the\rstenotic valve, and the frequency of trauma was increased by an         \rassociated regurgitant flow . renal hemosiderosis was not observed in   \rany patient with isolated mitral valve disease, or in those with        \rcombined mitral and tricuspid valve malformations .                     \r'),
 (247,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'tumor scanning with radioactive cesium .                                \r  fourteen patients with cancer were scanned 10 minutes to 48 hours     \rafter injection of radioactive cs. and satisfactory scans of the tumors \rwere obtained in seven . positive scans were obtained in large,         \rsuperficial tumors, in a pulmonary lymphoma, and in a carcinoma of the  \rupper third of the esophagus . the negative scans were all in abdominal \rtumors . correlations were made with data obtained from external        \rcounting and by well scintillation counting of biopsy specimens . two   \rmodes of uptake are suggested.. (a) early uptake due to vascularity and \rprobably not proportional to stable cesium content.. and (b) a later    \ruptake based upon greater alkali metal content of tumors than of normal \rtissue .                                                                \r'),
 (248,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lung scanning with colloidal risa .                                     \r  the use of colloidal risa injected intravenously in a particle size of\r10.50 microns followed by lung photoscanning offers a practical,        \ratraumatic method of visualizing pulmonary artery occlusions in the dog \rthe fact that the particles have a relatively short biological        \rhalf-life appears to decrease the radiation dose delivered and the      \rduration of occlusion of pulmonary capillaries as compared to ceramic   \rmicrospheres . work is in progress to apply this technique to the study \rof pulmonary artery occlusion in the human .                            \r'),
 (249,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'multivariate comparison of results of treatment in chronic lymphocytic  \rand chronic granulocytic leukemia .                                     \r  the results of several clinical trials have been analyzed by          \rmultivariate procedures which rely completely on laboratory findings and\rdo not involve scoring specific changes or subjective evaluations .     \rstatistically significant differences among drugs after three months of \rtherapy were demonstrated . a relationship between the multivariate     \rmethod and the subjective evaluation was demonstrated which indicates   \rthat if the subjective evaluation is an estimate of the physiologic     \rstate or prognosis of the patient, then so are the completely objective \rtechniques used here .                                                  \r'),
 (250,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'oxacillin--apparent hematologic and hepatic toxicity .                  \r  bone marrow depression and hepatocellular dysfunction developed in an \rallergic woman receiving 3.0 gm. of sodium oxacillin by mouth daily for \rnearly three months . discontinuing the drug and administering          \rcorticosteroids and antibiotics resulted in apparent recovery . the     \rtoxic potentialities of oxacillin should be appreciated .               \r'),
 (251,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'drugs and neonatal jaundice .                                           \r  this paper is not intended as an exhaustive review of bilirubin       \rmetabolism nor of the many factors which may result in exaggerated      \rphysiologic jaundice.. for such a review the interested reader is       \rreferred to the excellent articles by zuelzer and brown . brief mention \rhas been made of the mechanism by which certain drugs may contribute to \rthe development of hyperbilirubinemia . a few drugs, the water-soluble  \rvitamin k derivatives, sulfasoxazole (gantrisin), the salicylates, and  \rnovobiocin have been unequivocally shown to affect adversely the newborn\rinfant\'s ability to handle bilirubin . in time other compounds will     \rdefinitely be incriminated .                                            \r  it is important to remember that the administration of a drug to a    \rmother just prior to delivery may result in appreciable concentrations  \rof the compound in the infant\'s serum, and that drugs administered to   \rthe nursing mother may be excreted in breast milk and thereby absorbed  \rby the infant . careful consideration of the drugs given not only to the\rnewborn but also to the mother is therefore essential if we are to avoid\rwhat may be termed iatrogenic hyperbilirubinemia .                      \r'),
 (252,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'amputation in patients over 80 years of age .                           \r  although patients over 80 years of age can be expected to have poor   \rphysical reserve and many co-existing diseases, our observations show   \rthat nevertheless they can be subjected to surgical procedures without  \rundue mortality . the mortality rate can be maintained at a minimum if  \rthe surgeon considers the factors that contribute to its increase in the\relderly . this necessitates.. 1) careful evaluation of the patient and  \rtreatment of any pre-existing or co-existing disease, 2) proper control \rof electrolytes, 3) avoidance of infection, 4) prompt correction of any \rpostoperative hypotension, 5) postoperative pulmonary ventilation and   \rtracheal cleansing, and 6) avoidance of prolonged surgical procedures . \r  a group of 26 patients past the age of 80 years underwent amputation  \rof a lower extremity, without undue mortality (9 deaths) .              \r  lumbar sympathectomy is not considered advisable in these aged pa-    \rtients .                                                                \r  the standard mid-thigh operation can be questioned in the younger     \rpatient, but it is the procedure of choice for removal of a gangrenous  \rextremity in patients over 80 years of age .                            \r'),
 (253,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radical operation for ventricular septal defect in infancy .            \r  ventricular septal defect is the most common congenital anomaly of the\rheart in infancy, and has a poor prognosis . we have operated upon 18   \rinfants all under one year of age for ventricular septal defect . there \rhas been successful repair in 16 cases .                                \r  at present, hypothermia with a surface cooling method has proved to be\rsuperior to the artificial heart-lung machine because of the simplicity \rand the good operative results with its use . in addition, early        \roperation during the infantile period will cause less psychological     \rimpact on infants . these advantages are sufficient for us to advocate  \rradical operation of ventricular septal defect in infancy, even         \rincluding the severely ill children .                                   \r'),
 (254,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'specific suppression of tumor growth by isolated peritoneal macrophages \rfrom immunized mice .                                                   \r  methods were presented by which macrophages may be isolated from the  \rperitoneal cell population of mice . these cells, and for comparison    \rperitoneal lymphocytes and lymph node cells, were tested for immunologic\ractivity by injecting a mixture of the test cells and tumor cells       \rsubcutaneously into irradiated mice . each cell type, when obtained from\rimmunized mice, was capable of suppressing the growth of the specific   \rtumor cells . the results are discussed with respect to a possible      \rspecific immunologic function for macrophages in graft rejection .      \r'),
 (255,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of heterologous antiserum and complement on glycolysis of tumor  \rcells .                                                                 \r  the effect of heterologous antiserum and complement on glucose        \rmetabolism of rat ascites tumor cells was examined to clarify the       \rmechanism of the cytotoxic effect of antibody .                         \r  1. lactate-production of the target cells was inhibited by the        \rcooperation of antiserum and complement, while no inhibition was        \robserved when the cells were subjected to either antiserum or complement\ralone . the inhibition of lactate-production was observed under both    \racrobic and anacrobic conditions . no effect of the antiserum and       \rcomplement was observed on the oxygen consumption of the cells .        \r  2. the amount of antiserum necessary for the inhibition of            \rlactate-production of the cells was determined in the presence of a     \rdefinite amount of complement, and it was found that the degree of      \rinhibition was not in parallel with the concentration of antiserum      \rbeyond a certain threshold . on the other hand, a parallelism was       \robserved between the amount of complement and the rate of inhibition of \rlactate-production when different amounts of complement were added to a \rdefinite amount of antiserum .                                          \r  3. similar inhibitory effects of the antiserum and complement on      \rlactate-production of the cells from glucose, fructose-1, 6-diphosphate,\rand pyruvate suggested that the inhibition occurred toward the final    \rstep of glycolytic process of the cells .                               \r'),
 (256,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'soluble tissue antigens in human brain tumor and cerebrospinal fluid .  \r  an a-2 globulin antigen present in human glioblastomas and            \rimmunologically identical with antigens present in human brain, liver,  \rspleen, and metastatic carcinoma cyst fluid has been described . this   \rprotein antigen is not present in plasma, wbc, or normal csf . it has   \rbeen demonstrated in the csf of three of 27 patients with tumors of the \rcentral nervous system . when present, it may represent a specific      \rtissue protein fraction contributed by either the tumor itself or the   \radjacent cns tissue . the major protein components of normal and        \rabnormal csf are derived from, or, at least, antigenically identical to,\rthe plasma proteins .                                                   \r'),
 (257,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the apparent immunofluorescence of tissue mast cells .                  \r  both rat mast cells and rat cosinophils exhibited fluorescence in blue\rviolet light after treatment with fitc-conjugated rabbit anti-rat       \rg-globulin and in each cell this fluorescence was immunologically       \rnonspecific .                                                           \r  whereas cosinophils fluoresced after treatment with fluorescein alone,\rmast cells fluoresced only after treatment with a protein conjugate     \rcontaining g-globulin .                                                 \r  the phenomenon was observed in cells from different organs and the    \rfluorescence was seen to be associated with the cytoplasmic granules    \rnormally present in these cells .                                       \r'),
 (258,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the determinants of cerebrospinal fluid po2 the effects of oxygen and   \rcarbon dioxide breathing in patients with chronic lung disease .        \r  the lumbar cerebrospinal fluid po2 of some hypoxemic hypercapnic      \rpatients with chronic lung disease is the same as that of patients      \rwithout chronic lung disease . breathing 95 oxygen with 5 carbon dioxide\rincreased lumbar cerebrospinal fluid po2 more than breathing 95 oxygen  \rwith 5 nitrogen . the change in cerebrospinal fluid po2 is closely      \rrelated to the change in arterial pco2, and this relationship is similar\rto the relationship between arterial pco2 and cerebral blood flow in    \rpatients with and without hypercapnia . interpretation of these         \robservations must be qualified by the following.. cisternal             \rcerebrospinal fluid po2 differs from lumbar cerebrospinal fluid po2 in  \rits response to breathing oxygen with carbon dioxide,. regulation of    \rblood flow to the spinal cord and nerve roots is not known to be        \rcomparable to that of the brain,. and factors other than blood flow may \rhave contributed to the changes of cerebrospinal fluid po2 .            \r'),
 (259,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the behavior of lymphocytes in primary explants of human lung cancer in \rvitro .                                                                 \r  the activity of lymphocytes within outgrowths from explanted tissue   \rfragments of 20 human lung cancers has been studied . the study included\rcancer-bearing tissue explants from all cases and noncancerbearing lung \rtissue from 4 of the 20 cases . five major categories of lymphocytic    \rbehavior were derived from the study, namely.. (1) emigration and       \rmigration of lymphocytes from the explant,. (2) clustering of           \rlymphocytes around /target/ cells,. (3) ameboid transformation of       \rlymphocytes,. (4) lymphocytic congregation,. and (5) emperipolesis .    \rcriteria for these different lymphocytic activities have been amplified \ror introduced .                                                         \r  findings of particular interest were.. (1) the frequency of both via  \rble and nonviable lymphocytes within the vacuoles of other cells . this \robservation is considered to be an absolute criterion for the recogni-  \rtion of emperipolesis . a subsequent /inclusionbody/ appearance of the  \rdead lymphocytes has been observed . (2) the intimate relationship of   \rameboid forms of lymphocytes to selected cells, resulting in a          \rjuxtanuclear and frequently unipolar crowding of one cell by numerous   \rlymphocytes while nearby cells were totally devoid of ameboid           \rlymphocytes . reasons are given to support the impression that this     \rphenomenon is re lated to sensitization . there is also the possibility \rthat the phenomenon may indicate that the lymphocyte is /conditioned/ . \r(3) the apparent entry of the lymphocyte into the cell has been recorded\rby timelapse cinematography .                                           \r  a lymphocyte relationship to cancer cells was infrequently found      \ralthough explants of 15 of the 20 cases produced identifiable cancer    \rcells and lymphocytes emigrated from the explants of all 20 cases . it  \ris not apparent from this limited study whether this is a significant   \rfinding .                                                               \r'),
 (260,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ventricular septal defect with aortic insufficiency a clinical and      \rhemodynamic study of 18 proved cases .                                  \r  eighteen patients with the combination of ventricular septal defect   \rand aortic insufficiency were studied . nine also had infundibular      \rpulmonary stenosis . seventeen were treated by open-heart operations .  \r  the physical findings were those of a typical ventricular defect      \rmurmur and thrill together with an aortic insufficiency blow and a wide \rpulse pressure . a systolic murmur at the upper left sternal border with\rthrill is strongly suggestive of the additional lesion of infundibular  \rpulmonary stenosis, but the presence or absence of infundibular         \rpulmonary stenosis was indicated most accurately at cardiac             \rcatheterization and on inspection at operation . it was not of          \rsufficient severity for signs of additional right ventricular           \rhypertrophy to appear on the electrocardiogram .                        \r  retrograde aortography serves to demonstrate the severity of the      \raortic regurgitation .                                                  \r  the problem of the surgical correction of these lesions will be the   \rsubject of a separate communication .                                   \r'),
 (261,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radioisotope photoscanning as a diagnostic aid in cardiovascular disease\ra safe, simple method for diagnosing pericardial effusion and aneurysm .\r  radioisotope scanning is a safe, simple, and useful method for the    \rdiagnosis of pericardial effusion and aortic aneurysm . the whole-body  \rradiation dose, approximately 25 millirads from 300 of i 131-sodium     \riodipamide, is no greater than the dose received from a standard        \rposteroanterior chest roentgenogram or a blood volume determination .   \rthere are no side effects or complications from the procedure, and it is\rwell tolerated by the patient . the scan can be repeated at intervals to\rassess progress of the disease or response to treatment . cardiovascular\rscanning with radioactive isotopes can be recommended as a useful and   \rsafe diagnostic tool .                                                  \r'),
 (262,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of hematology and bone marrow morphology in vitamin e-deficient \rpigs .                                                                  \r  forty-four pigs were used in two experiments whose purpose was to     \rproduce a deficiency of vitamin e . the anemia and changes in bone      \rmarrow morphology occurring in the vitamin e-deficient state are        \rdescribed . the hematologic disorders include low hemoglobin and        \rhematocrit values, leucocytosis and granulocytosis . nuclear            \rabnormalities were observed in the erythroid precursors in the bone     \rmarrow, many of the cells being multinucleated . giant multinucleated   \rcells of megakaryocyte type were frequently found .                     \r'),
 (263,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'significance of blood groups in homotransplantation of marrow in the dog\r  ten dogs were given 1,500 r whole-body irradiation and an infusion of \rallogeneic marrow from a donor matched with respect to six erythrocyte  \rantigens . methotrexate was given to reduce secondary syndromes . four  \rdogs survived . in a similar experiment with 10 dogs, in which no effort\rwas made to match donors and recipients, three dogs survived . it was   \rconcluded that matching of donor and recipient for these six red cell   \rantigens did not increase significantly the longterm survival rate of   \rlethally irradiated dogs with allogeneic marrow grafts .                \r'),
 (264,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radioautographic studies of bone marrow lymphocytes in vivo and in      \rdiffusion chamber cultures .                                            \r  radioautography with tritiated thymidine has been utilized to examine \rthe turnover rate and origin of small lymphocytes in the bone marrow of \rthe guinea-pig .                                                        \r  very few marrow lymphocytes were initially labeled by a single        \rinjection of tritiated thymidine, but thereafter the number of labeled  \rlym phocytes rapidly increased to high maximum levels at 3 days .       \ranalysis of the labeling curves and grain counts indicates that the     \rpopulation of marrow lymphocytes is maintained in a dynamic steady state\rwith an average turnover time of 3 days or less .                       \r  suspensions of bone marrow cells were isolated from the circulation   \rwithin intraperitoneal diffusion chambers after short-term labeling with\rtritiated thymidine in vivo . although very few small lymphocytes were  \rlabeled when introduced into the diffusion chambers, a considerable     \rpercentage became labeled during the subsequent culture period .        \r  tritiated thymidine was also administered intravenously whilst        \rexcluded from one hind limb by the application of an occlusive          \rcompression bandage for 20 minutes . very few labeled small lymphocytes \rwere found after 72 hours in the tibial marrow of the initially occluded\rlimb, whereas the normal high percentage was labeled in the control     \rtibial marrow .                                                         \r  these experiments do not demonstrate any large-scale influx of small  \rlymphocytes from the blood stream into the marrow parenchyma . they     \rsuggest that newly formed small lymphocytes appear in the marrow as a   \rresult of the division of locally situated precursor cells, but the     \rmechanism of intramedullary lymphocytopoiesis is uncertain .            \r/transitional/ cells, intermediate in morphology between blast cells and\rsmall lymphocytes, synthesize dna and are actively proliferative, but   \rthey do not appear to account fully for the rate of lymphocyte          \rproduction .                                                            \r  certain large, undifferentiated labeled cells appeared in the bone    \rmarrow as a result of hematogenous migration . some implications of     \rthese findings are discussed .                                          \r'),
 (265,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'autoradiographic study on the origin and fate of small lymphoid cells in\rthe dog bone marrow.. effect of femoral artery clamping during in vivo  \ravailability of h3-thymidine .                                          \r  the origin and fate of small lymphoid cells in the dog bone marrow    \rwere studied autoradiographically by observing the effect of clamping of\rthe femoral artery during in vivo availability of h3-thymidine . heavily\rlabeled small lymphoid cells appeared in the bone marrow of the clamped \rleg 3 hours after injection of the tracer and increased in number up to \r6 days . the labeling indices of these cells, however, were             \rsignificantly lower than those of control marrow . a possible           \rinterpretation is that dog bone marrow contains two populations of small\rlympho id cells, one migrating into the marrow via the blood stream, the\rother originating from local precursor cells within the marrow . there  \rwas no evidence for a transformation of migrated small lymphoid cells   \rinto erythroblasts during the first 48 hours after injection of         \rh3-thymidine .                                                          \r'),
 (266,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the lymphocyte in guinea-pig bone marrow .                              \r  the structure and distribution of lymphocytes in the bone marrow of   \rnormal 400 g guinea-pigs have been studied by means of light microscopy,\relectron microscopy, and radioautography . the study of structural      \rorganization by all three techniques confirms the morphological identity\rof the marrow small lymphocytes with small lymphocytes in other         \rsituations and affords added proof of the presence of a series of cells \rtransitional in appearance between small lymphocytes and blast cells .  \runlike the small lymphocytes, transitional cells show evidence of dna   \rsynthesis . marrow small lymphocytes and transitional cells are         \rdiffusely scattered throughout the parenchyma, often situated in close  \rproximity to the sinusoidal endothelium . they are also found           \rcharacteristically concentrated within some of the sinusoids,. this is  \rtermed /lymphocyte loading/ .                                           \r  the findings are discussed with particular reference to the possible  \rorigin, interrelationship and fate of these cells .                     \r'),
 (267,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'surgical treatment of atrial septal defect under hypothermia .          \r  the technique of inflow occlusion under 30 c. hypothermia was adopted \rfor direct visual correction in 133 consecutive cases of atrial septal  \rdefect of the secundum variety and the associated anomalies .           \r  the use of extracorporeal circulation combined with hypothermia was   \rreserved for the repair of two cases of ostium primum defects .         \r  the over-all operative mortality was 4 .                              \r  post-operative evaluation showed that the results have been good in   \ralmost all patients, including those with pulmonary hypertension .      \r  since an ostium primum defect requires cardio-pulmonary bypass for its\rclosure, the pre-operative recognition of the defect is highly desirable\rin the selection of patients for operation and in planning the procedure\ritself .                                                                \r  the information derived from the clinical examination and appropriate \rdiagnostic studies has been found to be consistently accurate in the    \rpre-operative differentiation of the primum from the secundum defect .  \rtherefore, the unexpected discovery of a primum defect at operation was \rnot a problem .                                                         \r  in our experience, open-heart surgery under 30 c. hypothermia for the \rrepair of an atrial septal defect of the secundum type and the          \rassociated anomalies is a safe and practical technique and effectively  \rcorrects the anomaly with minimal risk .                                \r'),
 (268,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'internal cooling for general hypothermia .                              \r  a further presentation is offered on the advantageous use of          \rintragastric temperature control as an adjunct in general hypothermia . \ra device is described which accomplishes this end with no encountered   \rdeleterious side effects, minimal technical involvement, and minor      \rexpense . observations are recorded on rates of temperature change      \raccording to sex, weight, and type of surgery performed .               \r'),
 (269,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'late effects of regional renal hypothermia .                            \r  in summary, one can safely conclude that no deleterious effects were  \rcreated in dogs observed over a period of 3 years following renal       \rischemia of 6 hours\' duration protected by hypothermia . the blood      \rpressure failed to climb, there was no evidence of azotemia, and careful\rmicroscopic studies failed to reveal histological evidence of renal,    \rvascular or cardiac damage . renal function, as demonstrated by         \rcreatinine and pah, was preserved and there was no delay in wound       \rhealing .                                                               \r'),
 (270,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mesenteric vascular response to hypothermia .                           \r  1. total and segmental resistances were studied in the mesenteries of \r37 dogs, and the effects of hypothermia, changes in blood viscosity and \repinephrine on these resistances were compared .                        \r  2. cooling to 15 c. caused an increased mesenteric resistance in 94   \rper cent of animals with approximately 90 per cent of the resistance    \rrise contributed by the arterial segment . small vessel resistance      \rincreased in 52 per cent . there was no evidence of venous constriction \r  3. blood viscosity appeared to play a minor role .                    \r  4. it is suggested that hemorrhagic necrosis of the bowel wall is due \rto intense vasoconstriction in the precapillary vessels with subsequent \rdistal anoxia and cellular damage .                                     \r'),
 (271,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the response of dogs to perfusion and arrest of circulation at near zero\rcerebral temperatures .                                                 \r  1. twenty-six dogs were cooled by a whole body, closed chest perfusion\rtechnique to end perfusion brain temperatures of 14.1 to 0.2 c.         \rinclusive .                                                             \r  2. there were no deaths in the group of six dogs in which the end     \rperfusion brain temperature was 10.0 c. or higher .                     \r  3. in the 17 dogs cooled to brain temperatures of 5.0 c. or less there\rwere nine deaths, of which five occurred quickly from cardiovascular    \rfailure, while four resulted from gross neurologic disturbances .       \r  4. there was no evidence of aortic incompetence during whole body,    \rclosed chest hypothermic perfusion .                                    \r  5. the lower the temperature of the brain at the end of the cooling   \rperfusion, the greater was the passive transfer of heat from the        \renvironment .                                                           \r'),
 (272,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of graded hemorrhage on cardiopulmonary functions of hypothermic\rdogs .                                                                  \r  experiments were conducted on anesthetized dogs subjected to moderate \rhypothermia (28 c.) and then bled in percentages of the estimated blood \rvolume . respiratory work was not influenced by the degree of hemorrhage\rpulmonary ventilation, respiratory rate and tidal volume were not     \rinfluenced significantly as a result of blood withdrawal . physiologic  \rdead space as a percentage of tidal volume increased with hemorrhage .  \roxygen consumption decreased as the hemorrhage was made more severe,    \rwhereas carbon dioxide production was unchanged, indicating a shift in  \rthe respiratory exchange ratio . cardiac output decreased 78 per cent   \rfrom control level when 35 per cent of the estimated blood volume was   \rwithdrawn . systemic arterial pressures decreased markedly but heart    \rrate was not changed as a result of blood withdrawal . comparison of    \rresponses to hemorrhage in hypothermia and normothermia is discussed .  \r'),
 (273,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypothermia in management of acute renal failure .                      \r  1. prolonged hypothermia begun in the period immediately following the\rinfusion of epinephrine into the renal artery appears to give partial   \rprotection against renal damage .                                       \r  2. shorter periods of hypothermia do not appear to be beneficial .    \r  3. prolonged hypothermia at 28 to 30 c. has a mortality rate of 50    \rpercent\rto 60 percent .\r'),
 (274,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2803. effect of dosage on endotoxin-induced changes in the reticuloendothelial\rsystem of rabbits\rtissues were removed from rabbits 4\rand 24 hr. following an i.v. injection of 5,\r25, or 200 ug of endotoxin.  explants of\rtissues from normal and injected animals\rwere grown in a coagulated plasma medium\rand in medium containing 1 ug/ml of\rendotoxin.  the migration and growth of cells\rwere observed during the following week\rof incubation.  the inhibition or stimulation\rof cells of the reticuloendothelial system\r(res) at different host sites after endotoxin\radministration depended on the dosage\rand on the known capacity of different organs\rto take up circulating endotoxin.  macro-\rphage migration was suppressed in cultures\rof spleen removed 4 hr. after a dose of\rhibited by 200 ug, but macrophages in\rlymph node, testis, and thymus showed an in-\rcrease in numbers, in extent of migration\rand in phagocytic activity.  widespread\rres stimulation was seen in tissues removed\r24 hr after the largest dose.  in ad-\rdition to the restoration of re cell activity in\rspleen and lung there was a marked\rincrease in the migration of large phagocytic\rcells from bone marrow, as well as\rother organs.  macrophages from endotoxin-injected\ranimals were as sensitive as\rnormal macrophages to added endotoxin in vitro.\r'),
 (275,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3075. vaccinia pneumonia in mice.  a light and electron microscopic and viral\rassay study\rswiss white mice between 2 and 4 days of age\rdeveloped generalized vaccinia viral\rinfection 2 to 7 days after intranasal inoculation.\rgross and histologic evidence of\rpneumonia was seen in more than 80% of\rapproximately 300 mice.  virus was re-\rcovered in relatively high titers from the\rlungs (10   pfu per g) during the per-\riod when pneumonia developed; viremia\rwas also present, but virus titers in the\rblood stream remained much below those\rin the lungs.  histologically, vaccinia\rpneumonia was characterized by large swollen\rmononuclear cells giving rise to\rmarked widening of alveolar septa.  only\rscattered neutrophils were noted, usually\rin association with cell necrosis.  exudation\rof edema fluid and red cells into al-\rveoli was considered the result of viral\rreplication and cytopathic effect on cells\rcomprising alveolar septa.  various forms\rof vaccinia virus were observed by elec-\rtron microscopy within both \'type i\' and\r\'type ii\' alveolar lining cells, capillary\rendothelial cells, and interstitial cells\rwithin alveolar walls.  these infected inter-\rstitial cells were probably derived from\rfixed macrophages and were noted also\raround bronchioles.  virus particles were\rsimilarly observed in bronchiolar epi-\rthelium and surrounding smooth muscle\rcells.  the earliest pathologic ultrastruc-\rtural change noted in virus infected cells\rwas intracellular edema, evidenced by\rlow electron density of the background\rcytoplasmic material and dilatation of the\rendoplasmic reticulum.  more extensive\rchanges resulted in cell necrosis with\rrelease of virus particles into the extracellular space.\r'),
 (276,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1161. electron microscopy of the bovine lungs  lattice and lamellar structures\rin the alveolar lumen\rin an electron microscopic study of samples\rfrom the lungs of 20 normal cattle,\rand from 4 with high mountain disease, lattice\rand lamellar structures were obser-\rved free in the alveolar lumens in 25% of the\rnormal cattle and in 100% of those with\rhigh mountain disease.  in one specimen, a\rlattice and lamellar structure was ob-\rserved in a vacuole within an alveolar epithelial\rcell.  all others were extracellular.\rthe shape and dimensions of these lattice and\rlamellar structures were similar to\rthose described by other workers in experiments\rinvolving intratracheal injections\rof silicon and oleic and linoleic acid.  this is the\rfirst report of the structures free\rin the alveolar lumens of apparently normal cattle.\r'),
 (277,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1162. electron microscopy of the bovine lungs  the blood-air barrier in acute\rpulmonary emphysema\relectron microscopic studies of experimentally\rinduced acute pulmonary emphy-\rsema in 2 cows yielded the following findings\ralveolar epithelial edema and cyto-\rlysis, endothelial \'thinning\' and cytolysis,\rexcessive elastic and collagenous alveo-\rlar wall fibrosis, hyperplasia of alveolar\rwall smooth muscle, numerous intra-\ralveolar lattice and lamellar bodies, hyaline\rmembrane formation, hypertrophied\rendothelial perikaryons, numerous alveolar\rmacrophages, and alveolar epithelial\rsecretion of an electron-dense amorphous mass.\rit was postulated that the lattice\rand lamellar bodies were a result of degenerating\ralveolar epithelial cells.\r'),
 (278,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1560. the ultrastructure of the lungs of lambs.  the relation of osmiophilic\rinclusions and alveolar lining layer to fetal maturation and experimentally\rproduced respiratory distress\rthe lungs in 69 fetal and newborn lambs\rwere studied.  osmiophilic inclusion bodies\rfirst appeared at about 121 days gestation\rand their total number increased with\rmaturation.  normal surface activity of\rlung extracts was detectable a few days\rfollowing the appearance of inclusion\rbodies.  the excretory nature of the type ii\ralveolar epithelial cell, the phospholipid\rnature of the inclusion body content, the\rdecrease in the number of inclusion\rbodies and their loss of density associated\rwith respiratory distress and with the\rloss of normal surface activity of lung ex-\rtracts provide strong evidence that\rinclusion bodies are the source of pulmonary\rsurfactant.  a dense osmiophilic alveolar\rlining layer in mammals is described.\rsince the presence of such a layer is\rwell correlated with surface tension values\rand the number of inclusions, it is\rsuggested that this layer consists of surface\ractive substances.  the difficulty in\rdetecting such an osmiophilic layer in other\rmammals is thought to be, at least\rin part, due to species differences in the compo-\rsition of materials constituting the\rpulmonary surfactant.  cytologic immaturity\rexists until lamb fetuses reach 135\rdays gestation.  this is considered to be the\rbasis for the susceptibility of immature\rlambs to respiratory distress.  fibrin with\r230 a periodicity is a component,\ralthough a small one, of hyaline membranes in\rlambs.  in view of the fact that mature\rfibrin appearing as bundles of fibrils is rare-\rly found, it is suggested that the bulk\rof the hyaline membrane is not a mature fi-\rbrin, but probably consists of polymers\rof fibrinogen and serum protein.\r'),
 (279,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1685. differentiation of exfoliative broncho-alveolar disease from desquamative\rinterstitial pneumonia\rthree cases are presented of the pulmonary\rdisease described by liebow and asso-\rciates and named by them desquamative\rinterstitial pneumonia.  the cases support\rthe existence of the entity and the contention\rthat it had not been previously described.\ra differential diagnosis between exfoliative\rbronchoalveolar disease and desquamative\rinterstitial pneumonia is submitted.  clinical,\rroentgenologic and histopathologic mani-\rfestations are tabulated for each condition\rand the differences between them are em-\rphasized.  additional symptoms, changes\rand phenomena not previously recorded are\rintroduced.  the most distinctive differences\rbetween the 2 diseases were found in\rthe histopathologic manifestations.\r'),
 (280,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3831. lysosomes in the rat sciatic nerve following crush\rperipheral nerves undergoing degeneration\rare favorable material for studying the\rtypes, origins, and functions of lysosomes.\rthe following lysosomes are described\r(a) autophagic vacuoles in altered schwann\rcells.  within these vacuoles the myelin\rand much of the axoplasm which it encloses\rin the normal nerve are degraded (wal-\rlerian degeneration).  the delimiting\rmembranes of the vacuoles apparently form\rfrom myelin lamellae.  considered as\rpossible sources of their acid phosphatase are\rgolgi vesicles (primary lysosomes), lysosomes\rof the dense body type, and the endo-\rplasmic reticulum which lies close to the vacuoles.\r(b) mebranous bodies that accu-\rmulate focally in myelinated fibers in a zone extending\r2 to 3 mm distal to the crush.\rthese appear to arise from the endoplasmic reticulum\rin which demonstrable acid\rphosphatase activity increases markedly within 2 hours\rafter the nerve is crushed.\r(c) autophagic vacuoles in the axoplasm of fibers\rproximal to the crush.  the break-\rdown of organelles within these vacuoles may have\rsignificance for the reorganization\rof the axoplasm preparatory to regeneration.\r(d) phagocytic vacuoles of altered\rschwann cells.  as myelin degeneration begins, some\raxoplasm is exposed.  this\ris apparently engulfed by the filopodia of the schwann\rcells, and degraded within the\rphagocytic vacuoles thus formed.  (e) multivesicular\rbodies in the axoplasm of myelina-\rted fibers.  these are generally seen near the nodes of ranvier.\r'),
 (281,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2431. histochemistry of surface epithelial and pleural mucins in mammalian\rlung.  the demonstration of sialomucin in alveolar cuboidal epithelium\rsialo- and sulfomucins have been demonstrated\rhistochemically in the surface\rlayer of the lung and pleura from rabbit,\rsyrian hamster, guinea pig, mouse, and\rman.  sialomucin predominates in the distal\rbronchial tree and covers the alveolar\repithelial surface.  the possible significance\rof these observations is discussed.\r'),
 (282,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'617. maturation of postnatal human lung and the idiopathic respiratory distress\rsyndrome\rmaturation and pathologic alterations of the lung\rin 19 newborn infants who died of idiopathic respiratory\rdistress syndrome were studied by light-and electron\rmicroscopy.  normal lungs from 6 fetuses and 11 new-\rborns served as controls.  in all infants with idiopathic\rrespiratory distress syndrome, respiratory bronchio-\rles and alveolar ducts usually presented the histologic\rpattern of mature lungs, i.e. they were predominantly\rlined by type i cells, which also formed the epithelial\rcomponent of most blood-air barriers.  well expanded\ralveoli exhibited a similar pattern, whereas collapsed\ralveoli were lined by numerous type ii cells which par-\rticipated in the formation of poorly developed blood-air\rbarriers.  the capacity of type ii cells to produce in-\rclusion bodies seemed to increase with survival beyond\rthe 14th hr of age.  secretion of inclusion bodies and\rpresumably surfactant into alveolar spaces did occur\rbut only in the lungs of infants older than 2 days.  how-\rever, this process was not accompanied by reduction\rin the number of type ii cells per alveolus as in the nor-\rmal lung.  the distribution of pathologic changes in idio-\rpathic respiratory distress syndrome appeared to be\rdetermined by the degree of maturity of the air sacs.\rstructurally mature air sacs were associated with da-\rmage of epithelial lining and hyaline membrane forma-\rtion.  in contrast, collapsed alveoli revealed an intact\repithelial lining and marked septal edema but were free\rof hyaline membranes.  the findings of this study sug-\rgested that transudation of plasma through well develop-\red blood-air barriers was responsible for epithelial\rdamage and hyaline-membrane formation in air sacs.\rthey also suggested that alveolar collapse and presuma-\rbly lack of surfactant were related to abnormal matura-\rtion of the epithelial lining and to septal edema.\r'),
 (283,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'903. lattice structures and osmiophilic bodies in the developing\rrespiratory tissue of rats\rosmiophilic inclusions have been observed in the\rlungs of rats particularly in the 20-day rat embryo and\rnewborn up to 3 days post partum.  these inclusions\rare present in the large alveolar cells as dense lamin-\rated structures of variable size and configuration.  they\rgenerally consist of concentrically arranged membranes\rand have the appearance of myelin figures, usually with\ra dense center.  these osmiophilic inclusions are fre-\rquently seen in direct contact with the cell membranes\rand the alveolar space.  the alveolar space contains\rnumerous osmiophilic myelin figures which are thought\rto originate from the intracellular osmiophilic inclu-\rsions.  they may extrude through a channel formed in-\rside the cell or by rupture of the cell membrane.  secre-\rtion materials may occasionally be seen in the cyto-\rplasm of the large alveolar epithelial cells.  these cells\rappear to be in the process of degeneration.  their cell\rsurfaces are disrupted and the cytoplasm is continuous\rwith materials in the air space.  the lattice structure\rin the alveolar space may originate from the cytoplas-\rmic secretion material.  the cytoplasmic secretion ma-\rterial in the cell and the lattice structures in the air\rspace disappear after the rats are 3 days old.  (i,t*)\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (284,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'454. xanthogranuloma (xanthoma) of choroid plexus.  the origin of foamy\r(xanthoma) cells\ra case of a 3-month-old infant with intense pro-\rliferation of choroidal epithelium with foamy cells, a\rsecond similar case in a 9-month-old infant with gener-\ralized glycogen storage disease and a case of a 51-year-\rold male with bilateral xanthogranuloma of choroid\rplexus and proliferation of the choroidal epithelial cells\rare discussed.  the pathogenesis of the foamy xanthoma\rcells in the stroma of the choroid plexus, particularly,\ris discussed.  the authors believe that the origin of foamy\rcells and the mode of formation of such a xanthogranuloma\rcan be explained by the proliferative capability and the\rphagocytic activity of the choroid epithelium.  choroidal\repithelial cells can be regarded as fixed macrophages\rwhich becomes wandering phagocytes after detachment.\rdisintegration of these foamy cells then releases the\rlipid content into the interstitium and provokes a re-\rsponse of macrophages and multinucleated giant cells\rof the foreign-body type.  hemorrhage is also considered\ras a factor involved in the formation of xanthogranuloma.\r'),
 (285,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4. mixed hematopoietic and pulmonary origin of \'alveolar macrophages\' as\rdemonstrated by chromosome markers\rthe origin of alveolar macrophages was investiga-\rted in mouse chimeras in which the hematopoietic cells\rcould be identified by marker chromosomes.  by chro-\rmosome analysis it was found that in both normal lungs\rand in lungs exposed to an irritant, approximately two-\rthirds of the dividing cells which could be recovered by\rlung washing arose from the hematopoietic system and\rone-third were of pulmonary origin.\r'),
 (286,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'632. pulmonary alveolar proteinosis.  a study using enzyme histochemistry,\relectron microscopy, and surface tension measurement\rlung biopsies from 4 patients with pulmonary al-\rveolar proteinosis were studied using histochemical me-\rthods, electron microscopy, and surface tension mea-\rsurement.  the lipid-rich intraalveolar fluid contained\rmaterial with the staining reactions and ultrastructure\rof phospholipid.  although many alveoli were lined by\renzymatically active, secreting granular pneumonocy-\rtes, extracts of proteinotic tissue were not surface\ractive, and, in fact, inhibited normal surfactant.  some\rof the cells free in the intraalveolar material were de-\rgenerating sloughed granular pneumonocytes.  at the\rmargins of the lesions were lipid-filled macrophages\rwhich appear to play a role in the removal of the mate-\rrial.  these observations indicate that alveolar protein-\rosis is not a primary overproduction of surfactant and\rare consistent with the concept that the alveolar clear-\ring process is defective in this disease.\r'),
 (287,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1688. surface phenomena in lungs in health and disease\rin summary, the authors have attempted\rto bring together the multiple observations\rwhich seem germane to the understanding\rof surface phenomena in lungs in health\rand disease.  to this end, the contributions\rof anatomists and pathologists on the\rfine structure of alveolar cells and their\rlining are fundamental.  the concepts of\ralveolar stability required the special\rinsights of physiologists who were concerned\rwith the causes of bubble stability as\rthey related to the particular problems posed\rby a lung of several millions of bubbles\rarranged in parallel.  soon the contributions\rof the chemists became significant as\rmethods of identification and assay of the al-\rveolar lining material were of interest.\rclinicians asked what relevance these studies\rhad to atelectasis as it occurs in disease,\rand soon the question of when the surfac-\rtant appeared in development occurred to\rthose concerned with premature infants.\rstudents of metabolism began to focus on\rthe lung as a site of phospholipid synthesis,\rand their tools seem most promising at\rthis time in unearthing possible errors in\rmetabolism which may express themselves\rin disease.  surgeons who undertake per-\rfusion of the isolated lung ask the\rrequirements of that organ with respect to the\rnutrients and environment of the alveolar\rcells, and anesthesiologists inquire into\rthe possibilities of mechanical injury\rto the alveoli during artificial respiration.\rthe problems posed to the reviewers\rof a subject which touches so many disciplines\rare obvious.  doubtless some pertinent\rstudies have been omitted although uninten-\rtionally; others may have been\rmisinterpreted through lack of qualifications as spe-\rcialists in all specialties.  the\rauthors hope they have provided evidence that the\rforces of surface tension cannot\rbe ignored in an organ with an air-liquid interface\rof some 70 m2.  they further hope\rthey have described some of the properties of\rthe film at the alveolar-air interface\rwhich operate to produce stability of the alveoli.\rthey hold the belief that study of the\rmetabolism of the alveolar lining layer will\rfurther their understanding of a number\rof disease processes in which it may be\raltered.  and lastly, they hope for much\rcloser communication between workers in\rmany disciplines who can elucidate this\rremarkable subject best through cooperative\rstudies.\r'),
 (288,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1689. alterations in pulmonary surface active lipids during ex-\rposure to increased oxygen tension\rthe syndrome of progressive respiratory\rdistress, pulmonary edema, and increased\rpulmonary surface tension was induced in\r8 dogs by exposure to oxygen tensions\rgreater than 550 mm hg for 44.5 and 52\rhours.  pulmonary surfactant was extracted\rby endobronchial washing for measurement\rof lipid composition and surface activity.\rfive dogs developed respiratory distress\rwithout pulmonary edema.  in these dogs\rendobronchial wash surface tension was\rnormal or slightly increased, and total\rlipid distribution was essentially normal.\resterified fatty acids in the lecithin frac-\rtion were consistently altered with a\rreduction in palmitate and total saturated fatty\racids.  three dogs developed pulmonary\redema with increased surface tension, in-\rcreased total lipid and protein, and\rrelatively decreased total phospholipid in the\rendobronchial washings.  esterified\rfatty acids in the lecithin fraction were marked-\rly altered with palmitate levels about\r1/3 normal.  esterified arachidonate was pre-\rsent that was attributed to intra-alveolar\rplasma.  electron micrographs of the lung\rafter oxygen exposure showed thickening\rof alveolar basement membrane and altera-\rtions in the structure of the lamellar bodies\rof the type ii alveolar epithelial cells.\r'),
 (289,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3805. cisternal fluid oxygen tension in man\rmeasurement of cerebral oxygen tension\rin man has been hampered by technical dif-\rficulties.  the authors present a method\rin which a beckman microelectrode was\rintroduced into the cisterna magna and\roxygen tension measured, the hypothesis\rbeing that measurement of oxygen tension\rin a fluid which equilibrates with the\raverage cerebral oxygen tension should\rgive reliable measure of cerebral oxygen\rtension.  in their subjects, inhalation of\rpure oxygen produced an increase in the\roxygen tension in the cisternal fluid as\rwell as in the arterial blood without any\ralteration of the oxygen tension in the\rbulb of the internal jugular vein, whereas\rinhalation of 95% oxygen and 5% carbon\rdioxide increased the oxygen tension in the\rcisternal fluid as well as in the arterial\rand venous blood.  5% carbon dioxide in\rair produced an increase in the cisternal\roxygen tension; a fall in arterial blood\rpressure associated with the introduction\rof the suboccipital needle was accom-\rpanied by a decrease in cisternal oxygen\rtension which then rose simultaneously with\rthe increase in arterial blood pressure\rthat followed infusion of dextran.  intravenous\rinjection of xanthinol niacinate induced\rin all patients a more or less pronounced fall\rin arterial blood pressure and at the\rsame time the cisternal oxygen tension fell;\radministration of aramine was associated\rwith a rise in arterial blood pressure\rplus a rise in cisternal oxygen tension.\r'),
 (290,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4181. cerebrospinal fluid in man native to high altitude\rcsf ph was shown in a prior report to\rremain essentially constant during 8 days\rof acclimatization to 3,800 m.  in order\rto further evaluate the possible role of\rcsf acid-base equilibria in the regulation\rof respiration, 20 peruvian andean na-\rtives were studied at altitudes of 3,720-4,820 m.\rin 10 subjects at 3,720 m, means\rwere  csf ph 7.327, pco, 43, hco3-21.5,\rna+136, k+2.6, cl-124, lactate 30 mg/\r100 ml.  arterial blood  ph 7.43, pco, 32.5,\rhco3-21.3, na+136, k+4.2, cl-107,\rhematocrit 49, sao, 89.6.  in 6 subjects at\r4,545 m and 4 at 4,820 m csf values\rwere not significantly different; mean arterial\rpco, was 32.6 and 32.3, respectively.\rthe only significant variations with altitude\rwere the expected lowering of pao, to\r47 and 43.5 mm hg, and of sao, to 84.2 and\r80.7, and increase of hematocrit to\r67% and 75%, respectively.  the natives\rdiffered from recently acclimatized sea-\rlevel residents in showing less ventilation\r(higher pco,) in response to the ex-\risting hypoxia, and less alkaline arterial\rblood.  the difference appears to relate\rto peripheral chemoreceptor response\rto hypoxia rather than central medullary\rchemoreceptor.\r'),
 (291,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1116. na, k, ca, mg, and cl concentrations in choroid plexus fluid\rand cisternal fluid compared with plasma ultrafiltrate\rin 7 cats the concentrations of na,\rk, ca, mg, and cl were measured in plasma\rultrafiltrate, newly formed choroid\rplexus fluid, and cisterna magna fluid.  the\rchoroid plexus fluid did not differ\rfrom plasma ultrafiltrate in cl and k concentra-\rtion but contained higher na, markedly\rhigher mg, and lower ca concentrations\rthan the ultrafiltrate.  cisterna magna\rfluid differed from the ultrafiltrate with\rrespect to all 5 electrolytes, containing\rhigher concentrations of cl, na, and mg\rand lower concentrations of k and ca.\rit differed from choroid plexus fluid in con-\rtaining a higher concentration of cl but\rlower concentrations of k, ca, and mg.\rhco3-concentration, calculated on the\rbasis of the charge balance, was 7 mm/kg\rh2o higher in choroid plexus fluid than\rin cisterna magna fluid, suggesting an ele-\rvated ph at the former site.  without\rmeasurement of the potential difference be-\rtween the csf and plasma, definitive\rconclusions could not be drawn as to which\rcations were actively transported.  the fact\rthat the distribution ratio between cerebro-\rspinal fluid and ultrafiltrate of one divalent\rcation was in the opposite direction\rfrom that of the other, and that this was\ralso true of the monovalent cations, was\rtaken as evidence that the mechanisms\rinvolved in cation transfer are quite selec-\rtive.  though not proven, active transport\rwas considered the most likely explana-\rtion of these findings.  the data suggest\rthat these specific transfer mechanisms\rsubserve a homeostatic function with\rregard to mg and k in the cerebrospinal fluid.\r'),
 (292,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3230. cerebral hemodynamics, blood gases, and electrolytes\rduring breath-holding and the valsalva maneuver\rcontinuous recordings of arterial and\rinternal jugular blood oxygen tension, oxy-\rgen saturation, carbon dioxide tension,\rph, sodium and potassium, together with\rpeco2, blood pressure, and\relectroencephalogram were obtained to compare the\reffects of inspiratory and expiratory\rbreath-holding and the valsalva maneuver on\rthe cerebral circulation and cerebral\roxygen availability in man.  during the inter-\rval of tolerated breath-holding for\r69 seconds or less, jugular venous oxygen tension\rwas increased owing to increased\rcerebral blood flow resulting from an increase\rof arterial carbon dioxide tension.\rthere was a statistically significant correlation\rbetween changes in jpo2 and paco2,\rwhich proved to be more or less linear for\rboth increases and decreases of paco2 4 mm.\rabove and below control levels.  no\rthreshold was found for changes in paco2\raltering effective cerebral perfusion and\rcerebral venous po2, extremely small\rchanges in paco2 (less than 1 mm. hg)\raltered cerebral oxygen availability within\r10 to 20 seconds.  during the valsalva\rmaneuver a consistent reduction of jugular\roxygen tension was found associated\rwith the sudden fall in arterial blood\rpressure and reduction of arterial carbon\rdioxide tension.  the rapid changes in\rcerebral hemodynamics and cerebral oxy-\rgen availability during the procedure\rare briefly discussed.\r'),
 (293,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2344. respiratory and cardiovascular changes during rapid spon-\rtaneous variations of ventricular fluid pressure in pa-\rtients with intracranial hypertension\rin patients with intracranial hypertension\rthe ventricular fluid pressure (vfp)\rcurve is characterized by 3 main forms\rof spontaneous variations.  two of these\rforms are of a rhythmical nature, and\rare here called 1-per-minute waves and 6-\rper-minute waves, respectively, in\raccordance with the dominating frequency.\rthe third form - irregularly appearing\rwaves of large amplitude and duration -\ris called plateau waves in accordance\rwith the usual shape of the fluctuations.\rrespiratory and cardio-vascular changes\raccompanying these variations of the vfp\rwere studied by simultaneous recording,\rin various combinations, of the vfp, the\rpulmonary ventilation, the pco2 of the\rexpiratory air, the arterial and the venous\rblood pressure, and the pulse frequency.\rit was found that the rhythmic vfp vari-\rations of the 1-per-minute type occurred\rsynchronously with the respiratory peri-\rods in cheyne-stokes breathing.\rsynchronously appearing variations in systemic\rblood pressure, in pulse frequency,\ras well as in consciousness and in muscular\rtone of the limbs were also noted.  the\rrespiratory midposition shifted towards the\rinspiratory side during the periods of\rhyperpnoea.  the 6-per-minute waves were\rentirely synchronous with variations\rin the systemic arterial blood pressure of the\rtraube-hering-mayer type.  long\rsequences of these waves were observed only\rwhen the vfp level was considerably\relevated.  the plateau waves were not accom-\rpanied by corresponding elevations of\rthe arterial or venous systemic blood pres-\rsure.  simultaneously with the crests\rof the plateau waves sudden changes often\roccurred in the pulse frequency (from\rbradycardia to tachycardia), and in the res-\rpiratory pattern, sometimes also in the\rdegree of consciousness and in the muscu-\rlar tone.  there were also long sequences\rof 6-per-minute waves.  the deep, irre-\rgular breathing seen in this stage induced\ra considerable hypocapnia preceeding\rthe final critical fall in the vfp ending the\rplateau wave.  in most instances, how-\rever, this fall did not begin until several\rminutes after the appearance of the hypo-\rcapnia.\r'),
 (294,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'82. central nervous system lesions in rats\rexposed to oxygen at high pressure\radult female rats paralyzed by repeated exposures\rto oxygen at high pressure were found to have cns le-\rsions of 2 types  (1) focal necrosis of individual neurons\rwithin certain nuclear groups, and (2) complete or partial\rnecrosis of nuclear groups with frequent damage to mye-\rlin, axons, and glia in the area involved.  both types\rwere usually bilateral and symmetrical.  lesions of the\rfirst type were found consistently in the superior olivary\rcomplex, ventral cochlear nuclei, and nuclei of the spinal\rtract of cranial nerve v.  lesions of the second type were\rfound consistently in the substantia nigra and globus pal-\rlidus, were frequent in the rhinencephalon, and never\roccurred in the neocortex.\r'),
 (295,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'747. electrode size and tissue po2 measurement in rats exposed\rto air or high pressure oxygen\ra comparison has been made of values of\rpo2 recorded in several rat tissues with\r60-u or 330-u flexible gold electrodes.\ralthough qualitatively both sizes of elec-\rtrodes give similar results, the quantitative\rvalues of po2 differ.  such large differ-\rences as are found in some cases between\relectrodes varying only in physical di-\rmensions are thought to reflect the amount\rof trauma caused in the tissue under in-\rvestigation due to electrode insertion.\rerrors in po2 estimations due to tissue da-\rmage are considered to outweigh any other\rerrors such as those due to electrode\rcalibration.  soft, highly vascular tissues,\rsuch as liver, kidney and spleen, which\rshow macroscopic bruising over quite a\rlarge area when electrodes are inserted,\rshow the greatest difference in estimations\rof the po2 value.  recordings of tissue\rpo2 were made while animals breathed air\rand when compressed to 4 or 5 atm. in\rpure oxygen, and the pattern of response of\rtissue po2 to such exposure of the ani-\rmal to high pressures of oxygen is described.\r'),
 (296,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3384. adrenergic effects in splenic po2 of rats in air or oxygen\rat 5 atmospheres\roxygen tensions have been measured\rin the spleens of rats breathing air and during\rexposure of the animals to 5 atm abs\rof oxygen (hpo).  the response of splenic po2\rto compression was complex, usually\rreaching a peak value immediately after com-\rpression, then falling to a lower value.\rthis form of response has been termed a\rhump response.  after adrenalectomy\ror bretylium tosylate injection the hump res-\rponse of po2 after compression was\ralmost abolished, and the values of splenic po2\rat 5 atm were considerably higher\rthan in control animals.  a combination of adrena-\rlectomy and bretylium tosylate also\rmarkedly reduced the number of hump responses,\rbut unexpectedly significantly lowered\rsplenic oxygen tensions, both when the ani-\rmals were under ambient conditions\ror at 5 atm of oxygen.  cardiac rate and blood\rpressure were studied in an attempt\rto find the explanation of this latter effect, and\rwhile blood pressure was the same\rin adrenalectomized rats and control rats after\rbretylium injection, adrenalectomy\rpotentiated the bradycardia produced by brety-\rlium tosylate.\r'),
 (297,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'10642. the effects of antioxidants on high pressure oxygen toxicity\rseveral commonly used antioxidants have\rbeen tested for their effect against poison-\ring due to high pressures of oxygen (ohp).\rthe tests used were preconclusive pe-\rriod and survival time of mice at 5 atm\rabsolute oxygen, lung damage in rats ex-\rposed to 5 atm oxygen for 1 hr., and post\rohp paralysis in rats following deep\rpentobarbital-na anesthesia and ohp at 4\ratm for 30 min.  2,5-bis (1,1-dimethyl-\rpropyl) hydroquinone gave excellent\rprotection against ohp toxicity in all tests,\rand several other antioxidants also\rprotected against ohp toxicity but their potency\rand effectiveness varied for the\rdifferent criteria of oxygen poisoning tested in the\rexperiments.\r'),
 (298,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3716. glycolytic control mechanisms. i. inhibition of glycolysis\rby acetate and pyruvate in the isolated, perfused rat heart\racetate or pyruvate had similar effects\ron the over-all metabolism of glucose.  gly-\rcolytic flux was decreased in both the\rpresence and absence of insulin, glucose\roxidation was greatly decreased, and\rthe conversion of glucose to glycogen and lac-\rtate was promoted.  glucose phosphorylation\rwas decreased in the presence but not\rin the absence of insulin.  hexokinase,\rphosphofructokinase, glyceraldehyde phos-\rphate dehydrogenase, and pyruvic kinase\rare far displaced from equilibrium, while\rthe other enzymic steps of glycolysis\rare maintained either at equilibrium or fairly\rclose to equilibrium.  in different metabolic\rsituations, glycolytic flux may be affec-\rted by those steps which are far displaced\rfrom equilibrium.  increased levels of\rthe hexose monophosphates, and decreased\rlevels of the other glycolytic inter-\rmediates between fructose 1,6-diphosphate\rand pyruvate after the addition of 10 mm\racetate indicate that glycolytic flux was\rdecreased by inhibition of phosphofructo-\rkinase.  after the addition of 10 mm pyruvate,\rfructose 1,6-diphosphate, and triose-\rphosphate accumulated as a result of an\rinhibition of either glyceraldehyde phosphate\rdehydrogenase or phosphoglyceric kinase.\racetate had little effect on the total con-\rtent of oxidized or reduced di- or\rtriphosphopyridine nucleotides, but slightly de-\rcreased the ratio of nad to nadh2\rin the cytoplasm, as estimated from the ratios\rof lactate to pyruvate and a-glycerophosphate\rto dihydroxyacetone phosphate.  pyru-\rvate increased the total content of nadh2\rand nadph2 as shown both by an increase\rof fluorescence in the intact heart, and by\rtissue analyses, but the ratio of nad to\rnadii2 in the cytoplasm was greatly\rincreased.  these results demonstrate com-\rpartmentation of pyridine nucleotides\rbetween cytoplasm and mitochondria in the\rintact cell.  after the addition of acetate,\rcitrate was the only intermediate of the\rcitric acid cycle which increased greatly\rin amount, while oxaloacetate levels de-\rcreased.  after the addition of pyruvate,\rthe levels of citrate, a-ketoglutarate, ma-\rlate, and oxaloacetate were all greatly\relevated.  the glutamic-oxaloacetate trans-\raminase reaction as measured from the\rtotal contents of the reactants in the tissue\rremained close to equilibrium.  changes\rin the concentrations of the adenine nu-\rcleotides were insufficient to account for\rthe inhibition of phosphofructokinase, but\rthe results are consistent with control at this\rstep being mediated by citrate.\r'),
 (299,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'244. oxygen tension in human malignant disease under hyperbaric\rconditions\roxygen tensions were recorded continuously\rin tumours and normal tissues of 34 pa-\rtients pressurized in pure oxygen to 4 atmospheres\rabsolute.  mean rises to 620 mm.\rhg and 320 mm. hg for tumours and normal tissues\rrespectively were recorded.\rwith patients breathing air at atmospheric\rpressure 22/90 (24%) of tumour elec-\rtrodes registered po2values of less than 4 mm. hg\rcompared to only 2/39 (5%) of normal\rtissue electrodes.  the results obtained\rsuggest that oxygen polarography as a meth-\rod for determining po2 in \'solid\' tissues\rin vivo is complicated by many artefacts -\rparticularly tissue damage due to electrode\rtrauma - which reduce its value to clin-\rical research concerned with accurate\rinformation of absolute po2 values in intact\rtissues.\r'),
 (300,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7839.cortical ph and the blood-brain barrier\ra method was described for measuring\rthe ph, dc and ac potentials concurrently\ron the cerebral cortex of the adult cat,\runder conditions of controlled ventilation.\rkittens and rabbits were also studied.\rthe cortical ph response to i.v. nahco3\rwas acidic and was accompanied by a\rdc negativity, while the blood became alkaline.\rsuch an acidic response was present in\rthe rabbit and kitten.  it was not present\rin a number of other tissues in the cat,\rincluding the dura.  the cortical acidic\rresponse was not affected, qualitatively,\rby i.v. acetazolamide, prolonged hypoxia\ror 10% (v/v) co2.  it was reduced reversibly\rby 20% (v/v) co2.  it was not affected\rby removal of the arachnoid membrane.\rthe cortical ph response to an i.v. nh4+\rsalt solution was complex.  nh4c1 did not\rproduce an alkaline response.  the cortical\rph response to an alkaline or an acidic\rsodium phosphate solution was augmented\rbut not changed in its direction following\rtreatment of the cortex with n-butanol.\rthe results were interpreted in terms of\ra restriction of hco3- by the blood-brain\rbarrier, through which co2 can pass.  this\rrestriction is probably non-specific for\rinorganic ions, and perhaps for other\rsubstances.  it does not appear to be related\rto a low cerebral extracellular space,\rand is independent of substantial oxidative metabolism.\r'),
 (301,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7083. brain damage and paralysis in animals exposed to high pressure oxygen -\rpharmacological and biochemical observations\rsingle exposures of high pressure oxygen\r(ohp) at 30-66  gauge pressure caused\rcns damage and paralysis in rats and mice\rbut guinea-pigs, rabbits, and man did\rnot show such sequelae.  the cns damage\rin rats was greatly increased by cns-de-\rpressant drugs (pentobarbital, paraldehyde,\rn2o and phencyclidine) given before ex-\rposure to ohp.  the cns lesions were also\rpotentiated by raised respired pco2, by\racetazolamide and by nh4c1, whilst protection\rwas afforded by methaemoglobinae-\rmia by tham, by 2 4-dinitrophenol and by\rserotonin against the barbiturate and\rco2 potentiation of ohp brain damage.\rohp-induced brain damage was not modified\rby hypothermia (cp2), electroconvulsive\rshock treatment during ohp, cerebral x-\rirradiation, adrenalectomy or cortisone,\rslow decompression rates, spinal block\rwith local anaesthetic, \'conditioning\' of\rrats to ohp, hyper- and hypoglycaemia, or\ralterations in tissue histamine levels.\rthe results are discussed in relation to pos-\rsible biochemical mechanisms and\rtheories of oxygen poisoning.\r'),
 (302,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'8914. the effect of hypoxia on oxygen consumption of cerebral\rcortex, liver slices and of diaphragm in vitro during post-\rnatal development of the rat\roxygen consumption of slices from the liver\rand cerebral cortex and of the cut dia-\rphragm was determined in rats aged 5, 10,\r14, 20 and 25 days and in adult animals.\runder hypoxic conditions (gas phase 10%\roxygen, 90% nitrogen) oxygen consumption\rof liver slices and diaghragm is decreased\rby about 25% in all age groups.  hypoxia,\rhowever, did not affect oxygen consumption\rof slices of the cortex from 5-day-old\rrats and its inhibitory effect only appeared\rlater as the normal oxygen consumption\rstarted to rise.  the inhibitory effect of\rhypoxia was greatest in adult animals.\r'),
 (303,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5407. hypoxic-hypercapnic interaction in subjects with bilateral\rcerebral dysfunction\rto analyze cerebral influences modifying\rautonomic respiratory responses, the\rauthors compared normals and patients\rwith bilateral pyramidal tract disease for\rtheir ventilatory response to hypoxia and\rhypoxia-hypercapnia.  during eucapnia,\rthe 2 groups showed similar hypoxic\rresponses.  during hypercapnia, the ventilatory\rresponse to hypoxia was greater in the\rbrain-damaged subjects.  this apparent aug-\rmentation, however, was due entirely\rto anoxia interacting with an abnormally fa-\rcilitated carbon dioxide sensitivity\rcompared with normals, brain-damaged patients\rat pao,90-100 mm hg showed an 85%\rgreater co2 response, and at pao,50mm hg\rshowed a 79% greater co2 response.\rsince cerebral dysfunction facilitated the ven-\rtilatory response to hypoxia-hypercapnia\rcombined but not the response to hypoxia\ralone, the results imply that the 2\rrespiratory stimuli interact centrally rather than\rperipherally.\r'),
 (304,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3917. plasma free fatty acid and blood sugar levels in newborn\rinfants and their mothers\rsimultaneous plasma free fatty acid (ffa)\rand blood sugar levels were determined\rfor fasting newborn infants during the first\r24 hours of life, for their cord bloods,\rand for their mothers at delivery.  the\rfollowing observations were made.  in con-\rtrol infants the mean ffa level rose about\rthree times the cord level after birth\rand was accompanied by a 25% drop in the\rmean blood sugar level.  thereafter, the\rmean blood sugar level remained relatively\rconstant, but the mean ffa level varied\rfrom 2.5 to 3 times the cord level.  there\rwas no significant correlation between the\rlength of maternal fasting prior to delivery\rand the infant ffa level; there was,\rhowever, a significant negative correlation\rbetween the length of maternal fasting\rprior to delivery and the infant blood sugar\rlevel at 24 hours of age.  high ffa levels\roccurred in the infants of obese mothers\rand low levels were observed in infants with\rdelayed respirations, in infants of preeclamptic\rmothers, and in infants of diabetic\rmothers.\r'),
 (305,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2933. the essential fatty acid requirement of infants and the\rassessment of their dietary intake of linoleate by serum\rfatty acid analysis\rthe content of polyunsaturated fatty acids\rin serum total fatty acids was related\rto the dietary intake of linoleate in 243 infants\rtwo to four months of age and in 197\rinfants eleven to twelve months of age.  the\rcurves relating triene tetraene ratio\rto dietary linoleate indicated approximately\r1 per cent of total calories as minimal\rlinoleate requirement.  the exponential\requations relating dienoic, trienoic and\rtetraenoic acids to dietary linoleate were\rderived by computer methods.  these\ryielded constants from which the minimal\rnutrient requirement could be calculated.\rthe best estimates were obtained from the\rtriene and tetraene data for two to four\rmonths\' old infants and were found to be\rapproximately 1.4 per cent of the caloric\rintake.  the nutritive status with respect to\rlinoleate may be estimated by means\rof logarithmic regression equations.  the\requation for two to four months\' old infants\ris  log 10 dietary linoleate = -1.087 + 0.0432\r(di - tri + tetra).  the data for eleven to\rtwelve months\' old infants were found to have\rgreater scatter and give lower triene\rtetraene ratios at comparable linoleate intakes.\rthe scatter and displacement are\rconsidered to be due to supplements of solid food\rto the basic diet not considered in\rthe calculated dietary linoleate.\r'),
 (306,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'74. analytic study of the a- and b-lipoprotein micellar groups\rand of nonesterified fatty acids of the plasma in normal pregnancy\ran analytical study has been made on 39\rpatients, using a chemical method which\rallows the simultaneous detailed evaluation\rof the lipidic and a- and b-liproproteinic\rfractions of the plasma.  in addition the\rnon-esterified fatty acids have been titrated,\rthe b-proteins and the uric acid assayed,\rand numerous indices and deducible ratios\rmade from the data obtained.  the existence\rof quantitative dyslipidemia has been\rproven, starting gradually, especially in the\r4th-5th month of pregnancy, and most-\rly regarding the b-lipoproteins, prevalently\rthe slow subfractions, greater increase\rof glycerides than phosphatides and cholesterol,\rbut with a non-proportional in-\rcrease of b-proteins (lower proteinic content).\rit has, moreover, been noted that\rthere is a prevalent rise of free cholesterol in\rthe fraction of b-lipoproteins with\ra reduction of the total esterification coefficient.\rthe morphological picture of the\rlipidic rate in pregnancy shows characteristics\rwhich, according to the authors,\rare like those to be seen in the lipidic rate of\rmale presenility.\r'),
 (307,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'75. behavior of polyunsaturated fatty acids in physiological\rpregnancy\rby the enzymatic lipoxidase method of\rmacgee et al., the author measured polyun-\rsatured fatty acids (p.f.a.) in healthy\rpregnant women at full term of pregnancy.\rbefore labour there are in the blood 75-95\rmg.% of p.f.a., i.e. 10-15% more\rthan in non-pregnant women; during labour\rp.f.a. increase very much, 100-137\rmg.%, about 50% more than before labour.\r'),
 (308,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5196. effects of nutritional deficiency of unsaturated fats on\rthe distribution of fatty acids in rat liver mitochondrial phospholipids\rthe fatty acid composition of liver mitochondrial\rphospholipids from rats rendered\rdeficient in essential unsaturated fatty acids\rhas been determined, and compared\rwith that of rats fed a diet containing corn oil.\rin addition to marked reductions in\rthe amounts of linoleic and arachidonic acids\resterified at the b-position of ethanol-\ramine-, inositol-, and choline glycerophosphatides,\rthe deficiency resulted in ex-\rtensive changes in the distribution of saturated\racids at both the a- and b-positions.\rpalmitoleic and oleic acids were increased in\ramount in fat deficiency, and large\ramounts of docosatrienoic acids appeared in\rthese 3 phospholipids.  the fatty acids\rof the sphingomyelins were not altered as a\rresult of essential fatty acid deficiency.\rthe data demonstrate that each phospholipid\ris unique in the way in which its fatty\racid moieties change in response to feeding\ra fat deficient diet.\r'),
 (309,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3204. interventricular septal defects with aortic insufficiency\rsanchez f.-villaran e.\rthe coincidence of these 2 malformations\rpermits their diagnosis provided that a\rcareful evaluation is made of the hemodynamic\rand oximetric data, on the basis of\rspecific auscultatory features.  even then, a\rdifferentiation from other cardiopathies\rpatent ductus arteriosus with/without pulmonary\rhypertension, aortopulmonary sep-\rtal defect, interventricular communication,\rtruncus arteriosus, aneurysm of the\rsinus aortae ruptured into right cavities - is\rnot simple.  for this an analysis of the\rcourse of the syndrome together with the\rinformation supplied by phonocardiography,\rcatheterization, angiocardiography, radiology\rand ecg (in this order of importance)\rare indispensable.  an analysis is made of 5 cases\rin which, in the absence of ana-\rtomical confirmation, concrete data were obtained\ron which to base the diagnosis.\r'),
 (310,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2579. measurement of aortic regurgitation by upstream sampling with continuous\rinfusion of indicator\ra direct and theoretically valid method\rfor the measurement of aortic regurgitation\rinvolves the recording of indicator concentrations\rfrom the left ventricle and a down-\rstream site during aortic root injection.  however,\rthis method has yielded erratic\rresults when applied to man in the authors\'\rlaboratory when using the sudden in-\rjection technique.  therefore, the upstream\rsampling method, using continuous in-\rfusion of indicator, was evaluated in 18 patients\rwith aortic regurgitation during\rretrograde aortic and transseptal left ventricular\rcatheterization.  the continuous\rinfusion technique was compared with the technique\rof sudden injection in 10 patients\rand with aortic valvulography in 14 patients.\rmeasurements of forward flow obtained\rwith continuous infusions into the aortic root\rwere not significantly different from\rmeasurements obtained with sudden injections\rinto the pulmonary artery.  recordings\rof indicator concentrations from the left ventricle,\rduring continuous infusions into\rthe aortic root, demonstrated readily evident\requilibrium plateaus.  the resultant\rmeasurements of regurgitant flow were highly\rreproducible and not impaired by\rnonsimultaneity of upstream and downstream\rsampling.  the percentage error of\restimate at 95% confidence limits was 22% of\rthe measurement for regurgitant flow,\r13% for total flow, and 9% for the regurgitant\rfraction of total flow.  the correspond-\ring errors of estimate for the sudden injection\rtechnique were 4 times larger.  re-\rgurgitant flow by the continuous infusion method\rranged from 0.8-30.0 l/min, total\rflow from 3.0-36.0 l/min, and the regurgitant\rfraction of total flow from 12-86%.\rranking of patients by the magnitudes of regurgitant\rand total flow did not correspond\rto ranking by angiographic criteria of severity.\rhowever, an excellent correlation\rprevailed between angiographic grade and the regurgitant\rfraction of total flow,\rdemonstrating that this variable is the most meaningful\rexpression of severity.  the\rcorrelation (0.997) between the angiographic grade and\rthe regurgitant fraction\rmeasured by the continuous infusion technique was\rclearly superior to that obtained\rwith the sudden injection technique (0.894).  mild\rregurgitation was equivalent to\ra regurgitant fraction of <25%, moderate\rregurgitation to a fraction of 25-50%,\rmoderately severe regurgitation to a fraction\rof 50-75% and severe regurgitation to\ra fraction of >75%.  it is concluded that the\rupstream sampling method during con-\rtinuous infusion of indicator, because of its\rsensitivity, reliability, applicability to\rmultiple measurements, and validity in the\rpresence of mitral regurgitation is the\rmost useful method for quantifying aortic\rregurgitation in man.\r'),
 (311,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2950. aortico-left ventricular tunnel.  a cause of massive aortic regurgitation\rand of intracardiac aneurysm\rthe clinical, roentgenographic, hemodynamic\rand pathologic findings in a 14-year-\rold boy with aortico-left ventricular tunnel are\rpresented.  the accessory channel\rbetween the aorta and left ventricle resulted in\rmassive aortic regurgitation, and\rthe portion of the tunnel which traversed the\rventricular septum was aneurysmal,\rdisplaced the posterior wall of the right\rventricle and caused severe obstruction\rto right ventricular outflow.  the presence\rof associated cardiovascular anomalies,\rin this and previously reported cases,\rsuggests that the malformation is congenital\rrather than acquired.  the clinical and\rhemodynamic manifestations of aortico-left\rventricular tunnel are indistinguishable\rfrom those observed with the more common\rforms of aortic regurgitation, and the\rcorrect diagnosis can be established only by\rthoracic aortography.  the malformation\ris usually recognized in childhood; since\raortic regurgitant flow can be abolished by\rsimple closure of the aortic ostium,\rand without aortic valve replacement, the\rindications for operative treatment\rdiffer from those which apply in aortic\rregurgitation due to a valvular anomaly.\r'),
 (312,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'502. the haemodynamic implications of the bisferiens pulse\ra bisferiens carotid arterial displacement pulse\rwas recorded in 10 patients with\rsevere aortic valvular disease.  the braunwald\rtest indicated that moderately severe,\rsevere, or gross aortic regurgitation was present\rin each.  the absence of a peak\rsystolic aortic pressure gradient in certain cases,\rparticularly in those with the\rmost severe regurgitation, suggested their freedom\rfrom an element of stenosis.\rthe anacrotic wave and the peak of the aortic\rpressure pulse were found to coincide\rwith the percussion and the tidal waves of the\rsimultaneously recorded carotid ar-\rterial displacement curves.  it is suggested that\ramplitude of the peak of the anacro-\rtic wave is proportional to the rate of change of\rmomentum of the ejected blood, and\rthat the amplitude of the corresponding percussion\rwave of displacement is modified by\rthe distensibility of the artery.  the depth and shape\rof the trough between the two\rpeaks is thought to depend upon the magnitude and\rslope of the two waves rather than\rupon a venturi effect.  it is suggested that the condition\rof the arterial wall, the dia-\rstolic blood pressure, and the stroke volume can\rinfluence the pulse sufficiently to\rpreclude its use as a simple guide to the nature of\rthe aortic valve lesion.\r'),
 (313,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2753. left ventricular function following replacement of the\raortic valve.  hemodynamic responses to muscular exercise\revaluations of left ventricular myocardial\rfunction were carried out in 14 patients\r4-16 mth after stenotic or regurgitant\rmalformations of the aortic valve had been\rcorrected by valve replacement.  the\rcirculatory responses to exercise, judged by\rthe increases in cardiac output in relation\rto the increases in oxygen consumption,\rwere normal or only mildly reduced in 12\rpatients.  in 5 patients the relationships\rbetween the change in the left ventricular\rend-diastolic pressure and the alteration\rin the stroke volume were also normal, a\rfall or an increase in left ventricular\rend-diastolic pressure of less than 3 mm\rhg being accompanied by an increase in\rstroke volume.  in 8 patients, however,\rabnormal increases in the left ventricular\rend-diastolic pressure occurred during\rexercise, and in 4 the left ventricular end-\rdiastolic pressure was increased to levels\rabove 12 mm hg.  variable alterations in\rthe stroke volume accompanied these increases\rin end-diastolic pressure.  it is\rsuggested that in the 3 patients who exhibited\rsimultaneous increases in left ven-\rtricular end-diastolic pressure and stroke\rvolume, the changes were either a mani-\rfestation of the frank-starling mechanism,\ror primarily the result of a positive\rinotropic influence.  in the 5 patients who\rexhibited increases in left ventricular\rend-diastolic pressure, but no change or a\rfall in stroke volume, it is proposed\rthat a distinct depression of left ventricular\rperformance was present.  thus, while\rthe cardiac output response was adequate to\rmeet the stress of exercise in the\rmajority of the patients studied following aortic\rvalve replacement, determination\rof the relationship between the left ventricular\rend-diastolic pressure and the stroke\rvolume permitted the detection of abnormalities\rin the function of the left ventricle.\r'),
 (314,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2497. pulmonary atresia with intact ventricular septum\rwhen the pulmonary valve is atretic and\rthe ventricular septum intact, the right\rventricle usually consists of a small chamber\rwith a very thick wall capable of de-\rveloping high pressure.  this pathologic picture\ris associated with clinical findings\rsimilar to those in tricuspid atresia-cyanosis,\rdecreased pulmonary flow, left ven-\rtricular preponderance on the electrocardiogram,\rand early death.  the diagnosis\rmay be confirmed by heart catheterization and\rselective angiocardiography with in-\rjection into the right ventricle, but the risk is\rgreat.  surgery has never been suc-\rcessful in the past; but because of the equally\rhopeless prognosis on medical treat-\rment, attempts should continue to be made.\ranastomosis of the superior vena cava\rto the right pulmonary artery appears to offer\rhope of success in the future.\r'),
 (315,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1635. intra-atrial pressure measurement and electrocardiography in the\rdetailed diagnosis of atrial septal defect\rafter discussing the possibilities and\rlimitations of different methods for identifying\rthe anatomical type of atrial septal\rdefect, the authors suggest a more useful new\rmethod.  this consists in simultaneous\rrecording of both the pressure curve and\rendocavitary electrocardiogram during\rwithdrawal of the catheter from the left into\rthe right atrium.  in the ostium primum\rtype, the septal foramen has no infe-\rrior margin, and the point of the catheter\rduring retraction (unlike in the ostium\rsecundum type) rests on the intermediate\rsection of the atrioventricular septum.\rthe endocavitary electrocardiogram in the\rzone of passage between the two atria\rshows the typical pattern of the intermediate\rsection of the atrioventricular septum;\rthe pressure curve may show a pattern of the\ratrial of intravalvular type.\r'),
 (316,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1636. ventricular septal aneurysms.  a report of two cases\rtwo cases of ventriuclar cuptal aneurysm\rare reported, one in the membranous and one\rin the muscular portion.  the diagnosis was\rmade by selective left ventricular angiogra-\rphy.  it is suggested that these cases represent\rspontaneous closure of a ventricular septal\rdefect with weakness and aneurysmal formation\rdue to the high left ventricular pressure.\rboth are asymptomatic and hemodynamically\rwithin normal limits.  surgical repair\rof the aneurysms is not considered necessary.\r'),
 (317,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1642. electrode catheters and the diagnosis of ebstein\'s anomaly\rof the tricuspid valve\rthe successful surgical treatment of ebstein\'s\ranomaly calls for accurate pre-ope-\rrative assessment of the nature and severity of\rthe tricuspid valvular lesion.  the\rincreased risk of cardiac catheterization in this\rcondition has been matched by in-\rcreased experience of intracardiac techniques,\rand provided the examination is in\rskilled hands, patients with ebstein\'s anomaly\rshould be investigated in the same\rway as those with any other serious congenital\rheart lesion for whom surgery is con-\rtemplated.  the diagnostic value of electrode\rcatheters is discussed, and the intra-\rcardiac electrocardiographic features of ebstein\'s\ranomaly are illustrated.  false\rpositive and false negative records are demonstrated\rand the mechanism of their\rproduction is explained.  it is concluded that, though\rhelpful, intracardiac electro-\rcardiographic evidence should be regarded as confirmatory\rrather than diagnostic.\rrecords made with electrode catheters during cardiac\rcatheterization should be con-\rsidered only along with the other clinical,\relectrocardiographic, and radiological\rfeatures of the case, and should not be relied upon\ras the definitive method in the\rdiagnosis of ebstein\'s anomaly.\r'),
 (318,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3326. unusual aneurysm of the membranous interventricular septum\rthe case of a patient with a huge aneurysm of the\rmembranous interventricular\rseptum is presented.  this is believed to be the\rfirst such patient to have undergone\rsuccessful resection.\r'),
 (319,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'934. laevocardia with situs inversus.  a case report and a review of literature\ra case of levocardia, with\rinversion of the cham-\rbers of the heart and\rtransposition of the great vessels\rand situs inversus, has been described.\rgross cyanosis\rand clubbing were present and were due\rto a veno-arteri-\ral shunt through a right-sided superior\rvena cava open-\ring into the arterial atrium and\rpassage of venous blood\rinto the aorta through a ventricular\rseptal defect.  the\rcase was complicated with right-sided\rhemiplegia and\rwith the development of a liver abscess.\ra review of the\rliterature with prognosis and possible\retiology of the\rcondition has also been made.\r'),
 (320,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1831. postoperative aneurysm of the right ventricle\rtwelve patients with postoperative aneurysm\rof the right ventricular outflow tract\rafter corrective surgery for pulmonic valvar\rstenosis, ventricular septal defect and\rtetralogy of fallot are reported.  the literature\ris reviewed and the pathogenesis is\rdiscussed.  different diagnostic tests are evaluated\rstressing the role of roentgen\rexaminations and the importance of careful follow-up\rby intercalative chest roent-\rgenography.\r'),
 (321,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1991. ventricular septal defect with aortic regurgitation.\rmedical and pathologic aspects\rthirty-four patients with ventricular septal defect\rand aortic regurgitation, repre-\rsenting less than 5% of the patients with ventricular\rseptal defect, are discussed.\ra loud, systolic murmur, characteristic of ventricular\rseptal defect, is noted dur-\ring infancy, whereas evidences of aortic regurgitation\r(protodiastolic murmur and\rwide pulse pressure) does not usually appear until some\rtime between 2 and 10\ryears of age.  clinical and catheterization data indicate\rthat the principal hemody-\rnamic load is aortic regurgitation, whereas the\rventricular septal defect does not\rusually result in a large pulmonary blood flow or\rhigh pulmonary arterial pressure.\rin about 50% of the patients, a significant pressure\rgradient across the right ven-\rtricular outflow tract exists.  detailed pathologic\rstudies indicate that the ventricular\rseptal defects are high and anterior and encroach\rto a greater or lesser degree on\rthe membranous bulbar septum.  the right coronary\rcusp is the one most severely\rinvolved, and, by its prolapse, causes aortic\rregurgitation; the noncoronary cusp\ris always less severely affected.  the anatomic basis\rof the pressure gradient ob-\rserved across the right ventricular outflow tract is\rnot always clear.\r'),
 (322,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2431. the natural history of arrhythmias following septal defect reapir\rthe repair of 191 atrial and ventricular septal\rdefects between 1955 and 1961 was\rreviewed to determine the incidence and prognosis\rof arrhythmias related to operation.\rcases included 90 ventricular septal defects, 61\ratrial defects of the ostium secundum\rtype, and 40 of the ostium primum variety.\rnodal rhythms, second degree blocks,\rcomplete heart block, and flutter or fibrillation that\rpersisted after completion of operation\rwere analyzed, while intermittent ectopic beats,\rsinus tachycardia, and bundle branch\rblocks were excluded.  fifteen per cent of the\rpatients with ventricular defects, 17%\rwith ostium primum defects, and 35% with ostium\rsecundum defects developed abnormal\rrhythms associated with repair.  of 18 patients whose\rarrhythmias began during operation,\rthere were 8 deaths; no fatalities occurred in the 24\rpatients who developed arrhythmias\rin the postoperative period.  seven deaths were\rassociated with complete heart block and\rone with second degree block.  although only one\rhalf of the patients who developed\rarrhythmias had pulmonary artery pressure greater\rthan 30 mm. hg systolic, all fatalities\roccurred in this group.  four of the deaths followed\rsurgery with the use of the pump\roxygenator in children under 30 months of age.\rthirty-eight per cent of the abnormal\rrhythms that began in the postoperative period\rwere nodal.  flutter and fibrillation\rwere common following repair of atrial secundum\rdefects in patients over 15 yr. of age\rbut did not occur in younger patients.  deaths from\rheart block occurred in the first 30 days\rfollowing operation except one, 5 months later.\rsurvivors of complete heart block reverted\rto a less serious arrhythmia or normal rhythm\rwithin 3 months.\r'),
 (323,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1021. left ventricular angiocardiography in the study of ventricular\rseptal defects\rsixty-five cases of ventricular septal defect\rwere studied by left angiocardiography.\rthe left ventricle was entered by retrograde\rarterial catheterization with a catheter\rhaving a j-shaped tip.  this procedure appears\rto be little, or no more, hazardous\rthan right-sided angiocardiography.  ventricular\rseptal defects may be divided into\r5 types, depending on their location in the ventricular\rseptum.  the anatomic and\rradiological features of the septum and septal defects\rare described.  selective in-\rjection of contrast material into the left ventricle\ropacifies the blood passing through\rthe defect in the septum and permits preoperative\rlocalization of the defect in rela-\rtion to identifiable anatomic landmarks.  multiple\rdefects of the septum are well de-\rmonstrated.  such information may be of\rconsiderable value to the surgeon under-\rtaking repair of the septum.  left ventriculography,\roften combined with supraval-\rvular aortography, has been used, when indicated,\rto differentiate between mitral\rinsufficiency and ventricular septal defect and in\rthe detection of other cardiac ano-\rmalies whose manifestations are marked by those\rof the septal lesion.  this tech-\rnique is well suited to the postoperative study of\rpatients following repair of the\rseptal defect and for follow-up studies in patients\rnot operated upon to clarify the\rnatural history of defects in different portions of\rthe ventricular septum.\r'),
 (324,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4105. free fatty acid metabolism in chinese hamsters\rin normal chinese hamsters (cricetulus\rgriseus) the mean concentration of free\rfatty acids (ffa) in serum varied from\rgroup to group, but was (1) consistently 4\rto 9 times greater than in rats, dogs,\ror man; (2) slightly higher than in syrian\rhamsters; (3) two- to four-fold higher\rthan in fasting or alloxan-diabetic rats.  the\repididymal adipose tissue of the chinese\rhamster (1) had initial concentrations of\rffa comparable to those in the rat and\rsyrian hamster; (2) released, in the same\rtime interval, 8- to 10-fold more ffa\rin vitro than this tissue of the rat; (3) had\rhigher concentrations of ffa after incubation\rthan the incubated tissue of the rat.\rthe retroperitoneal (perirenal) adipose tissue\rof the chinese hamster was less ac-\rtive in release of fatty acids in vitro than the\repididymal, but was, however, more\ractive than the epididymal adipose tissue of\rthe rat.  these characteristics of ffa\rmetabolism in the chinese hamster were\rapparently attributable to species, not to\rage, diet, or sex.  in the chinese hamster,\rthe weight of the epididymal adipose tis-\rsue per gram of body was relatively high.\rit appears that in this species the rate of\rrelease of fatty acids from adipose tissue\ris great, leading to high ffa concentra-\rtions in serum.  in chinese hamster and rat\radipose tissues in vitro, glucose and in-\rsulin (separately) reduced the rate of release\rof ffa and the amount of ffa in the\rtissues, but glucose and insulin together\rproduced the greatest reduction.  the net\rreduction in ffa release by glucose and\rinsulin in vitro was greater in tissue from\rthe chinese hamster.  insulin markedly\rincreased glucose uptake by the adipose tis-\rsues of both species.  the possible relation\rof the results to spontaneous diabetes in\rthe chinese hamster is discussed.\r'),
 (325,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'95. changes in serum non-esterified fatty acid levels in spon-\rtaneous and in oxytocin induced labour\rthe nonesterified fatty acid (nefa)\rconcentration of serum rises progressively\rduring the course of normal labor.\rthe rise appears to be related to the duration\rof labor.  the use of oxytocin to induce\rand stimulate labor does not alter the normal\rpattern of rise in nefa provided it is\rgiven in physiologic dosage.  the levels of\rnefa in the umbilical vein and the\rumbilical artery at delivery are comparable and\ralways significantly lower than the\rmaternal level.  the maternal/fetal ratio varies\rbetween 1.7 1 and 3.9 1 in this series.\rfollowing delivery the nefa levels begin\rto fall almost immediately.  the rate\rof fall is 10-30% of the delivery value in the 1st\rhour, 30-50% within 18 hr. and 50-70% within 36 hr.\r'),
 (326,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1545. the effect of combined glucose and insulin infusions on\rthe lipoid and carbohydrate metabolism of the parturient\rwoman and of the fetus\rthe infusion of glucose with insulin during delivery\rwas used by the authors pri-\rmarily in order to determine, whether the utilization\rof glucose can be enhanced\runder these conditions.  they wanted to investigate,\rwhether the increase of unesteri-\rfied fatty acids in the cord blood which takes place\rafter a sole glucose infusion in\rthe mother, could be caused by the low capability\rof glucose utilization in the fetus.\rthe infusion during delivery which consisted of the\rapplication of 500 ml of 10%\rglucose and 16 u of insulin over a period of 30 min.\rbrought about a greater decrease\rof unesterified fatty acids in the parturient woman\ras compared with the infusion of\rglucose exclusively.  the reason for this result\ris thought to be due to a better utili-\rzation of glucose which is favorably influenced\rby insulin.  during the infusion of\rglucose with insulin, an increase in the values\rof lactic and pyruvic acid took place\rin the parturient women; this was probably due\rto an accelerated glycolysis and an\rincreased production of lactic acid, but not\rcaused by a higher share of the anaerobic\rmetabolism.  in the cord blood, there were\rlikewise increased values of lactic and py-\rruvic acid as a reflection of the higher values\rof these substances in the mother.  the\rformation of these products of metabolic\rbreakdown by the fetus, however, was not\rsignificantly increased.  after infusion of\rglucose with insulin, the other investigated\rparameter values, including those of the levels\rof unesterified fatty acids are found\rin the cord blood in similar amounts as after\rinfusion of glucose alone.  these re-\rsults cannot reliably prove the passage of\rinsulin through the placenta especially\rafter a continued study of the metabolic values\rin newborns.  as a proof of the passage\rof insulin through the placenta could not be\restablished, it is possible that after an\rintake of insulin the increase of unesterified\rfatty acids in the cord blood could be\rcaused by a relative insufficiency of the insular\rapparatus of the fetus.  the most\rprobable reason for the increase of unesterified\rfatty acids is the different depo-\rsition and metabolization of unesterified fatty\racids in the course of intrauterine\rlife.\r'),
 (327,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1547. glucose and nonesterified fatty acid levels in maternal\rand cord plasma\rthe authors established in 44 healthy women\rat the moment of delivery the contents\rof glucose and free fatty acids in the blood\rof the mother and of the umbilical cord.\rthe concentration of both substances was\rsignificantly higher in the mother than in\rthe infant.  the relation for free fatty acids\rwas 1.7 1, that for glucose 1.3 1.  the\rrelation glucose fatty acids in the mother was\rsignificantly different from that in the\rinfant.\r'),
 (328,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3294. epinephrine infusions in normal and toxemic pregnancies.\rii. plasma glucose, nonesterified fatty acid, and epineph-\rrine-norepinephrine alterations\rseven controls and 9 preeclamptic patients\rwere infused with different amounts of\repinephrine.  plasma nefa, glucose and\rcatecholamines were determined before,\rduring and after epinephrine infusion.  the\rtoxemic patient responds to the metabolic\reffects of infused epinephrine in a manner\rsimilar to that of the normal pregnant\rpatient.  the increased levels of nefa in\rpregnant patients are explained by a com-\rplicated biochemical mechanism involving\ran increased availability of cortisone-like\rsteroids, slightly increased amounts of thyroid,\rhormones, etc., resulting in an\ralteration of carbohydrate utilization.  the study\rleads to the conclusion that epi-\rnephrine is not an etiologic agent in toxemia of pregnancy.\r'),
 (329,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'766. a lipid-mobilizing substance in the serum of pregnant wo-\rmen, of probable placental origin\ra substance capable of inducing free fatty\racid (ffa) release was found in the sera\rof 12 from 13 pregnant women.  the rat\repididymal fat pad was used for bioassay.\rthis substance circulates in late pregnancy\rand disappears within 5 days post partum.\rit is present in crude placental extracts and\ris removed by their deproteination.  it\ris nondialyzable.  application of pituitary\rextraction procedure to placentae yielded\ractive fractions where pituitary growth\rhormone is usually found.  in accordance with\rthese facts a hypothesis concerning a part\rof metabolic changes occurring during preg-\rnancy was pronounced as follows.  the\rdescribed substance diminishes maternal glu-\rcose consumption through the elevation of\rplasma free fatty acids, or by direct in-\rhibition of glucose uptake, or both.  this\rpermits a preferential shunting of glucose\rto the fetus.  at the same time, increased\rplasma free fatty acid levels would serve\ras the alternative maternal energy substrate.\relevated maternal insulin levels during\rlate pregnancy stabilize the degree of maternal\rlipid mobilization.  the contrainsulin\rproperties of a substance capable of mobilizing\rfree fatty acids and inhibiting mater-\rnal glucose utilization would pose a diabetogenic\rchallenge, and in the face of com-\rpromised maternal insulin reserves, provoke\rovert or worsen existing diabetes\rmellitus.\r'),
 (330,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3682. metabolism of free fatty acids during perinatal life of lambs\rthere is a rapid rise of free fatty acids\rin blood plasma after birth in newborn\rlambs.  this study confirms this rise,\rcaused by an augmented mobilization of these\racids from the tissues.  norepinephrine\reasily mobilizes free fatty acids in adult\rewes.  in newborn lambs this special effect\ris lacking, though cardiovascular re-\rsponses are clearly demonstrable.  blocking\rthe sympathetic nervous system in\rnewborn lambs inhibits the rapid rise of free\rfatty acids after birth.  this is com-\rpatible with the concept, that increased activity\rof these sympathetic nerves after\rbirth is an important factor for free fatty acids\rmobilization.  during intrauterine\rlife there is an ample study of carbohydrates\rand the organism uses them as an\renergy source.  hypoglycaemia resulting from\rsudden carbohydrate deprivation at\rbirth, demonstrates with rising free fatty acids\rthe change-over to (tissue) fat as\rmain source of energy.\r'),
 (331,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1163. the effect of glucose infusions on the lipoid and the\rcarbohydrate metabolism of the parturient woman and\rthe fetus\rin 20 parturient women who were given glucose\rinfusions during the expulsive stage\rof labor, the authors were able to observe an unusual\rhyperglycemia and a decrease\rin unesterified fatty acids (uefa).  the uefa-level\rusually increases regularly\rduring delivery.  likewise, the values of esterified\rfatty acids (efa) showed an in-\rcrease above the normally present levels in women\rwho had received a glucose in-\rfusion during the expulsive stage of labor.  the\rresults show that during delivery\rboth hyperglycemia and the increase in lipoids\rare predominantly due to the energy\rdemands of the organism.  however, there is also\revidence that other, hitherto un-\rknown factors may play a role.  in the fetus,\rthe infusion of glucose leads to an in-\rcreased glucose retention.  the infusion, however,\rdoes not bring about a decrease,\rbut, contrary to the expectations, an increase\rin the uefa-values.  in general,\rsuch a reaction is not found in any of the\rsubsequent periods of life.  further inves-\rtigations were conducted in order to find an\rexplanation for the paradox uefa-\rreaction.  as shown by an analysis of the lactic\racid and the pyruvic acid values, the\rincrease in the uefa can most probably not be\rattributed to an impairment in the\rfetal metabolic conditions.  the administration\rof physiological saline infusions to\r10 parturient women under equal conditions\rrevealed that the cause for the uefa-\rincrease can apparently neither be found in\rhemodynamic changes due to the infusion\rnor in changes of the electrolyte balance, but\rrather in an adaptation insufficiency\rof the fetal islet cells, respectively in a different\rfat mobilization or fat deposition.\r'),
 (332,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1320. the plasma free fatty acid composition and blood glucose\rof normal and diabetic pregnant women and of their new-\rborns\rthe blood glucose and plasma ffa content\rand composition of the newborns of\rnormal women, gestational diabetics, and\rinsulin-dependent diabetics were analyzed.\rnormal maternal ffa levels were twice the\rfetal values; by 2 hr of age ffa in-\rcreased 4-fold over initial values in normal\rinfants, while infants of gestational\rdiabetics had a 3-fold rise, and those of\rinsulin dependent diabetics only 2-fold.\rblood sugar at the same time decreased and\rthere was an inverse relationship be-\rtween blood glucose in the normal infants and\rffa.  this relationship is altered in\rthe infant of the diabetic mother.  gas\rchromatography of plasma indicated a higher\rratio of unsaturated to saturated ffa in\rmothers compared to infants.  no pattern\rdifferences were noted between the normal\rand diabetic mothers, except that the\rlatter had higher oleic acid.  in the initial 2\rhr of life, the patterns changed, although\rno differences were noted between infants\rof diabetic mothers and normals.  the\robservations suggest  (1) the metabolic\rinterrelationships of glucose and ffa in\rthe normal infant are different from those\rin the infant of the diabetic mother, the\rlatter infant having a state of physiologic\rhyperinsulinism; (2) plasma ffa in the\rfetus is derived from both fetal fat synthesis\ras well as placental transfers; (3) the\rinfant of the diabetic mother does not differ\rfrom the normal as regards ffa com-\rposition.\r'),
 (333,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3107. lipids of human placenta\rthe chloroform-methanol-soluble\rcomponents of 4 human placentae were isolated\rby rubber membrane dialysis and gas\rchromatography, and analysed.  two thirds\rof the total lipids consisted of phosphatides\rwith lecithin as the main component\r(22.5%), colamine cephalin (13%)\rand sphingomyelin (7.5%).  free cholesterol form-\red 14% of the total lipids, while\rcholesterol esters accounted for 6% and trigly-\rcerides for 13%.  investigation of\rthe phosphatide fatty acids by gas chromatography\rshowed a content of 60% saturated,\r27% simple unsaturated and 12% polyunsaturated\racids.  the fatty acids of the triglycerides\rconsisted of about 50% saturated and\r25% each of simple and polyunsaturated\racids.  the polyenoic acids (30%) of the\rcholesterol fatty acids had a high content\rof linoleic acid, about one quarter that\rof the total acids.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (334,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'377. experimental study of sensitization to nickel\rsensitization was effected by epicutaneous\rapplication of nickel sulfate in\r15 guinea-pigs.  it was confirmed by the\rappearance of eczematiform lesions in\rskin tests with nickel sulfate.  for maintenance\rof the animals in good general\rcondition it was necessary to add vit. c and\rantiinfective agents to the diet.\rfor this reason the allergenicity of the ni\rsalt had to be augmented by the use\rof adjuvants (freund\'s complete adjuvant or alum).\rsuch adjuvants act by\rstimulating the res.  the method for\rsensitization of guinea-pigs to metal salts\rhaving been worked out, it is now proposed\rto study the mechanism of such\rsensitization, the biological disturbances\rinvolved and the possible existence\rof cross-sensitizations.\r'),
 (335,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2285. some remarks on the nickel dermatitis\rby non-occupational contact\rthis dermatitis represents 2% of the\rskin diseases observed at the\rallergologic outpatients department of\rthe dermatological clinic of milan.\rthe disorder is more frequent in women\rand prefers the thighs (girdles, keys)\rand the wrist (watch); its incubation\rperiod is generally long and a peculiar\rpapulo-vesicular follicular and lichenoid eruption often follows.\r'),
 (336,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3200. studies on the binding of protein by nickel.\rwith special reference to\rits role in nickel sensitivity\rthe reaction between nickel and proteins\rwas studied using the technique of\requilibrium dialysis.  in most of the experiments\rcrystalline bovine serum\ralbumen was used.  the nickel-protein complex\rwas of low stability, the quantity\rof nickel bound by the protein being dependent\ron the concentration of free\rnickel ions, the ph, and the particular protein used.\rthe sites of binding of\rthe nickel ions were primarily carboxyl and amino\rgroups.  the author concluded\rthat it was unlikely that nickel behaved as a\rhapten capable of initiating an\rallergic response.\r'),
 (337,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2596. experimental nickel contact sensitization in man\rin 16 of 172 male prisoners contact-type\rdelayed hypersensitivity was induced\rexperimentally by repeated application of\r25% nicl2 in a 0.1% sodium lauryl\rsulphate solution on the skin.  test reactions\rwith 5% nicl2 with occlusion\rwere found to be irritating.  no experimentally\rsensitized subject demonstrated\rclinical sensitivity to the metal in his environment.\r'),
 (338,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1013. hand eczema\rthe clinical aspects of 106 cases of hand\reczema are reviewed.  the clinical\rtypes are defined  nummular eczema, nickel\rallergy, atopic dermatitis,\rhyperkeratotic dermatitis of the palms, hand\reczema post partum, mycotic eczema,\rcontact dermatitis, occupational eczema and\ridiopathic eczema.  the results\rof the patch tests, the influence of\rpsychological and psychiatric factors,\rthe effect of water and cleansers, the\rdiagnosis, treatment and prognosis are\rdiscussed.  in 39% no significant causative\rfactor could be found.  in\rmany cases where causative factors could\rbe identified these were probably\rno more than contributory, superimposed\rupon an underlying idiopathic eczema.\r'),
 (339,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'670.  steroid aerosol spray in contact dermatitis.\rprophylactic use with\rparticular reference to nickel hypersensitivity\rproper use of topical aerosol dexamethasone\r(decadron) spray affords complete\rprotection to patients with nickel sensitivity.\rthis clinical result is\rconfirmed by the results of patch testing\rnickel-sensitive patients with a\r5% nickel sulfate solution and nickel coins.\ra combination of dexamethasone and\ran isopropylmyristate film is necessary\rfor successful prophylaxis; the\rindividual components alone do not protect\rthese patients.  clinical and patch\rtest results indicate that a moderate degree\rof protection is afforded to\rpatients with paraphenylenediamine sensitivity.\rpatch test results indicate\rthat the spray does not protect against\rpoison ivy and ragweed oleoresin,\rpotassium dichromate, certain rubber accelerators,\rand monobenzyl ether of\rhydroquinone.  it affords a moderate protection\ragainst formaldehyde.  no tests\rwere done with patients with formaldehyde\rhypersensitivity.  a fair degree of\rprotection was obtained by the use of the spray\rin housewives eczema presumably\rdue to irritants present in soap and detergents.\r'),
 (340,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2078. the pathogenesis of contact eczema due\rto detergents for domestic use\rthe thesis is maintained that eczema due\rto household detergents is\rpathogenically linked with allergic contact\rsensitization to metallic salts,\respecially chromium and nickel.  in a series\rof 20 cases of contact eczema\rattributable to detergents, the existence of\rsensitization to these metals was\rdemonstrated by the patch test.  likewise,\rin the analysis of 9 samples of\rdifferent detergents used for washing,\rin all of them chromium and nickel were\rfound to be present in a proportion which,\rfor either of these metals, varied\rbetween 1 and 5 p.p.m.\r'),
 (341,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4010. studies of nickel carcinogenesis.\rthe subcellular partition of nickel\rin lung and liver following inhalation of nickel carbonyl\rwistar rats were exposed by inhalation to\rnickel carbonyl either once only\rat a concentration of 80 ppm for 60 minutes\r(0.60 mg ni(co)4/l.air), or\rrepeatedly at 4 ppm (0.03 mg ni(co)4/l. air)\rfor 30 minutes 3 times weekly\rfor 1 year.  they were killed 24 hours after\r(the final period of) exposure.\rnuclear, mitochondrial, microsomal and supernatant\rfractions were isolated\rfrom lung and liver homogenates and measurements\rof the nickel, nitrogen\rand rna-content of each subcellular fraction\rwere made.  the greatest ratios\rof nickel to nitrogen were in the nuclear\rfractions of both liver and lung,\rbut increased amounts of nickel were also found\rin the microsomal and\rsupernatant fractions of both liver and lung\rand in the mitochondrial\rfraction of lung.\r'),
 (342,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'188. studies of nickel carcinogenesis;metastasizing pulmonary tumors in rats\rinduced by the inhalation of nickel carbonyl\rin a combined series of studies, 6 out of 409 rats (n.b. only 195 survived for\rmore than 3 wk.) exposed to nickel carbonyl developed pulmonary carcinoma\rwith metastases.  the lesions included the common types of pulmonary cancer,\rsquamous cell carcinoma, adenocarcinoma and anaplastic carcinoma.  all of\rthe pulmonary lesions were found between 24 and 27 mth. after the initial\rexposure to nickel carbonyl.  the amount of nickel found capable of inducing\rlung cancer in the rat was comparable to the amount of nickel inhaled by\rpersons smoking less than 15 cigarettes per day for a period of a year.  the\rmean weight of rats chronically exposed to nickel carbonyl was found to be\rconsistently less than that of the control rats throughout the entire 3-year\rperiod of study.\r'),
 (343,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'189. influence of age, sex and glandular extirpation on muscle carcinogenesis\rin rats\rthe carcinogenic effect of a single intramuscular injection of nickel sulphide\rin an aqueous suspension to which penicillin g had been added was compared\rin male and female castrated, hypophysectomized or intact, rats of different\rages.  the response seemed most marked in intact females injected when 2 mth.\rold.  castrated or hypophysectomized 2-month old females were less\rresponsive.  one-month old intact males were more responsive than 2-month or\r3-month old intact males, 1-month old castrated males, or 1-month old\rintact females.  more data would be required before firm conclusions could be\rdrawn from these results.\r'),
 (344,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3176. studies of trace metal metabolism  electron paramagnetic resonance of\rmanganese in ribonucleic acids\rthe electron paramagnetic resonance spectrum pattern of manganese was\rreadily detected in all of the samples of rna.  the resonance patterns\rindicate that manganese is present in rna in a divalent state and suggest\rthat manganese is located at the center of a distorted octahedron of oxygen\ratoms.  from the intensity of nominally forbidden resonances, the crystal\rfield splitting parameter d was estimated to be 0.02 cm -1.\r'),
 (345,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4790. metal chelates as potential reactivators of organic phosphate poisoned\racetylcholinesterase\ras part of a study to investigate metal chelates as possible reactivators\rof phosphate poisoned acetylcholinesterase, it is shown that chelates act\ras inhibitors of the enzyme.  in addition, copper and nickel chelates of\r2-pyridinealdoxime catalyze the decomposition of dfp and sarin.  compared to\r2-pam, however, these chelates are very poor reactivators, probably because\rof an improper alignment of the oxine oxygen in the chelate-enzyme complex.\r'),
 (346,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3446. effect of nicl2 on an isolated ranvier node\ran attempt was made to explain the extreme prolongation of the nodal\rpotential by 0.1-1.0 mm nicl2 in terms of the ionic theory.  the effects of\rnicl2 at room temperature are similar to those of temperature reduction\rdecreased maximum rate of rise of the action potential, lengthened action\rpotential duration, elevated threshold, increased tendency for repetitive\ractivity; in addition, the amplitude of the action potential is slightly\rincreased.  the long-lasting plateaus of the responses obtained under the\rcombined influence of nicl2 and temperature reduction are shortened by cathodal\rpolarization, strong anodal polarization and decrease of (na)0.  the plateau\rcan be prematurely terminated by short anodal pulses of critical amplitude;\rshort cathodal pulses reduce the duration of the plateau gradually with\rincreasing pulse strength.  increased (k)0 prolongs plateau duration; the\rsteep repolarization phase which normally terminates the plateau is\rreplaced by a long lasting after-depolarization with stepwise potential\rdecline.\rthe amplitude of k-depolarization is not influenced by nicl2 or temperature\rreduction.  1.0 mm nicl2 changes the relation between maximum rate of\rrise and steady-state polarization; the potential change required for 50%\rsodium inactivation is +8mv in normal ringer\'s solution and +16mv in the\rpresence of 1.0 mm nicl2 (22 c.).  1.0 mm nicl2 increases the time constant\rof delayed rectification as measured in na-poor solutions at 4 c. by a factor\rof about 2.  the decrease of action potential under cathodal polarization is\rslightly delayed by nicl2.  it is concluded that prolongation of the nodal\raction potential by nicl2 is due to delayed and reduced inactivation of na\rpermeability and delayed increase of k permeability; part of the nicl2-effect\rcould be explained by assuming competition between ni++ and ca++ for specific\rsites at the membrane.\r'),
 (347,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2302. the carcinogenic activities of n-hydroxy-2-acetylaminofluorene and its\rmetal chelates as a function of retention at the injection site\rthe carcinogenic activities of s.c. administered\rn-hydroxy-2-acetylaminofluorene\r(n-hydroxy-aaf) and a variety of its metal chelates indicate that greater\ractivity locally is associated with a longer retention of the chelates at the\rsite of injection with a slow release of n-hydroxy-aaf to the surrounding\rtissue.  no tumors were obtained at the sites of 4 injections of n-hydroxy-aaf\r(3.2 mg. /injection), but 4 and 16 of 20 rats developed sarcomas at the\rsites of 8 and 16 injections, respectively.  the nickelous, cobaltous, ferric,\ror cupric chelates induced moderate to high incidences of sarcomas with 1 or 4\rinjections; in these cases one-half of the administered n-hydroxy-aaf was\rretained at the injection site for 4-50 days.  the manganous and zinc chelates\rand the potassium salt were less active at the injection site; the\rhalf-retention times for these ranged from 2.5 hr. to 2.5 days.  the comparable\rhalf-retention time for n-hydroxy-aaf was about 2 hr.  injection of the metal\rderivatives s. c. with short half-retention times resulted in higher incidences\rof mammary tumors than injection of the derivatives with half-retention\rtimes of 4 or more days.  when administered in the food the cupric chelate\rof n-hydroxy-aaf induced the same spectrum of tumors as n-hydroxy-aaf,\rbut the incidences were lower.  while the prolonged retention of the material\rat the injection site may account for the greater carcinogenic activities of\rthe metal chelates, serious consideration must also be given to the possible\rimportance of chelation of carcinogens or their metabolites to cellular\rconstituents.\r'),
 (348,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'12083. generation of action potentials in single ranvier\'s nodes of isolated\rfrog nerve fibres under the influence of nickel and cadmium ions (russian)\rby experimenting on single ranvier\'s nodes of frog isolated nerve fibres it\rwas shown that, along with a marked prolongation of the repolarization\rphase of the action potential (ap), ni and cd ions also caused a rise of\rthe critical membrane depolarization level and an increased ap amplitude\rwith somewhat reduced steepness of its ascending phase.  ni and cd ions\rrestored the ap generation in the nodes of ranvier altered by a 0.01% procaine\rsolution, by an excess of potassium ions 00mm/1. of kcl) or by slight\rmechanical injury during dissection.  it was only with a reduced na\rconcentration in the medium that the restoration of ap could be achieved.\rni and cd ions considerably slowed down and weakened the cathodal rise of the\rcritical level and the ap reduction.  cysteine (10 -2 to 10 -3 m)\reliminated all the effects of the mentioned ions.  a suggestion is made that by\rbinding the sh-groups of the nerve fibre proteins, nickel and cadmium reduce\rthe rate of inactivation and the increase of potassium permeability in\rdepolarization and also weaken the initial inactivation and the increase of\rpotassium permeability in depolarization, as well as weaken the initial\rinactivation of the membrane (i-h), whenever this happened to be raised by\rprevious influences.\r'),
 (349,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1287. agnostic alexia and constructive apraxia with regressive evolution in\ra child of 12 yr. of age\rafter an acute encephalopathy, the etiology of which could not be determined,\ra boy of 11 yr. and 10 mth. of age developed a syndrome of agnostic alexia\rand constructive apraxia which was remarkably pure.  the intellectual\rfunctions were normal as determined by iq tests, speech was not disturbed\reither.  the child could not read or copy a text, but was fully able to write\r(both freely and dictated).  the patient could not read what he had written.\rthis shows the characteristic features of agnostic apraxia.  motor activity and\rperformance were normal, but the child had extreme difficulty in constructing\rgeometric forms, even elementary, either spontaneously or by copying.\rthis remarkable syndrome disappeared, and during its involution it was\rfollowed up.\r'),
 (350,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1288. the symptomatology of the parietal cerebral syndrome of the dominant\rhemisphere.  parietal dyslexia and conduction aphasia\rthis is a very comprehensive study on a patient.  in the beginning there was\ra pronounced gerstmann\'s syndrome, with autotopagnosia for parts of the face,\rdyspraxia and constructive apraxia and dyslexia.  the autotopagnosia and mild\rleft-right disturbances showed marked regression.  actual hemianopsia was\rnot observed, but tachistoscopy revealed that perception of the right field of\rvision was poor.  audiometric examination showed a conduction deafness and\rdisturbed binaural word synthesis.  the disturbances were examined\rmeticulously and tested for symptom relationships, which became evident\rin the various factors concerned with creative ability.\r'),
 (351,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4544. observations on colour agnosia\ra 56-year-old right-handed man, following the formation of a left posterior\rsubdural hematoma developed \'spelling dyslexia\' and impaired picture\rinterpretation, which resolved, and color agnosia, which persisted.  the latter\rimpaired the use both of color information and of the names of the colors.\rthis may be explained as a disorder impairing the recollection and formation\rof associations between color names and other types of information, with\rresulting interference in any task in which colors or their names have\rto be placed in a specific context.  the alternative views of willbrand (1887)\rthat here a limited dysphasia, and of sittig (1921) that a recognition defect\ris simultaneously present, cannot be excluded.  in the present and in\rpreviously reported cases the causative lesion seems to have been posteriorly\rlocated in the dominant hemisphere, in the borderland between the area\rreceiving visual input and the language or verbal recording area.\r'),
 (352,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'652. bitemporal hemianopia\rtwo stages can be distinguished in the development of bitemporal hemianopia\rin hypophyseal tumors.  the first stage is the consequence of direct pressure\rof the tumor on the lower side of the chiasma.  hence its start with upper\rquadrantic field defects.  in this stage the visual disorder is amenable to\rprompt and complete restoration.  with progressing growth of the tumor the\rsecond stage follows as consequence of constriction by the circle of vessels.\rin this stage nerve fibers are being destroyed.  therefore, after pressure\rrelieving operation no restoration occurs, or to a limited extent only.\r'),
 (353,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'387. ophthalmic manifestations of bilateral non-occipital cerebral lesions\rtwelve patients are described with neuro-ophthalmic symptoms resulting from\rbilateral cerebral lesions in areas other than the occipital lobes.  the\rsymptoms and signs are categorized as follows  group i  those showing\rpredominant disturbances in visual object recognition (visual agnosia) and\rdisturbances of visual spatial localization.  group iia  those having defects\rin voluntary control of eye movements (ocular motor apraxia).  group iib  those\rwith persistent palsies of conjugate gaze.  although these symptoms may be\rpresent to some extent with unilateral lesions, they are much more profound\rand less able to be compensated with bilateral lesions.  the evidence in the\rpresent cases suggests a biparieto-temporal localization for the lesions\rcausing visual agnosia, disturbances of spatial localization, and ocular motor\rapraxia, and a more frontal localization for the lesions causing prolonged\rparalysis of conjugate gaze.\r'),
 (354,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1774. the speed of reading.  basis for a clinical function test\ras an easily comprehensible measure for the capability of reading, the author\rrecommends the determination of the reading speed for supplementation of the\rocular function tests.  the method in question constitutes a senso-motor\refficiency test which is of value in the appraisal of haemianopias, paracentral\rand central defects of the visual field, in squint amblyopias and in\rspontaneous nystagmus.\r'),
 (355,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1303. the problem of visual agnosia\rthis is a critical assessment of the ancient and modern theories on visual\ragnosia.  an original description of the subjective world of these patients is\ralso given.  visual agnosia is a rare disorder, but it has led to comprehensive\rdiscussions, for instance, by the fact that the problem of normal visual\rperception is always involved.  bay\'s view, which denies the existence of\ragnosia as a separate phenomenon in perception disorders, is especially dealt\rwith.  it is affirmed that no case has been described in the literature\rin which visual agnosia is decidedly a pure and isolated phenomenon.\rmostly there are also disturbances in the intellectual interpretation of visual\rdata.  often there is metamorphopsia or asthenopia.  there is no localized\rprestriate gnostic center for visual impressions.  the older concept of higher\rand lower levels of perception and perception disorders is also criticized.\rvisual perception is not a passive, but a very active process, in which\rneurophysiological and psychological aspects are involved.\reach of these can be\rdisturbed, leading to various degrees of visual perception disturbance.\r'),
 (356,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2496. dysbarism among hyperbaric personnel\ra survey of the effects of hyperbaric exposure on 62 medical personnel exposed\rto 1,516 compressions and decompressions revealed no case of permanent ill\reffect.  pain in the ears or sinuses was the most common symptom but could\roften be ameliorated or avoided by the valsalva technique of forced\rinsufflation with the nostrils occluded.  the most serious symptoms\rencountered were 3 episodes of transient homonymous hemianopsia.  the\rclassic symptoms of decompression sickness\rextremity pains (the \'bends\'), pulmonary or\rsubsternal distress (the \'chokes\'), and skin dysesthesias occurred only rarely,\rand were so mild or so fleeting as to require no treatment.  a further\rreduction in symptoms without increase in decompression time may be\robtained by the inhalation of 100% oxygen during decompression stops at\rpressures below 26.8 pounds per square inch gauge (psig).\r'),
 (357,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2996. visual static agnosia with special reference to literal agnosic alexia\rthis is a report of 2, right-handed adults who had \'visual agnosia (with\rpredominance of literal alexia)\'.  recognition of letters was poor or\rnonexistent when the patient simply viewed the material (static method) but\rif the letter was slowly developed for them, they were able to identify it\r(dynamic method).  one patient had vascular pathology which was considered\rto involve both occipital lobes and the 2nd patient had the surgical removal of\rthe left occipital lobe for an angioma.\r'),
 (358,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1388. optic agnosia  semeiological and pathogenetic aspects\rthe authors discuss the classical concept of agnosia and make a survey of\rpathogenetical factors which determine its phenomenology.  the original and\rtraditional concept of such a term implied the loss of the capacity to\rrecognize objects, when the functions of sense organs are undamaged.  the\rpsychological studies on perception and the modern physiology of\rvision allow to avoid the dichotomy between sensation and perception and\rto affirm their identity.  cortex and recptors are closely bound and\rfunction in unison.\revery cortical alteration is thus reflected in sensorial functions; it is\rtherefore that on practical semeiological grounds it is possible to obtain a\rcongruous information of the corresponding cortical functionality through an\rexploration of sense organs carried out by suitable means.  since we are\rconfronted with functional changes, exploration methods must be fit to evaluate\rdynamic aspects of perception in connection with the temporalization and\rspatialization of stimuli.  such methods are now quite numerous and often\rcomplex  a particular stress is laid on local adaptation, flicker fusion, and\rtachistoscopy on account of their significance and suitability.  by such\rmethods it is possible to show those functional deficits or pathological\rdisturbances of sensorial functions which are also behind the pathology of\rvisual recognition.  fluctuation, extinction, alteration in the perception of\rmovement, both real and apparent, changes in adaptation to light and\rdarkness are all phenomena which can be detected instrumentally and which,\rat the same time, may be of determinant importance for the onset of \'agnosic\'\rbehaviour.  the complexity of the latter, on the other hand, cannot always\rbe explained by sensorial disturbances only  other mechanisms, with a function\rcomplementary but not less indispensable to the dynamics of perceptive\rprocesses, may intervene and interfere in it.  on the basis of the latest\rneurophysiological data the attention is called to ocular motility and\rproprioceptivity, centrifugal innervation of sensorial receptors, and\rvestibular afferences.  a particular clinico-pathogenetical significance is\rattached by the authors to the association of lateral visual disturbances with\raltered proprioceptive and kinesthetic information from the corresponding\rhalf-body  such association in fact is nearly always present among the factors\rresponsible for the most strictly \'spatial\' errors of \'agnosic\' pathology.  in\rthe light of these pathogenetical considerations as well as of suitable\rsemeiological findings, the authors deem it convenient to divide their cases\rinto 3 categories with distinct clinical features  (a) cases in which altered\rvisual behaviour may be related to changes of the visual function and of its\rcomplementary mechanisms; (b) cases in which hemianopia is associated with\ra homolateral deficit of somatic proprioceptivity; (c) cases in which the\rchanges in behaviour are chiefly, but not only, due to a dissolution\rof the symbolic sphere.\r'),
 (359,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2568. clinical observations on hemianopia (japanese)\rthe clinical findings in 19 cases of hemianopia were analyzed.  hemianopia was\rcaused most frequently by vascular lesions of the central nervous mianopsia,\rand by tumors.  wilbrand\'s prism sign, which is generally taken as evidence\rof an optic tract lesion, was positive in one case with a parietal lesion.  no\rcase showed a cogwheel movement of the eyeball.  optokinetic nystagmus was\rpositive in 3 cases, one of which proved to have a parieto-occipital aneurysm.\rthe etiological factor could not be identified in the remaining 2 cases.\rmacular sparing was found to be symptomatic of an occipital lobe lesion.\rincongruity of the 2 fields was observed in 2 cases with an occipital lobe\rlesion.  as for the prognosis, hemianoptic field defects remained stationary in\rcases of vascular lesions.  on the other hand perfect recovery of the visual\rfield defect occurred in cases with an occipital lobe tumor and in hypophyseal\rhypertrophy caused by pregnancy.  the visual acuity of hemianoptic patients was\rfairly good and no deterioration occurred during the observation period of\rabout 4 years.  only one patient out of the present series died.  these results\rsuggest that a favorable vital prognosis can be accorded to hemianoptic\rsubjects.\r'),
 (360,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1384. importance of campimetry and carotid and vertebral angiography in\rthrombosis of the posterior cerebral artery\rthe authors report a case of thrombosis of the posterior cerebral artery which\rpresented only lateral homonymous hemianopia and stress the importance of\rcampimetry and of carotid angiography beside vertebral angiography.\r'),
 (361,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'375. hemianopsia and glaucoma\rafter a discussion of the bibliographic references to the few observations on\rthe simultaneous occurrence of hemianopsias and glaucoma the author states on\rthe basis of his experiences the following points  homonymous hemianopsias\roccasionally take place in glaucoma, although no direct relation can be\restablished between the former and the glaucoma.  it has to be pointed out,\rhowever, that in other older patients, for example in those with retinal\rdetachment, neuritis, etc. who are likewise subjected to repeated and exact\rperimetry, such hemianopsias do not occur, or are to be found at a lesser rate\rthan in glaucoma.  a homonymous hemianopsia has to be taken into consideration\ralso in the event of a sudden impairment of the visual field in a glaucomatous\rpatient or when the hemianopic defect supervenes in addition to the visual\rfield defect due to glaucoma.  in cases of binasal hemianopsia, the\rsimultaneous presence of glaucoma is not a rare incident.  whether the\rbinasal hemianopsia is the result of the gradual development of a\rglaucomatous visual field with nasal defects or whether it constitutes an\rindependent symptom to a certain extent, cannot always be clarified\rin the individual case.  obviously the condition of the basal cerebral\rvessels plays a certain role in the development of glaucoma, even if\rthis role cannot be clearly defined as yet.  in cases of\rbinasal hemianopsia, a glaucoma has to be ruled out before radical diagnostic\rand therapeutic measures are carried out.\r'),
 (362,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1131. disorders of oculomotor functions in lesions of the optic pathway at the\rparieto-occipital level and their significance in topical diagnosis\rparesis of ocular movements to the hemianopic side is described in 9 patients\rwith acute vascular lesions in the parieto-occipital region.  in 7 cases the\rparesis was of the dissociated type with inability to follow the moving finger,\rwhile ocular movement in a verbally stated direction was quite normal.  in the\rremaining 2 patients in whom the oedema extended into the frontal region there\rwas complete paresis of all conjugate movements.  conjugate paresis receded\rhand-in-hand with the parietal symptomatology even if the hemianopia\rpersisted.  the oculomotor disorders referred to have never been observed in\rlesions which did not extend beyond the occipital region.  conjugate\rparesis has in all cases drawn attention to the presence of hemianopia\runobserved by the patients and this has led to a more accurate topical\rdiagnosis.\r'),
 (363,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2333. binocularity in anomalous retinal correspondence\rpatients with anomalous retinal correspondence demonstrate complete bitemporal\ror binasal hemianopia when tested for binocular vision; exotropes have a\rbinasal suppression and esotropes a bitemporal suppression.  this is contrary\rto the prevailing concept of the function of the peripheral retina in\ranomalous retinal correspondence.  6 references.\r'),
 (364,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2120. thioguanine in the treatment of certain autoimmune, immunologic and\rrelated diseases\rthe therapeutic effectiveness of 6-thioguanine has been evaluated over the past\r3 years in 19 patients with diverse syndromes.  only patients with severe\rdebilitating disease unresponsive to conventional therapy were treated.\rremissions occurred in 2 of 5 patients with systemic lupus erythematosus, in 1\rpatient each with dermatomyositis and necrotizing angiitis, 2 patients with\rpsoriasis and 2 of 4 patients with atopic disease.  improvement occurred in\rother patients with these diseases and in 2 of 4 patients with\rneurodermatitis.  two patients with scleroderma experienced only\requivocal benefit.  significant toxicity attributable to the drug\rwas observed in 5 patients.  assessment of the eventual value of\rthese agents in therapy requires further study.  hypotheses regarding the\rmechanism of action of these agents and the significance of clinical\rresponse are discussed.\r'),
 (365,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2469. the nature of collagen disease, particularly of systemic lupus\rerythematosus (sle), with special reference to renal lesions (japanese)\rfrom the results of examination of 161 autopsy cases of collagen diseases,\rrheumatic fever and polyarteritis nodosa (pn) are considered as diseases of\rhyperergic nature, showing pronounced specific manifestation in particular\rorgans.  as the reactivity becomes lower, this specific localization becomes\rless significant and many organs become affected in sle.  it may accordingly be\rsupposed that sle is not a disease of hypersensitivity but one occurring in\ra state of exhaustion of reactability after prolonged sensitization.  moreover,\ra sle-like syndrome arises not only in the end stage of parasepsis, nephritis,\rnephrosis and some cases of prolonged sensitization by myco.tb but also in\rpn,pss,dm and rheumatism.  it may therefore be conceivable that sle is\ra syndrome rather than a separate entity.  it is most important to consider\rwhether sle-like symptomatology may be regarded as a process equal to\ran auto-immunization and whether the key to morphological elucidation of the\rauto-immune phenomenon may lie hidden in this problem.\r'),
 (366,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'420. therapy of lupus nephropathies by 6-mercaptopurine\rcorticosteroid therapy improved the general prognosis of sle, but has no\rdetectable effect on the nephropathy and this is actually the main cause of\rdeath.  a new therapeutic method is presented using 6-mp purinethol (leupurin)\rwhich produced 2 remissions in 6 consecutive cases total and in 4 cases\rwith severe nephropathy definite remission.  it should be emphasized that 5 of\rthe cases reported had definite npn elevation, accordingly they are considered\rhopeless.\r'),
 (367,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2475. lupus erythematosus with fatal hemorrhage into the liver and lesions\rresembling those of periarteritis nodosa and malignant hypertension.\rimmunocytochemical observations\ra firmly established case of lupus erythematosus with histologic\rcharacteristics of periarteritis nodosa and fatal hemorrhage is presented.\rimmunocytochemical studies were done to explore the possibility of the vascular\rlesions being immunological in type.  by immuno-fluorescent techniques\ry-globulin, human serum complement, albumin and fibrinogen were demonstrated in\rthe vascular lesions.  y-globulin in the renal glomeruli was associated only\rwith complement.  the conclusion is that lupus erythematosus is primarily an\rimmunological disease with complex auto-immune mechanisms operative.\r'),
 (368,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'198. early experiences with azathioprine in ulcerative colitis.  a note of\rcaution\razathioprine was administered to 10 patients with ulcerative colitis classified\ras \'very severe\' in 2,\'moderately severe\' in 7 and \'relatively mild\' in 1\rpatient, in conjunction with \'standard\' therapy and adrenal corticosteroids in\r8 of the 10 patients.  the possible beneficial therapeutic effects of\razathioprine in this small series cannot be evaluated definitively because of\rthe concurrent medication and the preliminary uncontrolled observations.\rhowever, clinical improvement was apparent in 8 of the 10 patients; and in 2\rpatients, the favorable course occurred in the absence of steroid therapy.  in\r2 additional patients, the favorable course was maintained during the\radministration of azathioprine following the discontinuance of prolonged\rsteroid therapy.  in 1 patient, the administration of azathioprine was\rassociated with amelioration of an arthritis and pyoderma gangrenosum which did\rnot respond to the use of steroids and other medication.  immuno-suppressive\robservations were limited.  the established delayed hypersensitivity response,\ras reflected in various skin tests, was unchanged during the administration of\razathioprine.  azathioprine had no discernible toxic effects upon the kidneys\ror the liver in 2 patients, 1 with postnecrotic cirrhosis and the other with\rserum hepatitis.  gastro-intestinal symptoms (anorexia, epigastric discomfort,\rand nausea) occurred in 8 patients.  mild to moderate leukopenia developed in 8\rpatients and, in 2 individuals, was accompanied by thrombocytopenia.  temporary\ralopecia occurred in 1 woman.  the hematopoietic effects developed within 2 or\r3 wk of therapy with azathioprine at a dosage level of 4-6 mg/kg/day.\razathioprine does not exert the rapid beneficial effect in ulcerative colitis\rnoted with corticotropin and adrenal corticosteroids.  therefore, its use in\rsevere ulcerative colitis requiring intensive therapy probably is undesirable.\razathioprine, on the basis of these initial observations, may be considered for\rmoderately severe ulcerative colitis, under circumstances permitting controlled\rand prolonged therapeutic trial as adjunct medication, but with careful\rsupervision for prevention of toxicity, especially leukopenia.\r'),
 (369,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1281. effect of fluoropyrimidines on delayed cutaneous hypersensitivity\rthe ability to express delayed cutaneous hypersensitivity was assessed in 51\rpatients with carcinoma.  evidence is presented that 5-fluorouracil and\r5-fluoro-2\'-deoxyuridine paradoxically potentiate this parameter of immune\rresponsiveness.\r'),
 (370,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'248. data on etiology, pathogenesis, treatment results and survival period in\r560 patients with cirrhosis of the liver\rstatistics were compiled from a total of 560 cases chosen at random, of\rcirrhosis of the liver.  the figures refer to the age and sex of the patients,\ras well as to the etiology and the hepatic morphology.  as the date of death of\r304 of the subjects was known, it was possible to calculate the survival time\rafter the diagnosis was made.  only 36% survived the time of diagnosis by 1\ryear, 16% by 3 years, and 8% by 5 years.  these figures show that modern\rtherapy of liver cirrhosis has up to now not succeeded to prolong the life of\rthe majority of the victims.  in many cases, however, it is possible to a large\rextent to relieve the patients\' suffering by improving the appetite and the\rgeneral condition and by eliminating ascites and periods of hemorrhage and\rstupor.  particular attention should be paid to the prophylaxis of the disease\rand, by studying the survival time assessments and therapeutic reports, to the\rmethod of selection of the subjects.\r'),
 (371,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'897. chronic renal diseases and pregnancy  a review\ra review is given of the reciprocal relationships between chronic renal disease\rand pregnancy.  after a short review of the most important changes in renal\rfunction due to normal pregnancy, the diagnosis of chronic renal disease is\rdiscussed.  subsequently, the following complications of pregnancy are\rdiscussed individually  chronic pyelonephritis, chronic glomerulonephritis,\rlupus erythematosus, the nephrotic syndrome, diabetic nephropathy and\rpolycystic disease of the kidney.  the paper is concluded by a discussion on\rthe influence of pregnancy on the different renal affections.\r'),
 (372,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4193. the occurrence to cytomegalovirus infections in childhood leukemia.\rreport of three cases\rcytomegalic inclusion disease (cmid) presented the following clinical findings\rin three children with acute leukemia  persistent high temperature, cough,\rvomiting, diarrhea, hepatosplenomegaly, rales, and terminal icterus.\rpancytopenia was present in all, including two children in leukemic remission.\rroentgenographic evidence of pneumonia did not appear until the third week\rafter the onset of symptoms.  abnormalities in liver function tests were late\rfindings.  intranuclear inclusions were seen in urine sediments of two\rpatients.  in neither of these patients were intranuclear inclusions\rdemonstrable in the sputa.  virus culture from urine was done in one of these\rpatients and cytopathogenic changes characteristic of cytomegalovirus (cmv)\rwere demonstrated.  cmid was the cause of death in these three children, all\rof whom had received chemotherapy with agents known to have immunosuppressive\rproperties.\r'),
 (373,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'   . on chorea, lupus erythematosus, and cerebral arteritis\ra woman aged 33 developed chorea 10 yr after the onset of systemic lupus\rerythematosus (sle).  she had experienced an asymptomatic interval of\r8 yr.  the abnormal movements persisted for 5 mth, but then subsided\rafter short-term administration of 6-mercaptopurine.  there are 11 previous\rdescriptions of chorea patients with sle.  in 3 out of 4 autopsied cases,\rextensive cerebral lesions due to diffuse arteritis were found.  the cns\rchanges were quite similar to those found in chorea minor.\r'),
 (374,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1878. pharmacologic actions on cellular immunity\rthe following chapters of interest in the field of drugs and immunity processes\rare included  manifestations of cellular immunity.  states of reduced\rimmunologic reactivity.  present status of pharmacologic immunosuppression.\rtests for susceptibility of tuberculin reactions to pharmacologic action.\rtests for susceptibility of transplantation immunity to pharmacologic action.\rcomparative susceptibilities of tuberculin and skin homotransplantation\rreactions to pharmacologic action.\r'),
 (375,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2625. chromosome aberrations in human cells following treatment with imuran\rfive women with various collagen diseases were studied.  bone marrow aspirates\rwere obtained from each patient before and 12 to 24 days after start of imuran\r(azothioprine) therapy.  fifty metaphases from each sample were counted.  in\rpatients nos. 1 and 2 the increase in cells with structural abnormalities\rduring therapy is significant.  the aberrations found were mostly breaks of the\rchromatid and chromosomal type.  a few abnormal chromosomes were seen,\ramong which a ring chromosome.  in patient no. 1 chromatid exchanges were\rseen in three cells.\r'),
 (376,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3645. autoimmune hepatitis\rin 30% of 301 patients with cirrhosis, the cause was uncertain.  of these 90\rcases the clinical picture of active chronic hepatitis could be recognized in\r69, and 26 of these were characterized as lupoid hepatitis.  the relationship\rbetween active chronic hepatitis, lupoid hepatitis and sle was studied in 3\rgroups of 25 cases each.  a comparison was then made between the possible\retiological factors, the systemic manifestations, the survival rate, the\rhistological appearances, the biochemical tests, the autoimmune reactions\rand the results of the immunosuppressive drugs.  from this study a concept\remerged according to which a proportion of cases of cirrhosis occurring in\radequately nourished individuals can be attributed to the end result of an\rautoimmune reaction.\r'),
 (377,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'766. a comparison of the effects of selected cytotoxic agents on the primary\ragglutinin response in rats injected with sheep erythrocytes\ra comparative study was made of the effects of several cytotoxic agents, given\rat maximally tolerable doses, on the primary agglutinin response in rats\rimmunized with sheep erythrocytes given intraperitoneally.  antigen was given\rbefore, at the beginning, or in the middle of a 5-day course of drug\rtreatment.  chlormethine (mechlorethamine), 5-fluorouracil, and\r5-fluoro-2\'-deoxyuridine did not suppress the primary response\rsignificantly.  methotrexate, 6-mercaptopurine, 6-mercaptopurine roboside\rand 2-amino-6-((1-methyl-4-nitro-5-imidazolyl) thio) purine\rprolonged induction time and suppressed peak titer maximally\rwhen immunization was performed one to three days prior\rto drug treatment.  vinblastine did not affect peak titer, but did prolong\rinduction time when antigen was given 2 days prior to drug treatment.\rcyclophosphamide markedly prolonged induction time and suppressed peak titer\rirrespective of the time of antigen administration.  the antimetabolites\rappeared to suppress maximally the intermediate stage of the primary response.\rcyclophosphamide appeared to suppress all stages.\r'),
 (378,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1959. analysis of mechanism of immunosuppressive drugs in renal\rhomotransplantation\rdammin g. j.\ra long-term study of the mechanism of action of immunosuppressive drugs has\rbeen completed in bilaterally nephrectomized dogs with kidney homotransplants.\rover 1,000 test animals with 24 different drug protocols have been analyzed.\rincreasing numbers of long surviving animals have posed many questions\rregarding the status treated host.  the current drug protocol of azathioprine\rand diazoacetylserine (\'azaserine\') has produced 90% 50-day survivors and 50%\r100-day survivors.  the following observations have been documented  all\ranimals on prolonged drug therapy are immunologically competent; drug therapy\rcan be stopped successfully in some but not all animals; long surviving kidneys\rapparently are protected in some way in the new environment because a\rsecond donor kidney can be rejected while the first survives; retransplantation\rof a long surviving kidney back to its original host did not lead to a decrease\rin renal function; long surviving kidneys successfully retransplanted back\rto their original donors are rejected when transplanted to third party,\rnon-drug treated recipients; immune paralysis does not account for the\rprolonged survival because the second donor kidney which constitutes a double\rdose of antigen is rejected while the first continues to survive; absorption or\rmetabolism of the drug does not account for the variation in results because\rtwo kidneys, each from separate donors, can be rejected differentially in the\rsame drug treated host; and all hosts are sensitized against the recipient and\rthis sensitization continues even in those animals successfully weaned from\rdrugs.  additional analyses of the relationship of skin homografts and kidney\rhomografts reveal the following  skin homografts are universally rejected\rwithin 20 days by hosts treated with the drug regimen which protects kidney\rhomografts sometimes permanently.  when skin and kidney homografts from the\rsame donor are placed simultaneously skin survival is prolonged while kidney\rsurvival is shortened.  this paradoxical effect probably is explained by the\rproduction of antibodies by skin which are absorbed by the rejecting kidney.\radditional observations indicate that drug-treated animals, male and female,\rare fertile and that multiple rejection processes can produce generalized\rimmunological picture in the host similar to an autoimmune disease process.\r'),
 (379,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3083. myocardial toxicity of contrast agents used in angiography\rthe myocardial toxicity of many current and\rsome experimental contrast agents\rhas been studied in dogs, by use of a previously\runreported method of occlusion\rretrograde coronary venography as well as the\rfamiliar technique of selective\rcoronary arterial catheterization.  the following\rconclusions appear justified in\rthe light of the experiments   not only the\riodine-containing radicals with which the\rcontrast agents are so often identified (acetrizoates,\rdiatrizoates, iothalamates,\retc.), but also the final salification products appear\rto be responsible for the widely\rdivergent degrees of myocardial toxicity of contrast\ragents, to the point that differ-\rent salts of the same compound behave as entirely\rdifferent agents both chemically\rand biologically.  the results seem to indicate the\rdominance of sodium ion and/or\rthe protective effect of methylglucamine salts with\rrespect to the myocardial toxi-\rcity of current radiopaque media.  reported,\ryet unexplained, electrocardiographic\rchanges occurring within one to two seconds\rfrom the beginning of massive caval\rhigh-pressure injections appear to find a\rcausal relationship in the myocardial ir-\rritability induced by the distention of the\rcoronary veins and the myocardial infiltra-\rtion which is intentionally enhanced with\rour retrograde injection techniques.  a pe-\rculiar trait, shared in varying degrees by\rall radiopaque agents tested, is their\rability to increase coronary blood flow.\rthe clinical significance of this phenome-\rnon, however, remains to be established.\rthese studies re-emphasize the limita-\rtions of the standard toxicity studies conducted\rin animals.  it should be clear from\rthe results reported that agents to be\radministered into the coronary circulation\rdemand investigation in regard to their\rpotential toxicity by the methods described\rherein or variations thereof.  in fact,\rsimilar tests should be carried out for all or-\rgans to be subjected to radiographic\rexamination via the vascular bed.  the authors\rhope that this presentation will stimulate\rrenewed investigation, particularly in view\rof the growing clinical applications of\rselective cardiovascular opacification tech-\rniques.\r'),
 (380,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2476. studies on cardiac dimensions in intact,\runanesthetized man. i. description of techniques and their\rvalidation. ii. effects of respiration. iii. effects of\rmuscular exercise\ra method is described which permits\rmeasurement of relative changes in the exter-\rnal dimensions of individual cardiac\rchambers throughout the cardiac cycle in intact,\runanaesthetized man.  it consists of\rsuturing multiple radiopaque silver-tantalum\rclips to the surface of the heart at the\rtime of cardiac operations.  in the postopera-\rtive period, cineradiograms are\robtained and the distances between clips are mea-\rsured on each individual frame.\rthis technique has been found to be safe and has\rbeen employed in 68 patients without\rany complications.  as a result of studies in 8\rpatients utilizing biplane serial exposures,\rthe effects of rotation of the heart in the\rsagittal plane during the cardiac and\rrespiratory cycles were determined precisely.\rif clips were properly placed on the heart,\rthe possible errors resulting from such\rrotation were found to be quite small.\rduring inspiration right ventricular dimen-\rsions increased, while the opposite occurred\rduring expiration and during the val-\rsalva manoeuvre.  left ventricular dimensions\rexhibited little change during normal\rrespiration.  during deep, slow inspiration,\rthe changes in dimensions of the left\rventricle lagged behind those of the right\rventricle by 1 to 5 (generally 2 or 3) car-\rdiac cycles; the magnitude of the changes in\rthe dimensions of the left ventricle was\rsmaller than that which occurred in the right\rventricle.  the effects on ventricular\rdimensions of light muscular exercise performed\rin the supine position were studied\rin 9 patients.  the end-diastolic dimensions\rdecreased by an average of 6.0% of con-\rtrol in the right ventricle, and by an average of\r5.1% in the left ventricle.  end-sys-\rtolic dimensions decreased by an average of 5.6%\rof control in the right ventricle\rand by an average of 6.5% in the left ventricle.\rthese decreases are considered to\rapproximate one-half of the resting stroke volume.\rin the 4 patients in whom the\rrate of right ventricular pressure rise was determined\rcontinuously, exercise re-\rsulted in an elevation of dp/dt while ventricular\rend-diastolic dimensions decreased.\rthese data are interpreted to indicate that an\rincrease in myocardial contractility\roccurs during muscular exercise in man.\r'),
 (381,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3765. radioactive isotope determination of myocardial blood\rflow by surface counting and ratio formula\rwilkinson d.\rthe results presented here have a large\rscale error and a large scatter, so that\rthe authors recommend that further clinical\ruse of this method should not be at-\rtempted.  if the coronary portion of the flow\rrate curve exists, then a change in the\rpresent instrumentation is needed to allow\ruse of the technique of sevelius and\rjohnson in defining a coronary portion of the\rflow rate.  an attempt is made to\revaluate the possible source of errors.\r'),
 (382,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1379. risa-ventriculography and risa-cisternography\rsome general experience of the authors with\rrisa-ventriculography and risa-cis-\rternography is related.  they conclude that the\rformer technique may be particularly\ruseful in detecting intraventricular tumors and\rinternal hydrocephalus as well as\rassessing the efficiency of surgical shunts; the\rlatter technique may be useful in\rthe study of normal csf circulation as well as\rin cases of csf leaks, arachnoiditis\rand external hydrocephalus.\r'),
 (383,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3485. measurement of the cardiac output and ventricular\rvolumes by radiocardiography\rcardiac output was measured by external\rcounting after injection of radioisotopes\r(rihsa and erythrocytes-cr51).  the results\rin 113 subjects, including 16 normals,\rare presented and compared with the results\rby other methods.  cardiac output at\rrest and after exercise was compared in 65 subjects.\rthe principle of ventricular\rvolume measurement by radioisotope-cardiography is\rdiscussed.  the results of\rmeasurement of the ventricular volume in 17 normal\rsubjects and 90 patients, and\rof measurement of the ventricular volume in 57 patients,\rare presented.\r'),
 (384,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3762. aberrant left coronary artery\rfive cases of aberrant coronary artery are\rpresented, with emphasis on the angio-\rgraphic features and differentiation from\rendocardial fibroelastosis.  clinical and\relectrocardiographic features may suggest\rthe proper diagnosis, but only angio-\rgraphy can conclusively demonstrate the\rcontinuity between the pulmonary artery\rand the left coronary artery.  in these cases,\rblood flow was from the pulmonary\rartery to the coronary artery (forward) in 2\rcases, and from the coronary artery\rto the pulmonary artery (retrograde) in the\rother 3.  when the diagnosis of aberrant\rcoronary artery is suspected, selective\rleft-sided angiocardiography should be the\rangiographic procedure of choice.  the differentiation\rfrom endocardial fibroelas-\rtosis and other myocardiopathies is usually not a\rproblem with such a study, but\rmay be more difficult with intravenous angiocardiography.\rwith this latter type of\rstudy, the coronary arteries are not generally visible,\rbut a persistently thin la-\rteral aspect of the left ventricular wall should suggest\rthe proper diagnosis.  sub-\rsequent confirmation by a left-sided injection is advisable.\r'),
 (385,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4159. detection of heart shunts by means of i 125\rexternal scintillation detection of a pure dilution\rcurve originating in the right ven-\rtricle has been pursued by investigators for many\ryr.  the use of the soft photons\rof 125 i offers an improved method of determination\rby allowing excellent collimation\rthrough 2 mechanisms  (1) a small half value layer\rof 2 cm in tissue, and (2) uni-\rdirectionality, in part due to all-or-none photoelectric\rabsorption of these photons\ras compared with the pluridirectionality due to compton\rscatter in the case of 131 i.\rin 30 normal individuals, externally detected dilution\rcurves from the right heart\rventricle and arterial dilution curves obtained by arterial\rpuncture are compared.\rfive hundred microcuries of 125 i are injected into an\rantecubital vein.  the amount\rof radiation absorbed from a 500 uc dose in an adult of\r70 kilos is 1000 to 2000\rmrads when injected in the form of 125 i iodide.  the use\rof 125 i orthoiodohippu-\rrate is advised due to its short biological half-period and\rthe integrated whole-body\rradiation exposure is decreased 100-fold in comparison\rwith the 125 i iodide.  the\rshape of the right heart curve is very similar to the arterial\rdilution curve with a\r13   5% excess of counts originating outside the right ventricle\rarea.  the descending\rsegment of the right ventricle curve has a minimum count rate\rof only 12   2% of the\rpeak of the curve as compared with the arterial curve of 10\r   2.5%.  a mean t 1/2\rof the descending down slope of the right ventricle is 1.52\r   0.45 sec. for the right\rheart curve and 2.4   0.65 sec. for the arterial curve.\rthe clinical usefulness of this\rprocedure in 20 patients with atrial septal defects and 9\rpatients with ventricular sep-\rtal defects is analyzed.  it seems possible to perform selective\rright-heart radiocardio-\rgraphy by means of external precordial detection of 125 i.  the\rmethod is simple and\rreproducible.\r'),
 (386,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4160. clinical applications of quantitative radiocardiography. i.\rresults in normal subjects and changes with age\ra technique is described for routine determinations\rat the bedside of blood volume,\rcardiac output and pulmonary blood volume by means\rof the method of quantitative\rradiocardiography.  the instrumentation is simple,\rthe technique is easy to perform\rand causes little trouble to the patients, only one\rinjection of about 50 uc of rihsa\rbeing needed.  thirty-nine patients aged 17-83 yr.,\rfree of cardiovascular or re-\rspiratory disorders, were studied.  the results\robtained are in close agreement with\rprevious reports.  only the cardiac index showed a\rsignificant decrease with age,\rwhile the reduction of blood volume and of pulmonary\rblood volume was slight.  a close\rstatistical correlation was found between pbv and sv,\rand was interpreted as a\rdependence of pbv on sv.\r'),
 (387,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2725. demonstration of myocardial infarction by photoscans of\rthe heart in man\rintravenously injected radioiodinated oleic acid\rwas incorporated into heart muscle\rin sufficient concentration to permit recording photoscans\rof the heart in man.  in\r3 fatal cases of massive septal myocardial infarction,\rinjection of the radioiodin-\rated fatty acid (rifa) was made during life; at necropsy\rphotoscans of the excised\rheart showed a discrete area of absent radioactivity\rcorresponding to the infarcted\rinterventricular septum.  photoscans of the heart were\rmade during life in 42 pa-\rtients, 9 of whom had suffered recent myocardial infarction.\rthere were definite\rareas of deceased radioactivity corresponding to the location\rof the infarction,\rjudged by the electrocardiogram, in 4, and probable areas of\rdecreased radioactivity\rin 2, of the 9 cases of myocardial infarction.  the technic as\rpresently employed\rjust approaches the limits of definition of infarction in acute\rcases.  modification of\rthe biochemical principles or further development of the\ry-camera may bring the\rmethod to a level of diagnostic usefulness.\r'),
 (388,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2716. y-angiocardiography\rrecordings were made, simultaneously with\rthe y-cardiogram, of a pulmonary an-\rgiogram by means of a collimator placed in\rthe left scapular region and of carotid\rangiogram by a collimator centered on the axis\rof the external auditory canal.  the\r3 curves yielded very interesting information on\rthe chronology of the various car-\rdiac cycles.  the pattern of the pulmonary and\rcarotid y-angiograms was valuable\rin several pathologic conditions.  it is more logical\rto measure the cardiac output\ron the carotid curve than on the y-cardiogram,\respecially if there are shunts.  the\rpulmonary curve allows rectification of the time\rconstant of emptying of the left\rcavities of the heart.  as regards chronologic\rinformation on cardiac cycles, atten-\rtion is drawn to the fact that in the pulmonary\rcirculation long and short circuits\rcan be demonstrated.  the characteristic times\rcan be measured.  between the time\rthat the radioactive material appears in the left\rcavities and the time that it leaves\rthe carotid, there is an interval of 3-4 systoles,\rwhich represents the time neces-\rsary for left circular filling.  the validity of\rcalculation of the cardiac output with\rthe stewart-hamilton formula is discussed.\rthis is valid if the collimator covers\ra small volume of the principal channel.  it remains\rto be shown if such a calculation\ris valid for larger cavities, or for 2 cavities, through\rwhich the radioactive material\rpasses successively, and which have different c (t)\rfunctions as well as for all tissue\r\'seen\' by the collimator, some of which are not yet\rirrigated with the radioactive\rblood, while in other areas recirculation has already\rstarted.  these aspects, and\rtheir application to the pulmonary angiogram, are\rdiscussed in detail.  with the\rauthors\' technique, y-angiogram is\respecially valuable, as correc-\rtion for the time constant of the decrease of the left\rpeak is based on the lengthening\rof this curve.  this again serves as a basis for\rdetermining the left ventricular\rvolume.\r'),
 (389,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2717. the value of quantitative radiocardiography in the study\rof hemodynamics\rsix normal subjects and 7 patients with mitral\rstenosis were studied.  quantitative\rradiocardiographic investigations (rihsa) were\rperformed according to donato\'s\rmethod.  the stroke volume as well as the cardiac\routput were found to be decreased\rin mitral stenosis, the right ventricular evacuation\rratio diminished, and the pul-\rmonary circulation time prolonged.  the results\rpertaining to diastolic right ventricu-\rlar capacity, right ventricular resting blood volume\rand pulmonary blood volume\rproved inconclusive.\r'),
 (390,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3056. the localization of aortic shunts developed by a precordial\rregistration of i 131 injected into the aorta at different levels\ra technique for localizing shunts of aortic origin\ris described, based on the analysis\rof precordial records of i 131 injected at different\raortic levels.  seven patients with\rpatent ductus arteriosus (pda), 1 with a\rcoronary av fistula, 2 with ventricular\rseptal defect (vsd), 1 with atrial septal defect\r(asd), 3 with mitral regurgitation,\r2 with aortic regurgitation and 2 with systemic\rhypertension were studied.  retro-\rgrade arterial catheterization by seldinger\'s\rtechnique was performed in all the\rpatients, as well as right-sided catheterization\rin those with congenital cardiopathies,\rand transseptal catheterization in those with\rvalvulopathies.  a dose of 5-15 uc of na\ri 131 was injected at the levels of the aortic root,\rthe ascending aorta, the aortic arch,\rthe origin of the left subclavian artery (ductus\rlevel) and the descending aorta (post-\rductus level).  precordial curves were obtained by\rmeans of a 2-inch thallium-acti-\rvated nai crystal focused over the 3rd left intercostal\rspace at the sternal margin.\rthe shunt outlet can be detected by obtaining\rsimultaneous venous dilution curves\rfrom the right chambers and the pulmonary artery.\rthe latter technique was used\rin 2 patients with pda, 1 with coronary av fistula\rand 1 with vsd.  these curves\rwere obtained by continuous withdrawal of blood which\rhad flowed through a well\rscintillation counter.  the crystal pulses were carried\rto ratemeters which worked\rwith the following time constants  0.01-0.15 sec for the\rprecordial curves and 0.5\rsec for the venous curves.  a direct recorder with a\r5-mm/sec paper speed was\rused.  normal precordial curves after injecting above\rthe aortic valve were obtained\rin patients with arterial hypertension, mitral regurgitation\rand asd and vsd.  a\rswift downslope which fell down near the baseline level and\rthe recirculatory area\rwas observed.\r'),
 (391,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1671. the use of 99m tc pertechnetate in cardiac scanning\rtechnetium 99m pertechnetate has been utilized\rin the aas\' laboratory for scanning the\rcardiac blood pool.  the delineation of the heart\rpool and surrounding vasculature\ris comparable to that obtained with the standard\r131 i compounds now in use.  in the\rauthors\' hands 99m tc had the following advantages\rsince they routinely utilized\r99m tc for brain and thyroid scans, it is available,\reliminating the purchase and\rshelf decay of other materials.  three to 5 mc quantities\rmay be administered\rwith relatively low patient radiation dosage.  the\rassociated high count rate permits\rrapid scanning.  the identification of pericardial effusions\ris enhanced by the radio-\ractivity in the stomach which in some cases becomes\rabnormally separated from\rthe cardiac blood pool.\r'),
 (392,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012. the use of technetium 99m as a clinical tracer element\rthe physical properties, metabolism and\rradiation dose of tc 99m are discussed and\rcompared with those of i 123, i 125, i 131 and i 132.\rit is shown that with tc 99m the highest\r\'in vivo\' counting rates are obtained for a\rgiven internal radiation dose, so that mea-\rsurements of high statistical accuracy may\rsafely be made.  the y-ray energy is near\roptimum for scanning and the observation of\rtransients allowing light-weight collima-\rtors to be used.  while tc 99m tagged albumin\ris considered superior to risa for ap-\rplications such as brain scanning, placentography\rand the measurement of cardiac\routput, i 123 if it becomes available will be preferable\rfor thyroid scanning.\r'),
 (393,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2626. a study of central arteriovenous shunts by\rprecordial recording of radioalbumin dilution curves\rprecordial dilution curves of 185 patients were\rstudied, 56 of them without cardio-\rvascular disease, 48 with central arteriovenous\rshunts and 45 with various cardiac\rdiseases.  collimation was not used, allowing only\rminimal quantities of radioactive\rmaterial (0.5-2.2 uc. of i 131-tagged albumin) to be\rutilized.  the precordial focusing\rzone was a critical factor in this technique.  the\rapplication of different discrimina-\rtion factors, among them the ratio between the\rminimal concentration and the latter\r-an index proposed here - made possible the\rdiagnosis in 46 of the 48 patients with\rshunts.  this method was shown to be as sensitive\ras classical oximetry done during\rcardiac catheterization.  the curves in pure valvular\rstenosis do not show similar\rchanges to the shunts.  on the other hand, these\rchanges are shown in certain val-\rvular regurgitations.  this fact becomes the most\rimportant limiting factor in the\rdiagnosis of central arteriovenous shunts.  cardiac\rfailure does not preclude the\rdiagnosis, providing one can exclude valvular\rregurgitation by other means.  the\rmethod is thus, in spite of its limitations, of extreme\rvalue in diagnosing central\rarteriovenous shunts, especially when the results are\ranalyzed together with clinical\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (394,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'information.\r2724. primary epidermoid cancers of the lung.  electron micro-\rscopic study\ran electron microscopic study was made\rof 8 squamous cell, 3 undifferentiated,\rand 3 alveolar carcinomas of the lung on\rbiopsy specimens embedded in methacryl-\rate.  the squamous cell carcinomas were\rfound to contain cylindrical cells with\rglycogen granules, scanty mitochondria,\ra reticular endoplasm which was chiefly\rvesicular, numerous free ribosomes,\rand bundles of confluent fibrils in the desmo-\rsomes.  the authors also observed in\rthe center of the tumor nodes, cells richer\rin tonofibrils which enveloped the\rnucleus, and cells in which all the cytoplasmic\rorganelles had almost disappeared\rexcept for tonofibrils or cells packed with\rkeratohyalin and even lipid granules\rsometimes arranged in lamellar formations\rof the myelin type.  the picture as a\rwhole was that so often seen in the optic\rmicroscope tumor foci formed of\rslightly differentiated cells at the periphery\rwhich became more differentiated\ras one approaches the center.  the undifferenti-\rated cells resembled more the\rintermediate bronchial cells than the basal cells.\rthe paper does not describe the\rundifferentiated and alveolar carcinomas.\r'),
 (395,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1375. loss of neoplastic properties in vitro. ii. observations on\rkb sublines\rten sublines of the kb cell line obtained from\ra number of different laboratories\rwere reexamined with respect to chromosome\rnumber and heterotransplantability\rto the syrian hamster cheek pouch.  twelve\rclonal cultures derived from 2 of these\rsublines were similarly examined.  three\rsublines differed from one another and\rfrom the kb cell line originally studied,\rwhich was heterotransplantable with inocula\rof circa 10 cells.  only 2 of the sublines\rcould be heterotransplanted with inocula\rof less than 10 4 cells; 5 were heterotransplantable\rwith inocula of 10 4-10 6 cells; and\r2 failed to heterotransplant, even with\rinocula of 10 6 cells.  similar differences in\rheterotransplantability were observed\ramong the clonal derivatives of 2 of these\rsublines.  although the modal numbers of\rthese sublines and clonal derivatives were\rbasically similar, ranging from 73 to 80,\ra few lines had a chromosome of sufficient-\rly distinctive morphology to serve as a\rmarker.  there was, however, no apparent\rcorrelation between these minor karyotypic\rdifferences and heterotransplantability.\rpossible differences between non-heterotransplantable\rand heterotransplantable\rsublines with respect to the pattern of\rvariability in cytoplasmic protein and cyto-\rplasmic ribonucleic (rna) content per cell\rremain to be studied in detail.  for i of this\rseries of articles see exc. medica cancer, 1965, abstr. no. 2378.\r'),
 (396,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1377. establishment of a tissue culture strain jtc-14 from actino-\rmycin-induced ascites sarcoma, and its biological characters\rcell line jtc-14 has been maintained for more\rthan 2 yr. and subcultured 93 times.\rcells from the 10th subculture on subcutaneous\rinjection into mice produced tumors\ridentical with those produced by the original\rcells.  judged by the time taken to kill\rmice on intraperitoneal injection the tissue\rculture cells were not as malignant as\rthe original tumor cells.  after passage in\ranimals the cells were easily re-established\rin culture in vitro.\r'),
 (397,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1378. microcinematographic study of the mechanism of cancerous\rinvasion in cultures of normal tissue combined with malignant cells\rnormal myocardium of newborn c3h mice was\rcultivated in vitro in contact with\rhomologous sarcomatous cells (strain n1 and\rstrain nctc) and studied by micro-\rcinematography for 22 days.  it was found that\rthe tumor cells tend to move apart,\rand with more vigorous and rapid movements\rsome of them called \'commando\'s\'\rmake their way into the group of normal\rcells but are arrested wherever they meet\ra compact group of these cells.  this then\rdemonstrates, on the one hand, direct\raggresivity of the tumor cells and, on the\rother, the \'group\' defence of the normal\rcells.\r'),
 (398,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2413. the presence of lymphocytes in long term cultures of\rnewborn mouse thymic epithelium\rthymic epithelial cells derived from newborn\rmouse thymic fragments were cultured\rin vitro for over 22 mth.  subcultures were\rstarted by transferring minute cell\rsheets obtained by mechanical scraping of\rthe original culture when it was 14 mth\rold or older.  lymphocytes, many of them\rwith the morphological appearance of\rplasma cells, were seen in the subcultures.\rintact lymphocytes, as well as mitotic\rfigures were seen within cytoplasmatic vacuoles\rof the epithelial cells.  the possible\rbearing of these observations on the origin of the\rthymic lymphocytes is briefly\rdiscussed.\r'),
 (399,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3748. four separate tumour clones derived from a transplantable pleo-\rmorphic carcinoma of the lung in a heterozygous mouse\ra metastasising pleomorphic adenocarcinoma\rin the lung of an untreated hetero-\rzygous male mouse was successfully\rtransplanted to 4 brothers by the \'plating\'\rtechnique of henderson and rous.  by\r\'plating\' multiple small grafts in air bells in\rthe subcutaneous tissues of the new hosts\rit was possible to select 4 different clones\rof transplantable tumour for further study.\rthe histological peculiarities of\rdifferent parts of the original tumour\rwere reproduced in the different clones a i,\rii, iii, and b.  retrospective study\rof the primary tumour and of its metastases\rprovided some interesting clues to routes\rof metastasis and the selective survival of\rmalignant cells.  it is concluded that by\rthe cloning of transplantable cells, at the\rfirst serial passage, valuable information\rabout the histogenesis and potential\rmalignancy of the primary tumour can be\robtained.  lastly, the highly malignant\rcharacter of 4 clones of tumour cells apparently\rderived from the familiar clinically\rbenign adenoma of the mouse lung may\rbe of some interest, from the point of\rview of prognosis based on histology.\r'),
 (400,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2379. in-vitro culture of pulmonary tumors in hamsters caused by adenovirus 12\rit is known that the adenoviruses 12 and\r18 provoke malignant tumors in the\rnew-born hamster.  the authors made a study\rof the histogenesis of these tumors and\rexamined the specific changes brought about\rin the cells by the virus infection\rmalignancy, presence of viral antigen, reactions\rto superinfection.  when new-born\rhamsters were inoculated in the chest with\radenovirus 12, malignant tumors\rdeveloped in one or two months, in 16 animals\rout of 22.  these tumors presented\ran epithelial aspect and were of bronchiolo-alveolar\rorigin.  they were transplant-\rable in vivo; if they were cultured in vitro,\rthey consisted in the first few cultures of\rmacrophages, fibroblasts and epithelium.\rin subsequent passages, there was a\rprogressive disappearance of the macrophages\rand fibroblasts.  in some cases, the\rculture after seven passages was of a purely\repithelial nature, and when it was\rreimplanted into hamsters at this time it\rgave rise to the rapid development of an\repithelial tumor.  in the tumor cultures,\rno adenovirus could be demonstrated.\rnor could cultures of the pulmonary tumors,\ror cultures of normal hamster lung be\rinfected with adenovirus.  it appears that the\rlung of the hamster in an organotyp-\rical culture constitutes a means of choice\rfor the malignant transformation of\radenovirus 12.\r'),
 (401,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'133. demonstration, purification, and partial characterization of ab-\rnormal (hsl) antigens in stable human cell lines\rthe existence of abnormal human stable\rline (hsl) antigens common to a\rnumber of stable human cell lines, but\rabsent from normal human tissues and\rnormal human diploid cell strains in tissue\rculture, was demonstrated by agar gel\rmicroimmunodiffusion.  hsl was detected\rin hela-sj, hela-mba, hela-s3,\rchang conjunctiva, syverton\'s embryo\resophagus, chang liver, and j-iii.  it\rwas not detected in henle\'s human intestine\ror detroit-6.  it was absent from two\rnormal diploid strains, wi-38 and sj-dhl,\rand was not found in a variety of\rconcentrated extracts of fresh human\rorgans.  hsl was not associated with\rcontamination by pleuropneumonia-like\rorganisms (pplo) of cell lines.  the\rpurest hsl preparations obtained from hela-sj\rby ammonium sulfate fractiona-\rtion yielded absorption spectra characteristic of\rprotein and were inactivated by\rtrypsin.  sephadex chromatography indicated a\rparticle weight of approximately\r150,000; hsl was not sedimented at 125,000 x g.\rin 0.02 m po4 buffer, activity\rwas virtually completely eliminated after 2 minutes\rat 50 c., 8 minutes at 45 c.,\ror 80 minutes at 40 c.  preliminary studies with\rfluorescent anti-hsl globulin\rindicated that hsl was not a surface antigen;\rrabbit antisera to purified hsl\rfractions were not cytotoxic to hela cells.\rthe best preparations of hsl still\rcontained a trace of common human antigen\rand appeared to consist of multiple\rcomponents active in immunoprecipitation.\relectrophoresis indicated the in-\rhomogeneity of this material.\r'),
 (402,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1696. further comparative studies on two isogenic cell lines of autologous\rorigin, one of which is tumor-producing\ra single explant of normal lung tissue\rfrom an adult female mouse c57bl provided\r2 cell lines.  one remained normal\rand is referred to as pg, the other became\rmalignant and is designated as pt.\rwith successive in vitro passages by tryp-\rsinization the tumour-inducing capacity\rof the pt line considerably decreased its\rtumour-producing capacity as well\ras its acrobic glycolysis coefficient, while the\rpg line showed no appreciable\rchange.  results of chromosome studies are de-\rscribed, but proved inconclusive.\rsimilar experiments were also carried out on\rcell lines derived from the pt line\rand their results are discussed.\r'),
 (403,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1202. characteristics of human adenovirus type 12 induced hamster tumor\rcells in tissue culture\rcharacteristics of a human adenovirus\rtype 12 induced hamster tumor serially pro-\rpagated in vitro are described.  these\rinclude small cell size, epithelioid appear-\rance, rapid growth rate, resistance to\rsuperinfection with a-12, and transplant-\rability to weanling hamsters.  these cells grew\reither as monolayers or as balls of\raggregated cells detached from the glass,\rdepending on whether calf serum or horse\rserum was added to the eagle\'s medium.  attempts\rto demonstrate virus activity by\rsubculture of supernatant fluids and lysed cells into\rhela cells, mixed culture with\rhuman and hamster cells, electron microscopy,\rand inoculation of newborn\rhamsters with irradiated tumor cells were negative.\r'),
 (404,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'142. trials of heterotransplantation of human cancer in rabbits\rand kleisbauer a.\rtrials of transplantation of human\rtumours (some 20, almost all carcinomas) in\rthe pleural cavity of large rabbits\r(6 months old flanders, weighing 3 kg.) gave\rnegative results also when cortisone\rtreatment was associated with it, though in\rthe cortisone treated animals the\rnecrosis of the tumours was less massive.\rexamination of the grafted tumour\rwas carried out at different times (from 8 to\r365 days after transplantation) and\rwas also controlled by radiographic examina-\rtions.  detailed description of the\rgiant cell reactions around the tumours and in\rthe adjoining lung.\r'),
 (405,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1207. solitary mast cell granuloma (histiocytoma) of the lung.\ra histopathologic, tissue culture and time-lapse cinemato-\rgraphic study\ra pulmonary histiocytoma in a 57-year-old\rwoman was studied intensively histo-\rpathologically and by other techniques.\rabundant mast cells were found within the\rlesion, a previously unreported finding.\rtissue culture studies suggested that the\rprocess is reactive rather than neoplastic.\rsome plasma-cell granulomas of the\rlung may be mast cell histiocytomas.\r'),
 (406,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2773. the value of fluorescence cytology for the cytodiagnosis\rof pulmonary cancer\rthe paper discusses the test results\rof 527 tissue samples sent in for the cytodiag-\rnostics of lung cancer and compares\rthe method of ao-fluorochromation with other\rmethods of preparation.  by means of\rapplying ao-fluorochromation, the rate of er-\rroneously positive findings could be\rreduced.  the rate of erroneously negative find-\rings was somewhat higher but the total\rdiagnostic precision of 93% was 3% higher\rthan in all other methods applied.\r'),
 (407,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2774. pitfalls in the clinical and histologic diagnosis of broncho-\rgenic carcinoma\ra necropsy study of 380 cases of extrathoracic\rcarcinoma revealed that pulmonary\rmetastases occurred in almost 50% of the\rcases and bronchial metastases in over\r25%.  there were 39 cases (10.3%) in the\rseries with clinical features simulating\rbronchogenic carcinoma and in 24 (62%)\rof these cases there was cytologic and/or\rhistologic confirmation.  carcinomas of\rthe pancreas presented the greatest source\rof diagnostic error accounting for more\rthan one-third of the 39 cases; the primary\rsite second in frequency was carcinoma\rof the kidney.  bronchial metastases were\rchiefly responsible for the clinical,\rcytologic, and histologic findings compatible\rwith the diagnosis of bronchogenic\rcarcinoma.  secondary growths in the lungs may\rpresent roentgenologically as solitary\rtumors indistinguishable from primary lung\rcancer.  metastatic lesions in lymph\rnodes, bronchi, and lung may exhibit pleomor-\rphic features simulating squamous\rcell carcinoma.  the diagnosis of bronchioloalveo-\rlar carcinoma in resected lung tissue\ris a presumptive conclusion inasmuch as the\ridentical morphological features may\rbe reproduced by metastases from duct or\rglandular carcinomas.  the simulation\rof bronchogenic carcinoma by metastatic tum-\rors occurs with sufficient frequency to\rchallenge the diagnostic accuracy of deaths\rcertified as bronchogenic carcinoma\rwith necropsy exclusion of other primary sites.\r'),
 (408,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4396. effects of arginine deprivation, ultraviolet radiation,\rand x-radiation on cultured kb cells.  a cytochemical and\rultrastructural study\rcultured kb cells (derived from a\rhuman oral carcinoma) grown in monolayers\rwere injured by one of three agents\rstarvation by arginine deprivation or treatment\rwith high doses of either ultraviolet\rradiation or x-radiation.  the different agents\rproduced changes in nucleolar structure\rand varying accumulations of triglyceride\rand glycogen.  all three agents produced\ran increase in number and size of lyso-\rsomes.  these were studied in acid\rphosphatase preparations, viewed by both light\rand electron microscopy, and, occasionally,\rin vital dye, esterase, and aryl sul-\rfatase preparations.  ultrastructurally,\ralterations in lysosomes suggested that\r\'residual bodies\' developed in a variety\rof ways, i.e., from the endoplasmic retic-\rulum, multivesicular bodies, or autophagic\rvacuoles.  following all three agents,\rthe endoplasmic reticulum assumed\rthe form of \'rough\' or \'smooth\' whorls, and,\rafter two of the agents, arginine\rdeprivation or ultraviolet radiation, it acquired\rcytochemically demonstrable acid\rphosphatase activity.  near connections between\rthe endoplasmic reticulum and lysosomes\rraise the possibility that in kb cells, at\rleast when injured, the endoplasmic\rreticulum is involved in the formation of\rlysosomes and the transport of acid\rphosphatase to them.\r'),
 (409,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1106. the simultaneous use of extracorporal circulation and hypothermia in the\rsurgery of the heart\rthe operative technique of cardiac\rsurgery under conditions of deep hypothermia with\rsimultaneous use of a pump oxygenator\rand cardiopulmonary bypass is described.  in\rthe majority of cases the patients were\rcooled with water at 2 c. and the perfusion\rvolume was reduced by more than 50%\rduring hypothermia.  in others, a gradient of\r10 c. between blood and water was\rmaintained and the perfusion volume was reduced\rby less than 50%.  the data presented\rshow that neither technique leads to hypoxic\rchanges in the cerebrum and internal\rorgans, provided the mean arterial pressure\ris kept between 70 and 90 mm. hg during perfusion.\rthe overall mortality in the\rauthors\' 168 cases - most of which\rhad congenital heart disease - was 14.8%.  in 53\rcases of tetralogy of fallot - most\rof them cyanotic - the vsd was closed by taking\ra flap of tissue from the crista supraventricularis.\rin this group mortality was 24.5%.\r'),
 (410,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'464. cardiac performance in hypothermia.  an experimental study of left\rventricular power, oxygen consumption, and efficiency in dogs\rmultiple cardiac parameters have been measured\rin 30 dogs cooled to 20 c. aortic\rblood temperature.  the parameters have been\rexpressed both as absolute values\rand as percentages of normothermic values.\rat normothermia, dogs with closed\rchest had an ascending aorta flow of 154%\rand a left ventricular external power of\r183% of the corresponding values for dogs\rwith open chest.  both ascending aorta\rflow and left circumflex coronary artery flow\rwere reduced to 25% of normothermic level\rat 20 c.  aortic arch mean pressure was\rreduced to 50% of normothermic level\rat 20 c.  total peripheral resistance was\rincreased to 205% of normothermic level\rat 20 c.  left ventricular external power\rwas decreased to 11% of normothermic\rlevel at 20 c.  left ventricular oxygen\rconsumption was decreased to 31% of nor-\rmothermic level at 20 c.  mechanical\refficiency of the left ventricular myocardium\rwas decreased to 39% of normothermic level at 20 c.\r'),
 (411,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3270. tolerance of dogs to deep hypothermia.  controlled and maintained with a\rpump oxygenator\rthe advantages of hypothermia of below 10 c for 2 hr,\rinduced and maintained by\rextracorporeal circulation of 200 min.,\rwere compared to partial bypass of the\rsame duration during normothermia.\rin the normothermic group 9 dogs out of 12\rlived.  in the hypothermic group 6 dogs\rout of 15 (40%) survived when perfused at\rthe high flow of 55 cc/kg/min.  eleven\rdogs out of 15 (70%) survived when the flow\rrate was reduced to 25 cc/kg/min when\rthe temperature was below 10 c.  the death\rin the high flow group were due mainly\rto postperfusion lung changes even when low\rpulmonary venous pressure was assured\rby venting in the left atrial chamber.  me-\rtabolic acidosis occurred in all groups;\rthough greater in the high flow, with the\rlow flow intermediate between the former\rand the normothermic group.  this change\rto a great degree, can be explained by the lung changes.\r'),
 (412,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1593. bleeding tendencies associated with profound-hypothermia technics in\rneurologic surgery\rforty-three patients with bleeding intracranial\raneurysms were operated on under\rdeep hypothermia and with the aid of extracorporeal\rcirculation.  the open-thorax\rmethod was used in 18 cases and the closed-thorax\rmethod in 25.  the following\rpoints are made  (1) the closed-thorax method\ris considered superior to the open-\rthorax method in several respects; (2) meticulous\rhemostasis is essential to control\rthe oozing that occurs during extracorporeal\rcirculation under profound hypothermia\runtil the heparin antagonist can become\reffective and body temperature can return\rto normal; (3) significant thrombocytopenia\rmay develop during extracorporeal cir-\rculation, and inhibition of the thrombin-fibrinogen\rreaction by factors other than\rheparin may cause a major coagulation defect\rand may also, by mimicking the he-\rparin effect, lead to the excessive use of\rheparin antagonists; (4) pathologic changes\rin microcirculation during extracorporeal\rcirculation may be determinants of a\rhemorrhagic tendency.\r'),
 (413,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4088. the use of hypothermia and dehydration in the treatment of severe\rcerebral hypoxia\rthe rational for using hypothermia or\rcerebral dehydration is to suppress or re-\rverse progressive or delayed cerebral\rdamage after hypoxia.  it is suggested that\rdamage of this nature results from injury\rto the astroglia and oligodendroglia,\respecially the former.  experimental and\rclinical evidence favors lowering of the\rbody temperature immediately after any\repisode of hypoxia accompanied by impor-\rtant damage to the brain.  the rational\rfor using dehydration is insecure and its\rresults are uncertain.  this treatment\rshould probably be reserved for cases in\rwhich a raised cerebrospinal fluid pressure\rhas been proved, and in which other\rmeasures, especially hypothermia,\rare either not available or have failed.\r'),
 (414,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7828. selective cerebral hypothermia  physiology and technic\ra safe, suitable technique for producing\rselective brain cooling by a perfusion\rmethod is described.  of 15 dogs, 7 survived.\rthe salient features aiding survival\rare discussed.  the use of a direct vasodilator\r(papaverine) in the perfusate to\rrelieve vasospasm markedly reduced cooling time\rand represented the most signi-\rficant technical advance over previously\rdescribed methods.  an acid base analysis\rutilizing the siggaard-andersen curve nomogram\rwas performed on 4 dogs and no\rsignificant acidosis noted during selective brain\rcooling.  a definite arteriovenous\rlactic acid difference developed at hypothermic\rtemperatures indicating the brain\rmay metabolize this substance in preference to\rglucose at lowered brain tempera-\rtures, the reasons for which were discussed.\rthe rate of disappearance of physi-\rcally dissolved oxygen (po2) was measured\rin the brain following ischemia at dif-\rferent temperatures.  the average rate of\rdisappearance at 20 c. was 40% of the\rrate at 37 c.  the discrepancy between this\rfinding and the in vitro oxygen utili-\rzation rate at the same temperature was discussed.\r'),
 (415,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'948.cardiac activity in cranio-cerebral hypothermia\rthe onset of hypothermia rarely alters the heart\rrate.  as it deepens to 35-32, the\rrate slows, and at the level of 30-29 it usually\ramounts to only half its original va-\rlue.  at 28 or below, the development of\rbradycardia is observed.  after warming\rto 32 the normal heart rate is restored.\rduring operations on the abdominal organs\rthe heart rate is only slightly modified.\rthe appearance of solitary extrasystoles is\rrare and is usually associated with stimulation\rof the diaphragm.  the most marked\rchanges in the heart rate are observed during operations on the heart,\respecially if\rit is excluded from the circulation.  an\ridioventricular rhythm may develop before\rthe heart stops beating.  after removal of the\rligatures from the venae cavae the nor-\rmal rhythm is restored.  as the temperature\rfalls, the excitability of the myocardium\rincreases.  conduction is more resistant.\rareflexia continues even during direct sti-\rmulation of reflexogenic zones.  in the surgical\rstage of cranio-cerebral hypothermia\rit is clear that no significant degree of energy\ror hemodynamic insufficiency deve-\rlops, whether in experimental conditions or\rduring operations on patients.  at opera-\rtion a well-marked stabilization of the contractile\rpower of the myocardium may be observed.\r'),
 (416,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'946. respiration in hypothermia.  i. respiratory pattern and\racid-base balance in the blood\rmongrel dogs, under light pentobarbital anesthesia,\rwere made hypothermic by im-\rmersing them in ice water and then normothermic\rin warm water.  in the course of\rcooling, the respiratory rate and pulmonary\rventilation, after an initial increase,\rwere reduced as the rectal temperature fell,\rand spontaneous respiration was ar-\rrested at rectal temperatures of 21-25 c.\ralveolar pco2 was increased, after an\rinitial slight lowering, with the progress of\rhypothermia.  arterial ph and standard\rbicarbonate (jorgensen and astrup) decreased,\rand the alkalinity of the blood coh/\rch (winterstein) decreased markedly during hypothermia.\rthese findings suggest\rboth respiratory and metabolic acidosis as the\rmechanisms concerned.  in the course\rof rewarming all these changes disappeared rapidly\rand completely though the venti-\rlatory stimulation observed as an initial transitory\rphenomenon during cooling failed to occur.\r'),
 (417,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'896. studies on blood viscosity and its significance in anesthesia\rthe principles for measuring blood viscosity\rhave been discussed.  although blood\rdoes not behave in a newtonian manner,\rthe data obtained in in vitro measurement\rare useful.  a modified simple method for\rmeasuring blood viscosity relative to nor-\rmal saline has been described.  there is\ressentially no difference in viscosity be-\rtween fresh blood and heparinized blood and between plasma and serum.\rviscosity varies with the quantity and nature of proteins\rin plasma and the cellular concentra-\rtion.  halothane and thiopental sodium reduce\rblood viscosity and seem to be indicat-\red in conditions in which there is hemoconcentration\rand a tendency for red blood\rcells to aggregate.  cyclopropane, hypothermia,\rand norepinephrine tend to raise\rblood viscosity and would seem to be contraindicated\rwhen the microcirculation is failing.\r'),
 (418,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4612. flow considerations in regional cerebral hypothermia\rit is suggested that low flows are dangerous\rand may cause anoxia either directly\ror by interfering with cooling.  sixty dogs\rhave been subjected to local cerebral\rhypothermia by the method of femoral to\rcarotid cooling of arterial blood with per-\rfusion at a predetermined pressure rather\rthan predetermined flow rate.  the cir-\rcuit is described and its advantages for\rclinical use mentioned together with its in-\raccuracies as a method of scientific investigation.\rthese are chiefly concerned\rwith maintenance of systemic blood pressure\rwhich may require the injection of\rpressor agents.  evidence for reduction in flow\rat low temperatures is discussed\rand evidence presented that this is not only due\rto increase in viscosity but that\rthere is an active spasm, manifested by\r\'rewarming humps\' which occur in the\rcooling graphs.  mean carotid flow rates\rwere determined by a revolution counter\rattached to a pump of fixed stroke volume,\rthe output of which was linked to the per-\rfusion pressure and thus determined by the resistance.\rthe place of added co2\ris discussed particularly in relation to the fall\rin partial pressure which accompa-\rnies the cooling of the blood.  the addition of 5% co2\rdid not increase total carotid\rflows.  halothane had been used as an anesthetic\rbecause of its sympatholytic ac-\rtion.  it has increased flows by 37% and\rabolished \'rewarming humps\'.  rheomacro-\rdex used as a priming fluid instead of blood\rproduced increased flow averaging 75%\rbut did not abolish spasm.  it is suggested that\rcooling faster than 1 c. per minute\ris not intrinsically dangerous if spasm is prevented\rand high flow maintained by the methods described.\r'),
 (419,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4613. selective brain cooling produced by cerebral ventricular perfusion\rhypothermic cerebral ventricular perfusion\rwas applied to dogs.  shivering appear-\red to be directly related to the cns temperature\rrather than the peripheral body\rtemperature.  selective heating of the brain-stem\rproduced panting.  rewarming\rof the body was retarded by the initiation of heat\rloss mechanisms controlled cen-\rtrally when hyperthermic perfusion was used.\rshivering disappeared but panting\rwas unaffected by pentobarbital anesthesia.\rcooling of one or both frontal areas and\rthe anterior part of the third ventricle did not\rsignificantly affect the respiratory\ror circulatory systems but brain-stem hypothermia\rproduced distinct respiratory\rand circulatory reactions.  it is suggested that\rcooling of the 3rd and 4th ventricu-\rlar areas may be utilized for anesthetic purposes.\r'),
 (420,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1139. optimal coronary flow in the bypassed normothermic and hypothermic heart\ra series of experiments were conducted in dogs\rin which bypass flow, temperature,\rand direct coronary perfusion pressure were varied.\rcoronary flow, coronary ven-\rous saturation, myocardial oxygen consumption (mvo2),\rand coronary vascular re-\rsistance were assayed.  coronary flow as a percentage\rof total bypass flow did not\rvary appreciably at varying levels of bypass flow.\rinduction of hypothermia, when\rtotal bypass flow is constant, results in decreasing\rcoronary flow.  induction of hy-\rpothermia when maintaining a constant bypass pressure\rresults in an increasing\rcoronary flow with temperatures down to 22 c.\rfurther cooling causes a reduction\rin flow.  using isolated coronary perfusion at 100 mm. hg,\rcoronary flow fell and\rresistance rose during the first 15 min. of bypass.\rusing isolated coronary perfu-\rsion at 100 mm. hg, induction of moderate hypothermia\r(25 c.) caused an increase\rin coronary flow and venous saturation and a decrease\rin cardiovascular resistance\rand mvo2.  under the same conditions, induction of\rhypothermia to 18 c. produced\rsimilar changes but caused myocardial hemorrhage\rand ventricular fibrillation.  pro-\rfound hypothermia probably leads to excessive\rfragility of the capillary bed.  reduc-\rtion of perfusion pressure to 50 mm. hg at near\rnormothermia reduced coronary\rflow and slightly reduced venous saturation\rand mvo2.  the same reduction of perfu-\rsion pressure at 18 c. produced similar but\rless marked changes.  reduction to 25\rmm. hg at 18 c. markedly reduced coronary flow,\rvenous saturation, and mvo2\rinitially, but with partial recovery later.  from this\rdata of acute experiments in\rdogs, coronary perfusion using moderate hypothermia\r(about 31 c.) and 50 mm.\rhg, slightly pulsatile mean pressure appears optimal.\r'),
 (421,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'974. extracorporeal hypothermia without thoracotomy.  an ex-\rperimental study in the use of cold for neurosurgery and\rcancericidal perfusions\rthis paper includes minor clinical notes\ron open heart surgery and cancer perfusion\rbut contains no experimental information\ron neurosurgery or cancer perfusions.  a\rmethod of closed-chest hypothermic perfusion\rin 30 dogs is reported.  the authors\rutilize drainage of superior and inferior cavae\rby gravity.  the volume of venous\rdrainage sometimes enhanced by transfusions\ror 12.5% low molecular weight dex-\rtran determined the flow rate.  cooling was\rmaintained for quite variable periods\rapparently generally to an unspecified\resophageal temperature.  perfusion time va-\rried from 30 min. to 4 hr.  animals with\rlow flows were perfused longer, had a high-\rer incidence of ventricular fibrillation,\rand a very low survival rate.  eleven ani-\rmals survived.  all had pre-cooling flow\rrates above 40 ml./kg./min., good flow\rrates during the perfusion, and only 3 had\rventricular fibrillation.  flow rates and\rsurvival were increased in animals receiving\rlow molecular weight dextran.  four-\rteen of 15 animals with ventricular fibrillation\rwere defibrillated electrically, 8 re-\rgained \'adequate\' cardiac function, but only 3\rsurvived.  some interesting data on\rregional cooling of the lower half of the body\ris presented.  the authors conclude\rwithout sufficient evidence that the most\rimportant factor in the mortality in hypo-\rthermic perfusion is the ability to maintain\r\'a flow rate approaching the estimated\rnormothermic cardiac output of the animal\'\r'),
 (422,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2406. profound hypothermia\rthe aim of hypothermia is protection of vital\rcerebral structures from hypoxia\rduring aneurysm repair; profound hypothermia\ris also valuable in operating on\rcertain cardiac defects which cannot be repaired\reven with whole body perfusion.\rsince the time needed for aneurysm repair often\rexceeded the safe limit of 8 to 12\rminutes without circulation afforded by surface\rhypothermia of 29  to 30  c., the\rauthors have investigated the drew (open-chest)\rtechnic, the closed-chest method,\rand isolated cerebral perfusion.  the drew technic\rconsists of substituting two\rpumps for the heart while the patient\'s lungs act\ras the oxygenator.  because of its\rdisadvantages (the large amounts of blood needed\rand the morbidity due to intra-\rcardiac cannulation and median sternotomy), a\rclosed-chest method was developed,\rusing a mayo-gibbons vertical-sheet pump-oxygenator\rto provide the perfusion and\rextracorporeal cooling without requiring thoracotomy.\rin cerebral perfusion, blood\ris taken from one artery, pumped through a heat\rexchanger, and returned to another\rartery.  the authors describe anesthetic technics,\roffer comparisons of the three\rmethods, give instructions pertaining to the production\rof hypothermia, and list the\rproblems encountered in the management of these cases.\r'),
 (423,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3194. systemic hypothermia via gastric cooling\reight dogs underwent gastric cooling for\rsystemic hypothermia.  each dog was cooled\rwith the balloon filled with a \'safe\' volume\rbased on weight (20 ml/kg) and subjected\rto cooling with the balloon filled maximally,\rbut safely to a pressure of 10 mm hg.\rconsistently, the latter procedure was far\rmore efficient, averaging 2.6 times as\rrapid for all degrees of hypothermia.  a\rdecrease in core temperature by 7 c re-\rquired an average of only 28.4 minutes.\ron comparison with clinical reports of hy-\rpothermia induced by the usual gastric\rcooling, an improved efficiency of two-fold\rto three-fold is still noted.\r'),
 (424,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3820. the dubious haemopoietic\rstem cell function of the lym-\rphoid cells of the blood.\rautoradiographic studies on\rdogs\rthe migration, fate and turnover of\rlymphoid cells in blood and bone marrow of\rirradiated and non-irradiated dogs were\rstudied by serial autoradiography with co-\rping of the hind legs during the plasma\rclearance time of h3-thymidine injected into\ran anterior vein.  in irradiated dogs,\rthe h3-thymidine injection procedure was car-\rried out during the early recovery phase\rfollowing 250 r whole body x-irradiation.\rconclusive evidence of transformation of\rhematogenous bone marrow lymphoid cells\rinto hemopoietic precursors was not found.\rhowever, in the light of the individual\rgrain counts transformation of a few lymphoid\rcells into hemopoietic cells cannot be\rruled out.  the data obtained from a dog in the\rvery early recovery phase following\rwhole body irradiation strongly indicate such\ra transformation.\r'),
 (425,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3927. studies on growth and cytomorphosis\rin the thymo-lympha-\rtic systems - with special\rreference to the influence of\rthe thymus and the thyroid\rin guinea-pigs\rmigratory streams of lymphocytes between\rdifferent parts of the thymo-lymphatic\rsystem were evaluated by comparisons between\rlymphocyte populations in thoracic-\rduct lymph and arterial and venous blood,\respecially thymic venous blood.  by re-\rcording organ weights in sham-operated and\rthymectomized guinea-pigs, treated\rwith thyroxin or untreated, the importance\rof the thymus and the thyroid for growth\rand regeneration in the thymo-lymphatic\rsystem was studied.  the main results are\ras follows.  there is a considerable venous\routput of lymphocytes with low mito-\rchondrial content (small lymphocytes) from\rthe thymus in normal young guinea-pigs.\rthis explains the much higher incidence of\rsmall lymphocytes in blood than in tho-\rracic-duct lymph.  neonatal thymectomy\rcauses lymphatic hypotrophy with defi-\rciency of lymphocytes and pyroninophilic\rcells in relation to reticular ones.  body\rgrowth and survival of the animals are not\raffected.  in the thymus, exogenous\rthyroxin most probably promotes differentiation\rof large basophilic cells to small\rlymphocytes, resulting in an increased output of\rsmall lymphocytes.  in the lymph\rnodes, thyroxin promotes differentiation of large\rpyroninophilic cells (\'transitional\rcells\') into immature and mature plasma cells.\rthe effects of thyroxin on dif-\rferentiation are followed by an increased growth\rof the thymo-lymphatic organs,\rcharacterized by an increased incidence of large\rbasophilic cells and increased weight\rof the lymphatic organs.  growth of the thymus and\rlymph nodes precedes that of\rthe red splenic pulp.  this delayed splenic response\ris not due to a transformation\rof an increased number of immigrated thymic\rlymphocytes, as neonatal thymectomy\rdoes not prevent the thyroxin-stimulated\roccurrence of large basophilic cells in the\rred splenic pulp.  the thyroxin-stimulated\rgrowth of the lymphatic system is ac-\rcompanied by an increased output of larger\rlymphocytes through the thoracic\rduct, resulting in an increased number of\rlarger lymphocytes in the blood.  in\rpostnatally thymectomized animals, having a\rnormal (or above normal) amount of\rcirculating small lymphocytes, thyroxin produces\ra drastic decrease in the number of\rsmall blood lymphocytes, indicating a decreased\rdelivery and/or increased disappear-\rance of these cells to and from the blood, respectively.\rthis decrease in number of small\rlymphocytes is not seen in sham-operated animals.\ras judged by studies of organ\rweights, the thyroxin-stimulated growth and\rregeneration of the lymphatic tissue\rare influenced antagonistically by thymectomy\rand synergistically by local factors\rin involuted tissue.\r'),
 (426,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'815. the origin of macrophages\rfrom bone marrow in the rat\rskin windows\' and subcutaneous coverslips\rwere applied to rats in a study designed\rto identify the tissues in which the precursors\rof macrophages proliferate.  lympho-\rcyte-depletion by either chronic drainage from\rthe thoracic duct or 400 rads of x-\rirradiation failed to suppress the emigration of\rmacrophages or to reduce the pro-\rportion of them which became labelled after an\rinjection of tritiated thymidine.  x-\rirradiation with 750 rads suppressed\rthe emigration and the labelling of the exudate\rmacrophages.  both were restored to\rnormal when the tibial marrow was shielded\rduring irradiation.  radioactively-labelled\rcell suspensions obtained from thoracic\rduct lymph, lymph nodes, thymus, spleen\rand bone marrow were transfused into\rsyngeneic recipients.  the emigration of\rlabelled macrophages on to coverslips\rcould be demonstrated only in recipients\rof labelled bone marrow and spleen cells.\rlabelled monocytes were found in the blood\rof rats which had received injections\rof labelled bone marrow.  it was concluded\rthat in the rat, bone marrow, and to a\rlesser extent spleen, are major sources of\rthe macrophages which emigrate into\rfoci of acute, non-bacterial inflammation.\r'),
 (427,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1786. studies of the\rleucocyte compartment\rin guinea-pig bone\rmarrow after acute\rhaemorrhage and\rsevere hypoxia  evidence\rfor a common stem-cell\rafter a large acute hemorrhage,\rthe absolute le-\rvels of neutrophils, eosinophils, and\rbasophils in guinea\rpig bone marrow are considerably\rreduced.  all stages\rof differentiation are involved, the\rdecline in myelo-\rblasts and promyelocytes being\rparticularly marked.\rexposure to severe hypoxia also\rtemporarily depresses\rthe number of marrow granulocytes.\rbone marrow\rlymphocytes are only slightly reduced\rafter a single he-\rmorrhage but in the later stages of\rsevere hypoxia their\rnumbers are greatly reduced.\rassuming the supply of\rstem cells in the bone marrow\ris not unlimited, the de-\rcrease in marrow granulocytes\rand lymphocytes follow-\ring marked erythropoietic stimulation\rappears to favor\ra monophyletic theory of hemopoiesis;\ra heavy demand\rfor stem cells to differentiate into the\rerythron may\rtemporarily restrict the\rnumber entering the leukon.  the\rhypoxic animals showed\ra considerable loss of body weight\rand the notable reduction\rof marrow lymphocytes in the\rlater stages of hypoxia\rmay be specifically related to a\rgeneralized atrophy of\rlymphoid tissue.  using h3-thymi-\rdine there is evidence\rof active dna synthesis in guinea\rpig metamyelocytes.\ralthough dna-synthesis was found\rin metamyelocytes of\rnormal marrow, after hemorrhage\rthese cells form a much\rlarger proportion of the total\rsynthesizing cells in the\rgranulocyte compartment and\ralso the ratio of labeled\rmetamyelocytes to myelocytes\ris considerably increased.\rmicrospectrophotometric\rmeasurements of the feulgen\rdna-content of metamyelo-\rcytes after hemorrhage show\rthat there are 2 populations\rof these cells.  one group has\rvalues typical of resting or\rnonsynthesizing cells but a 2nd\rgroup shows a complete\rrange of dna-values up to levels\rcharacteristic of those\rfound in dividing cells.  certain\rsmall mononuclear cells\rwith minimal but deeply basophilic\rcytoplasm are a dis-\rtinctive group of dna-synthesizing\rcells in marrow af-\rter hemorrhage.  morphologically,\rthere appears to be a\rcomplete sequence between these\rcells and procrythro-\rblasts.\r'),
 (428,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3831. relative ability of parental\rmarrow to repopulate lethal-\rly irradiated f1 hybrids\rlethally irradiate (c57bl x 101)f1 mice\rinjected with a mixture of 10 million\rc57bl and 10 million 101 bone-marrow\rcells were repopulated only by the 101\rbone-marrow cells.  experiments with other\rcell mixtures indicated that the 101\rmarrow was relatively nine times as efficient\ras c57bl marrow in repopulating\rlethally irradiated (c57bl x 101)f1 mice.\rresults from additional strain combina-\rtions suggested that the behavior of the\rdonor marrows was not determined solely\rby h-2 factors.  c57bl marrow, which\rfrequently regresses in irradiated f1 mice,\rhas shown to be relatively less capable\rof repopulating the recipient than regularly\rretained parental marrow.  the differences\rin the relative abilities of parental mar-\rrows to repopulate f1 mice cannot as yet be\rfully explained.  they might be corre-\rlated with physiological differences between\rthe parental marrows or with a micro-\renvironmental advantage of one hematopoietic\rcell type over another in the irradiated\rrecipient.  immunological and physiological factors\rthat might favor this selective\rgrowth are discussed.\r'),
 (429,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3832. pluripotent stem cell function\rof the mouse marrow\r\'lymphocyte\'\rbone marrow from normal and polycythemic\rmice was filtered through glass wool\rcolumns to remove cells other than \'lymphocytes\'.\rfor a given number of nucleated\rcells, filtered marrow was more efficient than\rthe original marrow in repopulating\rthe spleen of an isogenic recipient previously\rexposed to lethal irradiation.  the\rproliferative capacity of both the filtered and\runfiltered marrow suspensions ap-\rpeared to be a constant function of the number\rof small and medium \'lymphocytes\'\rpresent and not of any other cell type.\r'),
 (430,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2045. the effect of\runilateral limb shield-\ring on the haemopoietic\rresponse of the\rguinea-pig to gamma\rirradiation\rguineapigs were exposed to\r150 r  -irradiation\rwhilst approx. 1/5 of the total bone\rmarrow was protect-\red by shielding 2 limbs.  quantitative\rcell counts of both\rthe shielded and irradiated marrow\rwere combined with\robservations on the thymus, spleen\rand blood during the\rrecovery period, and compared\rwith the effects of whole-\rbody irradiation.  following\rwhole-body irradiation\r(150 r) the thymus shows a\rdelayed secondary cellular\rdepletion coinciding with a\rmarked splenic hyperplasia.\rboth phenomena were eliminated\rby limb shielding.  the\rlymphocytes in the irradiated\rmarrow of partially shiel-\rded animals continued to show\rboth the overshoot and the\rsecondary fall in numbers which\rcharacterize recovery\rfrom whole-body irradiation\r(150 r).  after an initial fall\rin numbers of erythroid and\rgranulocytic precursors,\rthe shielded marrow showed\ra temporary increase in\rgranulocytopoiesis coinciding\rwith an abortive phase of\rgranulocytopoiesis in the irradiated\rmarrow.  there was\rno evidence of any effective colonization\rof irradiated\rmarrow by cells from the shielded marrow.\rthe signi-\rficance of these findings is discussed.\r'),
 (431,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4311. studies on intravenous transfusion\rof thymus cells and\rlymphnode cells.  iii. influence of\rtransfused thymus cells\rand lymphnode cells on the bone\rmarrow\rin rabbits transfused with thymus cells and\rlymphnode cells the peripheral blood and\rbone marrow were studied.  the transfusion\rof thymus cells caused a peripheral\rlymphocytosis and a diminution of lymphoid\rcells in the bone marrow of both young\rand adult rabbits.  the transfusion of lymphnode\rcells resulted in a peripheral lympho-\rpenia, and an initial increase and a subsequent\rdiminution of lymphoid cells in the\rbone marrow.  it is suggested that lymphoid cells\rin the bone marrow may be lympho-\rcytes which are stored or discharged according\rto a variety of conditions.  further-\rmore, thymus cells are thought to mobilize\rlymphocytes from the bone marrow to\rthe peripheral blood.\r'),
 (432,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5041. studies on hypoxia.  iii. the\rdifferential response of the\rbone marrow to primary and\rsecondary hypoxia\rtwenty-five adult male guinea pigs were\rplaced in a decompression chamber, at a\rsimulated altitude of 14,000 feet for 5 days,\rthen kept in ordinary air for 5 days,\rand finally returned to the decompression\rchamber to be subjected to hypoxia a\rsecond time, for periods ranging from 1\rto 5 days.  during this period of secondary\rhypoxia quantitative studies were made\rof the changes in the blood and bone marrow.\rin secondary as in primary hypoxia there\ris a significant increase in the nucleated\rred cells of the marrow.  in secondary\rhypoxia, however, there is a very marked\rincrease in the marrow lymphocytes,\rwhereas in primary hypoxia the lymphocytes\rfall.  the marrow reticulocytes remain\rat a fairly constant level despite marked\rfluctuations in erythropoiesis.\r'),
 (433,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1044. an investigation of lymphocyte\rproduction in guinea-pig\rbone marrow\revidence from a variety of experiments indicates\rthat lymphocytes are produced in\rguinea-pig bone marrow.  under certain conditions\rthe numbers produced appear to\rbe considerable.  during recovery from irradiation\rthere are numerous telophases\rin marrow smears which appear to be forming small\rlymphocytes.  moreover, many\rlymphocytes are still found in shielded bone marrow\rafter the rest of the body, in-\rcluding the conventional lymphoid tissues, has\rreceived lethal or supra-lethal irra-\rdiation.  almost 50% of these cells are formed\rafter the irradiation.  finally, when\rbone marrow is cultured in the peritoneal cavity\rof a host whose own lymphocyte\rproduction has been suppressed by irradiation,\rsmall percentages of newly-formed\rsmall lymphocytes are found in this marrow.\r'),
 (434,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'103. repopulation of bone marrow\rin mice  number and type of\rcells required for\rpost-x-irradiation protection\rfractionation of cells from mouse bone\rmarrow and autologous mouse spleen indi-\rcates that the cell responsible for bone\rmarrow repopulation and x-irradiation\rprotection resembles the small lymphocyte.\rexperiments with injection of different\rnumbers of bone marrow and spleen cells\rand observations on survival obtained by\rfractional irradiation of the entire body and\rof extirpation of the shielded spleen\rafter irradiation indicate that approximately\r3 x 10 4 cells of this type are required\rto provide 50% survival, and that approximately\rthis number migrates from the\rshielded extremity or spleen of a mouse per hour\r(slightly faster for spleen and slower for bone marrow).\r'),
 (435,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'104. hyperbasophilic cells as an\rindication of proliferation of\rbone marrow transplanted to\rirradiated dogs\ra study was made of hyperbasophilic cells\rwhich appeared following transplantation\rof bone marrow to 20 irradiated mongrel\rdogs of both sexes.  in the main series of\rexperiments the animals were irradiated\rwith a dosage of 600 r., using a four-tube\rrum-3 x-ray machine  voltage 200 kv,\rcurrent 10 ma, filters 0.5 cu mm + 1.0\rmm.al, target distance 60 cm., rate\r18-22 r./min.  at 1-2 days after irradiation,\ra suspension of bone marrow cells in a\rdosage of 10 9 - 5 x 10 9 nuclear cells was\radministered i.v.  the marrow was\robtained by aspiration from various skeletal\rbones or by compression from the\rsternum, ribs and other bones.  a study was made\rof the morphological composition\rof the blood and bone marrow before irradiation\rand at 1-5, 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30\rdays after irradiation and transfusion of bone mar-\rrow, and thereafter at 10-15 days\rintervals.  smears of blood and marrow were\rstained with azure-ii-eosin.  it was\rfound that distinctive cells with basophilic proto-\rplasm and frequent incidence of an\rimmature nucleus were present in the blood of\rdogs following irradiation with 600 r.\rand transplantation of bone marrow.  hyper-\rbasophilic cells appeared in the blood\rat 2 - 4 days after transplantation and attained\ra maximum 14 - 21 days later; thereafter\rtheir number diminished rapidly.  the\rtrend of number of hyperbasophilic cells\rcoincided with that of other donor elements\r(leukocytes, erythrocytes).  hyperbasophilic\rcells were not found during acute radia-\rtion sickness in dogs which were not given\rinjections of bone marrow.  they were\rfound 3 mth. after transplantation of bone\rmarrow to nonirradiated puppies at 2-3\rdays of age.  when the irradiation dosage\rwas increased to 800-1,000 r., the number\rof hyperbasophilic cells increased and\rattained a peak sooner than after the 600 r.\rdosage.  such cells were formed from\rthe donor cells.\r'),
 (436,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'172. autoradiographic\rstudies of lymphoid\rcells in blood and\rbone marrow of nor-\rmal and irradiated\rdogs\rthe migration, fate, and\rturnover of lymphoid\rcells in blood and bone marrow\rof 4 irradiated and 4 non-\rirradiated dogs were studied\rby serial autoradiography\rwith clamping of the hind legs\rduring the plasma clear-\rance time of h3-thymidine\rinjected into an anterior\rvein.  in irradiated dogs, the\rh3-thymidine injection pro-\rcedure was carried out during\rthe early recovery phase\rafter 250 r of whole-body\rx-irradiation.  the results on\r2 irradiated and 2 normal\rdogs were described in de-\rtail.  migration of lymphoid\rcells from blood to marrow\rparenchyma was confirmed\rin the irradiated dogs.  con-\rclusive evidence of transformation\rof these cells into\rhemopoietic precursors was not\rfound.  the relative\rnumber of large lymphoid cells,\rthe labeling index of\rthe whole population of lymphoid\rcells, and that of small\rlymphoid cells were increased\rin irradiated marrow;\rfew initially labeled small\rlymphoid cells could also be\robserved.  these data indicate\rthat the pattern of pro-\rliferation of lymphoid cells is\rchanged in irradiated re-\rgenerating bone marrow.\r'),
 (437,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'175. lysozyme in bone\rmarrow and periph-\reral blood cells\rby means of an indirect\rhistochemical technique,\rthe intracellular lysozyme of\rthe formed elements of the\rperipheral blood and bone marrow\rwas estimated.  evi-\rdence is presented that monocytes,\ras well as mature\rneutrophils and their precursors\rextending back to the\rprogranulocyte, contain significant\ramounts of this en-\rzyme.  a rare mature eosinophil\rdemonstrated a trace\rof lysozyme activity.  there was\rno evidence of lyso-\rzyme activity in basophils,\rerythrocytes, megakaryo-\rcytes, platelets, plasma\rcells, tissue mast cells or\rbone marrow\rreticuloendothelial cells.\r'),
 (438,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1770. proliferative activity of the\rlymphatic tissues of rats as\rstudied with tritium-labelled\rthymidine\rcytokinetic data are presented, employing\rquantitation of h3dna in the lymphatic\rtissues of normal rats serially sacrificed\rafter h3tdr administration.  a marked\rdifference in the patterns of initial labeling\rand label loss was observed between the\rthymus and peripheral lymphatic tissue.\rthe data are compatible with other indica-\rtions of rapid cell renewal in the thymus.\rthere is suppression of initial uptake of\rh3tdr into the dna of each large lymphocytic\rprogenitor cell in the thymus, appa-\rrently because of a feedback of thymidine\rcontaining material from small lympho-\rcytes in the thymus.  depletion of the thymus\rof small cells, as by operative stress\ror whole body x-ray, leads to a marked\rincrease in the uptake of h3tdr into the\rdna of large thymocytes.  this finding,\rwhich is in agreement with the previous\rfindings of sugino et al. suggesting transfer\rof thymine nucleotides from small thy-\rmus lymphocytes to precursor cells, may or\rmay not be related to the apparent\rtransfer of dna label between thymic cells.\rthe evidence for the latter consists of\rthe curvilinear dilution of the dna label in\rthe thymus proliferating cell population\rand the relationship between the rate of dna\rlabel dilution in large cells and the\rdna in the small cells in the thymus.  after\rthe dna label in progenitor cells in\rthe thymus and lymph nodes has entered the\rsmall cell population, the subsequent\rdilution of grains in these dividing cells follows\rthe same slope as the loss of radio-\ractivity from the entire lymph node.  there is a\rlong retention of some h3dna label\rin the dividing lymph node cell population.  this\rsuggests that the loss of radioacti-\rvity from the dividing cells and from the small\rcell population as a whole occurs e-\rqually.  this pattern prevails regardless of\rwhether the percentage of large and\rsmall cells is altered experimentally.  these\rfindings can be explained by an inter-\rchange of the dna nuclear label between small\rlymphocytes and large lymphocytes.\rthis could occur by some process such as\rphagocytosis or pinocytosis, or by trans-\rformation of the small lymphocyte into a large,\rdividing cell.  the data fit best with\rthe latter possibility.  all or any of these\rmechanisms would lead to an equilibration\rof the dna label between large and small\rcells.  this finding prevents the assign-\rment of a finite life span to lymphocytes on\rthe basis of dna labeling kinetics.  ne-\rvertheless, there appear to be at least two\rdifferent types of lymphocytes.  one,\rthe \'thymus-type\' lymphocyte, is found in the\rthymus cortex, bone marrow and ger-\rminal centers of lymphoid follicles.  the other\rtype, found abundantly in the wide-\rspread peripheral lymphatic tissue, shows a\rvery prolonged retention of dna la-\rbel and is believed to be recirculating,\r\'immunologically committed\' cells described\rby others.  these cells do not appear to\renter the thymus cortex.\r'),
 (439,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'6674. the free and glucuronic acid-bound\r17-hydroxy-corticosteroids in the\rplasma of patients with cancer of the\rbreast on i.v. infusion of acth\rseventeen patients with advanced mammary\rcancer were given an infusion with\r3 u. of acth in 5 hr. and 6 others an infusion\rof 25 u.  determinations were made\rof the plasma 17-hydroxy-corticosteroids,\rfree and bound to glucuronic acid both\rbefore and after the infusion.  in rapidly\rgrowing carcinomas, high initial values\rwere found for the free corticosteroids\r(more than 20 ug./100 ml. of plasma).\rthe ratio of free to bound corticosteroids is\rfor stage iv patients 1.8 on the average,\rand approximately 1 for the mixed\rforms stage iv + m.  these ratios are not\raltered by acth.  shifts in the ratio\rof free to bound corticosteroids with acth\rtreatment can be seen, depending on\rthe initial value of the free corticosteroids.\rthe administration of 3 u. is enough\rand the 5 hr. value is some 70%, related to a\rmaximal stimulation with 25 u.\r'),
 (440,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4179. reduced estriol excretion in patients\rwith breast cancer prior to endocrine\rtherapy\rthe urinary quotient of estriol/estrone +\restradiol-17b(eq) was measured chemically in\rwomen with and without breast cancer, as an in-\rdex of the ratio of noncarcinogenic impeded es-\rtrogens to mammary carcinogenic estrogens.  in\r34 controls, the median eq was 1.3 before and 1.2\rafter menopause, with only 21% of the patients sub-\rnormal.  in 26 breast cancer patients without endo-\rcrine treatment or recent surgery, the median eq\rwas 0.5 and 0.8 respectively, with 62% of the pa-\rtients subnormal.  after major surgery or hormo-\rnal therapy, only 23% of 53 patients were subnor-\rmal, no remissions being observed unless the eq\rrose toward normal.  matching of 24 controls and\rpatients in pairs by age and ovarian status in the\rwilcoxon test indicated that the decreased eq ex-\rcreted in untreated cancer was significant at the\r0.2% confidence level.  the marked increase in eq\rinduced by castration and androgen, estrogen, and\rcorticosteroid therapy suggests that normaliza-\rtion of a precancerous metabolic imbalance be-\rtween impeded and active estrogens derived from\rovarian and adrenocortical sources contributed to\rarrested growth of estradiol-dependent metastases.\r'),
 (441,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1107. urinary excretion of estrone,\restradiol and estriol by pa-\rtients with breast cancer and\rbenign breast disease\rpremenopausal patients with breast cancer\rand benign breast disease appear to ex-\rcrete a significantly lower percentage of\rthe total estrogen as estrone and a signifi-\rcantly higher percentage as estriol than\rwomen in the premenopausal control group.\rthere was no significant difference in the\rexcretion of total estrogen between cancer\rgroups and controls in good health.\rpostmenopausal patients with cancer excreted\rhigher levels of estriol than postmenopausal\rcontrol groups.  the increase in estriol\rexcretion cannot be explained by debilitation.\r'),
 (442,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5323. systemic effects of androgenic\rand estrogenic hormones in advanced\rbreast cancer\rthe systemic effects of diethylstilbestrol\r(45 patients), testosterone propionate\r(48 patients), and both hormones (22 patients)\rwere studied during the treatment\r(six weeks to over three months) of advanced\rbreast cancer in postmenopausal\rwomen.  serious complications included\rinduced hypercalcemia and fluid re-\rtention.  physiologic effects such as\rurinary incontinence (diethylstilbestrol),\rvirilization (testosterone), or nausea and\rvomiting did not necessitate disconti-\rnuance of treatment.  androgenic therapy\rstimulated erythropoiesis.  observa-\rtions on the systemic reactions to these\rhormonal agents definitely contribute to\rthe evaluation of sex steroid therapy.\r'),
 (443,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3478. the effect of dehydroepiandrosterone\ron the 17-hydroxycorti-\rcosteroids in the plasma in various stages\rof cancer and other diseases of\rthe breast\rthe reducing effect of dehydroepiandrosterone\ron the plasma corticosteroids is\ron the average shortened in advanced\r(stage iv) cases of breast cancer.  in 3\rgroups of patients, the lowest corticosteroid\rlevels were found up to 6 hr. after\rinfusion of dehydroepiandrosterone-phosphate.\rin patients with mastopathy the\reffect was still detectable 12 hr. later; in patients\rwith breast cancer in stage iv the\rinitial levels were reached at that time.  in\rcases with stages i and ii lesions, the\rfindings were intermediate.  the shortening\ris attributed to a more intensive\rtransformation of dehydroepiandrosterone in\radvanced cases of breast cancer.\r'),
 (444,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5274. urinary excretion of estrone,\restradiol and estriol by patients with\rprostatic cancer and benign prostatic\rhypertrophy\rand hopkins c.e.\rurinary estrone, estradiol, and estriol\rfractions excreted by 21 patients with\rprostatic cancer, 17 patients with benign\rhypertrophy, and 59 clinically well\rsubjects were assayed to determine whether\rdifferences exist.  absolute levels of\restrone, estradiol, and estriol fractions were\rnot significantly different.  the\rexcretion of relatively lower levels of estrone\rand estradiol, and relatively higher\rlevels of estriol by patients with prostatic\rcancer compared to clinically well\rsubjects resulted in significantly lower\rproportions of the total estrogen being\rexcreted as estrone and estradiol.  differences in\rthe proportions of estrogen frac-\rtions between patients with benign hypertrophy\rand clinically well subjects were\rnot significant.  with the exception of a significantly\rhigher percentage of the total\restrogen being excreted as estrone by the patients\rwith benign hypertrophy,\rdifferences between that group and the cancer\rgroup were also not significant.\rclinical variations between the 3 groups, and\rwithin the cancer and hypertrophy\rgroups, preclude assignment of significant\rdifferences to prostatic dystrophies\ralone.  cancer patients experiencing inanition\rdue to a loss of appetite excreted\rsignificantly lower levels of estrone than patients\rwho reported no loss of appetite.\rsignificantly lower levels of estrone were excreted\rby patients with benign hyper-\rtrophy hospitalized 6 days or more compared to\rpatients hospitalized 5 days or less.\ra significantly higher urinary estrone-androsterone\rratio was present in the cancer\rgroup than in the clinically well group.  it is not\rbelieved, however, that an arbi-\rtrary ratio can be used to suggest an internal\restrogen-androgen imbalance.\r'),
 (445,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'28029 enzymic synthesis of steroid\rsulfates.  ii. presence of steroid sulfo-\rkinase in human mammary carcinoma\rextracts\rextracts of human primary and secondary\rmammary carcinomas were shown to\rcontain steroid sulfokinase(s) in every case\rexamined.  examination of normal\rbreast tissue surrounding the tumors revealed\rvery weak steroid sulfokinase\ractivity in some instances.  this was thought to\rbe due to the fibrous nature and\rpoor cellularity of the normal breast tissue.\rnormal ovarian tissue specimens,\robtained from cancer patients undergoing\roophorectomy, did not generally\rcontain the enzyme, but trace levels were detected\rin 1 of 5 specimens examined.\rsteroids, without necessarily showing conversion\rto steroid sulfate, were observed\rto increase the incorporation of s35-sulfate into\rone of the products formed enzy-\rmically on incubating breast tissue extracts\rwith s35-adenosine-3\'-phosphate-5\'-\rphosphosulfate.\r'),
 (446,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3752. steroid excretion in early breast cancer\rpatients with advanced breast cancer\rwho subsequently fail to respond to adrenalec-\rtomy or hypophysectomy have been\rfound to excrete abnormal amounts of the\rurinary metabolites of androgen and\rcortisol.  when similar measurements are\rcarried out on patients with early breast\rcancer, it is found that approximately half\rthe cases presenting for mastectomy are\ralso excreting abnormal amounts of these\rsteroids.  subsequent follow-up shows that\rthese cases tend to have a poor progno-\rsis, and a trial had therefore been started\rin which the abnormality is being cor-\rrected.  in addition, it seems possible that\rthe deficiency in adrogen excretion may\rprecede the onset of the disease.  this\rproblem is being investigated in a trial\rinvolving urinary steroid estimations in\r5000 normal women.  the measurements\rare being compared with the subsequent\rdevelopment of breast cancer.\r'),
 (447,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2365. the excretion of oestrone, pregnanediol\rand pregnanetriol in breast\rcancer patients.  i. excretion after spontaneous\rmenopause\rthe urinary excretion of oestrone, pregnanediol and\rpregnanetriol was determined\rin a series of postmenopausal breast cancer patients\rreceiving no endocrine treat-\rment.  the steroid excretion was studied\rboth in relation to the age of the patients\ras well as in relation to the time elapsed\rsince the last menstrual cycle.  the results\rindicate that after an initial slow decrease\rfrom the age of the menopause onward,\rthe excretion of oestrone and preganediol\rincreases again.  a new maximum was\rfound in the group 10-15 yr. after the\rmenopause.  the excretion of pregnanetriol\rhowever, remains relatively constant\rafter a more rapid fall during the first few\ryears after the menopause.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (448,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2366. the excretion of oestrone,\rpregnanediol and pregnanetriol in breast\rcancer patients.  ii. effect of ovariectomy,\rovarian irradiation and corticos-\rteroids.\rthe urinary excretion of oestrone,\rpregnanediol and pregnanetriol was determined\rin breast cancer patients at different\rstages of their endocrine treatment.  the\rresults demonstrate that corticosteroids\rin substitution doses (cortisone 50 mg. daily\ror prednisone 10 mg. daily, divided in 4\rdaily doses) are very effective in depressing\rthe excretion of all 3 steroids in postmenopausal\rpatients.  this is in agreement with\rthe clinical impression that these easily tolerated\rsmall doses of corticosteroids have\rthe same therapeutic effect as adrenalectomy in\rpatients with breast cancer.  the\rresults indicate that the ovaries may contribute\rto the production of oestrogens for\rmany years after the menopause, and that this\rproduction is depressed by ovarian\rirradiation.  this is in agreement with the clinical\robservation that ovarian irra-\rdiation has a therapeutic value in postmenopausal\rwomen with breast cancer.\r'),
 (449,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'414. estimation of the urinary\r17-ketosteroids in the diagnosis of car-\rcinoma of the prostate\rin 33 patients with histologically\rconfirmed carcinoma and in 37 patients with\rconfirmed benign hyperplasia of the\rprostate the amount of neutral 17-ketosteroids\rwas estimated in 24-hr. samples of\rurine.  the results revealed that, contrary to\rreports in the literature, this diagnostic\rmethod is quite unreliable.  raised\r17-ketosteroid levels were found also in\ra high percentage of control subjects.\rmoreover, the estimation of 17-ketosteroids\ris a very laborious biochemical\rmethod and involves a relatively great\rexperimental error.\r'),
 (450,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2820. influence of small doses of corticosteroids\ron the excretion of pregnanetriol and oestrone\rin a series of patients with breast cancer\rexcretion of oestrone and pregnanetriol\rwas determined.  with administration of\rcorticosteroids oestrone excretion in\rpostmenopausal women diminished   67%.\ra decrease of pregnanetriol ex-\rcretion values was observed as well.  evidently\ra low oestrone excretion in patients\rsubjected to corticosteroid therapy is due to a\rdepression of the adrenal function.\r'),
 (451,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5062. urinary ii-deoxy-17-oxosteroids\rin british and japanese women with\rreference to the incidence of breast cancer\rjapanese women excrete more andosterene\r(5a) relative to aetiocholanone (5b)\rthan do british women living in tokyo.  the\rmean 5a/5b ratio in the former is 1.3\rand in the latter 1.0, and these means differ\rsignificantly.  the ratio is markedly\raffected by thyroid function, and thyroid\rdisease has been reported to affect the\rincidence of breast cancer which in japan is\ronly one eighth of that in white women\rin north america or great britain.\r'),
 (452,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5318. the plasma 17-ketosteroids and\r17-hydrocorticosteroids in women\rwith breast cancer\rin 100 women in the menopause with breast cancer\rthe mean level of plasma 17-\rketosteroids (17-ks) and 17-hydroxycorticosteroids\r(17-ohcs) was significantly\rhigher than in normal women of equivalent age.\rin 67 young women only the\rlevel of the plasma 17-ohcs was significantly higher\rthan normal.  in menopausal\rwomen with breast cancer whether treated or not\rthere is no correlation between\rthe level of the plasma 17-ks and that of 17-ohcs.\r'),
 (453,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5319. urinary porter-silber chromogens\rfollowing intravenous metho-\rpyrapone and acth in patients with breast cancer\rurinary porter-silber chromogens have been\rmeasured in 2 groups of patients\rwith breast cancer before, during and after\rintravenous methopyrapone and\racth administration.  the control group\rconsisted of females free of disease\r5 years or more following mastectomy while\rthe study group had documented\rmetastatic disease.  no significant difference in\rthe urinary porter-silber chromo-\rgens was found between the 2 groups on any day\rduring the course of the study and\rwere within the range of normal as measured\rin this laboratory.  it is concluded\rthat the functional reserve capacity for both\rpituitary acth secretion and adreno-\rcortical steroidogenesis in patients with\radvanced metastatic breast cancer is rela-\rtively normal.\r'),
 (454,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2349. amyloidosis in the autopsy material of the pathology department of\rtuberculosis institute, warsaw, in 1945-1962\rthe autopsy material of the pathology\rdepartment of the tuberculosis institute, in\r1945-1962, included 1218 postmortem\rexaminations of patients who died from tuberculo-\rsis.  in 111 cases tuberculosis was\rcomplicated by amyloidosis.  in 1945-1957 amy-\rloidosis accounted for 8.7% of the cases;\rin 1958-1962 this percentage was 10.8.\rthere was no difference in the incidence\rbetween men and women, the only difference\rbetween the two sexes was that the peak\rtuberculosis fatality curve in men was in\rthe 40-60 years age group, and that of\ramyloidosis at the 20-30 age group, while in\rwomen the greatest number of death from\rtuberculosis was in the 20-30 age group,\rand from amyloidosis in the 30-40 age group.\r'),
 (455,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'766. certain features of the haemogram in patients with pulmonary tuberculosis\rcomplicated by amyloidosis (russian)\rregression of amyloidosis in the early stages\rseems possible and for this reason\rrussian clinicians are exploring the possibilities\rof finding means of early diagnosis\rof this complication.  the author studied 300\rcomplete clinical blood analyses made\rin 60 patients, viz. 30 with chronic fibrocavernous\rand cirrhotic forms of tb com-\rplicated by amyloidosis and 30 with the same forms\rof tb without amyloidosis.  from\rdetailed serial study of the haemogram in patients\rwith pulmonary tb it is possible\rto diagnose associated amyloidosis of the internal\rorgans in its initial stage.  the\rpresence of amyloidosis of the internal organs can\rbe inferred from the following\rchanges in the blood picture  (a) the appearance of\rnormochromic and hypochromic\ranaemia in patients with various forms of tb (with\rthe exception of tb of the kidneys,\rintestinal tract or larynx, and of caseous lymph\rnodes), (b) progressive increase\rin the leucocyte count with a neutrophil shift to\rthe left not corresponding with a\rphase of quiescence of the main disease, (c) consistently\rhigh esr in the absence\rof an active process, (d) thrombocytosis in the phase of\rsubsidence of a flare-up,\rand also changes in the thrombocytic formula tending\rtowards the appearance of de-\rgenerative forms and old and mature thrombocytes.\r'),
 (456,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1319. diffuse tracheo-bronchial amyloidosis  a rare variant of a protean disease\ra patient with diffuse tracheo-bronchial\ramyloidosis is described; brief clinical\rdetails supplement those published in a\rprevious report (prowse,1958) and are\rfollowed by an account of the necropsy\rfindings and the histological appearances\rat the site of amyloid deposition.  the\rliterature is reviewed and arguments are\radvanced in favour of a common aetiology\rfor amyloidosis in all its forms.  if this\racts through the immunity mechanism, it is\rsuggested that variations in the site,\rstrength, duration, and frequency of the\rantigen stimulus and the antibody response\rmay determine the nature and distribution\rof the amyloid deposits.\r'),
 (457,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2091. modern methods of treatment of visceral amyloidosis in patients with\rpulmonary tuberculosis (russian)\rthe immediate and long-term results of\rtreatment during 1945-1962 of 414 patients\rwith pulmonary tuberculosis complicated\rby amyloidosis were studied.  hormonal\r(corticosteroid) therapy is the pathogenetic\rtreatment for visceral amyloidosis and\ris indicated in the proteinuric and early\redema-hypotonic phase of amyloidosis when\rthe functional capacity of the kidneys and\rthe liver is still adequate.  in the azotemic\rphase of amyloidosis, hormonal (corticosteroid)\rtherapy is not indicated, since it\rleads to rapid deterioration in the patient\'s\rcondition.  since hypoxemia is one of the\rmain factors in the pathogenesis of amyloidosis,\roxygen therapy is rational patho-\rgenetic therapy for patients with pulmonary\rtuberculosis complicated by hypoxemia\rand with symptoms of the proteinuric or\redema-hypotonic phase of amyloidosis\r(without ascites), in the form of\rsubcutaneous introduction of oxygen or oxy-\rgeno-peritoneum.  in patients with\rpulmonary tuberculosis surgical interven-\rtion on account of the main process\ris indicated only in the early stages of amyloi-\rdosis when pronounced functional\rdisorders of the kidneys and liver are absent.  co-\rjoint therapy using protein vitamins\r(particularly ascorbic acid), hormonal (corticos-\rteroid) preparations, oxygen and\rdesensitizing agents and elimination of all foci of\rinfection is indicated in treatment\rof pulmonary tuberculosis with even the earliest\rsigns of amyloidosis.\r'),
 (458,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2317. the use of needle biopsy of the liver in the diagnosis of visceral\ramyloidosis in patients with pulmonary tuberculosis (russian)\rthe results of 86 puncture biopsies of the\rliver in 84 patients with pulmonary tuber-\rculosis (55 men and 31 women aged from\r18 to 73 yr.) for the purpose of diagnosing\ramyloidosis are reported.  puncture was\rperformed when amyloidosis was suspected\ron the basis of the case history (destructive\rprocess of more than 2-3 years\' duration),\rclinical signs in the form of enlargement of\rthe liver and spleen, edema, changes\rin the blood picture and blood protein formula,\rand changes in the urine (proteinuria,\rcylindruria, isohyposthenuria).  amyloidosis\rwas diagnosed or its presence surmised\rbefore puncture in 23 patients; the puncture\rbiopsy confirmed the diagnosis in 14\rand refuted it in 9 of them.  in 8 patients without\rclinical symptoms, amyloidosis\rwas diagnosed on the basis of the puncture biopsy\ralone.  in 9 cases with fatal out-\rcome, the post-mortem findings coincided with\rthe results of the bioptic puncture.\rof the 62 patients in whom amyloidosis was not\rdetected by biopsy, 31 had moderate\rdystrophic changes and 9 had marked dystrophic\rchanges while in 22 cases no patho-\rlogical changes were found; 6 of these patients\rlater developed amyloidosis.  these\rfindings supported the contention that liver\ramyloidosis is linked with dystrophic\rchanges in the epithelial cells.  marked\rdystrophic changes can precede amyloidosis\ror may occur simultaneously with it.  moderate\rdystrophic changes are quite common\rin patients with an exacerbating tuberculous\rprocess in the lungs.  the wide applica-\rtion of bioptic puncture of the liver in indicated\rcases can increase our knowledge\rof the morphological changes taking place in the\rliver in tb.\r'),
 (459,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2701. the role of certain additional factors in the development of amyloidosis,\rand its prophylaxis in patients with pulmonary tuberculosis (russian)\rin patients with chronic fibrocavernous\rtuberculosis of the lungs, any toxic-aller-\rgic side reactions to antibacterial therapy,\rchronic foci or infection and diseases\rwith an allergic component can contribute\rto the development of amyloidosis.  the\rearly detection and clearing of chronic\rfoci of infection and effective measures\ragainst even mildly pronounced toxic-allergic\rside reactions are of prime impor-\rtance in the prevention of amyloidosis.  the\runsystematic and prolonged administra-\rtion of antibacterial preparations, along with\rtheir toxic side effects, tends to in-\rcrease the incidence of amyloidosis in patients\rwith chronic fibrocavernous pulmon-\rary tb.  individual constitutional factors are\rof great importance in the development\rof side effects.  side reactions to chemopreparations,\rin cases of hypofunction of\rthe liver and kidneys and autonomic\rdysfunction promote the development of dys-\rtrophic processes, as is confirmed\rby the high frequency of toxic-allergic reac-\rtions in patients with fibrocavernous\rpulmonary tb who later develop amyloidosis.\rthe administration of desensitizing drugs\rto patients showing side reactions there-\rfore helps to prevent amyloidosis in cases\rof chronic fibrocavernous tb, and chemo-\rtherapy should be automatically combined\rwith the administration of desensitizing\rand stimulatory drugs in this class of case.\r'),
 (460,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1835. the decrease of the steroids in the urine in the course of lung tb.\r(the therapeutic value of their increase after calciferol)\rquantitative determination of the urinary\rsteroids in 38 patients with extensive ul-\rcero-caseous pulmonary tb confirmed\rthat the 17-ketosteroids are always decreased\rin these cases.  calciferol, in the form\rof one ampoule of vit.  d2 of 600,000 u.\revery 10 days, in combination with active\rtuberculostatic drugs, in the majority of\rthe cases leads to an increase of the\rurinary 17-ketosteroids from 50 to 100% in 2\rmth.  it appears that the calciferol\rexerts its action through proteolysis; it stimulates\rthe liquefaction and evacuation of the\rcaseous material.  this proteolytic effect is\rrelated to that of the mineralocorticoids,\rwhich are phlogistic and proteolytic sub-\rstances.  calciferol offers the advantage\rover these substances that it does not affect\rthe electrolytes and is well tolerated by\rthe organism.  for this reason, good results\rmay be expected from its administration\rin cases of extensive pulmonary tb, in\rwhich the myc. tuberculosis has remained\rsensitive to the administered tuberculostic\rdrugs but nevertheless does not proceed\rtowards recovery because of the marked caseous\rlesions.  in such cases calciferol treatment\rleads to a rapid and pronounced decrease\rof the radiological shadows, improves the\rgeneral condition and also modifies the\rsteroid metabolism rendered abnormal by the disease.\r'),
 (461,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1837. development of amylosis in less than 2 months in the course of a primary\rtb infection\rthe case is reported of a previously healthy\ryoung north-african male, in whom\ra post-primary ulcero-infiltrative tb in less\rthan 2 mth. led to the development of\rvisceral amyloidosis, which could be confirmed\rby biopsies of the kidney and liver.\rduring treatment with antibiotics,\rthe hepatic amyloidosis regressed parallel with\rthe improvement of the tb, and the\rbiological signs of the renal amyloidosis dis-\rappeared with the exception of a\rpronounced proteinuria, the persistence of which\rrenders the long-term prognosis highly doubtful.\r'),
 (462,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2216. the relations between lupus erythematosus and diseases of the\rlympho-reticular system\ra case report of a patient with led\r(aged 48 years), who developed secondarily\ra lymphoblastic sarcoma.  when the\rsarcomatous degeneration of the lympho-\rreticular system became apparent,\rthe serological and immuno-hematological tests,\rtypical for led, were negative.  to\rinterpret the observation, 62 further patients\rwith lymphogranuloma, lymphosarcoma,\rleukemias, other malignant tumors, sar-\rcoidosis, and tuberculosis were investigated\rserologically and immunohematolo-\rgically.  antinuclear factors were found in\rserum of 4 patients with lymphogranulo-\rma, one patient with anaplastic carcinoma,\rand one patient with metastasizing\rmixed parotid-tumor.  the identity of the\rantinuclear antibodies with those found in\rled could not be proved by different methods.\rthe importance of certain diseases\rof the lympho-reticular system for the production\rof antinuclear factors was dis-\rcussed.\r'),
 (463,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4417. value and significance of the prednisolone test in diseases of the kidney\rtwelve normal subjects, 18 cases of\rtubulo-interstitial nephropathy, 12 cases of\rglomerular nephropathy and 17 cases\rof other renal disorders were investigated.\rall patients were given a prednisolone\rtest, with urine culture before and after the\rtest, and in many instances determination\rof the urinary osmolarity; the urinary\rsediment was examined with the sternheimer\rand malbin staining technique and\rwith the peroxydase stain to investigate the\rurinary cytology.  with the criteria\radopted, the test was negative in the normals\rand was positive in 61.1% of the cases\rof chronic pyelonephritis and in 12.1% of the\rremaining cases of unequivocally non-\rinfectious renal disease.  the increase of the\rurinary bacterial count after cortico-\rsteroid administration, and investigation of the\rvarious components of the urinary\rsediment also supplied useful diagnostic\rinformation.  on the contrary, the stern-\rheimer-malbin stain for the urinary\rsediment proved of little use.\r'),
 (464,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'564. tumoral amyloidosis of the lung\ran incidental finding at necropsy on a woman\raged 95 was a tumor-like mass, 8.5\rx 6.5 x 6 cm., in the lower lobe of the left lung.\rthe detailed structure of this\rmay suggested angioma of hamartoma; the stroma\rand some vessels contained\ramyloid.  amyloid is not uncommon in the stroma\rof tumors.  a summary of 17\rtumoral amyloid cases reported by others is included.\r'),
 (465,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7364. experimental amyloidosis in immunity\rmuch of interest in the mechanism of\rexperimental amyloidosis as a result of the\rparenteral introduction of foreign protein\rhas been centered around the nature of\rthe links leading to cytological and biochemical\rchanges in tissues and body fluids.\rsome of the authors suggested that such links\rmay be of immunological nature.\rthere is however, no clear-cut proof either\rin favor of or against the theory of an\rimmunological origin of amyloid.  since\rinjection of proteins during the perinatal\rperiod prevents an immune response when\rthe animal is subsequently challenged\rwith the same antigen, the authors studied\ramyloidosis caused by casein in mice\rtreated after birth with this protein.  mice\rexposed soon after birth to casein ac-\rquire an immune tolerance to this antigen.\rthis was demonstrated by the absence\rof circulating antibodies as measured by the\rdisappearance of i-labeled casein\rfrom the circulation and by means of passive\rhemagglutination tests with ascitic\rfluids.  both tolerant and control animals\rdeveloped amyloidosis to the same extent.\rthe results imply that the pathogenesis of\ramyloidosis does not rest upon a classic\rimmunological basis; they do not exclude\rthe possibility, that the disease may be\rdue to some auto-immune process.\r'),
 (466,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3535. electron microscopic study of six cases of human renal amyloidosis\rthis study is particularly concerned\rwith  (a) the basal membrane in the different\rstages; and (b) the intercapillary spaces\rin the early stages.  the conclusions may\rbe put as follows  (1) the amyloid substance\rseems to have a fibrillar structure\rfrom the start.  (2) when the walls of the\rperipheral capillary loops are thickened\rby voluminous amyloid deposits, the\rhyaline aspect of the primitive basal membrane\rpersists, but its structure is altered by\rthe presence of multiple amyloid fibrils.\r(3) on the other hand, in the initial stages,\ramyloid fibrils cannot be seen in the\r\'lamina densa\' of the basal membrane; they\ronly appear on the epithelial and endo-\rthelial surfaces of the membrane.  this suggests\rthat amyloidosis represents an\rabnormal precipitate of extrinsic origin, rather\rthan a transformation \'in situ\'\rof the basal membrane.  (4) in the very early stages\rof amyloid infiltration into the\rglomeruli the fibrillar substance is found first in\rthe intercapillary spaces, only\rlater does it reach the peripheral capillary walls.\r'),
 (467,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3544. morphology and development of infectious-toxic affections of the kidneys\rin pulmonary tuberculosis (russian)\rthe kidneys of 75 patients dead from tb of\rthe lungs and of 30 rabbits with pulmonary\rtb were examined.  the first lesions develop\rin the glomeruli, followed by changes\rin the stroma and tubules.  infectious-toxic\raffection of the kidneys is a complex and\rprolonged process involving organic immune\rreactions, lymphostasis, venous stasis\rand finally nephrosclerosis.  infectious-toxic\rlesions were found in one third of the patients\rwho died of pulmonary tb.  these changes had\rproduced clinical manifestations, on the\rbasis of which the following affections had been\rdiagnosed  nephritis, nephrosis, amyloi-\rdosis.  antibacterial therapy of the pulmonary\rprocess reduced the renal lesions.  how-\rever, severe infectious-toxic affection of the kidneys\rmay develop after recovery from\rpulmonary tb.\r'),
 (468,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3553. diffuse nodular amyloidosis of the lungs\rin a 59-year-old man, who 12 yr. previously\rhad ceased working in an aluminium\rfactory and who had died from respiratory\rinsufficiency, the postmortem examination\rrevealed disseminated nodules in the lungs.\rthe nodules were sharply defined, of\ra greyish color and of a doughy consistency\rand could easily be removed from their\rcapsules.  the diagnosis of amyloidosis was\rmade on the basis of the histological\rfindings, the staining qualities of the material,\rits intraseptal and periarteriolar\rlocalization, and the existence of plasmocytic\rinfiltrates and foreign-body giant-cell\rgranulomas.  amyloid deposits were also found\rin the spleen, kidney and some\rcoronary branches.  in regard to the pathogenesis,\rit is suggested that the exposure\rto aluminium products for more than 10 yr. might\rhave constituted a predisposing\rfactor.\r'),
 (469,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3724. the bacterial induction of homograft sensitivity. ii. effects of\rsensitization with staphylococci and other microorganisms\rheat-killed strains of staph. aureus and staph.\ralbus can induce in guinea pigs a\rstate of altered reactivity to skin homografts\rwhich is indistinguishable from that\rwhich results from sensitization with homologous\rtissues or group a streptococci.\rchallenge of suitably prepared recipients\rwith 1st-set skin homografts obtained\rfrom unrelated randomly selected donors\relicits white graft reactions or accelera-\rted rejections of such grafts.  other bacteria\rtested included lancefield streptococcal\rgroups b, c, d, e, g, h, l, and o,\rpneumococcus types ii, iii, xiv and a rough\rstrain, c. xerosis, b. subtilis, e. coli,\ra. aerogenes, s. typhimurium, pr. vul-\rgaris, n. catarrhalis, h. influenzae, and\r2 human virulent strains of myc. tuber-\rculosis.  none of these microorganisms was\ractive in the induction of homograft\rsensitivity in the guinea pig.  pretreatment of\rrecipients with gram-negative bac-\rterial suspensions was associated with a slight\rincrease in the mean survival time\rof 1st-set skin homografts.  results of this study\rsuggest the presence in staphylo-\rcocci, as well as in group a streptococci, of antigens\rrelated in their biologic ef-\rfects to tissue transplantation antigens.\r'),
 (470,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'6590. structure and function of cross-linked dna. i. reversible denaturation and\rbacillus subtilis transformation\rreaction of nitrous acid with dna\rresults in covalent linkage of complementary\rpolynucleotide strands.  the resulting\rmaterial denatures reversibly and retains\rbiological activity in bacterial transformation.\r'),
 (471,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4958. the mechanism of messenger-rna replication in bacteria\rthe transformation of bacillus subtilis\rsb25 his-tryp-by two linked genetic mar-\rkers under the action of hybrid molecules\rof dna was investigated.  the molecular\rhybrids were obtained by thermal denaturation\rand annealing of a mixture of two\rdna\'s, each one extracted from a single\rauxotrophic strain (h25 his-and 168 tryp-).\rthe formation of the heterozygous dna\rdouble helices was proved by special experi-\rments.  the transformation procedure\rexcluded dna synthesis by recipient cells\rprior to the formation of enzymes for\rhistidine and tryptophane synthesis.  it was\rfound that heterozygous molecules of\rdna are able to transform in these conditions\rthe double auxotrophic cells to prototrophic\rones.  this means that both strands of\rthe dna double helix can serve as templates\rfor the m-rna synthesis.  the possi-\rbility of a secondary replication of m-rna\routside the chromosome under the action\rof rna-polymerases, using rna as a primer,\ris discussed.\r'),
 (472,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2567. the molecular basis of histidase induction in bacillus subtilis\rbacillus subtilis growing at 37  on\rglutamate, as only carbon source, is induced\rto form histidase by l-histidine.  this\renzyme, converting histidine to urocanic\racid, was isolated in a purified form.\ra highly sensitive and convenient assay for\rthe induced enzyme is described and\rapplied to show that histidase appears in the\rcell 5 min. after addition of the inducer.\rhistidase-synthesizing capacity appears\rafter 2 min. and decays exponentially after\raddition of actinomycin (an inhibitor\rof dna-dependent rna synthesis).  the\rhalf-time value of histidase-synthesizing\rcapacity of 2.4 is high, compared with the\rhalf-time value of messenger rna.\rthe histidase formation after addition of\ractinomycin was not only due to protein\rsynthesis directed by accumulated m-rna\rbut also by conversion of an enzymatical-\rly inactive protein, present on the moment\rof actinomycin addition and product of\rthe specific m-rna, to the active enzyme.\rthe existence of this enzyme pre-\rcursor was shown by means of experiments\rperformed in the presence of chlor-\ramphenicof.  finally, numerical values for\rthe steady state of histidase synthesis,\rreached 9 min. after addition of the inducer,\rare calculated, on the basis of ki-\rnetics of histidase synthetic capacity, precursor\rand enzyme formation  the cell\rcontains sufficient precursor to form\rapproximately 100 molecules of histidase.\rthe cell produces approximately 50\rmolecules histidase per min.  the cell ac-\rquires and loses, every minute, the\rcapacity to make 15 molecules of histidase\rper minute.  the maximal enzyme\rlevel is 15,000 molecules per cell.\r'),
 (473,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2542. symposium on the fine structure and replication of bacteria and their\rparts. ii. bacterial cytoplasm\rcomparison of the fine structure of the\rcytoplasm of the bacterial cell with that of\rthe \'cell in general\' reveals important\rdifferences leading to the conclusion that, in\rthe bacterial cytoplasm, there is little\rdifferentiation into separate functional en-\rtities.  there is no nuclear membrane, and\rfine fibrils appear to extend from the nucleo-\rplasm into the cytoplasm where they may\rexpand in all directions.  the cytoplasm is not\rnecessarily intersected by membranous\rprofiles of special configuration, as is borne\rout by e. coli b and other gram-negative\rorganisms.  when membranous profiles\rof special configuration are present, as\rin the gram-positive b. subtilis, these\rdo not appear differentiated into clearly\rdefinable endoplasmic reticulum, golgi\rsubstance, microbodies, etc., and mitochondria.\ras for kinetosomes, the presence\rof centrioles is perhaps not very likely.  the\rexperiments in which tellurite is re-\rduced in the cells suggest that there are\rstructures at the base of the flagella with\rreductive capacity.  however, upon application\rof the tetranitro-blue tetrazolium\rtechnic to b. subtilis, these are not stained.\rthey are presumably identical with\rbasal granules.  the membranous structures\rin b. subtilis are called chondrioids\rby the author because probably one of their\rfunctions is that they are the sites of\rthe respiratory enzyme chain.  in the\rgram-negative p. vulgaris, the probable site\rof the respiratory chain has a structure\rvery different from that in the bacillus; it\ris not clear whether membranes are\rinvolved in their structure.  morphologically,\reven in b. subtilis chondrioids differ\rfundamentally from the mitochondria in that\rthey are not built up from composite\rmembranes, they are extensions of the plasma\rmembrane, and they may not be completely\rclosed systems.  regarding this last\rpoint, it was observed that chondrioids may\rpossibly stand in open connection with\rthe cell\'s environment, since its lumen is not\rseparated from the cell wall by a\rplasma membrane.  although as yet nothing is\rknown about this, it does not seem to\rbe precluded that these membranous organelles\rmay function also as intracellular\rtransport systems.  contrary to porter\'s ideas\rabout er, the chondrioids are not\rextensions of a nuclear envelope, but of the\rplasma membrane.  on the other hand,\rthey are in the nuclear area, in direct contact\rwith the nucleoplasm, and therefore,\rperhaps, they need not carry in their interior\rsome dna, as is now becoming known\rfor ordinary mitochondria.  the chromatophore\rvesicle is of a simple structure and\rin connection with the plasma membrane.  it is\rcovered by a single membrane and\rthus resembles the granum disc, but it is much\rsmaller.  in tissue cells, an im-\rportant function of the er is the support of protein\rsynthesis by ribosomes bound\rto their surfaces.  evidence is now accumulating\rthat the active complexes for poly-\rpeptide synthesis in bacteria are also membrane-bound\rand are series of 70s ribo-\rsomes using the same messenger rna molecule.\rit remains a contradictory situ-\ration that the particles obtained here through release\rof cytoplasm from protoplasts\rin diluted, rather crude fixing media, and identified\ras ribosomes, could not be\rrecognized as such in thin sections of the ryter-kellenberger\rfixed protoplasts.\rthis point is much in need of clarification.  but\reven if the cytoplasm in the thin\rsections of the protoplasts is in a state of\rdispersion brought about artificially, it\ris still apparent from the various micrographs\rthat basically the cytoplasm is a\rnetwork of presumably linear arrays, with many\rinterconnections due to fibrillar\rsystems.  fibrils from the nucleoplasm penetrate\rdeeply into the cytoplasm.  the\rpresence of fine fibrils of various thicknesses,\relectron densities, and orientations\rmakes high-resolution study of the cytoplasmic\rdetails an intriguing prospect from\rwhich much fundamental information can be\rgained.  the organizational pattern on\rthe ultrastructural level in bacteria reveals\rfundamental similarities and divergen-\rcies from that in the \'cell in general\'.\r'),
 (474,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'906. molecular mechanism of genetic recombination in bacterial transformation\rthe mechanism of dna incorporation into\rthe recipient cell chromosome was in-\rvestigated in a b. subtilis transformation\rsystem.  the recipient cells were auxo-\rtrophic for 2 linked markers.  hybrid dna\rused for transformation was heterozy-\rgous for one of these markers.  no differences\rin transformation activity were found\rwhen the effect of native and hybrid dna was\rcompared.  according to the authors\rthis observation is easily explained if we accept\rthat each of both complementary\rstrands of the donor dna can be incorporated\rinto the recipient chromosome with\requal probability.  the results on the segregation\rof genetic characters in the pro-\rgeny of transformed cells are also consistent\rwith the model of independent incorpo-\rration of both dna strands.  some calculations\rwere done on the probability of the\rintegration of a single dna strand carrying a\rparticular genetic marker, and on the\rprobability of recombination leading to double transformants.\r'),
 (475,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1520. multiplication of bacteriophages\rthe reproduction of bacteriophages requires\rthe participation of bacterial metabol-\rism.  synthesis of the viral protein components\ris accomplished by the same me-\rchanism as ordinarily produces bacterial\rproteins; however, for the synthesis of\rnucleic acids (dna or rna) enzymes may\rbe required which are not present in non-\rinfected bacteria; their formation is then\rinduced by the virus itself.  the fundamental\rbiological processes of replication, transcription\rand translation are discussed in\rthis context.\r'),
 (476,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1361. the mechanism of histidase induction and formation in bacillus subtilis\rthe role of the inducer, l-histidine, in the\rsynthesis of histidase (l-histidine am-\rmonia lyase) in b. subtilis was investigated.\rit was found that induced cells poisoned\rwith actinomycin, an inhibitor of rna synthesis,\rlose their capacity for the forma-\rtion of a protein precursor of histidase at a rate\rwhich is independent of the presence\ror absence of the inducer.  these results show\rthat the inducer does not increase\rthe intracellular level of histidase-specific\rmessenger rna by preventing the des-\rtruction of the major portion of this material,\rthe fraction that is engaged in pro-\rtein synthesis.  the possibility has not been\rexcluded that the inducer exerts its\reffect by bringing about the stabilization of\rthe messenger rna that is still attached\rto dna or has not yet become attached to\rribosomes.  alternatively, the inducer may\ractually stimulate the synthesis of\rhistidase-specific messenger rna.  the conver-\rsion of the precursor to active enzyme\rappears to involve polymerization of mono-\rmers, rather than the release of\rribosome-bound inactive enzyme.\r'),
 (477,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1362. the synthesis of phage and host dna in the establishment of lysogeny\ra method of extraction is described which\rprevents excessive fragmentation of bac-\rterial dna.  the larger bacterial dna can\rthen be separated from the phage dna\ron sucrose gradients.  the relative amounts\rof phage and host dna made at various\rtimes during infection of s. typhimurium\rwith phage p22 leading to lysogeny have\rbeen determined.  phage-specific dna\rsynthesis begins at about 4 min, continues\rto increase for 2-4 min, and then decreases\runtil complete repression is attained\rat 16 min.  autonomous phage dna synthesis\rremains repressed from then on.  bac-\rteria-specific synthesis proceeds at a\rdecreasing rate until about 16 min, when\ralmost complete inhibition is reached.\rwhen dna synthesis recovers in the in-\rfected cells, only host-specific material\ris made.  a new species of dna, which is\rmade only when phage dna is synthesized,\rhas been detected.  the possible implica-\rtions of these findings in the understanding\rof the lysogenic interaction is discussed.\r'),
 (478,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'438. lag period characterizing the entry of transforming deoxyribonucleic acid\rinto bacillus subtilis\rthe kinetics of appearance of transformants\ras a function of time of exposure to\rdna has been studied.  a short lag period\rof approximately 1 min at 37 c is evi-\rdent when the transformation is terminated\rwith deoxyribonuclease.  the length of\rthis lag is independent of the genetic trait\rtransferred.  moreover, the lag is unaf-\rfected by transforming dna concentration,\rby the presence of homologous unmarked\rdna, and by shearing and cross-linking of\rthe transforming dna.  the lag shows\ra strong inverse temperature dependence.\rthe energy of activation is 13.9 kcal.\rthe lag is abolished when the transformation\ris terminated by washing instead of\rby addition of deoxyribonuclease.  these results\rare taken to indicate an immediate\radsorption of dna to cells, followed by a\rdeoxyribonuclease-sensitive period of\r1 min, during which time the genetic trait\ris entering the cell.  these results make\rfeasible an investigation of the configuration\rassumed by the dna molecule during\rentry into the cell.\r'),
 (479,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'439. configuration of transforming deoxyribonucleic acid during entry into\rbacillus subtilis\ra correlation was obtained between map\rdistance and the length of the lag period\rpreceding the appearance of pairs of genetic\rtraits after the addition of dna to a\rcompetent culture of b. subtilis.  the results\rare taken to indicate that dna enters\rcompetent cells in lengthwise fashion.\rthe smallest length of transforming dna\rwhich can participate in a recombination\revent, and the number of nucleotide pairs\rwhich enter the cell per unit time, have\rbeen estimated.  the evidence indicates\rthat only part of the lag period is devoted\rto the transport of dna into the cell.\rthe significance of these results with\rrespect to the mechanism of entry of dna\rinto the cell is discussed.\r'),
 (480,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2564. chemical inactivation and reactivation of transforming dna (russian)\rthe kinetics of the inactivation of linked\rand unlinked genetic markers by means\rof hno2 or uv light was studied.  closely\rlinked markers are inactivated simul-\rtaneously, unlinked markers are inactivated\rindependently.  it seems that the\rchemical attack on dna impairs a large part\rof macromolecule, including many\rcistrons.  it was shown by genetic experiments\rthat chemical inactivation prac-\rtically does not influence the process of dna\rinclusion into competent cells.  by\rmeans of viscosity measurements it was\rshown that the molecular weight and\rmacromolecular properties of dna do not\rsignificantly change during chemical\rinactivation by means of hno2.  two explanations\rfor the inactivation of trans-\rforming activity of dna are discussed  (1) structural\rdeteriorations, preventing\rintegration of dna molecule into the genome of\rrecipient cell, or (2) deletion of\ra chain unit out of dna chain resulting in wrong\rreading of code triplets.  it was\rpreviously described in the literature that extensive\rinactivation leads to a state\rof dna, apparently more resistant than the initial one.\rinactivation does not con-\rfirm to exponential kinetics.  the authors discuss the\rcoding mistake hypothesis\ras an explanation for this remarkable fact.  extensive\rhno2 or uv light action re-\rsults in multiple lesions in the dna molecule and\rleads to reactivation because\rthe deletions restore correct reading of the code\rin a large part of dna molecule.\ron the basis of this explanation reactivation of\rchemically injured dna by means\rof fusion and annealing with homologous but\rgenetically inactive dna, or by slight\rfragmentation of dna by means of ultrasonic\rvibrations may be expected.  attempts\rto achieve reactivation by both methods gave\rpositive results.\r'),
 (481,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2565. separation of the transforming and viral deoxyribonucleic acids of a\rtransducing bacteriophage of bacillus subtilis\rthe authors used the transducing b. subtilis\rphage ps 10 and present the fol-\rlowing experimental data  dna isolated from\rps 10 is effective for transformation\rof competent b. subtilis cells.  ps 10 dna is\rdistinguishable from b. subtilis dna\rby its higher density in a cs2so4 gradient and\rits lower thermal denaturation\rtemperature.  the transforming activity present\rin dna from ps 10 denatures at\ra temperature characteristic of b. subtilis dna\rrather than of viral dna.  the\rtransforming activity of ps 10 dna bands in a\rcs2so4 gradient with bacterial dna.\rthis data indicated that bacterial dna is\rincorporated into phage ps 10 without\rbeing integrated in the viral dna.  this incorporated\rbacterial dna is involved\rin transduction.\r'),
 (482,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2529. repair of damage induced by a monofunctional alkylating agent in a\rtransformable, ultraviolet-sensitive strain of bacillus subtilis\ra uv sensitive, transformable strain of\rb. subtilis (uvr-) was unable to carry out\rhost cell reactivation of the virulent\rbacteriophage spo1.  the ratio of the slopes\r(kuvr-/kuvr+) of the uv inactivation curves\rwas 6-8 for cells or for whole phage, and 2\rfor indole+ transforming dna or for\rspo1 phage dna measured in a transforming\rsystem.  whole phage inactivated with\rnitrogen mustard showed greater survival on\ruvr+ cells than on uvr-; there was no such\rdifference for whole phage inactivated with\rmethyl methanesulfonate.  whole uvr+ cells\rrecovered from uv induced damage, as\rdetermined by an increase in extractable\rtransforming activity during a period of\rincubation in which net dna synthesis did\rnot occur.  uvr- cells were unable to reco-\rver from uv induced damage but they did\rrecover from methyl methanesulfonate\rinduced damage in similar experiments.\rdensity labeled (h2n15) methyl methanesul-\rfonate treated uvr+ cells incubated in (h1n14)\rmedium containing (h3) thymidine show-\red a 3-fold increase in extractable transforming\ractivity, with no formation of new\rdna molecules as determined by pyknometric\ranalysis.  the repair of damage in-\rduced by uv irradiation differs by at least one\rstep from the repair of damage in-\rduced by methyl methanesulfonate.\r'),
 (483,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1451. the biosynthesis of 5-hydroxymethyldeoxyuridylic acid in\rbacteriophage-infected bacillus subtilis\rwhen phage  e, which contains\r5-hydroxymethyluracil in its dna in place of thymine,\rinfects b. subtilis, enzyme changes\roccur in the host organism which can account\rfor the synthesis of the abnormal base.\rdeoxycytidylate deaminase increases at\rleast 90-fold and the product of its action,\rdeoxyuridylic acid, is converted directly\rinto the deoxynucleotide of 5-hydroxymethyluracil\rby a hydroxymethylase enzyme.\rthe activity of thymidylate synthetase, which also\ruses deoxyuridylic acid as\rsubstrate, decreases rapidly after phage infection.\r'),
 (484,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5574. death anxiety in children with a fatal illness\rthe author reports studies of a series\rof 50 children hospitalized because of fatal\rillness due to leukemia or some other\rform of cancer.  it was postulated that the\ryounger children would experience\rseparation anxiety while the older children\rwould be more likely to experience\rdeath anxiety.  in general the hypothesis\rwas supported by the results of the study.\rthere was some evidence to indicate that\rthe younger children perceive death\ranxiety but deal with it in more symbolic form.\rin older children, it was felt that boys\rtended to react to death anxiety by acting out\rbehavior while girls tended to become depressed.\r'),
 (485,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1209. the theory and practice of the family diagnostic.  ii. theoretical\raspects and resident education\rfamily intervention and observation have proved\ruseful in 3 areas.  the 1st of these is observation of the\rpsychosocial context in the patient.  on admission to a\rmental hospital the phenomenon of extrusion and separ-\ration from the family is evident, and the need for study\rof the interaction between the patient and his family\rmilieu is vital.  the 2nd area where the family inter-\rview has a major role is resident education.  the tra-\rditional medical education of the ill prepares the stu-\rdent for consideration of the multifactorial problems of\remotional disorder in which balances between mem-\rbers of a group may be the issue rather than external\rpathogenes.  the family interview offers a unique point\rof observation of factually evident and emotionally con-\rvincing group data.  in addition to the observation of\rfamily phenomena, mutual understanding of others\'\rproblems is created.  finally, the family interview\rserves as an instrument for data collection and hypo-\rthesis seeking in relating individual psychopathology\rto family adaptations.  the patient and his family at\rthe time of admission are dealing with a crisis.  some-\rtimes this is traumatic, such as the unexpected loss\rof a young marital partner, an unexpected illness, or\ra financial reverse.  more commonly, however, it is\rdevelopmental being a natural part of the life cycle.\rcharacteristically, the developmental task involved\rin dealing with the crises has been postponed so that\rone does not see the family at the age specific and ap-\rpropriate time for this task.  the crisis emerges dis-\rruptively because of inevitable biological maturation,\rpersonal decision, or social expectation.  a primary\rconcern of the leader is to determine what life task is\rbeing faced.  families have a mentally ill member not\rmerely because they are dealing with the vicissitudes\rof life.  they are unable to cope with the crisis, be-\rcause of the feelings which are aroused.  each life cri-\rsis leads to a particular constellation of effects in any\rgiven family.  these include primarily, sadness, anger,\rand guilt, but there may well be specific affective con-\rstellations appropriate to different developmental tasks.\rthe patient\'s inability to cope with a life crisis is due\rto his particular adaptation of a style of dealing with\rfeelings that is employed by other members of the family.\r'),
 (486,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'265. studies in personality.  ii. a bio-psychological and experimental\rapproach to problems of human adaptation in modern society\rexperimentally determined fixation-ambivalence\rmeasures are related to some anxiety estimates obtain-\red from a projective test in a group of male adolescents.\rit is shown that (1) fixation increases with increase in\rcorporal injury anxiety when ambivalence is kept con-\rstant, (2) ambivalence increases with increase in separa-\rtion anxiety when fixation is kept constant, (3) extremely\rhetero-fixated subjects show presence of intense guilt\rand absence of aggression towards the mother; one ef-\rfect of this system of organizers seems to be\rsuicidal\rtendencies, (4) extremely ambivalent subjects have in-\rtense separation anxiety; one effect seems to be suicidal\rtendencies combined with high ambition and impaired\rcognitive capacity.\r'),
 (487,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2837. early indicators of outcome in schizophrenia\rthe case material of 50 persons who\rwere seen at a child guidance center in child-\rhood or adolescence and were later\rhospitalized with schizophrenia were examined\rintensively.  the study concentrated\respecially on the differences associated with\rchronicity vs. hospital release.  the\rfollowing 12 factors were significantly related\rto chronicity  (1) psychotic or schizoid\rpathology in the mothering person, (2) no se-\rparation of any kind from the pathogenic\rfamilies, (3) pre-illness history of poor so-\rcial and sexual adjustment, (4) failure\rto continue in treatment (during childhood)\rfor at least 3 mth., (5) less acting out\rin the community, (6) neither disorientation\rnor confusion on admission, (7) no\rsymptoms of depressive psychosis, (8) premor-\rbid schizoid personality, (9) no clear\rprecipitating events, (10) no concern with dying\rduring the acute phase of the illness,\r(11) length of onset over 6 mth., and (12) schi-\rzophrenic reaction in patients\' heredity.\ritems 1, 2, and 5 were derived from early\rlife history data and are thought to be\rnew to the literature of prognosis in schizo-\rphrenia.  the remaining 8 factors can be\rscored from hospital data alone, and have\rbeen cited in previous prognostic studies.\r'),
 (488,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4854. on the formation of object-relations and identifications of the\rkibbutz child\rsome of the issues relevant to the early\rstages of object relation formation and\ridentification of kibbutz children are\rdiscussed.  for this purpose the child rearing\rmilieu of the kibbutz child is described\rand some clinical illustrations are given.\rthe relationship to the mother is seen\ras the main object-relation and those to the\reducators as transient-interchangeable\rneed-satisfying relationships.  on the basis\rof retrospective analytical material it\rappears that in the course of development\rthe two relations as well as the two\rrespective, originally distinct, object represen-\rtations are synthetised into one.  the\rconditions of communal education, character-\rised by double object-relation formation\rfrom birth on, are seen as factors that in-\rtensify the \'normative crisis of infancy\',\respecially the transition from the symbio-\rtic to the separation-individuation stage\rof object-relation development.\r'),
 (489,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4846. the meaning of crying\rthe multiple meanings of crying are\rreviewed and, in particular, stress is laid\ron tears as a response to some type of separation loss.\r'),
 (490,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2953. the death of a parent\rin the case of depressive illnesses the death\rof either parent prior to the child reach-\ring the age of 15 seemed to be correlated\ras a significant contributory factor.  with\rthis exception, statistical studies suggest\rthat it is the death of a mother in the first\r7 yr. of a child\'s life, as opposed to that\rof a father, that is potentially an etiologi-\rcal factor for the future development of\rpsychoses, delinquency and psychoneuroses.\rthe case histories of 6 boys who had lost\rtheir fathers were given.  in each instance\rthere was distinct evidence that the psychological\rsymptoms and behavioral disturb-\rances were to be attributed in large measure\rto the effect of the death upon the child,\rand that in some cases the symptom choice was\rto be correlated with specific cir-\rcumstances surrounding the death of the father.\rin some cases it was the unresolved\rgrief reaction in the mother which helped to\rperpetuate the disorder in the child.  re-\rsolution of this in the mother during therapy\rled to improvement in the child\'s func-\rtioning.  in other instances improvement\roccurred especially when the child ceased\rto be preoccupied with a close identification\rwith the dead father.  those boys who\rwere involved most closely in their mother\'s\rgrief reactions were the ones who were\rmost disturbed.  the brief treatment given\rthese boys and their mothers appeared\rto be responsible for the considerable\ramelioration of symptoms that resulted.  ther-\rapeutic intervention is worthwhile,\respecially in those instances where there is an\runresolved grief reaction in the mother.\r'),
 (491,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1848. the child\'s concept of death\rin this translation of a paper, which first\rappeared in 1912, it is shown, according\rto freud, how far a child\'s appreciation\rof being dead differs from its true signifi-\rcance.  death means a reversible decrease\rin life functions, that can be interrupted\rat any time, like sleep.  at other times it\rmay mean a temporary separation; but\ralways it is in man\'s power to change it.\rin this concept, the child\'s unconscious\rfinds license for his sadism.  cruelty to\ranimals and death wishes against persons\rclose to him appear, in overcompensation, as\rexaggerated pity for dead creatures\rand the belief in man\'s power over life and death.\r'),
 (492,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1849. mother child interaction during separation individuation\rafter a stage of normal autism during the\r1st weeks of extrauterine life, the infant\rpasses into a symbiotic phase, gradually\remerging from this stage of dual unity at\rthe end of the 5th mth and during the 6th mth.\rjust before this, the next phase\rseparation individuation begins.  four\rcharacteristic subphases of this separation\rindividuation process are described\rdifferentiation, the practicing period, association\rand a stage, characterized by unfolding\rof complex cognitive functions.  the relation\rof mother and child throughout these\rsubphases are studied and illustrated by clinical\rmaterial.  a poor relation between mother\rand child in 1 subphase does not necessarily\ror usually preclude impressive changes\rfor the better in the next subphase.\r'),
 (493,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2736. the emotional needs of children in hospital\rhospitalization of a child for physical\rreasons brings with it separation from pa-\rrents, siblings and familiar surroundings,\ras well as the probability of subjection\rto frightening and painful procedures.\runless steps are taken to prevent or modify\rthe resultant stress, behavioral\rdisturbances may arise and may result in per-\rmanent damage to the developing personality.\r'),
 (494,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2906. early childhood separations\revery child in this long-term study of child\rrearing showed significant reactions to\rordinary separations by about 1 yr. of age.\rthe similar pattern of response in this\rgroup of children suggests a biologically\rdetermined cause.  the clinging reaction\rappeared when the child became mobile and\rable to move away from his mother re-\rgardless of the frequency or duration of his\rseparations.  the majority of the mothers\rdid not understand this natural phenomenon\rand regarded the clinging and crying of\rthe 1-year-old as evidence of spoiled or\rregressed behavior.  the pediatrician can\rbe helpful to a mother by anticipating and\rexplaining separation responses, by indi-\rcating their universality, and by giving\rspecific recommendations for gradual changes\rto modify these reactions.\r'),
 (495,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'9787. changes in developmental quotient under two conditions of maternal\rseparation.\rdevelopmental scales were\radministered to 2 groups of infants during and sub-\rsequent to a temporary period of institutionalization.\ralthough both groups experienced maternal separa-\rtion, only 1 group was subjected to deprivation, in\rthat it received very much less stimulation than the\rother.  results from a longitudinal testing program\rshow that the scores of the deprived group during\rthe period of separation were significantly lower than\rthose of the nondeprived group, no progressive de-\rterioration of scores took place in the course of\rinstitutionalization, immediately following return\rhome, while the scores of the nondeprived group re-\rmained constant, those of the deprived infants jumped\rto the level of the other group.  3 theories regarding\rthe mechanism underlying the association between\rdeprivation and developmental retardation are exam-\rined and it is suggested that an explanation in moti-\rvational terms best fits the results obtained.\r'),
 (496,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1808. separation anxiety  a factor in the object relations of\rschizophrenic patients.\rthe thesis is advanced that\rspecial vulnerability to separation anxiety is a crucial\rfactor in the schizophrenic\'s difficulty in establishing\rand maintaining satisfactory interpersonal relationships.\r2 major reasons for this are lack of autonomy and lack\rof object constancy.  without a stable autonomous\rcapacity for self-regulation and adaptation, he is inordi-\rnately dependent upon others for help, protection, and\rdirection.  without object constancy, he is unable to\rmaintain a stable representation of the needed person in\rthe latter\'s absence.  evidence is presented from the\rintensive psychotherapy of schizophrenic patients.\rmany of the vicissitudes of the doctor-patient relation-\rship center about the patient\'s separation anxiety and\rhis attempted defenses against it.  these include clinging,\rperceptual and cognitive distortions designed to deny\rseparation, and recourse to substitute objects.  promi-\rnent in many of these efforts is the attempt to reverse\rpassive victimization into active mastery.  the practical\rimplications of this thesis for the treatment of schiz-\rophrenic patients are discussed.\r'),
 (497,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'9101. separation experiences and health records in a group of normal adults.\rabout 25% of 455 ostensibly normal ss\rreported a recent \"separation experience\" as defined\rin this study.  the frequency of visits to the dis-\rpensary for symptomatic complaints was not signifi-\rcantly higher among those who reported separation\rthan among those who did not.  the data suggest\rthat an apparent association between relatively high\rcornell medical index score and history of separation\rexperience may be understandable in terms of a cause-\reffect relationship between separation experience and illness.\r'),
 (498,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'11306. separation and attempted suicide.\rof 3 groups of psychiatric patients-at-\rtempted suicides, those with suicidal urges, and non-\rsuicides-there were significantly more attempted\rsuicides among patients with a history of childhood and\rantecedent separation than controls.  in childhood the\rsignificant difference was found primarily in the period\rfrom birth to 7 yr.  there was no significant interaction\rbetween childhood and antecendent separation and\rsuicide attempt or suicide urge.\r'),
 (499,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1463. investigations of lens protein and microelectrophoresis of\rhydrosoluble protein in senile cataract\rthe investigations on lens protein and\ron agar-microelectrophoresis of hydro-\rsoluble protein in normal lenses and in those affected with senile cataract re-\rvealed the following facts  (1) in opaque\rlenses, a diminution of the total protein\rand the soluble protein takes place, as\rwell as an increase in the amount of in-\rsoluble protein.  the decrease in the\rquantity of soluble protein is higher than the\rincrease of insoluble protein which does\rnot only point to a transformation of the\rsoluble protein into the insoluble variety,\rbut also to the disappearance of a protein\rfraction from the lens.  changes in the\rquantity of soluble protein are accompanied\rby the decrease of protein in slow fractions\rof the electropherogram and even by\rthe disappearance of these fractions and\rthe increase of the amount of protein in\rfractions of medium velocity.  with the\rdevelopment of cataract and the mature\rphase of cataract, all these processes\rbecome more and more distinct.  in this\rrespect, a strong parallelism exists between\rthe protein changes and the clinical\rpicture of senile cataract.  (2) qualitative\rand quantitative changes which occur in\rthe protein of normal lenses with advancing\rage show a character similar to those\rin senile cataract, however, they are less\rpronounced.  in this instance, the de-\rcrease in the quantity of soluble protein is\rlikewise closely associated with the\rdiminution of the protein content in the slow\rfractions of the electropherogram.\r(3) the changes in the soluble protein content\rof the lens and the alterations of\rthe protein amounts in the slow fractions which\ralways accompany the former,\rplay the principal role in the aging process\rof the lens and in the development of\rsenile cataract.  (4) the investigations\rseem to indicate that the aging processes,\rof lenses as well as the development of\rsenile cataract are of a similar character,\rbut of different intensity.  (5) undoubtedly,\rthe processes of transition from slow\rfractions of soluble protein into faster ones\rand the transformation of part of the\rsoluble protein into insoluble protein which is\rlikely to be associated with these\rprocesses as well as the partial disappearance\rof total protein from the lens seem\rto play a very important part in the mechanisms\rpertaining to the development\rof cataract.\r'),
 (500,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1949. studies on the soluble proteins of bovine lens.  immuno-\rchemical analyses of protein fractions\rthe lyophilized soluble lens proteins\rwere dissolved in 0.005 m phosphate buffer\rat ph 6.8 and the solution was subjected to\rcolumn chromatography on deae (die-\rthylamino ethyl) cellulose.  elution was\raccomplished by changing the ph and ionic\rstrength of the eluting buffer.  the components\rwere fractionated by stepwise elu-\rtion.  the lens proteins were separated into\r17 fractions by column chromatogra-\rphy.  these fractions were compared with\ra, b and y crystallines for electrophore-\rtic mobility, and the antigenic purity of each\rfraction was examined immunochemi-\rcally.  the results showed that while the\rfractions were not completely pure they\rwere purer than the a, b and y crystalline\rfractions, and that f-1-a, b, c and d\rcorresponded to y crystalline, while\rf-2-a, b, c, d, e and f corresponded to b\rcrystalline and f-3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 and\r9 to a crystalline.\r'),
 (501,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3107. studies on y-crystallin from calf lens.  ii.  purification and\rsome properties of the main protein components\rfour proteins belonging to the y-crystallin group\rwere purified by chromatography\ron sulphoethyl-sephadex and phosphate-cellulose\rcolumns.  the proteins were homo-\rgeneous in gel and immunoelectrophoresis\rexperiments and could be crystallized.\rtheir molecular weights, n-terminal amino\racid sequences and antigenic structures\rwere all similar, but their amino acid\rcompositions and the sulphydryl groups con-\rtained showed certain dissimilarities.  it\ris probable that the 4 proteins possess\rsmall differences in their primary structure,\rwhich are not associated with the\rantigenic sites and which may have arisen\rfrom mutations during evolution.\r'),
 (502,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3105. studies on the subunits of a-crystallin and their recombi-\rnation\rearlier investigations have shown that, in\rthe presence of high concentrations of\rurea, a-crystallin from bovine lens is split\rinto a number of subunits with apparent-\rly different electrophoretic mobilities but\rsimilar molecular weights.  the recom-\rbination of these subunits after removal of\rthe urea has been studied by ultracentri-\rfugation and immunoprecipitation techniques.\rit was found that maximal recombina-\rtion was obtained when the ionic strength\rduring the removal of the urea was high\r(>0.2), whereas at low ionic strengths a\rmolecule with only half the molecular weight\rof native a-crystallin and a much lower\rsedimentation coefficient was obtained.  a\rcomplete recovery of the structure of\rnative a-crystallin was never obtained, even\rat high ionic strengths, as was evident\rfrom electrophoretic and quantitative preci-\rpitin analyses.  the subunits were\rfractionated by chromatography on deae-cellu-\rlose in the presence of 7 m urea.\rthe purification was followed by polyacrylamide-\rgel electrophoresis.  after removal of\rthe urea at high ionic strength, 2 of the\rfractions obtained showed reactions of\ronly partial identity with native a-crystallin\rin immunodiffusion tests, but all other\rfractions showed complete identity.  the\rdifferences in the electrophoretic\rmobilities of the fractions in the presence of\rurea persisted after removal of the urea.\rall fractions had much higher sedimen-\rtation coefficients in the absence of urea\rthan in its presence, although the values\rfor urea-treated unfractionated a-crystallin\robtained after removal of the urea\rwere not reached even at high ionic strengths.\rthe amino acid composition of the\rfractions was found to differ.  these\robservations suggest that a-crystallin is com-\rposed of a number of chemically different,\rbut related, subunits of approximately\rthe same size, which are bound together\rby nonspecific, noncovalent bonds, pos-\rsibly hydrophobic bonds.  moreover,\rwhen isolated, these subunits have the ability\rto associate and form molecules of\rhigh molecular weight.\r'),
 (503,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3106. fractionation of b-crystallin from calf lens by gel fil-\rtration\rb-crystallin was isolated from calf lenses\rby a combination of gel filtration on\rsephadex g-75 and vertical-column zone\relectrophoresis.  it was subdivided into\r4 fractions by subsequent gel filtration on\rdextran gels with low cross-linkage.\reach fraction showed only 1 major peak in\rthe ultracentrifuge, the sedimentation\rcoefficients of which were 13.6, 9.6, 4.9 and\r4.2 s for fractions i-iv, respectively.\rhowever, all 4 fractions contained some\radditional minor components, as revealed\rby sedimentation and immunoelectrophoretic\ranalyses.  the fractionation procedure\rmay be of value as a first step in the isolation\rof individual proteins of the b-crystal-\rlin group.\r'),
 (504,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'195. properties of a cold-precipitable protein fraction in the\rlens\ra soluble protein fraction which precipitates\rin aqueous solutions at temperatures\rbelow 10  c has been isolated from the rat\rlens.  this fraction appears to be re-\rsponsible for the reversible \'cold cataract\'\rwhich has been seen to develop when\ryoung mammals are exposed to temperatures\rbelow 10  c.  as the rat ages, the\rconcentration of this protein fraction\rdecreases, but the fraction does not com-\rpletely disappear, even from the lenses\rof 3-year-old rats.  although the molecular\rspecies comprising this fraction appear to\rbe homogeneous in the ultracentrifuge,\rdisc electrophoresis and immunodiffusion\rhave shown that they are a heterogeneous\rmixture of a-, b- and y-crystallin subunits.\rthe ability of the cold-precipitable\rprotein (ccp) fraction to precipitate in the\rcold depends upon its concentration and\rthe ionic strength and ph of the solvent.  in\rsolutions of ph 4.0, some aggregation\rof the 4 s cpp occurs to form a 17 s component,\rwhich no longer precipitates in\rthe cold.  the ability of this protein fraction to\rprecipitate in the cold may depend\ron hydrophobic bonding and its influence on the\rconformation of the protein.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (505,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'773. the effect of radiation on lenticular epithelial enzymes\rin young rabbits\rthe mitochondrial fraction and the soluble\rfraction of the epithelial cells of the lens\rfrom 6-week-old new zealand white male\rrabbits, exposed to 800 r of whole-head\rx-irradiation, were evaluated for glucose\r6-phosphate dehydrogenase, isocitrate\rdehydrogenase, malate dehydrogenase,\rglutathione reductase, glyceraldehydephos-\rphate dehydrogenase, purine nucleoside\rphosphorylase, nadph2 diaphorase, and\rnadh2 cytochrome c reductase activities.\rincreased enzyme activities were noted\rin the irradiated lenticular tissues for\rpurine nucleoside phosphorylase, nadph2\rdiaphorase and nadh2 cytochrome c\rreductase.  decreased activities for glucose\r6-phosphate dehydrogenase, malate\rdehydrogenase, glutathione reductase and gly-\rceraldehydephosphate dehydrogenase\rwere observed in the lenticular tissues of ir-\rradiated animals.  the activity of isocitrate\rdehydrogenase was the same in the ir-\rradiated and in the control animals.\r'),
 (506,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'465. conversion of a-crystallin of bovine lens into insoluble\rprotein in vitro\ra-crystallin can be converted into an insoluble\rform by treatment with alloxan and\rto a very small extent with iodoacetate.\rother reagents such as hcl, naoh, reduced\rglutathione, hydrogen peroxide,\rmercaptoethanol, were not able to convert a-crys-\rtallin into an insoluble form.  the\ralloxan treated insoluble a-crystallin could be made\rsoluble by treatment with 7 m urea.\rthe product thus made soluble had the same\relectrophoretic mobility as a-crystallin,\rbut showed cross reaction with a-crystallin\rin ouchterlony plate and did not have\rproteolytic activity.  alloxan was effective in\rproducing cataract of rabbit lens when very\rsmall amounts were injected into the\raqueous.\r'),
 (507,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1972. structural studies of a-crystallin\ra-crystallin has been isolated from the cortex\rof ox lens by isoelectric precipitation\rfollowed by chromatography on deae-cellulose.\rthe amino acid composition is in\ragreement with that reported for a-crystallin\rprepared by a different method.  there\ris one thiol group/20,000g. of protein\r(20,000 is the order of magnitude of the sub-\runit molecular weight), and disulphide\rbonds are absent.  the thiol group has been\ralkylated with radioactive iodoacetate\rin the presence of urea.  partial acid hydroly-\rsis of the alkylated protein gives,\raccording to the conditions, mainly 3 radioactive\rpeptides or nearly exclusively one\rradioactive dipeptide.  the dipeptide is n-seryl-\r(s-carboxymethyl) cysteine, ser-cmcys.\rthe 2 other peptides are probably the tri-\rpeptides related to ser-cmcys.  the\rsimplest interpretation of these results is that\rthe sequence around the cysteine residue\ris a common structural feature of the sub-\runits of a-crystallin.\r'),
 (508,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1751. on the subunits of a-crystallin\ra-crystallin was isolated from total\rwater-soluble lens extract by preparative zone\relectrophoresis on starch or pevikon\rc870 blocks and purified by density gradient\rcentrifugation and sephadex chromatography.\rthese preparations were treated with\rurea or sodium dodecyl sulphate and\rsubmitted to electrophoresis on polyacrylamide\rgels containing either urea or sodium\rdodecyl sulphate.  whereas in 7 m urea a large\rnumber of zones was detected, only\rthree bands were observed in 1% sodium dodecyl\rsulphate.  on the other hand, the\rsedimentation coefficient had the same value in both\rmedia.  the authors re-investigated the\rn-terminal amino acid content in the starch block\rpreparations and compared the result\rwith that obtained from the preparations isolated\raccording to their new procedure.  the\rconcentration of dinitrophenyl-glutamic acid\rwas lower in the purified samples.\rurea-treated samples had the same concentration\rof n-terminal glutamic acid whereas\rthe concentration of the \'trace\' end-groups did\rnot change.  sedimentation-diffusion\requilibrium in the analytical ultracentrifuge\rrevealed a slight heterogeneity in the\rpurified samples.  electron micrographs of\relectrophoretic and of further purified\rsamples were very similar.  at neutral or\rslightly alkaline ph they showed almost\runiform spherical aggregates in which a\rsubstructure was observed.  at acid ph,\rcoiled filaments rather than small globules\rcould be demonstrated.\r'),
 (509,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1752. separation of the soluble proteins of bovine lenses on\rpolyacrylamide gels\rthe soluble proteins of bovine lenses were\rseparated by gel filtration on polyacryl-\ramide gels.  the presence of ethylenediaminetetra-\racetate in the buffer was found\rto be essential for achieving a good separation\rof the lens homogenate into four\rfractions - a, b, c and d.  ultracentrifugal,\relectrophoretic and immunochemical\ranalyses were used to compare these fractions\rwith the soluble crystallin fractions\rof the lens.  fraction a was compared\rwith a-crystallin, fractions b and c with\rb-crystallin and fraction d with y-crystallin.\rthe distribution of these four protein\rfractions in the nuclear and cortical parts\rof calf and cow lenses was determined.\rthe oxidation-sensitive protein fraction of\rthe calf lenses was separated from\rfraction b on an se-sephadex column.\r'),
 (510,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1745. the deaggregation of bovine lens a-crystallin\rsedimentation equilibrium studies of lens\ra-crystallin at neutral ph indicate that\rthis material is composed of a number\rof different sized species.  a study of the\reffect of alkali upon a-crystallin indicates\ra progressive deaggregation of the ma-\rterial with increasing ph.  sedimentation\requilibrium studies were performed at ph\r12.8 as well as in guanidine hydrochloride,\r7 m urea, and with succinylated material.\runder all of these conditions a molecular\rheterogeneity was observed.  the data\rindicate that independent species coexisted\runder most dissociating conditions.  the\rweight average molecular weights of the\rsuccinylated, and of the alkali-, urea-,\rand guanidine hydrochloride-treated\rmaterial were found to have an integral relation-\rship of 8 4 2 1, respectively.  since a\rconstant ratio of m2 mw was found, it was\rconcluded that the same spread of\rdistribution of molecular species occurred for\reach of the deaggregating conditions.\rthe results in guanidine hydrochloride could\rnot be evaluated in this manner because\rof a small concentration dependence.  these\rconclusions imply that not only the\rweight average molecular weight in 7 m urea\rbut the actual molecular weight of\reach individual species in urea was one-half of\rthe value to be found in alkali and\rone-quarter that of the succinylated material.\r'),
 (511,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1747. the problem of albuminoid\ralbuminoid is the main constituent of the\rinsoluble fraction of the lens proteins.\ralbuminoid from the cortex of ox lens has\rbeen fractionated on deae-cellulose in\r7 m urea; peptide maps of the fractions\rare very similar to those from the corre-\rsponding fractions from a-crystallin.\ralbuminoid can be regarded as an insoluble\ra-crystallin.  an undiluted ground lens\ris clear but becomes turbid on dilution.  if\ralbuminoid is present in the normal lens,\rit does not cause turbidity even when the\rcellular structure is disrupted.  it is\rperhaps more likely that the albuminoid is\rformed on dilution of the lens mush.\rthe high concentration of proteins in the lens,\respecially in the nucleus, entails a high\rdegree of order, which will be destroyed\ron dilution  this phenomenon may well be\rconnected with the precipitation of the\ralbuminoid.\r'),
 (512,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'787. further autoradiographic studies of the lens epithelium.\rnormal and x-irradiated rat eyes\rcell proliferation and migration in\rthe lens epithelium of normal and x-irradiated\rrat eyes were studied by means of\rautoradiography after labelling with tritiated\rthymidine.  cells of the normal lens\repithelium require 16 hr. to pass from the\rbeginning of the synthesizing period\rto the completion of mitosis.  this interval is\rpartitioned as follows  s period,\rapproximately 10 hr.; g2, slightly less than 5 hr;\rand mitosis, 72 min.  following division,\rlabelled daughter cells migrate from the\rgerminative zone to the postequatorial\rrows, and by 2 weeks after tracer injection\rmany radioactive nuclei are found in the\rlens bow.  epithelial cells irradiated while\rin the dna synthesis phase undergo\rdegeneration beginning approximately 8 hr.\rafter exposure.  the onset of cell death\rcorresponds to the time at which these cells\rwould normally be preparing for mitosis\rindicating that they die in abortive divisions.\ra small percentage of the originally\rlabelled cells survived until 3 days after irradi-\ration, but by 2 weeks this number fell\ralmost to zero.  the loss of radioactive cells\roccurred most rapidly in the equatorial zone.\r'),
 (513,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2627. chicken lens development  epithelial cell production and\rmigration\rin the earliest stages of chicken lens\rdevelopment, cell division occurred over the\rentire lens.  cell division first stopped\rin the posterior side of the lens vesicle, as\rthe cells differentiated into primary lens\rfibers.  after the annular pad developed,\rcell division occurred, for the most part,\rin the anterior surface epithelial cells.\rshortly after hatching and thereafter, a\rgerminative zone, consisting of a narrow\rband of epithelial cells adjacent to the\rannular pad developed.  the cells from the\rgerminative zone migrated slowly and\rdifferentiated first into annular pad cells and\rthen into lens cortex fibers over an\restimated 2-year period.  this slow migration\rof cells in the lens is discussed in\rrelation to the failure of the adult chicken to de-\rvelop radiation cataracts.\r'),
 (514,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1494. selenium content of fish flour in relation to kwashiorkor and dental\rcaries\rthe fact that fish flour was shown to be a rich source of\rdietary selenium (169 p.p.m. may have important implications (i.e. deleterious\reffect on teeth) in the treatment and prevention of protein malnutrition.  it\rindicates that some disease syndromes in man may be a manifestation of selenium\rdeficiency.  it is recommended that the role played by selenium in protein\rmalnutrition should be given serious consideration by research workers.\r'),
 (515,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2192. selenium content of fresh eggs\rduring a study of effects of traces of se on dental caries the authors\rdetermined this element in eggs.  whole egg contains appreciable\ramounts of se; this is found chiefly in the yolk (mean value 0.324\r0.039 p.p.m.) with only 0.051 0.029 p.p.m. in the white.\r'),
 (516,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1541. selenium content of human milk  possible effect on dental caries\rselenium appears to be a factor capable of increasing susceptibility to\rdental caries in children and rats.  in an area considered to be\rnonseleniferous, milk collected from 15 mothers (17-44 yr. old) of low\rsocio-economic class had a mean selenium content of 0.021 p.p.m.\r(standard error  0.003).\r'),
 (517,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1577. mode of action of selenium in relation to biological activity of\rtocopherols\rdietary selenium at levels below 1 ppm has a partially beneficial effect\rupon nutritional muscular dystrophy but is ineffective or detrimental\rat higher levels.  the role of selenium in improving the effectiveness of\rvitamin e is due at least in part to the fact that dietary selenium increases\rthe retention of the a-tocopherols, especially d-a-tocopherol.  this has been\rshown by chemical determination of plasma tocopherols and also by tracing the\ractivities of tritiated tocopherols and selenium75 in serum and in various\rfractions of serum proteins in chicks receiving these nutrients alone and in\rcombination.  se75 and h3-a-tocopherol activities followed each other very\rclosely in the serum proteins.  these studies indicated that vitamin e may be\rcarried by a selenolipoprotein fraction associated with serum y-globulin.  thus,\rone biological role of selenium appears to lie in a selenium-containing\rcompound which acts as a carrier of vitamin e and which may function in\rabsorption, retention, prevention of destruction, and perhaps transfer across\rcell membranes of d-a-tocopherol, thereby enhancing its biological activity\rin the blood and perhaps in cells throughout the body.\r'),
 (518,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3123. effect of sodium selenate on acute poisoning with thallium\rexperiments were performed on wistar rats weighing 150-200 g.  thallium was ad-\rministered s.c. in doses of 20 mg/kg and 30 mg/kg.  sodium selenate was\rgiven per os in doses of 10 mg/kg 2 hr after poisoning and 5 mg/kg daily\rfor the next 2 days.  results indicate that sodium selenate protects the\ranimals from death.  it binds the thallium ions and increases their deposition\rin organs.  comparison of the level of thallium in organs of treated rats\rshows that selenate increases in liver by 290.6%, in kidneys by 326.8% and in\rbones by 210.0%.  no influence of selenate on excretion of thallium in the\rurine was found, but fecal excretion of thallium increased by an average of\r45% of the treated animals.\r'),
 (519,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2281. inhibition of active transport of sugars through rat intestine in vitro.\rii. action of mepacrine, atractyloside and selenite\rit is shown that mepacrine, atractyloside and selenite, which had been regarded\ras inhibitors of intestinal absorption of glucose, are inhibitors of active\rtransport of sugars in sacs of everted jejunum of rat (wilson and wiseman\'s\rmethod).  mepacrine 5 x 10 -3 m and 10 -2 m inhibit, by 85% and 100%\rrespectively, the active transport of galactose.  with atractyloside 10 -5 m\rand 10 -3 m, the inhibitions were 77% and 100% and, with selenite 10 -4 m and\r10 -3 m, about 70%.  in general the inhibitors are effective within orders of\rmagnitude which are similar in vivo and in vitro.  atractyloside is rather more\reffective in vitro than in vivo, and mepacrine rather less.  it is easier to\rachieve total inhibitions of the active transport of sugars in vitro than of\rintestinal absorption from isotonic solutions in vivo.\r'),
 (520,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2284. analogs parasympathetic neuroeffectors.  ii. comparative pharmacological\rstudies of acetylcholine, its thio and seleno analogs, and their hydrolysis\rproducts\racetylthiocholine and acetylselenocholine exert acetylcholine-like effects on\rthe guinea-pig ileum and frog rectus abdominis preparations.  with the\rlatter preparation, responses to acetylthiocholine and acetylselenocholine,\rin contrast to that to acetylcholine, are not enhanced by the addition of an\ranticholinesterase.  this is attributable to the relatively high activity of\rthe hydrolysis products, cholinethiol and cholineselenol; acetylthiocholine\rand acetyselenocholine undergo enzymatic hydrolysis at approximately the same\rrate as does acetylcholine.  the hydrolysis products of acetylthiocholine and\racetylselenocholine, which have effects on the guinea-pig ileum comparable\rto those of the parent esters, are readily oxidized in air to the relatively\rinactive choline disulfide and choline diselenide, respectively.  these\robservations are helpful in explaining many of the apparently contradictory\rstatements in the literature regarding the actions of acetylthiocholine.\r'),
 (521,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3604. cytotoxicity of organophosphorus compounds.  comparative activities of\rtrimethyl derivatives of thiophosphoric and selenophosphoric acids on vegetable\r(pisum root) and human (hela) cells\rof the 4 compounds studied, the seleno compounds were more cytotoxic for\rhela cells than their thio analogues, whereas the activities on pisum\rroot cells were equal.  the parent phosphoric acid derivatives have a\rwider activity range on hela cells than the seleno and thio derivatives.\rfurther studies are in progress.\r'),
 (522,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3640. poisoning with sodium selenite\rchronic poisoning with na selenite (in the drinking water) causes hepatic\rcirrhosis, usually of atrophic type, in rats.  in rabbits there seems to be a\rdefinite diabetogenic action, while attempts to demonstrate such action in\rdogs have so far given inconclusive results.  the difference between these\r2 species is perhaps due to the technique used (different spacing of injections\rfor practical reasons).  the action of selenite on the pancreas is discussed\rand it is pointed out that se can replace s in sh groups, thus rendering the\rlatter ineffective.  both in effects on the liver and in those on the pancreas\rse seems to resemble alloxan.\r'),
 (523,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2552. the tissue distribution of se75 -selenouracil and se75 -selenourea\rwhen selenium analogues of thiouracil and thiourea labelled with se75 were\rinjected into rabbits, high radioactivity appeared in lung, liver and kidney.\rthe animal\'s lungs could be visualised by photoscanning, but quality was\rpoor, and neither compound is recommended for trial for lung or\radrenal scanning in man.\r'),
 (524,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1142. sodium selenate toxicosis  pathology and pathogenesis of sodium\rselenate toxicosis in sheep\rthe pathogenesis of selenium toxicosis was studied in 30 ewes fed subtoxic to\rtoxic levels of sodium selenate for 1 to 5 mth.  seventeen of the 30 died of\rselenium toxicosis.  the most severe and consistent pathologic changes were\rfound in the myocardium and lungs.  myocardial alterations were focal to\rdiffuse degeneration, necrosis and early replacement fibrosis.  pulmonary\rchanges, consisting of edema and interstitial hemorrhages, were typical of the\rdegenerative processes which characterize passive congestion of the lungs\rresulting from left ventricular insufficiency.  atrophy of lymphoid centers\rin the spleen and lymph nodes was common.  degenerative changes were\roccasionally found in liver, kidneys, and gastrointestinal tract.\r'),
 (525,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1143. sodium selenate toxicosis  the distribution of selenium within the body\rafter prolonged feeding of toxic quantities of sodium selenate to sheep\rthe distribution of selenium in the body tissues of adult sheep fed subtoxic to\rtoxic quantities of sodium selenate daily for 1 to 5 mth. varied with the\rtissue\rtype and with the level and duration of selenium consumption.  selenium\rconcentration was highest in the liver, followed by (in descending order)\rthe kidneys, lungs, spleen, myocardium, skeletal muscles, and brain.\r'),
 (526,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1172. studies on selenium toxicity and chondroitin sulfate and taurine\rbiosynthesis in the chick embryo\rfourteen-day-old chick embryos were used in in vivo experiments.  a toxic\rselenite treatment did not cause a reduction in the extent of sulfate-s\rincorporation into chondroitin sulfate or into taurine or a reduction in the\robserved tissue levels of these metabolites.  rather, the taurine level was\rsignificantly greater with the embryos which received selenium.  the extent of\rthe incorporation of selenite-se into the metabolites was low or not\rsignificant.\r'),
 (527,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'843. reactions of seleno- and sulfoamino acids with hydroperoxides\rreactions of methionine, cystine and their selenium analogues with\rhydrogen peroxide and organic peroxides have been studied.  methionine reacts\rmost rapidly with hydrogen peroxide but selenocystine causes the most\rdecomposition; both react much more slowly with organic peroxides.  the results\rsuggest that selenocystine may act as a biological antioxidant.\r'),
 (528,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2127. selenium toxicity in domestic animals\rthe article, with an extensive bibliography, is a compendium of available\rinformation on selenium toxicity in domestic animals.  literature reveals\revidence of organically bound se being more biologically active, when given\rorally to domestic animals, than inorganic se salts.  there is also variation\rin toxicity of organic se analogs.  when exposed to ruminal digestion, there is\rconsiderable reduction of se salts to the relatively biologically inactive\relemental se; which may result in fecal excretion of se, as such, to as much\ras 40% of a single oral dose.  fluorine, molybdenum, chromium, vanadium,\rcadmium, zinc, cobalt, nickel and uranium increase se toxicity.  arsenic and\rtungsten give some protection against it.  bromobenzene, benzene, and\rnapthalene\rmobilize tissue se and stimulate its excretion.  since se preparations designed\rfor topical application in treatment of skin disease have been available for\ruse\rin both man and dogs, the literature has reported cases of poisoning from\rmisuse\rof such preparations.  selenium, properly used, can be a valuable therapeutic\ragent, though certain salts of se must be regarded as potentially toxic.\rhowever, there is considerable latitude between therapeutic and/or nutritional\rand toxic doses of these salts.\r'),
 (529,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1845. further studies on specific transplantation antigens in rous sarcoma of\rmice\rmice allografted with different sarcomas, induced by the schmidt-ruppin variant\rof rous sarcoma virus (rsv-sr), showed a resistance against subsequent\risografting of 9 different rous sarcomas.  transplantation\rresistance could also be induced by\rrous mouse tumor cells x-irradiated with 8000 r\ror with cell-free tumor extracts,\rcontaining no demonstrable virus.  no\rtransplantation resistance could be demon-\rstrated after allograft pretreatment with\rvarious polyoma tumors or non-viral tu-\rmors.  allograft pretreatment with rous\rtumors induced no demonstrable resistance\ragainst isografting of polyoma tumors.\rinoculation of rsv-sr or rous chicken sar-\rcoma suspension into adult mice gave\rno clear cut resistance against isograft-\ring of mouse sarcomas.  neither after\rallografting of rous tumors nor after virus\ror chicken sarcoma inoculation into adult\rmice could virus-neutralizing activity be\rdemonstrated in the sera.  the results\rdemonstrate the presence of common, speci-\rfic transplantation antigen(s) in different\rrous sarcomas in mice and speak against\ran identity between the transplantation\rantigen(s) and viral antigen(s).\r'),
 (530,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1846. anaphylactic tests in model tumour antigen investigations\rthe efficacy of anaphylactic tests in detecting\r\'tumor\' antigen in serum was investi-\rgated.  a simple model of a tumor-antigen\rstudy was carried out using rat tissue\rand rat serum, with bovine y-globulin (byg)\racting as a mock cancer antigen.  it\rwas found that if byg (absolute dosage 100\rug.) had formed 1/6 of the antigen mix-\rture used for sensitization it was readily\rdetected when present in a concentration\rof 10-3 in the serum used for challenge,\rbut not invariably detected in a concentra-\rtion of 10-4.  if byg (absolute dosage 50\rug.) had formed approximately 1/50 of the\rsensitizing mixture, it was infrequently\rdetected even when present in the challeng-\ring serum in a concentration of 10-2.  it\ris concluded that anaphylactic tests used in\rthis context do not have a very high\rsensitivity or discriminatory capacity.\r'),
 (531,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1066. the effect of lymphoid cells from\rthe lymph of specifically immunised sheep\ron the growth of primary sarcomata in\rrats\rthe growth of primary fibrosarcomata induced in\rrats with 3:4-benzpyrene was retarded by the injection\rof lymphocytes obtained from the efferent duct of a\rlymph node in a sheep immunized with a piece of the\rtumor to be treated.  the action of the heterologous lym-\rphocytes was specific to the particular tumor used for\rimmunization suggesting that reaction against tumor-\rspecific antigens is involved.  the cells responsible are\rbelieved to be medium-sized pyroninophilic lymphocytes\rwhich may stimulate the immune system of the host to\rreact against the autochthonous tumor.\r'),
 (532,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2570. treatment of canine neoplasms with autogenous vaccinial preparations\rinbred mice with transplantable sarcoma\rand carcinoma were treated with im-\rplants of their tumours which had been\rgrown in strains of mice normally resistant\rto the tumours.  complete regression of\rtransplantable tumours was noted in 22%\rof the treated mice and 78% had life\rspans double that of untreated controls.\rone dog with spontaneous scirrhous\rmammary carcinoma and another with\rlymphosarcoma were treated with implants\rof their own tumours after growth in\rcortisone-treated mice.  regression of the\rspontaneous neoplasms followed in both\rcases.  it is suggested that growth of a\rneoplasm in a foreign host alters the mole-\rcular structure of the neoplasm, making it\rantigenic when returned to the original\rhost.  antigens produced are also effective\ragainst the original lesions.\r'),
 (533,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'744. studies on protein and nucleic acid metabolism in virus-in-\rfected mammalian cells.  the formation of a virus-specific\rantigen in krebs ii ascites-tumour cells infected with ence-\rphalomyocarditis virus\rkrebs ii mouse ascites-tumor cells infected\rwith encephalomyocarditis virus were\rfound to contain, in addition to mature virus,\ra virus-specific protein antigen.  an\rassay, based on the ability of this antigen\rto block the neutralization of purified virus\rby its specific antiserum, was developed.\rthis antigen was present both in the cul-\rture fluid 17 hr. after the infection of cells\rwith virus and intracellularly, where its\rtiter increased at a time when viral capsid\rprotein was being synthesized.  within the\rcell, it was mostly localized in the soluble\rcell sap.  in contrast with virus, the anti-\rgen did not agglutinate sheep erythrocytes,\rand its immunological properties were\rdestroyed by digestion with trypsin.  ribonucleic\racid was not detected in concentrat-\red preparations of the antigen, nor was the titer\rof antigen affected by ribonuclease.\rthe antigen had a sedimentation coefficient (20 )\rof approx. 14s, and its diffusion co-\refficient, determined by the method of allison and\rhumphrey (1960), was 3.2 x 10-7\rsq. cm. sec.-1.  the particle weight of the antigen\rwas hence 420,000   40,000.  the\rcapsid protein from purified encephalomyocarditis\rvirus could be degraded by treat-\rment with ethanolamine into a protein of sedimentation\rcoefficient (20 ) of approx. 4s.\rthe 14s antigen, when similarly treated, yielded\ra protein of similar size.  however,\rno such smaller antigen was detected in virus-infected\rcells.  it is concluded that the\rnon-hemagglutinating antigen represents a polymeric\rform of the basic viral capsid-\rprotein molecule and that it is synthesized in the\rcytoplasm of infected cells.  it may\rbe either an intermediate or a by-product in the\rprocess of viral capsid-protein syn-\rthesis.\r'),
 (534,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1368. immunologic competence and induction of neoplasms by\rpolyoma virus\rthymectomy at 3 days of age in several\rinbred strains of mice and in an f1 hybrid\rresulted in a strikingly increased frequency\rof neoplasms following infection with\rpolyoma virus.  age susceptibility was extended\rto at least 30 days of age in highly\rresistant c57bl mice.  the usual stigmata\rassociated with thymectomy at birth were\rnot found in the 3-day thymectomized mice.\rnonetheless the methods used to restore\rimmunologically deficient thymectomized\rneonates were also effective in restoring\rthe capacity to resist polyoma virus tumor\rinduction: adult syngeneic spleen cells,\rthymus tissue in millipore diffusion chambers\rand syngeneic thymus grafts.  growth\rcurves of polyoma virus in kidney, salivary\rglands and liver were quite similar in\rthymectomized and intact litter mates.\rhemagglutination-inhibition antibodies deter-\rmined periodically up to 30 days after\rinfection were also similar in both groups.\rthese results are discussed in terms of\ra concept involving virus-specific \'tumor\'\rantigens and the immunologic status of the animal.\r'),
 (535,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1848. antigen analysis of sera from patients with malignant\rtumors by immunodiffusion methods\rimmunoelectrophoresis and ouchterlony\'s\rmethod were used for the antigen analy-\rsis of sera from 320 cancer patients; 250\rnormal or non-tumorous cases served as\rcontrols.  immunoelectrophoresis showed\rabnormal precipitin lines which could not\rbe demonstrated in normal sera.  most of\rthe abnormal antigens were demonstrated\rin the a2- and b1-globulin fractions.  the\rdistribution of these antigens differed in\rindividual cases and was not related to the\rhistopathological classification and site\rof the tumors.  however, these antigens\rincreased in parallel with growth of the\rtumors and disappeared or markedly\rdecreased after surgical removal of the tumor\rtissue.  almost all sera of patients with\rmyeloma, leukemia, and malignant lymph-\roma formed one characteristic line in\rthe b2-globulin region and they could be dif-\rferentiated from the patterns in cases of carcinoma.\r'),
 (536,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2354. isoantigenic properties of tumors transgressing histocompatibility\rbarriers of the h-2 system\rsublines capable of transgressing h-2 histocompatibility\rbarriers have been derived\rfrom strictly strain-specific tumors by 1) passage\rthrough newborn hosts of a\rforeign genotype; 2) passage through adult h-2\rincompatible recipients pretreated\rwith isoantisera directed against the tumor cells.\rthe nonspecific character induced\rby these procedures was usually expressed in a\rnumber of different h-2 incompa-\rtible recipients.  the changes responsible for\rthe conversion to nonspecific growth\rappeared to proceed in a stepwise fashion.\rexpression of the nonspecific character\rrequired exposure to the foreign host environment\rfor more than 30 days.  at this\rstage and during the subsequent 3 transfer\rgenerations, reversion to strain-specific\rgrowth occurred on back-transfer to the\rstrain of origin; after 4 passages in the\rforeign hosts the nonspecific character was\rpermanently established, however, and\rcould not be reverted by prolonged passage\rin the original host genotype.  the\rgrowth rate of strain-specific tumors and\rtheir nonspecific sublines was compared\rin the strain of origin.  no difference was\rfound with one tumor, while the strain-\rspecific line grew better than the nonspecific\rsublines with another.  this difference\rwas detected in the homozygous strain of\rorigin and in different semi-isologous f1\rhybrids.  all lines grew better in the\rhomozygous strain than in the f1 hybrids,\rhowever.  a comparison was made\rbetween the concentration of h-2 isoantigenic\rsurface determinants in strain-specific\rtumors and their nonspecific sublines by a\rquantitative absorption technique in\rvitro.  all nonspecific sublines had a lower\rconcentration of h-2 isoantigens than\rthe strain-specific tumors.  this suggests\rthat nonspecific tumors develop as a result\rof immunoselection of variants resistant\rto the homograft reaction and are characterized\rby a lowered concentration of\rh-2 antigens.\r'),
 (537,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2371. participation of 7s and 19s antibodies in enhancement and\rresistance to methylcholanthrene-induced tumours\rserum factors responsible for enhancement\rand resistance to methylcholanthrene-\rinduced tumors in a syngeneic system in mice\rwere studied.  they were found to be\rpart of the serum immunoglobulin system.\rthe active components of specific anti-\rtumor serum were always contained in the\r7s (y-2) and 19s (y-1m) fraction, while\rno activity was detected in the 4s fraction.\rin sera which in the given dose enhanced\rgrowth of the tumor graft, enhancing activity\rwas present in both the 7s and 19s\rfraction of the serum and was higher in the\rformer.  in sera which in the given dose\rinfluenced the interaction of the organism with\rthe tumor by producing resistance\rto the tumor graft, both fractions were again\ractive, the activity of fraction 19s\rbeing higher than that of fraction 7s.\r'),
 (538,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2372. the effect of immunity against sex-antigen on a tumour\rgraft containing sex-antigen\rthe tumor bp 1 induced by benzpyrene in c57bl\rmale mice contains sex-antigen.\rsex-antigen is not lost during growth of tumor\ragainst immunity directed against\rthis antigen.  the tumor, however, becomes\rmore resistant to immunity and the\rcontent of sex-antigen is decreased.\r'),
 (539,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2373. factors influencing the induction of enhancement and re-\rsistance to methylcholanthrene-induced tumours in a syn-\rgeneic system\ractive immunological enhancement of the\rgrowth of methylcholanthrene-induced tu-\rmors was demonstrated in a syngeneic\rsystem in mice.  enhancement was detected\r3-5 wk. after preimmunization with\rirradiated tumor suspension and was succeeded\rafter the 6th wk. by the development of\rresistance to the tumor.  analysis by means\rof adoptive and passive transfer showed\rthese to be true immunological phenomena.\renhancement and resistance were transferred\rby serum and by the lymph node cells\rof preimmunized mice.  threshold doses of\rtumor cells were found to be the most\rsatisfactory for the detection of resistance\rand enhancement in this system.\r'),
 (540,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5512. antigenic properties of human tumours\rpreliminary studies on the antigenic\rproperties of human tumours have been\rcarried out using heterologous antisera,\rprepared in rabbits, against a number of\rdifferent cancerous and normal tissues.\rafter repeated absorptions, antisera\rwere obtained which reacted only with\rtissue antigens.  some antisera, after ab-\rsorption with normal tissues, reacted only\rwith tumours.  seventy-two tumour and\r31 normal tissue extracts were studied\rby means of the ouchterlony agar gel\rdouble diffusion technique.  the results\rshowed the presence of an antigen or\rantigens in some human malignant tumours\rwhich were not detectable in normal\rtissues, in foetal tissues, or in hela cells.\rin addition, there was some loss of\rnormal tissue antigens from tumours.\rattempts are being made to isolate and\rcharacterize these tumour and normal\rtissue antigens.\r'),
 (541,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5514. the incorporation of sv40 genetic material into adenovirus 7 as\rmeasured by intranuclear synthesis of sv40 tumor antigen\rthe l.l. strain of adenovirus 7, free of\rdetectable infectious sv40 virus, induced\rsv40 tumour antigen, demonstrable by\rfluorescent antibody staining, in green mon-\rkey kidney, rabbit kidney, hamster embryo\rand human embryo kidney cell cultures.\rin green monkey and human cell cultures\rthere was a cytopathic effect and more\rcells contained the sv40 tumour antigen\rthan in the other types of culture.\radenovirus 7 viral antiserum neutralized\rthe sv40 tumour antigen inducing\rability of the l.l. strain virus but anti-sv40\rmonkey serum and serum from sv40\rtumour bearing hamsters did not.  an\radenovirus 7 preparation propagated\rexclusively in human tissue did not induce\rthe sv40 tumour antigen.  the sv40\rtumour antigen was entirely localised within\rthe cell nuclei and appeared to be\rtransmitted to daughter cells during mitosis.\r'),
 (542,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'264. fluorescent antibodies to human cancer-specific dna and\rnuclear proteins\rspecific antigens have been demonstrated\rin certain cancers.  in this study they were\robtained from an adenocarcinoma of the\rcolon and an ewing\'s sarcoma.  homogenates\rwere prepared and male rabbits were\rimmunized.  the animals were bled to death\r10 days after the last injection.  testing\rincluded fluorescent antibody methods and\ragar-gel horizontal double-diffusion precipitin\rtest.  the pattern of reaction of these\rantibodies against various cancers seems to\rbe dependent upon the source of the\rcancerous dna-bound proteins and the salt\rconcentration used in their isolation.\rhuman cancer-specific cross nuclear antigens\rseem to be cross reacting rather\rthan identical in structure.  the cancer-specific\rantibodies could be removed only\rwith absorption of the immune globulins with\rcancerous tissues.  salt-soluble human\rdna-bound proteins from an adenocarcinoma\rof the colon and an ewing\'s sarcoma\rinduced the formation of cancer specific\rantibodies which showed positive fta re-\ractions (to a maximum titer of 1/128) against\r95% of the cancerous tissues studied.\rthese cancer-specific antibodies gave\rsimilar fta reactions with cell nuclei of\rnormal appearing liver parenchyma\radjacent to metastatic carcinoma of colon, nor-\rmal appearing colon near to metastatic\rcarcinoma of the colon, normal appearing\rcolon near to carcinoma of the colon,\rand a long-standing case of chronic ulcerative\rcolitis.  evidence is shown that this finding\rpossibly may represent a serological\rdetection of an early or latent cancerous\rchange in morphologically normal cells.\rthese cancer-specific antigens have been\ridentified as rounded, intranuclear dna-\rbodies and nuclear proteins which can be\rspecifically destroyed by dnase trypsin.\r'),
 (543,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'266. immunology of the cancer cell: tumour-specific antigens\rafter a broad historical survey of immunological\rstudies of cancer, a review is given\rof the evidence showing that antigens present in\rnormal cells are missing from the\rmalignant cells that arise from the same tissue.\rthis evidence is considered in con-\rjunction with the deletion hypothesis of carcinogenesis,\rand the author emphasizes,\rthat in his view, the key event in carcinogenesis\ris enzymatic deletion.  antigenic\rgain and intensification in the course of spontaneous,\rchemical, and viral carcino-\rgenesis is reviewed, together with experiments\rdemonstrating the existence of\rtumour-specific antigens.  the question is then\rposed: if tumours have specific anti-\rgens, why is evidence for their rejection so scanty?\rthe occasional spontaneous re-\rgression points to host resistance but its rarity\rsuggests that tolerance generally\rdevelops.  consideration is given to the\rapplication of immunological methods to\rtherapy and although current achievement\rin this field is limited, new immunological\rstratagems might yet transform the picture.\rfinally a plea is made for the integra-\rtion of the disciplines of immunology and\rcellular differentiation.  the prospect is\rraised that through a synthetic and holistic\rapproach we might discover the suscepti-\rbility of the cancer cell to re-differentiation\rand re-recognition.\r'),
 (544,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effets de la carence potassique\rchez le rat sur le squelette,\rle cholesterol plasmatique\rl\'histologie des surrenales\rr. habib, j. lefebvre et p. royer\rpotassium deficiency in the male rat at the time of weaning,\rprovokes an increase in the weight of the suprarenals, an\ratrophy of the glomerular zone and a lipoid hypertrophy of\rthe fasciculae.\rit causes a rise in the level of the blood cholesterol.  it\rreduces the phosphate level in the blood and increases the\rphosphate in the urine.\rthe blood calcium level is not altered but a hypocalciuria is\rnoted.\rit leads to a severe osteopathy which has been investigated\rby radiography, microradiography and histological and bio-\rchemical study of the skeleton.  the following are the charac-\rteristics : arrest of osseous growth, delay of maturation, arrest\rof chondrogenesis, formation of dense metaphyseal lines or\rlines of arrest, osteoporosis.\rthese facts are discussed and compared to the analogous\rchanges found in the syndrome of chronic idiopathic hypo-\rkalaemia with hyperkaluria in the infant.\r'),
 (545,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'vergleichende renale phosphatelearance-untersuchungen\rbeim hyperparathyreoidismus und beim sog.  phosphatdiabetes\rthe analysis of the function of the kidneys give a contribution to\rthe pathophysiology of two different diseases of general osteopathies\rwhose pathogenesis or etiology are still not clear in some points.  the\rphosphate clearance pre- and postoperative in one patient with hyper-\rparathyroidism showed that after the removal of the adenoma of the\rparathyroid the renal reabsorption of phosphate improved only tempo-\rrary as a secondary form of hyperparathyroidism was already present.\rin a patient with a \"phosphatdiabetes\" the clearance examination showed\rthat under a high dosage of vitamin d the reabsorption of phosphate did\rnot increase.  based on these results we have not continued therapy\rwith vitamin d which is certainly not indifferent.  comparative renal\rclearance examinations were carried out in 10 patients which did not\rshow any disturbances of calcium/phosphate-metabolism.\r'),
 (546,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the unreliability of the titan yellow method\rfor the determination of magnesium\rin patients receiving intravenous\rcalcium gluconate\rgluconate was found to interfere with the determination of magnesium by the\rtitan yellow method.  with this method, false low results were found in the\rserum and urine of patients receiving intravenous calcium gluconate.  the\rinterference can be prevented by ashing of the specimen.\r'),
 (547,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'absorption and excretion of toxogonin, an alkyl-phosphate antidote,\rafter intramuscular injection in man\rtolerance, absorption and urinary excretion stu-\rdies of toxogonin (bis-(4-hydroxyiminomethyl-\rpyridine-1-methyl) ether dichloride), a specific anti-\rdote in poisoning by esterase-blocking organic\rphosphates, were made on 11 men by intramuscular\rinjection of 250 mg. (ca. 3 mg./kg.) of the drug,\rgiven by self-injection ampoules.  injections made\rwith the automatic ampoule autule caused no local\rirritation.  certain facial symptoms reported can for\rthe time being be regarded as resorptive side-effects\rof toxogonin.  maximum blood levels of 6 ug./ml.\rwere recorded within 20 minutes.  even after four\rhours the level was still 1-2 ug./ml., a concentra-\rtion amply sufficient to ensure reactivation of blood\resterases.  of the injected dose, 52% was excreted\rin the urine after two hours, 87% after eight hours.\rtoxogonin appears to pass through the body un-\rchanged.\r'),
 (548,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the study of osteoporosis\rand osteomalacia\rradiological evidence strongly suggests that\rosteoporosis (with the possible exception of acute\rimmobilization osteoporosis) may be an irrever-\rsible condition.  the changes therefore to be\rexpected in calcium balance when an osteoporotic\ris treated are small compared with those often\rseen in osteomalacia.  methods of obtaining more\raccurate calcium balances are needed to show\rthese small changes, especially when a high\rcalcium intake is used.  the method of continuous\rmarking of stools with chromium sesquioxide\rseems to provide just such a method.  using this\rmethod, it has so far proved impossible to obtain\rprolonged large positive calcium balances in\rosteoporosis on either high calcium intake,\ranabolic hormones, or sodium fluoride.\rtwo alternative therapies to vitamin d have\rbeen explored for use in vitamin d-resistant\rosteomalacia.  atp has been found to be inneffective.\rintravenous phosphate alone has been ineffective\rin producing positive calcium balances, but is\reffective as a complement to vitamin d under\rcertain conditions.\r'),
 (549,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the aetiology and treatment of\rurinary calculus\rinvestigations in this laboratory have been\rbased on the hypothesis that calculus formation is\rprimarily a process of crystallization from super-\rsaturated solutions rather than one of adsorption\ron a specific protein matrix, as has been postulated\rby boyce and his colleagues (boyce and king,\r1963).  that crystallization is the primary factor\ris strongly suggested by the recent studies of\rvermeulen, lyon and gill (1964).  these authors\rproduced artificial concretions which closely\rresembled urinary calculi by immersing a rotating\rwire loop in normal urine for several days and\rslowly adding the appropriate stone-forming\relements.\rif the above hypothesis is correct then the\rfactors of primary interest in urinary stone\rformation are those responsible for supersaturation,\rnucleation and crystal poisoning.  much remains\rto be learnt about these various factors, their\rinter-relationships, and their relative importance.\rthe significance of the urinary colloids (proteins,\rmuco-proteins and polysaccharides) in calculus\rformation is still not clear but it is probable that\rthey play an important secondary role in binding\rcrystalline precipitates to form a non-friable\rcalculus.  since time is an important factor in\rcrystal growth such non-specific binding by\rproteins would increase the chances of stone\rgrowth and retention within the upper urinary\rtract.\r'),
 (550,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'control of idiopathic hypercalciuria\rthe paper discusses the causes of hypercalciuria and describes\r15 cases of different origins all of which presented similarly\rwith renal stones.  the diagnosis of idiopathic hypercalciuria\rwas made by exclusion.  the effects of dietary restriction of\rcalcium, sodium bicarbonate, cortisone, sodium phosphate,\rsodium phytate, and cellulose phosphate were demonstrated by\rcalcium and phosphorus balance techniques.  all were shown\rto have some urinary-calcium-lowering effect.  finally, a\rchlorothiazide derivative--namely, bendrofluazide--was also\rdemonstrated to have a hypocalciuric effect, and the mode of\raction is discussed.\r'),
 (551,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of parathyroid hormone and other proteins in vitro\ron mitochondrial metabolism\rit is apparent that in addition to parathyroid hormone, several\rnon-hormonal basic proteins stimulate mitochondrial respiration, ion\rtransport, and atpase, but inhibit the 32pi-atp exchange reaction.\rthus these effects may not be so uniquely a measure of the biological\ractions of parathyroid hormone as the previous reports suggested.\rrasmussen et al. (1964) have also isolated from parathyroid\rextracts a protein that is inert in vivo but stimulates mitochondrial\rtransport of phosphate in vitro.  they postulated that this protein\rmight be yet another biologically important factor produced by para-\rthyroid glands.  the latter speculation may not be warranted in view\rof the uncertain specificity of protein effects on mitochondria.  all\rof our tests completed to date show that the non-hormonal parathyroid\rproteins c1 and c2 are unrelated either biologically, immunologically,\ror chemically (by amino-acid analysis) to the parathyroid hormone.\rfurther rigorous studies are necessary to precisely determine\rwhether any effects of parathyroid hormone on mitochondria validly\rreflect the mechanism of action of the hormone and whether it is sound\rto use the in vitro tests as bioassay tools.\r'),
 (552,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the treatment of phosphatic encrusted cystitis\r(alkaline cystitis) with nalidixic acid.\rphosphatic encrusted cystitis is caused by\rpersistent infection by b. proteus or ps. pyocyaneus\rassociated with an alkaline urine.  its incidence\rmay be increasing and may follow megavoltage\rtherapy of a bladder tumour.  its incidence in\rpost-radiation cases is 2 per cent.\rmandelamine often fails to relieve this\rcondition.  in this series of ten patients who had\rfailed to respond to mandelamine, eight\rresponded to treatment with nalidixic acid.  no side\reffect of treatment was noted in the series.\rnalidixic acid is of value in the treatment of b. proteus\rinfections of the urinary tract, and is the drug\rof choice in the treatment of phosphatic encrusted\rcystitis.\r'),
 (553,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'role of the liver in the glycoprotein mobilizing property of\rparathyroid extract\rstudies were carried out to de-\rtermine the action of hepatectomy on the\rglycoprotein action of pte as well as on\rpte-induced renal calcification and deposi-\rtion of glycoprotein.  our data showed that\rin hepatectomized rats, pte no longer caused\ran elevation in serum glycoproteins.  how-\rever, hepatectomy did not alter the forma-\rtion of glycoprotein tubular casts produced\rby pte administration.  the data suggest\rthat the liver is the major source of the ele-\rvated serum glycoproteins found in rats re-\rceiving pte.  in addition, it is possible that\rpte may have a direct stimulating action\ron biosynthesis of glycoprotein by the kidney.\r'),
 (554,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'distribution and excretion of radioactivity after parenteral\radministration of radioactive polydiethylstilbestrol phosphate\rto rats and a cow.\rpolydiethylstilbestrol phosphate\r(psp), a water soluble polyester of phos-\rphoric acid and diethylstilbestrol, was in-\rjected in rats and a cow and the distribution\rand excretion of radioactivity were followed\rin both species.  after a subcutaneous or\rintramuscular injection the bulk of the radio-\ractivity was accumulated at the site of injec-\rtion.  the disappearance of radioactivity from\rthis depot was very slow.  as late as 90 days\rafter the injection into rats, 20% of the\radministered radioactivity was still accumu-\rlated at the site of injection.  the liver was\rvery effective in removing labeled material\rfrom circulating blood.  twenty-four hours\rafter intravenous injection in rats, about\r50% of the radioactivity was recovered from\rthis organ.  the distribution of radioactivity\rin the cow indicated that the polymer was\rpreferably accumulated in organs containing\rreticuloendothelial cells.\r'),
 (555,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'study of phosphate excretion by the stop-flow\rtechnique\rm. de myttenaere\rthe stop-flow technique has been applied to the dog in an attempt to\rrule out tubular secretion of phosphate and to locate the site of action of\rparathyroid hormone (p.t.h.) on the renal tubule.  under the experimental\rconditions used, no significant inward transtubular movement of p32 could be\rdemonstrated, ruling out tubular secretion of phosphate.  stop-flow\rexperiments performed in parathyroidectomized dogs before and after p.t.h.\radministration demonstrated inhibition of phosphorus reabsorption by the\rhormone.  in addition, the stop-flow pattern indicated that this\rphenomenon took place mainly in the distal part of the proximal tubules.\r'),
 (556,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stupor, hypercalcemia and carcinoma of the\rrenal pelvis\rsince albright suggested that some tumors\r\"might be producing parathyroid hormone,\" hy-\rpercalcemia associated with malignant tumors with-\rout bony metastases has been recorded with increas-\ring frequency.  transitional-cell carcinoma of the\rrenal pelvis is here added to the list of neoplasms\rthat hypercalcemia may accompany.\r'),
 (557,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'anodized aluminium grains labelled with radiophosphorus\rfor medical purposes\rg. b. fasolo, r. malvano, u. rosa and e. zimmer\rinterstitial b-therapy, by implantation in tissues of\rradioactive sources, is widely applied to the treatment\rof certain forms of human malignancies.  among the\rradio-elements proposed for this therapeutic technique,\ryttrium-90 and gold-198 are the most generally used.\rradiophosphorus (32p) shows some attractive features\rbecause of its suitable half-life (14.3 days) and its rather\rhigh-energy b-emission (maximum energy 1.71 mev);\rbut the use of this radionuclide is limited by the diffi-\rculties found in the preparation of safe solid sources.  the\ronly techniques we have found in the literature are those\rreported by riechert and mundinger and by rames and\rmoravek, who used respectively small plastic capsules\rfilled with phosphomolybdic acid solution, and ca(po4),\rgrains, labelled with phosphorus-32.  these methods\rrequire a delicate preparative work, and, moreover, a\rlarge b-self-absorption effect can be expected in both\rcases.\ra new simple method for the preparation of grains\rlabelled with phosphorus-32 basically consists in ad-\rsorbing labelled po4 3- ions on an active aluminium oxide\rfilm produced by anodic oxidation of aluminium wire.\rthe adsorption capacity of the oxide film for po3 3- ions\ris quite high, but the process is reversible: the phos-\rphorus-32 activity is partially desorbed, even after\r\'sealing\' in boiling water, when the labelled wire is kept\rin isotonic sodium chloride solution.\r'),
 (558,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of parathyroidectomy and ferric dextrin\rupon calciphylactic sensitization by uremia\rexperiments on the rat indicate that calciphy-\rlactic sensitization can be achieved by bilateral\rnephrectomy.  intravenous administration of a\rferric dextrin preparation (fe-din) induces\rselective calcification in the buccal mucosa,\resophagus, trachea and mediastinum of the\rnephrectomized rat although it produces no such\rchanges in intact control animals.  conversely,\rfe-din prevents the cardiovascular calcification\rnormally elicited by nephrectomy.  parathy-\rroidectomy protects the nephrectomized rat\ragainst the fe-din-induced calciphylaxis.\rhence, it may be concluded that: 1) autologous\rparathyroid hormone, in amounts secreted by\rthe glands, can act as a calciphylactic sensitizer\rand 2) fe-din is highly effective in protecting the\rcardiovascular system against uremic damage.\r'),
 (559,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mediastinal parathyroid adenoma\ra case of hyperparathyroidism with hypercalcemic crisis is presented.  the\rtumor was a well differentiated and encapsulated parathyroid adenoma, un-\rusually located in the anterior mediastinum, lying both within and without\rthe pericardial sac.  the surgical approach was directly through the sternum\rwith a mediastinal exploration.  the postoperative course was uneventful and\rgratifying, with complete correction of both symptoms and abnormal laboratory\rfindings.\r'),
 (560,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'clinical experience with\rprimary hyperparathyroidism:\revaluation of treatment\rforty-four patients with \"operatively proven\" hyperparathyroidism were\revaluated to decide 1) whether or not the diagnosis could be substantiated\rby some postoperative observations other than the gross anatomic diagnosis\rof the operative specimen and 2) what the long term value of operative\rtreatment would be.  it was found that an immediate and significant fall\rin urinary phosphorus excretion best documented the diagnosis of primary\rhyperparathyroidism.  over intervals up to 10 years, follow-up of the\rpatients suggested a favourable response of the disease to operative\rtreatment.\r'),
 (561,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the dilution test as a measure of renal function in niobium-poisoned rats\rcontrol, female, albino rats given a water load of 50 ml/kg, excreted\r50 per cent of this load as urine within 94  11 minutes (teu50).\rthe administration of a single intraperitoneal dose ranging from 10\rto 30 mg nb/kg resulted in 2- to 4-fold increases in the teu50 value\r24 hours after the niobium was injected.\rwhen niobium was complexed with ascorbic acid prior to injection the\rteu50 value was within control limits.  however, rats given a single\rintraperitoneal dose of niobium and then given 3 doses of ascorbic acid at\rintervals of 1, 3, and 6 hours showed teu50 values that were not markedly\rdifferent from those observed in rats given niobium only.\rincreased teu50 values were observed in rats given single intraperitoneal\rdoses of uranyl nitrate (1.2-2.4 mg u/kg), mercuric chloride (2.0 mg hg/kg)\rand sodium tripolyphosphate (480 mg/kg).\r'),
 (562,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'influence of parathyroid activity on ion\rexchange in various tissues\r1. balance data from three patients with hypoparathyroidism, who were\rgiven parathyroid extract, are presented.  the metabolic response was\rcomplex.  the data demonstrate losses of phosphate, magnesium, sodium\rand potassium which were not accounted for by destruction of either bone\ror non-osseous tissues.  preferential depletion of these minerals from bone,\ror loss from non-osseous tissues, must be presumed.\r2. the exchange of ca45, mg28, and p32 in a spectrum of rat tissues has\rbeen studied in sham operated, parathyroidectomized, and parathyroid\rextract treated rats.  the effects of parathyroidectomy on the development\rof magnesium deficiency were determined.\r3. four hours after parathyroidectomy, increased transport of calcium\rinto bone, kidney, intestine, liver, brain, and muscle was found.  six days\rafter parathyroidectomy equilibrium had been reestablished and exchange\rrates were identical to those in sham operated animals.\r4. the administration of parathyroid extract was associated with de-\rcreased transport of ca15, mg28, and p32 into bone.  ca15 exchange in kidney\rwas reduced but in all other tissues exchange of ca15 and mg28 was in-\rcreased.  p32 exchange in both intestine and kidney was mardedly increased\rin animals receiving the extract.\r5. parathyroidectomy greatly minimized the manifestations of mag-\rnesium deficiency in young rats on magnesium deficient diets.\r6. the results suggest that parathyroid hormone may affect the trans-\rport and exchange of calcium, magnesium, and phosphate (and perhaps\rsodium and potassium) in tissues other than those usually considered to\rbe target organs.\r'),
 (563,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of alkalosis on plasma concentration and urinary\rexcretion of inorganic phosphate in man\racute respiratory and metabolic alkalosis have\rbeen shown to depress plasma phosphorus con-\rcentration in normal man.  the fall in plasma\rphosphorus concentration is greater in respiratory\rthan in comparable levels of extracellular meta-\rbolic alkalosis.  this fall is not attributable to in-\rcreased renal excretion or to migration into red\rblood cells.  the evaluation of low serum phos-\rphorus concentrations should always be carried\rout with a knowledge of the ph and total co2\rcontent of the plasma.\r'),
 (564,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the relationship between vitamin d and parathyroid\rhormone\rmarit von stedingk\rthe effect of parathyroidectomy and parathy-\rroid hormone administration upon the concentra-\rtions of plasma calcium and phosphate have been\rmeasured in vitamin d-deficient rats and the re-\rsults compared to those observed in d-fed ani-\rmals.  also, the influence of dietary calcium and\rphosphate content upon these responses has been\rinvestigated.  parathyroidectomy in the d-fed ani-\rmal results in a rapid fall in plasma calcium and a\rbiphasic plasma phosphate response with an initial\rfall followed by a striking rise.  in contrast,\rparathyroidectomy in the d-deficient rat is fol-\rlowed by no significant change in plasma calcium\rand an immediate rise in plasma phosphate that\rcan be prevented by the administration of para-\rthyroid hormone.  dietary phosphate restriction\rabolished the effect of parathyroidectomy in both\rgroups of animals.\radministration of a dose of 500 u of hormone\rto the intact d-deficient rat had little influence\rupon plasma calcium; a dose of 2,000 u did in-\rcrease plasma calcium.  a dose of 25 u was suffi-\rcient to increase the plasma calcium of the d-fed\ranimal.  these results are discussed in relation\rto the effects of vitamin d and parathyroid hor-\rmone upon mitochondrial metabolism.\r'),
 (565,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'decrease in serum and urinary phosphorus in man\rin the course of pyrotherapy\rduring the fever\rpeak occurring a few hours after the in-\rjection, urinary phosphorus (up) dis-\rappears entirely.  this fact cannot be\raccounted for by the parallel decrease in\rgfr, because serum phosphorus level\r(sp) does not increase (as it would be\rexpected to, should retention occur) but\ron the contrary, it, too, declines to a\rmarked degree.\rthe possibility that changes in sp and\rup could have been brought about by an\rincreased utilization of glucose was also\rconsidered.  an intravenous glucose toler-\rance test (method of macho and licko\r(8)) was carried out in another group of\rpatients on control days and on days of\rpyrotherapy five hours after the pyrogen\radministration.  an increase in the rate of\r\"glucose utilization\" was observed\r(table 2).  however a different opinion is\rfound in the literature.  in the course of\rglucose tolerance tests, conn (3) and\rcomparini (9) observed a lowered rate of\rglucose utilization in febrile subjects.\rmalizia (10) found an accentuated rate\rof decline of serum phosphorus during\rglucose tolerance tests in subjects with\rhigh temperatures, but the glycemic\rresponses did not differ from those ob-\rtained when controls without fever were\rsubjected to the same tests.  whether it\rbe for utilization purposes or not, the\rfact remains that a massive transfer of\rphosphorus from the serum into the\rtissues takes place in fever.\r'),
 (566,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'relationship of maximal tubular phosphate\rreabsorption to filtration rate in the dog\ra maximal renal tubular rate of reabsorption of phos-\rphate (tmp) has been demonstrated in the normal dog.  in\rthe dog, as in the man, considerable variability in the tmp\roften occurs.  while some of this variability remains unex-\rplained, a direct relationship between glomerular filtration\rrate (gfr) and tmp can be demonstrated when the gfr is\rvaried over a wide range.  this relationship suggests that\rglomerular intermittency may exist in the dog.\r'),
 (567,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'human growth hormone\rclinical measurement, response to hypoglycemia and suppression by\rcorticosteroids\ra standard test of growth-hormone secretory ca-\rpacity, based on radioimmunoassay of plasma growth\rhormone after insulin hypoglycemia, is described.  in\rnormal subjects a standard insulin tolerance test, caus-\ring an average blood glucose drop to 34 per cent of\rresting values, produced a mean rise in growth hor-\rmone to 45.2 millimicrogm. per milliliter at one hour,\rwith a total range of 25 to 70 millimicrogm. per mil-\rliliter.  no response was observed in 5 hypopituitary\rsubjects.\runder comparable hypoglycemic stimulation glu-\rcocorticoid-treated patients showed a marked in-\rhibition of the growth-hormone response, which was\rrelated to dose.  subjects receiving more than 60 mg.\rof cortisol equivalent per day showed a mean plasma\rrise to 6.7 millimicrogm. per milliliter (range, 1.5\rto 13 millimicrogm.).  subjects receiving 20 to 60 mg.\rof cortisol equivalent per day showed a mean rise to\r16.6 millimicrogm. per milliliter (range, 13 to 20\rmillimicrogm.).\rinhibition of human growth hormone was also\raffected by duration of glucocorticoid treatment, be-\ring greater with long-term than with short-term ad-\rministration.\r'),
 (568,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'obesity and plasma levels of insulin and\rgrowth hormone\rstudies of serum levels of glucose, free fatty acids, insulin, and growth\rhormone during prolonged fasting suggest that insulin and growth hormone are\rnot responsible for certain metabolic abnormalities accompanying obesity.\r'),
 (569,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypophysectomy, replacement therapy, and the tolerance of the\reuryhaline killifish, fundulus heteroclitus, to hypotonic media\rhypophysectomized fundulus heteroclitus, as previously reported, survive only a\rfew days after transfer from salt to fresh water.  survival time is the same\rwhen fish are tested 2 weeks or 2 months after hypophysectomy.  gradual\rdilution of the external medium produces failure at an average salinity of\r0.26% (0.67-0.02%).  this salinity is comparable to that causing failure after\rabrupt transfer.  although failure is associated with hypochloremia, daily\rinjections of a balanced salt solution or 0.6% nacl shorten survival.\rdaily injections of teleostean neurohypophysial peptides, arginine vasotocin\r(2.25 and 0.0225 pressor mu per gram) and isotocin (1.32 and 0.026 oxytocic mu\rper gram) do not prolong survival.  an extract of caudal neurosecretory tissue\r(urophysis) from male tilapia mossambica had no beneficial action at doses of\r50 ug per gram every other day.  purified ovine prolactin.  105 mu per gram on\ralternate days, maintained survival of 10 of 11 fish for the duration of the\r28-day test period in fresh water, irrespective of the period of pretreatment\rin salt water.  purified bovine prolactin prolonged survival and 2 of 6 fish\rwere maintained for 28 days.  purified bovine growth hormone was ineffective.\rmonkey growth hormone containing 2 u per milligram of prolactin activity,\radministered at a dose of 20 ug per gram (equivalent to 40 mu per gram\rprolactin activity), prolonged survival.  human growth hormone containing 4 u\rper milligram of prolactin activity, at a dose of 20 ug per gram (equivalent to\r80 ml per gram prolactin activity) also prolonged survival and 4 of 6 fish\rwere maintained for 28 days.\rthe ability of pituitary preparations to protect hypophysectomized\rf. heteroclitus from failure in fresh water appears to be related to their\rprolactin activity and not to their content of neurohypophysial peptides.\rthis suggests that an adenohypophysial hormone resembling mammalian prolactin\ris essential for survival of this fish in hypotonic external media.  carp\rpituitary preparations do not protect hypophysectomized f. heteroclitus\ralthough f. heteroclitus pituitaries are known to be effective.\r'),
 (570,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'resistance to human growth hormone in pituitary dwarfism:\rclinical and immunologic studies\rthirteen pituitary dwarfs have\rbeen treated with human growth hormone\r(hgh), and growth acceleration with doses of\r5-7 mg/week has been observed in all but one\rpatient.  on therapy, this 7 1/2-year-old girl grew\rat a rate of 1.05 cm/month for 7 months.\rthereafter, despite larger doses of growth\rhormone (15 mg/week), growth rate fell to\r0.27 cm/month.  this rate of growth persisted\rafter stopping hgh.  on retreatment on 2\roccasions, acceleration of growth did not\roccur.  antibodies to hgh, absent in her\rserum before treatment, were repeatedly\rdemonstrated in her serum in high concentra-\rtion (hgh binding capacity up to 100 mg/1)\rduring treatment.  comparable titers of anti-\rbody have not been found in any of the 12\rother patients receiving long-term hgh treat-\rment.  the specificity of the human anti-hgh\rserum differed from rabbit anti-hgh serum.\rwhereas both monkey growth hormone\r(mgh) and hgh were effective inhibitors of\rthe binding of hgh-131i by rabbit antiserum,\ronly hgh was an effective inhibitor with\rhuman antiserum.  in like manner, a crude\rplacental extract which was an effective in-\rhibitor for rabbit antiserum was ineffective\rwith human anti-hgh serum.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (571,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'influence of alloxan diabetes on\rgrowth hormone content of the rat hypophysis\rhomog-\renates of adenophypophysial tissue obtained from alloxan-\rinjected adult male rats varying in duration and severity of\rdiabetes, as well as from diabetic rats maintained on an\rinsulin replacement regimen, were assayed in immature\rhypophysectomized female rats.  the ability of these crude\rhypophysial extracts to encourage tibial cartilage width ex-\rpansion gain in body weight, and to depress hematocrit and\rblood area levels was determined.  significant decrements in\rability to increase epiphysial cartilage width and ability to\rdepress hematocrits were noted 14 to 28 days following injection\rof alloxan.  increasing the intensity of the diabetic state was\rassociated with decreased growth-promoting potency of hypo-\rphysial preparations as well as with decreased ability to\rinfluence the hematological indices.  hypophysial extracts taken\rfrom insulin-treated diabetic rats contained more growth\rhormone than equivalent amounts of tissue obtained from\rcontrol rats.  it is concluded that the adenohypophyses of\rdiabetic rats contain diminished amounts of growth hormone\rand the insulin repairs or encourages greater than normal ac-\rcumulation of somatotrophin in these animals.\r'),
 (572,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pheochromocytoma\rwithout hypertension\rthe patient developed symptoms of pheochromo-\rcytoma about 15 years after the diagnosis of\reosinophilic adenoma of the pituitary gland.  the\rpredominating symptoms were profuse sweating\rand tachycardia.  hypertension, hyperglycemia, and\rglycosuria were absent.  the relation of the quan-\rtity and the relative composition of catechol\ramines to the symptomatology is discussed.  some\rspeculation regarding the etiological importance of\rhypersecretion of growth hormone in pheochromo-\rcytoma seems to be in order.\r'),
 (573,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypoglycemia, growth retardation, and probable\risolated growth hormone deficiency in a\r1-year-old child\ra heretofore unreported association of defects, namely hypoglycemia, growth\rretardation, and deficiency of serum growth hormonelike activity in a\r1-year-old child is described.  human growth hormone (hgh), 3 mg. a day for 7\rdays, doubled the fasting blood sugar, prevented the postprandial hypoglycemia,\rand reversed the sensitivity to tolbutamide and leucine.  treatment with 1 mg.\rof hgh 3 times a week produced a growth of 7 inches in 3 months compared to a\rgrowth of 1 inch in the previous 13 months.  since the protein-bound-iodine and\rthe response to methopyrapone were normal and the blood level of growth hormone\rwas low, this case is presented as a probable isolated growth hormone\rdeficiency.\r'),
 (574,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'production, secretion, and availability\rof insulin\ra more precise understanding of the metabolic phase of diabetes mellitus\rrequires reliable information concerning the synthesis, manner of release and\rtransport of insulin, as well as of the behavior of agents which interfere with\rthe actions of the hormone by inhibition or destruction.  we shall deal with a\rvariety of these problems here and it might be helpful at the outset to outline\rfirst our present understanding of the chemical structure of insulin since\rmany useful hints flow out of a consideration of the nature of the molecule.\r'),
 (575,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth and growth retardation\rvarious attempts have been made over the years to define growth.  from\rthe standpoint of this review, growth is the physiological accretion of new\rtissue which is reflected in the acquisition of protein and water.  this\rprocess in almost all instances leads to increase in size (length, weight, and\rvolume) and actively progresses from the fertilization of the ovum to the\rperiod of sexual maturity where millions of cells are present in a state of\radvanced organization.  with further time, growth is less and, indeed, may\rbecome negative insofar as cells are lost.\r'),
 (576,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'long-term treatment of hypopituitary and of\rachondroplastic dwarfism with human\rgrowth hormone\rwe have treated an 8 year old hypopi-\rtuitary dwarf intermittently with hgh\r(wilhelmi) for 4 years.  with 1 mg. 3\rtimes a week the monthly growth rate\rwas 1/4 inch.  as treatment continued he\rbecame resistant.  increasing the dosage\rto 3 mg. 3 times a week at the age of 12\rinduced a monthly growth rate of 2/5\rinch.  this growth-promoting effect is at\rleast as great as that reported for the\rli and raben preparations.  we have\ralso treated a 15 year old severely de-\rformed \'achondroplastic\' dwarf for a\ryear.  with 3 mg. 3 times a week he\rgrew 1/2 inch in the first month.  the\rspurt in growth subsided.  with 5 mg.\r3 times a week he grew another 1/2 inch\rin a month, but growth was not main-\rtained.\r'),
 (577,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acromegaly\rthe effects of various steroid hormones on the\rinsulin-induced growth hormone response\rand peter h. forsham\rthe availability of a sensitive assay for human growth hormone has made\rit possible to directly measure the effects of various agents purported to\ralter growth patterns.  acromegalic patients present a special problem both in\rearly diagnosis and in therapy.  being able to measure growth hormone in\rthese patients provides an accurate index of activity and a precise measure\rof therapeutic effectiveness.\rin an attempt to determine whether a pituitary block of growth hormone\rsecretion is feasible in this condition, a study was made of the effects of\restrogen, androgen and glucocorticoid administration on growth hormone\rresponse to a standard insulin tolerance test in a patient with active acro-\rmegaly.  in the dosage schedules used in this study, it was not possible to\rsuppress either basal growth hormone secretion or blunt its responsiveness\rto the normal physiologic stimulus of hypoglycemia.\r'),
 (578,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'practical human growth hormone\rpreparation and clinical use\rhuman growth hormone was prepared from\racetone-dried pituitary powder by hot glacial\racetic acid extraction and subsequent precipita-\rtion by sodium chloride and cold acetone.  the\ryield was 13 per cent and the preparation was\rcalled practical growth hormone in recognition\rof its complement of corticotropin.\rtreatment of two dwarfs with practical growth\rhormone in aqueous solution, 1 or 2 mg intra-\rmuscularly on alternate days, accelerated the\rgrowth rate and there were no physical signs or\rlaboratory indications of adrenal stimulation or\rother adverse effects.  the preparation is recom-\rmended for its safety, simplicity and relatively\rgood yield.\r'),
 (579,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypophysectomy and the lipolytic action of epinephrine in vitro\rthe response of normal adipose\rtissue to epinephrine (0.05 ug/ml incubation\rmedium) is completely abolished by hypo-\rphysectomy of the donor rats.  treatment of\rhypophysectomized rats with crude, whole\rrat pituitary extract restored the lipolytic ac-\rtion of epinephrine to normal.  posterior pi-\rtuitary extract and corticotropin replacement\rwas without effect.  thyrotropin injections\rproduced a partial, and growth hormone\rtreatment a full restoration of the lipolytic\raction of epinephrine.  treatment of hypo-\rphysectomized rats with cortisol or cortico-\rsterone reestablished the sensitivity of their\radipose tissue to epinephrine, but only when\rrelatively large doses of these hormones were\rgiven.  physiological doses of triiodothyronine\r(1 ug/rat/day), however, restored the nor-\rmal response to epinephrine.  it is concluded\rthat several endocrine factors can influence\rthe lipolytic action of epinephrine but that\rtheir physiological importance cannot yet be\rquantitated.\r'),
 (580,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'c-acetyl bovine growth hormone\ra procedure is described for labeling bovine growth hormone\rand human albumin with c-acetylation.  the labeled molecule\rwas biologically and antigenically similar to unlabeled bovine\rgrowth hormone.  following administration of the labeled\rhormone to animals, the label appeared to remain attached to\rthe growth hormone molecule for at least 4 hours.  administra-\rtion of the labeled hormone promoted growth in hypophysec-\rtomized rats and increased the free fatty acid concentration\rin rabbit serum to a degree comparable with that seen following\radministration of unlabeled growth hormone.  rabbit anti-\rbovine growth hormone serum neutralized the rat growth\rresponse to the acetylated hormone, and immunized rabbits\rhad altered isotope dilution and no increase in serum free fatty\racids after intravenous injection of the labeled hormone.\r'),
 (581,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth hormone\rgrowth hormone influences protein, fat,\rcarbohydrate, and mineral metabolism.  it\rpromotes nitrogen retention, growth of\rcartilage, transportation of amino acids\rthrough the cell wall, and incorporation of\ramino acids into protein.  this factor mo-\rbilizes free fatty acids from adipose tissue\rand increases the serum concentration of\rthese substances; long-term administration\rof this hormone is followed by depletion of\rbody fat stores and inhibition of fatty acid\rsynthesis.  in diabetic subjects growth hor-\rmone administration is followed by hyper-\rglycemia, glycosuria, and ketosis; its effect\ron carbohydrate metabolism in normal sub-\rjects is more subtle.  sodium, potassium, and\rinorganic phosphate are retained following\rthe administration of growth hormone.\rhypercalciuria also accompanies such treat-\rment, an effect mediated through the para-\rthyroid glands.\rhuman growth hormone may be detected\rin the serum through the use of the radio-\rimmunoassay.  the hypothalamus is inti-\rmately involved with the control of the\rsecretion and release of growth hormone\rfrom the pituitary.  there is a correlation\rbetween the availability of glucose for me-\rtabolism and the plasma concentration of\rgrowth hormone; when glucose is unavail-\rable growth hormone is released in order to\rprovide a substitute source of energy, fatty\racids.\rthe administration of growth hormone\rto the patient with hypopituitarism is fol-\rlowed by growth in many instances, but it\rhas not usually been effective in promoting\rgrowth in individuals with other abnormali-\rties.  acquired resistance to the effect of\rgrowth hormone is accompanied by the de-\rvelopment of antibodies directed against\rthis protein.\r'),
 (582,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recent advances in physiology of bone: part i\rour introductory textbook summarizes knowledge of the biochemistry and\rphysiology of bone and calcium metabolism up through 1960.  in this lecture,\rwe will outline a few important advances appearing since that time.  references\rto the original literature need not be repeated here.  the\robject is to bring some of the subjects we are investigating up-to-date and\rto present new problems for laboratory research.  the hypothetical new hormone,\rcalcitonin, of copp and cameron will be discussed in detail in dr. mclean\'s\rlecture on the parathyroid glands and bone.\r'),
 (583,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hyperplastic lesions of mouse mammary\rglands after treatment with 3-methyl-\rcholanthrene\rhyperplastic lesions were present in the mammary glands of\rmice treated with 3-methylcholanthrene and exogenous hormones.  the\rlesions were similar to those found in glands that were exposed to mammary\rtumor virus.  it is probable that the production of mammary gland hyper-\rplastic lesions could serve as a measure of the effectiveness of a chemical\rcompound as a carcinogenic agent for the mammary gland.\r'),
 (584,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bone growth and metabolic studies of premature\rinfants treated with human growth hormone\rthe influence of exogenous human\rgrowth hormone on growth and metabo-\rlism of premature infants was observed.\rit was not possible to register any in-\rcrease of linear bone growth after hormone\radministration; concomitantly urinary hy-\rdroxyproline excretion did not change\rsignificantly.\rnitrogen balance studies indicated a\rsharp increase of nitrogen retention, due to\ra reduced urinary excretion, in all infants.\rcalcium and phosphorus balances rose in\rthree out of four premature infants treated\rwith growth hormone, but the characteris-\rtic sth calciuric action of sth was not\robserved.  furthermore, sth failed to in-\rduce any significant increase in nefa\rserum concentration of premature infants.\rit may therefore be concluded that the\rmetabolic response of premature infants to\rsth differs consistently from that normally\robserved in more mature subjects.\r'),
 (585,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth hormone action on rat liver rna\rpolymerase\rthe effect of growth hormone on the activity of the\rrna polymerase measured in this system is shown in\rtable 2.  it can be seen that hypophysectomy of the rat\rresults in decreased activity of the rna polymerase and\rthat the injection of 1 mg of human growth hormone into\rthe rat 12 h before death increased the enzyme activity\rboth in hypophysectomized rats and in normal rats.\rhowever, the stimulating effect of growth hormone was\ronly seen in the absence of high concentrations of ammon-\rium sulphate; raising the ionic strength of the assay\rmedium abolished the growth hormone effect.  it should be\rmentioned that addition of growth hormone in vitro in the\rpresence or absence of ammonium sulphate has had no\rsignificant effect on the labelling of the rna by the\rnuclear preparations.\r'),
 (586,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mammary growth in rats treated with somatotropin during\rpregnancy and/or lactation\rgroups of rats received daily\rinjections of 2 mg somatotropin (sth) from\reither day 3-19 of pregnancy or day 1-13\rof lactation.  another group of rats received\rgraded increments (0.5-3.0 mg) of sth\revery 6 days during both pregnancy and\rlactation.  other groups of rats served as\rpregnancy and lactation controls.  mammary\rgland deoxyribonucleic acid (dna) content\rwas determined in all rats and milk yield\rwas determined in all rats carried to day\r14 postpartum.  significant increases in mam-\rmary dna occurred in all rats treated with\rsth irrespective of dose or schedule of in-\rjections when compared to gestation controls.\ra significant elevation in mammary dna\rabove the lactation control level was also\revident in rats receiving the hormone and\rcarried to day 14 of lactation.  milk yield\rof rats treated with graded increments of\rsth was significantly greater than that of\rcontrol lactators but milk yield of rats re-\rceiving a constant daily dose of the hormone\rdid not differ from that of controls.\r'),
 (587,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth retardation accompanying diabetes insipidus: an additional\rmechanism?\rfrom the above considerations, we may divide patients with nephrogenic\rdiabetes insipidus into at least two categories: (1) those who fail to respond\rto currently available therapeutic products as well as to their own presumably\rnormal secretion of adh; (2) those with similar similar unresponsiveness to\rtreatment but with presumably reduced secretion of adh.  the adh-growth hormone\rtheory may well account in part for growth retardation in the later group.\r'),
 (588,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on growth hormone secretion\rin rats with the hypophysis autotransplanted\rto the kidney capsule\rthe secretory capacity of the pituitary gland, autotransplanted to the\rkidney capsule, was studied with special regard to the secretion of growth\rhormone (gh).  body weight, body length, tibial epiphyseal width and\rthe mammary gland development after testosterone stimulation were\rstudied.\rbody growth and tibial epiphyseal width were markedly reduced in the\rrats with transplanted hypophysis, but not as much as in the hypophys-\rectomized controls.  after injections of 0.25 mg testosterone propionate\rdaily for 10 days, only a few groups of alveoli were seen in the mam-\rmary glands of the transplanted rats.  these observations show that there\ris a considerable deficiency of gh in rats with the pituitary gland auto-\rtransplanted to the kidney capsule.  however, the development of a few\ralveoli in the mammary glands is in favour of the theory that a small\ramount of gh is secreted from the transplanted pituitary tissue.\rinjections of a purified vasopressin preparation (pitressin) in the rats\rwith autotransplanted hypophysis did not influence body growth, tibial\repiphyseal width or mammary gland development.  further, no effect of\rpitressin was seen on the tibial epiphyseal cartilage of rats with intact\rpituitary gland as has been reported by del vecchio et al. (1958) and\rhiroshige & itoh (1960).  these experiments therefore do not support the\rview that vasopressin acts as a gh releasing factor.\r'),
 (589,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of human growth hormone in\rhypopituitary dwarfism\rhuman growth hormone (hgh) raben has been\rused in a dosage of 2 mg./m.2/day or 5 mg./m.2 twice\rweekly.  this dosage is probably in or below, but\rcertainly not above, the range of physiological\rreplacement therapy.\rin a standardized five-day metabolic hgh test\rhypopituitary dwarfs retain more n than children\rwithout gh deficiency.  this test is valuable\rdiagnostic help in hypopituitary dwarfism.\ra prolonged treatment with hgh accelerates\rgrowth in hypopituitary dwarfs but not in children\rwithout gh deficiency.  growth rate, induced by\rthis treatment, is first above average and later average\ror below average for age.  this decreasing response\rto hgh is typical for the general phenomenon of\rcatch-up growth and is not caused by the develop-\rment of antibodies.\rof 9 hypopituitary dwarfs, treated for at least 9\rmonths, 3 were growth resistant from the beginning\rin spite of a high n retention in the preceding hgh\rtest.  this resistance is caused by the development\rof high titres of specific hgh antibodies in the very\rfirst few months of treatment.  these antibodies\rsuppress the effect of hgh both on metabolism and\ron growth.  the unexpected occasional induction in\rman of antibodies against a homologous protein\rhormone is of great interest.  the possibility that\rthese antibodies might be active not only against the\rhomogenous but also against the endogenous hormone\rcould have a far-reaching biological importance.\r'),
 (590,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of short term administration of\rhysiological doses of human growth hormone\rin three patients with turner\'s syndrome\rh. e. sjoberg\rthe effect of apparently physiological doses of human growth hormone\rwas investigated in three patients with turner\'s syndrome in short term\rmetabolic balance studies.  the subjects presented an abnormal sex chro-\rmosome constitution and an increased level of sulphation factor activity\rin serum.\rtwo dose levels of hormone were used, and there appeared an anabolic\rresponse to both.  no correlation with dose was obtained for any of the\rparameters used except for urinary magnesium, where the retention was\rgreater with the higher dose.  the sulphation factor activity of serum in-\rcreased during hormone administration in the one case studied in this\rrespect.\rthe urinary excretion of hydroxyproline was within the normal range in\rthe two patients studied in this respect, and was not altered by growth\rhormone.\rall patients had an increased urinary excretion of creatine which at\rpresent cannot be explained.  the creatinuria diminished during growth\rhormone treatment.\rthe mechanism behind the retarded growth is discussed.  it is suggested\rthat a major factor might be a defect in the center for linear growth,\ri.e. the epiphyses that would make these less responsive to all the factors\rnormally stimulating the growth processes in the epiphyseal zones.\r'),
 (591,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of growth hormone\ron kidney transamidinase in the\rhypophysectomized mouse\rthe role of growth hormone and certain other endocrine factors in re-\rgulating kidney transamidinase has been investigated in the mouse.  the\rkidney transamidinase values are low following hypophysectomy.  growth\rhormone administration in doses of 0.5 to 5.0 ug/day (ovine nih) restore\rthe enzyme activity towards normal.  a bioassay for growth hormone is\rsuggested based on the determination of the total kidney transamidinase.\rintact mice that had been given relatively large doses of triiodothyronin\rhad low enzyme activities.  enzyme values in alloxan-treated mice were\rnormal.\r'),
 (592,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'influence of hormones on tumor growth and plasma prolactin levels in rats\rbearing a pituitary \"mammotropic\" tumor\rthe effects of estradiol, cortisol acetate, thyroxine, or thiouracil on\rtumor growth, organ weights, and plasma prolactin levels were determined\rin rats bearing a furth pituitary \"mammotropic\" tumor (mtt.f4).  this\rtumor is known to secrete large amounts of adrenocorticotropin, somatotropin,\rand prolactin, but no follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone,\ror thyrotropin.  at the dose levels used, estradiol significantly suppressed\rtumor growth without influencing body growth, and it partially inhibited\renlargement of the adrenals and atrophy of the thymus.  cortisol acetate\rsignificantly reduced both tumor and body growth.  thyroxine had no significant\reffect on tumor growth but enhanced the somatotropic effect as indicated by\rincreases in body growth and organ weights.  thiouracil had no significant\reffect on tumor or body growth, although it significantly increased thyroid\rweight.  estradiol, cortisol acetate, and thyroxine each increased the plasma\rprolactin levels of the tumor-bearing rats.\r'),
 (593,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies with human growth hormone\rten dwarfed patients whose short stature was of\rvarying aetiology were studied by investigation of\rsome of the metabolic effects of human growth\rhormone, 10 mg. being administered daily for a\rperiod of 5 to 9 days.  the patients were maintained\ron a constant diet during a preliminary control\rperiod, while receiving hgh, and in 7 patients from\r2 to 7 days in the post-hgh period.  hgh produced\ra reduction in serum cholesterol, with a\rrebound on withdrawal, in 7; a delayed clearance of\rfat from the blood after a fat load in 9; and the\rappearance of pre-b lipoprotein in the fasting state,\ras measured by paper electrophoresis, in all of them.\rthe fall in serum cholesterol and the rebound on\rwithdrawal of hgh has some relevance to the\robservation that hypercholesterolaemia occurs in\rsome hypopituitary patients even in the absence of\rhypothyroidism.\rno change was observed in tests of thyroid and\radrenocortical function during the short-term high\rdosage administration of hgh.\rhypopituitary patients show a considerable\rretention of nitrogen on hgh administration, and\rwe have confirmed the work of prader and his\rcolleagues that this provides a valuable diagnostic\rtest for growth hormone deficiency.  the measurement\rof urinary nitrogen excretion after the withdrawal\rof hgh also promises to be a useful investigation\rin the differential diagnosis of short stature.\rnitrogen excretion in the withdrawal phase in\rhypopituitary children returns slowly to its pre-hgh\rlevels; two non-hypopituitary dwarfed\rchildren excreted much more nitrogen in the withdrawal\rperiod than they retained in the hgh\rperiod.  one primordial dwarf showed a negligible\rchange in urinary nitrogen excretion both in the\rhgh and in the post-hgh periods.\r'),
 (594,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hormonal modification of the distribution of 1-amino-\rcyclopentanecarboxylic acid-1-c14 in the rat\rfour hormones have been examined for their ability to alter the distribution\rin the rat of the new model amino acid,\r1-aminocyclopentanecarboxylic acid-1-c14.  although\rthe total tissue concentrations of this\ramino acid were considerably less than those\rfound previously for a-aminoisobutyric acid,\rthe changes produced by the hormones were\rmuch the same for both amino acids.  hydrocortisone\relevated the liver level of 1-aminocyclopentanecarboxylic\racid within 2 hr.\rbovine growth hormone accelerated entry of\rthe amino acid into both skeletal muscle and\rliver of hypophysectomized rats within 1 hr.\rtestosterone propionate elevated its distribution\rratio in the kidney but not in skeletal\rmuscle, whereas b-estradiol significantly increased\ruptake of the model amino acid only\rby the immature uterus.  only growth hormone\rproduced a significant change in the serum\rlevel of 1-aminocyclopentanecarboxylic acid\runder the conditions used.\r'),
 (595,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'insulin and insulin antagonism\ras i said earlier, no simple answer\rhas yet emerged from the large amount of\rresearch that has been directed toward determining\rthe nature of the substance or substances\rresponsible for the diabetes-inducing\rand insulin-antagonizing actions of the\ranterior lobe of the pituitary gland, and to\rascertaining their mechanism of action.\rgrowth hormone and corticotropin certainly\rqualify, but so do any other factors that can increase the mobilization of fats\ras plasma albumin-bound free fatty acids.  the idea\rthat the yet incompletely characterized insulin\rantagonist in the pancreas may be\rliberated into the blood under the influence\rof growth hormone and may play a role in\rthe process by which growth hormone diminishes\rthe activity of insulin in promoting\rthe utilization of glucose is attractive to me,\rbut still remains to be confirmed.\r'),
 (596,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'relationships of growth hormone, steroids and relaxin in the\rtransformation of pubic joint cartilage to ligament in\rhypophysectomized mice\rthe histological changes occurring\rin the pubic joint of hormonally\rtreated intact or hypophysectomized mice\rhave been studied.  estrogen treatment resulted\rin bone resorption and transformation\rof the cartilage caps of the pubic bones to\rfibrocartilage in intact mice but not in hypophysectomized\rmice.  furthermore, relaxin\rfailed to influence the appearance of the pubic\rjoint of estrogen-primed hypophysectomized\rmice, whereas it induced the development of\rlong interpubic ligaments in intact mice.\rwhen growth hormone (sth) was administered\rto hypophysectomized mice, the pubic\rjoints responded to estrogen with bone resorption\rand transformation of the cartilage caps\rto fibrocartilage.  sth treatment also restored\rthe ability of the pubic joint of hypophysectomized\rmice to proliferate long interpubic ligaments\rwhen estrogen and relaxin were administered.\rprogesterone specifically inhibited\rligament formation due to relaxin injection\rwithout altering the histological changes\rassociated with estrogen treatment, both in\rintact mice and in sth-maintained, hypophysectomized mice.\r'),
 (597,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of testosterone propionate and growth hormone on\rgrowth and chemical composition of muscle and other\rtissues in hypophysectomized male rats\rthe effect of testosterone\rpropionate and growth hormone on the\rgrowth of muscle, bone, pelt, viscera and\rseminal vesicles was studied in hypophysectomized\rmale rats.  testosterone (0.1 mg/day)\rstimulated growth in the levator ani muscle\rand seminal vesicles but had no effect on the\rother tissues studied.  growth hormone (0.1\rmg/day) accelerated growth in all tissues\rexcept the seminal vesicles.  testosterone did\rnot enhance the growth-promoting effect of\rgrowth hormone in any tissue except the\rlevator ani muscle.  growth hormone stimulated\rdeposition of myosin, sarcoplasmic\rproteins, collagen and alkali-soluble proteins\rin the thigh muscle of hypophysectomized\rrats.  the composition of the muscle in treated\rand control hypophysectomized rats was the\rsame as that in normal rats.  growth hormone\ralso increased the collagen, keratin-clastin\rand globular protein content of the pelt.  the\reffect of growth hormone on the proteins of\rmuscle and pelt was not enhanced by testosterone.\rtestosterone given alone had no effect\ron the chemical composition or content of the\rmuscle and pelt in hypophysectomized rats.\r'),
 (598,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth hormone and diabetes mellitus\rsince the advent of insulin the vascular and neurological\rlesions have replaced ketoacidosis as the major\rproblem in diabetes.  although good control of hyperglycemia\rand glycosuria with diet and insulin may\rinfluence favorably the development of the ocular angiopathy,\rthere remains a high incidence of these\rlesions with resulting blindness despite such good\rcontrol.\rgrowth hormone may be a major factor in the\rpathophysiology of diabetes mellitus and its effects\rmay be a reflection of the genetic disturbance.  its importance\rwas first realized by the classical experiments\rof houssay and those of young which revealed its\rdiabetogenic effects in experimental animals.  the association\rof acromegaly with diabetes has been for a\rlong time the major argument in support of the hypothesis\rof the diabetogenic effect of growth hormone\rin man.\r'),
 (599,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experiments on the contribution of somatotrophin to prenatal growth in the rat\rhypophyseoprivus in a fetal rat induced by decapitating the fetus in utero\rretards fetal growth.  this effect can be prevented by injected somatotrophin.\rthese observations substantially support the view that in the normal rat\rshortly before birth the fetal somatotrophin from the developing hypophysis\rgoverns in part the prenatal growth which occurs at that time.  although\rcomplete hypophysectomy of a pregnant rat retards\rthe growth of fetuses, the manner\rof its action is obscure.  in an individual litter, combined hypophysectomy\rof the mother and hypophyseoprivus in a fetus retards fetal growth but not\rto any greater extent than hypophysectomy of the mother without\rhypophyseoprivus in the fetus.  in the intact fetus injections of somatotrophin\r(armour) do not accelerate fetal growth, presumably because ample fetal\rsomatotrophin from the developing hypophysis is present.\r'),
 (600,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'insulin and protein metabolism\rthe present status of protein synthesis within cells has\rbeen outlined.  protein is formed in the absence of insulin;\rthe net formation of protein is accelerated by insulin.  the\reffects of insulin on protein metabolism take place independently\rof the transport of glucose or amino acids into the\rcell; of glycogen synthesis; and of the stimulation of high\renergy phosphate formation.  in the case of protein metabolism,\ras in certain studies on the pathways of glucose and\rfat metabolism, these observations reveal striking intracellular\reffects of insulin in many tissues.  within most\rtissues the effect of insulin appears to find expression predominantly\rat the microsomal level.  incidentally, other\rhormones which affect protein metabolism such as growth\ror sex hormones appear to act at the microsomes.  the fact\rthat insulin exerts effects on protein metabolism at other\rintracellular sites as well as the above independent effects\rleads one to agree that its action consists of a stimulation\rof multiple, seemingly unrelated, metabolic events.\rthe fact that an immediate effect of insulin on protein\rsynthesis is independent of the immediate need for extracellular\rglucose or amino acids does not mean that the\rsustained functioning of cells is likewise independent.  the\rbiochemist is fully aware of metabolic defects in diabetes\rwhich are not altered by insulin in vitro, but which demand\rvarying periods of pretreatment of the animal.  it is\ralso known that in diabetes some proteins (enzymes) may\rbe deficient while others may be produced in excess in the\rabsence of insulin.\rit is suggested that the physician desires at least two\rkinds of relation between these fundamental studies and his\rpatients.  one is the possible relation of a deficiency of insulin\raction to pathological processes in tissues which have\rnot as yet been examined by the methods described.  the\rother is the need for more accurate measurements of the\rmetabolic disorder and its control than such things as\rurinary and blood glucose.  in developing such future improvements,\rthe place of insulin in protein biosynthesis\rmust be kept in mind.\r'),
 (601,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the influence of blood glucose on the plasma\rconcentration of growth hormone\ra. berson, m.d.\ra sensitive and specific assay method has been used to\rdemonstrate acute changes in plasma hgh in normal and diabetic subjects.\rhgh secretion is suppressed by glucose administration\rand markedly stimulated by hypoglycemia, by interference\rwith intracellular glucose utilization.  high levels of hgh\rwere also observed during prolonged fasting, after exercise,\rand four to six hours following oral glucose administration.\rabnormalities in hgh secretion were found in association\rwith acromegaly and obesity, and following section of the\rhypophyseal stalk.\rthe half time for disappearance of endogenous plasma\rhgh is twenty to thirty minutes.\r'),
 (602,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'failure to thrive: the diencephalic syndrome of infancy and childhood\rwe have presented a case of a patient with an\rastrocytoma of the optic chiasm who demonstrated\rthe features of the \"diencephalic\" or\r\"failure-to-thrive\" syndrome.  overactivity, overalertness\rand emaciation were significant symptoms\rin this patient.  roentgenograms characteristically\rdemonstrate normal bone growth,\rgood muscular outline, and absent subcutaneous\rfat.  increased growth hormone was found and\rmay be a factor in the disturbed lipid metabolism.\r'),
 (603,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'increased stature\rthe fact that some patients respond to growth-hormone\radministration with linear growth does not indicate growth-hormone\rdeficiency or hypopituitarism.  yet this appears to\rbe the main factor that led these authors to assume that\rtheir patients were suffering from hypopituitarism.  the\rconclusion that children with growth retardation should be\rsubjected to a short trial period of treatment with growth\rhormone to single out those who are deficient in growth hormone\ris therefore of questionable validity.\rrather, because of the limited supply of human growth\rhormone, it appears that much more stringent criteria for\radministration of human growth hormone should be advocated.\revery effort should be made to uncover the patients\rwho might benefit from growth hormone by utilizing reliable\rtests of pituitary function and perfecting a suitable growth-hormone\rassay.  those who have more than suggestive evidence\rof hypopituitarism and growth-hormone deficiency\rshould then be treated and carefully evaluated for response\rafter long-term treatment.\r'),
 (604,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on language disorders in young children: a reorganization of thinking\rcurrent questions and confusions about\rthe use of the term aphasia with reference\rto young children seem often to\rreflect semantic problems accruing\rfrom professional habits of thinking in\rterms of etiologic and pathologic labels.\rit is argued that if the term aphasia is\rgeneralized simply to refer to inabilities\ror interferences in the development of\rlanguage comprehension and use, then\rit is the task of an evaluating group to\rdescribe as well as possible, and in detail,\rthe specific impairments of function\rin each child.  this task commonly\rrequires the use of an extensive period\rof \"diagnostic teaching,\" wherein care\ris taken to explore which sensory and\rmotor modalities are working and\rwhich are not, and whether integration\rof various stimuli is taking place.\rsome current ideas are discussed with\rreference to descriptions of impairment,\rcausal factors that are fairly unique in\rchildhood, some thoughts about the\rneurophysiology of the human \"language\rsystem,\" and some psychosocial\rfactors important for language-learning.\rspecial attention is given to various relations,\rin terms of temporal resolving\rpower, between sensation and sensory\rintegration.  a scheme, or model, is suggested\rwhich may prove fruitful for\rexperimental design in attacking some\rof these problems at a prelanguage or\rpremeaning level.  it is argued that the\rproportion of \"unknowns\" can be reduced\rby careful study based on information\rabout impaired functions within the sensory-integrative-motor complex,\rwithout particular regard for \"site and\rextent of lesion.\"\r'),
 (605,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'therapy for hearing-impaired children\rin comparison with the u.s.a. and\reurope, canada is still in the early\rstages of developing rehabilitative services\rfor speech and hearing-impaired\rchildren and adults.  they are available\rin some large canadian cities, but in\rthe opinion of the authors, these services\rand more should be made available\rto the hearing impaired of every canadian community.\rspecialists in the rehabilitation of\rcommunication problems, along with\rmembers of other medical, paramedical and social services, recognize\rthe vast variety of communication\rproblems that can occur in persons\rof all ages, the tremendous handicap\rthat such problems represent to the\rindividual, the loss that such handicapped\rpersons represent to our society\rand the pressing need for efficient and\reffective rehabilitation.  more practically,\rit is hoped that this article has\rmade its readers more aware of the\rvast variety of rehabilitative procedures\ravailable today for the hearing\rimpaired.  with a better understanding\rof the problems of defective hearing,\rit is hoped that all readers, professional\rand non-professional, will join\rin mutual support for the establishment\rof these vitally needed services\rin their respective communities.\r'),
 (606,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'baby habits, genesis and ontogenesis\rfor adam may be looked upon\ras the personification of paleolithic\rman-100,000 generations of primitive\rhuman animal-whose evolution\rcan be of vast importance to\rthe understanding of the ontogenesis\rof the behavior of babies.  not\rfor nothing did the deuteronomist\rreiterate \"remember the days of\rold, consider the years of many generations\"\r'),
 (607,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'speech therapy with selected patients with\rcongenital velopharyngeal inadequacy\rthis paper has described the clinical speech problems of three patients\rwithout cleft palates but with velopharyngeal inadequacy.  pharyngeal\rflap surgery was performed on each patient after speech therapy was\rfound to be ineffective following systematic trial.  therapy continued\rfollowing the surgery.  the youngest child, a first grader, realized normal\rspeech following the surgery and therapy.  the two other children continue\rto have aberrant but improved speech.\r'),
 (608,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stimulus overload, action cycles, and the completion gradient\rsystematic inquiries into the origin of certain emotional disturbances\rof infants show that consistent maternal care is vital for the\rchild\'s normal physical, psychic, and social development, indeed,\rfor his survival.  the most elementary precondition for consistent\rmaternal care is the physical presence of the mother or her substitute.\rit has, however, become increasingly apparent that children\'s\rdevelopment can also be stunted, and that they suffer damage of\rvarying extent by the attention of, and close contact with, a mother\rwho dispenses what seems to be the \"wrong kind of mothering\".\ra model of the mother-baby interaction is proposed to explicate\rthe dynamics of the \"wrong kind of mothering\" and its\rconsequences: my proposition is that the mutual exchanges between\rmother and baby consist in a give and take of action and\rreaction between the two partners, which requires from each\rof them both active and passive responses.  these responses form\rseries and chains, the single links of which consist in what i call\r\"action cycles,\" each completed in itself and at the same time\ranticipating the next link.  i designated these seriated response\rexchanges as the \"precursor of dialogue,\" as a primal dialogue.\rthe dialogue acts as a vector of the baby\'s development,\rinfluencing its direction and stimulating it to adaptive efforts and\rpsychic growth.  it follows that inappropriate mothering (quantitatively\ras well as qualitatively) results in what is referred to at\rthis time as the \"derailment\" of the primal dialogue.\rcontrolled experiments with animals, findings of experimental\rpsychology, and, lastly, clinical findings illustrate the\rmechanics of the derailed dialogue and its sequelae.\rin the cases under review a surfeit of stimulation, a psychic\roverloading, resulted in the derailment of dialogue.  overloading\rprevents its subject from completing actions or responses initiated\rby him.  long-lasting overload results in the cumulation of \"incompleted\raction cycles\".  the sequelae of this cumulation are\rprofound changes in the behavior of the individual.  these changes\rare manifested in a departure from the norms of individual and\rsocial behavior patterns that are maladaptive for the individual\rand asyntonic with his society, that is, asocial.\rthe derailment of the dialogue is triggered, perhaps even\rcaused,\rby the nature of the social setting.  one setting, over-population,\ris extensively discussed in connection with an animal\rexperiment, and the implications for the human community are\rexamined.\r'),
 (609,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'children at kelbourne\rkelbourne school, glasgow, which educates both\rspastic and aphasic children, is the first school of its\rkind to be administered by a local education authority.\rits aphasic department, largely experimental in nature,\rcontains children aged three to eight.  in the spastics\rdepartment there are 45 children with severe physical\rhandicaps and their ages range from 3 to 16.\rthe school, which celebrated its golden jubilee last year,\rhas its origins in the maryhill hall public school for\rdefective and epileptic children which opened in 1907\rwith 12 pupils in premises of which, as an h.m.i. reported\rfour years later, \'it was impossible to speak favourably\'.\rthe report continued, \'a public hall, used frequently in\rthe evenings for public entertainments, lacking proper\rcloakrooms, bare in appearance, and generally comfortless,\rshould not be used for this purpose\'.  the inspector\'s\rwords did not go unheeded and seven years later the\rchildren were transferred with others to the new buildings\rof percy street special school.  in the 1950s the name was\rchanged to kelbourne school.\rbetween and through two world wars the school\rprovided education for physically and mentally handicapped\rchildren but in 1955 a new unit was added and\rspastic children were admitted for the first time.\rgradually the emphasis shifted from children with other\rphysical and mental handicaps to the cerebrally palsied\rand finally the entire building became available for\rspastics.  two years ago the aphasic children joined the\rschool.  miss e.f. hamilton is the headmistress.\r'),
 (610,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'deafness\rmethods of detection, diagnosis, and management of deafness\rin children depend so entirely on a knowledge of the processes\rinvolved in communication by speech and in the acquisition of\rthis skill that i propose to consider them first.  it will be found\rthat the practical steps to be taken in dealing with patients flow\rnaturally from this knowledge.\r'),
 (611,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pharyngoplasty in speech\rwhere adequate palate repair is undertaken at 1 year there is no indication\rfor pharyngoplasty as well at that age.\rpharyngoplasty is indicated as a \"supportive\" operation only when the\rresult of the palate repair can be assessed (5 years plus), and where the\rspeech result proves disappointing.\rthe figure of 171 pharyngoplastics in 944 cases applies to the known speech\rresults up to april 1963.  it follows that with follow-up of the more recent\rprimary cases pharyngoplasty may well be necessary in some.\rthe hynes pharyngoplasty has proved to be the most satisfactory.\r'),
 (612,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'verbal effects in the intermediate-size transportation problem\rpreschool children were given an intermediate-size discrimination problem,\rtold before each response that the reward was under the \"medium\" stimulus:\rand 1- and 3-step transposition tests.  during training, group i was\rgroup ii was told that it was \"not under the big or little one\"; and group\riii was not told anything.  the verbalizations were not given during the\rtests.  groups i and ii learned the initial discrimination faster than group\riii, and transposed more than group iii, but there was a distance effect\rin all three groups.  these results, and other data, suggest that the\rdeficiency in the verbal control over motor behavior in young children arises\rfrom deficiencies in both the decoding and encoding processes.\r'),
 (613,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the acquisition of formal features of language\rchildren from different groups do not learn the same uses and functions for\rlanguage.  but every child must learn the formal features, or the \"code\" for\rhis language, thus creating a constant in every language acquisition situation.\r'),
 (614,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mongolism-some clinical aspects\rthis is a review of 86 mongoloids seen over 5 years at the nebraska psychiatric\rinstitute.  one-half of the sample were evaluated before their second\rbirthday.  eighteen per cent of the cases for whom birth weight data were\ravailable weighed less than 5 1/2 lbs., double the national rate for\rprematurity.  there was a bi-modal distribution of mother\'s age at the birth of\rthe mongoloid child.  pregnancy, labor and delivery complications were\rreported in almost one-half of the cases.  seven per cent were breech\rdeliveries.  all cases were mr.  the most frequent type was moderate.  most\rfrequently mentioned characteristics were: generalized hypotonia (all but 2\rcases); psychiatric disorders, 11 cases; abnormal eeg, 8 cases; hearing loss,\r5 cases.\r'),
 (615,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'learning problems in children: ii. emotional aspects\rat the last meeting we tried to deal with a general over-all approach\rto the problem of learning, considering it not merely as a problem in\rreading, but learning in general which begins at birth.\rwe hope to deal with this problem at a relatively high level and we\rwant to have the emotional problems dealt with in this manner rather\rthan in terms of diagnostic criteria.  the child with learning problems\rshould not be compartmentalized in terms of \"organicity\" and \"nonorganicity\".\rthe subject of this talk, then, is emotional issues in learning.\r'),
 (616,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'management of communication problems in infants and children\rearly detection and referral of a\rchild with a hearing or speech-language problem\ris feasible and in most cases, very critical.  further\rconsultation can then be obtained and the child\rplaced on a training program geared to his needs.\r'),
 (617,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the formation of a cleft palate unit- a preliminary report\rwith cleft palates, as in other surgical fields, changing\rtechniques and better management of the patient as a whole\rrender inexcusable the operative procedures that merely\rdrag together the edges of the defect and then leave a\rcosmetically and functionally crippled child, to adapt itself\ras best it may to the harsh competition of the outside\rworld.\rironically the problem of congenital defects increases as\rour competence to deal with them advances.  in the past\rthese cases struggled to take their place on the marriage\rmarket but the more skilled our rehabilitative procedures\rbecome, the more likely are they to perpetuate their disability,\rsince a significant number show a hereditary tendency.\r'),
 (618,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acquisition of language\ralthough the work of bullowa, jones, and bever has some of its greatest\rpromise in the light it may shed on the development of functions of language\rin children, the promise cannot be realized unless the authors give\ra great deal of explicit attention to the framework of such analysis, for there\ris not, as may be the case for phonological and grammatical development,\ranything like a satisfactory body of linguistic theory and method as to the\rterminal state.  while a good deal may be learned without such a theory, and\rnecessarily must be so learned, since the work in progress cannot be suspended\runtil such an unpredictable millenium, it still would be a pity if the\rchance were lost for the interaction of the acquisition of data and the\rimprovement of theoretical notions.\rlet me complete my discussion by developing my argument in two\rways: (a) by briefly stating the nature of the problem with regard to the\rterminal state of verbal development, (b) and by indicating what present\rand future contribution such fields as anthropology, sociology, and social\rpsychology may be able to make to the solution of the problem.\r'),
 (619,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the speech production and spoken language of the deaf\rthe distinction was made between speech production and spoken language in\ranalysing the oral output of those with hearing impairment.  a brief review of\rstudies in both areas was undertaken, including the report of a new electronic\rvisual monitoring device, the glossal transducer.  it was postulated that the\rdeaf utilise a unique visual-to-motor conversion within the brain when speaking\rand monitor conscously by tactile-kinaesthetic control.  the more recent\rstudies relate to the syntactical features of the speech of the deaf.  these\rshow that deafness creates telegraphic speech with reduced sentence length and\romissions of essential words such as functors.  the speech of the deaf seems to\rcontain mostly nouns and verbs, with a limited number of words used to expand\rverb forms.\r'),
 (620,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cognitive functioning in early infantile autism: an examination of four cases\rby means of the wechsler intelligence scale for children\rthe results are communicated which were obtained from an examination,\rby means of the wechsler intelligence scale for children, of four cases of\rearly infantile autism.  these cases had developed in such a way that a\rreliable investigation by means of a mental test had become possible.\raccording to their full scale iq\'s the four cases fell within the category of\rdull normal intelligence or less.  all of them showed a considerable\rdiscrepancy between the verbal and the performance iq, the performance iq being\rof much higher value.  the composition of the autistic test profiles was\rcharacterized by a large variability in the subtest scores, discriminating the\rautistic group significantly from non-autistic control groups.  the subtest\rscore divergencies, responsible for the large variability, showed a distinct\rpattern, being specific for the autistic group as a whole.  this group could\rbe considered as a distinct group particularly by a marked tendency to achieve\rpoorly and far below the subject\'s average level in the subtests comprehension\rand vocabulary, and to achieve superiorly and far above that level in the\rsubtests block design and object assembly.  by specifying the mental functions,\rconditional for success in these four subtests that occupy extreme positions\rwithin the autistic test profiles, it was concluded that the autistic patients\rapparently were able to achieve well, or even superiorly, only if the task\rcould be performed on a purely perceptual level.  but they failed as soon as\ran appeal was made to thinking proper.  this was thought to be due to a\rdisability in dealing with imaginary things and imaginary situations, or,\rin other words, to an incapability to objectify what is not actually present\rin the subject\'s concrete situation.  it is proposed that this impairment\rcould be reduced to a lack of symbolic means, being the correlate of a\rdefective or insufficiently developed language in the patients.  it is further\rproposed that children suffering from early\rinfantile autism might not be able,\ror at a later stage only, to reach that level of language development in which\rwords can be used as symbols,\rrepresenting absent things and absent situations.\r'),
 (621,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'otologic care of cleft palate cases\rthe purpose of this study was to review the ear pathology\rin 480 patients whose cleft palates had previously been repaired.\rdespite concern over speech regression, tonsil and\radenoid surgery was carried out on 66 of these patients.  when\rcarefully done, this was accomplished with considerable overall\rimprovement, particularly for the benefit of the conductive\rhearing loss.\rsixteen cases had exact documentation of these results by\rvirtue of speech recording and accurate audiometric records.\r'),
 (622,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital heart disease, deaf-mutism and associated somatic malformations\roccurring in several members of one family\rm.d. and patrick h. lehan, m.d.\ra unique family is described in which the\rmother and four of her eight children have pulmonary\rstenosis.  two of the four affected children\rare deaf-mutes; one of these has, in addition\rto the pulmonary valvular stenosis, idiopathic\rhypertrophic subaortic stenosis.  all the affected\rchildren had several associated somatic malformations.\rgenetic and nongenetic factors and\rtheir role in the development of the malformations\rare discussed.  it is suggested that the cardiac\rdefect is transmitted by a single non-sex-linked\rgenetic factor (dominant autosomal\rinheritance).  in the presence of a normal karyotype\rit appears that a single dose of either a\rpoint mutation, or a small deletion or translocation\ris the most likely cause.\r'),
 (623,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'histidinemia\ra review of published reports of\rhistidinemia indicates that this condition\rhas a variability of clinical and biochemical\rexpression.  three children with histidinemia,\rborn of a consanguineous marriage\rare reported here.  they had blond hair,\rblue eyes, speech defects, mental retardation,\rand a peculiar eeg abnormality.  they\ralso exhibited characteristic biochemical\rfindings of the disease: elevated blood and\rurine histidine, increased urine imidazolepyruvic\racid, and a sustained high rise in\rplasma histidine following an oral histidine\rtolerance test.  they did not, however, have\rthe reduction of skin histidine a-deaminase\ractivity which has been observed in some\rchildren with this condition.  tests for determination\rof heterozygotes in the family\rwere not successful.\rparental consanguinity and normal skin\ra-deaminase activity set these children apart\rfrom other reported cases.  the first lends\rsupport to the hypothesis that histidinemia\ris inherited as an autosomal recessive trait;\rthe second supports the idea that the genic\rfault which results in reduced histidine a-\rdeaminase activity can be expressed to a\rdifferent degree in different tissues.  these\rchildren seem to represent a variant of\rhistidinemia where liver histidase activity is\rreduced while skin histidase activity is\rpresent.\r'),
 (624,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'interpretation within the metaphor\ranalytic investigation of the use of the metaphor was first given impetus\rby ella freeman sharpe (1950), who explored the symbolic\rmeaning of particular metaphoric phrases with reference to the body\rand libidinal needs.  currently, interest has become focused upon the\ruse of the metaphor as a self-conscious, rational therapeutic technique\rof communication, of particular value with those patients who have\rreached \"the borderline of sanity\".  ekstein (1961) and ekstein and\rwallerstein (1957) have emphasized that the use of the metaphor\rshould be regarded as an essential technique for gradually establishing\rcommunication and initial insight with borderline and schizophrenic\rpatients but that it must not be regarded as a treatment technique\rin itself.  it is but a preliminary approximation to the final therapeutic\ract, which ultimately will consist of a classical interpretation\rat the level of the secondary process.  the use of the metaphor derives\rits primary value from maintaining contact with patients who are\rconstantly in danger of being inundated by a break-through of primary-\rprocess material.\r'),
 (625,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evolution of a characteristic speech disorder in\rjuvenile cerebral lipidosis\rjuvenile cerebral lipidosis is being diagnosed with increasing frequency in\rthis country, especially in schools for the visually handicapped.  the\rmanifestations of rapidly developing loss of vision, seizures, muscular\rrigidity, ataxia, retinitis pigmentosa and eeg abnormalities are well known in\rthis disorder.  a speech disorder described as a \"lolling, stammering speech\"\rwas mentioned by sjogren (1931) in his comprehensive description\rof juvenile amaurotic idiocy, but this has not been emphasized in\rrecent descriptions.  this report, based upon an analysis of 5 cases,\rdescribes the evolution of a characteristic form of speech pathology that\ris invariably present in juvenile cerebral lipidosis.\rthe initial speech abnormality seen early in the disorder is a hesitancy of\rspeech and occasional repetition of words.  in time, dysarthria becomes\revident with slurring, nasality and impairment of phonation similar to that\rseen in pseudobulbar palsy.  in addition to the dysarthria, a highly\rcharacteristic perseverative speech appears which often has a close resemblance\rto true stuttering.  this stuttering-like speech has been observed in 4 of the\r5 cases at some time during the course of their illnesses.  as the speech\rpatterns deteriorate, the patient becomes less communicative and finally lapses\rinto mutism.  the speech disorder is often the most disabling aspect of this\rsyndrome.\r'),
 (626,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'relation of crying activity in early infancy to speech and intellectual\rdevelopment at age three years\rrosenfeld\rcries of 38 infants, age 4 to 10 days, were measured for outburst\rfrequency during the most active 20-sec. period of crying.  crying\rscores showed a significant correlation (.45) with stanford-binet iq\rat 3 years, a borderline correlation (.32) with cattell iq at 15 to 20\rmonths, and a nonsignificant trend with speech ratings at 3 years.\ralthough no correlations were adequate for individual prediction,\rinfant crying is deemed worthy of further investigation as a possible\rindicator of intellectual potential.\r'),
 (627,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'labial supportive appliance\rthe patient with a repaired cleft lip and palate and an associated\rdisplacement and deficiency of the premaxilla presents problems which\rmay be of concern to the plastic surgeon, speech pathologist, orthodontist,\rand prosthodontist.\rthe upper lip may appear flat or retruded in relation to the lower lip.\rwhen maxillary anterior teeth are missing, either congenitally, naturally\r(as in the mixed dentition period), or because of neglect, the upper lip\rmay appear to be rolled under the premaxilla.  the lower lip usually\rassumes a characteristic \'pouty\' appearance.\rthis complex of tissue deformities also may be important in the articulation\rof speech sounds.  fricatives and plosives are difficult to produce\rcorrectly because of the malposition of the lip.  there may be interference\rwith direction of air current, contact of tongue to alveolar ridge, and\rnormal contact of lips.\rcorrective procedures are designed to improve the labial profile and to\restablish more normal relationships of intraoral structures.  these\rprocedures, employed individually or in combination, may include othodontic\rmovement of maxillary segments, dental prosthesis, and cheiloplasty.\ranother more recently developed adjunct involves autogenous\rosscous implantation in the cleft areas.\r'),
 (628,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'heterogeneity of the \'cleft palate population\' and research designs\rthe primary point made in this paper is that we must reject the notion\rthat there is some inherent, universal commonality among individuals\rwho are born with a cleft lip and/or cleft palate.  we must recognize the\rvarious pertinent subgroups within this population.  this does not mean,\rhowever, that one must always recognize the smallest subgroup in doing a\rgiven study.  on the contrary, we would defend the use of fewest possible\rsubgroups consistent with the specific research purpose.  nevertheless, we\rfeel that time spent considering the purposes of a study and the subgroups\rwhich need to be identified will tend to minimize the number of\rcontradictory results, and will assist us in the interpretation of the\robservations that our insight and technology make possible.\r'),
 (629,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cineradiographic comparison of normal to noncleft subjects with velopharyngeal\rinadequacy\rcineradiographic studies of the normal subjects were compared with\rstudies of noncleft subjects who demonstrated velopharyngeal inadequacy.\rthe following conclusions were made: a) there was a significant difference\rbetween soft palate length in normals and the velopharyngeal inadequacy\rgroup.  b) there was not a significant difference between depth of nasopharynx\rin normal and the velopharyngeal inadequacy group.  c) the\rdifference of the means of the soft palate length and depth of nasopharynx\rbetween the normals and velopharyngeal inadequacy group was significant.\rd) the thickness of the soft palate was greater in the normal than the\rabnormal group.  e) in 70% of the normal and velopharyngeal inadequacy\rgroups the height of soft palate elevation was above the palatal plane.   f)\rin 80% of the normal group the height of velopharyngeal closure took\rplace below the palatal plane.  none of the subjects in the velopharyngeal\rinadequacy group obtained velopharyngeal closure.  g) there was no significant\rcorrelation between amount of gap and voice quality.  h) there was\rno significant correlation between amount of gap and intelligibility of\rspeech.  i) there was a difference between vital capacity readings for the\rvelopharyngeal inadequacy group with nose occluded and unoccluded.  j)\rthe correlation coefficient between quality judgment and intelligibility\rjudgment was highly significant.\r'),
 (630,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'spontaneous verbal rehearsal in a memory task as a function of age\ra distinction is made between 2 alternative hypotheses for explaining an\roften-reported deficiency in verbally mediated performance during early\rchildhood: (1) the verbal response is made, but tends not to mediate\rperformance (\"mediational-deficiency hypothesis\"); (2) the verbal response\rtends not to be made (\"production-deficiency hypothesis\").  a study is\rdescribed which attempts to meet the ideal criteria for a test of the\rproduction-deficiency hypothesis.  the method used was that of direct\robservation of s\'s spontaneous verbalizations, and the hypothesis was confirmed\rby the finding that kindergarteners are less likely than older children to\rrehearse stimulus names in a nonverbal serial recall task.\r'),
 (631,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'early experience and the socialization of cognitive modes in children\rthis paper deals with the question: what is cultural deprivation and how\rdoes it act to shape and depress the resources of the human mind?  the\rarguments presented are: first, that the behavior which leads to social,\reducational, and economic poverty is socialized in early childhood; second,\rthat the central quality involved in the effects of cultural deprivation is a\rlack of cognitive meaning in the mother-child communication system; and, third,\rthat the growth of cognitive processes is fostered in family control systems\rwhich offer and permit a wide range of alternatives of action and thought and\rthat such growth is constricted by systems of control which offer predetermined\rsolutions and few alternatives for consideration and choice.\rthe research group was composed of 160 negro mothers and their\r4-year-old children selected from four different social status levels.\rthe data are presented to show social status differences among the\rfour groups with respect to cognitive functioning and linguistic codes and\rto offer examples of relations between maternal and child behavior that are\rcongruent with the general lines of argument laid out.\r'),
 (632,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recovery of mycoplasmas in the study of\rhuman leukaemia and other malignancies\rnumerous reports have been published concerning the\rnecessity of testing for the presence of mycoplasmas before\rthe interpretation of experiments performed in cell\rcultures.  such tests are especially important when\rthe presence of viruses is suspected, since recent evidence\rindicates that some mycoplasmas are capable of eliciting\ra transmissible cytopathic effect.\rin addition, some mycoplasmas and viruses share\rproperties, such as size, filterability, morphology in\relectron microscopy, sensitivity to ether, ability to\rhaemagglutinate and cause haemadsorption, interference\rwith virus replication in vitro, lack of inhibition by certain\rcommonly used antibiotics and inhibition of growth by\rhomologous antiserum.  thus, the absence of ordinary\rbacteria and moulds in preparations eliciting a cytopathic\reffect in cell cultures is an unreliable criterion for viral\ridentification.  great caution should be exercised in\rclassifying new agents as viruses, especially as myxo-\rviruses, without adequate testing to exclude their identity\ras mycoplasmas.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (633,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pneumonia due to mycoplasma pneumoniae\rits incidence in the membership of a co-operative medical group\rruth mcmahan, edmund r. clarke, william a. maccoll, and j. thomas grayston\ra total of 1051 cases of pneumonia occurred in\r72,992 persons who were members of a medical\rco-operative in the period december 1, 1963, to\rdecember 31, 1964.  the annual rate of pneumonia\rwas 12.9 per 1000.  isolation of mycoplasma pneumoniae\rfrom throat swabs was attempted in over\rhalf the cases reported, and paired blood specimens\rwere obtained in one third.  on the basis of laboratory\rexamination of these specimens, the incidence\rof clinically recognized pneumonia due to m. pneumoniae\rwas between 1 and 1.5 persons per 1000\rper year.\ralthough peak rates of pneumonia occurred under\rfive years of age (45 per 1000) pneumonia due to m.\rpneumoniae was uncommon in this age group.  it\rwas most common in children five to nine years old,\rand was frequently the cause of pneumonia in adolescents\r(ten to nineteen years of age).  the rates in\rchildren in primary school was twice the average\rincidence.  m. pneumoniae pneumonia also differed\rfrom the pneumonias of other etiology in that it\roccurred throughout the year, with no seasonal excess\rwhereas total pneumonia showed a predominance\rin winter.\rthe typical clinical syndrome of the pneumonias\rin which m. pneumoniae was isolated was one of\rprominent systemic manifestations of headache and\rfever, but few respiratory symptoms occurred except\rcough.  upper-respiratory-tract complaints and an\relevated white-cell count were much more frequent\rin the other pneumonias.  the patients with m.\rpneumoniae pneumonia were almost never hospitalized\rbut suffered significant absenteeism.  they\rcame from larger families, usually with children of\rschool age.  reporting physicians were usually correct\rin diagnosing these pneumonias as \"atypical\" or \"viral.\"\r'),
 (634,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'establishment of a turkey flock free of \'n\' strain mycoplasma\rmycoplasma of the \'n\' strain are frequently isolated from\rturkey poults affected with airsacculitis but free of\rmycoplasma gallisepticum.  research on the \'n\' strain has\rbeen impeded by the presence of a high proportion of\rturkey poults with airsacculitis in all breeding flocks\rexamined, by the difficulty of culturing and identifying\rthe mycoplasma strains, and by the lack of a practical\rserologic test.  this communication describes the establishment\rof a small nucleus of \'n\'-free turkeys from a commercial\rbreeding flock known to carry \'n\' mycoplasma.\rhens and toms for the production of \'n\'-free poults were\rselected from the parent flock by serology and culture.\r'),
 (635,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'septicemia due to mycoplasma hominis type 1\rviola m. young, ph.d., and sheldon m. wolff, m.d.\ra febrile illness that followed therapeutic abortion\rand was accompanied by the presence of\rmycoplasma hominis type 1 in the blood is described.\rthe patient upon recovery exhibited a specific\rantibody response to the mycoplasma isolated\rfrom the blood, as well as to another strain of the\rsame serotype.  these findings are regarded as additional\revidence for the pathogenicity of m. hominis\rtype 1 organisms, particularly in situations favoring\rtheir dissemination from the female genital\rtract.\r'),
 (636,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'infectie door mycoplasma hominis bij een pasgeborene\rmycoplasma hominis infection in a newborn child.  --in a baby\rborn by a difficult forceps delivery, abscesses began to form\rin the neck a few days after birth.  mycoplasma hominis was\rrecovered from the pus.\r'),
 (637,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some intraspecies differences in antigens on\rthe surface of certain living human cells\rsurface antigens of several types of living cells of human\rorigin were partially characterized with hyperimmune antisera prepared in\rthe rabbit against living hela cells and living, uncultured, full-term, human\ramnion cells.  hemagglutination, mixed-agglutination, and direct and\rindirect immunofluorescence (fab) techniques were employed.  with\rthese techniques and fractional absorption procedures, common and specific\rcell antigens were detected on the surface of several human living cells:\runcultured and primary amnion, two established human cell lines (rp am 1\rand u amnion) of presumed normal origin and two (hela and hep-2) of\rpresumed malignant origin, and human erythrocytes.  none of the antigens\rwere found on nctc 2555 mouse cells.  the human cells possessed species-\rrelated antigens demonstrable by hemagglutination.  after removal of\rthe hemagglutinins by absorption with human erythrocytes, antibody in high\rtiter for the homologous cells was detected by fab methods.  in addition,\rsome changes in antigens on the surface of amnion cells during primary\rculture were observed.  finally, an antigen was found on hela and hep-2\rcells, by use of anti-hela serum absorbed with human erythrocytes and rp\ram 1 cells, that was not found on either human erythrocytes, uncultured\ramnion cells, or on the cells of the two established amnion cell lines.  at\rthe dilutions used in the tests, antibodies to the abo blood group isoanti-\rgens, forssman hapten, or adsorbed serum proteins could not account for\rthe antigens detected.  the possibility that mycoplasma sp. antigens\rwere responsible for the reactions was inconsistent with the results.  the\rspecificity of the fab methods on living cells was confirmed.\r'),
 (638,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'coombs-positive hemolytic anemia and generalized amyloidosis in\rmice following transmission of subcellular leukemic material\rfollowing transmission with\rcell-free supernatant fluid or with virus ex-\rtract of leukemic tissue or plasma from vari-\rous types of murine plasma cell leukemias\ra disease developed, characterized by hyper-\rgammaglobulinemia, weight loss, anemia,\rmarked splenic, renal and hepatic amyloido-\rsis and plasma cell infiltrations in the lungs.\rthe disease was also transmissible through\rthe placenta or with the milk of infected\rmice.  in dba/2 males the incidence of the\rdisease was much higher (100%), the sur-\rvival shorter and the anemia much more\rsevere than was the case in dba/2 females\rand in (dba/2 x cba) f1 mice of both\rsexes.  it is proposed that the development\rof the lesions is mediated through an auto-\rimmune mechanism created by the antigenic\reffect of the virus-transformed host cells.\r'),
 (639,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the ph 6 antigen in strains of pasteurella pseudotuberculosis\rand its relation to biological activities\rit may be concluded that only part of the p.\rpseudotuberculosis strains can synthesize the ph\r6 antigen, whereas this property seems to be\rshared by all the strains of p. pestis.  as in the\rcase of p. pestis, three kinds of biological activi-\rties were related to the presence of the ph 6\rantigen isolated from a strain of p. pseudotubercu-\rlosis.\r'),
 (640,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'serological relationships among human mycoplasmas as shown\rby complement-fixation and gel diffusion\rand robert m. chanock\rantigenic relationships among human\rmycoplasmas were studied by complement-\rfixation and agar gel diffusion techniques.  four\rrecognized human species.  mycoplasma hominis\rtype 1, m. hominis type 2, m. salivarium, and\rm. fermentans were antigenically distinct in\rthese tests.  in addition, m. pneumoniae (eaton\ragent, the etiological agent of cold agglutinin-\rpositive atypical pneumonia) was different from\rthese four species.  although these species were\rdistinct, evidence of shared antigenic components\rwas obtained in complement-fixation and agar\rgel diffusion tests.  since rabbits were immunized\rwith mycoplasmas grown in rabbit muscle infu-\rsion broth supplemented with rabbit serum or,\rin the case of m. pneumoniae, with infected chick\rembryo lung suspension, the possibility that the\rheterologous reactions resulted from antibody\rto growth medium components could be excluded.\rfour recent mycoplasma isolates from the oro-\rpharynx were analyzed, and three were shown to\rbe closely related to m. hominis type 1, and the\rfourth was closely related to m. salivarium.\ralthough the recent isolates could not be dis-\rtinguished from the related \"prototype\" human\rspecies by complement-fixation, differences could\rbe detected by the agar gel diffusion technique.\r'),
 (641,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mammalian cell cultures contaminated with\rpleuropneumonia-like organisms\rii. effect of pplo on cell morphology in established\rmonolayer cultures\rthe occurrence of cytopathogenic changes in monolayer cultures of\rpplo-contaminated mammalian cells has been shown to be related to\rdeficiency of arginine in the medium.  the same effects were seen when the\rcell culture medium was depleted by pplo prior to application to pplo-free\rcell cultures even though viable pplo were no longer present.  the fact that\rthe same picture resulted in the absence of pplo when either arginine or\rglucose were omitted from the medium would indicate that, while the defi-\rciency created under the conditions described was specific, the cellular\rchanges could as well be the result of omission or depletion of other mam-\rmalian cell growth requirements.  the importance of surveillance of cell\rlines for the presence of pplo to avoid misinterpretation of cytopathogenic\reffects was stressed.\r'),
 (642,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'suppression of rous sarcoma virus growth in tissue\rcultures by mycoplasma orale\ran agent\rwhich produced cell destruction in human diploid and chick-embryo fibroblasts\rwas isolated from wi-26 strain of human diploid fibroblasts and shown to be a\rmycoplasma.  the multiplication of rous sarcoma virus (rsv) and rous associated\rvirus (rav) was inhibited in wi-26, wi-38, and chick-embryo fibroblasts\rinfected with this mycoplasma.  the mycoplasma isolate, designated strain 941,\rreacted strongly in the complement-fixation test with antiserum to mycoplasma\rorale ch19299, an isolate obtained from the human oral cavity.  the cytopathic\reffect of mycoplasma strain 941 could be eliminated by growing the mycoplasma\ron an artificial agar medium before inoculation into chick-embryo fibroblasts.\rserial passage in chick-embryo fibroblasts restored the cytopathogenicity of\rthe agar-grown mycoplasma.  however, growth of rsv and rav was inhibited by\rboth the tissue culture-grown and the agar-grown 941 strain, and also by the\rch19299 strain which did not produce any cytopathic effect.\r'),
 (643,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a method for direct demonstration of pleuropneumonia-like\rorganisms in cultured cells.\rdirect microscopic observation\rof pleuropneumonia-like organisms (pplo)\rin cell cultures is easily accomplished follow-\ring hypotonic treatment, air-drying and\rstaining with orcein.  a rapid technique using\rfl human amnion cells, inoculated with su-\rpernatant from suspected cultures, is de-\rscribed.  the demonstration of pplo con-\rtamination of 30 cell lines by this rapid\rmethod was in complete agreement with re-\rsults of pplo-agar techniques.\r'),
 (644,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a fatal septicemic disease of infant puppies caused by\rcytopathogenic organisms with characteristics of mycoplasma.\rpathogenic organisms were iso-\rlated from 2 outbreaks of a fatal septicemic\rdisease of infant puppies and from dog kidney\rcells that degenerated spontaneously.  the iso-\rlates were indistinguishable serologically and\rpossessed characteristics of mycoplasma.  the\rpathogenic organisms were cytopathogenic for\rdog kidney cell cultures, and in inoculated\rpuppies, produced pathological changes that\rresembled those seen in natural cases.  le-\rsions consisted principally of necrosis and\rhemorrhage.  the isolates were culturally and\rserologically distinct from recognized canine\rmycoplasma species.\r'),
 (645,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chromosome changes in pplo-infected fl human amnion cells.\rcharacteristic chromosome\rchanges were observed in pplo-infected fl\rhuman amnion cells.  these changes included\ra gradual reduction in chromosome numbers,\rincrease in chromosome aberrations, and the\rappearance of 3 new varieties.  although some\rof the aberrations appeared early after infec-\rtion, most changes developed slowly, over a\rperiod of several months.\r'),
 (646,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on mycoplasma pneumoniae\rinfection in sweden\rsera from 107 cases of pneumonia and 132 cases of milder respiratory\rinfection were examined by the cf test against m. pneumoniae antigen.\rthirty-five patients with pneumonia and 2 patients with bronchitis had\rserologic evidence of m. pneumoniae infection.  all cases which had a\rsignificant antibody rise with the cf test also showed a corresponding\rrise with the fluorescent antibody test.  m. pneumoniae was isolated\rfrom 10 of 18 serologically positive cases.  cold agglutinins were demon-\rstrated in 17 of 37 cases (46 per cent) with m. pneumoniae infection.\rm. pneumoniae infections occurred during all seasons of the year and\rwere most common in older children and young adults.  the clinical\rfeatures of the cases with m. pneumoniae infection in this study re-\rsemble those described in similar investigations in other countries.\r'),
 (647,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'spontane genetische veranderungen am zellstamm l (earle)\rthe chromosomal constitution of a clone of the cell strain ,,l\'\' was studied by\rrepeated chromosomal analyses within 2 years.  there resulted the stability of\rthe cellular clone with regard to the tested feature for the duration of about\rone year.\rthe maximal number of chromosomes amounted to 60-64.  in later tests a spon-\rtaneous doubling of the chromosomal number (maximum 120 chromosomes) was\rascertained.  the cause of this phenomenon could not yet be cleared up.  this\rnew chromosomal pattern remained unchanged in the subsequent examination period\rof 6 months.\ras was proved by these observations, under the present cultivation-conditions\rcell populations can be retained stabile in vitro for a certain period.  the\rdefined substances, however, still imply unknown factors which may have a\rmutagenous effect, so that sudden changes of cell populations may result.  the\rrespective physiological features are hardly known as yet.\r'),
 (648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chromosome changes in human diploid-cell cultures infected\rwith mycoplasma\rthis communication shows that mycoplasma may also\rchange cell chromosomes, and therefore emphasizes the\rneed for caution in interpreting experimental results\rwithout adequately testing for the presence\rof mycoplasma.  chromosome damage similar\rto that described here has been induced by\rviruses in cell cultures and in blood cul-\rtures.  chromosomal abnormalities have\ralso been reported in blood cultures and bone\rmarrow from leukaemic patients.\r'),
 (649,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evaluation of tylosin in\rpreventing egg transmission of\rmycoplasma gallisepticum in\rchickens\rthe inoculation of mycoplasma gallisepticum infective\ryolk into the left posterior thoracic air sac of laying chickens\rresulted in an infection which produced a rate of egg infection\rsatisfactory for experimental purposes.  culturing of all live\rembryonating eggs as well as all dead and infertile eggs was\rnecessary to determine the rate of egg infection.  tylosin,\reither injected subcutaneously, administered in the drinking\rwater, or employed in an egg-dipping solution, greatly reduced\rbut did not completely eliminate egg infection.  in the 3 egg\rdipping trials, only 11 isolates of m. gallisepticum were ob-\rtained from 2329 tylosin-dipped eggs, compared to 400 isolates\rfrom 2984 control eggs.\r'),
 (650,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'epidemiology of mycoplasma pneumoniae\rinfection in families\rand ruth mcmahan\rthe transmission and clinical manifestations of in-\rfection with mycoplasma pneumoniae were studied in 114\rfamilies in which there was a case of atypical pneumonia.\rm pneumoniae was isolated from a throat culture of the\rindex pneumonia patient in 36 of these families.  trans-\rmission to other family members occurred in 23 of the\r36 families.  in these 23 families, 84% of the children\rand 41% of the adults were infected.  the index cases\rare included.  of the total 59 patients with family-contact\rinfections, 42 had lower-respiratory-tract symptoms, 6\rhad pharyngitis alone, 9 (all children) were asympto-\rmatic, and 2 had probably unrelated symptoms.  the\rtime intervals between cases within a family suggested\ra median incubation period of 23 days.  treatment with\rtetracycline seemed neither to cure the symptoms com-\rpletely nor to abolish the carrier state that often lasted\rone to three months.\r'),
 (651,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case of salpingitis due to pleuro-pneumonalike\rorganisms\ra case of acute salpingitis following a diagnostic curettage and\raspiration of the pouch of douglas is described.  this case was resistant\rto penicillin and streptomycin therapy.  a pure culture of pleuropneu-\rmonia like organisms (pplo) grew from pus removed from the secon-\rdary pyosalpinx by aspiration.  these organisms were sensitive to tetra-\rcycline which cured the adnexal infection.  no pplo were found in the\rvaginal discharge.\rpplo have frequently been isolated from the vaginae of healthy\rand infected women.  however, only 9 cases of pelvic inflammatory\rdisease with a pure culture of pplo have been reported.  the possibi-\rlity that these growths of pplo in the internal genitalia followed the\ruse of antibiotic therapy is discussed.\rinfection with pplo should be considered when pelvic inflam-\rmatory disease proves resistant to the common antibiotics.\r'),
 (652,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the serological differentiation of mycoplasma strains (pleuro-\rpneumonia-like organisms) from various sources\ra complement fixation test with rabbit antisera was used to differentiate 82\rcultures of mycoplasma from man, mammalian cell cultures, laboratory rats and\rmice, cattle, goats, poultry, embryonated eggs and sewage.\rseventeen serotypes were distinguished, 5 from man, 1 from mammalian cell\rcultures, 4 from rats and mice, 4 from cattle and goats, 2 from poultry and one\rsaprophytic.  most of these corresponded to recognized species of mycoplasma,\rbut 1 of human origin (represented by 1 strain, navel), and 1 from tissue\rcultures (5 strains), may represent new species.  r38, one of the serotypes\rfrom rats, could be distinguished from the species m. arthritidis, but is\rprobably an antigenic variant rather than a distinct species.  two species\rhitherto recognized as distinct m. arthritidis and m. hominis type 2, could not\rbe distinguished and appear to constitute a single species.  these findings\rillustrate the necessity, from the viewpoint of taxonomy, of comparing\rmycoplasma strains by serological methods.\rthe serotypes of human and animal origin were largely host-specific.\rexceptions were the inclusion of m. arthritidis from rats and m. hominis type 2\rfrom man in a single serotype, the finding of a bovine organism among the\rstrains isolated from goats and of a saprophytic strain in a rat.\rin relation to the aetiology of disease in man and animals, the isolation of\ran endogenous mycoplasma from embryonated eggs used to passage infective\rmaterial illustrates the importance of identifying these organisms\rserologically.  the demonstration of mixed mycoplasma infections in lesions\rin two rats shows the necessity of adequately purifying all cultures of\rmycoplasma before examination.\r'),
 (653,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'spiramycin in the treatment of experimental\rmycoplasmosis in day-old chicks and turkey\rpoults\rday-old chicks and turkey poults experimentally infected with\rm. gallisepticum have been treated at the time of infection, with\rspiramycin administered by subcutaneous injection or drinking water\rmedication.\ra dose of 100 mg/kg. bodyweight by subcutaneous injection or an\r0.04 per cent. concentration in the drinking water continuously for\rthree days eliminated the infection in most of the birds, which\rremained free of air-sac lesions and did not react to the slide agg-\rlutination or haemagglutination inhibition tests.\r'),
 (654,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'further studies of agents isolated from tissue cultures inoculated\rwith human leukaemic bone-marrow\rd. a. woods\rmycoplasmas were isolated from tissue cultures inoculated\rwith bone-marrow from leukaemic patients.\rall cultures which showed a cytopathic effect contained\rmycoplasmas.\rthere was no evidence of mycoplasmas in control cultures.\rthe mycoplasmas isolated seemed biologically and serologic-\rally to be of one strain which was different from any previously\rreported as being isolated from human sources although there\rwas some relationship to a rodent mycoplasma, m. pulmonis.\rmycoplasmas cannot readily be distinguished from viruses\relectron-microscopically.\rthe relationship of mycoplasmas to leukaemia is not yet\rclear.\r'),
 (655,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'microbiological studies of reiter\'s disease\rattempts were made to demonstrate viruses and\rpplo in body fluids and synovial tissues of patients\rwith various rheumatic diseases.  all attempts to\rdemonstrate viruses were negative.  pplo were\rlooked for in 499 specimens from 114 patients with\rrheumatic and non-rheumatic diseases.  whereas\rthese organisms were readily isolated from genito-\rurinary specimens, they were found in none of 31\rsynovial fluid specimens.  they could not be grown\rfrom synovial tissue biopsies of patients with\rrheumatoid arthritis, ankylosing spondylitis, gout,\rgonococcal arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, traumatic\rarthritis, or arthritis accompanying ulcerative colitis,\rbut they were present in one and possibly in two of\reight synovial tissue specimens from patients with\rreiter\'s disease.  complement-fixation tests were\rnegative in nine patients with reiter\'s disease,\rincluding the two from whose synovial tissues\rpplo were thought to have been isolated.\r'),
 (656,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recovery of a pleuropneumonia-like organism\r(p.p.l.o.) from the genitalia of the female\ralbino rat\rthe genital organs of seventy-seven nonproductive breeder female rats\rwere examined grossly and histologically and bacteriological cultures of the\ruterus and ovaries were made.  three of the seventy-seven animals showed a\rpurulent salpingitis and oophoritis.  a pleuropneumonia-like organism was\risolated from the uterus and ovaries of 29% of the animals examined.  the\rcultures obtained from the genitalia were compared with the p.p.l.o. isolated\rfrom the middle ears of some of these same animals and the two appeared to be\ridentical.  intraperitoneal injection of the p.p.l.o. cultures into young\rrats and mice produced oophoritis and salpingitis in the mice but not in the\rrats.\r'),
 (657,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chronic respiratory disease in mice and rats\rchronic respiratory disease (crd) in both mice and rats embraces two\rseparate entities, namely: infectious catarrh caused by mycoplasmas\r(pleuropneumonia-like organisms) and enzootic bronchiectasis by a virus.\rthe two syndromes are discussed in regard to their etiology, pathologic\rmanifestations, and transmission.  particular attention is paid to the relation\rof mycoplasmas to infectious catarrh.  the morphologic and cultural\rcharacteristics of the catarrhal types of these organisms are considered\rfrom the standpoint of differential diagnosis.  the importance of crd in the\rmaintenance of breeding colonies and in the use of animals for experimental\rpurposes is stressed.  methods for the establishment of specific pathogen-free\rcolonies, as a means of control, are briefly outlined together with\robservations on a cesarean-derived line of swiss mice.\r'),
 (658,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'further observations of the lymphomas\rof african children\rduring 1963, cytopathogenic, filtrable agents were frequently encountered in\rcultures of embryonic human kidney cells following their inoculation with\rsupernatant fluids from primary human amnion cultures which had previously been\rexposed to extracts of tumors and other specimens from east african children\rwith malignant lymphomas of the kind described by burkitt and others.  the\rresults seemed noteworthy because they suggested an intimate association\rbetween the agents and the disease, and also because of the nature of the\risolations which involved two phenomena, an initial induction of a peculiar\rspindling and twisting of the amnion cells\r(fig. 1) and subsequently destructive changes\rin kidney cells inoculated with fluid from such altered amnion cultures.  the\rdirect inoculation of embryonic kidney cells with extracts of tumors or bone\rmarrow never caused cytopathogenic effects nor did the isolated, transmissible\ragents have the capacity to induce the amnion lesions.  nevertheless,\rthe two effects were closely associated and clearly related to the specimens.\rthe cytopathogenic agents were later cultivated on protein-rich media and\rfound to have the characteristics of mycoplasma.  they failed to induce\rtumors in a variety of animals, and serologic tests in which they served as\rantigen gave suggestive but inconclusive evidence of a relationship to the\rdisease.  the mycoplasma also failed to induce the amnion lesions caused by\rthe specimens.\r'),
 (659,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mycoplasma species of man\rat present, six distinct species of mycoplasmas\rare known to infect man.  certain biological and\recological properties of these agents have been\rdefined.  one species, m. pneumoniae, has been\rdefinitely shown to be an important respiratory-\rtract pathogen, and another species, m. hominis\rtype 1, may play a role in respiratory-tract and\rgenital-tract disease.\r'),
 (660,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pleuropneumonia-like organisms\rdespite their small size, the pplo carry\rthe full complement of the chemical com-\rpounds and enzymes contained in larger\rbacteria and in cells.  they contain both\rdna and rna, and in their independent\rmetabolism they are essentially like other free\rliving cells in contrast to the viruses which\rhave no independent metabolism outside the\rliving host cell.  several strains of pplo have\rbeen cultivated from the mucous membranes\rof apparently normal human subjects, espe-\rcially from the respiratory and urinary tracts.\runtil recently, however, definite evidence of\rthe association between the pplo and clear-\rly defined clinical disease in the human sub-\rject was lacking.  in 1962 it became evident\rthat the so-called eaton \"virus,\" originally\risolated by eaton and his associates in 1944\rfrom patients with primary atypical pneu-\rmonia, was in reality a pleuropneumonia-like\rorganism.  typical pplo colonies are pro-\rduced on a cell-free agar medium which is\renriched by the addition of blood serum or\ryeast.  a number of strains of pplo has now\rbeen identified, and in recognition of their\runique characteristics, they have been classi-\rfied in a separate order, the mycoplasmatales,\rgenus mycoplasma.\r'),
 (661,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'problems of disease of\rparathyroid glands\rif biochemical tests indicate unequivocally\rthat there is a functioning parathyroid tumour,\rusually an adenoma, its removal will relieve\rsymptoms and prevent any further damage to\rorgans such as the kidneys.  in 80 per cent,\rof such cases the operation is not particularly\rdifficult to anyone with experience of thyroid\rsurgery.  the tumour is seldom of great size,\rusually less than half an inch in diameter, but\ra careful search in the expected position, in\rclose apposition to the posterior surface of the\rthyroid lobes, will usually reveal it.  such\radenomata are usually more brown in colour\rthan the normal yellow gland; but in some 20\rper cent, of cases one or more of the glands\rmay be aberrant, or possibly absent, and super-\rnumerary glands may be present.  it is usually\rone of the lower pair of glands which occupies\ran ectopic position and, as i explained in the\routline of the embryological development, it\rmay accompany the thymus into the mediasti-\rnum, rather a vast area in which to seek a small\rtumour.  such an exploration cannot be lightly\rundertaken, but if the evidence is indisputable\rthe burden must be shouldered.  it is correct\rpolicy, i believe, first to carry out a thorough\rexploration of the neck, and if this proves un-\ravailing, to inspect the mediastinum through a\rsternum-splitting incision some two weeks later,\rrather than completing this major undertaking\rat one session.\r'),
 (662,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the age factor in experimental hypertension\rof the dca type in rats\rrats aged 25 and 86 days were sensibilised by unilateral nephrectomy and a week\rlater were given 1.1 mg/100 g dca every third day for 6 weeks and a 1% nacl\rsolution to drink.  the younger rats reacted with a greater increase in blood\rpressure, more so male rats.  hypertrophy of the heart and kidneys and\rmortality and supression of growth were also all more evident in the younger\rage group.  only male rats given the steroid hormone starting from day 25\rshowed permanent suppression of growth.\r'),
 (663,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'response of a serum glycoprotein to tissue injury\rand necrosis\r1. the response to necrosis, hyperplasia and tumour growth\ra serum glycoprotein of the rat underwent a 20-fold increase during 15 days\rgrowth of the walker tumour and this increase was not affected when the rats\rwere treated with terramycin.  the protein increased at the same or a greater\rrate when rats were subjected to ischaemic necrosis of one kidney or of two-\rthirds of the liver.  boiled kidney tissue, on the other hand, had little\reffect upon the protein response, and kidney hyperplasia had none.  it is\rsuggested that this protein increase is a response to substances liberated from\rdamaged or necrotic cells.\r'),
 (664,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the natural history of autoimmune\rdisease in nzb mice\ra comparison with the pattern of human\rautoimmune manifestations\rall mice of the nzb/bl strain spon-\rtaneously develop serological and\rpathological evidence of autoimmune dis-\rease during adult life.  the nzb/bl strain\rwas developed by dr. marianne bielschow-\rsky in dunedin, new zealand, by inbreed-\ring from an outbred colony of mixed coat\rcolor.  several inbred strains--nzb, nzc,\rnzo, nzw, nzy, and others, have been\revolved in dunedin from the original col-\rony.  evidence for autoimmune disease in\rthe nzb strain was first reported by\rbielschowsky, helyer, and howie who\rfound evidence of an autoimmune hemo-\rlytic anemia.  the dunedin group used the\rpresence of agglutinins for ficin-treated red\rcells as the index of the disease.\r'),
 (665,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the remaining kidney in irradiated\rsurvivors of wilms\'s tumor\rthe intravenous urograms of 10 patients\rwho had survived 5 years after irradiation\rfor wilms\'s tumor were studied for kidney\rsize and configuration.  the diseased kidney\rhad been removed by nephrectomy.\rthe remaining kidneys had been sub-\rjected to varying doses of ionizing radia-\rtion at the time the area of the diseased\rkidney was irradiated.  in none was there\revidence of atrophy.  all were within the\rrange of expected normal size and most of\rthem were enlarged.\r'),
 (666,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cellular proliferation and deoxyribonucleic acid\rsynthesis in compensating kidneys of mice\rand the effect of food and water\rrestriction\rcompensatory enlargement of the kid-\rney occurred after unilateral nephrectomy\rin mice.  fourteen days after the removal of\rone kidney the surviving renal tissue                                  6\rweighed 23 per cent more than single kid-\rneys from sham-operated animals.  the\rhyperplastic response of the cortex on the\rsecond postoperative day was 8 times\rgreater than that seen in the same zone of\rkidneys from sham-operated animals.  by\r10 days after surgery the mitotic index of\rthe cortex returned to control values.  the\router medulla also underwent hyperplasia\rbut only on the second day following\runilateral nephrectomy was the increase\rsignificant.  an increase in mitotic activity\rwas found in the inner medulla of surviving\rkidneys, but it was not statistically signifi-\rcant.\rboth starvation for 48 hours and water\rrestriction for 60 hours prevented the hyper-\rplastic responses in the remaining kidneys\r2 days after unilateral nephrectomy.  when\rwater was given 48 hours after unilateral\rnephrectomy (after 60 hours of water\rrestriction) significant increases in mitotic\ractivity were noted in the cortex of remain-\ring kidneys on the fourth and fifth post-\roperative days.  however, even after free\raccess to food was allowed (after 48 hours\rwithout food) no significant increase in\rmitotic frequency of the remaining kidney\rwas found.\rdeoxyribonucleic acid synthesis in con-\rtrol kidneys of mice was highest in the cor-\rtex and lowest in the inner medulla as\rrevealed by radioautographic studies fol-\rlowing the injection of tritiated thymidine.\rtwo days following removal of one kidney\rthe labeling index of the cortex of remaining\rkidneys increased 3-fold.  no statistically\rsignificant increases of deoxyribonucleic\racid synthesis were noted in either the outer\ror inner medullary regions of the remaining\rkidneys.\r'),
 (667,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'compensatory renal enlargement\rhypertrophy versus hyperplasia\rafter unilateral nephrectomy in the mouse, the compensatory growth\rof the remaining kidney is characterized by an increase in rna and\rprotein synthesis within the first hour.  dna synthesis remains un-\rchanged for about 18 hours and then rises to a maximum at 48 hours.  by\rthe end of the fifth day, when dna synthesis has passed its peak and is\rin decline, cellular hyperplasia has accounted for only one-fourth of the\rincrease in kidney weight.  thus it is shown that cell hypertrophy is both\rthe primary and the predominant response in the early phase of compen-\rsatory renal enlargement.\r'),
 (668,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cell proliferation\rin experimental hydronephrosis\rand compensatory renal hyperplasia\rmitosis counts and autoradiographic counts of nuclei labeled with\rtritiated thymidine were made in the renal cortex of male rats in which\rthe left ureter was ligated.  these were compared with corresponding\rcounts in the remaining kidney after left nephrectomy, and in sham-\roperated controls 24, 48 and 72 hours after operation.  the cortex of\rthe kidney on the obstructed side showed a greater number of tritium-\rlabeled nuclei and mitotic figures than in the kidney undergoing com-\rpensatory hyperplasia.  epithelial and interstitial cells responded simul-\rtaneously on the obstructed side, whereas in the remaining kidney after\rnephrectomy, the epithelial response preceded a slight interstitial re-\rsponse by 48 hours.  the contralateral kidney in rats subjected to\rureteral ligation showed no response.\rwe concluded that the early response of increased dna synthesis\rand cell division in the obstructed kidney was not mediated by humoral\rfactors; it was localized and probably had a different mechanism than\rthe proliferative response occurring in compensatory renal hyperplasia.\r'),
 (669,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal factors in the pathogenesis of hypertension\rrenal arteriography and other modern diagnostic procedures have provided\rthe means of establishing a close relationship between high blood pressure and\rrenovascular disease.  many of these cases are amenable to surgical cure.  at\rthe present time there is no single test for the definitive diagnosis of renal\rhypertension.  careful and intensive studies are mandatory in the selection of\rcases suitable for surgery, since hypertension has many etiologic factors and\rinvolves many complex and sometimes obscure mechanisms.  aortography,\rintravenous urography and split-function tests are among the most important\rmethods for definitive diagnosis and for the planning of appropriate surgical\rprocedures.\rat operation, the most commonly observed cause of renal arterial con-\rstriction in the elderly is atherosclerosis, whereas in younger patients it is\rhyperplasia of the intimal and muscular coats of the renal artery and its\rbranches.  renovascular surgery may require a variety of technical procedures.\rin the successful cases there is a striking and permanent reduction in blood\rpressure.\rthe accuracy of blood pressure readings is emphasized, since hypertension\ris usually discovered for the first time during the course of a routine\rphysical examination.\r'),
 (670,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cell proliferation in compensatory renal growth\rrats with one kidney removed showed a progressive increase in weight of the\rremaining kidney over a six-week period.\rautoradiographic and radiochemical studies with 3h-thymidine indicated that the\rincrease in new kidney cell formation was maximal forty-eight to seventy-two\rhours after unilateral nephrectomy.  this early response was chiefly due to the\rproduction of new cells by the renal cortical tubules.  normal rates of tubule\rcell turnover were achieved two weeks after operation.  the glomerular tufts\rcontained fewer new cells and their peak production was delayed to the\rone-week period with a slow decline thereafter.\rrats forty-eight hours after unilateral nephrectomy were chosen as a model to\rstudy the effect of various substances on the magnitude of new cell formation.\rthe number of dna-synthesising cells in the stimulated kidney was reduced by\rtreatment with hydrocortisone, acth, 9,10-dimethyl-1,2-benzanthracene, and\r1,2-benzanthracene; the numbers were increased by the administration of\rdeoxycorticosterone and aldosterone.\r'),
 (671,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of adrenalectomy on\rthe parathyroids in nephrectomized rats\rrat parathyroids were studied both after nephrectomy and after com-\rbined nephrectomy and adrenalectomy.  as early as 24 hours after\rnephrectomy there were morphological indications of increased para-\rthyroid activity in the form of increased glandular volume and enlarged\rcell nuclei.  the corresponding changes after combined nephrectomy and\radrenalectomy were less marked and the total serum calcium was higher\rthan after nephrectomy only.  these observations suggest that the adrenals\rcould induce a change in calcium homeostasis opposite to that of the\rparathyroids.\r'),
 (672,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pathogenesis of polycystic kidneys\rmicrodissection confirms our previous de-\rscription of an uncommon variety of poly-\rcystic kidney found only in the newborn\rperiods.  it is characterized by symmetrical\renlargement caused by saccular or cylindri-\rcal increase in size of all collecting tubules.\rthe number and relative length of different\rgenerations of collecting tubules are normal.\rnephrons are present in normal numbers,\rand their attachment to collecting tubules is\rnormal.  the pattern of the nephrons is nor-\rmal except for minimal localized areas of\rdilatation.  interstitial connective tissue is\rnot increased.  intrahepatic bile ducts are in-\rvariably cystic.  siblings may be affected.\rwe believe that in such kidneys the be-\rhavior of the ampullae of the branches of the\rureteral bud is normal and that secondary\rhyperplasia of the interstitial portions of the\rbranches is responsible for the greatly in-\rcreased renal size.\r'),
 (673,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'concurrence of hyperplasia and\rneoplasia of the parathyroid glands\rthe concurrence of parathyroid hyperplasia\rand neoplasia in a group of six patients is re-\rported.  two patients had long-standing renal\rdisease with azotemia and hyperphosphatemia.\rin both hypercalcemia developed while they\rwere under observation and they were found to\rhave parathyroid adenomas as well as hyper-\rplasia of the other glands.  a third patient\rfollowed an apparently similar course.  one pa-\rtient with primary hyperparathyroidism due to a\rlarge mediastinal adenoma displayed hyper-\rplasia of other glands in association with moder-\rate renal insufficiency.  two patients with pri-\rmary generalized parathyroid hyperplasia were\rfound to have superimposed neoplastic lesions:\rmultiple adenomatous nodules in one, adenocar-\rcinoma in the other.\rthese observations add new dimensions to the\rdiagnosis and therapy of parathyroid disorders.\rthey indicate the necessity of examining all four\rparathyroid areas at time of surgery.  they also\remphasize that hypercalcemia developing in\rpatients with chronic renal disease is a manifesta-\rtion of autonomous parathyroid function.\r'),
 (674,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experimentelle nierenvergroberung nach unilateraler\rnephrektomie bei ratten\runtersuchungen mit 3h-thymidin\rin this paper it is attempted to clarify certain questions as to the mechanism\rof compensatory renal hypertrophy by means of histological, cytological, and\rautoradiographical examinations in nephrectomy experiments on young and grown\rrats.  based on the results of this investigation the process of compensatory\rrenal hypertrophy must be imagined as follows:\ras early as two hours after unilateral nephrectomy, a distinct increase of the\rmitosis index without a simultaneous increase in dna-synthesizing cells was\robserved in the remaining kidney.  it is assumed that a cell division of\rpolyploid cells is involved, which were in a prolonged premitotic rest phase.\rafter a latent period of 48 hours, the dna-synthesizing cells and dividing\rcells start to increase.  the maximum of the regenerative processes is reached\rbetween the 3rd and 4th day after nephrectomy.  twenty days after unilateral\rnephrectomy, the regenerative processes are largely concluded.\rall tubule sections participate in the compensatory renal hypertrophy.\ralthough the regenerative processes are most marked in the central section,\rone cannot speak of the development of an actual indifference zone in the\rregenerating kidney.\rin young test animals, compensatory renal hypertrophy is determined more\rby mitotic cell division, in older test animals more by polyploidization\rprocesses.\rthe results of these investigations provide no certain indications for the\rassumption that amitotic nuclear divisions play a major part in compensatory\rrenal hypertrophy.\rproliferation processes which in extent and localization run parallel to the\rregeneration of the parenchyma, are also observed in the cells of the\rconnective tissue of the renal vessels.\r'),
 (675,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'abscopal effects of whole-body\rx-irradiation on compensatory hypertrophy\rof the rat kidney.\rthe weight and dna content of normal growing (i.e., intact), and\rhypertrophying (i.e., following uninephrectomy) rat kidneys were\robtained from several hundred sprague-dawley white rats.  the\reffect of whole body x irradiation with 500 rad and local irradiation\rto the kidney with 1000 rad, was then determined by following the\rrate and degree of hypertrophy and the dna content of the kidney.\rwhen calculated on the basis of body surface area, a constant ratio\rof kidney weight and of kidney dna was found in the normal, non-\rhypertrophying kidneys of 5-12 week old rats.  after 21 days of\rhypertrophy these values increased approximately 50 per cent over\rnormal in rats 4-6 weeks old at the time of nephrectomy.  for\ranimals 6-14 weeks old at the time of nephrectomy the corresponding\rincrease was only about 20 per cent.\rfollowing uninephrectomy and x irradiation with 1000 rad to the\rexteriorized remaining kidney, 4 week old rats whose bodies were\rlead-shielded during irradiation showed no body weight growth\rretardation, no significant difference in the dna content of the\rkidney, and a small but significant decrease in weight increment\rof the hypertrophying kidney after 21 days.\rrats exposed to 500 rad of x rays with the kidney shielded during\rirradiation, when compared with nonirradiated controls, showed body\rweight growth retardation, a reduction in the dna content of the\rkidney, and a reduction in the amount of kidney hypertrophy 21 days\rfollowing uninephrectomy.  a still greater inhibition of both kidney\rcompensatory hypertrophy and the increase in dna content of the\rkidney occurred after 500 rad whole body irradiation.\rfood restriction in nonirradiated 4 week old rats resulting in\rbody weight growth retardation, elicited a marked reduction in\rkidney weight and in dna content of the hypertrophying kidney 21\rdays after uninephrectomy.\rit is concluded that the reduction in kidney hypertrophy following\rwhole body x irradiation with 500 rad is due in some measure to an\rabscopal or indirect effect, secondary to decreased body weight.\r'),
 (676,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radiation effects renal enlargement in the mouse\rthree hours following unilateral\rnephrectomy weanling female cf-1 mice were\rsubjected to local abdominal or total body\rexposure to either 500 or 600 r.  other\rgroups were given 1350 r to half the abdomen\rwith and without prior nephrectomy.  signifi-\rcant decreases in renal weight gain compared\rto controls were obtained in the 600 r total\rbody group and in the locally irradiated ani-\rmals given 1350 r.  when the renal weight\rchanges are compared on the basis of the\rratio of renal weight to body weight in per\rcent, an increase from .64% to .95% is seen\rin animals subjected to nephrectomy alone.\rthe final value in all of the irradiated and\rnephrectomized groups was similar, ranging\rfrom .93% to 1.0%.  the results suggest that\rirradiation in these dose ranges does not\rexert a direct inhibitory effect on renal weight\rincrease but it limits body weight gain which\rinfluences kidney weight.\r'),
 (677,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal hyperplasia and neoplasia\rin rats given dimethylnitrosamine\rmultiple foci of hyperplasia and neoplasia were induced in the kidney\rof rats that had been dosed orally with dimethylnitrosamine.  the younger rats\rand the male sex had a greater incidence of renal tumors.  the hyperplastic\ror neoplastic lesions were classified into two groups on the basis of their\rhistogenesis, namely that of tubular epithelial origin and that of interstitial\rcell origin.  dimethylnitrosamine is recommended as a useful chemical\rcompound for the study of renal carcinogenesis.\r'),
 (678,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the role of age and x-irradiation on kidney\rfunction in the mouse\rfemale mouse kidneys show a decline with respect to age in the ability to\rconcentrate the urine during a 24-hour water fast.  x-irradiation early in\rlife has no measurable long-term effect on this process.\rkidney cortex slices of old female mice can concentrate p-aminohippuric\racid against a concentration gradient equally as well as slices from young\rmice.  there is no loss in this ability by cortex slices from young or old\rfemale x-irradiated mice.\rit is uncertain whether compensatory renal hypertrophy after unilateral\rnephrectomy declines with age in nonirradiated mice.  x-irradiation does\rcause a reduction in the degree of compensatory renal hypertrophy in the aging\rmouse.  this reduction may represent a loss in the ability of kidney cells to\rundergo cell division.\rthe administration of testosterone propionate to old mice during compen-\rsatory renal hypertrophy results in an increased hypertrophy.  the increase is\rrelatively the same for irradiated and nonirradiated mice, indicating the lack\rof a long-term effect of x-irradiation to reduce the ability of a target\rorgan to respond to a hormone.\rthe over-all conclusion of this study, with respect to \"radiation-induced\raging,\" is that x-irradiation of the female swiss mouse early in life does not\rhave a pronounced effect on kidney function late in life but may have a long-\rterm effect on those processes concerned with cell division.\r'),
 (679,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hyperaldosteronism, hyperplasia of the\rjuxtaglomerular complex, normal\rblood pressure, and dwarfism:\rreport of a case\ra patient with the syndrome of hyperal-\rdosteronism, hyperplasia of the juxtaglo-\rmerular complex, dwarfism, and normal\rblood pressure is reported in detail.  in this\rpatient, the aldosterone secretion rate in-\rcreased significantly and the serum potas-\rsium rose slightly with sodium depriva-\rtion.  with a low-sodium diet urinary sodi-\rum fell to zero.  spironolactone with a low-\rsodium diet raised serum potassium to nor-\rmal.  infusion of albumin, however, resul-\rted in a rapid increase in serum potassium\rand a fall in aldosterone secretion rate.  the\runique features in this patient are the re-\rsponse to albumin and the lowering of uri-\rnary sodium to zero in response to a low-\rsodium intake.  in all other essentials, the\rcase resembles the two previously reported\rcases.  treatment by subtotal adrenalecto-\rmy was not curative.\r'),
 (680,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidney and the\rzona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex in\rthe sodium losing and the hypertensive\rforms of virilizing adrenal\rhyperplasia\rpathological and biochemical observations\rare presented in two cases of virilizing ad-\rrenal hyperplasia: one of the sodium-losing\rtype and the other of the hypertensive type.\rexamination of the kidneys revealed hyper-\rtrophy of the juxtaglomerular cells in the\rcase exhibiting excessive sodium loss.  the\radrenal cortex showed hypertrophy of the\rzona glomerulosa.  it is hypothesized that\rthe chronic state of sodium loss caused\rchanges in the intravascular compartment\rwhich led to compensatory activity of the\rjuxtaglomerular cells with resultant stimula-\rtion of the zona glomerulosa.\rexamination of the hypertensive case\r(known to involve a different enzyme defi-\rcit) showed hypertrophy of the zona glom-\rerulosa without hypertrophy of the juxta-\rglomerular cells.  the intrinsic overproduc-\rtion of sodium-retaining steroids associated\rwith the genetic defect in this clinical form\rcould account for both the hypertension\rand the absence of hypertrophy of the juxta-\rglomerular apparatus.\r'),
 (681,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on eperythrozoon infection in sheep\rthe intravenous inoculation of blood from sheep in the parasi-\rtaemic stage of eperythrozoon infection produced detectable\rparasitaemia in recipient sheep within 7 days.  the parasitaemia\rlasted from 3 to 12 weeks and was accompanied by anaemia and\roccasionally by icterus.  no other symptoms developed and in a\rcontrolled experiment on hoggs there was no significant difference\rin weight gain between infected and control animals.\ra concurrent attack of tick-borne fever led to the disappearance\rof eperythrozoon from the circulating blood.  it is suggested that this\rphenomenon may be caused by the pyrexia.\rthe incubation period following the inoculation of infected blood\rin ten 3 to 4 week old lambs varied from 3 to 6 weeks.  in eight of\rthese animals the symptoms were less severe than in adult sheep, but\rthe two smallest lambs developed a profound anaemia and failed to\rgain weight.\rculture of the organism on sheep blood agar or on sheep kidney\rmonolayers was unsuccessful as was the attempted transmission of\rthe infection to mice.\rthe transference of keds and lice from infected to uninfected\rsheep failed to transmit the infection, but a sheep was infected by the\rintravenous inoculation of ground-up lice from an infected animal.\rthe only characteristic histopathological changes in infected\rsheep were lymphoid hyperplasia of the malphigian corpuscles in the\rspleen and deposition of haemosiderin in the cells of the proximal\rconvoluted tubules in the kidney cortex.\r'),
 (682,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'age differences in cellular\rproliferation in rat kidneys\rthe hyperplastic response to unilateral ne-\rphrectomy after 48 hours in the cortex and\rmedulla of the remaining kidneys of weanling\rand young adult rats was studied by means of\rautoradiography.  tritiated-thymidine, which\ris destined exclusively for nucleoprotein synthe-\rsis, was administered to 11 control and 11 ex-\rperimental rats 4 hours prior to sacrifice.\rlabeled tubular cells were rare in control\rtissues, especially in medulla, where the per-\rcentages did not differ greatly for the two age\rgroups.  in the cortex of controls such cells were\rthree times more frequent for weanling rats\rthan for adults.  significant increases in per-\rcentages of labeled cells over control levels\rwere found in both regions of the remaining\rkidneys for both age groups.  the percentage of\rincrease was greater in medulla than in cortex\rand most pronounced in medulla of the young\radult rats.\r'),
 (683,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'phospholipids of the sexual segment of the kidney of the\rindian house lizard, hemidactylus\rflaviviridis ruppell\rthe indian house lizard, hemidactylus flaviviridis breeds seas-\ronally.  in a sexually mature male lizard, from october to\rmay of the following year, the secondary and tertiary collecting\rtubules of the kidney are hypertrophied forming the sexual seg-\rment.  the development of the sexual segment is synchronous with\rthe testicular cycle and maximum development occurs during the\rperiod when the testes are spermatogenically active.  the sex-\rual segment is not developed in the females in any season of the\ryear; it is completely regressed in males during sexual quiescence\r(june and july).  injection of 4.0 mg of testosterone propionate\rover two weeks stimulated the regressed sexual segment to hyper-\rtrophy in males during quiescence and also in females.  the\rapical portions of the cells of the sexual segment are loaded\rwith granular secretions which are stained with baker\'s acid hae-\rmatein and phosphomolybdic acid-stannous chloride, indicating the\rpresence of choline - containing phospholipids.  the composi-\rtion of the phospholipids of the sexual segment, which is a unique\rfeature of the lizards and snakes, is unknown.  this preliminary\rcommunication describes the isolation and quantitative estimation\rof phospholipids present in the sexual segment of the indian house\rlizard, hemidactylus flaviviridis ruppell.\r'),
 (684,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(on the erythropoietic effect of different\rtissue suspensions)\rthe stimulating effect on erythropoiesis of regenerated liver and hyper-\rtrophic kidney tissue after partial hepatectomy and unilateral nephrectomy\rrespectively was studied in the rat by means of the erythrocyte count, haemo-\rglobin determination, reticulocyte count and 59fe utilization.  the\rreticulocyte count and 59fe utilization increased significantly after treatment\rwith normal liver and renal tissue and more strongly after regenerated liver\rand hypertrophic kidney tissue.  the same effect was seen after treatment\rwith the sera of rats which had undergone partial hepatectomy or unilateral\rnephrectomy.\r'),
 (685,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hemihypertrophy and medullary sponge kidney\rcongenital hemihypertrophy is an over-\rgrowth of one side of the body which is\rassociated with an asymmetry beyond the ex-\rpected range.  it is to be distinguished from\rhemiatrophy in which atrophy or withering of\rone half of the body has occurred, usually be-\rcause of neurological lesions.\rthis condition of hemihypertrophy, though\rrare, is very frequently associated with other\rcongenital abnormalities.  these include several\rin the urogenital tract, such as hypospadias,\rcryptorchidism, unilateral renal hypertrophy\rand an increased incidence of wilms\' tumour.\r'),
 (686,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chemical aspects of compensatory renal hypertrophy\rthe effect of unilateral nephrectomy on the size and composition of the\rremaining kidney has been investigated in rats.  in normal rats the right\rkidney is, on the average, significantly heavier than the left and has a\rhigher total content of dna and rna.  the 2 kidneys have almost identical\rratios of rna/dna and protein/dna.  after unilateral nephrectomy the surviving\rkidney increases steadily in wet and dry weight for the 1st 4 days after the\roperation.  this is accompanied by a much slower increase in total dna\rcontent and by a dramatic increase in rna/dna ratio.\rthe rna/dna ratio in kidney is also affected by diet, being higher on a\rhigh-protein than on a low-protein intake.  moreover, the rise in rna/dna\rratio that follows unilateral nephrectomy is greater in animals fed a\rhigh-protein diet.  the changes in kidney weight and in total contents of dna,\rrna, protein, and lipid phosphorus resulting from the feeding of a high-protein\rdiet were found to be of approximately the same magnitude as those in the\rremaining kidney 4 days after unilateral nephrectomy.  the rna/dna and\rprotein/dna ratios are also greater in rats fed a diet containing 10% urea,\rbut the increase is much less than that in the remaining kidney after\runilateral nephrectomy.\r'),
 (687,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the antidiuretic mechanism of hydrochlorothia-\rzide in the treatment of diabetes insipidus\rthe changes in water and electro-\rlyte balance during hydrochlorothiazide\rtherapy in 2 patients with vasopressin-\rdeficient diabetes insipidus were studi-\red.  in 1 case, under fixed daily so-\rdium intake, the urinary sodium excre-\rtion markedly increased on the first day\rof treatment, but the urinary volume\rbegan to fall on the second day and per-\rsisted low for 3 days after discontinua-\rtion of the drug.  in the other case the\rurinary volume markedly decreased\rwhen the daily sodium intake was strict-\rly limited.  it further decreased on\rhydrochlorothiazide therapy but after\rsodium intake was restored it returned\rto the pretreatment level despite con-\rtinued use of the drug.\rthe antidiuretic action of hydro-\rchlorothiazide in the treatment of dia-\rbetes insipidus is believed to be related\rto the sodium depletion state of the body\rbrought about by increased output or\rdecreased intake of sodium.  sodium\rand water reabsorption in the proximal\rconvoluted tubules in the kidney in-\rcreases and the amount of glomerular\rfiltrate reaching the distal convoluted\rtubules decreases.  thus the final\rurinary volume falls.\r'),
 (688,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the action of oral diuretics\rin diabetes insipidus\rchronic administration of chlorothiazide and\rother thiazide analogues in diabetes insipidus\rresults in a striking reduction in urinary volume\rwith increase in urinary osmolality.  this curious\rantidiuretic action was first described by\rcrawford & kennedy (1959), and though it has\rsince been widely confirmed in both the pituitary\rand nephrogenic forms of the disease, its precise\rmechanism remains obscure.  a number of\rinvestigators have sought to explain the phenom-\renon entirely on the basis of the renal actions of\rthese drugs (earley & orloff 1962, goodman &\rcarter 1962), whilst others have contended that\rabatement of polyuria may be secondary to a\rcentral effect of the thiazides in decreasing thirst\r(robson & lambie 1962, skadhauge 1963).\rover the past two years, we have conducted\rdetailed in-patient studies of the action of\rvarious diuretic drugs of the thiazide and other\rseries in a group of 7 patients with pituitary\rdiabetes insipidus.\r'),
 (689,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'investigations into the thiazide-induced antidiuresis in\rpatients with diabetes insipidus\rplasma sodium, osmolality and serum\rchloride, together with creatinine clear-\rance, were studied before and during\rthiazide treatment of 7 patients with\rdiabetes insipidus.\rthe diuresis was reduced by 28-39%.\rthe urine osmolality was increased by\r7-128%.  an average decrease in plasma\rsodium of 4 meq/i, in plasma osmolality\rof 21 mosm/kg, and in serum chloride of\r8 meq/i was observed.  only in one pa-\rtient was the creatinine clearance re-\rduced significantly.  the thirst-feeling was\rreduced even from the first day of treat-\rment.  the diuresis was not minimal until\rthe third to fourth day.  if the diuresis was\rcorrected for the extra electrolyte ex-\rcretion initiated by the thiazide, the\rantidiuresis was found to be operating to\rthe full extent even on the first day of\rtreatment.\rit is concluded that the antidiuresis is\rmainly secondary to the natriuresis and to\ra certain degree due to a decreased thirst-\rfeeling; but there seems also to be a direct\rrenal action, involving at least a reduc-\rtion of the glomerular filtration rate.  a\rpronounced antidiuresis was found by a\rwater deprivation test after thiazide\rtreatment in one patient.\r'),
 (690,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'salt and water\rthe antidiuretic effect of thiazides is thus the\rresult of the induced sodium deficit.  the fall in\rserum osmolality may be contributory by\rreducing thirst.  as depletion of body sodium will\rbe self-limiting the major hazard to the use of\rthiazides is potassium depletion.  treatment of\rpatients with vasopressin insufficiency type of\rdiabetes insipidus with thiazides is only indicated\rfor those who are intolerant of hormone replace-\rment.  in nephrogenic diabetes insipidus thiazides\rhave a more important therapeutic application.\r'),
 (691,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nephrogenic diabetes insipidus\rchlorothiazide has been found of value in\restablishing and maintaining adequate hydra-\rtion in some patients; its exact mechanism of\raction is not known.  the antidiuretic effects\rof chlorothiazide and its analogues have been\rstudied in six patients with ndi, two of\rwhom were infants less than six months of\rage.  dehydrated infants showed a dramatic\rresponse to treatment.  with those unable to\rachieve an optimal fluid intake prior to treat-\rment, the initial beneficial response was asso-\rciated with an increased fluid intake.  follow-\ring this initial antidiuretic response, a vari-\rable degree of \"escape\" or resistance to the\raction of the drug commonly occurred.  de-\rspite the unpredictability of a prolonged anti-\rdiuretic response, a therapeutic trial of chloro-\rthiazide in ndi seems warranted if diet alone\ris not sufficient to maintain hydration.  it must\rbe remembered, however, that this drug is po-\rtentially toxic.\r'),
 (692,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fluid and electrolyte metabolism in nephrogenic diabetes insipidus\rthe body fluid volumes have been fol-\rlowed in two infants with nephrogenic\rdiabetes insipidus.  without treatment both\rpatients had a low extracellular fluid\rvolume (ecv) and a normal to low-\rnormal total body water (tbw).  following\rthiazide therapy (case 1) and during a\rfluid deprivation test (case 2) a further\rreduction of ecv and tbw was found.\runtreated both patients revealed a se-\rvere hypernatriemia without any increase\rin the urinary aldosterone excretion.\rthe first patient had a cerebral atro-\rphy and a rightsided hydronephrosis, a\rhigher diuresis and a lower concentration\rcapacity was found on this side.  the\rpatient was treated continuously with\rthiazide.  when an ordinary house diet\rwas given this drug could only maintain\rnormal electrolytemia in combination\rwith spirolactone.  a considerable increase\rin height and psychic development took\rplace during this combined treatment.\rit is noted, that nephrogenic diabetes\rinsipidus may be present in infants with\runexplained fever and vomiting in the\rabsence of polydipsia and polyuria.  the\rurine may even be hypertonic.\r'),
 (693,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'diuretics in pediatric practice\rclinical notes and comments\rwith the development of more and more\rpotent oral diuretics in recent years, these\rdrugs which were once looked upon as being\rof only limited usefulness in pediatrics are\rnow receiving clinical application.  they per-\rmit a new approach to the management of\redematous states.  that most of them can be\rgiven orally is a significant advantage, par-\rticularly when coupled with their relative lack\rof toxicity.  although the number of patients\rin the pediatric age range who require these\ragents is relatively small, they are valuable\radjuncts in the management of chronic renal\rdisease, refractory heart failure, and hyper-\rtension.  this discussion reviews their pharma-\rcology and clinical indications.\r'),
 (694,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the role of aldosterone and vasopressin in the postural\rchanges in renal excretion in normal subjects\rand patients with idiopathic edema\rthe effects of the upright posture\r(leisurely walking for 2 hours) on half-\rhourly urine volume, and excretion of\rsodium and creatinine were studied in\r13 normal subjects and 13 patients with\ridiopathic edema, while they drank 150\ror 300 ml. of 0.14 per cent sodium\rchloride solution every half hour.  when\rthe 2 hours of walking were compared\rwith a preceding recumbent period of\r4 hours, both groups were found to show\ra significant antidiuresis upright.  the\radministration of ethanol during the last\rhalf hour of recumbency abolished the\rfall in urine flow and in free water clear-\rance during the first hour of walking in\rthe normal subjects and significantly re-\rduced this fall in the patients with\redema.  sodium excretion in the normal\rsubjects was slightly but not significantly\rlower when upright than when recum-\rbent, but in the edematous patients was\rsignificantly lower when upright and fell\rprogressively over the 2 hour period.  ad-\rministration of spironolactone or d-\ramphetamine increased sodium excretion\rduring recumbency in both groups but\rincreased sodium excretion upright only\rin the edematous patients to equal that\rof the normal subjects.  creatinine excre-\rtion was not changed in either group by\rposture or drug therapy.  similar studies\rwere performed on 5 patients with un-\rtreated diabetes insipidus and on 6 pa-\rtients with adrenal insufficiency treated\rwith hydrocortisone alone.  lack of al-\rdosterone (in adrenal insufficiency) did\rnot increase the amount of sodium ex-\rcreted above that of normal subjects in\rrecumbency and did not prevent the oc-\rcurrence of significant sodium retention\rin the upright posture.  however, lack\rof adh (in diabetes insipidus) delayed\rthe antidiuresis upright for 30 minutes.\rthe results indicate that adh release\ris probably responsible for the reduction\rin urine volume during the first 30 min-\rutes after assuming the upright posture,\rbut not thereafter.  the excessive magni-\rtude of the orthostatic antidiuresis in\ridiopathic edema probably results from\ra cause other than adh release, since it\ris not completely overcome by ethanol.\rreduced na excretion during 2 hours in\rthe upright posture can occur in the\rabsence of circulating aldosterone, but\rthe abnormal magnitude of the na re-\rtention in the patients with idiopathic\redema probably results from hyperal-\rdosteronism.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (695,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the use and mode of action of ethacrynic acid\rin nephrogenic diabetes insipidus\rthe use of diuretic agents in the treatment\rof nephrogenic diabetes insipidus had been re-\rported to result in decreased urine volume\rand decreased clearance of free water.  a\rstudy of the use of ethacrynic acid, a potent\rsaluretic agent, was instituted in patients\rwith nephrogenic diabetes insipidus in an\rattempt to achieve a significant antidiuretic\rresponse while allowing a liberal sodium diet.\rintravenous ethacrynic acid resulted in de-\rcreased urine volume, decreased clearance of\rfree water and decreased rpf and gfr.\rprolonged oral administration of ethacrynic\racid promoted a significant antidiuretic re-\rsponse when the daily sodium intake was\rlimited to 60 meq.  the effect of ethacrynic\racid on renal function, potassium and chlo-\rride excretion, and uric acid metabolism are\rdiscussed.\r'),
 (696,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the treatment of pituitary responsive\rdiabetes insipidus\rin evaluating therapy in diabetes insipidus, it is important to note we\rare altering only ten per cent of the reabsorption function of the kidney.\rthe kidney function in a case of diabetes insipidus is as efficient in its\ractivity as are biological tests.  the purpose of therapy is patient\rconvenience, economy, and normal function in society.  the diabetes insipidus\ritself does not alter the life span, however, secondary factors may introduce\rit into a health problem.\rlysyl-8-vasopressin nasal spray is effective, offers a maximum of conve-\rnience, and has produced no untoward reactions.\rit is, as expected, ineffective in the treatment of extrapituitary (pituitary\runresponsive) diabetes insipidus.\r'),
 (697,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'antidiuretic effect of hydrochlorothiazide\rin diabetes insipidus\rand ch\'iuan-lu\r12 cases of diabetes insipidus\rwere studied during hydrochlorothia-\rzide therapy under a fixed diet.  the\rsymptoms, blood pressure, urinary\rvolume, blood and urinary electrolytes,\rplasma volume, electrocardiogram and\rhypertonic saline intravenous drip test\rwere compared before and after treat-\rment.\ra daily dose of 100-150 mg\rbrought down the urinary volume to\rabout 50% of the pretreatment value.\rthe initial antidiuretic effect was noted\r8 hours after medication and the\rmaximal effect after the fourth or fifth\rday.  owing to the kaluretic action of\rthe drug, 2-4 gm of potassium salt was\ralso given each day.  satisfactory re-\rsults were obtained with dietary sodium\rion at not more than 200 meq daily, but\ringestion of excessive table salt fre-\rquently diminished or even destroyed\rthe therapeutic effect.\rthe physical signs, blood pres-\rsure and ecg were essentially un-\rchanged and the plasma volumes were\raltered after treatment.  the hyper-\rtonic saline test was improved in some\rof the patients.\rlow salt syndrome was fre-\rquently encountered as the therapy\rcontinued over 1 month.  but this and\reven secondary failure could be pre-\rvented by timely use of intermittent or\ralternative regimen.\rthe therapeutic mechanism,\rindications and side effects of the drug\rwere briefly discussed.  the drug might\rpossibly act through the mechanism of\rsalt depletion, contraction of extracel-\rlular fluid volume and decrease of renal\rglomerular filtrate, and in consequence\rurinary volume decreases and thirst is\ralleviated.\r'),
 (698,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of hydrochlorothiazide on water intake\rand plasma osmolality in diabetes insipidus in\rthe rat\ra fall in plasma osmolality accompanied the reduction of urine volume in\rrats with hypothalamic diabetes insipidus, given hydrochlorothiazide and an\rotherwise normal diet.  the plasma concentration was not reduced with a\rhigh sodium intake, although urine volume still fell.  normal rats and hypo-\rthalamic obese rats increased their water turnover after hydrochlorothiazide,\ryet their plasma concentration fell.  moreover the antidiuretic response to\rvasopressin, which is purely renal, was also accompanied by plasma dilution;\ralthough it is self-evident that rats which drink less are less thirsty, the\rreduction in thirst after hydrochlorothiazide may not be a direct result of the\rchange in plasma osmolality.\ras previously shown in patients (kennedy and hill, 1963) a high sodium\rintake increased free water clearance in diabetes insipidus but did not\rinterfere with the reduction of polyuria by hydrochlorothiazide, whereas a high\rpotassium intake reduced free water clearance and prevented any effect of the\rdrug on urine volume.\r'),
 (699,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'antidiuretic properties of chlorothiazide\rin diabetes insipidus dogs\rchlorothiazide was found to decrease\rurine volume and increase urine con-\rcentration in diabetes insipidus dogs.\rthere was no change in gfr, rpf,\rtmpah, plasma volume, extracellular\rfluid or total body water.  the one con-\rsistent altered function was a decrease\rin \"free water\" clearance.  diazoxide and\rmercuhydrin were not antidiuretic.  it is\rbelieved that the antidiuretic action is\rdependent on the chlorothiazide-induced\rsaluresis.  although the mechanism of\rthis antidiuresis has not been clearly de-\rfined, it seems best explained by postu-\rlating a decrease in filtrate reaching the\rdistal nephron (giving a decreased final\rurine volume) coupled with inhibition of\rsolute reabsorption in the distal tubule\r(preventing the selective reabsorption of\rsolute in the distal tubule that is nor-\rmally seen, accounting for the increase\rin urine concentration).  the possible\rrole of the mineralocorticoids in the\rantidiuretic response to chlorothiazide\rtherapy was investigated in diabetes in-\rsipidus and adrenalectomized dogs.  ad-\rministration of sodium-retaining steroids\rto diabetes insipidus dogs did not re-\rproduce the urinary changes associated\rwith chlorothiazide therapy.  in addition,\rthe antidiuretic response to chlorothia-\rzide was not altered by adrenalectomy\ror spironolactone administration.  there-\rfore, the presence of the sodium-retain-\ring steroids are not essential for the anti-\rdiuretic response of chlorothiazide in\rdiabetes insipidus.\r'),
 (700,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stable strontium in human bone: geographical and age\rdifferences in the united kingdom and their\rcorrelation with levels of strontium-90\ra re-assessment has been made of published data of other workers on sr and\r90sr in human bone.  in different parts of great britain the mean ratio of\rstable sr to ca in adult human bones ranged\rfrom 240 to 475ug/g.  extreme values\rwere found even as close as 40 miles apart (carlisle v. westmorland).\rperinatal levels of stable sr were correlated with adult levels.  an estimate\rof placental discrimination may be derived from the ratio, perinatal level:\radult level of about 0.7.\rthe concentration of stable sr in bones of children from 2 to 5 years old or\rmore was not demonstrably different from that of adults except in one area,\rcarlisle.  with the striking exception of london and south-east england the\rchange from perinatal to adult levels occurred in the 2nd year of life: there\rwas no particular change during the first 9 months or so.  in london and\rsouth-east england the pattern of change with age was quite different: there\rwas a progressive rise in sr level from shortly after birth to the end of the\r1st year by which time adult levels were reached.  it is concluded that\rgeographical differences need to be taken into account when making\rphysiological deductions about turnover of bone salt from changes with age in\rthe level of stable sr.\rwhen children in the south-east of england and the rest of the united kingdom\rwere compared, there seemed to be a broad inverse correlation between levels of\rstable sr and of 90sr.\rdetailed analysis of perinatal results from one area suggested that the level\rof stable sr in bone was somewhat higher in summer than in winter and somewhat\rhigher in anatomically normal babies than in babies dying with gross congenital\rdefects.  90sr showed the seasonal change only.\r'),
 (701,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fibrin and thrombosis in the central nervous system\rin children with particular reference to\rcongenital hydrocephalus\rwhile rare metabolic and degenerative diseases of\rthe central nervous system in children are reported\rat great length, the much commoner diseases\rrelating to vascular incidents are rarely discussed.\ronly those aspects of disease of the central\rnervous system related to thrombosis and the\rdeposition of fibrin will be discussed here; diseases\rrelated to general vasculitis and aneurysm are\romitted.  the conditions discussed here fall into two\rmain categories: first, the presence of thrombosis in\rsmall blood vessels or in the large superficial veins\rdraining the brain, and second, the deposition of\rfibrin either in the ventricles or on the membranes\roverlying the brain in association with thrombotic\rlesions, haemorrhage, or infiltration.\r'),
 (702,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus due to unrecognized cerebellar\rastrocytoma treated by ventriculoatrial\rshunt for four years\ra case of a 9-year-old girl is presented in whom prolonged palliation of signs\rof increased intracranial pressure, presumed to be due to aqueductal\robstruction, was achieved by means of a ventriculoatrial shunt.  four years\rafter placement of the shunt, signs of a cerebellar mass became apparent.\rthe neoplasm, a cystic astrocytoma, was subsequently totally resected and\rthe shunt was removed.  air studies demonstrating diminution of ventricular\rsize within this four year period are compared.\r'),
 (703,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus\rthe problem of hydrocephalus, formerly a hopeless one, has in recent years\rbegun to yield to clinical research.  the indications for the new forms of\rtreatment, and their drawbacks, are clearly delineated in this discussion by a\rleading authority in the field.\r'),
 (704,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a case of unilateral hydrocephalus secondary to occlusion of\rone foramen of monro\ra unique case of unilateral obstructive hydro-\rcephalus secondary to occlusion of one foramen of\rmonro by gliomatosis in a 3-day-old infant is\rreported.\r'),
 (705,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'calcification within congenital aneurysms\rof the vein of galen\rthirty-one cases of aneurysm of the\rvein of galen had been reported previ-\rously.  calcification within the wall of the\raneurysm was visible on plain skull roent-\rgenograms in 6 of this number.  the present\rcommunication describes an additional\rcase in which calcification of the aneurysm\rwas discovered at the age of 9 years, the\ryoungest patient heretofore reported.\r'),
 (706,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ventriculo-venous shunts for infantile hydrocephalus\ra review of 48 hydrocephalic patients\rtreated with atrioventricular shunts during a\r5-year period has been presented.  we have\rdiscussed function of the shunt, complica-\rtions of the procedure, and revisions neces-\rsitated by nonfunctioning.  the overall 75\rper cent survival rate and 14.3 per cent in-\rfection rate is comparable to that in other\rseries.  the major cause of death in our pa-\rtients has been infection.\rour experience to date supports the ob-\rservation that spontaneous arrest of the hy-\rdrocephalic process does not occur once a\rventriculo-venous shunt has been estab-\rlished.\rmeticulous introduction of a ventriculo-\rvenous shunt appears to be the present treat-\rment of choice for patients with severe hy-\rdrocephalus.  results are only satisfactory\rwhen the patients are carefully followed\rand complications recognized and treated\rpromptly.\r'),
 (707,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital malformations of c.n.s.\rit seems that only a small proportion of malformations of\rthe central nervous system can be explained in simple genetical\rterms and that most are dependent, to some extent at least,\ron environmental factors.  the nature of these has yet to be\rdetermined.  dr. williamson found that the maternal aunts,\runcles, and cousins of her index cases of anencephalus and\rspina bifida were more frequently affected than the paternal\rrelatives were.  she suggested that mothers of affected\rchildren had some genetic factor which modifies the intra-\ruterine environment and thus predisposes the embryo to these\rmalformations.  such a hypothesis opens up interesting\rpossibilities, but before accepting it one would have to be\rsatisfied that the higher incidence in maternal relatives is\rnot merely due to the fact that the history is obtained in\rmost cases from the mother.\r'),
 (708,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experimental studies on cerebrospinal\rfluid flow\ra mixed suspension of kaolin and lyco-\rpodium was injected into the cisterna magna\rof dogs.  blockade of csf space was produced\rsuccessfully in 63 of 75 dogs; in 48 of the 63,\rventricular dilatation of more than interme-\rdiate degree was observed.\rin these hydrocephalic dogs experimental\rshunting was performed either between the\rlateral ventricle and the lumbar cistern or be-\rtween the unilateral lateral ventricle and the\rcontralateral cerebral subarachnoid space.  uni-\rdirectional, steady csf flow averaged 0.15 ml. per\rhour in the cases of the former shunting,\rand the flow averaged 0.25 ml. per hour in the\rcases of the latter shunting.\rcsf flow rate from the ventricle toward the\rcerebral subarachnoid space was larger when\rintraventricular pressure was higher.  this in-\rcrease in flow rate parallel to increasing pres-\rsure probably results from an increase in csf\rabsorption.  there seems to be an upper limit\rof the flow rate as the pressure is raised.\rtransient reflux of csf flow was induced by\rjugular or abdominal compression.\rfollowing intravenous administration of hy-\rpertonic solutions, csf flow rate decreased\rparallel to the fall of csf pressure and re-\rgained the original value as the pressure was\rrecovered.  when the pressure fell as low as\r50 mm. of water the flow almost stopped.\r'),
 (709,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the dandy-walker syndrome\rthe dandy-walker syndrome is a specific\rmorbid entity in which the fourth ventricle\ris grossly dilated and there is a congenital\rmalformation of the cerebellar vermis.  it is\rnearly always associated with atresia of the\rforamen of magendie, and in many cases with\ratresia of the foramina of luschka also.  the\rlateral and third ventricles are usually dilated.\rfigure 1 illustrates a specimen of the condition.\rmost cases present in infancy, but others are\rdiscovered in childhood and in adult life.  the\roldest patient recorded to have had this anomaly\rwas aged 59 years.  the first recognized case\rwas published by dandy and blackfen in 1914,\rbut the best early description of the condition\ris that of taggart and walker (1944), who\rconcluded that the cerebellar lesions were\rconsequent upon the atresia of the foramen of\rmagendie.  in 1954 benda proposed the term\r\"dandy-walker syndrome\".\r'),
 (710,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a probable epidemic of congenital\rhydrocephalus in 1940-1941\ra peak in the incidence of congenital hydrocephalus in 1940-41 is described;\rreasons are given for believing it to be a genuine phenomenon, though it is too\rlate to find the cause.\repidemics of malformations are to be detected promptly only if the incidence\rof malformations in a defined population is studied continuously; and for some\repidemics the population studied must be very large indeed.\r'),
 (711,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'functional craniology: an aid in\rinterpreting roentgenograms\rof the skull\ranalysis of the form of the skull is\rfacilitated by considering it to be composed\rof a number of functional components.  for\rthe roentgenologist\'s purposes, division into\rthe facial or somatic skeleton and the neu-\rral skeleton is valuable, as is the recognition\rof three functionally separate portions\rwithin each calvarial bone: the inner table,\rthe diploe and the outer table.\rthe base of the skull is the only por-\rtion that is preformed in cartilage.  this ac-\rcounts for the unusual appearance of the\rskull in achondroplasia.  in addition, the\rbase apparently is more closely related to\rfacial and general somatic growth than to\rneural growth.\rcalvarial bone forms directly from\rmembrane within the cerebral capsule.\rconsequently, the size and shape of the cal-\rvaria directly reflect the form of the grow-\ring neural mass.\rthe inner table of the calvaria at all\rages is intimately related to the dura mater\rand directly reflects the form of the dura\rmater.  consequently, the inner table re-\rflects the form of the arachnoid mater and,\rusually, of the brain as well.\rthe outer table of the calvaria serves\rnot only to protect the brain but also to\ranchor many of the intrinsic and extrinsic\rmuscles of the skull.  its form, particularly\rin thick-skulled mammals such as the pig,\ris determined more by the demands of these\rmuscles and of the scalp than by the form\rof the brain.\rthe principal function of the diploe\ris to form a lightweight yet rigid separation\rof the two osseous tables.  in addition, it\rserves as a site of hematopoiesis; for this\rreason it may tend to a specific volume at a\rgiven age.\rthe calvarial sutures oppose separa-\rtion of the bones of the calvaria while al-\rlowing relative motion between them.\rwhen the calvarial bones are passively car-\rried apart with the expanding cerebral cap-\rsule by the growth of the neural mass, their\rareas are increased by the deposition of\rbone in the suture margins.  the sutures,\rhowever, do not function as epiphyses and\rhave no innate growth potential: removal\rof a suture does not disturb final skull form.\rbecause the calvaria represents ossi-\rfication of the cerebral capsule, it is small\rwhen the neural mass is small.  the de-\rformity of the skull and the secondary\rchanges that occur in the air sinuses and\rthe diploe can be explained in terms of\rthe functional cranial components.  the op-\rposite changes occur when the neural mass\ris abnormally large.\rthe correlation between skull size and\rintelligence is only fair.  the presence of a\rbrain of distinctly abnormal size, however,\rmay be inferred from plain roentgeno-\rgrams of the skull.\rpremature closure of the cranial su-\rtures may be due to an abnormal form of\rthe cranial base and possibly of the primi-\rtive chondrocranium that precedes it.  the\rabnormality is mediated through the dural\rfiber tracts that underlie the major cal-\rvarial sutures.\r'),
 (712,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus: changes in formation and absorption\rof cerebrospinal fluid within the\rcerebral ventricles\rformation, flow and absorption of\rcerebrospinal fluid were measured in normal\rand progressively hydrocephalic dogs by\rsteady-state studies during ventricular per-\rfusion.  the formation of cerebrospinal fluid\rwas found to be constant, independent of\rhydrostatic pressure, and unaffected by the\rdevelopment of hydrocephalus.  the normal\rdog produced 0.016 ml. cerebrospinal fluid\r/min. in the lateral ventricles, 0.011 ml. cere-\rbrospinal fluid/min. in the 4th ventricle and\r0.20 ml. cerebrospinal fluid/min. in the sub-\rarachnoid space.  the intraventricular forma-\rtion of fluid was calculated to be 0.24 ml.\rcerebrospinal fluid/min./gm. of choroid\rplexus, and 0.3x10-3 ml. cerebrospinal fluid\r/min./cm.2 of ependymal surface.\rabsorption of cerebrospinal fluid was\rfound to take place within the ventricles as\rwell as in the subarachnoid spaces.  the re-\rsistance to absorption of cerebrospinal fluid\rin the normal ventricle was much higher than\rin the hydrocephalic ventricle.  the decrease\rin resistance occurred as the ventricular\rvolume increased and the ependyma became\rflattened so that in chronic hydrocephalus\rthe resistance was not significantly different\rthan in the normal dog.  the theory of re-\rstricted diffusion was applied to the data to\rcalculate the diffusive permeabilities of crea-\rtinine and urea, and from this the mean pore\rradius within the ventricle.\rusing formation of cerebrospinal fluid\rand data on absorption, the hydrocephalic\ranimals could not be distinguished from the\rnormal with sufficient accuracy to suggest\rusing this as a clinical test.  the reason for\rthis is that intraventricular pressure has\ralways been considered as if it were constant\rwhen, in fact, it is changing constantly.  the\rproblem of ventricular enlargement concerns\rthe ability of the craniospinal contents to\radjust to and absorb the small but very rapid\rchanges in intracranial contents that occur\rwith each beat of the pulse.\r'),
 (713,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dural sinus pressure\rin normal and hydrocephalic dogs\rsimultaneous measurement of cerebro-\rspinal fluid pressure (csfp) and venous\rpressure in the anterior (ssvp) and poste-\rrior sagittal sinus (tvp) has demonstrated\rthat in the normal dog the mean pressures are\rrelated as follows: csfp>ssvp>tvp.\rthe statistical relationship between the pres-\rsures has shown a poor correlation of ssvp\rand tvp with changes in csfp.  on the\rother hand, in the hydrocephalic dog, ssvp\rrises to meet csfp and is related to fluid\rpressure in a 1:1 fashion.  this could be ex-\rpected to cause a \"non venting\" of acute\rchanges of csfp and a decrease in fluid ab-\rsorption.  it is postulated that the mechanism\rof ssvp elevation is a partial occlusion of\rthe sinus.\r'),
 (714,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'intraventricular papilloma\ra case of intraventricular papilloma of the left\rlateral ventricle is reported.  craniotomy was\rperformed and removal of the tumor was ac-\rcomplished without incident.\rthe literature is reviewed.\ran unusual although perhaps relatively unim-\rportant observation in the reported case was that\rfor four or five days postoperatively the patient,\ra 17-month-old female, kept her head tilted to\rthe right but at the time she left the hospital she\rwas holding it erect and unsupported and was\rsustaining weight satisfactorily on both feet.\r'),
 (715,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'five-year comparative study of hydrocephalus in\rchildren with and without operation (113 cases)\ron the basis of a 5-year study of 113 hy-\rdrocephalic children of whom 65 were oper-\rated on early with ventriculo-atrial shunting\rand 48 were not operated on, all of them hav-\ring been studied periodically in a similar\rmanner to determine mortality, morbidity,\rintelligence, and related factors, the follow-\ring conclusions are justified:\rthe program in which shunting opera-\rtions were done apparently gives significant\radvantages to the children over the program\rin which no shunting operations were done\r(based on life-table data projected from birth\rto 10 years)\rsurvival: 61.8 per cent as compared to\r22.2 per cent;\rnumber of competent children (i.q. of\r75 or better): 33.8 per cent vs. 5.5 per\rcent;\rnumber of noncompetitive children\r(i.q. below 75): 27.6 per cent vs. 16.7\rper cent.\rthe major cause of death and morbid-\rity in both groups is infection.\rin the operative group, morbidity\rassociated with the shunting procedure is\rrelated to obstruction of the shunt and\rsepticemia.  the early occlusions show a\rcorrelation with abnormal, inflammatory\rtype of spinal fluid being shunted into the\rblood stream.  the late obstructions are\rassociated with mechanical breakage of the\rshunt or factors of growth causing retraction\rof the cardiac end from the atrium.  prompt\rre-establishment of a functioning shunt has\rbeen possible in all instances.  periodic follow-\rup examinations, irrespective of symptoms,\rhave proved invaluable in early recognition\rof malfunctioning shunts.  septicemia usually\rrequired removal of the shunt.\rfrom the program of periodic evalua-\rtions, including \"bubble\" ventriculograms,\rstudies of clearance of risa, and psycho-\rlogical testings, correlations showed:\rintellectual ability seemed associated\rwith width of cerebral mantle;\rwidth of cerebral mantle in hydrocepha-\rlus decreases with ventricular pressures\rof 120 or over; it increases with pres-\rsures less than this;\rprolonged shunting of cerebrospinal\rfluid can give dramatic increase in\rwidth of cerebral mantle, apparently\rirrespective of basic etiology of the\rhydrocephalus;\rintellectual capacity could not be cor-\rrelated with the basic etiology of the\rhydrocephalus, but did correlate in-\rversely with duration of increased in-\rtracranial pressure.\rthe many etiologies of hydrocephalus\rrequire large numbers of patients in each\rgroup for thorough evaluation.  factors\rfavoring such studies should be carried out in\rmedical centers where appropriate disciplines\rcan study in depth.  prevention should be the\rultimate goal.\rin the operative group, only 1 patient\rcompensated his hydrocephalic process and\rno single patient demonstrated \"arrest\" of or\rrecovery from the basic hydrocephalus-pro-\rducing process in spite of numerous attempts\rto demonstrate this.  this might imply a\rnecessity for life-long shunting of cerebro-\rspinal fluid in these cases.\r'),
 (716,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus\rany present day definition of\rhydrocephalus is very loose.  the\rauthors would rather adopt the\rconcept that hydrocephalus is an\rabnormal condition characterized\rby excessive amount of cerebrospi-\rnal fluid with or without enlarge-\rment of the head.\rthe most common cause of\rhydrocephalus is arachnoiditis fol-\rlowed by congenital anomalies.  a\rneoplasm is a rare cause.\rthe ideal surgical procedure\ris the placement of a ventriculo-\ratrial shunt, using either pudenz\ror halter valves.  where these\rvalves cannot be availed of the\rchoice is between a conservative\rwaiting with medical support and\rventricular tapping from the older\rsurgical shunting procedures, like,\rventriculo-peritoneal, choroidoplex-\rectomy, thecal-fimbia, subarach-\rnoid-ureteral, and others.\r'),
 (717,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recognition and treatment of hydrocephalus following\rspontaneous subarachnoid hemorrhage\reight adult patients with hydrocephalus\rsecondary to spontaneous subarachnoid hem-\rorrhage have been presented with a discus-\rsion of diagnosis and treatment.  a number of\rpossible mechanisms for the development of\rventricular dilatation in this condition have\rbeen advanced and pathological data have\rbeen presented in 2 cases.\r'),
 (718,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital malformations.\rclinical and community considerations\rtwo of the most significant medical\revents of the century, the epidemic of\rpost-rubella anomalies in australia\rduring 1940 and 1941 and the pan-\rdemic of thalidomide embryopathies\rin europe and elsewhere during 1960\rand 1961, have demonstrated clearly\rthe importance of monitoring programs\rto record the occurrence of congenital\rmalformations at group (for example,\rhospital) and community (especially\rcity) levels.  the principle of report-\ring malformations and utilizing the\rdata for service programs or, better\rstill, for prevention, is not new, but\rthe methodical use of vital statistics\rin a scientifically constructed surveil-\rlance system is new.  so also is the\rjoint endeavor on the part of clinicians,\rpublic health workers and basic scien-\rtists to reconstruct an epidemiology of\rdeformity on the basis of time, place,\rperson distributions of malformations.\ra primary need has been for stand-\rardized methods of classifying and\rreporting congenital malformations.\r'),
 (719,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the family history of spina bifida cystica\rthe family histories of 722 infants who\rwere born with spina bifida cystica were\rstudied.\rthe index cases were referred for sur-\rgical treatment and were not selected in any\rway from the genetic point of view.\rintensive inquiries were made to ob-\rtain a complete family pedigree, including\ra prospective follow-up of siblings born after\rthe index case.\rof 1,256 siblings 85 or 6.8% had gross\rmalformation of the central nervous system:\rspina bifida cystica in 54, anencephaly in 22,\rand uncomplicated hydrocephalus in 9.\rof 306 children born after the index\rcase 25 (8%) or 1 in 12 were affected.\rthere was a progressive increase in\rmultiple cases in the family with increasing\rfamily size.  in sibships of five or more, mul-\rtiple cases occurred in 24.1%.\rin 118 families cases of gross malfor-\rmation of the central nervous system were\rknown to have occurred among members of\rthe family other than siblings.  cases oc-\rcurred in three generations.\rit is possible that spina bifida cystica\rmight be a recessively inherited condition.\r'),
 (720,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pulmonary vascular changes complicating\rventriculovascular shunting for hydrocephalus\ra patient is described in whom pulmonary hypertension and cor\rpulmonale were noted 3 years after placement of a ventriculovascular\rshunting apparatus for treatment of hypdrocephalus.  in addition,\rthe histologic sections of lung tissue obtained from 65 patients with hy-\rdrocephalus who died at various intervals following placement of a\rventriculovascular shunting apparatus were reviewed with regard to vas-\rcular alterations.  a high incidence of \"old\" and \"multiple\" pulmonary\rvascular lesions was found in this group compared to the incidence\rin control subjects.  this difference can be attributed to the operative\rprocedure.  the lesions in postmortem material were not\rwidespread and did not suggest the diagnosis\rof pulmonary hypertension on purely histologic grounds.\r'),
 (721,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'etiology of trypan blue induced antenatal\rhydrocephalus in the albino rat\rwistar strain albino rats were injected with 1 cm3 of a 1% solution\rof trypan blue.  three types of dye were used: matheson, coleman and bell,\rchroma-gesellschaft and a highly purified sample.  the dyes were injected on\rdays 6, 7, and 8 of gestation.  fetuses were excised from days 16 through 20,\rfixed, decalcified where necessary, embedded in paraffin, serially sectioned\rand stained.  newborn young were treated similarly.  chroma-gesellschaft\rtrypan blue was without reproductive or teratogenic effect at the above doses.\rincreasing the dose did not increase the teratogenicity but did yield a\rdecrease in litter size.  both matheson, coleman and bell trypan blue and the\rpurified sample were teratogenic.  the most frequent neural defect observed\rwas hydrocephalus.  serial sections of the newborn hydrocephalics showed an\roccluded or extremely tenotic aqueduct of sylvius in 31 of 33 sectioned\ranimals.  the fetuses collected from days 18 through 20 also had occluded or\rstenotic aqueducts if hydrocephalic.  aqueductal stenosis or occlusion was\rpresent in 17-day-old fetuses, but hydrocephalus was not conclusively\rdemonstrated at this age.  sixteen-day-old fetuses did not have aqueductal\rocclusion in any of those examined, but stenosis was evident.  it is concluded\rthat the defect predisposing to hydrocephalus in the young of trypan blue\rtreated rats of this strain is aqueductal stenosis or occlusion.\r'),
 (722,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bilateral papilloma of the choroid plexus\ra rare case of bilateral papilloma of the choroid plexus\rin a five-and-a-half-year old hydrocephalic girl is pre-\rsented.\rthe tumor encountered at autopsy was not suspected\rduring life, the existing hydrocephalus being attributed\rto either cytomegalic inclusion disease or toxoplasmosis.\rafter post mortem examination, it was evident that\rthe hydrocephalus was due to two factors; hypersecretion\rfrom the tumor itself, and obstruction at the level of the\rsylvian aqueduct by a delicate, tense, translucent mem-\rbrane.\ran interesting and uncommon additional feature of\rthis case was the presence, within the choroidal papillo-\rma, of well-formed haversian bone.\ra plea is made for regularly considering papilloma of\rthe choroid plexus in the differential diagnosis of hydro-\rcephalus in children, for here, early diagnosis and treat-\rment might conceivably result in total cure.\r'),
 (723,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the diagnosis of hydrocephalus\rthe early diagnosis of hydrocephalus\ris imperative if definitive steps for\rits correction are to be effective.\rtransillumination is a fairly accurate\rprocedure that may offer the earliest\rmeans of determining whether or not\rthe infant\'s head is enlarging.\rhowever, serial head measurements\rconstitute the easiest and most\raccurate method for early detection\rof hydrocephalus.  charts of normal\rhead size of full-term and premature\rinfants are available to aid the\rphysician in evaluating any deviation\rfrom normal.  once the condition has\rbeen detected, it is up to the\rneurosurgeon to determine the\rtreatment plan.  the operative procedure\rmost widely used for shunting the\rexcessive cerebrospinal fluid is\rinsertion of a spitz-holter valve.\rearly detection and improved treatment\rmethods will help prevent irreversible\rintellectual damage likely to develop\rif hydrocephalus continues unchecked.\r'),
 (724,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'infantile hydrocephalus and hematoma in the posterior fossa\rwe have presented a case of hydrocephalus in\ran infant, the basic cause being intracranial\rhemorrhage in the perinatal period.  surgical re-\rmoval of a hematoma in the posterior fossa did not\rgive permanent relief of the raised intracranial\rpressure.  a lumbar air study at this stage dis-\rclosed information that the passage through the\rintracerebral cerebrospinal-fluid pathways was\rnormalized whereas the extracerebral ones still\rwere occluded by arachnoiditis.  the condition\rnecessitated a ventriculo-atrial shunt.\r'),
 (725,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'urinary excretion of i131-diodrast injected intraventricularly\rin communicating hydrocephalus and aqueduct stenosis\rnine cases of expansive infantile hydro-\rcephalus were investigated by injecting\rsmall amounts of i131-diodrast intra-\rventricularly.  urinary excretion of the\rtracer was determined during the first\r4-5 hours after injection.  the cumulative\rexcretion of diodrast from the c.s.f. dif-\rfers in cases with communicating hydro-\rcephalus from those with stenosis of the\raqueduct.  the investigation is rapid and\reasily performed and has not produced any\rside effects.\r'),
 (726,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'gastrointestinal\rulceration and central\rnervous system lesions\rthere is both a real and an apparent in-\rcrease in the incidence of severe gastroin-\rtestinal ulceration due to central nervous\rlesions.  some of this increased incidence\rreflects recently devised iatrogenic measures\rincluding new drugs and surgical therapy.\rin adults, cerebrovascular lesions are the\rcommonest single cause of acute peptic ul-\rceration found at autopsy.  in children, we\rfound 25 instances of upper gastrointestinal\rulceration due to central nervous system le-\rsions in 1,750 autopsies.  two general ana-\rtomical categories could be recognized: acute\rulceration and malacias.\ra variety of causative central nervous sys-\rtem lesions was responsible in these 25 cases,\rthe commonest being bacterial meningitis.\rother causes were poliomyelitis, brain tu-\rmor, hydrocephalus, etc.\rtheories of pathogenesis are presented.\rmore experience with both drug and surgical\rtherapy is needed.  the recent development\rof local freezing techniques offers promise\rfor reduction of mortality.\r'),
 (727,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mansonia crassipes as the natural vector of filarioids, plasmodium gallinaceum\rand other plasmodia of fowls in ceylon\rit would appear from these\robservations that m.\rcrassipes is the natural vector of\rp. gallinaceum of fowls\rin ceylon and possibly of other\rspecies of plasmodium of\rfowls or of related avian hosts.\rif one of the other\rplasmodia from m. crassipes is\rin fact p. lophurae\rthen this will be the first record\rof p. lophurae from\rthis part of the world.  we are,\rhowever, not certain\rwhether the fowl is the natural\rvertebrate host of\rp. lophurae in ceylon.\rwe have seen crithidial forms in\rthe midgut of engorged\rwild-caught m. crassipes.  this\rmosquito may, therefore,\rprove to be the vector of the\rtrypanosome as well.  the\rtrypanosome differs from\rtrypanosoma gallinarum and\rt. calmettei which have previously\rbeen reported from\rfowls.\r'),
 (728,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'filariasis in portuguese timor, with observations on a new microfilaria\rfound in man\rthe results are described of an\rinvestigation into filariasis in portuguese timor.\rtwo types of microfilariae were\rfound in blood films: one was wuchereria bancrofti\rand the other, referred to as the timor\rmicrofilaria, is probably a new species.\rblood surveys showed that w.\rbancrofti and the timor microfilaria were widely\rdistributed in the territory but that infection\rrates were usually low.\rclinical lesions were few and mild;\relephantiasis was confined to oedema of the\rlower limbs below the knee.\rthe timor microfilaria resembles\rthat of brugia malayi in general staining\rreaction and appearance and in the possession\rof two nuclei in the terminal thread, but\rdiffers in over-all length, in cephalic-space ratio,\rand in failure of the sheath to stain with\rgiemsa.  it is nocturnally periodic.  it was\rrapidly removed from the peripheral blood\rby treatment with diethylcarbamazine citrate\rin daily doses of 9.3-13.3 mgm. per kgm. body\rweight or 3.3-5.0 mgm. per kgm. body weight\rfor seven days.  only damaged fragments of\radult female worms were recovered.\rthe timor microfilaria was not\rfound in cats, dogs or monkeys.\rthe vectors of filariasis in timor\rare still unknown.\r'),
 (729,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dipetalonema obtusa (mccoy,1936) comb. n. (filarioidea:\ronchocercidae) in colombian primates, with a description of the adult\rmicrofilaria obtusa mccoy, 1936, was identified in\rthe blood of 29 (31%) of 93 cebus\rcapucinus and c. albifrons from northern colombia, but was not\rfound in an additional 42 c. apella and\r99 saimiri sciurea from other areas in colombia.  the adult male\rand female, recovered from the peri-\resophageal connective tissue of the infected animals, are described\rin detail.  dipetalonema obtusa (mc-\rcoy, 1936) comb. n. resembles tetrapetalonema marmosetae faust,\r1935, but is smaller and the right\rspicule is complex, not simple.\r'),
 (730,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'experimental onchocercal ocular lesions in the chimpanzee\rthis is the first attempt to produce\ronchocercal eye lesions with microfilariae of\ro. volvulus in the chimpanzee.\rlive microfilariae, once in the anterior\rchamber of the eye, could penetrate the an-\rgle of the anterior chamber, the iris, the\rciliary body, the choroid and the vitreous.\rmost of the microfilariae injected alive\rinto the anterior chamber of the eyes of the\rchimpanzee died within a short time.  com-\rparison, therefore, could not be made be-\rtween the effects of live and dead micro-\rfilariae.\rmicrofilariae debris was demonstrated\rwithin giant cells for the first time.\rsubconjunctival and limbal infiltration\rwith incipient pannus, inflammation within\rthe trabecular meshwork of the angle of the\ranterior chamber and extensive active iri-\rdocyclitis were demonstrated in histologic\rsections, although the conditions were clini-\rcally quiescent.\rthe posterior segment lesion of oncho-\rcercal chorioretinal degeneration could not\rbe reproduced.\rsubcutaneous and intravenous injec-\rtions of worm extracts, derived from human\ronchocercomas, may have contributed to the\ronset of active choroiditis.  this sensitization\ralone, without the intraocular injection of\rmicrofilariae, had no effects on the eye.\rvarious aspects of the pathogenesis of\rhuman onchocerciasis are discussed on the\rbasis of present experimentation.\r'),
 (731,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the occurence of dirofilaria magnilarvatum price\rand brugia sp. in philippine monkeys\rof 356 macaca philippinensis examined, three were\rfound infected with dirofilaria magnilarvatum price, 1959.\rone of these was infected also with a species of brugla.\rboth species showed a sub-periodic type of microfilarial\rperiodicity.  these observations suggest that philippine\rmacaques may serve as reservoirs for sub-periodic\rb. malayi on palawan, where high rates of infection have\rbeen found in people living in small villages in the\rforests.  mansonia bonneae was found naturally infected\rwith third stage larvae of d. magnilarvatum.  it is sug-\rgested that monkeys may serve as reservoirs for sub-\rperiodic b. malayi on the island of palawan, where high\rrates of infection with this species have been observed\rin people living in small villages in the forest.\r'),
 (732,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the filarial parasites of the eastern gorilla in the congo\ra survey for parasites has been undertaken in 20 mountain\rgorillas (gorilla gorilla beringei) from the eastern congo kivu\rprovince.\rsix full-grown (two males and four females),\rthree adolescents\r(one male and two females), and eleven\ryoung gorillas were\rexamined, some of them during several\rconsecutive months.  nine\rautopsies were performed.\rno protozoa were discovered in the blood.\rplasmodium parasites\rwhich are common in gorillas and chimpanzees\rfrom west africa\rwere never found in the eastern congo primates,\rincluding ten\rother gorillas examined previously and some fifty chimpanzees.\rsevere diarrhoea with a balantidiasis picture developed in two\ryoung gorillas.  autopsy revealed however an intensive infection\rwith oesophagostomum stephanostomum and resulting fatty degenera-\rtion of the liver.  oligotrichida belonging to the genus troglodytella\rwere commonly found in the intestinal tract.  oesophagostomum\rstephanostomum eggs were consistently present in the stools of\rthe gorillas and autoinfection caused the death of several young\rgorillas 4 to 6 weeks after their capture.\rmany microfilariae were found in the blood and the skin.  pre-\rliminary communications were published mentioning the existence\rof four different microfilariae in the blood of gorillas and of three\rothers in the dermal layers of the skin.  after a detailed study seven\rspecies have been identified and described:  dipetalonema leopoldi,\rd. gorillae, d. vanhoofi, d. streptocercum, microfilaria binucleata,\rloa loa gorillae n.subsp. and onchocerca volvulus.  three of the\rworms described have so far been discovered only in gorilla gorilla,\rnamely dipetalonema leopoldi, d. gorillae and loa loa gorillae.  two\rof them were previously known from the chimpanzee, namely\rd. vanhoofi and microfilaria binucleata.  one species, d. strepto-\rcercum, first discovered in man and later described from the chimpan-\rzee, is now also known from gorilla gorilla.  onchocerca volvulus has\rbeen found in only one of the 20 gorillas examined.  gorilla gorilla\rberingei in eastern congo might become through close contact\rwith man and his filarial vectors an abnormal or accidental host of\rd. streptocercum and onchocerca volvulus or else might be considered\ras an original reservoir of these filarial parasites of man.\r'),
 (733,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a pilot project for the control of filariasis\rin thailand\rin a village in kanjanadit district of surat-thani province, south thailand,\rwhere a field station for filariasis studies had been established by the\rbangkok school of tropical medicine, blood films were examined from 977 persons\r(95.5 per cent. of the total population of 1,023).  two thick films (each of\r20 c.mm.) were prepared from each person and stained with giemsa.  it was found\rthat 21.1 per cent. of the people harboured microfilariae (all brugia malayi).\relephantiasis was found in 5.3 per cent. of the population.\rmicrofilarial periodicity was studied in 25 persons; in every case it was\rfound to be markedly nocturnal.\rthe blood of 98 cats, 52 dogs and two monkeys was also examined.  no b. malayi\rlarvae were recovered.\rmosquitoes were caught and identified.  in an initial survey, 4,557 mosquitoes\rwere examined, of which 568 were mansonia spp.  in 4,136 dissections, b. malayi\rlarvae in stage ii were found in one m. uniformis and in stage iii in another;\rthe infection rate for m. uniformis was 0.6 per cent.\rspraying with ddt was carried out in all the houses during the last phase of\rthe investigation.  it resulted in a slight decline in the numbers and\rpercentage of mansonia mosquitoes caught.\rdiethylcarbamazine was administered to as many of the villagers as possible,\rin a dose of 5 mgm. of the citrate salt per kgm. body weight once weekly for\rsix weeks.  eight hundred and eighty-eight persons received the drug (86.8\rper cent. of the population).  considerable side-effects were observed in\rnearly all microfilaria-carriers.  blood examinations were repeated one month\rand again one year after cessation of the drug.  it was found that the\rproportion of microfilaria-carriers had decreased from 21.1 per cent. to 2.2\rand 2.2 per cent. respectively, the filariasis infection rate from 26.1 per\rcent. to 8.6 and 8.5 per cent., and the mean microfilarial density of all films\rfrom 4.8 per 20 c.mm. blood to 0.48 and 0.12.  larvae of b. malayi were not\rfound in mosquitoes dissected one month and one year after the mass therapy.\r'),
 (734,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on loiasis in monkeys.\riv.--experimental hybridization of the human and\rsimian strains of loa\rin the cameroons rain-forest there exist two strains of loa, each apparently\revolving in its own host-vector complex (duke and wijers, 1958).  the natural\rsimian parasite which is found most abundantly in the drill (mandrillus\rleucophaeus), is characterized by the large somatic size of the adult worms\rand microfilariae and by its nocturnal microfilariae periodicity.  it is\rtransmitted among the monkey population by the crepuscular canopy-dwelling\rchrysops langi and c. centurionis.  the natural human parasite has diurnally\rperiodic microfilariae and is transmitted by the day-biting anthropophilic\rc. silacea and c. dimidiata (bombe form).  it can also be transmitted\rexperimentally to the drill, in which host the parasites are of small somatic\rsize and maintain their diurnal periodicity.\ras the two strains of contrasting periodicity can be maintained in drills, it\rwas decided to try cross-mating them to produce hybrids.  the present paper\rdescribes the methods by which this was done, records the characteristics of\rthe hybrid parasites, and suggests that, when interbreeding, the two strains\rsegregate according to a simple mendelian pattern as regards periodicity and\rsomatic size.\r'),
 (735,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'development of dirofilaria immitis in anopheles quadri-\rmaculatus after exposure of the microfilariae to a\rfreezing temperature\rblood samples containing dirofilaria\rimmitis microfilariae were stored frozen for\rperiods ranging from 24 hr to 4 months,\rthawed at 38 1c and\rfed through an animal-derived bandrode membrane to laboratory-reared anopheles\rquadrimaculatus.  the microfilariae were capable of developing to the third or\rinfective larval stage and migrating to the head and labium of the mosquito.\r'),
 (736,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'advances in filariasis\respecially concerning periodicity of microfilariae\ra review is given of some advances in our knowledge about filariasis during the\rpast ten years.\rit is urged that investigations should be continued on methods to facilitate\rthe control of filariasis in large populations, by means of\rdiethylcarbamazine--e.g. incorporation of the compound in cooking salt, as\rwas done with chloroquine against malaria.  furthermore, steps should be taken\rto protect young people against filariasis by systematic treatment in the\rschools.\rin order to understand the cyclical disappearance of microfilariae from the\rperipheral blood and their accumulation in the lungs, the movements of\rmicrofilariae in the pulmonary capillaries has been studied by cinematography.\rapparently their accumulation in the lungs is not due to mechanical retention,\rbut perhaps they migrate round and round in the pre-capillary network of\rarterioles.\rthe periodicity of microfilariae is best considered as a biological rhythm.\rapparently the microfilariae have a circadian rhythm of their own which is\rentrained and synchronized by stimuli from the circadian rhythm of the host.\rjudging by experiments with monkeys containing microfilariae of edesonfilaria\rmalayensis, the most effective of these stimuli from the host seems to be the\rrhythmic variation of body temperature which occurs every 24 hours.\r'),
 (737,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'attempts to transmit wuchereria bancrofti to cats and to a toque monkey\rthere are no records of the larval development of wuchereria bancrofti in\rexperimental animals.  in attempts to transmit periodic w. bancrofti to\rdomestic cats and to a toque monkey we recovered from one of the cats an\rinfective larva that had undergone some development.  this finding was\rreported in a preliminary note (dissanaike and niles, 1963); the present paper\rgives the experimental details and describes the larva.\r'),
 (738,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the periodicity of microfilariae.\rx. the relation between the circadian temperature cycle\rof monkeys and the microfilarial cycle.\rmonkeys were used whose blood contained the microfilariae of edesonfilaria\rmalayensis, which has a nocturnal periodicity.\rartificial lowering of the body temperature during the daytime caused the\rmicrofilaria count in the blood to rise; and artificial raising of the body\rtemperature during the night caused it to fall almost to zero, i.e. inversion\rof the normal circadian temperature rhythm of the body was followed by\rinversion of the microfilarial rhythm.\rthe hypothesis is put forward that the circadian rhythm of the microfilariae\rof e. malayensis (but probably not of the microfilariae of some other species)\ris entrained by the circadian rhythm of body temperature, which thus provides\rthe \"effective stimuli\" to which these microfilariae respond.\r'),
 (739,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the periodicity of microfilariae\rix. transfusion of microfilariae (edesonfilaria) into\rmonkeys at a different phase of the circadian rhythm\rthis paper reports experiments in which microfilariae at one phase of their\rcircadian rhythm were transfused into a host at another phase of the circadian\rrhythm, in an attempt to analyse the relative importance of the rhythms\rinherent in the microfilariae and of those in the host for the production of\rthe well known periodic migrations.  the experiments were performed with\redesonfilaria malayensis (yeh, 1960) present in a macaca monkey from thailand.\r'),
 (740,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'biliary tract morphology and prognosis\rof biliary atresia\rin 86 infants who did not have extrahepatic \"hepatic\" ducts, present\robservation after use of artificial\rbile ducts suggests that the presence of the\rgallbladder may be of good prognostic significance in biliary atresia.\rthere are 11 long-term survivors (as of october 1965) up to 8 1/4 years of\rage (100 months) after use of artificial bile ducts in 86 babies.  a\rgallbladder was identified in 10 of the 11 infants.\rother specific factors for this prolonged survival pattern in these infants\rwith biliary atresia have not yet been identified, although suggestive\rcorrelations among minimal hepatic fibrosis, maximal bile ductule\rproliferations and the presence of the gallbladder were noted.\rit is suspected that if any opportunity for long-term survivals exists for\rinfants to overcome the tragic occurrence of biliary atresia that the\rsurgeon should avoid trauma to the hepatic pedicle.\rwe may be able to provide a \"guarded\" rather than a \"pessimistic\" prog-\rnosis when the gallbladder is found in the babies with biliary atresia.\r'),
 (741,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'current concepts in the management\rof congenital biliary atresia\rthe current management of congenital\rbiliary atresia at the university of cali-\rfornia, los angeles is reviewed.\rbiliary enteric decompression was\rperformed on 18 of the 27 patients, eight\rof whom are presently alive (29.6%).\rthese figures are higher than the cure rate\rof 8% previously reported.\rdescribed recently.  five additional patients\rwith extrahepatic atresia underwent biliary\rdecompression by means of a hepatic\rlymphaticojejunostomy.\rearly diagnosis of biliary atresia is im-\rperative in order that any corrective sur-\rgery may be performed before advanced\rbiliary cirrhosis develops.\r'),
 (742,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital atresia of\rthe extrahepatic bile ducts\rbecause congenital atresia of the extra-\rhepatic biliary tract is almost always fatal,\rexception to this course becomes of interest.\rthe remarkable history of one such infant\rwas reported in 1960 when he had attained\rthe age of 2 1/2 years and, after three opera-\rtions, he was in good health developing nor-\rmally and free of jaundice.  since he is now\r8 1/2 years of age, has had two more opera-\rtions, is still free of jaundice, and is again\rin good health, his further course since 1960\rshould be of interest.\r'),
 (743,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neuroaxonal dystrophy in congenital\rbiliary atresia\rneuroaxonal dystrophy has been described in 8 patients with congenital\rbiliary atresia.  the characteristic changes include axonal dystrophy, a mild\rloss of nerve cells and a variable degree of astrocytic reaction, mainly in the\rgracile, cuneate and trigeminal nerve nuclei in the medulla, and rarely in\rother parts of the central nervous system.\rthe neuroaxonal dystrophy in these patients is remarkably similar to that\rin patients with prolonged mucoviscidosis and in experimental vitamin\re-deficient rats.\rit is strongly suggested that the neuroaxonal dystrophy in these patients\rwith congenital biliary atresia is a manifestation of prolonged vitamin e\rdeficiency.\rthe neuroaxonal dystrophy in these patients is also similar to that seen\rin aging and bears resemblance to the axonal change encountered in a group\rof heredo-degenerative diseases, the various forms of \"hallervorden-spatz\rdisease\".  the pathological similarity between these diverse conditions\rwarrants further investigation as to the possible metabolic\rrelationship between them.\r'),
 (744,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'extrahepatic biliary atresia: comments on the\rfrequency of potentially operable cases\rin a 10 year period, 35 infants with extrahepatic biliary atresia were\rencountered.  twenty-eight babies, who were subjected to surgery and operative\rliver biopsy, are discussed.  although an operable lesion was detected at\rlaparotomy in only one baby, 5 further potentially correctable lesions were\rdiscovered in the 14 necropsies performed.  review of the literature revealed\rthat few authors have discussed necropsy findings and that confirmation of the\rdiagnosis by liver biopsy has been neglected in many cases, including some\rof those claimed as surgical cures.  it is concluded that the frequency of\rpotentially operable forms of biliary atresia is not really known.\r'),
 (745,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'metabolism and excretion of c14-labeled bilirubin in children\rwith biliary atresia\rand judson g. randolph\rradioactive bilirubin was injected intravenously\rinto 3 children with biliary atresia.  the isotope\rover a period of ten to fourteen days was recovered\rprincipally in the urine.  sixty per cent of the label\rin the urine was found to be in the form of bili-\rrubin.  distribution of the radioisotope was observed\rto be principally extravascular but not, as in other\rforms of jaundice, in the same distribution as albumin.\rdaily turnover of bilirubin was several times greater\rthan the calculated normal daily production of bili-\rrubin.  this was assumed to be due to increased\rhemoglobin breakdown, confirmed by survival studies\rof cr51-tagged red cells.  the serum half-life of intra-\rvenously administered radioactive bilirubin may have\ruseful prognostic value in children with biliary atresia.\r'),
 (746,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'central regulation of enzyme activity and synthesis\rin embryonal and adult mammalian tissues\ractivity of non-specific hexokinase (hk) in soluble fraction and,\rparticularly, in mitochondria of embryonal liver is much higher than\rin the adult rabbit; it decreases in the prenatal period, gradually\rapproaching adulthood values postnatally (fig.1).  embryonal liver\rlacks specific glucokinase (gk) (1,2), although during the second half\rof embryonic development there occurs incretion of insulin, known\rto induce gk synthesis in the liver of alloxan diabetic animals (3,4).\ractivity of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (g6p dh) in\rsoluble liver fraction is subject to quite similar changes during\rembryonic development.\r'),
 (747,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'ribonuclease activity in hepatic nuclei during development\rmammalian liver undergoes marked qualitative and quantitative changes\rduring the development from the embryonic to the adult stage.  many of these\revents are associated with the derepression or repression of certain enzymes\rwhich may be related to specialized subcellular activity.  the involvement\rof ribonucleic acid in the transcription of the information from the genome\rinto the construction of a finished protein molecule has prompted a study of\rbiosynthesis of the rna during differentiation.  although considerable effort\rin this regard has been expended in amphibian1-5 and avian6,7 systems, as well\ras in the sea urchin8-11, a paucity of literature exists with mammalian liver.\raccordingly, an investigation of the alterations in rna metabolism which\roccur during the development of the rat embryonic liver has been undertaken.\rthis report concerns the fluctuations in nuclear ribonuclease during hepatic\rdevelopment and some of the properties of the enzyme.\r'),
 (748,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an electron microscopic study of developing gall\rbladder epithelium in the rabbit\rthe gall bladder epithelium of the\radult rabbit consists of two types of cells.\rthe first and more common type shows features associated with absorption,\rnotably microvilli, limited pinocytosis, some lysosomes and an elaboration of\rthe lateral cell membrane and intercellular spaces.  the mitochondria are\rconcentrated in a subapical band.\rthe second and more infrequent type is a dark rod-shaped cell of unknown\rfunction but which may be a dehydrated epithelial cell.\rfoetal epithelial cells lack the functional adult characteristics; the mito-\rchondria are uniformly distributed.  in addition they display basal granules\rand apical apocrine bullae.\repithelial cell damage and white cell infiltration occurs between 24 days\rafter birth or just after.\rjust before birth some epithelial cells are very large and pale with smooth\routlines, others are more dense and display vigorous pinocytosis.\radult characteristics are acquired at or immediately after birth and pino-\rcytosis subsides.  it is believed that water resorption occurs before the\rfunctional changes which allow continuous passage of water into the\rcirculation.\r'),
 (749,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital anomalies of the cystic duct\rand phineas rabinovitch\ranomalies of the cystic duct, of four differ-\rent types, are reported.  the characteris-\rtic anatomic appearance and embryonic\rdevelopment of each of these anomalies\rare described and the clinical and surgical\rsignificance discussed.\r'),
 (750,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lesions of the liver in hereditary\rmetabolic diseases\rwhether the various cells of the liver, both parenchymal and stromal,\rreceive genetic misinformation in all hereditary diseases caused by gene\rmutation is unknown, but the metabolic capabilities of these several cell\rtypes are so diverse that it is not surprising that their involvement in\rmany such diseases can be demonstrated by clinical, pathological, or bio-\rchemical methods.  repetitive abnormality of the liver has apparently not\rbeen defined for any disease caused by quantitative (i.e., chromosomal)\rgene anomaly, whether produced by nondisjunction, translocation, or\rmajor deletion, perhaps because relatively few such diseases have been\rdescribed.  as a result, the genetically determined disorders of the liver\rsurveyed in this paper appear to be the result of conventional \"single\rgene\" abnormalities, and to be transmitted in affected families by men-\rdelian mechanisms.\r'),
 (751,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acid catabolic enzyme activity in relation\rto accessory limb and cancer initiation in amphibia\rcathepsin and acid phosphatase were determined in livers and kidneys\rof adult rana pipiens and triturus viridescens.  organ-specific and species-\rspecific differences in distribution of these enzymes were found, as well as\rconsiderable differences in the effect triton x-100 on the two enzymes.\ra heterogeneous population of lysosomes in respect to enzyme content and\rstability is deduced.\rwe have found positive correlations between catheptic activity of the\rimplant and host tissue dissociation, and between acid phosphatase and\rinducibility, as features of the phenomenon of implant-induced accessory\rlimb formation in urodeles.  further, we have found a positive correlation\rbetween catheptic activity and resistance to virus-induced renal adenocar-\rcinoma development in rana pipiens.\r'),
 (752,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neonatology\rconsiderable progress has been made in the\rknowledge of bilirubin metabolism since the char-\racterization of \"direct\" (conjugated) bilirubin as an\rester glucuronide.  the metabolic pathway involved\rin this hepatic conjugation is now well established\rand has been the subject of excellent reviews by\rsherlock and billing.\rsherlock\'s diagrammatic representations of biliru-\rbin metabolism (fig. 1) and of the possible mecha-\rnisms of jaundice (fig. 2) are reproduced here\rbecause they furnish a clear picture to serve as a\rreference point for the discussion to follow.\rit is interesting to re-examine current concepts of\rthe etiology of physiologic jaundice with this dia-\rgram in mind.  jaundice may occur for a number of\rreasons, described below.\r'),
 (753,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'red cell glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency--a newly\rrecognized cause of neonatal jaundice and kernicterus in canada\rseven male newborns of chinese, greek and\ritalian origin presented with severe hemo-\rlytic jaundice due to red cell glucose-6-\rphosphate dehydrogenase (g-6-pd) defi-\rciency.  in five, the hemolysis was precipi-\rtated by inhalation of mothball vapours in\rthe home.  kernicterus was evident upon\radmission in six infants and was fatal in\rfour of these.\rg-6-pd deficiency should be suspected as\ra cause of jaundice in all full-term male\rinfants of these ethnic groups.  the diag-\rnosis can be confirmed in any hospital by\rthe methemoglobin reduction test.  in areas\rsimilar to toronto, canada, where these\rhigh-risk ethnic groups prevail, the follow-\ring measures are recommended: (1) detec-\rtion of g-6-pd deficient newborns by\rscreening cord bloods of all infants of these\rethnic groups: (2) protection of affected\rinfants from potentially hemolytic agents\rsuch as naphthalene, certain vitamin k\rpreparations, and sulfonamides; and (3) ob-\rservation of serum bilirubin levels to assess\rthe need for exchange transfusion for hyper-\rbilirubinemia.\r'),
 (754,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'trisomy 17-18 syndrome with congenital\rextrahepatic biliary atresia and congenital\ramputation of the left foot\rthe phenotypic characteristics of\rthe 17-18 trisomy syndrome have been well\rdescribed.  among the most recently docu-\rmented cases of this syndrome are those\rwith findings of agenesis or aplasia of various\rbones of the forearm and hand, in addition\rto the more classical symptoms.\rwe have recently studied a case of trisomy\r17-18 syndrome with congenital absence of\rthe left foot, and congenital extrahepatic\rbiliary atresia.\r'),
 (755,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'differentiation of explanted fragments of\rearly chick blastoderm\rii. culture on protein-deficient medium\renriched with rna\rposterior fragments of head process\rblastoderms were cultured in vitro for two\rdays on a protein-deficient medium sup-\rplemented with various rna\'s, after which\rthey were grafted over the chorio-allantoic\rmembrane for eight to nine days.\rpancreatic (adult) rna enhanced\rthe development of the entodermal epi-\rthelium.\rheart (adult) rna caused hyper-\rplasia of the epidermis with, in some cases,\rkeratinized papillary projections.\rbrain (embryonic) rna produced a\rpapillomatous epidermis with giant epi-\rdermal cysts that were keratinized and\rfibrillar as in feather formation.\rliver (embryonic) rna had no vis-\rible tissue modifications.\rin the controls there was no keratini-\rzation, nor papillary formation of the epi-\rdermis.  the epidermal cysts were very\rsmall, unkeratinized and devoid of fibrillar\rorganization.\rthe results are discussed in terms of\rrelationships of proteins from brain, mus-\rcle and skin.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (756,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the inhibition of cell aggregation by a pure\rserum protein\rthe aggregation of embryonic chick and quail limb bud, heart and liver cells\rin a shaker system has been investigated in order to elucidate the mechanism of\rcell adhesion.\ra new method of assessing aggregation is described and evaluated; this\rmethod involved measurements of aggregation kinetics.  it was found that the\rmeasured kinetics agree closely with flocculation kinetics, which provides a\rdirect quantitative measurement of adhesiveness in terms of the\rprobability of an adhesion forming on contact between two cells.\rusing this technique it was confirmed that aggregation is inhibited at\r1-2 c. in the presence of serum but not in its absence.  the kinetics of\raggregation in the presence of serum at 37 c., the lack of inhibition of\raggregation at 1-2 c. by serum which has been \'conditioned\' by the presence of\rcells, and the similar lack of inhibitory power of serum which has been\rpre-treated with antiserum antibodies, all suggest that serum contains a\rfactor which inhibits aggregation until destroyed by cellular metabolism.\r'),
 (757,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'les icteres du nouveau-ne en dehors\rde l\'incompatibilite foeto-maternelle\rstatistical data pulled off a study of 30 haemolytic neonatal icteri\rnot linked to a foeto-maternal incompatibility, and of 200 non haemo-\rlytic neonatal icteri.  among this latter, the two most important groups\rare the malformative icteri (69 cases) and the neonatal hepatitis\r(109 cases).  the difficulties of the diagnosis frequently rencountered\rbetween these two groups clearly appear in the comparative statistical\ranalysis of the clinical, histological and evolutive data.\r'),
 (758,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the immunological development of the human\rfetus\rthe normal human fetus is said not to be engaged in the formation of immuno-\rglobulins; the immunoglobulins present in the serum of the fetus and the\rnewborn are considered to be of maternal origin.  in favor of this opinion is\rthe observation that directly after birth the serum of the newborn contains an\rappreciable amount of igg, with gm groups identical with those of the mother\r(68-70).  the level of the igg of the neonate decreases gradually during the\rfirst 3 months (3,27,71), which is generally explained by the catabolism of\rthe maternal igg, whereas the formation by the newborn infant is still\rinadequate to maintain the original level (16,27).  the best evidence for the\rtransplacental passage is the almost complete absence of igg in the serum of\rnewborn infants from mothers with agammaglobulinemia (3,27).\rthe transfer of the immunoglobulins appears to be a selective process\r(13, 15).  while igg is readily transferred, there is little, if any,\rtransfer of iga and igm, as has been shown by ultracentrifugation and\rimmunoelectrophoretic studies of the serum (12, 16, 19, 20) and the analysis\rof maternally-transferred antibodies (31-33).  with more sensitive techniques\rsuch as the double diffusion test in agar or quantitative immunochemical\rtechniques, however, minute amounts of both igm and iga have been detected\rin fetal blood as well as in cord blood from mature and immature neonates\r(12, 19, 20, 23, 26).  since large molecules do not pass the placenta, this\rmay indicate that the trace amounts of igm originate in the fetus itself, but\rtransplacental passage has not been completely excluded.\rthe absence of immunoglobulin formation has been associated with the absence\rof plasma cells in the lymphoid tissues and bone marrow of the normal human\rfetus and the newborn.  it has been reported that these cells do not appear\runtil a few weeks after birth (2, 3, 14, 25, 34).  however, in pathological\rconditions such as congenital syphilis and toxoplasmosis the human fetus has\rbeen found to respond to the antigenic stimulus with intrauterine formation of\rplasma cells after about the sixth month of gestation (24,25).\r'),
 (759,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'galactosemie congenitale\rthis observation of a case of congenital galactosemia with\ra particular familial incidence gives the opportunity of a\rbrief review on the subject.\rof a certain point of view we must consider that galac-\rtosemia is much more frequent than we suppose, that there\rare many severe cases with a reserved prognosis, that even\rwith very slight degree of galactosemia, the disease must\rreceive the most careful attention from the pediatrician.\r'),
 (760,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'postnatal changes in the portal circulation\rduring foetal development a large portion of the\roxygenated umbilical blood flows through the\rumbilical recess directly into both main portal\rbranches.  accordingly, these are exposed to the\rumbilical blood pressure and have a wide\rby contrast, the trunk of the portal vein is narrow\rand there is probably only a small blood flow through\rit from the inactive digestive tract, though the\rpressure in it is approximately the same as in the\rumbilical vein or perhaps somewhat higher.\rimmediately after birth the liver is deprived of the\rsubstantial umbilical blood flow.  the portal\rvenous pressure falls to about one-quarter of the\rumbilical venous pressure at birth.  however the\rpressure gradient between the portal veins and\rinferior vena cava remains constant.\r'),
 (761,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pattern of serum transaminase activity\rin neonatal jaundice due to cytomegalic inclusion\rdisease and toxoplasmosis with hepatic involvement\rthe pattern of serum transaminase ac-\rtivity that evolved in a newborn infant with\rcongenital toxoplasmosis and in another new-\rborn infant with congenital cytomegalic in-\rclusion disease is described.  this enzymatic\rpattern was unlike that found in infants with\rany other cause of neonatal jaundice studied\rto date.\r'),
 (762,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'impaired development of rat liver enzyme activities at\rbirth after irradiation in utero\rdevelopment of activity of three liver enzymes at birth was studied in rats re-\rceiving 180 rads of x-rays on day 15 of gestation.  at 20 days of gestation,\ractivities of lactic and glycerophosphate dehydrogenases and\rglucose-6-phosphatase were not altered.  the subsequent increases in enzyme\ractivities in the 3 days between 20 days of gestation and 1 day of age were\ronly 30 to 60% of those observed in controls.  this finding suggests that\rirradiation in utero may alter later development of enzyme activity in the\rperinatal period.\r'),
 (763,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(cytological and cytochemical study of\rhepatic cells in the human embryo)\rchanges in golgi apparatus and mitochondria as well as in the contents of\rnucleic acids, proteins, polysaccharides, lipids and iron in the hepatic cells\rof developing human embryo were studied; the data obtained in human embryos and\radults were compared.  it was found that during the developmental process some\rchanges in localisations of golgi apparatus and iron salts were taking place.\rthe contents of rna and polysaccharides in the cytoplasm increased:\rmitochondria in the form of granules were revealed throughout the embryonic\rperiod and in adults.  no essential alterations in the contents of dna,\rproteins, and lipids were noted.\r'),
 (764,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'risk of severe jaundice in\rglucose-6-phosphate-dehydrogenase\rdeficiency of the newborn\rthe incidence of g.-6-p.d. deficiency and neonatal\rjaundice in all male infants born in one year in an area of\rthe island of lesbos was studied.\rof 634 infants tested, 29 (4.6%) were found to be\rg.-6-p.d. deficient.  hyperbilirubinaemia of 16 mg. per\r100 ml. or over was observed in 34% of g.-6-p.d.-\rdeficient newborn males and in 9.1% of those with normal\renzyme activity--in more than half of them in the absence\rof incompatibility or prematurity.\rthis is the first time that such a high incidence of\rsevere neonatal jaundice has been reported in both a\rg.-6-p.d.-deficient and a g.-6-p.d.-normal group.  it is\rpostulated that in the population of lesbos a second\rfactor increases the incidence of neonatal jaundice,\respecially when this factor is combined with g.-6-p.d.\rdeficiency.\r'),
 (765,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of b-glucuronidase acti-\rvity in bile and liver of devel-\roping chick embryos and chicks\rin search for the reason of the occur-\rrence of unconjugated bilirubin and\rbiliverdin in chick-embryo and in chick\rbile the possibility of a b-glucuronidase\rfunction must be taken into serious con-\rsideration.\r'),
 (766,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'jaundice in infancy\rmost causes of jaundice in infancy are discussed.  the empha-\rsis has been on those syndromes solely or usually encountered\rin the neonate and infant.\r'),
 (767,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'absence of the cystic duct\ra case of congenital absence of the cystic\rduct is described, the 18th reported case in\rthe literature.  the embryogenetic basis of\ranomalies of the extrahepatic biliary tree\ris discussed.  methods of early operative\rrecognition and surgical management of\rthe anomaly are suggested.\r'),
 (768,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'familial extrahepatic biliary atresia\ra fifth family with familial congenital\rextrahepatic biliary is described.\rclinically and pathologically familial\rand nonfamilial biliary atresia are similar\rexcept for a predominance of males in the\rfamilial condition.\rthe sex incidence and association of\rother congenital anomalies is discussed in\rrelation to a possible etiology.  further in-\rformation must be correlated and new facts\runcovered before the nature of this syn-\rdrome will be known.\r'),
 (769,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'linfangiografia no estudo da filariase linfatica\rin the first part of the present paper a study is presented\rof the lymphangiogram of the normal african; the author has\rnoticed that it is coincident with the one of the white indi-\rvidual.\rthe second part includes the lymphangiographic examina-\rtion and the observation of lymph circulation (via risa)\rduring the several stages of lymphatic filariasis.\reven during the asymptomatic stage, lymphangiography\rshows ganglial hypertrophy with a slight fibrosis and occa-\rsional discreet alterations of the lymphatic trunks.\rin the symptomatic stage, the lymphangiographic aspects\rvary according to the disease\'s different stages and there is\rnot always a relationship between the duration period of the\rsymptoms and the changes observed.\rin lymphangites, there are frequent alterations of the\rlymphatic trunks, i.e., increase in caliber, extensive and seg-\rmentary dilatations, numerical decrease with visualization of\ranastomoses and higher permeability.  circulatory trouble evi-\rdences itself not only by a decrease in the rate of the lymph\rflow, but also by a very marked ganglial retention.\rin adenites, in spite of the marked ganglial hypertrophy\rdue to intense sclerosis, there may be no considerable altera-\rtions in the lymphatics, but risa already shows clear circula-\rtion troubles leading to lymphatic stasis.\rin adenolymphoceles, the obstruction at the primitive-iliac\rlevel causes the lymph flow to deviate through the pre-sacral\ranastomoses and reflux to the inguinal glands, thus causing\rtheir dilatation and the formation of varicosities in the affe-\rrent lymphatics.\rin lymphedemas, our lymphangiographic results together\rwith risa\'s allow us to assume that the pathogeny is chiefly\rinfluenced by three factors: lymphatic obstruction due to lym-\rphangitis, insufficiency of the collateral ducts, and ganglial\rsclerosis.\r'),
 (770,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'adjuvant chemotherapy in cancer of the\rlarge bowel\rthe completeness of reporting, the avail-\rability of continuous statistical analysis to\rwarn of adverse effects, and the accumulation\rof 300 cases a year have demonstrated that this\rcooperative study group can provide a rela-\rtively quick assessment of a new approach to\rtreatment of cancer of the large bowel.  it is\rhoped that a study begun in january, 1962, on\rthe use of 5-fluorodeoxyuridine as an adjuvant\rto adequate excisional surgery may demon-\rstrate that, with a drug known to produce\robjective remissions in 20 per cent of a group\rof unresectable cases of colon carcinoma\rthe five year survival rate in curative resections\rmay be improved.\r'),
 (771,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cancer chemotherapy by prolonged arterial\rinfusion\rour current experience is reported with\r136 patients treated by prolonged arterial\rinfusion chemotherapy.  the patients pre-\rsented a variety of far advanced cancers un-\rsuitable for conventional surgical or roent-\rgen therapy.  antimetabolite solution, either\rmethotrexate or a fluorinated pyrimidine,\rwas injected continuously through a small\rplastic catheter into the unobstructed artery\rto provide a high regional drug concentration\rfor days to weeks.  the patients have received\rdrug infusion for up to 45 days.  their course\rhas been followed for up to 37 months after\rtreatment.\rmethotrexate with antidote therapy by\rsystemic administration of citrovorum fac-\rtor was used preferentially in most patients.\ra fluorinated pyrimidine, most commonly,\r5-fluoro-2\'-deoxyuridine, was preferred for\rhepatic artery infusion of liver metastases.\r'),
 (772,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the montgomery tube to palliate\rhypopharyngeal cancer\rthree cases of advanced, incurable cancer of the hypopharynx\rhave been presented.  in each instance, the simple procedure of insert-\ring an available prothesis served as an effective palliation for an\rotherwise difficult or hopeless situation.\r'),
 (773,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'adjuvant cancer chemotherapy\rdevelopment of a dosage schedule for adjuvant cancer chemotherapy\rin surgical cases\ran account is given of the development\rof a dosage schedule for adjuvant can-\rcer chemotherapy for surgical patients.\rthis treatment was administered for\rtwo purposes:\ras an adjuvant to radical surgery\rto reduce the risk of blood-borne\rmetastases.\ras a palliative measure for non-ra-\rdically operated and inoperable pa-\rtients.\rfor these purposes 3 dosage levels\rwere fixed:\ra maximum tolerated dose for ad-\rjuvant therapy.\ra maximum tolerated dose for pa-\rrenteral palliative therapy.\ra maximum tolerated dose for oral\rpalliative therapy.\rfor this treatment the authors used\r2 antimitotics, sp-i and sp-g, both of\rwhich are podophyllin derivatives.\r'),
 (774,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'surgical palliation for lung cancer\rthe results of resecting incurable lung cancer\rin an effort to improve the terminal course of a\rsmall number of patients are briefly presented.\rthis is not a comparative study and no in-\rferences or conclusions are justified regarding\rthe choice of this form of therapy as palliation\rin preference to other forms of palliative ther-\rapy; however we do believe that the terminal\rcourse of the patient with lung cancer is bene-\rficially effected by removal of the primary\rtumor whenever this is technically feasible.\r'),
 (775,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'management of advanced endometrial\radenocarcinoma with medroxyprogesterone\racetate\ra basis for progestin therapy for patients\rwith advanced endometrial adenocarcinoma\ris presented.  the criteria for selection of\rpatients for hormone therapy and the sched-\rule of administration of medroxyprogester-\rone (provera) is discussed.  evaluation of\rpatients for objective changes only, i.e., by\rvisual, palpable, histologic, or roentgeno-\rlogic means, revealed complete or partial\rremission with significant palliation in 8 of\r20 patients (40 per cent).  response to me-\rdroxyprogesterone therapy is apparently re-\rlated to degree of differentiation of the pri-\rmary neoplasm, the well-differentiated le-\rsions being more responsive.  documentation\rof tumor effect by serial biopsies during\rtreatment provides an index to the histologic\rchanges this progestin produces in suscep-\rtible cases.  the effects of therapy upon\rserial urinary hormone excretion rates is\rdocumented in several patients.\ron the basis of our experience, the treat-\rment of patients with advanced endometrial\radenocarcinoma with the potent progestin\rmedroxyprogesterone seems justified.\r'),
 (776,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chemotherapy of breast cancer\rthe majority of cancer patients who are\rreferred for chemotherapy are in far advanced\rstages of the disease.  the difficulty in deliver-\ring an effective dose of an oncolytic agent\rto the involved areas may limit the results of\rtreatment unless the patient\'s tumor is an un-\rusually responsive one.  the variability in re-\rsponse between apparently similar cases of\rcancer of the same cell type has become in-\rcreasingly evident, and is as puzzling as the\rfact that 20 per cent of patients with breast\rcancer will live 5 years with no treatment.  the\rdecisions as to the choice between chemother-\rapy and hormone therapy, as well as to the\rchoice of the chemotherapeutic agent to be\remployed, may be difficult.\ras experience increases, the usefulness of\rchemotherapy in the treatment of cancer is\rbecoming increasingly apparent.  it also has be-\rcome apparent that chemotherapy cannot be\rregarded as a curative procedure in advanced\rcancer even though an occasional patient ap-\rpears to have been cured.  however, the value\rof the oncolytic agents in prolonging useful\rsurvival time, ameliorating many of the dis-\rtressing symptoms associated with cancer, and\rproviding the physician with an extra tool for\ra positive program in the care of the cancer\rpatient is now established.\r'),
 (777,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'clinical experience with palliation\rof metastatic adenocarcinoma with\r5-fluorouracil chemotherapy\rchemotherapy of solid tumors is becoming a\rmore and more helpful therapeutic tool.  it\ris probable that within a few years chemother-\rapy will become firmly established as an ad-\rjunct to the primary treatment of solid tumors.\rperhaps someday a cancerocidal chemical will\rbe devised that can actually act as antibiotics\rdo on bacteria.  for this reason it is important\rfor all surgeons interested in the treatment of\rcancer to try to keep abreast of the recent ad-\rvances in the field of chemotherapy.  surgeons\rshould also begin to use some of the technics for\rpalliation of incurable patients so that when\rthese drugs are added to the armamentarium of\rprimary treatment of cancer, they will be\rfamiliar with the various technics and the mode\rof actions of the drugs.\r5-fluorouracil (5-fu) has had extensive clin-\rical use and has produced significant palliation\rin breast and colon cancers with about a third\rof these patients receiving palliation for five to\rsix months.\r'),
 (778,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pelvic perfusion and carcinoma\rof the rectum\ra method of regional chemotherapy through\risolation of the pelvis has been presented.\rall of the subjects were near the terminal\rstage at the time of perfusion.  the survival\rtime and degree of palliation have been en-\rcouraging.\r'),
 (779,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'carcinoma of the esophagus\ra survey of fifty-seven patients with cancer\rof the esophagus occurring over a twenty year\rperiod is presented.  the presenting complaints\rof the disease, methods of diagnosis, and char-\racteristics of the disease are discussed.  three\requal treatment groups consisting of no treat-\rment, x-ray treatment, and surgical resection\rwere compared and the results were extremely\rpoor.  only one patient in all three groups sur-\rvived longer than two years.  it was our con-\rclusion, supported by the opinion of others,\rthat x-ray therapy gave the best palliation in\rmost cases and that surgical resection for cure\rshould be used in only the most suitable pa-\rtients.\r'),
 (780,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'carcinoma of bladder: cobalt therapy\rfrom 1959 to 1962, 202 patients have received\rradiotherapy for carcinoma of the bladder.  radi-\rcal therapy with cobalt-60 has been done in 121\rof these cases.  these patients received tumor\rdoses in excess of 5000 rad in 3 weeks.  of 49 pa-\rtients followed for 2 years after radical treatment,\r28 are alive.  sixteen out of 32 patients with\rstage b2, c or d tumors are alive; while 15 pa-\rtients survived out of 30 with tumors of grades\r3 and 4 (broders\').  four of the 28 survivors had\rcystectomy performed and none showed residual\rdisease in the bladder or lymph nodes.  the com-\rplications of radiotherapy presented were not\rconsidered to be excessive.\rwe believe that radiotherapy should be the\rinitial treatment for patients with infiltrative\rcarcinoma of the bladder.  the survivals pre-\rsented at 2 years are better than those quoted for\rradical cystectomy (whitmore and marshall)\rand useful bladder function is preserved for the\rmajority of survivors.  we reserve cystectomy for\rspecific indications.\r'),
 (781,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'polyposis of colon\ras seen in\rprivate practice\rfamilial polyposis of the colon may\rpresent itself in a variety of clinical en-\rtities.  from the cases discussed in this\rpaper the following forms may be enu-\rmerated:\r(1) an asymptomatic phase with dis-\rcrete polyposis.\r(2) a mildly asymptomatic stage\rwith diffuse polyposis.\r(3) a premalignant phase with car-\rcinomas in situ.\r(4) grossly malignant phase char-\racterized by anemia and carcinomatosis,\rpossibly of multicentric origin.\rto secure a complete cure it is im-\rperative that the clinician discover and\rthe surgeon treat the disease in its pre-\rmalignant state.\rworthwhile palliative results may be\robtained by surgery in incurable cases\rby extensive resection of the primary\rlesions and subsequent resection of any\rrecurrences or metastasis, whether local\ror distant by second and third looks is\rnecessary.\rspecial emphasis should be paid to\rthe emotional problems of the patients.\ran encouraging, sympathetic attitude on\rthe part of the surgeon is essential and\rrewarding.\r'),
 (782,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'systemic chemotherapy\rfor cns metastases\rof solid tumors\rof the 13 cases studied, remissions were ob-\rtained in eight.  this 62% remission rate is not\rsignificant because of the number of variables\rpresent.  however, we believe that chemother-\rapy for this type of patient is indicated, as sup-\rported by the reported data.  the results suggest\rthat the blood supply to solid tumors is different\rfrom that of tumors associated with hematopoi-\retic disorders.  the latter respond very poorly,\rif at all, to systemic therapy.  although we were\rnot able to measure the central nervous system\r(cns) lesions exactly, the regression of the\rcns symptomatology was significant.  in pa-\rtients who had other demonstrable metastatic\rdisease, those lesions also regressed.  with this\revidence we feel that patients with metastatic\rcns lesions, even when these have recently\rresulted in paralysis or seizures, should be con-\rsidered for systemic chemotherapy.\r'),
 (783,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'combined 5-fluorouracil and supervoltage\rradiation therapy in the palliative manage-\rment of advanced gastrointestinal cancer:\ra pilot study\rmalcolm y. colby, margaret a. holbrook\r5-fluorouracil in combination with supervoltage radiation\rtherapy was employed in the palliative treatment of 44 pa-\rtients with advanced gastrointestinal carcinoma.\ra total dose of from 40 to 50 mg. per kilogram of body\rweight of 5-fluorouracil given by rapid intravenous injection\rat the onset of radiation therapy was found to be relatively\rsafe and tolerable.  larger doses were associated with excessive\rtoxicity and mortality.\ra sufficient number of patients achieved objective and\rsubjective palliation to justify controlled study of the possible\radditive or synergistic role that 5-fluorouracil may have when\rcombined with radiation therapy.\r'),
 (784,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'palliation by radiotherapy\rthe purpose of radiotherapy in the management\rof cancer of the lung is first to cure the disease;\rsecond, to prolong useful and comfortable exist-\rence; and third, to provide comfort and relief of\rsuffering to those who are symptomatic and in-\rcurable.\rcancers of the lung vary quite widely in their\rresponse to radiation.  those of glandular origin,\rthe adenocarcinoma, are more often than not of\rmodest susceptibility and sometimes quite resis-\rtant.  the very undifferentiated, the so-called oat-\rcell cancers, are often of exquisite sensitivity, re-\rsponding to irradiation almost like lymphomas.\rmost cancer of the lung, however, is squamous-cell\rcarcinoma and as such may be considered to be\rmoderately radiosensitive in much the same order\rof magnitude as squamous-cell carcinoma of the\rskin, cervix or larynx, and should, in theory, be\rcurable by this means in the same degree.  unfor-\rtunately, this has to date not been found to be\rtrue.  the reasons are principally two: first and\rforemost, by the time a diagnosis is made, cancer\rof the lung has more often than not, estimated at\r80% and more, spread beyond the site of origin,\rthus making cure by any effective means presently\ravailable unlikely.  second, the substrate in which\rthe cancer grows, the lung, tolerates radiation less\rwell than do the tissues which surround the highly\rradiocurable epithelial cancers such as carcinoma of\rthe skin, cervix, and larynx, thus making an un-\rfavorable therapeutic ratio.\r'),
 (785,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chlorambucil-prednisolone therapy\rfor disseminated breast carcinoma\rover a 7 1/2-year period, 71 patients with\rdisseminated breast cancer were treated\rwith combined alkylating-agent-cortico-\rsteroid therapy.  chlorambucil and pred-\rnisolone were the drugs of choice.  these\ragents, administered orally, produced no\rserious or disagreeable toxic effects.  twen-\rty-four patients (33.8%) had objective\rregression of six months\' duration or long-\rer; average survival time after therapy\rwas 23.9 months.  results are statistically\rsimilar to those obtained with sex-steroid\rand endocrine-ablation therapy, presum-\rably because the three modalities have a\rsimilar mechanism of action, ie. suppres-\rsion and/or eradication of endogenous\restrogen.\r'),
 (786,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recent advances in the treatment of\rcancer of the esophagus\rwhether combining surgery and supervoltage radiation therapy will\rnoticeably improve the 5-year survival rate for carcinoma of the esopha-\rgus remains to be seen.  it is encouraging, however, to observe at the time\rof operation that the previously irradiated esophagus is firmly encased in\rfibrous tissue, which gives the impression that the danger of disseminating\rtumor at the time of resection is diminished.  in addition, the fibrosis sug-\rgests that the tumor that had spread locally, beyond the limits of surgical\rexcision, may have been destroyed.\r'),
 (787,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cyclophosphamide in the management of\radvanced bronchial carcinoma\rforty patients suffering from advanced bronchial\rcarcinoma who were treated with cyclophospha-\rmide are reviewed.  the selective effect of the drug\rin tumours of the oat-cell type is noted.  it is\rsuggested that relapses which occur while the\rpatient is on oral maintenance therapy may be\rcontrolled by a further intravenous course of\rcyclophosphamide.\rfull clinical and statistical details of all the\rpatients referred to in this paper are available on\rapplication to the author.\r'),
 (788,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'esophageal obstruction\rthe use of an endoscopically inserted tube in the\rcare of esophageal carcinoma\rour experience suggests that the en-\rdoscopic insertion of intraluminal tubes\rprovides a relatively simple and reason-\rably safe method of dealing with some\rof the problems which arise in the man-\ragement of patients with esophageal car-\rcinoma.  such tubes would appear to be\rof particular use in handling the prob-\rlems of obstruction and regurgitation in\rpatients with incurable tumors, but may\ralso be helpful in preparing severely\rdebilitated patients with esophageal car-\rcinoma to withstand the rigors of opera-\rtion and radiation therapy.\r'),
 (789,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'palliative radiation therapy\rthe care of the patient with \"incurable\" cancer may be\rdirected by physicians of various backgrounds and per-\rsuasions.  if this physician has little experience in such\rcare, he is prone to be influenced by still prevalent atti-\rtudes of therapeutic futility or by equally unjustified\rpremature claims for widely publicized methods recent on\rthe scene.  surgery and radiation therapy remain the\rdominant treatment forces for the patient with cancer.  it\ris unfortunate that lack of demonstration of good radiation\rtherapy has led to unjustified condemnation of the method\rrather than the user, with resultant loss to the patient\'s\rwelfare.  to obtain maximal benefit, radiation therapy\rmust be allowed indications and contraindications like any\rtherapeutic modality.  these must be the responsibility of\rthe therapeutic radiologist.  application of realistically\rstringent indications and contraindications does not lessen\ruseful accomplishment, but avoids unnecessary morbidity,\rwaste of time, money and effort, and delay in seeking\rsuitable treatment.\r'),
 (790,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'carcinoma of the middle ear\rthe results of radiotherapy in a relatively large\rnumber of cases of carcinoma of the middle ear\rare reported.  the crude 5 year survival rate of 100\rcases is 29%.  there is no difference in survival\rbetween those cases who had a preliminary\rmastoidectomy and those who did not.  the use of\rmegavoltage x-rays probably increases the survival\rrate.\r'),
 (791,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sustained palliation in\rovarian carcinoma\rmanagement of 64 cases of advanced\rovarian carcinoma has been analyzed.\ran attempt is made to compare the\rvalue of radiation and the value of chloram-\rbucil, using salvage time and sustained pal-\rliation as end points.\rchlorambucil, an outpatient oral medi-\rcation, appears to be as efficacious as ra-\rdiation in advanced ovarian carcinoma.\rchlorambucil may be used before or\rafter irradiation therapy.\rpleural and peritoneal effusion respond\rfavorably to chlorambucil 80% of the time.\rthe possibility of using a different\rdosage schedule is discussed.\r'),
 (792,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'clues in dealing with\rcancer patients\rit is clear that the patient with cancer changed\rhis pattern of communication at different stages of\rthe disease.  these patterns in communication were\rthe basis or clues for the doctor and paramedical\rpersonnel to consider in making total care more\reffective.  the bedside clinician of past days knew\rthese clues instinctively in his wise ministrations.\rthanks to a gifted social worker these have been\rnow made manifest to help all of us in dealing\rwith cancer and perhaps other chronic relentless\rdiseases.\r'),
 (793,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radon and radioactive seed volume implants\rfor extensive recurrent vaginal-pelvic cancer\rradioactive seed volume implants for\rextensive recurrent vaginal-pelvic cancer\rresult in extended control of otherwise\runtreatable disease.  immediate and early\rreactions are practically nonexistent.  late\rcomplications are also rare, the most\rserious being severe hemorrhagic cystitis\rin 2 of the author\'s 13 patients.\r'),
 (794,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'terminal cancer nursed at home\rperhaps the most difficult part of mrs. brown\'s illness,\rwas that she herself knew all about it.  she had been a\rnurse for most of her working life, and was only too aware\rof the deteriorating process of carcinoma.  there were\rtimes, of course, when she would try to deceive herself, say-\ring that there was always hope that something new in the\rway of treatment would turn up, and life would then be\rworth living again.\r'),
 (795,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'advanced cancer of the breast\rtreated primarily with irradiation\rthe five-year results in 109 patients\rtreated primarily with irradiation for\rcancer of the breast, mostly in the late\rstages, have been analyzed.\rin all cases, the initial intent was to\rcontrol with x radiation alone the primary\rtumor involving the breast and its entire\rlymphatic drainage.  irradiation remained\ressentially the sole method of treatment in\r84 cases.  postirradiation mastectomy was\rperformed in the 25 other patients, who\rinitially had been considered inoperable.\rthe plan of treatment has consisted of a\rsingle continuous course of radiation ther-\rapy, protracted over a period of seventy-\rfive to one hundred days and administered\rin 3 closely integrated phases.  tissue\rdoses, superficial and deep, must be\rbrought to the highest levels required for\rmaximum biological effects within the\rtolerance of the structures involved.\rthe immediate effects of irradiation\ralone have been remarkable.  the re-\rgression of neoplastic manifestations in the\rbreast and palpable nodes, the degree of\rhealing of ulcerated carcinoma, and the\rincidence of recurrence have been re-\rcorded and assessed to determine the\refficacy of treatment.\r'),
 (796,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the management of disseminated\rcancer of the breast\rwhen mammary cancer has spread to tissues beyond\rthe breast and axilla, the disease is incurable by present\rday methods.  however the patient may be greatly helped\rand tumor growth retarded by skillful and sympathetic\rapplication of irradiation, surgical ablation, hormone ad-\rministration, and chemotherapy.  given in conjunction\rwith analgesics, sedatives, and ataractic drugs, these\rmeasures can frequently reduce disability and pain and\rprolong the period of useful comfortable life.\r'),
 (797,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'toilet training of an autistic eight-year-old through\rconditioning therapy: a case report\roperant conditioning techniques have been successfully\rused in the treatment of a wide variety of be-\rhavioral problems including hysterical blindness (brady\rand lind, 1961), tics (barrett, 1962), psychotic\rsymptoms (lindsley, 1956; 1960, 1961), reading disabilities\r(rachman, 1962) stuttering (flanagan et. al.,\r1958) enuresis (mowrer and mowrer, 1938; lovibond,\r1961, 1963a, b) and encopresis (neale, 1963;\rmadsen, 1965).  neale (1963) successfully treated three\rout of four encopretic children using operant\rtraining techniques.  in the case of one 9-yr-old boy, with\ran 18 month history of encopresis, going to the\rtoilet was rewarded by a candy, praise and recording the\revent in a special book in the boy\'s presence.\rsoiling was not inadvertently rewarded (e.g. attention) or\rpunished; the boy would be given a clean pair\rof pants without comment.  neale reports that response to\rtreatment was rapid and complete and 6 months\rafter toilet training there had been no relapse in bowel habits.\rprocedures similar to those used by neale were used in\rthe case reported here.  positive and, in a\rsmall number of instances, negative reinforcement were used\rto toilet train an 8-yr-old boy diagnosed by\ra child psychiatrist/neurologist as having infantile autism.\r'),
 (798,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'incidence of symptoms of early infantile autism in\rsubsequently hospitalized psychiatric patients\rthis study was concerned with the\rrelationship between the occurrence dur-\ring the first two years of life of symptoms\rof early infantile autism, as retrospective-\rly reported by the mothers of s\'s and\rsubsequent adjustment.  the mothers of\r69 unmarried young hospitalized psychia-\rtric patients were interviewed to deter-\rmine the presence or absence of each of\r28 different signs contained in a check\rlist.  the signs represent characteristic\rfeatures that are reportedly often found\rin conjunction with early infantile autism.\ras a control, 50 mothers of high school\rstudents residing in the community and\rpresenting no significant adjustment prob-\rlems were questioned in regard to the\rvery same items.\rthe results indicated that there were\rsignificantly more symptoms reported for\rpatients than for normals, and that this\rfinding applied to the overall number of\rsymptoms as well as to several subcate-\rgories of symptoms.  the items classified\runder the heading of \"social withdrawal\"\rappeared to be the most sensitive in dif-\rferentiating the groups.  it was also found\rthat 11 of the 28 signs distinguished be-\rtween the patients and normals, with all\rexcept one occurring more frequently in\rthe former group.  it was concluded that\ra significant relationship existed between\rthe reported presence of symptoms that\rare often associated with severe and early\rego impairment and subsequent status as\ra mental hospital patient.  this study does\rnot provide any direct answer to the ques-\rtion of what proportion of children with\rinfantile autism are later able to make an\radequate adjustment outside of a mental\rhospital.\r'),
 (799,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'eeg abnormalities in early childhood schizophrenia:\ra double-blind study of psychiatrically distrubed\rand normal children during promazine sedation\reeg tracings during promazine sedation\rwere obtained on 58 children who had\rautistic or symbiotic childhood psychosis.\rfor comparison eeg\'s were done under\ridentical conditions on 4 other groups of\rchildren: 44 with chronic undifferentiated\rschizophrenia; 37 non-psychotic children\rwith severe, acting-out behavior disorders;\r10 with neuroses; and 13 psychiatrically\rnormal children.  final clinical diagnoses\rwere made without knowledge of the eeg\rreadings as determined for this study, and\rthe eeg\'s were all placed in random order\rand read without any knowledge of the\rclinical diagnosis.  eeg abnormalities ac-\rcepted were focal slowing, focal spikes,\rparoxysmal spikes and waves, and par-\roxysmal spikes and waves with independent\rspikes.\ramong the 149 patients 51% had abnormal\rrecords.  none of the psychiatrically normal\rchildren had eeg abnormalities.  except\rfor the neurotics, the eeg abnormalities\rwere qualitatively and quantitatively sim-\rilar in the psychiatric patients.  the\rmost frequent abnormalities were ir-\rregular paroxysmal spike and wave com-\rplexes, often best seen during the\rtransition from wake to sleep.  of the 149\rpatients, 33% had this complex, either alone\ror with independent spikes.  although these\rcomplexes were most frequent in the au-\rtistic-symbiotic group, the incidence was\rnot statistically significantly different from\rthe higher performing, chronic undiffer-\rentiated schizophrenics who had communi-\rcative speech or the non-psychotic children\rwith acting-out behavior disorders.\rof the 58 autistic-symbiotic children, 19%\rhad seizures, which is similar to the 13%\rseizure incidence in the remaining 91 psy-\rchiatric patients.\rwhether the cerebral dysfunction im-\rplied by this study is a primary disorder\ror is secondary to some factor such as the\reffect of prolonged anxiety on body chem-\ristry cannot be decided at this time.  never-\rtheless, an organic concomitant has been\rdemonstrated in 51% of the psychiatrically\rdisturbed children.  by increasing the\ramount of time included in the eeg sam-\rple, the incidence of electrical abnormalities\rmight be even higher.\r'),
 (800,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on early infantile psychosis.\rthe symbiotic and autistic syndromes\rin conclusion, i wish to state that the\rcore of child psychosis must\rbe sought in one or the other of the\rdescribed distortions of the sym-\rbiotic phase.  in the first case, what lay\rat the heart of the psychotic dis-\rturbance was the marked emotional\runavailability of the mother,\rwhich alternated with a purely physical\rextreme closeness during the\rbreast-feeding situations, and particularly\rwith the destructiveness of\rthe mother\'s unpredictable rage attacks.\rthe contrasting experiences\rdrove the child to the autistic warding\roff of any human contact and\rthe de-animation of the world of reality.\rconstitutional factors could\rnot, in this case, be evaluated with any\rdegree of accuracy.\rin the second case, it was, by contrast,\rthe mother\'s ever-presence\rthat created an unendurable instrusion\rupon and interference with\rthe structuralization of the budding ego,\rwhich constitutionally and\rperhaps predispositionally may have been\rvery vulnerable.  this made\rit impossible for the infant to experience\rthe normal alternation of\rthe gratification-frustration sequences at\rhis own pace; it also made\rthe process of individuation in the\rseparation-individuation period\rone which was beset with abysmal panic.\rin both instances, we can see that it was\rprimarily in the severe dis-\rtortions of the normal symbiosis that the\rchild psychosis had its roots.\r'),
 (801,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'autopathy:follow-up of cases\rthe publication of two papers\rrecently in the acta paedopsychiatrica by\rd. arn. van krevelen on the subject of \"autistic\rpsychopathy\", has stimulated the author\rto present 5 cases which appear to conform to\rhis description.  the only value of this brief\rcontribution lies in the fact that they have all\rbeen followed up for at least 10 years, and\rthis may give some idea of the eventual results\rin this type of cases.\r'),
 (802,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sensory dominance\rin autistic imbecile children and controls\rin a previous experiment (hermelin and\ro\'connor, 1964) it was found that autistic\rand control imbecile children responded most\rfrequently to a light stimulus in conditions of\rbimodal, simultaneous stimulation.  however,\rthe role of the relative intensity level of the\rstimuli remained to be determined.  in the\rpresent experiment a light and a sound, or a\rlight and a verbal command were presented\rsimultaneously in various intensity combina-\rtions.  all responses, irrespective of the stim-\rulus to which they were made, were\rrewarded.  autistic, mongol, and nonmongol\rimbecile children were tested.  in addition to\ra tendency for visual dominance results\rshowed that independent of modality, high\rintensities affected all groups.  nonmongol\rimbecile children also responded significantly\rmore frequently to the verbal than to the\rsound stimulus, while the other two groups\rdid not.\r'),
 (803,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dreaming sleep in autistic twins\reach of 5-year-old identical autistic twins\rwas observed during one spontaneous all\rnight sleep session during which their\relectroencephalogram, eye movement, heart\rrate, and chin muscle potential were recorded.\rthese autistic twins showed a similar\rpatterning and amount of dreaming sleep to\reach other and to that reported for normal\rchildren of the same age.\r'),
 (804,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'twins discordant\rfor early infantile autism\ra pair of heterozygous twins discordant\rfor early infantile autism is reported and the\rrelevant literature reviewed.  although mani-\rfest organic factors were ruled out, the twins\'\rphysical development was different.  a spe-\rcific emotional etiology was not demon-\rstrated.  the few available twin studies offer\rfindings consistent with the hypothesis that\rgenetic factors are relevant to the develop-\rment of childhood autism.  evidence is also\rpresented that impaired acquisition of lan-\rguage may have hereditary determinants.\ra second set of probably homozygous\rtwins are reported who were also discordant\rfor autism.  this second case suggests that,\ralthough genetic factors may play a part, in\rsome cases the syndrome of infantile autism\rappears to be a reversible one.  in view of\rthis set of twins and of kanner\'s sibling data,\rthe role of genetic factors remains obscure,\rand more twin studies properly documented\rwith blood typing are needed.\r'),
 (805,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evaluation and treatment planning\rfor autistic children\rinfantile autism is considered to be a re-\raction on the part of an immature organism\rat a primitive and undifferentiated stage of\rego development.  little choice of defensive\rreactions is available; the possibility of sub-\rlimation does not exist and, even though\rother object relationships are gradually\rdeveloping, the mother is still the child\'s\rprimary object.  at this vulnerable develop-\rmental stage, a wide range of pathological\rcircumstances, ranging from the most severe\rfamily psychopathology to the most adventi-\rtious physiological traumata or the most un-\rfortunately malignant circumstances, may\rconstitute an acute or cumulative cata-\rstrophic stress.  the primitive organism\rtends to respond to this overwhelming stress\rwith a paranoid reaction which is directed at\rthe mother (regardless of the actual etiologi-\rcal variables) because the mother is still the\rchild\'s primary object.  we believe that the\rchild then responds with an autistic reaction\rand shows varying degrees of simple with-\rdrawal, obsessional behavior, magical or de-\rlusional thought processes, and consequent\rdisruption of developmental skills, speech,\rand relationships with others.\rmany families can and do make every\reffort to counter the paranoid reaction of the\rchild and do not respond to his rejection with\rcounterrejection and counterwithdrawal.\rsome of the child\'s autistic symptoms may\rabate without formal treatment.  yet, since\rthe mother (and family) are the primary\robjects of the child\'s paranoid attitude, it is\rfelt that formal therapeutic intervention is\rnecessary to modify the paranoid core of\rthe autistic reaction.\r'),
 (806,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a twenty-five year view of\rtherapeutic results\rthus this group of ten patients shows a complete range of\rchronic schizophrenia from a bright pseudoneurotic never hospitalized,\rto an inaccessible patient chronically hospitalized for 20 years.\rphysiological therapy in the form of metrazol-induced convulsions\rgiven in the course of a puberty schizophrenic psychosis, has been\rhelpful to some by making them more accessible for the total treat-\rment program in the hospital or by raising their margin of tolerance\rsufficiently so that they could live at home and attend public schools\rat least for a time and at best, indefinitely.\rseveral of the most regressed, deteriorated patients in state hospitals\rfor many years, have been brought back to some level of meaningful\rliving again by the current drug therapy program, and are still im-\rproving.\rnow we have not determined who the sinner may be.  there are\rmany who will believe that the mother is always the sinner; is she\rnot schizophrenogenic?  there are others who will believe that the\rindividual himself is the sinner since, after all, is he not the one\rwhose behavior and fantasies are schizophrenic?  however, there will\rbe many of you attending this fifty-second annual meeting of the\ramerican psychopathological association, who will judge the speaker\rto be the sinner, for have i not given you this wealth of clinical ma-\rterial without charts, graphs, or statistical evaluation?\r'),
 (807,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'group psychotherapy with preschool\rpsychotic children and collateral\rgroup therapy of their parents:\ra preliminary report of the first two years\ra group approach in the treatment of preschool-aged psychotic children is\rreported.  autism is a defense against loss of the symbiotic partner.  the\rgroup of children penetrates this defense and forms a \"group ego,\" which\rconstitutes one pole of a new therapeutic symbiosis from which\rseparation-individuation can occur.\r'),
 (808,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'autistic reactions in early childhood:\rdifferential diagnostic considerations\rthe term \"autism\" is frequently used today\rin the differential diagnosis of the severe\remotional disturbances of early childhood.\rhowever, to label a child as \"autistic\"\rpresents some formidable problems with\rregard to definition of the term, the specific\retiological-diagnostic implications, and\rtreatment considerations for any given\rchild so designated.  the purpose of this\rpaper is to briefly review some of the\rhistorical psychiatric background of the term\r\"autism\", its more recent ramifications,\rand our clinical experiences in this field.\r'),
 (809,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'infantile autism: a family approach\rthe autistic child appears to be unable to integrate or to respond to\rstimuli, both from an internal source, the body, as well as from external\rsources, such as human contact.  we have noted in the children at our\rresidential treatment center how in their preliminary period with us they\rappear to be unaware of their body; they give the impression of being\rinsensitive to pain, display little autoerotic behavior, inflict injury on\rthemselves, such as hitting their heads against objects and biting their own\rbodies, with little outward display of distress.  in working with these\rchildren in therapy, one of the guideposts for change and for growth is a\rdisplay on the child\'s part of an increased body awareness and autoerotic\rbehavior.  for example, one child who developed polio during his early stay\rat the clinic residence did not communicate this to anyone and it was only\rmade known by observing the child\'s dragging one leg (memorial guid-\rance clinic, 1959).  later, he was able to point to his body and to indicate\rpain.  another child, who at first seemed to be quite unaware of both himself\rand others, concurrent with his growing display of affective expression\rtoward the therapist also manifested pleasure through genital stimulation,\rwas quite ticklish, and when injured would display the area of pain quite\rreadily.\r'),
 (810,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an analysis of the language of fourteen\rschizophrenic children\rfourteen schizophrenic (autistic) children were studied by means of detailed\rbehavioural histories and observations.\rthe language recorded in history and observation protocols was analysed and\rcompared with available data on normal children.\rall schizophrenic children were grossly retarded in their language development\rand all measures of this correlated highly with a previous overall clinical\rassessment of the severity of illness.\rthe most striking abnormalities in the language of the children studied were\rstereotyped repetition of utterances appropriate to an earlier developmental\rlevel or to a previous environmental context, accompanied by a lack of normal\rexpressions of curiosity and of responsiveness to changing environmental cues.\r'),
 (811,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a behavioural and electroencephalographic\rstudy of autistic children\rshort biographies are given of 10 children,\rage 3 to 6 years, diagnosed as suffering from\rkanner\'s syndrome (early infantile autism).\ran analysis was made of the free-field acti-\rvities of these children compared with a group\rof normal children of similar age.  electro-\rencephalographic studies were also carried out\ron all 10 children, and in two it was possible\rto carry out simultaneous behavioural and\reeg observations by means of telemetry.\rthe children were observed for three minute\rperiods in four environments of varying\rcomplexity: a. an empty room; b. the same\rroom with toy wooden blocks present; c.\rblocks plus passive adult; d. blocks plus active\radult.  except in a the visual fixations and\rmanipulatory activities were of significantly\rshorter duration in the autistic children than\rin the normals, lacked clear \'cut-off\' points\rand showed relatively little variability between\renvironments.  the autistic children as a\rwhole showed virtually no constructive play in\rcontrast with the normals, though more\rtime was spent in contact with play materials in\rthe social environments.  changes in the\rtime spent in locomotion, gesturing, block-play\rand manipulation of other objects in the\renvironment showed that the autistic children\rwere acutely responsive to changes in their\renvironment, including the presence of the social\rstimulus.  if the autistic children were\rsubdivided into those who characteristically showed\rstereotypies and those who did not, the\rlatter sub-group showed a behaviour structure which\rwas very similar to that of the normals,\rwhereas the stereotypy sub-group was clearly\rdifferentiated from both the normal children\rand the non-stereotypy sub-group.\reight autistic children had waking eeg\rrecords characterized by low voltage irregular\ractivity without any established rhythms;\rone child, a record containing irregular alpha\rand another unstable theta activity.  two of\rthe children with \'flat\' laboratory eegs showed\rmore rhythmic, higher voltage records when\rtheir eegs were telemetred in environment a.\rthey also showed less stereotyped behaviour.\rin environments b and d they showed pro-\rgressively more irregular eeg activity and\rmore stereotypy.\rthe hypothesis is advanced that autistic\rchildren are in a chronically high state of physio-\rlogical arousal.  the findings of the present\rstudy and those of other workers are discussed\rwith respect to this hypothesis.\r'),
 (812,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the autistic child in the school and the\rschool-nurse teacher responsibility\rautistic children demonstrate a more persistent pattern of retreating\rfrom reality than is apparent in those children categorized as normal.\rsome psychologists have established the cause of symptoms in the autistic\rchild as extreme anxiety which forces withdrawal from social contact.\rsuch anxiety is reported to have its initial occurrance during the age\rrange of one to five years.  a sense of security which is considered es-\rsential for a child is gained through overt manifestations of love, care and\rapproval of those adults most closely associated with him.  when this\rneed is not satisfied, the child\'s attempts at self-realization and esteem\rare deterred or thwarted, and a state of anxiety may result.  the severity\rof the anxiety may be the forerunner of a schizophrenic disorder.  such\ra condition can develop in a child, an adolescent or an adult.  schizo-\rphrenia, a serious mental illness, is considered to be a major cause for\radmitting patients to mental institutions.\ranother school of thought has placed infantile autism in the category\rof a disturbance resulting from abnormalities of development during the\rintrauterine period.  such a congenital condition is not categorized as\rmental retardation.\ryet another concept of autism conceives of the problem as the absence\rof an innate ability or capacity for developing meaningful contacts with\rother people.  a detachment of varying degrees persists where human\rcontacts are concerned.\r'),
 (813,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the autistic child\rthe conditions most frequently mistaken\rfor autism are speech disorder, brain damage\rand mental deficiency, each a prominent\rsymptom of the psychotic child.  careful his-\rtory and close observation to disclose symp-\rtoms of withdrawal, lack of ego, compulsion\rfor sameness, and displays of intelligence\rgive incomplete clues to the diagnosis.\rthe etiology of autism is uncertain.  sev-\reral factors seem significant.  the important\rrole of organic damage of the brain is under-\rscored by the coincidence of epilepsy, eeg\rand neurological abnormalities in these chil-\rdren.  in our series seizures of various types\roccurred in 25%, eeg abnormalities in 58%,\rand minor neurological deficits in 70% of\rthe cases.  environmental factors are quite\robviously important in many instances.  the\remotional and behavioral pattern of the par-\rents toward the infant is often incriminated.\rseparation, inattention, coldness, rejection,\retc. have been found in many situations.  fa-\rmilial incidence of psychoses is low; so is\rthat of autism in siblings.\r'),
 (814,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'shadow therapy\rshadow therapy was developed at sunland\rtraining center in gainesville, florida, because of communica-\rtion difficulties with disturbed, psychotic children.  it was con-\rjectured that subjects would reveal their anxieties and conflicts\rmore readily in a simulated night situation.\rthe therapy was conducted in a darkroom with projector\rlight used to produce silhouettes and their accompanying\rshadows as additional stimuli.  twelve subjects attended.  in\rthis article, the reaction of a child who was autistic and severely\rdisturbed is used as an illustration of subject reactions.  in the\rplayroom, he exhibited static behavior; in the darkroom, re-\rgressive-transcendential behavior.  he also transcended his usual\rlevel of vocalizing and socializing.\r'),
 (815,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'language training in the treatment\rof the autistic child\rfunctioning on a retarded level\ra preliminary study to\rdetermine the effect of language and\rspeech therapy on the development of\rcommunication and the lessening of un-\rrelatedness in a group of non-verbal,\rautistic children functioning on a retarded\rlevel is reported.  on the basis of the re-\rsults of the study, it is suggested that the\rinclusion of language and speech therapy\rtechniques be considered in developing a\rtreatment program for such children.\r'),
 (816,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the convergence and interaction of visual,\rauditory, and tactile responses in human\rnonspecific cortex\rthe relation between the electrical responses in the human brain and\rmental processes of integration and association is perhaps the most chal-\rlenging of all the problems facing neurophysiologists today.  until quite\rrecently the prospect of unifying physiological and psychological concepts\rby electro-encephalographic (eeg) techniques seemed to be receding\rbecause of the baffling complexity of the intrinsic electrical rhythms, and\rthis difficulty has still not been overcome.  the most intriguing, and at\rthe same time most elusive, of the properties of these rhythms is that,\ralthough often remarkably constant in their variations with respect to\rtime, they fluctuate also, in a much less regular manner, within the three\rdimensional space of the brain.  the continuous analysis and display of\rsuch a phenomenon presents serious difficulties, and no method has yet\rgiven entirely satisfactory results.\rthe incentive to construct adequate equipment and to design and per-\rform crucial experiments is undoubtedly limited by the uncertainty as\rto whether the information likely to be obtained in this way is essential\rto understanding brain mechanisms; few experimenters imagine that it\rwould be sufficient.\r'),
 (817,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'infantile autism and the schizophrenias\rin a paper published in 1943, entitled \"au-\rtistic disturbances of affective con-\rtact,\" i reported from the children\'s psychi-\ratric service of the johns hopkins hospital\robservations of 11 children (8 boys and 3\rgirls) who had in common a pattern of be-\rhavior not previously considered in its\rstriking uniqueness.  the symptoms were\rviewed as a combination of extreme alone-\rness from the beginning of life and an anx-\riously obsessive desire for the preservation\rof sameness.  i concluded the discussion by\rsaying: \"we must assume that these chil-\rdren have come into the world with an\rinnate inability to form the usual, biologi-\rcally provided affective contact with people,\rjust as other children come into the world\rwith innate physical and intellectual handi-\rcaps.  if this assumption is correct, a further\rstudy of our children may help to furnish\rconcrete criteria regarding the still diffuse\rnotions about the constitutional components\rof emotional reactivity.  for here we seem to\rhave pure-culture examples of inborn au-\rtistic disturbances of affective contact.\"\rin my search for an appropriate designa-\rtion, i decided in 1944, after much groping,\ron the term early infantile autism, thus\raccentuating the time of the first manifesta-\rtions and the children\'s limited accessibility.\r'),
 (818,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'autistic children\rautism is a form of childhood schizophrenia.  a sudden\rseparation from his mother or traumatic shock in\rearly life causes the child to reject the world of nor-\rmal relationships.  leading him back to the original\rtraumatic situation is part of the treatment described\rin this article.\r'),
 (819,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'gilles de la tourette syndrome in an autistic child\ra case of gilles de la tourette syndrome\rpresenting an early infantile autism is\rdescribed.  the treatment applied is outlined.\r'),
 (820,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'psychodrama for disturbed children\rpsychodrama is especially adaptable to the treat-\rment of mentally ill children.  it evokes a degree\rof spontaneity and involvement that is difficult to\rattain with many group therapies, and it offers situa-\rtions in which the children can participate as actors\ror as observers.  competition and restriction are\rminimal: the child can do what comes naturally.  in-\rdeed, much of children\'s natural play is in the form\rof dramatic activity.  their make-believe is, how-\rever, more intense than acting, for a child becomes\rthe person or thing he pretends to be: a fireman,\ran indian, a horse, a tiger.\r'),
 (821,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the speech and language abilities of\remotionally disturbed children\rthe speech and language disorders of\rthese severely disturbed children can be\rdivided into two categories which relate\rto the type of psychiatric disturbance.\rthe autistic-schizophrenic children used\rbizarre forms of language or did not use\rcommunicative language at all.  the non-\rautistic-schizophrenic, the neurotic, the\rprimary behaviour disorder, and the\rminimally brain-damaged children as a\rgroup, had similar speech and language\rproblems to normal children but of a\rmore severe and frequent nature.  their\rproblems were predominantly in the\rareas of speech and language develop-\rment, articulation, rate of speech and\rfluency.  the children with primary be-\rhaviour disorders had the more severe\rspeech and language problems.\r'),
 (822,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a study of childhood schizophrenia\rand early infantile autism\r(part i--description of the sample)\rfollowing a period of observation of\rthree months\' duration, a group of twelve\rautistic schizophrenic children were se-\rlected for a treatment program.  the\rgroup was selected on criteria which\rwould allow a reasonable chance of suc-\rcessful treatment in a group homo-\rgeneous enough to allow statistical con-\rsiderations to be valid.\ryounger age, average intellectual func-\rtioning, presence of an intact family in\ror near to metropolitan toronto and a\rfirm diagnosis of autistic schizophrenia\rwere the limiting factors.\rrather distinct differences were noted\rin this treatment group as opposed to the\rlarger observation group.  the dis-\rtinguishing characteristic was undoubted-\rly the speech abnormalities present.\r'),
 (823,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'discussion sur les pseudo-tumeurs osseuses\rdes hemophiles\rdoctors queneau and josso each described one\rcase of pseudo-tumour of the calcaneum analagous\rto that described by trillat and favre-gilly; they\rdemonstrated x-rays; dr. alagille referred to a\rhaemophilic cyst of the maxilla and dr. favre-gilly\rto a cyst of the perineum; dr. kugler had seen a\rcase where an erroneous diagnosis of osteosarcoma\rhad been made.\r'),
 (824,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of joint position on the pressure\rof intra-articular effusion\rit is known that joints with symptomatic effusions are held spontaneously in\rcharacteristic positions and that movement of these joints increases pain.  in\rthe study reported here, a correlation was made between the hydrostatic\rpressure of a joint effusion and the joint\'s position.  the results indicate a\rpossible relationship between intra-articular pressure and pain.\r'),
 (825,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haemophilic blood cyst\ra mongol boy of ten, a known haemophiliac, was seen in the orthopaedic\rdepartment of southmead hospital in may 1962 with a swelling of the left foot.\rthe parents were aware of a steady increase in size since the swelling was\rfirst noticed two months before.  on examination, a cystic swelling was seen to\roccupy the forefoot, the skin on the dorsum being stretched over it and a\rdusky red in colour (fig. 1).  radiographs showed destruction of the proximal\rtwo-thirds of the third metatarsal bone, an appearance consistent, it was\rthought with destruction from within by an expanding lesion (fig. 2).  the\rdiagnosis of a haemophilic blood cyst was made.\r'),
 (826,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment and prevention of chronic haemorrhagic\rarthropathy and contractures in haemophilia\rorthopaedic treatment of joint deformities in thirteen patients with\rhaemophilia is reviewed over a period of seven years.\rforms of treatment discussed include open operation, manipulation under general\ranaesthesia, continuous traction, splintage and physiotherapy.  the amount of\rintravenous therapy required for each form of treatment is indicated.\rin discussing prevention of joint deformity the histories of a further eighteen\rpatients have been taken into account.  it is concluded that initially painless\rhaemarthroses provide the main threat to joint deformity in haemophilia.\rthe best preventive treatment is early immobilisation followed by prolonged\rsplintage and physiotherapy; intravenous therapy with antihaemophilic factor\rplays a less important role here than in other forms of haemorrhage.\revidence is presented that joint deformity in severe haemophilia can often be\rentirely avoided.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (827,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'osteopatia in emofilia\rthe aa. present the case material of the literature and one\rpersonal remark of extrarticular osteopathy in\rhemophilia.  they examine the anatomic and clinical picture of\rthe illness in its most important and less known\rpeculiarities and they dwell upon the curative medico-surgical\rproblems of the affection.\r'),
 (828,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'la plasmatherapie a minima dans le traitement de la\rdouleur des hemarthroses hemophiliques\rsome fifty clinically similar cases of hemophilic hemarthrosis were, after\rimmobilization, either treated with placebo and plasma perfusion or else with\rcorticoids and analgesics.\ra very small quantity of plasma is sufficient to stop the pain for the\rfollowing few hours.\rit is attempted to give a physio-pathologic explanation which would seem in\raccord with the pathogenic studies on hemophiliac by r. marx et al.\r'),
 (829,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effet analgesique immediat des injections de plasma\rpour hemarthroses recentes du genou des hemophiles\ra single injection of 20 ml of lyophilized fresh plasma per kg body weight is\rproposed as a treatment in recent cases of knee hemarthrosis with an\rimportant distension of the capsule, so as to achieve hemostasis, and reduce\rthe evolutive period.  pain is always acute and permanent in such cases of\rhemarthrosis; it subsides during the plasma injection, or immediately\rafterwards.\r'),
 (830,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hip disarticulation in a\rpatient with hemophilia\rdisarticulation of the hip in a hemophiliac patient\rwas performed because of a severe osteomyelitis\rinvolving the entire right femur and was lifesaving.\rthe following are suggestions for hemotologic man-\ragement: (1) infected wounds in hemophiliac pa-\rtients should be left open initially.  (2) electro-\rcautery should not be used in an infected wound of\ra hemophiliac patient.  (3) a safe fibrinogen prepa-\rration potent in the antihemophilic factor is now\ravailable in this country and is a highly significant\radvance in the surgical treatment of hemophilia.\r'),
 (831,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haemophilia in sweden\rvii. incidence, treatment and prophylaxis of\rarthropathy and other musculo-skeletal\rmanifestations of haemophilia a and b\rthe clinical material consisted of 242 of the 308 known haemophiliacs\r(a and b) in sweden.  the investigation included clinical examination of\rall major joints in 95 of 116 patients with severe haemophilia, in 38 of\r65 patients with moderate haemophilia, and in 24 of 127 patients with\rmild haemophilia, and roentgen examination of practically all joints\rfound to be abnormal at the clinical examination.  in addition information\rabout 7 patients with severe haemophilia, 21 with moderate haemophilia,\rand 57 with mild haemophilia was obtained by questionnaire only.\rthe degree of arthropathy (grades 2, 3 and 4) was classified largely\raccording to depalma and cotler (1956).  evaluation of general disability\rwas made with regard to ability to manage (walk, dress, eat, toilet) with-\rout help.  this latter evaluation comprised also extra-articular manifesta-\rtions of haemophilia.\r'),
 (832,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'interet de la radiotherapie dans les hemarthroses\rrecidivantes du genou chez l\'hemophile\rradiotherapy was delivered at a dose of 100 r\rrepeated from 7 to 10 times, to 22 knees of haemo-\rphiliac children presenting recurring arthropathies.\rirradiation had no harmful effect on growth of\rpatients; it was beneficial in two thirds of the cases,\rreducing considerably the number per annum of\rhaemarthrosis onsets; one third of the patients\rshowed no significant result: the number of onsets\rwas the same in the following year.\rtotally the average of infirmary stays due to knee\rhaemarthrosis was 175 days in the year before radio-\rtherapy and 25 days in the following year.\rthe authors think that these results justify this\rtherapeutic method.\r'),
 (833,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'discussion sur les donnees radiologiques\rdans les arthropathies des genoux\rprofessor marchal acts as moderator.\rdr. le coeur wonders if the fringed appearance of\rcondyles has really a pathological significance; that\rappearance could be normal in young children, but,\rin the opinion of dr. queneau, it seems to be patho-\rlogical in older children.\rit seems to dr. favre-gilly and dr. queneau that\rscalariform traits occur more frequently in haemo-\rphiliac children than in normal ones.\rdr. le coeur thought that fibrillary decalcification\rwas the ultimate stage of decalcification, whereas\rdr. favre-gilly has the impression that it represents\rin haemophiliac subjects an early stage anterior to\rhomogeneous decalcification.\raccording to brinkhous, densification of synovial\rmembranes are a result of an infiltration of the joint\rcartilage due to haemosideraemia; this is also the\ropinion of dr. favre-gilly and dr. izarn.\rdr. izarn asks if geodes are caused by intra-\rosseous haemorrhages or necroses; dr. queneau and\rdr. de mourgues think that anatomical data con-\rcerning haemophiliac subjects are insufficient for\rthat question to be answered.\r'),
 (834,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'etude radiographique des genoux de 100 hemophiles\rde 7 a 15 ans\rradiographic examination of the knee were syste-\rmatically performed in 100 haemophiliac subjects\raged from 7 to 15 years, 64 of whom had a bilateral\rhaemarthrosis, 30 had only one knee affected and\r6 were uninjured.\ran intra-articular opacification, observed in\r29 knees, corresponded to a recent haemarthrosis.\rdensification of the synovial membrane was ob-\rserved in 25 knees and corresponded to iron\rdeposits.\ran interlinear pinch was present in 52 knees.\rerosions of articular surfaces are especially fre-\rquent (78 knees) or homogeneous (28 knees).\rhypertrophy of condyles or knee-caps, broadening\rof intercondylian space, crushing of internal tibial\rdisk, genu valgum and posterior subluxation of tibia\rare osseous deformations that are encountered.\ratrophy of femur diaphysis explains the frequency\rof fracture of femur.\rsome of these aspects seem to occur early (inter-\rlinear pinch, erosion of the surfaces), others are\rtardier (geodes, decalcification).\ra relation between the intensity of abnormal radio-\rlogical findings and the severity of sequelae does\rnot always exist, but one can observe major radio-\rlogical alterations only when there is a major bio-\rlogical disturbance.\r'),
 (835,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'blood vascular disorders in\rconnection with the nose,\rthroat and ear\rthese disorders include (1) those having lesions\rprimarily in the nose, throat or ear, and (2) those\rproducing symptoms and signs in nose, throat\rand/or ear only as a part of their symptomatology\rand involve other organs as well.  we will con-\rsider the lesions in connection with the nose,\rthroat and ear separately.\r'),
 (836,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'volkmann\'s ischaemia\rvolkmann\'s ischaemia is the name given to a sequence\rof events originally described by volkmann in 1881.\rbasically the condition consists of the replacement of\rthe limb flexor muscles by fibrous tissue following injury or\rocclusion of the main arterial supply of blood to these\rmuscles.  the condition is rare fortunately--mainly because\rof improved methods of prevention.  the flexor muscles of\rthe toes are sometimes affected, but the commonest group of\rmuscles so damaged are the flexor muscles of the forearm.\rtotal arterial occlusion to a limb for several hours usually\rcauses frank gangrene; partial or total occlusion for shorter\rperiods may give rise to ischaemic contracture.  the muscles,\rbeing deprived of their blood supply, die and are sub-\rsequently replaced by fibrous tissue.  like all scars, the fibrous\rtissue contracts, producing the complete picture of\rvolkmann\'s ischaemic contracture.  the forearm is thin and\rwasted, and the fingers are held in flexion owing to the\roverall shortening of the flexor muscles.  in severe cases, if\rthe nerves are also affected or if the entire muscle mass is\rreplaced by fibrosis, the fingers may be totally paralysed\ras well.\r'),
 (837,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'klinik der polyarthrosen\ramong the degenerative affections of joints\rthe symptoms of the arthrosis of\rthe joints of the fingers with heberden-nodes,\rthe bouchard-nodes of the inter-\rdigital joints, the polyarthrosis - on those subjects\rcoste and forestier wrote about\rand how they were described by lffb too - and the\rarthropathies of chronic gout are\rmore thoroughly discussed.  the rare conditions,\ras the arthrotic changes in hemo-\rphilia, psoriasis and metabolic disorders are\rmentioned.  a wider area is dedicated\rto the differentiation between degenerative and\rinflammatory diseases.  it is refer-\rred to, that gout more often occurs in our days\rand one is forced to calculate with\rit more than some years ago.  it is also referred\rto the significance of the serolo-\rgical reactions for the differential diagnosis.\rthe most important diseases are\renumerated, which do not belong to degenerative\rpolyarticular affections of joints,\rbut which very often get mixed up with them.\r'),
 (838,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'major surgical procedures,\rincluding amputation,\ron a hemophiliac\rvarious surgical procedures in a hemo-\rphilia a patient, including amputation above\rthe knee, are reported.  human cohn fraction\ri (fibrinogen/ahg) was used to ensure\rnormal hemostasis.  the patient\'s ability to\rform a firm clot within a normal time was\rmeasured and treatment was prescribed in\raccordance with serial studies with the\rthrombelastograph.\r'),
 (839,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the prevention of crippling\rin haemophilic children\rchildren who are severely affected with haemo-\rphilia or christmas disease suffer repeated\rhaemorrhages into joints and muscles after trivial\rinjuries.  these episodes of bleeding produce\rcumulative crippling.  the haemarthroses tend to be\rrecurrent; each episode produces some damage to\rthe joint surface and the immobility during con-\rvalescence leads to muscle weakness.  thus after\rrecovery the joint becomes increasingly liable to\rrenewed bleeding.  the deep muscle haematomata\rcan produce crippling by actual destruction of\rmuscle tissue, by pressure on important nerves or\rarteries, by contractures which develop during\rhealing and by failure of resolution of the original\rhaematoma leading to chronic cyst formation.\r'),
 (840,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'throat and nose surgery\rin patients with\rconstitutional haemostatic defects\rsuccessful surgery in patients with defective\rhaemostasis is becoming possible and it is of inter-\rest to detail the problems encountered in nose and\rthroat surgery.\r'),
 (841,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hemophilic arthropathy\rjaromir priborsky, zora antalovska\rthe authors report their experience with joint\rdiseases in 54 patients suffering from hemo-\rphilia, 49 of them being cases of hemophilia a,\r5 of hemophilia b.  21 patients were children\rup to the age of 14 years.  bleeding into the joints\roccurred in 66.6% of patients.  in the age\rgroup over 14 years the cases of bleeding into\rthe joints were more frequent (78.8%) than\rin the age group up to 14 years (47.7%).\rthere were no differences as to bleeding into the\rjoints and the seriousness of articular changes\rbetween the cases of hemophilia a and hemo-\rphilia b.  in most cases the bleeding into the\rjoints began between the 6th and the 14th year\rof age.  bleeding into the joints as the first\rmanifestation of a hemophilic condition occurred\ronly in 9.3% of patients; in most cases other\rhemophilic manifestations preceded.  in spite of\rthis fact the joint manifestations were often\rwrongly diagnosed as tuberculous arthritis, rheumatic\rfever, progressive arthritis, and were treated\raccordingly.  most usually the large joints (knee,\relbow, ankle) were affected with bleeding and in\rthem the changes were also the most serious.  the\rjoints of both halves of the body were\raffected uniformly.  in most cases several joints were\raffected while monoarticular localization\rwas observed in 16.6%.  the seriousness of articular\rchanges was dependent mainly on the\rnumber of repeated bleedings into one and the same\rjoint, although other factors (weight bearing\rof the joint, complexity of the joint, treatment) may be\rof decisive importance in the individual\rcases as well.\raccording to clinical (especially from\rthe functional point of view) and x-ray criteria the\rarticular findings were classified into three\rgroups: in the first group the function of the joint\ris preserved, in the second limited and\rin the third practically extinguished.  the following\rlaboratory tests were carried out: erythrocyte\rsedimentation reaction, latex test for the rheu-\rmatoid factor, c-reactive protein, mecoprotein\rtyrosine and weltmann\'s coagulation test.\rthe findings were normal even in cases of\rirreparable articular changes unless acute bleeding\rinto the joint or in some other localization,\ror some other complicating disorder was present\rsimultaneously.\rthe therapy of hemophilic arthropathy\rremains troublesome owing especially to a frequent\roccurrence of articular bleeding.\ra close cooperation of the hematologist\rand the rheumatologist or the orthopedist may con-\rtribute to the improvement of the fate of\rthese patients.\r'),
 (842,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'prevention and treatment of joint deformity in haemophilia\rexperience in treating established joint deformities in 27 patients, and\rpreventing the development of deformtiy in 10 younger patients, during the last\r8 years, has shown that there are two types of haemorrhage, which require\rdifferent treatment to prevent chronic deformity.\r'),
 (843,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the haemophilic pseudotumour\ror haemophilic subperiosteal haematoma\rthe case history of a haemophiliac in whom a large haematoma of the thigh was\rtreated by amputation of the limb is described.\rexamination of the available radiographs and of the histology led to the\rconclusion that the cyst was subperiosteal in origin.\revidence is presented to support the hypothesis that haemophilic pseudotumours\rare always associated with subperiosteal haemorrhage, and that those\rhaemophilic cysts which are confined to muscle have little or no effect on the\radjacent bone.\r'),
 (844,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'actinomycin d and the response to parathyroid hormone\ractinomycin d inhibits the effect of\rparathyroid hormone upon bone, as measured\rby ca mobilization, without altering\rits effects upon the renal excretion of\rphosphate and ca in rats.\r'),
 (845,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'aspects of circadian periodic changes in\rphosphorus metabolism in mice\rkinetic studies on the p32 content of\rmouse brain phosphorus fractions following\rthe intraperitoneal injection of p32-labeled\rorthophosphate were performed during\rtwo selected segments of the 24-hour time scale.\rthe results of these studies suggest\rthat the circadian periodicity in relative\rspecific activity of brain phospholipids\ris probably a consequence of a variation in the extent\rof p32 incorporation into brain\rinorganic phosphate and is not indicative\rof a periodicity in the rate of intermediary\rphospholipid metabolism.  data on the postinjection\rtime course of the specific activities\rof plasma inorganic phosphate, liver inorganic phosphate,\rand liver phospholipid\rsuggest a similar explanation for\rthe circadian periodic changes in relative\rspecific activity of liver phospholipids.\ra circadian rhythm of inorganic phosphate\rconcentration in mouse plasma is demonstrated.\rconsideration of a mathematical\rmodel suggests that the observed within-day\rvariation in p32 distribution and the\rcircadian periodicity of phospholipid relative\rspecific activity in liver and brain\rare a consequence of this periodicity in\rplasma phosphate content.  a significant\rwithin-day variation in total phosphorus\rcontent of liver was observed.  the disturbance\rof mice incident to p32 injection\rhas a marked effect on the plasma content\rof inorganic phosphate and corticosterone.\r'),
 (846,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'specificity of the inhibition of tubular\rphosphate reabsorption by certain amino-acids\rthe inhibition of tubular phosphate\rreabsorption by certain amino-acids is a highly\rspecific one in which differentiation between\rsuch closely related compunds as the\rd and l isomer is clearly possible.\r'),
 (847,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'localization of phosphaturic effect of\rparathyroid hormone in nephron of the dog\rthe renal mechanism and tubular site of the phosphaturic action of\rparathyroid hormone were investigated by clearance and stop-flow\rtechniques in one intact and seven thyroparathyroidectomized\rdogs.  administration of hormone caused a significant increase\rin the excretion of phosphate without increasing the filtered\rload.  stop-flow analysis indicated that in the absence of parathyroid\rhormone most of the filtered phosphate was reabsorbed\rin the proximal tubule, and that the hormone increased the\rrate of phosphate excretion by inhibiting this reabsorptive\rmechanism.  p32 injected during stopped flow showed no significant\rtransport across the renal tubule despite the presence of\rexcess parathyroid hormone.  significant p32 activity appeared\rin the stop-flow collections simultaneously with the appearance\rof new filtrate.  there was no evidence that parathyroid hormone\rmediated a secretory process for phosphate excretion.\r'),
 (848,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the regulation of growth hormone secretion\rin the present communication we summarize\rour investigations on the control\rof secretion of hgh using radioimmunoassay\rfor the measurement of plasma\rgh. the assumption, implied throughout this\rpresentation, that changes in\rsecretory rate are responsible for acute\rchanges in plasma concentration of\rhgh appears reasonable since the\rfluctuations in plasma hgh concentration\rare often too rapid to be caused solely by\ralterations in hormonal\rdegradation or excretion.  for slower changes\rin plasma hgh concentration,\rhowever, alterations in the rate of removal\rof hormone from the body fluids\rmight play a contributory role.  however,\rthere is no evidence that important\rchanges occur in the rate of removal of\rhgh from the circulation except in\rpatients who have developed antibodies\rto hgh following treatment with hgh.\r'),
 (849,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'early infantile autism and receptor processes\rthe syndrome of early infantile autism is examined\ras a function of deviation in\rnear-distance receptor usage.  these receptor\rdeviations are compared with normal\rreceptor hierarchies developing from near\rto distance receptor dominance.  the\ravailable information is consistent with the\rview that early infantile autism involves\rearly sensory deprivation.  this sensory\rdeprivation results from an interaction\rbetween a constitutional deficiency inhibiting\rcertain reticular arousal functions\rand mothering tending to understimulation.\rtreatment of the young autistic child is suggested\rincluding stimulation and communication\rvia the available near receptor\rsystems.  in the framework of sensory development,\rdirections for the study of early\rdiagnosis and treatment are indicated.\r'),
 (850,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on compensatory renal hypertrophy.  i.  effect of\runilateral ureteral ligation and transection\rdata are presented comparing the relative rate\rof compensatory renal hypertrophy\rand hyperplasia of the control kidney of rats\rfollowing either unilateral ureteral\rtransection, ligation, or nephrectomy.  the growth\rof the control kidney on the unoperated\rside was strikingly slower after ureteral\rtransection and ligation when\rcompared with that resulting from the removal\rof one kidney.  progressive hydronephrosis\rwas observed on the operated side following\rureteral transection and\rligation and was more pronounced in the latter.\rdegree of hypertrophy of the control\rkidney showed a close correlation with degree and\rduration of the hydronephrosis of\rthe kidney on the operated side.  these observations\rhave been interpreted as indicating\rthe operation of a control system regulating\rkidney growth in response to\rchanges in some way related to kidney size.\r'),
 (851,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of the changes in growth\rand dna synthesis in the rat kidney\rduring experimentally induced\rrenal hypertrophy\rthere is a high rate of accumulation of\rnewly synthesized dna in the kidney after folic\racid injection, compared with the small increase\rduring the first few days after unilateral nephrectomy.\rthere is a large increase in the water content\rof the kidney after folic acid which does not\roccur after unilateral nephrectomy.  the changes\rin the wet and dry weight and the rna and dna\rcontent of the kidney have been compared after\radministration of folic acid, unilateral nephrectomy\rand unilateral nephrectomy followed by folic\racid 24 hr later in an attempt to study the nature\rof these differences.  after unilateral nephrectomy\rthere was a steady increase in wet weight, dry\rweight and rna content of the kidney, each parameter\rreaching about 35 to 40% above normal by\r14 days, by which time the dna content had increased\rby only about 25%.  an increased rate of\rdna synthesis was found between 2 and 4 days,\rreturning almost to normal by 7 days.  after folic\racid injection there were very large increases in\rwet weight (60%), rna content (100%) and dna content\r(70%) during the first 4 days accompanied by\ra smaller increase in dry weight (30%).  thereafter\rthese parameters declined, relative to body weight,\rreturning almost to normal by 14 days.  the rate\rof dna synthesis was greatly increased as early\ras 24 hr after injection and reached a much higher\rlevel than that found after unilateral nephrectomy,\rbefore returning to the normal level by 7 days.\rwhen unilateral nephrectomy was followed 24 hr\rlater by folic acid injection, the increases in\rweight, nucleic acid content and rate of dna synthesis\rwere greater than at the corresponding\rtimes after either treatment alone.  marked differences\rwere found in the labeling indices of kidney\rcells after either unilateral nephrectomy or folic\racid injection.  the latter treatment resulted in very\rlarge increases in all three zones of the kidney,\rwhereas after unilateral nephrectomy the responses\rof the cortex and outer medulla were much lower,\rwith no significant increase in the inner medulla.\rwhen both treatments were combined, the response\rof the remaining kidney was similar to, though\rmore exaggerated than, that of the normal kidney\rafter folic acid injection.\r'),
 (852,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal and adrenal relationships\rin compensatory hyperplasia\rthe compensatory renal hyperplasia that\rnormally follows unilateral nephrectomy\ris abolished by bilateral adrenalectomy if\rrats are maintained on fresh drinking\rwater, but is restored when saline drinking\rwater is provided or if such animals are\rinjected with doca.  the adrenals are also\rimportant for the increased proliferation\rcaused by unilateral hydronephrosis.  these\rexperiments suggest that the role of the\radrenal cortex in renal hyperplasia may be to\rsecrete mineralocorticoids, which\rpromote the retention of sodium and thereby\rstimulate cell division in the kidneys.\r'),
 (853,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a genetic study of neonatal obstructive jaundice\r58 children with extrahepatic biliary atresia, 7 with intrahepatic\rbiliary atresia and 50 with \'neonatal hepatitis\' were analysed\rconcerning diagnostic criteria, natural history, familial, clinical\rand pathological data.  in extrahepatic biliary atresia, there is no\revidence of a familial tendency, influence of maternal age, birth\rorder or disturbance of foetal development.  in \'neonatal hepatitis\',\rthere were 4 consanguineous parents, suggesting a mutant\rautosomal gene in homozygous form.  some infants with the genotype\rfor \'neonatal hepatitis\' may manifest a very mild or a very severe\rform, so, a diagnosis was not made.  an apparent excess of males\rover females may be another evidence of failure of manifestation of\rthe genotype.  but \'neonatal hepatitis\' may be a manifestation of\rmore than one disease.  in \'neonatal hepatitis\' the birth weight\rshows a marked decrease, perhaps as a sequence of disturbed liver\rfunction in the foetus.\r'),
 (854,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'parathyroid extract-induced changes in the oxidation of citrate,\rsuccinate and other organic acids by liver.\rparathyroid extract (pte) or partially\rpurified parathyroid hormone administered in\rvivo markedly altered the oxidation\rin vitro by rabbit liver minces of citrate, -keto\rglutarate-c, succinate-c, fumarate-c\rand lactate.  with ca ++ present in the\rincubation medium, minces from pte\rtreated animals produced more co and had\ra greater o consumption than did control\rminces.  this stimulation was due, in part\rat least, to a more rapid decline in metabolic\ractivity of the control tissues.  when\rca++ was absent, total metabolism was\rincreased and the tissue derived from pte\rtreated animals was less active than the\rcontrol tissue.  the effect was detected as\rearly as 4 hr after injection (750 u/kg)\rand could be elicited with as little as 200 u\r(at 14 hr).  the action of pte could not\rbe duplicated by the injection of cacl into\rthe animal.  the data suggest that one effect\rof treatment was a general inhibition of\roxidation.  the stimulation of metabolism\rcould be a consequence of this inhibition\ror a separate unrelated alteration.\r'),
 (855,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'actinomycin and erythropoiesis and the production of erythropoietin in\rmice.\rin b6d2f female mice a single dose of 10\rof actinomycin will suppress normal\rerythropoiesis (fe erythrocyte uptake).  in\rpolycythemic mice 2 is enough to\rprevent the stimulatory effect of 0.25 a units\rof erythropoietin.  the curves of suppression\rand recovery versus time support the\rhypothesis that erythropoietin acts\rfor a short time in an early stage of\rerythropoiesis; after this early stage developing\rcells are no longer so sensitive to actinomycin.\rrecovery, even from repeated\rdoses, is rapid and adequate.  amounts of\ractinomycin which are adequate to abolish\rerythropoiesis do not prevent the new appearance\rof erythropoietin in the plasma of\rhypoxic mice.\r'),
 (856,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the ultrastructure, histopathology, and\rhistochemistry of the parathyroid glands of pregnant\rand nonpregnant cows fed a high level of vitamin d.\rthe parathyroid glands of pregnant and\rnonpregnant cows were studied by light and\relectron microscopy following the daily\rfeeding of 30 million units of vit d for 30\rdays and compared to untreated controls.\rin both the pregnant and nonpregnant cows\rthe parathyroid glands became markedly\ratrophic with a diminution in the amount of\rparenchyma compared to the untreated controls.\rafter vit d feeding the number of\ractively secreting dark and intermediate\rchief cells was reduced and the percentage\rof inactive (light) and atrophic chief cells\rwas increased.  the parathyroid glands\rof the vit d-fed, nonpregnant cows were\rdominated by severely atrophic chief cells.\rthese cells were characterized by their\rhighly irregular shape, shrunken nucleus\rand cytoplasm, widened intercellular spaces\rtraversed by numerous cytoplasmic\rprocesses, increased electron density, few\rsecretory granules, inactive ergastoplasm\rand golgi complexes.  atrophic chief\rcells were not present in the untreated\rcontrols.  the predominating cell type in\rthe parathyroids of the vit d-fed pregnant\rcows were the inactive chief cells.  in contrast\rto the atrophic chief cells, they were\rlarger and more regular in shape with\rrelatively straight cell membranes.  they\rwere comparatively electron-transparent,\rcontaining more glycogen and fewer\rsecretory granules.  organelles concerned\rwith protein synthesis and packaging into\rsecretory units were poorly developed.\rinactive chief cells were observed only\roccasionally in the parathyroid glands of\runtreated pregnant cows where the actively\rsecreting dark and intermediate chief cells\rpredominated.\r'),
 (857,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of heparin and parathyroid extract an acid phosphatase in bone.\r   to test the theory that heparin\rmight stimulate acid\rphosphatase in the bone of\ryoung rats, heparin, pte,\ror a combination of both were\rinjected.  after an appropriate\rtime interval acid phosphatase\ractivity of bone of\rtreated animals was compared\rwith controls.  it was\rfound that heparin enhanced\rthe pte-stimulated acid\rphosphatase activity of both\rcalvaria and metaphysis but\rnot diaphysis.  the possible\rrelation of these facts to\rthe presence of lysosomes in\rosteoclasts was discussed.\r'),
 (858,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the isolation of thyrocalcitonin and study of its effects in the rat.\r   the thyroid secretes a\rpolypeptide hormone (thyrocalcitionin)\rwhich is effective\rin lowering plasma calcium\rand phosphate.  the hormone\rcan be extracted from\rthe thyroid of the rat, dog,\rpig, goat, ox, and monkey.\rthe isolation of the hormone\rfrom pig thyroid by a combination\rof salt fractionation\rand gel filtration is described.\rone microgram of\rthe pure material is very\ractive in the rat.  thyrocalcitonin\rremains effective after\rparathyroidectomy, after\rnephrectomy, after overdosage\rwith vitamin d, during vitamin\rd deficiency, and during\rcalcium or magnesium deficiency.\rits action is not prevented\rby prior administration\rof actinomycin d.  a\rsingle injection does not change\rsoft tissue calcium but\rinfusion for 12 hr lowers cardiac\rmuscle calcium.  it is\rconcluded that this new thyroid\rhormone acts on bone\rand that it probably plays an\rimportant role in normal physiology.\r'),
 (859,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of actinomycin d on parathyroid-induced\rchange in bone and kidney.\ractinomycin d (amd), an antibiotic known to\rinhibit dna-directed rna synthesis,\rwas used to study parathyroid-induced changes\rin ca mobilization in vivo and in vitro\ras well as renal excretion of ca and phosphate\rin rats.  intact and parathyroidectomized\rrats subjected to peritoneal lavage were\radministered amd, and changes in\rca, p, and mg in lavage and serum were\rexamined.  amd consistently lowered the\rca transfer into the peritoneal rinse in both\rthe intact and parathyroidectomized animals,\ralthough the drop in ca was more acute\rif the animals were pretreated by subcutaneous\rinjections of amd than if amd was\radministered as a component of the\rrinse.  pretreatment of lavaged animals with\ramd prevented the expected increase\rin osteoclast numbers in the distal metaphysis\rof the femur but had no effect if administered\ras a component of the peritoneal rinse.\rthe incubation of femora removed\rfrom both intact and parathyroidectomized\ranimals resulted in media ca levels that\rwere significantly lower after 4 hr. incubation\rwhen amd was added in vitro.  however,\rtransfer of recently injected ca into\rthe incubation medium from animals\rtreated with amd was increased.  in addition,\rparathyroidectomy of animals subsequent\rto administration of amd still resulted\rin expected changes in ca and p in the\rurine although amd significantly increased p\rexcretion in both intact and parathyroidectomized\ranimals.  it was concluded that\rendogenous parathyroid hormone requires\rthe continuous production of enzymes ultimately\rresponsible for its action on bone\rand kidney, but that this action is not necessarily\rrelated directly to the production\rof m-rna.\r'),
 (860,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'inhibition by actinomycin d of bone resorption\rinduced by parathyroid hormone or vitamin a.\ractinomycin d inhibits cell proliferation in\rcontrol cultures of embryonic rat bone\rand prevents the stimulation of bone resorption\rby parathyroid horome (pth) or vit.\ra.  with a dose of 0.004 /ml. of actinomycin\rd, pth effects are only partially inhibited\rand this inhibition can be overcome\rby increasing the dose of pth.  these\rfindings suggest that these agents act competitively.\r'),
 (861,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'j. clin. endocr. 1965, 25/4 (457-464).\rantagonism between parathyroid extract and adrenal\rcortical steroids in man.\rmetabolic balance studies were done in 2\rpatients with hypoparathyroidism who\rreceived hydrocortisone of prednisone\rduring the administration of parathyroid\rextract.  administration of prednisone was\rassociated with phosphate retention,\rdecreased urinary ca, decreased serum\rca, citrate and glycoprotein concentrations,\rand increased serum phosphate.\rexcretion of parathyroid activity in the\rurine of 1 patient was uninfluenced by the\radministration of prednisone.  it is concluded\rthat the antagonistic effect of the\radrenal cortical steroids was expressed\rat the biochemical sites of action of the\rparathyroid extract in bone and kidney,\rthat the steroids reduce parathyroid secretion\rbut that their administration probably does not\rresult in degradation or inactivation of\rthe hormone.\r'),
 (862,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'tissue distribution of electrolytes, ca and mg in experimental\rhyper- and hypoparathyroidism.\rthe effects of experimental hyper- and\rhypoparathyroidism on plasma and tissue\rdistribution of electrolytes and tissue\rexchangeability with ca and mg were studied\rin dogs following acute renal pedicle\rligation.  in hyperparathyroidism, plasma concentrations\rof mg and inorganic p as\rwell as ca were increased.  a greater accumulation\rof ca occurred in some tissues\rand a lesser accumulation in others than\rin acute hypercalcemia of comparable\rseverity and the fractional rate of exchange\rof tissue ca was 30% more rapid than\rin control and acute hypercalcemic dogs.\rbone exchange of ca was not significantly\rincreased.  cell mg concentrations were\rnot appreciably altered by hyperparathyroidism\rexcept for a significant 9% decrease\rin myocardium, but the fractional rate\rof exchange of tissue mg was increased.\racidsoluble p concentrations were decreased\rin 3 tissues and na and c1 concentrations\rwere decreased by 10 to 25% in 4 tissues.\rin hypoparathyroidism, in addition to a\rdecreased plasma ca, the increment\rin plasma inorganic p that usually occurs\rafter renal pedicle ligation was 75% less\rthan in control dogs.  cell ca concentrations\rwere decreased by 10-40% but the\rfractional rate of exchange of tissue ca was\runaltered.  although cell mg concentrations\rwere unaltered a 40% increase occurred\rin the exchangeability of skeletal muscle\rmg.  tissue na and c1 concentrations were\rdecreased by 20% in 2 tissues.  it has been\rpreviously reported that hypercalcemia\rincreases cell ca concentrations by raising\rthe extracellular ca concentration gradient.\revidence has also been presented that\rhypercalcemia directly inhibits cell\rinflux of mg and na and cell efflux of k.\rwith altered parathyroid activity, 2 types\rof effects are observed: those which are\rdependent upon an abnormal extracellular\rca concentration and those which appear to\rbe due to intrinsic effects of parathormone\ron cell cation transport.  the present\rdata are compatible with the hypotheses\rthat parathormone stimulates bidirectional\rtransport of cell ca and p, stimulates\rcell influx of mg and opposes the effects of\rhypercalcemia on cell transport of univalent ions.\r'),
 (863,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the inhibition of respiration and phosphorylation in kidney\rmitochondria by parathyroid hormone administered in vivo.\r   parathyroid hormone administered\rin vivo to rabbits\rproduced a metabolic alteration\rin kidney cortex\rmitochondria, evidenced by\rdiminished respiratory rate,\rrespiratory control, and p:o\rratio with a series of substrates\rincluding pyruvate plus\rfumarate, succinate,\rketoglutarate, malate, citrate,\rand isocitrate.  the adenosine\rtriphosphate-inorganic\rphosphate exchange reaction\rrate was decreased and\radenosine triphosphatase\ractivity was increased compared\rto control mitochondria.\rthese changes did not become\rapparent until about 12 hr.\rafter injection, were undiminished\rby 24 hr., and could\rbe elicited with as little as 200\rusp units of hormone.\runder identical conditions liver\rmitochondria were unaffected.\rdiphospho- and triphosphopyridine nucleotides\rin combination frequently elevated\rthe respiration in\rparathyroid-treated mitochondria\rclose to or above control\rlevels with citrate and isocitrate\rbut not with the\rremaining substrates and had\rno effect on respiratory\rcontrol with any of the substrates.\rthe effects of the\rhormone could not be duplicated\rby elevating and maintaining\rin otherwise normal rabbits\rserum ca concentrations\rat twice normal level\rfor 6 hr. it is concluded\rthat the effects produced by\rparathyroid hormone on kidney\rare multiple in nature and\rrelated to the ca++\rraising potency of the preparations.\r'),
 (864,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sudden hypocalcemia in normal and hypoparathyroid subjects.\r   serum calcium concentration was suddenly decreased\rin 10 normal and 4 hypoparathyroid subjects\rby the infusion of 50 mg/kg of disodium edta over a\r30- to 45-minute interval.  the return rate to pre-infusion\rvalues of the serum calcium concentration was the\rsame in both groups.  serum phosphate showed a marked,\rtransient decrease 30 min after the infusion in normal\rindividuals, but not in those with hypoparathyroidism.\rthe hypophosphatemia was followed by a marked\rincrease in phosphate clearance in the normal group and\ra decrease in the hypoparathyroid group.  urine phosphate:\rurine creatinine x 10 (up:uc x 10) and urine\rphosphate: urine osmolality x 10 (up:uo x 10) ratios\ralso reflected an increased phosphate excretion in the\r2 groups.  a simple clinical measure of parathyroid\rfunction is suggested by determining the up:uo x 10\ror the up:uc x 10, or both, ratios before and 3 to 6\rhr after intravenous infusion of disodium edta.\r'),
 (865,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'parathyroid function in chronic renal failure.  a statistical survey\rof the plasma biochemistry in azotaemic renal osteodystrophy.\r   a collection has been made of 134 personal and\rpublished cases of azotemic osteodystrophy in which\radequate information was available concerning the\rpathological state of the bones.  measurements were\ravailable of the plasma calcium, plasma phosphate, and\rblood-urea-nitrogen in all cases, and of plasma bicarbonate\rand plasma proteins in a representative sample.\rthe plasma levels of calcium and phosphate in the whole\rseries of 134 cases were not related reciprocally but\rwere correlated directly.  these data were further analyzed\rby allocating each case to either of 2 sub-groups,\raccording to the type of pathological lesions present in\rthe bones.  in one group there was evidence of defective\rmineralization of skeletal tissues, in the form of either\rrickets or osteomalacia, and the plasma-calcium was\rfound to be statistically sub-normal.  in the other group\rthere was no primary defect of mineralization but the\rlesions of generalized osteitis fibrosa were present and\rthe plasma calcium was statistically normal.  there was\rno significant correlation between the plasma levels of\rcalcium and phosphate in either sub-group; and the plasma\rphosphate was significantly higher in the group with\rthe higher plasma calcium levels.  the data indicate that\rin patients with renal osteodystrophy, contrary to general\rbelief, the plasma calcium varies independently of the\rplasma phosphate.  since these results imply differences\rin parathyroid function among patients with azotemic\rosteodystrophy, a survey has also been made of\rthe recorded parathyroid weights in chronic renal failure.\rgeneralized osteitis fibrosa and the accompanying normal\rlevels of plasma calcium are associated with greater\rparathyroid hypertrophy than is found in most cases\rof chronic renal failure or cases with defective mineralization.\rthe various data are interpreted in relation\rto the known metabolic disturbances and natural history\rof azotemic osteodystrophy.  by analogy with states of\rsimple vitamin d deficiency, it is suggested that hypocalcemia\rand relative unresponsiveness to the calcemic\raction of parathyroid hormone are related to an acquired\rresistance to vitamin d.  the group of cases with statistically\rnormal plasma-calcium prove that the parathyroid\rglands can function effectively in some patients\rwith chronic renal failure, irrespective of the level of\rthe plasma phosphate.  the size of the glands and the\reffects of sub-total parathyroidectomy in patients of this\rgroup suggest that the normal plasma calcium results\rfrom an increased production of parathyroid hormone.\rthe more advanced renal failure in the normocalcemic,\ras compared with the hypocalcemic, cases could mean\rthat the development of an effective degree of secondary\rhyperparathyroidism is a function of the duration of the\rrenal disease.  it seems likely that when the parathyroid\rresponse is sufficient to overcome the effects of the vitamin\rd resistance it also entails the development of generalized\rosteitis fibrosa, healing of the defect of mineralization\rand increased liability to metastatic calcification.\r'),
 (866,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'albright\'s hereditary osteodystrophy.  report of a family with studies\rof bone remodeling.\r   two members of a single family, each representing\rdifferent forms of albright\'s hereditary osteodystrophy,\rhave been presented.  the kindred pattern is\rsimilar to those of other reported families and is consistent\rwith a sex-linked or autosomal dominant mode of\rinheritance.  the importance of a course of intramuscular\rparathyroid extract for proof of parathyroid hormone\rresistance is emphasized.  biopsy specimens of rib,\rlabeled in vivo with tetracycline, were studied microscopically.\rthese new observations indicated cellular\rdefects in bone remodeling shared by the propositus and\rcase 2, which may explain the low rates of bone turnover\rfound in each.  immunologic studies established the\rpresence of a substance antigenically similar to parathyroid\rhormone in the parathyroid tissue of the propositus.\rthe pathogenesis of albright\'s hereditary osteodystrophy\rand atypical forms of parathyroid hormone\rresistant hypocalcemia is discussed.\r'),
 (867,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acute hyperparathyroidism: a surgical emergency.\r   acute hypercalcemic crisis of hyperparathyroidism\ris a surgical emergency.  diagnosis is often difficult\rbecause of the polymorphous character of the\rsymptoms.  the variable clinical features of the syndrome\rare described emphasizing the frequent occurrence of\rgastrointestinal symptoms, especially duodenal ulcer of\rrecurring pancreatitis in the antecedent history as well\ras the better known occurrence of renal and skeletal\rmanifestations, which precede the crisis in all but a few\rcases.  despite the variability of the clinical manifestations,\rthe total syndrome forms a distinctive pattern\rwhich should be recognizable once it is known.  previously\rreported cases have been reviewed and an additional\rcase reported.  the differential diagnosis, aids\rin identification of the tumor and prospects for more\reffective control of the hypercalcemia are discussed.\rat the present time, early surgical removal of the tumor\ris the only effective treatment.\r'),
 (868,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'actinomycin d inhibition of intestinal transport of calcium and\rof vitamin d action.\r   actinomycin d injection inhibits the actions of vit d\rin increasing concentrative transport of ca across the\rintestinal wall in vitro and in raising serum ca concentrations\rof fasted vit d-deficient rats.  actinomycin d blocks\rthe transport of ca across the mucosal surface of vit d\rdeficient as well as vit d-treated rats so that its action is\ron the ca transport system, rather than on the stimulatory\reffect of vit d.  this inhibitory effect of actinomycin d on\rca transport is present within 3 hr of its s. c. injection\rand is less marked at 18 hr which suggests a direct interaction\rwith the ca transport system.  under the same conditions\ractinomycin d does not influence the transport of\r1-tyrosine across the intestinal wall in vitro.\r'),
 (869,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on hydroxyproline excretion and corticosteroid-induced\rdwarfism: treatment with human growth hormone.\r   two children who had been receiving large doses\rof corticosteroids for years and were growing at a retarded\rrate were treated with human growth hormone.\rgrowth rate increased 2.5 to 3-fold and urinary hydroxyproline\rexcretion which was initially low increased\rto the normal level.  when treatment was stopped, growth\rrate and hydroxyproline excretion decreased promptly.\r'),
 (870,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a comparison of human placental lactogen (hpl) and human growth hormone\r(hgh) in hypopituitary patients.\r   the conclusions based on the studies reported are\rthat placental lactogen (hpl) at a dose level of 200 mg./\rday did not induce a positive nitrogen balance in two hypopituitary\rsubjects.  in addition, lactogen does not augment\rthe nitrogen retaining effect of growth hormone\rwhen given in a dose of 200 mg./day.\r'),
 (871,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radiation necrosis of the brain in acromegaly.\rradiation therapy of pituitary tumors can\rcause necrosis of the brain (4 cases are reported),\rparticulary if a carefully considered schedule of\rdosimetry is exceeded.  the error can be due to\rrepeated courses of treatment or too rapid administration.\rthe cerebral lesions develop after a\rlatent period of months and are progressive and\roften fatal.  appropriate pituitary surgery is preferable\rto multiple treatment with radiation.\r'),
 (872,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'   experiences with hgh treatment of twelve hypopituitary\rdwarfs for periods varying from 6 to 41 months\rare reported.  all the patients were considered to have\rhypopituitarism from birth, four of them of the hereditary\rtype, four possibly due to traumatic birth or neonatal asphyxia,\rand four from an unknown cause.  in six\rpatients detailed information concerning growth during\rthe first year of life could be obtained.  all of these patients\rhad a degree of growth retardation before one\ryear of age.  we consider this to be the rule rather than\rthe exception in pituitary dwarfism.  the most important\rdiagnostic evidence was a marked degree of growth retardation\raccompanied by a pronounced delay in skeletal\rmaturation, and, in most cases, signs of secondary\rhypothyroidism, increased insulin sensitivity, and a\rpoor response to metopyrone administration.  none of\rthe patients who had passed the normal age of puberty\rhad maturated sexually.  all twelve patients responded\rwell to hgh therapy.  during the first year of treatment\rthe average height increment was 10 cm. (\'catch-up\' growth).\rwith continued treatment a normal rate of\rgrowth, about 6 cm./year, was obtained.  there was no\rdisproportionate acceleration of skeletal maturation in\rany of the patients.  none of them has so far become resistant\rto hgh administration.  the oldest patient has\rreached normal height.  whether this will be possible\rnot only in the moderately severe, but also in the most\rsevere cases of pituitary dwarfism, can not yet be stated.\rthe possibility of using human gonadotrophic hormones\rin an attempt to produce sexual maturation in\rthese patients is discussed briefly.\r'),
 (873,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of retarded growth with human growth hormone.\rresults of treatment with human growth hormone\rin the following 3 cases are discussed:\rfemale hypopituitary dwarf of 17 yr.,\rwho grew 10 cm. in 20 mth.; a boy\rof 14 yr. with constitutional retarded growth,\rin whom the growth rate increased;\rand in a case of primordial dwarfism in a girl\rof 10 yr. in whom the growth curve\rwas unaffected by the treatment.\r'),
 (874,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'genetic pituitary dwarfism with high serum concentration of growth\rhormone new inborn error of metabolism?.\r   a description is given of three siblings with hypoglycemia\rand other clinical and laboratory signs of growth\rhormone deficiency but with abnormally high concentrations\rof immunoreactive serum growth hormone.  since\rexogenous growth hormone was active in these patients,\rthe endogenous secretion of an abnormal growth hormone\rmolecule is postulated.\r'),
 (875,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth-hormone deficiency in man:\ran isolated, recessively inherited defect.\r   a deficiency of human growth hormone not associated\rwith other pituitary deficiencies was observed in\rmidgets with sexual ateliosis, a form of dwarfism inherited\ras an autosomal recessive trait.  body proportions,\rsexual development, birth weight, and postpartum lactation\rare normal in this syndrome.\r'),
 (876,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of short stature in children and adolescents\rwith human pituitary growth hormone (raben).  experience\rwith thirty-five cases.\rhuman pituitary growth hormone (raben) was\revaluated by longitudinal study of\rgrowth as a therapeutic agent in the treatment\rof short stature.  clinically significant\rincreases in growth rate were achieved in 11\rof 13 hypopituitary patients.  no significant\rimprovement in linear growth rate was\rnoted with a dose of 2 mg 3 times\rweekly in children whose short stature was due\rto other conditions.  no adverse reactions\rwere noted; thyroidal, adrenal or gonadal\ractivation was not observed.  growth\rwas stimulated, probably without an undue increase\rin bone age, though this point\rdemands continued scrutiny.  owing to the limited\rsupply of this material it is recommended\rthat it be used only in cases of documented\rgrowth failure, and a protocol\rfor evaluation of therapeutic response is discussed.\rthough not a panacea for treatment\rof short stature, human growth hormone\rfulfils a unique and invaluable role\rin replacement therapy for the hypopituitary dwarf.\r'),
 (877,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the development of bilateral adenomatous adrenal hyperplasia\rin a case of cushing\'s syndrome of eighteen years\' duration.\ra case of cushing\'s syndrome of 18 years\'\rduration is presented.  the disease\rbegan when the patient was 8 years old and\rwas partially controlled by pituitary\rradiation when she was 13.  however, clinical\revidence indicate low grade but continuous\radrenocortical activity for the next 13\ryears.  the probable suppression\rof gh secretion by the increased steroid levels\rduring her growth period provides\ra reasonable explanation for the dwarfism of\rthe patient.  the administration of 8 mg\rof dexamethasone per day failed to decrease\rurinary steroid excretion.  bilateral\rnodular hyperplasia was found at surgery.\rit is suggested from the evidence presented\rthat this patient\'s disease began first\ras a primary pituitary process but\rduring the long duration of the acth secretion\rit evolved into one of autonomously\rfunctioning bilateral nodular hyperplasia.\r'),
 (878,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypopituitarism: a study of growth\rhormone and other endocrine functions.\r   pituitary function was evaluated in 25 adults with\revidence of hypopituitarism or enlargement of the sella\rturcica.  growth hormone secretory function was measured\rby radioimmunoassay of plasma samples taken\rbefore and after insulin-induced hypoglycemia in a standardized\rtest of growth hormone reserve.  all patients\rexhibited significant defects in growth hormone secretion,\ras indicated by the failure of this hormone to rise\rto normal levels in response to hypoglycemia.  the order\rof frequency of hormonal loss was: growth hormone,\rgonadotropin, adrenocorticotropic hormone, thyroid\rstimulating hormone.  no pattern of deficiency was characteristic\rfor any particular etiology of hypopituitarism.\rone patient with asymptomatic enlargement of the sella\rturcica (accidentally discovered) had an isolated loss\rof growth hormone secretory capacity.  two patients in\rthe series demonstrated intrinsic deficiency of thyroid\ras well as pituitary secretion, and both had elevated\rliters of antithyroid antibodies.  this study represents\rthe first direct evaluation, by radioimmunoassay of\rgrowth hormone function in a series of hypopituitary\radults.  it demonstrates a remarkably high prevalence\rof growth hormone loss, and suggests that the growth\rhormone response to hypoglycemia may be one of the\rmost sensitive tests for the diagnosis of hypopituitarism.\r'),
 (879,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypoglycemia and dwarfism associated with the isolated\rdeficiency of growth hormone.\rthe authors have studied a 7-year-old dwarfed\rboy with a history of severe, recurrent\rhypoglycemic episodes since age 1 and\rretarded bone age.  hepatic, adrenal,\rand thyroid function were normal.  he demonstrated\rfasting hypoglycemia with blood\rsugars of 30-40 mg./100 ml.  he was not sensitive\rto l-leucine but showed insulin\rsensitivity and hypoglycemic unresponsiveness.\rglycogenolysis in response to both\radrenaline and glucagon was appropriate.  fasting\rplasma gh levels were less than\r1 m g./ml. (normal 1-3), and no rise was seen\rafter insulin-induced hypoglycemia.\rsimilarly, these low gh levels did not rise 3-6\rhr.  after a glucose tolerance test.\rtreatment with hgh reversed the alterations\rin carbohydrate metabolism.  it is\rconcluded that the patient suffered from an isolated\rgh deficiency which resulted in\rdwarfism and alterations in carbohydrate metabolism.\r'),
 (880,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of growth hormone in hypothalamo-pituitary\rdwarfism. i. the metabolic effects of human growth hormone.\rhuman growth hormone, isolated by raben\'s\rmethod, was given in 2 to 5 mg. daily\rdoses over periods from 1 to 12 days to 7 patients\rwith pituitary-hypothalamic dwarfism.\rthe metabolic effects were as follows:\rnitrogen retention with a variable\rreduction in blood urea.  the plasma amino-acid\rconcentration did not alter after\ri.m. injection of the hormone during fasting.\ran accompanying retention of intracellular\rcomponents, in such proportions required\rfor protoplasm formation.\risotonic expansion of the extracellular compartment,\rwithout change in the plasma\relectrolyte concentrations.  retention of phosphorus,\rsometimes a rise in plasma\rphosphate; increased intestinal calcium absorption,\rhypercalciuria, no alteration\rin plasma calcium; an increase in plasma citrate\rand citrate urinary excretion;\rthe calcium and phosphate retention was reversed\ron stopping treatment.  mobilisation\rof fat stores with lipid catabolism: this\rwas accompanied by a well marked\rincrease in nefa concentration for some hours\rafter hormone injection in the\rfasting state, after a period of hypoglycaemia\rand low nefa levels.  a complex,\rbiphasic action on glucose metabolism.  fasting\rblood sugar levels are altered,\ras are the glycaemia in various tests such as\rfasting, insulin injections, tolbutamide\radministration, intestinal hyperglycaemia.\racceleration of intermediate\rmetabolism with increased blood citrate\rconcentrations and 24 hours urinary\rexcretion of  -ketoglutaric acid.  in one test\rduring fasting the blood citrate increased\r4 hours after hormone injection.  after\ran oral load of sugar the blood citrate\rand  -ketoglutaric acid concentrations\rdid not alter.  a progressive gain in\rweight has been found during treatment, partly\rreversible on stopping treatment,\rcorrelating with the intracellular nitrogen retention\rand expansion of the extracellular\rspace, despite mobilisation of fat reserves.\r'),
 (881,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'serum chorionic \'growth hormone-prolactin\' and serum pituitary\rgrowth hormone in mother and fetus at term.\rchorionic \'growth hormone-prolactin\' (cgp) and\rpituitary hgh were measured in\rmaternal and fetal blood obtained simultaneously\rat term from 29 pregnant women\rand their fetuses utilizing sensitive radioimmunoassay\rprocedures.  the mean concentration\rof serum cgp in maternal venous blood\rwas 5.6  g/ml (sem0.39) whereas\rin umbilical venous serum the mean concentration\rwas 0.019  g/ml (sem 0.003),\ra 300-fold difference.  contrariwise, the mean\rconcentration of serum hgh in maternal\rserum was 5.9 m g/ml (sem 0.52) and\rin umbilical venous serum the level\rwas 33.5 m g/ml (sem 4.6).  the ratio of serum\rcgp/hgh in maternal venous serum\rwas 1076 in contrast to 0.57 in umbilical venous\rserum.  the findings strongly suggest\rthat cgp is secreted by the syncytiotrophoblast\ralmost exclusively in a unidirectional\rmanner into the maternal circulation.\rfurther, it is unlikely that an appreciable\rexchange of hgh occurs between the\rmaternal and fetal circulations.  the\rdata support the view that the growth hormone-like\rmetabolic changes observed in\rpregnancy are attributable to the effects of cgp\rand are consistent with the hypothesis\rthat cgp is an important metabolic hormone\rof pregnancy exerting its actions\ron the mother and possibly the placenta, but only\rindirectly on the fetus.\r'),
 (882,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of abdominal operation on glucose tolerance and serum levels of\rinsulin, growth hormone, and hydrocortisone.\r   abdominal operations of moderate severity are\rfollowed by high fasting blood-glucose levels and a reduced\rtolerance to intravenous glucose which persists\rfor at least 72 hours after operation.  fasting plasma-insulin\rlevels are raised after surgery.  intravenous glucose\rproduces much higher levels of serum-insulin and\rgrowth hormone in the immediate postoperative period.\rcorticotrophin infusion increases the plasma-hydrocortisone\rlevels and reduces glucose assimilation to a\rgreater extent than operation, but has no effect on serum-insulin\ror growth-hormone levels.\r'),
 (883,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'plasma growth hormone concentration in the rat determined by\rradioimmunoassay: influence of sex, pregnancy, lactation, anesthesia,\rhypophysectomy and extrasellar pituitary transplants.\r   the assay used is described in detail.  several experimental\rconditions were studied, both to validate the\rmethod and to determine factors which regulate gh secretion\rin this species.  in fasting sprague-dawley rats\rweighing 150-200 g, mean plasma gh concentration in\rfemales was 94.2 17.3, and in males, 54.9 12.0 m g/ml.\rgh levels in lactating rats were determined to be in\rthe normal range for females, thereby providing evidence\rthat this assay does not detect prolactin.  gh levels were\rnot elevated in pregnant rats.  hypophysectomy led to a\rfall below detectable levels of gh.  intraocular pituitary\rtransplants failed to raise gh levels in hypophysectomized\rhosts.  gh levels in male, but not in female, rats\rare depressed by brief periods of ether anesthesia.  these\rfindings and the results of pituitary transplantation experiments\rare further evidence that the nervous system\ris involved in the regulation of gh secretion.\r'),
 (884,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'clinical features of the alalies (russian).\rthe term \'alalies\' is applied to the various\rstates of absence or insufficient development\rof speech in children, resulting\rfrom defective development or affections\rof the speech centers before the development\rof speech.  from the clinical\rstudy it is possible to distinguish between several\rforms: motor, sensory, and\rsemantic alaly with signs of amnesia.  the\rcauses are multiple: trauma, perinatal\rcerebral hemorrhage, inflammatory processes,\rmetabolic disorders before the\rdevelopment of speech, and alimentary and\rtrophic disorders.  the alalies show\rvarying degrees of severity.  in most children\rsuffering from alaly, neurological\rsigns can be demonstrated on the right side,\ran indication of the organic nature of\rthe condition.  the presence of local symptoms\rin the various forms of alaly is\roften associated with signs indicating involvement\rof adjacent regions of the cerebral\rhemispheres in the pathological process\rwhich would explain why the alalies\rare often complex.  the character of the alalies\rdepends on functional disorders\rresulting from the lesion in the frontal, anterior,\rmotor, temporal or parietal\rregion of the dominant cerebral hemisphere.\rpatients with alaly often show neurotic\rreactions, resulting from the disorders\rof the processes of inhibition and excitation\rof the cerebral cortex and the subcortical\rformations.  early treatment of\rthe alalies with drugs combined with logopedic\rand pedagogic measures gives good results.\r'),
 (885,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an unusual form of acquired aphasia in children.\ran unusual form of acquired aphasia-both\rreceptive and executive is described\ras occurring in 10 children, 6 girls and 4 boys.\rthe onset occurred between 5 and\r6 yr. of age with one or more epileptiform\rattacks-which were not repeated-but\rwere followed by some degree of hearing\rloss (later improving), failure to\rcomprehend spoken language and finally loss\ror impairment of executive speech.\rexamination of csf and peg yielded normal\rresults.  eeg\'s were abnormal mainly\rin the temporal leads.  the disorder appeared\rself-limiting and throughout non-verbal\rintelligence was not imparied.\r'),
 (886,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'childhood echolalia in delayed, psychotic and neuropathologic\rspeech patterns.\rsome linguistic analytical procedures and\rpreliminary findings from controlled tape-recorded\rsamples of a group of echolalic\rchildren are reported together with the\rclinical and experimental rationale for the\rinvestigation.  the subjects are echolalic\r3-yr. olds and a group of young clinical referrals\rrepresenting a variety of pathological\rconditions.  variables selected for\rstudy include the proportion of echo to\rnon-echo and silence, the quality and appropriateness\rof the non-echoed speech, the\ramount of the stimulus echoed, the nature\rof the triggering stimulus, the deviation of\recho pattern from stimulus pattern, pitch-loudness-time\rvariations, and the child\'s\rchronological and mental ages.  early quantitative\rresults yielded very similar echo:\rnon-echo:silence percentages with echolalia\rrepresenting a mean of about 40% of the\rconversation of each experimental group.\r'),
 (887,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'speech as a landmark in development.\rit is attempted to demonstrate how observations\rof children\'s speech and language\rdevelopment may serve as valuable indicators of\rtheir general physical, intellectual,\rand emotional progress.  speech lag or breakdown\rmay corroborate other suspect\rareas of development or may point the way to them.\rspeech and language disorders\rseldom originate in the mouth.  ideas must precede\rspeech, and speech is a direct\rcorrelate of intelligence.\r'),
 (888,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the applicability of individualized programed instruction\rin the education of deaf children.\rverbal behavior is learned behavior and as\rsuch is guided by the same principles\ras any other learned behavior.  the parents\'\rrole is mainly to help the young deaf\rchild conceive of language as a socializing\rprocess and to help shape language behavior\rtoward the use of verbal symbols.\rthe teacher\'s role in the deaf child\'s\rprogress as a language user includes (1) helping\rthe child discover how the structure\rof his language operates and (2) guiding\rhim in the process of acquiring clear\rconcepts.  the learning of a language is a highly\rindividualized process and requires\rthousands of hours of practice.  efficiency\rin language teaching to the deaf\rhas not been generally achieved by traditional\rmethods.  the teacher of the deaf\rneeds extra help in order to provide the individualistic\rkind of teaching to insure\rverbal over-learning by the child.  self-tutoring\rprogramed materials offer this\rhelp.  programs are so constructed that a child\rproceeds through the program step\rby step with a probability of maximum success\rbecause of constant feedback as to\rcorrectness of his responses.  for younger\rchildren the use of a machine seems\rdesirable while for older children the program\rmay appear in book form, on film\rstrip, and any other visual medium.  well constructed\rprograms should be correlated\rwith classroom instruction.\r'),
 (889,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the impact of individual differences on language learning.\ra matrix of extrinsic and intrinsic factors affecting\rlanguage learning in the prelingually\rdeaf child is considered.  particular\remphasis is placed on the effects\rof parental attitudes on both the emotional\rstability of the home and on the provision\ror restriction of experience.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (890,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the oral language performance of premature children and controls.\rfifty-one premature children born in 1955\rand 1956 were compared with 55 normally\rborn subjects with birth weights over\r2,500 grams.  they were tested on\rtapped patterns, auditory memory span,\rauditory discrimination, word recognition,\rlanguage comprehension, articulation,\rresistance to articulation disintegration,\rword finding, story telling, number of words\rused, mean length of 5 longest sentences,\rsentence elaboration, grammatical\rerrors, definitions and categories.\rthe mean age of both groups was 5.8 and the\rpremature children\'s performance\rwas inferior to that of children born at term.\r'),
 (891,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'speech and reading problems in childhood.\rthe following communicative disorders\rhave been discussed: functional articulation\rdefects, delayed speech development,\rstuttering, hearing loss, cleft palate,\rneurological disorders, and reading disorders.\rthese disorders rarely have a\rsingle cause.  they are the result of an\rintermingling of many factors, some physiological\rand some psychological, some\rresiding within the child and some in the\rparents and environment in general.  delayed\ror defective speech is a cause for\rgreat concern to most parents and teachers.\rthe public health worker who listens\rwith an attentive and sympathetic ear may\rallay some of this anxiety and thus help\rfoster healthy emotional development in\rthe child.  the existence of a more serious\rcondition underlying the presenting communication\rproblem, even if sensed by the\rparents, is frequently denied.  the public\rhealth worker can assist the parents in\rthe painful process of facing up to their\rfears.  a child with a communication problem\ris still a child and the public health worker\rby simply reflecting this to the parents\rand advising them on normal child-raising\rpractices can, again, be of help to the\rchild.  children with speech deviations are\rexposed to an overabundance of well-intentioned\rspeech correction at home.\rmost of it is ineffective; some of it, unfortunately\ris harmful.  while the worker\rmay not be in a position to offer specific\radvice on a particular child, the manner\rin which the parents and teacher are handling\rthe child\'s communication problem\rcan be explored and damaging practices\rpossibly eliminated.  the fact that there\rmay be a diagnostic and treatment center\rto which the child can be referred does\rnot vitiate the public health worker\'s role.\rthe public health physician and public health\rnurse have a valuable contribution\rto make in helping the parents, school,\rand child accept the chronic nature of the disorder.\r'),
 (892,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'disorders of communication in young children.\rthe normal development of spoken language is\routlined.  the causation, differential\rdiagnosis, individual assessment and management\rof developmental disorders of\rcommunication in young children are briefly discussed.\r'),
 (893,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acquired aphasia in children.\rthis report concerns the cases of 21 boys\rand 11 girls studied over a period of several\ryears while rehabilitation was carried\rout.  the general conclusions fall under\r3 headings: (1) symptomatology as compared\rwith that of aphasia in the adult; (2) the\rcourse of the disorder; (3) prospects of the\rlevel of intellectual performance in the\rfuture of the children.  in 13 cases, cerebral\rdamage had resulted from traumatic\rcontusion; in 10 cases from an intracranial\rnontraumatic hematoma (vascular malformation,\raneurysm or angioma); in 2 cases\rthe aphasia followed operation for a\rcerebral astrocytoma; in 2 further cases\rocclusion of the left middle cerebral artery\rhad occurred; and in the remaining 5 cases\rno precise diagnosis was made.\r'),
 (894,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the causes of delayed development of speech.\rspeech develops parallelly and simultaneously\rwith psychophysical development of\rthe child, arising from internal need and\runder the influence of external factors.  not\rall children are given the chance to develop\rin favorable conditions and to pass through\rall the phases of development without some\rinjury.  the various possibilities when a\rchild may be injured and hampered in the\rdevelopment of speech are discussed.  the\rtesting of the sense of hearing in children\rwith a cleft palate is also included-out of\r181 cases of cleft palate, in 72 cases there\rwas decrease of the sense of hearing exceeding\r30 db.  this additional injury of\rthe child with a cleft palate, if remaining unnoticed,\rmay make the treatment of speech\rabnormality difficult.  the necessity of\rdiagnostic team investigation and the treatment\rof children with speech disturbances\rare emphasized.\r'),
 (895,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'concept learning in culturally disadvantaged children as\ra function of verbal pretraining.\rwhile research indicates that verbal pretraining\rhas a positive influence on the discrimination\rlearning performance of subjects\rof normal intelligence, a comparable\rinfluence has not been shown for other types\rof conceptual tasks for retarded subjects.\rthe purpose of this experiment was\rto investigate the effects of stimulus\rpretraining on concept learning by subjects\rwho had a \'high risk\' of being classified\ras mentally retarded at some future time.\ra group of 27 \'higher risk\' and 27 \'lower\rrisk\' subjects was randomly divided into\r3 pretraining groups: verbal label, attention,\rand control.  subsequent to pretraining on\rthe stimuli used for transfer task 1, subjects\rin each group were presented with a\rconcept learning task (transfer task 1).\rafter reaching the criterion of learning on\rtransfer task 1, subjects were presented\rwith a second, new, concept learning task.\ranalysis of the data revealed that there\rwere no significant performance differences\rbetween risk groups and that pretraining\rhad a significantly positive effect on performance.\r'),
 (896,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'concept development and language instruction.\rthe author describes factors related to,\rand the errors that may occur in concept\rdevelopment in children.  the contributions\rof language for the deaf child\'s conceptual\rdevelopment are stressed.  included\rare a review of what concepts are, psychologically,\rand an example of how concepts\rmay be presented, educationally, in the classroom.\r'),
 (897,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'formal speech characteristics as a diagnostic aid in childhood\rpsychosis.\rthe frequency of use of various grammatical\runits in the spontaneous conversational\rspeech of adults and children has been\rnoted by many authors to be fairly stable.\rthe hypothesis that idiosyncratic distributions\rmight be found in certain specific\rdisorders of ego functioning was tested\rin relationship to childhood psychosis.  some\rsupport was found for this, as well as\rfor some contemporary psychological and\rpsychoanalytical interpretations of phenomena\rseen in childhood psychosis.\r'),
 (898,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cerebral dominance and speech acquistion in deaf children.\rin examining the prediction that left cerebral\rdominance, as indexed by hand and\rsighting preference, should be a positive accompaniment\rof speech learning in individuals\rwhose cerebral speech areas are likely\rto be in the left hemisphere, it was\rfound that over a 10-12 year period of formal\reducation right-handed-right-sighting\rdeaf students consistently earned higher speech\rgrades than their right-handed-left-sighting\rand right-handed-mixed-sighting counterparts\rmatched on the basis of\rhearing loss.  this finding supports the hypothesis\rthat the cerebral mechanisms\rrelevant to speech acquisition are simplified,\rfacilitated, and/or less prone to\rinterference when control of speech, hand, and\reye is localized primarily in 1\rhemisphere of the brain.\r'),
 (899,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a color test for the measurement of antibody to the non-acid-forming\rhuman mycoplasma species.\r   a metabolic inhibition test\rfor the measurement of\rgrowth inhibiting antibodies to\rthe non-acid producing\rhuman mycoplasma species is\rdescribed.  the test is\rbased upon the ability of these\rorganisms to metabolize\rarginine with a resultant alkaline\rshift in the ph of the\rmedium.  the alkaline shift is\rinhibited by specific antiserum.\rlabile accessory factor(s)\rpresent in unheated\rguinea pig serum potentiates\rthe inhibitory effect of antiserum.\rthe test is sensitive\rand specific for the measurement\rof antibody to mycoplasmas\rin rabbit immune\rand human convalescent serum.\r'),
 (900,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'serologic epidemiologic studies with m. pneumoniae. i. demonstration\rof an hemagglutinin and its inhibition by antibody.\r   a new direct, specific\rhemagglutination reaction\rwith live m. pneumoniae is described.\rthis requires the presence of a natural antibody\rfor the red cell in the\rhorse serum employed in the\rdiluent.  although vervet\rmonkey erythrocytes generally\rhave been employed,\rhuman and rabbit cells may be\rused.  hemagglutination\rcan be inhibited by specific antibody\rbut heat inactivation\rof the sera is required,\rwhether they be human or\ranimal in origin.  antibodies\rpersist for many years and\rare passively transferred to\rthe fetus.  a micro variation\rhas been devised.  the test\ris useful for diagnostic\rand epidemiologic studies and,\rin reverse, can be utilized\rfor the rapid serologic\ridentification of new isolates.\rthe method is limited,\rat present, to m. pneumoniae.\r'),
 (901,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'serologic epidemiologic studies with m. pneumoniae. ii. prevalence of\rantibodies in several populations.\r   the prevalence of antibodies\rfor m. pneumoniae\rwas determined in 6 populations\rby means of a new\rserologic test.  among members\rof a population of \'normal\'\rfamilies, no one under\rage 15 had antibodies.\rnone of the latter acquired an\rinfection during the following\ryear.  of 67 children in\ra home, only 3 had antibodies.\rthe 7 cottage mates\rof one of these children\rwho had acquired an infection,\rremained uninfected.  in\ra group of 124 elderly persons,\r65 (53%) had antibodies.\ra similar proportion of 76 persons\rattending a rheumatic\rfever prophylaxis clinic\rwas positive.  in this population\rit was demonstrated that\rantibodies could persist\rin undiminished titer for at least\r10 yr.  of 169 point\rbarrow residents, 68% had\rantibodies.  above age 15\rthe rate was approximately\r90%.  two companies of\rnaval recruits who had similar\rpositive antibody rates\rat the beginning of training,\racquired antibodies in\rrather divergent patterns, 63%\rin one and 26% in the\rother.  m. pneumoniae infections\rseem to be sporadic\rand to produce epidemics only\rinfrequently in civilian\rpopulations.\r'),
 (902,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'growth and survival of mycoplasma neurolyticum in liquid media.\rmaximal growth of m. neurolyticum (between\r10 and 10 colony-forming units/ml)\rwas obtained after 3 days of incubation\rat 36 c in broth media containing 10% agama\rhorse serum.  when whole horse serum\rwas used in the medium, a complement-mediated\rinhibition was observed.  this\rinhibition could only be detected when growth\rwas followed by daily plate counts.  maximal\rgrowth was delayed for about 24 hr by\rthe horse serum, and the inhibition was\rspontaneously reversed at the temperature\rof incubation.  penicillin g was also found\rto have a temporary inhibitory effect.\rthis was detected with as little as 40 units/ml.\rmaximal growth was delayed until\rthe 6th day of incubation, when 200 units/ml\rwas present, and until the 16th day,\rwhen 1,000 units/ml was present.  the\rsurvival of m. neurolyticum at undetectable\rlevels in cultures during the incubation\rperiod presented an \'eclipse\' phenomenon\rwhich has not been explained.  the recrudescence\rof growth in such cultures late in\rthe incubation period illustrates the events\rwhich may occur when mycoplasmas are\risolated from clinical material by prolonged\rincubation in the presence of inhibitors\rsurvival data showed that m. neurolyticum\rhad greatest stability at ph 8.0, with\rreduced viability at ph 9.0, 7.0, 10.0, and\r6.0, in that order.  the data on growth\rand stability suggest a close relationship\rbetween the species of mycoplasma studies\rand bacteria.\r'),
 (903,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hela cells resistant to bromodeoxyuridine and deficient in thymidine\rkinase activity.\rmutant sublines of hela s3 cells resistant\rto growth inhibition by bromodeoxyuridine\r(budr) have been isolated.  the resistant\rcell lines (hela bu-10, hela bu-15,\rhela bu-25, hela bu-50, and hela bu-100)\rproliferated in the presence of 10,\r15,25,50, and 100 mg/ml budr, respectively.\rextracts from hela bu-25, hela\rbu-50, and hela bu-100 cells exhibited\r2-5% of the thymidine-h, deoxyuridine-h,\rand bromodeoxyuridine-h phosphorylating\ractivities of parental hela s3 cells.\rhela bu-10 and hela bu-15 cell extracts\rwere also deficient in thymidine kinase\ractivity, yielding approx. 43% and 8%,\rrespectively, the thymidine kinase activity\rof parental hela s3 cells.  the deficiency\rin thymidine kinase activity of hela bu-100\rcells was not due to negative feedback inhibition\rby high levels of budr or to interference\rwith the thymidine kinase assay by\rinhibitors or competing enzymes in the\rhela bu-100 cell extracts.  following 5 weekly\rpassages in media lacking budr,\rthe hela bu-100 cells did not exhibit increased\rthymidine kinase activity.  moreover,\rmixtures of extracts from hela s3\rand hela bu-100 cells displayed a thymidine\rkinase activity equivalent to the sum\rof the activities or extracts prepared,\rrespectively, from the hela s3 and hela\rbu-100 cells.  radioautographic studies\rhave shown that after hela s3 cells were\rincubated for 6 hr with thymidine-h,\r35-45% of the nuclei were heavily labeled\rwith radioactivity.  however, fewer hela\rbu-100 cells displayed labeled nuclei and\rthe nuclei were only lightly labeled.\rhela bu-100 cell extracts contained normal\ramounts of thymidylate synthetase,\rthymidilate kinase, and uridine kinase activities.\rfollowing infection by vaccinia\rvirus, high levels of thymidine kinase activity\rwere induced in hela bu-100 cells.\r'),
 (904,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a note on the taxonomic status of strains like \'campo\',\rhitherto classified as mycoplasma hominis, type 2.\rthe classification of strains similar to\rmycoplasma strain pg 27 of \'campo\' as\rmyc. hominis type 2 should be withdrawn.\rthese strains have now been identified\ras myc. arthritidis.\r'),
 (905,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chromosome studies of human cells infected in utero and\rin vitro with rubella virus.\ra cytologic study of metaphase chromosomes\rwas undertaken to determine if damage\rto the genetic apparatus of human cells may\rbe induced by rubella virus and whether\rsuch damage produces the pathology seen\rin newborns from mothers infected early\rin pregnancy.  fibroblast cell strains were\rinitiated in vitro from embryonic material\robtained by therapeutic abortion of fetuses\rfrom rubella-infected mothers.  embryonic\rmaterial from spontaneous and non-rubella\rtherapeutic abortions yielded similar\rcell strains for infection in vitro.  the\rresults from both types of studies were as\rfollows: (a) virus shedding cell strains were\robtained from all types of organs cultivated,\rwhich indicated wide dissemination\rof virus in the fetuses from rubella-infected\rmothers.  (b) chronic infection could\rreadily be established by in vitro infection\rand no cytopathic effect was noted.\r(c) although many strains continued to shed\rvirus throughout months of in vitro cultivation,\rno changes in growth properties\roccurred with the exception that infected\rstrains from lung tissue showed limited\rgrowth capacities.  (d) from observations\rof over 2,000 metaphases, neither obvious\rchromosomal rearrangements nor non-disjunctional\rchanges were observed in\rstrains infected naturally or experimentally.\r(e) among 17 rubella abortion-derived\rcell strains there was a marked elevation\rin frequency of chromosome breakage in\r3 instances (18%, 29%, 68%,).  (f) a correlation\rbetween virus shedding in vitro and\rincreased chromosome breakage was noted\ralthough this was not complete.  (g) the\rcombined average frequency of chromosome\rbreakage in one set of 7 rubella-abortion\rstrains was 18%; in the other set of 9 abortus\rstrains, 9.8%.  (h) similarly, a slight,\rbut significant elevation in average chromosome\rbreak frequency (9.8%) was obtained\rin four cell strains which had been experimentally\rinfected in vitro with rubella virus\r(uninfected cells: 5.2%).  although effects\rupon the chromosomes were demonstrated,\rthese were restricted to slight general elevations\rin frequency of breakage above\rnormal values.  very high increases in breaks\rwere sporadic.  it appears more likely\rthat the general fetal abnormalities associated\rwith rubella infection in vivo result\rfrom possible effects of the virus upon growth\rrather than from effects upon the\rchromosomes.  however, the studies were\rrestricted to fibroblasts cultured in\rvitro; and effects on other types of cells\rmay have greater implications for this\rquestion.\r'),
 (906,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fine structure of staphylococccal l-forms.\r   l forms of staph. aureus and bacterial cells were\rprocessed by the same technique for electron microscopy.\rultrathin sections allowed comparison of structural units\rand indicated that staphylococcal l form units of all\rsizes lack the rigid cell wall and the compact, fibrillar\rnuclear area of bacterial cells.  the l form units are\rbound by a typical \'trilamellar\' membrane comparable\rto that described for mycoplasma species.  nuclear\rareas in staphylococcal l forms present a diffuse appearance\rand could not be correlated with size of any\rparticular structural unit.  many small units were seen\rwithin large bodies and possibly are involved in the reproductive\rprocess.  no evidence of division by formation\rof septa or by pinching off of cytoplasmic fragments\rwas obtained from the electron micrographs.\r'),
 (907,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'respiratory virus vaccines. ii. mycoplasma pneumoniae (eaton agent)\rvaccines.\r   purified and concentrated formalin-killed vaccines\rwere prepared from m. pneumoniae propagated in\rserum-free artificial medium.  the vaccines were\raqueous or were incorporated in alum or emulsified\rpeanut oil (adjuvant 65) adjuvant.  two or 3 different\rconcentrations of mycoplasma were included in each\rpreparation.  serum neutralizing and cf antibody responses\rwere measured in hamsters, monkeys, and in\rinstitutionalized persons following 1,2,3 and sometimes\r4 vaccinations.  all of the preparations were\rhighly antigenic in animals and in man.  alum vaccines\rwere better than aqueous vaccines and those in adjuvant\r65 appeared to give best results although the bleeding\rtimes were not always optimal for demonstrating\rmaximal effect.  persons who were without detectable\rantibody initially and thus would be most vulnerable to\rinfection gave better responses to the vaccine than did\rthose with pre-existing antibody.  alum vaccine is an\racceptable formulation for use in man, and only 2 doses\rof such vaccine were necessary to induce neutralizing\rantibody in 90% of the persons who were initially without\rdetectable antibody.  no local or systemic reaction\rof clinical consequence was noted in any of the persons\rvaccinated.  recent unpublished findings, which indicate\ra high degree of effectiveness of the alum vaccine\rin stimulating antibody in preschool children and in\rprotecting children and adults against the natural disease,\rare mentioned.\r'),
 (908,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'isolation of mycoplasma pneumoniae from adults with respiratory\rinfections.\risolation of mycoplasma organisms from the sputum\rwas attempted in 254 patients with various syndrome\rof respiratory disease.  isolates were obtained in 56% of\rthe 197 patients with pneumonia, 50% of patients with\rchronic bronchial diseases who were not treated with\rtetracycline, and 33% of persons with acute upper respiratory\rinfection.  these differences are not statistically\rsignificant and indicate a nonpathogenic role for m.\rpharyngis and m. salivarium which were the strains most\rfrequently isolated.  the highest frequency of isolation\rwas from males 15 to 30 yr. of age.  isolation of m.\rpneumoniae requires one to 2 weeks:therefore, it is not\ruseful for rapid diagnosis.  also, it underestimates the\rprevalence of infection, especially if patients have received\rtetracycline.  of the serologic tests, complement-fixation\r(cf) was the most specific.  the growth\rinhibition test (tri) was the most sensitive and was\rsignificantly related to atypical pneumonia.  the 2 tests\rmay measure different antibodies against m. pneumoniae.\rserum cold agglutinins developed in many cases\rof pneumonia and were poorly discriminatory in etiologic\rdiagnosis.  m. pneumoniae infection occurred in a\rminimum of 8% and a maximum of 20% of civilian patients\rhospitalized for pneumonia during the season studied.\rserologic evidence for m. pneumoniae was rare in\rlobar pneumonia.  in nonlobar pneumonia, m. pneumoniae\raccounted etiologically for 13% to 50% of cases.  the incidence\rof m. pneumoniae infection was constant in\rdifferent seasons but greatest relative to the occurrence\rof pneumonia in the fall and spring.\r'),
 (909,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'color test for the measurement of antibody to t-strain mycoplasmas.\r   a metabolic inhibition technique for the measurement\rof antibody to t-strain mycoplasmas was developed,\rbased upon the ability of t-strain mycoplasmas to\rmetabolize urea with the concomitant production of ammonia,\rand the ability of specific, antiserum to inhibit\rthis ammonia production.  phenol red added to the\rmedium served as an indicator of ph change resulting\rfrom ammonia production.  specific antiserum to t-strain\rmycoplasma t-960 was prepared.  the t-strain\rorganism was shown to be serologically distinct from the\rrecognized large-colony mycoplasmas.  antibody to\rmycoplasma strain t-960 in human sera was demonstrated\rwith the metabolic inhibition technique.\r'),
 (910,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effect of mycoplasma on interferon production and interferon assay in\rcell cultures.\r   the influence of mycoplasma on the production\rand action of interferon was studied in cultures of both\rl and human embryonic kidney (hek) cells.  m. hominis\r1, the negroni agent, and the f12 mycoplasma were\rused for infection of l cells, and m. hominis 1 and m.\rpneumoniae for inoculation of hek cells.  all strains\rwere capable of multiplication in the culture systems\remployed.  none produced detectable levels of interferon,\rand responsiveness of the cells to induction of interferon\rby virus remained unaltered.  infection with mycoplasma\rdid not impair the sensitivity of the cells to the action of\rinterferon, nor was the replication of vesicular stomatitis\rvirus noticeably diminished.\r'),
 (911,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'recovery and characterization of a herpes-like virus from dog kidney\rcell cultures.\ra transmissible agent was recovered from\rprimary dktc which developed a spontaneous\rcpe.  characterization and serological\rstudies of the virus indicated that\rthe virus was a new member of the herpes\rvirus group.\r'),
 (912,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'immunopathologic changes in rheumatoid arthritis synovium.\rsynovial tissue from 8 children and 7 adults\rwith rheumatoid arthritis was examined\rfor localization of immunoglobulins and complement.\rthree cases were found to\rhave c\' and immunoglobulins within the cytoplasm\rof synovial cells, four cases\rhad discrete localization within the connective\rtissue stroma; the remaining 7 cases\rdemonstrated larger, more weakly staining\rcollections which were found more diffusely\rthroughout the synovium.  no immunoglobulin\ror complement localization was\rpresent in 10 out of 11 additional patients\rwith forms of joint disease other than\rrheumatoid arthritis.  correlation of these\rresults with the clinical findings and\rjoint fluid c\' assays was made.\r'),
 (913,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electron microscopic studies of mycoplasma (pplo strain 880) in\rartificial medium and in tissue culture.\rmycoplasma strain 880, isolated from a leukemic\rpatient, was studied in broth\rcultures and in several cell culture lines.\rthis strain exhibited considerable pleomorphism\rin size, internal structure, and\rshape, including forms with filamentous\rprojections.  the most common form observed\rwas 0.5 to 1 in diameter and\rhad a nuclear area of fibrillar strands, probably\rdna.  the cytoplasm of the organisms\rcontained ribosome-like granules and\ra flattened vacuole which indented the\rnuclear area.  there were various other forms,\rincluding \'elementary bodies\' 100m\rin diameter that were very electron-dense.\rin the tissue culture lines in which\rthe cells grew as a monolayer, the mycoplasma\rwere closely associated with the\rcell surface and were occasionally seen in\rmembrane-lined cytoplasmic vacuoles.\rin cell lines that did not attach to the glass,\rthe mycoplasma were fewer and not\rattached to the cell surface.  although the\rultrastructure of this strain is similar\rto that of previously described strains, there\rare differences in details of structure\rwhich may be related either to the growth\rconditions used or to characteristics of\rthe strain.  the various forms of the organism\rare consistent with the suggestion\rthat mycoplasma may have several mechanisms\rof reproduction (growth).  the intracellular\rmycoplasma may be protected from\rantibiotics.  this would partly explain\rthe difficulty of eradicating mycoplasma from\rinfected cell cultures.\r'),
 (914,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'long-term prognosis and the response of schizophrenic children\rto drug therapy: a controlled study of trifluoperazine.\r   it is evident from this study that treatment and\rcontrol groups must be matched for severity of illness,\rsince this affects the responsiveness to pharmacological\ras well as to other types of treatments.  the use of\rthe double-blind technique does not of itself guarantee\ra well-controlled study; the comparison of 2 or more\rtreatment regimes may be misleading if the groups are\rnot matched, or if the matching is not based on critical\rfactors.  in this study, both the response to the nonpharmacologic\raspects of treatment and the type of\rresponse to the drug itself were related to the initial\rseverity of language impairment.  thus the major developmental\rdefect which determines long-term outcome\rfor schizophrenic children in this group also predicted\rthe immediate responsiveness to treatment.  within the\r2 major prognostic subgroups of young schizophrenic\rchildren, those with speech and those without, are children\rwith different profiles of disordered development\rand different patterns of assets and handicaps.\r'),
 (915,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the long-term treatment of a psychotic child in a psychiatric hospital.\r   description of one phase of the long term psychotherapy\rof a 6 yr. old psychotic boy, within the framework\rof a mental hospital.  the first part deals briefly\rwith the lay-out and the structure of a new unit for emotionally\rdisturbed children.  underlining the well-known\rimportance of the therapeutic milieu in the treatment\rand care of the mentally ill particularly important when\rthe patients are children.  the child presented was diagnosed,\rwhen admitted, as a case of severe childhood\rpsychosis, of the autistic type.  the unusually rich data\rat disposal were obtained through non-verbal communication,\rbecause the child has no language.  nevertheless,\rhe can express himself clearly through play and gestures.\rthe analysis of this precious clinical material focuses\rthe discussion on the existence and the quality of\ran object-relationship preceding the psychosis, the importance\rof the \'early unusual sensitivities\' in the formation\rof a premature and fragile ego and the method\rof choice in the treatment of childhood psychoses.\r'),
 (916,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comments on a case of infantile psychosis.\ran account is given of a case of infantile\rmutism which depended not so much upon\ra true autism as on a withdrawing into\rhimself as a defence against a dangerous and\rthreatening environment.  there was a\rspectacular and unusual improvement of the\rsymptomatology with psychotherapy.\r'),
 (917,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the problems of infantile autism and psychiatric nosology.\rin psychiatric literature the syndrome of\rearly infantile autism has been divided\rinto several subgroups (as, for instance,\rthe subgroup of kanner and the subgroup\rof asperger) and has been assigned to\rdifferent mental conditions (schizophrenia,\rpsychopathy, neurosis).  these distinctions\rand classifications are thought to be\rcontroversial, so long as the etiology of\rearly infantile autism is unknown.  nor\rshould any \'psychiatric school\' claim to\rhave the \'right\' concept of schizophrenia,\rsince the etiology of schizophrenia, too,\rhas not yet been discovered.  in this particular\r\'pre-scientific\' situation of psychiatry\rit seems more promising to analyze\rthe individual mental case and to concentrate\ron clinical symptomatology instead\rof discussing arbitrary \'nosological entities\'.\r'),
 (918,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'families of children with early childhood schizophrenia.\remotionally disturbed children were divided\rinto 3 groups on the basis of their\rdiagnoses of: (1) autism or symbiosis,\r(2) chronic undifferentiated schizophrenia,\rand (3) other forms of emotional disturbance.\rthe 3 groups were compared statistically\ron the following demographic measures:\r(1) educational level of parents; (2)\roccupational level of father; (3) prevalence\rof broken homes; (4) male-female ratio\rin each patient group; (5) ordinal position\ramong siblings; (6) ordinal position\ramong siblings of same sex; and (7) age of\rparents at birth of child.  results indicated\rthat families of children diagnosed\ras autistic or symbiotic show many\rsimilarities to those with the diagnosis of\rchronic undifferentiated schizophrenia.\rin general, the parents in these 2 groups\rwere better educated and were employed\rin more highly rated occupations than parents\rof otherwise disturbed subjects.\rbroken homes were prevalent in the group\rof disturbed nonschizophrenic children,\rbut not in the autistic or chronic undifferentiated\rschizophrenic groups.  the male-female\rratio was not significantly different\ramong the 3 groups; in the autistic\rgroup, specifically, it was 2.8:1.  the data\rrevealed no trend in ordinal position.\r'),
 (919,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'childhood psychosis.\ra description is given of the diagnostic criteria\rput forward by creak and her associates\rin 1961 for what they have called\r\'schizophrenic syndrome of childhood\'.\rpsychotic reactions in childhood are grouped\rinto: (1) childhood schizophrenia, (2)\rorganic states with psychosis, (3) mental\rsubnormality with psychosis, (4) sensory\rdeprivation, (5) neurosis, and (6) manic-depressive\rpsychosis.  it is suggested that\rthe generic term \'psychosis\' is the best\ravailable, and a classification is presented\rand discussed.\r'),
 (920,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'psychotic reactions of childhood: experiences of a mental retardation\rpilot project.\r   clinical team evaluations are presented of a group\rof 32 psychotic children who were initially thought to be\rmentally retarded.  emphasis is placed on consideration\rof as many aspects of the total picture as possible with\rdiagnosis resulting from a synthesis of the individual\rpieces of information.  caution is suggested regarding\rinterpretation of incomplete psychological test findings,\respecially in regard to prognosis.  the results of this\rstudy offer guidelines for differential diagnosis between\rpsychosis resulting from primary emotional disorders\rand psychosis superimposed on a chronic brain syndrome\rin children.  questions are raised about early infantile\rautism as a unitary syndrome on the basis of etiology.\rthe need for a better and more comprehensive diagnostic\rclassification of the psychotic reactions of infancy and\rearly childhood is stressed.  this must be developed\rbefore valid comparisons of treatment and prognostic\rconsiderations can be made among groups of clinicians\rworking in the field.\r'),
 (921,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'modification of autistic behavior with lsd-25.\r   lsd-25 appears to offer a useful adjunct to the\rpsychotherapy of autistic children because of its positive\reffect in areas which are closely related to the process\rof psychotherapy.  a pair of identical male autistic twins\rwas periodically administered 50 of lsd-25 and\robserved for behavior changes.  control and drug observations\rwere made while the subjects were placed in a series\rof standard test situations referred to as the socialization\rtest, social isolation test, peek-a-boo, pat-a-cake,\rface-to-face, hand-holding and following tests.\rdiverse behaviors were recorded in the areas of self-stimulatory\rbehavior, social interaction and affect.\rrecordings were made using an esterline angus multiple\rpen recorder.  all behaviors were measured in total time\rappearance and plotted as percent time in appearance.\rconsistent behavioral changes resulted after lsd in that\rthe subjects demonstrated an increase in eye-to-face\rcontact, an increase in laughter and smiling behavior\rand decrease in self-stimulatory behavior.\r'),
 (922,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the influence of organic and emotional factors on the origins, nature\rand outcome of childhood psychosis.\ra group of 65 children diagnosed as \'child\rpsychosis\' (or one of its synonyms)\rwas followed up for an average of 15 yr.\rnone of the parents were schizophrenic;\r6 (10%) had a parent who had psychiatric\rtreatment for neurosis.  only 2 children\rhad a sib with transient autistic episode.\rnone had sibs with the adult type of\rschizophrenia.  these findings are felt to\rmilitate against the view that child\rpsychosis is part of the schizophrenic group.\ramong the 65 children: 40% had an\ri.q. below 50, 40% between 50 and 80 and\ronly 20% above 80.  the i.q. was found\rin general to be a good predictor of later\rperformances.  mental retardation is\rregarded as a primary component of the\rclinical picture.  evidence of brain damage\rwas conclusive in 15 children (24%) who showed\repileptic attacks (developing in 10\rof them during the follow-up).  speech disorders\rwere the most outstanding manifestation.\rfive children had confirmed receptive\raphasia and 14 others show some\revidence of it.  in 75% of the speaking children\recholalia was noted; 11% had abnormalities\rof delivering spoken words.  the\rview that reduction of speech is due\rto social withdrawal is rejected.  psychogenic\rfactors and parental attitude were\rnot found to be relevant to the etiology.  the\rpsychosis is not considered primarily\remotional in origin, although emotional\rrelationships as well as educational management\rhave considerable influence on the\routcome of the disease.\r'),
 (923,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'compliance and resistance in the conditioning of autistic children:\ran exploratory study.\rtwelve autistic children between 4 and 9 yr\rof age were asked to choose red objects\rand square objects from a stimulus array.\rten subjects made correct choices\rsignificantly less often than chance, that is,\rthey avoided emitting correct responses.\rthe subjects were given 60 conditioning\rtrials in which choices of either red or\rsquare objects were reinforced.  those who\rattained either concept subsequently\rperformed perfectly when asked to produce\rboth red and square concepts; the other\rsubjects continued giving fewer-than-chance\rcorrect responses.  thus, conditioning\rtrials elicited in some subjects an increased\rtendency to comply with the experimenter\'s\rinstructions.  the results suggest\rthat more attention should be paid to\rthe distinction between responses that\rautistic children are unable to make and\rresponses that they are unwilling to make.\r'),
 (924,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the etiology of autistic syndromes of children.\rexamination and treatment of 92 children\rand youths with the autistic syndromes\rof early childhood over a period of ten years\rled to the impression that these\rdisorders are a primary organic syndrome\rof manifold etiology.  this view is\rsupported by many relevant clinical\rexperiences and data, which are discussed\rin detail.\r'),
 (925,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'acquisition of imitative speech by schizophrenic children.\rtwo mute schizophrenic children were taught\rimitative speech within an operant\rconditioning framework.  the training\rprocedure consisted of a series of increasingly\rfine verbal discriminations; the children\rwere rewarded for closer and closer\rreproductions of the attending adults\' speech.\rit is found that reward delivered\rcontingent upon imitation was necessary for\rdevelopment of imitation.  furthermore,\rthe newly established imitation was shown\rto have acquired rewarding properties\rfor the children.\r'),
 (926,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hallucinations in children at a state hospital.\r   hallucinations in children at referral and upon admission\rto a state hospital were studied by reviewing\rrandomly selected charts of current patients.  there\rwere no significant differences in the incidence of\rhallucinations in boys and girls, between racial groups,\rand between schizophrenic children under 12 and over\r12.  the children diagnosed psychosis with convulsive\rdisorder had the highest incidence of hallucinations\r(81%); those diagnosed childhood schizophrenia had an\rincidence of 70%; and children diagnosed primary behavior\rdisorder had the lowest incidence (35%).  specific\rauditory, visual, and olfactory hallucinations were described.\rthe nature of hallucinations in boys and girls\rwas similar.  psychotic children tended to have more\rbizarre hallucinations than nonpsychotic children.  there\rwas no difference in the nature of hallucinations among\rthe different groups of psychotic children.  although this\rpopulation consisted of severely disturbed and deprived\rchildren who had a high incidence of hallucinations,\rthese hallucinations were of simple content and not\rorganized into delusional systems.\r'),
 (927,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of childhood schizophrenia.  a three-year comparison of day\rand residential treatment.\r   a carefully designed study of 13 day-treatment\rchildren matched individually with 13 residential children\ris presented.  in each case the diagnosis of schizophrenia\rwas carefully confirmed on the basis of impairment\rin human relationship, disturbance in personal\ridentity, resistance to change, unusual preoccupations,\rperceptual and cognitive disorders, and panic reactions.\rthe ages ranged between 6 and 11.  the children were\rselected, as the result of matching, with regard to age\rof onset, culture, and family organization.  intactness\rof the family structure was required.  residential treatment\rimplied round-the-clock therapeutic interaction\rwith the child for 7 days each week, 12 mth of the year.\rday treatment consisted of 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. care\r5 days a week for 9 mth of the year.  staff distribution\rwas identical in the 2 groups, but in the day-care group\rthe teacher assumed a larger relative position in the\rworld established for the child.  all children were matched\rin ego status at the beginning of the experiment\rby means of the wisc and psychiatric evaluation,\rchanges in this status being measured by the wisc and\rthe metropolitan achievement test series.  the results\rindicated no significant improvement in either day or\rresidence in those schizophrenic children who, on admission\rhad unscorable wisc tests and who were the\rmost severely impaired in ego structure.  among the\rchildren scorable on the wisc, the organic groups in\rday and in residential treatment showed equivalent degrees\rof progress, the non-organic children in residence\rgave evidence of more improvement than did the\rmatched children in day treatment.\r'),
 (928,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'visual versus tactual receptor preference in normal and schizophrenic\rchildren.\r   receptor preferences between visual or tactual\rstimuli were measured in schizophrenic and normal\rchildren; 4 pairs of standardized choice situations between\rvisual or tactual stimuli were used, with the time\rof engagement with either stimulus constituting the\rpreference measure.  schizophrenic children between the\rages of 7 and 9 were compared with same aged normal\rchildren.  a group of retardates were used for ma control.\rschizophrenics were significantly lower in visual\rpreference than the same aged normals, and an age trend\rfor increased visual preference was found in the normal\rsample.  retardates showed greater visual preference\rthan schizophrenics of comparable ma.  some implications\rfor theory of schizophrenia were discussed.\r'),
 (929,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of folic acid on growth and deoxyribonucleic acid synthesis\rin the rat kidney.\r   the effect of a single injection of folic acid (250\rmg/kg of body wt) on growth of the rat kidney was studied.\rthe patterns of the response were found to be essentially\rsimilar in animals aged between 3 wk and 12 mth.\rmaximum values of kidney weight and nucleic acid content,\rrelative to body weight, were found at 4 days at\rfolate administration.  the increases in wet and dry\rweights at this time were approx. 80% and 30% resp.\rabove the control weights, and the percentage dry matter\rof the kidney was significantly lower than normal during\rthis period.  at 4 days the rna content of the kidney was\ralso maximal, being about 90% greater than the control\rvalue, and the dna content after 4 days was increased\rby about 60%.  whereas the dna values in 6-wk-old rats\rwere slightly lower at 7 and 10 days than at 4 days, in\r12-mth-old animals a further small increase was observed\rat 7 days, suggesting a prolongation of dna synthesis\rin the older animals.  autoradiographic studies of\rdna synthesis with thymidine-h have shown a greatly\rincreased labeling index in all zones of the kidney following\rfolate injection.  maximum values were observed\rat 48 hr in the cortical zone, but the patterns of the\rchanges in the medulla were less well defined.  the labelling\rindices in the kidneys of 12-mth-old rats remained\rabove normal for a longer period than in 6-wk-old rats.\rthese results concur with the evidence of an increased\rdna contents of the kidneys of older rats between 4 and\r7 days after folate.\r'),
 (930,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'renal renin in unilaterally nephrectomized hypertensive rats.\rjuxtaglomerular index, renal pressor\ractivity and width of the zona glomerulosa\rwere normal in unilaterally nephrectomized\rhypertensive rats maintained on a normal\rsodium intake, increased in those\rsubjected to sodium depletion and decreased\rin those receiving 1% saline.  this indicates\rthat renin formation and secretion are\rmost likely the result of the sodium state\rof the animal rather than loss of a renin-stimulating\ragent in the contralateral or\runclipped kidney.  failure of sodium to influence\rthe degree of hypertension in\runilaterally nephrectomized hypertensive rats\rmilitates against a direct quantitative\rrelationship between blood pressure and the\rrenin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.\r'),
 (931,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypertensive vascular disease produced by homologous renin.\radministration of rat renin to uninephrectomized\rrats reproduced most, if not all,\rthe changes (hypertension, vascular disease,\rhypertrophy of the zona glomerulosa\rof the adrenals) found after partial constriction\rof the renal artery.  this is taken\ras evidence that the renal pressor system\rplays a major role in the pathogenesis\rof renal hypertension.\r'),
 (932,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'effects of hypophysectomy and growth hormone on renal compensatory\rhypertrophy in rats.\r   the effect of hypophysectomy on renal compensatory\rhypertrophy (rch) was observed in unilaterally\rnephrectomized rats receiving no therapy and those\rreceiving replacement therapy and was compared to the\rrch attained by non-hypophysectomized unilaterally\rnephrectomized rats at 2, 5, and 10 days.  in the latter\rgroup there was an initial rapid rch seen at day 2\rwhich continued, but at a slower rate, through day 10.\rin the hypophysectomized group without replacement\rtherapy there was also an initial rch in the first 48 hrs.\rhowever, instead of the rch continuing there was a\rregression in kidney size at 5 days and with no subsequent\rchange at 10 days.  in the hypophysectomized group\rreceiving hormone replacement there was an initial\rrch comparable to the other 2 groups, but the further\rrenal enlargement at 10 days was much less than that\rof the non-hypophysectomized animals.  the results of\rthis experiment and of other reported studies imply\rexistence of a renotropic factor which is not produced\rin the pituitary, but which requires an intact pituitary\rfor full effectiveness.\r'),
 (933,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'extrarenal fibromuscular hyperplasia.\r   clinical, radiologic, and pathologic studies on\r19 patients with lesions in the extrarenal arteries that\rresembled fibromuscular hyperplasia are described.\rin 11 patients fibromuscular hyperplasia was present\rin the renal arteries.  patients with involvement of the\rceliac artery were the only ones who had symptoms of\rvisceral ischemia.  fibromuscular hyperplasia of the\rinternal carotid arteries was observed in 6 patients, 2\rof whom had symptoms of cerebral ischemia.  nine patients\rwith fibromuscular hyperplasia of the carotid or\rrenal arteries had intracranial aneurysms, and in 2\rothers intracranial hemorrhage developed in the absence\rof demonstrable aneurysms.  the histologic similarities\rbetween intracranial aneurysms and other\rtypes of aneurysms that appear in patients with fibromuscular\rhyperplasia, the frequency of intracranial\raneurysms in patients with extracranial fibromuscular\rhyperplasia, and the similar sex and age incidence suggest\ra common etiologic origin.\r'),
 (934,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some speculations on the nature and significance of developmentally\rsmall kidneys (renal hypoplasia).\rrenal hypoplasia may take several forms.\ramong these the best known is perhaps\rrenal dysplasia in which the parenchyma\ris maldeveloped.  other forms of hypoplasia\rin which the renal parenchyma is normally\rformed but merely diminished in amount,\rdo exist and may have severe clinical\rconsequences.  the finding at postmortem\rexamination of anatomically small kidneys\rin children who suffered excessive or\runexplained dehydration has prompted the\rthought that renal tubular insufficiency may\rresult from renal hypoplasia.\r'),
 (935,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a study of induced renal hyperplasia using autoradiography.\rto establish a base line for future\rautoradiographic investigations, compensatory\rrenal hyperplasia was studied using tritiated\rthymidine.  labelled cells were infrequent\rin the tubular tissues of control kidneys.\rin the kidneys remaining after unilateral\rnephrectomy there was a 5- to 6-fold\rincrease in the cortex and a 12- to 13-fold\rincrease in the medulla of labelled tubular\rcells over the numbers seen in control\rtissues.  the findings obtained here are in\ragreement with the observations made in\rearlier investigations with routine methods\rof staining and mitotic observation.\r'),
 (936,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'compensatory structural and functional changes in the kidney.\rthe radiographic assessment of the renal\rsize and the factors influencing renal\rhypertrophy are discussed.  the importance\rof compensatory hypertrophy and its\rprognostic significance is emphasised.\rthe changes are correlated with renal function\ras measured by the glomerular filtration\rrate and renal plasma flow.\r'),
 (937,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bilateral renal hypoplasia of the pig.\rbilateral renal hypoplasia of the pig is described\rand is compared with a previous\rdescription.  the defect was observed in 19\rpiglets out of a total of 73 born in 8\rlitters, sired by one large white boar.\rtwelve affected piglets died at or soon\rafter birth and 7 died between the ages of 11\rand 69 days.  inheritance by a simple\rautosomal recessive factor is suggested by\rthe evidence.  grossly the condition\rwas characterized by varying degrees of\rhypoplasia and persistence of fetal lobulation.\rmicroscopically, the dominant feature\rwas the poor development of the collecting\rtubule system.  it is concluded that\rthe basic defect is a failure of development\rof mesonephric mesenchyme.\r'),
 (938,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the effect of nortestosterone phenylpropionate on compensatory\rhypertrophy of the remaining kidney after unilateral nephrectomy.\rforty-eight hr. after unilateral nephrectomy,\rboth in non-castrated and in castrated\rmale mice the relative dry weight of the\rremaining kidney increased significantly.\rthis compensatory hypertrophy was significantly\rstimulated as early as 96 hr. after\roperation by treatment with 19-nortestosterone\rphenylpropionate (= npp) at the\rtime of operation.  the percentual increase\rof the kidney weight was approximately\rthe same in non-castrated as in castrated\rmice.  the absolute initial values as well\ras the resulting values 96 hr. after operation\rwere higher in non-castrated male\rmice than in castrated animals.  the number\rof cells and the dna concentration per\rg. tissue decreased during the period of\rnon-stimulated compensatory hypertrophy\rin both groups of animals.  npp caused a still\rfurther decrease.  the concentration\rof dna per cell did not change.  following\rnon-stimulated compensatory hypertrophy,\rthere was no change in the rna concentration\rper g. tissue or per cell in castrated\rmice.  in non-castrated mice the concentration\rincreased.  npp caused approximately\rthe same percentual increase of rna\rconcentration in non-castrated as in\rcastrated animals during the period of compensatory\rhypertrophy.  the difference between\rboth groups of mice in the rna\rconcentration in the remaining kidney\rfollowing stimulation of the compensatory\rhypertrophy by npp was statistically significant.\r'),
 (939,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'thyroid and pituitary gland activity during compensatory renal\rhypertrophy.\rautoradiographic studies with tritiated\rthymidine showed an increased synthesis of\rdna and cellular proliferation of the\rthyroid and pituitary during compensatory\rrenal hypertrophy.\r'),
 (940,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the influence of thyroid hormone on renal function during the course\rof compensatory hypertrophy.\rduring the course of compensatory hypertrophy\rof the kidney, glomerular filtration\rand renal plasma flow increased to a less\rextent in thyroidectomized animals than\rin control animals.  the secretory capacity\rof the renal tubules of thyroidectomized\ranimals increased insignificantly during\rcompensatory hypertrophy, but increased\rmarkedly after administration of thyroid hormone.\r'),
 (941,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'kidney cell proliferation after unilateral nephrectomy as related\rto age.\r   the effect of unilateral nephrectomy on the\rnumber of cortical kidney cells undergoing dna\rsynthesis and mitosis was measured by tritiated\rthymidine autoradiography in both weanling and\radult rats.  among the unoperated control animals,\rthe weanling rat group showed a base line labeling\rindex of 0.59%, and the adult animals, one of 0.11%.\rthe response to unilateral nephrectomy resulted\rin a peak value of 3.6% in the weanling animals and\r1.2% in the adult animals, both occurring at 36 hr.\rmitotic indices were 0.056% in the weanling control\ranimals and 0.0062% in the adults, with a peak\rof 0.30% and 0.088%, resp., at 36 hr. separate\rcounts of tubule and stromal cells in the cortex\rrevealed that the maximum increase in % labeled cells\roccurred later in the stromal cells than in the\rtubule cells; the stromal cells not reaching a\rmaximum until 57 hr after nephrectomy.  the findings\rindicate that, although the relative proliferative\ractivity is much lower in adult animals, a similar\rresponse, qualitatively, is obtained in both groups\rafter unilateral nephrectomy.\r'),
 (942,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'influence of the adrenal glands on dna synthesis in normal\rand compensating kidneys.\rthe role of the adrenal glands in controlling\rthe synthesis of dna in normal and\rcompensating kidneys of rats given saline\rdrinking fluid was studied using tritiated-thymidine\rand radioautography.  adrenalectomy\ralone increased significantly the\rlabeling of the renal cortex and medulla of\rotherwise intact rats.  two days following\runilateral nephrectomy of rats with intact\radrenal glands, the number of labeled\rnuclei in the remaining kidney increased by\rfactors of about 4 and 2.5 in the cortex\rand the medulla, respectively.  adrenalectomy\rmoderately decreased the hyper-plastic\rresponse of the cortex of the remaining\rkidney, but increased still further\rthe labeling index of the medulla.  by 5 days\rafter unilateral nephrectomy of rats\rwith intact adrenal glands, neither the cortex\rnor the medulla of the remaining kidney\rexhibited a marked hyperplastic response.\rin adrenalectomized animals, also,\runilateral nephrectomy caused only slight\rincreases in the labeling indices of the\rcortex and the medulla of the remaining kidney.\r'),
 (943,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'auto-radiographic studies of the protein metabolism of the single\rkidney in the nephrectomized rat.\rrats were subjected to unilateral nephrectomy,\rfollowing which the protein metabolism\rof the other kidney, which exerted\ra compensatory activity, was studied\rwith h-labelled l-phenylalanine, at different\rintervals (3hr. to 7 wk.).  two\rphases of enhanced incorporation of amino-acids\rinto the cells of the convoluted\rtubules were found, with one maximum\rafter 6 hr., at which time the uptake is\rlimited to the cytoplasm, and a 2nd maximum\ron the 4th day, when the nucleus is\requally involved.  in the course of the 2nd\rphase of enhanced amino-acid uptake,\rthere is also an increased mitotic index\rof the epithelia of the tubules.  in the\rcollecting tubules, there was only one phase\rof enhanced amino-acid uptake, with a\rmaximum on the 4th day, also coinciding\rwith an increased mitotic index.  the\rincrease of the number of cells of the kidney\rwas determined by a study of the variations\rof the mitotic index.  the mean\rmultiplication factor in the beginning amounts\rto 1.6.  the protein metabolism is increased\r1.3 times.  the increase of the volume\r(factor 1.3) and the increase of the protein\rmetabolism per unit of volume (factor 1.3)\rof the hypertrophic kidney result in a\rtotal increase of the protein metabolism\rof 2.1 times, once the adaptation process\ris complete, so that the residual kidney\rhas approximately the same protein\rmetabolism as 2 normal kidneys.\r'),
 (944,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'two brothers with nephrogenic diabetes insipidus.\rthe patients, a 5-year-old and a 13-year-old\rboy, had suffered from polydypsia\rand polyuria since the age of 1 yr.  physical\rand mental retardation, hyperchloremia,\rand lowering of kidney concentrating power\rwere observed.  the patients were resistant\rto pitressin.  they were considered\rto be suffering from nephrogenic diabetes\rinsipidus caused by a recessive heredity factor.\r'),
 (945,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies on the sweat in renal diabetes insipidus during\rtreatment with saluretics.\rdescription of a 5-month-old boy suffering\rfrom familial diabetes insipidus.  his\rsweat as well as that of his mother had an\rincreased nacl content.  chlorthalidone\rand fursemide had a different effect both\ron the quantity and on the nacl content of\rthe sweat.  a single dose of chlorthalidone\rdecreased the nacl content for a short\rtime, but increased the quantity of sweat\rduring 3 days.  fursemide given intermittently\rproduced a decrease of the sweat nacl\ralso during the intervals and an increase\rof the quantity of sweat; however, as a\rcontraregulation during the intervals, the\rquantity of sweat decreased and at the same\rtime the urea content increased.  from\rthe isotonic serum filtrate in the sweat\rglands ho and nacl were reabsorbed in\rthe ducts and the urea concentration\rincreased but the reabsorption of ho and nacl\rdid not go parallel, therefore the sweat is\rhypotonic.  this regulation is altered in\rdiabetes insipidus, therefore the high values\rof nacl.  without changing the osmolarity,\rna is exchanged with k.  this mechanism\ris accentuated if the na-concentration\ris high.\r'),
 (946,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'diabetes insipidus treated with synthetic lysine vasopressin.\ra case of diabetes insipidus was associated\rwith an eosinophilic granuloma in a\r2.5-year-old child.  partial control of symptoms\rwas achieved with pitressin tannate in\roil, 7.5 u. i.m. on alternate days.  synthetic\rlysine vasopressin i.m. controlled\rthe urine output at a dose of 5 u. 8-hourly,\rbut the preparation was not well tolerated.\rit was therefore given by the nasal route,\rand over a 6-month period the diabetes\rwas controlled with a dose of 14 u. t.d.s.\r'),
 (947,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the action of vasopressin in renal diabetes insipidus.\ras the water-retaining action of antidiuretic\rhormone is eliminated in renal diabetes\rinsipidus, the steps in na transport can\rbe separately determined.  vasopressin\rinduced a prompt increase in freewater\rclearance and urinary volume, as well\ras a delayed increase in sodium clearance.\rit is suggested that vasopressin brings\rabout stimulation of sodium reabsorption in\rthe ascending limb of henle\'s loop.  it\ris supposed that both physiological actions\rof antidiuretic hormone - the antidiuretic\rand the sodium-active effect - become operative\rin two different places in the nephron\rand synergistically produce a maximum\rconcentration of urine.\r'),
 (948,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pituitary diabetes insipidus associated with progressive urinary\rtract dilatation.\ra case of pituitary diabetes insipidus with\rassociated obstructive urinary tract\rchanges is described.  the patient was treated\rboth by surgical correction of lower\rtract obstruction as well as by control of\rthe diabetes.  reversal of anatomic changes\rover a 1-year followup period is demonstrated.\r'),
 (949,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the antidiuretic effect of angiotensin in diabetes insipidus.\r   the effect of angiotensin (val-5-hypertensinii-asp- -amide)\rwas studied in 2 children with diabetes\rinsipidus (a 9 yr old boy with diabetes insipidus neuro-hormonalis\rand a 4 yr old girl with diabetes insipidus\rrenalis) in whom the clearances of inulin, pah, na and\rurea and the osmolar and free-water clearances were\rexamined.  angiotensin produces a prompt antidiuresis\rwhich is combined with a gross decrease of the na-clearance.\rthe osmolality of the urine is increased only slightly\rand the free-water clearance does not become negative,\rboth effects being contrary to those seen with vasopressin.\rthe antidiuresis and antinatriuresis can be produced\rin salt-loaded and salt-deprived states.  furosemide\rreverses the effects of angiotensin.  the clearance of\rurea is not changed by angiotensin as long as the glomerular\rfiltration rate remains normal.\r'),
 (950,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'polyuria in children.\r   twelve polyuric children have been investigated in\rthe present report from their etiologico-clinical aspect\rand they have been classified into four broad groups.  the\rfirst group of diabetes insipidus syndrome included 4\rcases - 3 of idiopathic type and one of the acquired variety\rdue to hand-schuller-christian-disease.  the 4 cases\rin the second group of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus\rafter further investigations were diagnosed as renal\racidosis (1 case), other renal tubular syndromes with\rmultiple defects (2 cases), and hypokalaemic nephropathy\r(1 case).  the third group of polyuria due to chronic renal\rfailure has been exemplified by one case.  the fourth\rgroup of 3 cases had compulsive water drinking as the\rprobable etiology.  in addition to the illustrative case\rhistories, a practical diagnostic approach in the context\rof physiopathology of normal urine excretion has been recommended.\r'),
 (951,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of diabetes insipidus: synthetic lysine vasopressin\rnasal solution.\rtwenty patients with vasopressin-deficient\rdiabetes insipidus were treated with a\rnasal solution of synthetic lysine vasopressin.\ruse of the nasal spray 2 to 8 times\rdaily controlled polyuria in all patients\rwithout recurrence of the side effects\roccasionally observed with posterior pituitary\rpreparations of animal origin.  one\rpregnant patient was well controlled to term\rwithout undesirable uterine stimulation.\rbecause of its ease of administration,\rthe absence of significant water\rretention (if used judiciously) and the freedom\rfrom potentially serious allergic\rreactions to foreign protein, this synthetic\rpreparation is recommended for clinical use.\r'),
 (952,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'synthetic lysine vasopressin nasal spray in the treatment\rof diabetes insipidus.\rthirteen patients with diabetes insipidus\rwere satisfactorily and conveniently\rtreated with synthetic lysine vasopressin\rnasal spray, the material being administered\r3 to 5 times per day in a total daily\rdosage ranging from 35 to 125 u.  a\rtransient decrease in effectiveness was noted\rduring periods of upper respiratory\rinfection or allergic rhinitis.  the only adverse\reffects of the nasal spray consisted\rof minor nasal irritation in 3 patients and\rincreased frequency of bowel movements\rin one child after he increased the dose in\ran effort to concentrate and restrict\rurine volume.  in hydrated normal subjects,\rlysine vasopressin administered s.c.\ris 7.4 times as effective as the nasal spray preparation.\r'),
 (953,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'diabetes insipidus treatment with 8-lysine vasopressin in a nasal spray.\rsynthetic 8-lysine vasopressin administered\ras a nasal spray to 3 patients with diabetes\rinsipidus resulted in excellent control\rin one.  in the other 2 it was of some\rvalue as therapy supplemental to pitressin\rtannate in oil.  the patient who was\radequately controlled with \'spray therapy\' alone\rrequired the sprays every 3 hr. during\rthe day, but none during the night.\r'),
 (954,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'salt and water distribution in hereditary and in induced hypothalamic\rdiabetes insipidus in the rat.\rsalt and water metabolism and the distribution\rof na, k, and water in gastrocnemius\rand in aorta were measured in spontaneous\rhereditary hypothalamic and in surgically\rinduced diabetes insipidus in the rat.\rthe degree of severity in the 2 types of the\rdisease was estimated in terms of salt\rand water handling.  water turnover in 24 hr.\rwas about equal to body weight in the\rhereditary disease and about 60% of body weight\rin the induced disease.  skeletal muscle\rna increased more than 20% in the familial\rdisease, and the gain involved both cells\rand environment.  there was no corresponding\rloss of k.  similar changes of\rlesser degree were noted in the induced\rdisease.  the degree of na accumulation\rappears to be partially dependent on the\rduration of the disease.\r'),
 (955,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'antidiuresis induced by saluretics in diabetes insipidus.\rin hypothalamus-pituitary and less regularly\rin nephrogenic diabetes insipidus some\rdiuretics cause a fall in diuresis mainly\rdue to reduced excretion of free water.\rthis adh-like action, not correlated with\rthe extent of the natriuretic action or with\rsalt depletion, depends on a direct effect\rof the drug on water permeability in the\rdistal tubule and is suppressed by cortisone.\rit is maximal for the thiazide\rderivatives and diminishes progressively\rwith mercurial compounds, spirolactones\rand triamterene in that order and is absent\rfor acetazolamide.  the reduction in\rglomerular filtration and increased proximal\rreabsorption of na following salt\rdepletion induced by the diuretics is of less\rimportance and irregular in appearance.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (956,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital hydronephrosis.\rhistological study of the renal parenchyma\rin cases of hydronephrosis is a guide for\rsurgical treatment.  if the renal parenchyma\ris reduced in thickness to 3 mm. or less\rit leads to complete atrophy.  but if the\rthickness is more than 3 mm. conservative\rprocedures are justified.\r'),
 (957,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neurohypophysial principles in rats with familial hypothalamic\rdiabetes insipidus (brattleboro strain).\rantidiuretic and oxytocic assays were\rperformed on tissues from 3 female rats with\rfamilial hypothalamic diabetes insipidus (di)\rand on 3 normal females.  oxytocic\ractivity was only slightly lower in the pituitaries\rfrom the di rats.  antidiuretic activity\rin the pituitaries from 2 di rats was\rno more than that expected from their\rcontent of oxytocin.  thus, these pituitaries\rappeared to contain oxytocin but not\rarginine vasopressin.  the hypothalami from\rthese 2 rats showed minimal antidiuretic\ractivity, which might have been due to\roxytocin or vasopressin.  the pituitary\rfrom the third di rat contained more antidiuretic\ractivity than could be due to oxytocin.\rantidiuretic responses to extracts of\rpituitary and hypothalamus from this\rrat resembled those produced by arginine\rvasopressin.  this pituitary appeared to\rcontain about 1/100 the normal amount of\rvasopressin.  since vasopressin can inhibit\rdiuresis in these di rats, it would appear\rthat they have a specific deficiency of\rendogenous arginine vasopressin.\r'),
 (958,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'familial renal diabetes insipidus.\rrenal diabetes insipidus has been known\rfor 20 yr. only.  the first german report\ron such a case appeared in 1957.  nevertheless\rthis disease appears to be more\rfrequent, also in germany.  a report is\rgiven on 4 infants from 2 families with a\rverified diagnosis.  in the one family there\rwere 3 other cases with the features\rof the disease (polydipsia, polyuria, low\rsg of the urine).  in the other family\ranamnestic studies revealed 5 such cases.\r'),
 (959,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evaluation of 20 years\' experience with the treatment of hydrocephalus\rin infants.\ra total of 394 infants were examined between\r1943 and 1962.  till 1961, 369 infants\rwere examined and 246 were operated on (66.7%);\rthis group is analyzed.  laurence\'s\ropinion on the favorable spontaneous\revolution is not agreed to and the\rmerits of surgical treatment are proved.  a\rdynamic form of hydrocephalus in\roperated infants is shown; the patients who\rwere not operated on suffered from other\rdiseases combined with macrocephaly which\rmust be distinguished from hydrocephalus.\ra spontaneous arrest of the process\rwas observed in only 14 children, e.g.\r3.8%, as compared with laurence\'s 42.6%.\rthe cause and pathological findings are\ranalyzed in 102 infants operated on between\r1957 and 1962.  a great discrepancy\rbetween the time of the onset of first symptoms\rand the time of operation was found.\rthis disease manifests itself in 50% of infants\rin the first month of life, but the average\rage of infants at the time of operation is\r6.1 mth.  only 3% of infants are operated\ron in the first month.  thirteen operating\rprocedures were used in the 20 yr. under\rreview.  until the introduction of deviation of\rthe csf into the jugular vein or into\rthe cardiac atrium, 15.33% of the infants\rsurvived 1 yr. after operation.  since the\rintroduction of this procedure the survival\rrate of infants was 67.8%.  in spite of\rthe late operation about 27% of surviving\rchildren showed an average mental\rdevelopment.  surgical treatment of dynamic\rhydrocephalus is advocated.  they\rconsider this method as the only means of helping\rthe infant at present.\r'),
 (960,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cerebrospinal fluid dynamics in the arnold-chiari malformation.\ra method using radio-iodinated serum albumin\rto measure the volume of the ventricular\rsystem, and the rate of disappearance\rof csf from the lateral ventricles, has\rbeen described.  newborn infants with a rate\rof flow less than 70 ml. /24 hr. after\rsurgical repair of the myclomeningocele\rwill develop progressive hydrocephalus\rrequiring a ventriculo-atrial shunt.  the\rtest can be used to detect the patency of a\rventriculo-atrial shunt, and may allow safe\rremoval of the shunt in selected patients.\r'),
 (961,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'coexistent cranial and spinal defects with hydrocephalus in five\rinfants.  the etiology and significance of craniolacunia in these\rdefects.\rthe clinical, roentgenographic and etiologic\rfactors in 5 infants with varying cranial\rdefects (craniolacunia and craniofenestra\ror cranial meningocele), hydrocephalus,\rand spinal defects (meningocele or myelomeningocele)\rare described.  all of the\rinfants expired of bacterial complications.\rthe etiologic factors and significance\rof cranial defects in these coexistent\rmalformations of the central nervous system\rare reviewed.\r'),
 (962,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus and myelomeningocele.  central nervous system infection.\ra series of 38 incidents of cns infection\rin 34 patients with hydrocephalus,\rmyelomeningocele, or both have been summarized.\rgram-positive organisms occurred\rmore frequently and caused infections\rresulting in a mortality of 33%.  the gram-negative\rorganism induced infections\rresulted in a mortality of 60%.  nearly 50% of\rthe infections occurred in patients before\rany shunting procedure was done.  the\rstaphylococcus caused two-thirds of the\rinfections in patients with a shunt in situ.\rno obvious portal of entry could be\rdemonstrated in a majority of patients.  of 5\rpatients who received nonspecific prophylactic\rtherapy because of an oozing\rmyelomeningocele 4 survived.  of the 5 given\rno prophylactic therapy, one survived.  a\rcombination of kanamycin, sodium\rmethicillin, and chloramphenicol appeared in\rvitro to be effective against most of the\rgram-positive cocci.  the combination of\rchloramphenicol, kanamycin, and\rpolymixin b appeared in vitro to be an effective\rcombination against most of the gram-negative bacilli.\r'),
 (963,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'myelomeningocele and hydrocephalus.  the first year of 50 patients.\rfifty infants with hydrocephalus and\rmyelomeningocele were treated comprehensively\rby a team of specialists.  patients\rwere evaluated at death or the first birthday,\rwhichever occurred first.  twenty\rpatients died, 13 from bacterial infection.\rthirteen of the survivors were classified\ras noncompetitive, that is, were thought\rto have a poor prognosis based on a\rdevelopmental quotient of less than 80.  seventeen\rpatients were judged competitive; in\reach case the latest developmental quotient\rwas more than 79 and the urinary tract\rwas not irreversibly decompensated.\rdevelopmental quotient was based on motor\rdevelopment, adaptive behavior, language\rdevelopment, and personal-social development.\rthis report is a progress report\rin a longitudinal study.  in comparison\rwith a previously surveyed group the results\rseem encouraging: current data from 39\rolder patients followed 6 to 13 yr. show\r2 competitive survivors, 11 noncompetitive\rsurvivors, and 26 deaths.\r'),
 (964,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pneumoencephalographic changes in the cavum septi pellucidi and their\rclinical significance.\rthe pneumoencephalographic appearances and\rclinical problems associated with\rcommunicating and non-communicating cavum\rsepti pellucidi are discussed on the\rbasis of 11 cases.  non-communicating csp\rmay lead to intermittent headaches due\rto variations of intracranial pressure and\robstruction to the flow of csf.  in rare\rcases, representing a special etiological\rgroup, the foramina of monro and the\raqueduct may be narrowed.  a communicating\rcsp is generally associated with mild\rto moderate symmetrical internal hydrocephalus.\rin the author\'s opinion this is in\rmost cases a direct result of the cavum, since\rfluid continues to be formed in the\rcavum after communication with the rest of\rthe ventricular system has been established.\rthe conditions resemble those in\rhypersecretory hydrocephalus.  for these\rreasons the author rejects the view that a\rcommunicating csp is of no clinical\rsignificance.  in some cases the possibility of a\rcombination of a cavum with a cerebral\rmalformation must be considered.\r'),
 (965,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'posterior scalloping of vertebral bodies in uncontrolled hydrocephalus.\rtwo cases of extensive posterior scalloping\rof the vertebral bodies are presented\rin men aged 17 and 23 years, having\rlong-standing hydrocephalus.  two\radditional cases with scalloping of only one\rlumbar vertebra when partially controlled\rhydrocephalus has been present for a shorter\rtime are also noted.  no previous\rassociation between these entities has been\rrecorded.  it is supposed that the increased\rintraspinal pressure which must have\rbeen present in the first 2 patients for\rmany years, was present near the time of\rclosure of the epiphysis at the junction of\rthe arch and the bodies and caused not only\rwidening of the spinal canal but also\rexcavation of the vertebral bodies.  scalloping\rof vertebral bodies has been described\rin: (1) neoplasms (neurofibromas,\rmeningiomas, gliomas, hemangio-endotheliomas,\rhemangiomas, lipomas): (2) intraspinal\rcysts (intradural arachnoid cysts,\rtarlov\'s perineural cysts, thoracic extradural\rcysts in kyphosis dorsalis juvenilis):\r(3) congenital anomalies of the spine and\rcord (fusion defects, myelodysplasia,\rhydromyelia, absence of a single vertebral\rpedicle, meningoceles): and\r(4) neurofibromatosis (with or without a thoracic meningocele).\r'),
 (966,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electroencephalographic picture of the infantile hydrocephalus.\rin 50% of 33 cases of congenital hydrocephalus\rthe eeg examinations were normal.\rasymmetry of the eeg recording was the\rmost common abnormality encountered\rboth in congenital and in acquired hydrocephalus.\rnone of the children examined\rrevealed any focal neurological symptoms.\rit is concluded that eeg examinations could\rbe useful in differentiating congenital from\racquired hydrocephalus, because a normal\reeg recording suggested the congenital\rnature of the condition.\r'),
 (967,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'consecutive hydrocephalus.  report of 2 cases.\rtwo patients, each with 3 consecutive hydrocephalic\rnewborns, are reported.  consanguinity\rwas present in both families.  a\rgenetic basis for the hydrocephalus is suggested.\r'),
 (968,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fanconi\'s anaemia with hydrocephalus and thyroid abnormality.\ra case is described in a girl who suffered\rfrom dwarfism due to congenital hypoplasia\rof the pituitary and from other congenital\rmalformations.  the pancytopenia\rmanifested itself at the age of 2 yr. and was\rresistant to a combined corticosteroid-testosterone\rtreatment.  unusual findings in\rthis case were congenital hydrocephalus,\rhypoplastic spleen, and hypoplasia of thyroid\rtogether with persistently high pbi\rserum levels but without apparent changes\rin thyroid function.\r'),
 (969,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dandy-walker-taggart \'syndrome\' (a case report).\rdandy-walker-taggart \'syndrome\' in a\r6-month-old girl has been substantiated by a\rcorrelation of clinical and pathological\rfeatures.  all 3 exit foramina of the 4th\rventricle have failed to open, resulting in\rsevere cystic dilatation of the ventricle and\rhypoplastic distortion of posterior midline\rcerebellar structures.\r'),
 (970,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hydrocephalus due to smallpox occurring in the fetal period.\rout of 450 cases of hydrocephalus in the years\r1959-1962, 15 were found whose mothers\rhad contracted variola after the 3rd\rmonth of pregnancy.  based on these personal\rcases and the sparse data in the literature,\rthe clinical, epidemiological,\rradiographical (skull), biological and histopathological\raspects are presented (2 fatal\rcases were histopathologically examined).\rit could be demonstrated that the hydrocephalus\roccurred as a manifestation of a disease\rinvolving the fetus and was caused\rby a variola infection during gestation; inferences\rare given from the eeg and examination\rof the liquor.\r'),
 (971,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'air-pantopaque ventriculography in congenital hydrocephalus and\rmyelomeningocele.\ra study of the csf pathways by combined pantopaque-air\rventriculography in infants\rwith congenital hydrocephalus and myelomeningocele\ris presented.  the advantages\rof this method are discussed.  combined pantopaque\rand air ventriculography provides\rnot only a demonstration of the extent of\rthe hydrocephalus but also the exact\rlocation and cause of the obstruction.  in infants\rwith myelomeningocele it permits\rthe disclosure of unmanifested hydrocephalus\rand coexistent intracranial malformations.\rthe early detection of the latter is very\rimportant for the complete evaluation,\rmanagement and prognosis.  the introduction\rof pantopaque into the ventricular\rsystem of infants did not produce an immediate\rreaction and did not precipitate\rdeterioration of the clinical status.  retention\rof small amounts of pantopaque in the\rlateral ventricles did not interfere with the function\rof bypassing procedures.\r'),
 (972,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'two cases of dandy walker\'s syndrome.\rdandy walker\'s syndrome refers to a particular\rkind of malformative hydrocephaly\rcharacterized anatomically by association with\ra more or less considerable agenesis\rof the cerebellar vermis and with an imperfection\rof the foramina of luschka and magendie.\rthe dysgenetic nature of this picture is\robvious, but the pathogenesis of the\rhydrocephaly is not simple and the etiology remains\robscure.  the malformation is\rcompensated more or less quickly in the life of\rthe subject.  the clinical picture is\rthat of a hydrocephaly by a tumor of the posterior\rfossa.  the diagnosis can and must\rbe carried out by x-ray examination, the ventriculographic\rimages being pathognomonic.\rthe extreme ease of surgical restoration of\rthe passage of flow and the effectiveness\rof timely operation emphasize the interest\rof this syndrome, which turns out to\rbe a rare kind of curable malformative hydrocephaly.\rthe authors report 2 unpublished\rcases in respect of 3-yr.-old children.  the first,\ralready going back several years\r(1945) had unfavorable postoperational results.\rthe second (1962) recovered completely,\rwithout sequelae, after resection of the\rposterior wall of the cyst.\r'),
 (973,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'incidence and treatment of post-meningitic hydrocephalus in the newborn.\rthe incidence of meningitis in the first\rfew weeks of life is higher than in any comparable\rperiod of life, even if cases associated\rwith spina bifida cystica are excluded.\rthe gravity of the prognosis even since\rthe introduction of many powerful antibiotic\rdrugs has been frequently emphasized.\ramong the 7 cases which occurred in a maternity\runit, 5 eventually made a complete\rrecovery.  in a group of 19 infants who developed\rpostmeningitic hydrocephalus and\rwere referred either with still active meningitis\ror the postmeningitic state, only 1\rinfant could not be treated by a ventriculocaval\rshunt.  this infant and 4 others died\rlater.  of the 14 survivors, 7 recovered\rwithout sequelae, in spite of extreme hydrocephalus\rwhich was demonstrated by air\rstudies before operation.  the degree of\rhydrocephalus, no matter how severe, is no\rcontraindication to operation.\r'),
 (974,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'comparative values of thick drop and concentration methods detection\rof filaria infection.\rblood was drawn from the finger and vein\rin 246 students from 11 p.m. to 2 a.m.\rto compare the diagnostic efficacy of thick\rdrop method vis-a-vis concentration\rmethod.  infection rate was found to be the\rsame (2.5%) by both methods, and 5\rstudents harbouring infection were found to\rbe positive by both methods.  infestation\rrate in the concentration method was\rhigher being 14 per slide against 4 per\rslide in the thick drop method.\r'),
 (975,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'filariasis in its relation to a a bo, mn, kell, duffy and rhesus blood\rgroups and secretor factor.\r603 filariasis patients have been studied for\ra a bo blood groups; 281 for duffy,\rkell and rhesus blood groups; 178 for secretor\rfactor; and 503 for mn blood groups,\rto find out if there is any association between\rfilariasis and these blood groups.\rno association, whatsoever, has been found\rbetween the blood groups studied and\rfilariasis.\r'),
 (976,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a polyethylene tube culture method for the diagnosis of parasitic\rinfections by hookworms and related nematodes.\rstudies were made in amami island and in\rbangkok to compare the diagnostic efficiency\rof direct microscopical examination,\rtest tube culture and the newly devised\rpolyethylene tube culture method for the detection\rof filariform larvae.  the results\rshow that the new technique has a number of\radvantages over the other methods.  it\ris more sensitive than the others for the detection\rof cases of slight infection and\rgreatly reduces the risk of overlooking small\rnumbers of larvae.  polyethylene tubes\rare extremely cheap, compact and light, and\rcan be very easily disposed of after\ruse.\r'),
 (977,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some observations on the effects in vivo of varying ambient temperatures\ron filarial worms of snakes.\rnew information was obtained on the biology\rof filarial worms from experiments\rusing constrictor constrictor mexicanus\rboas, infected with macdonaldius oschei\rworms.  the microfilariae of m. oschei are\raperiodic with respect to the light cycle,\rbut fluctuate sharply in density from day\rto day.  maximum minimum levels occur\rapprox. 2 days apart.  the microfilariae\rare larger and more variable in size on\rthe days of maximum density than on the\rdays of minimum density.  it is suggested\rthat the smaller microfilariae on the days\rof low parasitemia are those that have\rbeen born recently and that they enlarge\rduring the following 48 hr. before they enter\rthe peripheral capillaries.  low ambient\rtemperatures have little effect upon m.\roschei.  exposure of the host to ambient temperatures\rabove 36 c for a period of\r24-48 hr. appears sufficient to kill adult\rm. oschei.  all microfilariae apparently die\rwithin 144 hr. at this temperature, and in\rslight infections.  they disappeared from\rthe blood altogether within that period.  microfilariae\rfrom an infection 20 times\rmore severe, however, were not eliminated\rfrom the circulation prior to the death\rof the host after 288 hr., although all those\robserved were either decomposed or\rdistorted and apparently dead.  the indication\rthat the temperature serves as a limiting\rfactor for the parasite at a point several\rdegrees lower than that postulated for\rthe host species, is probably correlated\rwith the nocturnal habits of the host.\r'),
 (978,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'preliminary report on the leucoconcentration technique applied to the\rstudy of microfilaraemia.\rin a case of filariasis due to wuchereria\rbancrofti the routine leucoconcentration\rtechnique used in the demonstration of steinberg\'s\rneoplasic cells in circulating\rblood was applied.  this method makes it\rpossible to obtain considerable enrichment.\rdemonstration of filaria can be performed\rduring daylight.  from the material\robtained, preparation of specific antigens,\rthat make possible an immunological\rdiagnosis, may be carried out.\r'),
 (979,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'concentration techniques of sanguicolous microfilariae.\ra technique is described for concentration\rof sanguicolous microfilariae, a modified\rharris and summers method.\r'),
 (980,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pathology of schistosoma japonicum in the taiwanese monkey\r(macaca cyclopis).  i.  comparison of formosan and japanese strains.\rii.  effect of passing the formosan strain through japanese snails.\ri.   nearly equal recovery rates of adult worms\rfrom taiwanese monkeys (macaca\rcyclopis) infected with formosan or japanese\rstrains of sch. japonicum were recorded.\rworm recovery rates from the monkeys\rwere low when comparison was\rmade with the highly susceptible laboratory\rrabbit, signifying only partial susceptibility.\rformosan strain granulomas in\rthe liver contained fewer eggs but\rwere considerably more severe and extensive\rthan japanese strain granulomas.\rthe possibility that the large, atypical granulomas\rcould be reactions to young,\rdegenerating formosan worms is discussed.\ran alternative hypothesis to explain\rthe dissimilar reactions, that formosan strain\reggs are stronger tissue irritants\rthan those of the japanese strain, is proposed.\rii.   the formosan strain of sch. japonicum\rwas passed through the japanese snail\rintermediate host (oncomelania nosophora)\rfor 4 consecutive generations.  progressively\rrising rates of snail infection and\rmortality were recorded.  the resultant\rlaboratory strain of formosan schistosome\rwas used to infect taiwanese\rmonkeys.  monkeys infected with the natural\rformosan strain and natural japanese\rstrain served as controls.  worm recovery\rrates were similar in the 3 groups.\rgranulomatous responses in the liver produced\rby the laboratory strain were compared\rwith the large atypical granulomas of\rthe natural formosan strain and the\rconventional granulomas of the natural japanese\rstrain.  the new formosan strain\rappeared altered toward characteristics possessed\rby the japanese strain.\r'),
 (981,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a review of immunologic methods for the diagnosis of filariasis.\rthe author reviews the historical application\rof the skin test, cft, precipitin test,\rhaemagglutination and bentonite flocculation,\rand prausnitz-kuestner test to the\rdiagnosis of various filarial infections in\rman and animals, with a discussion of\rareas requiring further study.  he is of the\ropinion that with standardization of techniques,\rimmunologic methods can be made\rto furnish a reliable means of diagnosis,\rnotwithstanding the past unreliability of such\rmethods.  a bibliography arranged in\rchronological order lists 125 papers covering\rthe period from 1916 to 1962, and a\rsupplementary list of references includes\r22 recent papers on general aspects of\rthe subject.\r'),
 (982,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'schultz-dale reaction with sera of eosinophilic lung patients - a\rpreliminary report.\rschultz-dale tests have indicated that specific\rantibodies to metabolite products\rof microfilariae are present in the serum\rof an e. l. patient and that diethylcarbamazine\rin concentrations of 1:2000 - 1:1000\rwere required to cause perceptible\rcessation of contraction in intestinal strips\rused.  sufficient tests have not yet been\rcompleted to indicate a consistent relationship\rbetween any particular filarial\rspecies and eosinophilic lung disease.\r'),
 (983,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an evaluation of the bentonite flocculation and indirect\rhemagglutination tests for the diagnosis of filariasis.\rthe indirect haemagglutination test and the bentonite\rflocculation test utilizing a\rsaline extract of dirofilaria immitis have been\revaluated.  the test was reactive\rwith sera from individuals with infections of\racanthocheilonema perstans and showed\rhigher titres for symptomatic patients with\rmicrofilariae in the blood.  in a group\rof 42 symptomatic patients, 92% of 13 microfilariae-positive\rpatients and 62% of 29\rmicrofilariae-negative patients showed positive\rserologic tests.  in a group of 15\rasymptomatic individuals with microfilariae\rin the blood, 67% were positive.  from\ra group of 295 asymptomatic microfilariae-negative\rindividuals, 21 sera (7%) were\rpositive.  testing 632 sera from 295 normal\rmissionaries, 84 normal americans,\rand 253 individuals with various other parasitic\rand bacterial infections, an overall\rnon-specific response of 10% was obtained,\rutilizing the following criteria for a\rpositive serologic test: (1) haemagglutination\rtitre of 1:200 or higher with a positive\rflocculation of 1:5 or higher, or (2) a haemagglutination\rtitre of 1:400 with a negative\rflocculation reaction.  sera from 141 patients\rwith helminth diseases showed a non-specific\rrate of 21%.  this high rate was due\rto cross-reactions with trichinosis\rsera (35%), schistosomiasis (20%) and ascariasis (27%).\rsince the schistosomiasis\rand ascariasis sera were from individuals born\rin an area endemic for filariasis,\rthe reactions may represent a serologic response\rto past experience with filariasis.\ronly 5% of 112 sera from individuals with non-helminthic\rdiseases and 5% of 84\rsera from normal individuals were positive.\r'),
 (984,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'filariasis in mountain province, luzon, republic of the philippines.\ran endemic focus of w. bancrofti in mountain\rprovince, luzon (calaccad valley),\ris discussed.  an 11% microfilaremia rate\rwas found.  the parasites were probably\rbrought into this area in the original human\rmigration, as recent immigrants came\rfrom non-infected areas.  no infection was\rfound in children under 12 yr. of age,\rwhich correlates with spraying of the area\rsince 1953.  however, some people live\rin unsprayed houses, and children may\rbecome infected.  with coming road development\rand urbanization, culex p. fatigans\rwill move in and undoubtedly increase\rtransmission.  currently anopheles minimus\rflavirostris is the most important\rlocal vector.  aedes (finlaya) niveus was\rprobably also a vector.\r'),
 (985,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'immunological studies on filariasis.  iii.  isolation and purification\rof antigen for intradermal skin tests.\ran antigen for intradermal skin tests was\rextracted from the homogenate of dirofilaria\rimmitis with a phosphate buffer at\rph 7.2 and purified by sephadex g-100 gel\rfiltration, cm-cellulose chromatography and\rdeae sephadex a-50 column chromatography.\rthe finally purified antigen, fscd1,\rwas a protein with a small amount of\rcarbohydrate (2.5%) and gave a relatively\rbroad band by electrophoresis on cellogel\rfilm.  the aminoacids detected by high-voltage\rpaper-electrophoresis of the acid\rhydrolyzate of the antigen were lysine, arginine,\rglycine, alanine, glutamic and\raspartic acids, and valine.  wheals and an\rerythema appeared within 15 min. of the\rinjection of the antigen 0.05 , on proved filariasis\rpatients.  cross reactions were\rexamined in patients with p. westermani,\rs. japonicum, hookworm, a. lubricoides\ror e. vermicularis, but only weak skin reactions\rwere noticed in all cases.  the\rprotein nature of the antigen was further proved\rby the fact that proteolytic enzymes\rdestroyed the antigenic activity to a considerable\rextent.\r'),
 (986,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'human filariasis.  identification of species on the basis of staining\rand other morphologic characteristics of microfilariae.\rnew staining procedures for human microfilariae\rare described.  the morphologic\rdetails characteristic of each species are\rillustrated with apparent greater clarity\rthan previously obtainable.  a simple key\rto the human microfilariae is outlined,\rbased on criteria clearly demonstrated with\rthese stains.\r'),
 (987,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'immunological studies on filariasis.  iii.  fractionation and\rpurification of antigen for intradermal skin reaction in filariasis.\rit had been reported that the antigen tca\robtained from adult worms of dirofilaria\rimmitis produced noticeable reactions in\rfilariasis patients in whose blood microfilariae\rcould be demonstrated.  further fractionation\rand purification of this antigen\rwas attempted in order to study the\rsubstance responsible for the skin\rreaction and to obtain a more reliable\rantigen with high sensitivity and specificity.\rthe fraction fs obtained by treatment\rsimilar to that described in\rthe previous report was used as parent material.\rby gel-filtration and sephadex\rg-100 column chromatography of antigen fs,\rantigen fsi, which produced noticeable\rreactions in the filariasis patients,\rwas obtained.  this highly reactive antigen\rfsi was separated into 6 fractions, viz.fsc-1,\rfsc-2, fsc-3, fsc-4, fsc-5 and\rfsc-6, by cm cellulose chromatography.\rthe 6 antigens were tested at the 1\r(protein component) level on patients infected\rwith wuchereria bancrofti.  antigen\rfsc-4, containing 1,500 of protein and\r40 of carbohydrate per ml., was\rmost active.  next, the further fractionation\rof antigen fsc-4 by deae-sephadex\ra50 column chromatography was carried\rout to yield 4 antigens, viz.fscd-1,\rfscd-2, fscd-3 and fscd-4.  the 4 antigens\rwere tested at the 0.05 (protein\rcomponent) level on filariasis patients. antigen\rfscd-1 produced the most noticeable\rskin reaction in the patients.  the elimination\rof protein components from antigen\rfscd-1 was attempted with nagase (a proteolytic enzyme)\rand pronase to obtain\rantigens fscdn and fscdp.  each of\rthese 2 antigens was tested on the patients\rproved to have filariasis, but the reaction\rproduced by the injection of each antigen\rwas weaker than that produced by antigen\rfscd-1.  it may be inferred from these\rstudies that the substance responsible for\rthe skin reaction is proteinic.\r'),
 (988,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'identification of canine microfilariae.\rthe importance of microfilarial identifications\rin diagnosing canine filariasis was\remphasized by comparing the significance of\rinfections due to different species.\rpersonal experiences and an analysis of published\rreports found the modified knott\rmethod to be the simplest and most practical\rof the reliable methods.  its usefulness\rwas improved by new morphologic criteria for\rdifferentiating microfilariae.  microfilarial\rconcentrations in peripheral blood from\ra number of naturally infected dogs\rwere determined.  the average count for 44\rdogs infected with dirofilaria immitis\rwas only 24,430 (range: < 50 to 168,350) per\rml. of blood compared with an average\rof 235 (range: < 50 to 2,450) per ml. for 100\rdogs infected with dipetalonema reconditum\ronly.  of 38 dogs with inapparent infections\rof d. immitis, 17 had microfilarial\rconcentrations within the range found for infections\rof d. reconditum only.  male and\rfemale dogs with d. reconditum had similar\rconcentrations of microfilariae.\r'),
 (989,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chemotherapy of metastatic gastro-intestinal cancer.\r   cancer of the digestive tract is the commonest\rcause of death from neoplastic disease in the united\rstates.  a large number of patients with these forms of\rincurable cancer may be candidates for specific anti-tumor\rdrug therapy.  the criteria employed for the selection\rof patients for systemic or regional chemotherapy\rare reviewed and methods of treatment are outlined.\rsystemic chemotherapy, using fluorinated pyrimidines,\rthe antifol, methotrexate, and the alkylating agent, cytoxan,\rhas been found to be of significant practical value\rin 10 to 30% of the patients receiving these anticancer\rdrugs.  protracted hepatic artery infusion chemotherapy\rin patients with primary and secondary hepatic neoplasms\rand tumors of the biliary system has resulted in\robjective tumor response and associated clinical benefit\rin 60% of the patients treated.  length of survival has\rbeen prolonged in patients with advanced metastatic liver\rcancer from primary tumors of the colorectum.  it is\rconcluded that systemic and regional cancer chemotherapy,\rin selected cases, has contributed to the practical\rmanagement of patients with incurable cancer of the\rgastrointestinal tract.\r'),
 (990,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'palliative treatment of osseous metastases from carcinoma of the breast\rand carcinoma of the prostate with radio-active phosphorus and\rtestosterone.\rfifty-three patients suffering from pain arising\rin bony metastases from carcinoma\rof the breast and prostate are discussed.\ra method of palliative treatment is outlined\rand the results reported.\r'),
 (991,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'regional chemotherapy by prolonged arterial infusions in head and neck\rtumors.\rmethotrexate was injected into the superficial\rtemporal or superior thyroid artery\rby perfusion: 100 mg./1. (20drops/min.)\revery day for 8 days.  the area to be irrigated\rwas decided on by preliminary perfusion\rof patent blue violet 11%.  results\rin 54 inoperable patients were: deaths 7,\rfailures 19, improvements 28, total regressions 3.\rpain was relieved in 3/4 of the patients.\r'),
 (992,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'intra-arterial infusion emphasizing treatment of malignant neoplasms.\rthis review of the english medical literature\rsummarizes most of the significant\rpapers concerned with intra-arterial infusion.\rthis technique of cancer therapy is\reffective for palliation of many advanced primary\rand recurrent cancer patients.\rhead and neck cancer patients form the largest\rgroup of patients that have been treated\rbecause of the easily accessible arteries.\rhowever, almost any involved organ\rcan be infused by external approaches to the\rfemoral, brachial and common carotids.\rmost oncolytic chemotherapeutic agents can\rbe given via the intra-arterial route at\rnotably increased dosages with the exception\rof 5fudr.  partial and complete regression\rof many tumors can be obtained with\rpresent day chemotherapeutic agents\rfor 1 or 2 mth.  the best therapeutic results\rhave been in patients with head and neck\rand pelvic tumors.  currently infusion techniques\rusing small mobile pumping units\rpermit the patient to be ambulatory during course\rof anti-tumor therapy.  complications\rfrom intra-arterial infusion are usually\rminor but serious complications do\roccur such as embolic phenomena to the cns\rwith internal carotid infusion; aplastic\rbone marrow from drug toxicity, hemorrhage\rfrom tumor degeneration.  technical\rcomplications of the infusion may not be life\rthreatening but frequently prematurely\rterminate the therapy.  continued interest in\rthis form of therapy appears inevitable.\r'),
 (993,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'prolonged intra-arterial chemotherapeutic infusion in cancer therapy;\rits indications and limits.\rin this review article (48 references) the principles\rof cancer treatment using continuous\rintra-arterial chemotherapy are described.\rselection of patients, operative\rtechnique and complications are dealt with.\rtwo cases are presented which have\rbeen infused with methotrexate (1050 and 1600 mg.)\rwith partial or complete objective\rremission: a woman of 72 with a carcinoma\rof the amygdaloid fossa, and a man\raged 27 with a reticulosarcoma of the rhinopharynx.\r'),
 (994,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'intra-arterial chemotherapy for cancer metastatic to liver.\rtwenty-two patients with cancer metastatic\rto the liver were treated by the intra-arterial\rinfusion of cancer chemotherapeutic\ragents.  the drugs were introduced\rdirectly into the hepatic artery in 10 patients\rand into the aorta to the level of the\rceliac axis in 12 patients.  no significant differences\rin results were observed in the\r2 groups.  of the 10 patients who received cancer\rchemotherapy via the hepatic artery,\rone remains alive 2 mth. after treatment;\r3 died in the immediate posttreatment\rperiod; 7 survived from 1-17 mths after\rtreatment, an average survival of\r6.1 mth.  all 12 patients who were treated by\rthe intra-aortic administration of cancer\rchemotherapy have died; 3 patients died\rin the immediate posttreatment period; the\rsurvival time of the remaining 9 averaged\r3.7 mth.  an objective significant shrinkage\rof the metastases in the liver was\robserved in 6 patients (3 treated by the intra-hepatic\rartery route and 3 via the aorta);\rthis lasted from 1-10 mth.  subjective palliation\rwas observed in 12 patients (5\rtreated by the intrahepatic artery route and 7\rby the intra-aortic route).  the major\rcomplication noted was leukopenia; to a lesser\rdegree, hepatic failure.  in those patients\rwith poor metabolic reserve and in\rthose who had received chemotherapy,\rirradiation or both in the immediate past,\rthe complications were severe.  the need\rfor critical screening for the proper selection\rof patients as candidates for cancer\rchemotherapy is discussed.\r'),
 (995,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cancer chemotherapy by continuous intra-arterial infusion.  experience\rof the veterans administration surgical adjuvant cancer chemotherapy\rinfusion study group.\rtwo hundred fifty-one patients with advanced\rcancer have been treated with 365\rcourses of intra-arterial cancer chemotherapy.\rthis technique and its complications\rand results are analyzed and discussed.\robjective response was obtained in\r57% of the patients treated.  the best results\rwere obtained in epidermoid carcinoma\rof the head and neck and the poorest\rin primary brain tumors and intra-abdominal\radenocarcinomas.  ten per cent\rof all patients receiving at least 1 course\rof therapy and available for evaluation obtained\rworthwhile palliation for 6 or more\rmonths.  ten patients have had satisfactory\rresults for periods of 12 to 28 months.\rit is concluded that arterial infusion\rchemotherapy may be of benefit in\rthe palliation of patients in whom other more\rconventional methods have failed or\rare contraindicated.  the frequency of serious\rcomplications suggests that at present\rthis form of therapy should be used only\rby individuals and groups with special\rinterest and experience in chemotherapy.\rmuch further study of this type of cancer\rtreatment is needed and various areas of\rinvestigation are suggested.\r'),
 (996,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'treatment of cancer by bacterial toxins.\rthe initial experience with toxin therapy for\rsarcoma and melanoma is reported in\r3 groups of patients: toxins used as an adjunct\rto operation in potentially curable\rpatients, palliative treatment for metastatic\rtumor and toxin therapy supplemented\rby radiotherapy for localized symptomatic\rtumor masses.  the experience has not\rbeen encouraging in the first 2 groups.  in 6\rof 8 patients in the 3rd group there was\rmarked objective remission of tumor subsequent\rto irradiation.  further study is\rindicated in the use of radiotherapy following\r\'priming\' with bacterial toxin injections.\r'),
 (997,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'radiotherapy of malignant rectal and anal tumors.  methods and results\rin 271 cases.\rthe results are given of the treatment of\r271 patients (9 cases of anal and 262 of\rrectal carcinoma) with conventional deep\rtherapy and ultrahigh kilovoltage irradiation.\rthe total 5-year survival rate\rwas 14%.  with surgical treatment it is,\raccording to a survey of the literature made\rby reifferscheid, 19.9%, according to\rguleke 20-25%, and according to ottenheimer\r21.3%.  a total of 39 patients\rreceived irradiation after questionable radical\rsurgery, and 11 patients received\rpalliative irradiation after palliative surgery\r(in most of these cases an anus praeter\rwas performed).  altogether 48 patients\rreceived palliative irradiation without\rsurgery, and 45 patients received irradiation\rbecause of recurrence after apparent\rradical surgery; 11 patients received irradiation\rbecause of metastases after apparent\rradical surgery and 6 patients because\rof metastases after palliative surgery.\rultrahigh kilovoltage radiation treatment\rshowed better results than conventional\rdeep therapy.  irradiation with 1,200-1,600 r.\ron the site before surgery in stage\rc cases gives higher 5-year survival rates,\raccording to dukes (henschke;stearns et al.).\r'),
 (998,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the management of advanced cancer.\rpatients with incurable cancer may receive\rsubstantial relief of disabling mental\rand physical symptoms by constant and continuous\rmedical management.  while usually\rof limited value, certain measures of\rboth specific anticancer therapy and\rnonspecific supportive therapy may relieve\rthe symptoms and sustain the patient\'s\rmorale.  general supportive measures\rof value and the various cancer chemotherapeutic\rcompounds and techniques of\radministration of these drugs are reviewed\rfrom the standpoint of patient selection,\rpractical application to various\rforms of cancer, and limitations of these agents\rin patients with advanced cancer.\r'),
 (999,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evaluation of ileal conduit as a palliative procedure.\rduring the 6.5 yr. period ending july 1963,\r107 ileal conduit operations were performed\rat the city of hope medical center in\rthe treatment of carcinoma of the bladder\rand other pelvic organs.  the character\rand extent of the lesions are described\rin detail.  the details of the surgical procedure\rare discussed.  complications including\rpyelonephritis, uremia, enteric and urinary\rfistulas, wound infections, and thrombophlebitis\rwere common.  twenty-eight of the\r107 patients died during the postoperative\rperiod.  fifty-nine of the 79 surviving\rpatients are known to have died, mostly\ras a result of recurrent, uncontrollable carcinoma.\rthe procedure was considered\rpalliative in 39 patients.  in 12 of these patients\rthe lesion was removed and the conduit\restablished in one stage; 2 patients died.\rin only 1 of the surviving 10 patients\rwas the tumor under control.  the average term\rof survival was 8.5 mth.  the procedure\rwas carried out in 2 stages in 4 cases;\r2 patients died after the 2nd stage.\rthe 2 surviving patients lived 1.5 and 4 3/4 mth.,\rrespectively.  an ileal conduit\ralone was established in 23 patients, 8 of whom\rdied after the operation.  the average\rtime of survival was 4.5 mth.; 1 patient\rwas alive after 11 mth.  it is concluded\rthat an ileal conduit in conjunction with total\rcystectomy in 1 stage is indicated as\ra palliative procedure but only when severe intractable\rsymptoms exist and only when\rpatients are carefully selected.  the procedure\ris poorly tolerated in older persons.\r'),
 (1000,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cancer chemotherapy by continuous intra-arterial infusion of\rmethotrexate.\rcontinuous intra-arterial infusions of methotrexate\rwere used in the treatment of\r45 patients with malignant disease of the\rhead and neck, 16 patients with advanced\rcancer of pelvic organs, and 7 with malignant\rlesions of the lower limb.  in 4 patients\rwith epidermoid lesions of the head\rand neck there was complete regression\rof the local tumor.  thirty-three other patients\rbenefited from treatment for varying\rperiods of time, but the remaining 30\rshowed no response.  eight patients died\rduring or immediately after treatment; all\rhad advanced cancers of the head-and-neck\rregion.  the mean total dose of methotrexate\rgiven in the patients with no response\rwas significantly less than in those\rwith partial regression of the tumor.\rthis suggests that the greater the total dose\rof methotrexate tolerated, the greater\rthe chance of beneficial response.  the role\rof continuous intra-arterial chemotherapy\rin the management of malignant disease\ris discussed.\r'),
 (1001,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'management of advanced ovarian carcinoma.\rthe life graph is presented for the purpose\rof illustrating the results of treatment\rfor patients with ovarian carcinoma who\reventually died from their disease.  it includes\rall patients regardless of initial stage\rof disease, histology of the tumor, or\rtherapy employed.  the series is a selected\rone because of the type of patient referred\rto the medical oncology service, and\rit demonstrates that almost 2/3 of the patients\rdied within 2 yr. of diagnosis.  all\rpatients received active, aggressive anti-tumor\ras well as supportive therapy, although\rthere was no formal protocol for patient\rmanagement.  it might be possible, employing\ra standardized therapeutic approach-irradiation\rwhen indicated to the entire\rabdomen in the dose range of 3,500\rrads, followed by judicious use of currently\ravailable anticancer drugs when the\rdisease recurs-to produce a modest increase\rin the 2-year survival figures.  since\rmost series show that approximately 75%\rof patients with ovarian carcinoma are in\rstage iii of iv when first diagnosed, more\rattention might be directed to earlier\rdiagnosis.  while it is an important field for\rinvestigation, methods of facilitating\rearly diagnosis are not apparent at the moment.\rcontrolled trials of adjuvant therapy\rfor stage i and ii disease in which approximately\r40% of recurrences are seen\rshould be expanded.  this might consist of\rinstillation of radioactive or chemical\ragents into the abdominal cavity, the use of\rsystemic chemotherapy during or immediately\rafter operation, or infusion of drugs\rinto the abdominal aorta.  for stages\riii and iv controlled trials of drugs alone,\rsequentially, or in combination with or\rsubsequent to irradiation seem indicated.\rfinally, efforts to find more effective\ranticancer drugs must continue.\r'),
 (1002,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'liver resections for embolic metastases from cancer of the colon and\rrectum.\r   two patients, who underwent resections of the\rleft lobe of the liver for embolic metastases from primary\rcancers of the colon and rectum, are reported.\rthe internal anatomy of the liver, as it relates to the\rtechnic and terminology of resections, is reviewed.\rcases of liver resection performed for embolic metastases\rfrom cancer of the colon and rectum, found in an\rextensive review of medical literature, are classified\rand the results are analyzed.  resection of either half\rof the liver (hemihepatectomy) for embolic metastasis\rfrom cancer of the colon or rectum, so rarely cures\rthe patient and carried such a high operative mortality\rrate, that it is seldom, if ever, justifiable.  the lesser\roperations (left lobectomy or right-lobe metastasectomy)\roften can be performed simultaneously with the primary\roperation and are occasionally followed by freedom from\rrecurrence for periods of 5 yr or more.  they are justifiable\rif the metastasis is situated favorably in the liver\rfor complete removal, and if the primary lesion appears\rto be curable.\r'),
 (1003,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'palliative treatment of nonresectable lung cancer by upper hemibody\rperfusion of chlorimine (short-acting alkylating agent).  experience\rwith five cases.\r   a method is discussed for providing palliative treatment\rfor patients with nonresectable lung cancer by\rmeans of administering a short-acting alkylating agent\rto the upper half of the body while temporarily occluding\rthe circulation to the lower half of the body.  with proper\rselection of patients and an awareness of the potential\rcomplications, the procedure appears to be safe and effective.\r'),
 (1004,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'congenital extrahepatic biliary atresia.  a successful operated case on\rductus hepaticus obstruction.\rthe author briefly reviews the history and\rthe anatomical manifestations and the\rgenesis of congenital extrahepatic biliary atresia,\rand its associations with other\rabnormalities.  he collected 957 cases in the\rliterature from ladd\'s first successful\roperated case up to the end of the year 1961.\rin publications he found 177 theoretically\rcorrectable cases and 124 which were\rrecovered.  in 1 of 2 personal cases\rhe performed successfully a hepatico-duodenostomy\rin a 7-week-old girl.  four\ryears later the girl had developed normally\rand she was absolutely without symptoms\rand signs.  the author, discussing the\rdifferential diagnostic problems, stresses\rthe diagnostic value of the gradually increasing\rdirect serum bilirubin, proposing\rthe term \'ex juvantibus differentiation\' alluding\rto the differential diagnostic evaluation\rof the time which passes until the surgical\rexploration; he also emphasizes the\rneed of early-latest up to the age of 8 weeks\rperformed-surgical exploration.\raccording to him the administration of vit. k\ris advantageous.  he supposes the cause\rof the postoperative dehiscence of the operative\rwound lies in the metabolic changes\ras a result of icterus.  the author in his own\rcase, the relieved drainage of the\rbilio-digestive anastomosis solved by the help\rof a polyethylene nasal tube and\rwhich could be most safely removed by the\rsurgeon.  with statistical data of other\rauthors and personal cases, the author points\rout that the correctable cases occur\rin 19.8% of all the cases.  one may hope for\rsuccessful operations on an average\rin 10.2% of all the cases and 50.8% of the correctable\rones.  fatal complications,\rthe author believes, can be reduced by early surgery.\r'),
 (1005,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'icterus neonatorum simplex.\rstudies in 50 guinea-pigs demonstrate that at\rbirth there is no activity of glucuronyltransferase.\rafter birth activity gradually\rincreases and reaches its highest\rlevel on the 3rd day of life.  hereafter a gradual\rdecrease can be shown.  the suggestion\ris made that glucuronyltransferase is\ran adaptive enzyme.  the results\rsupport the hypothesis that neonatal jaundice\ris caused by an inability of the liver\rof the newborn to excrete bilirubin.\r'),
 (1006,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the importance of steroid hormones in hyperbilirubinemia, and icterus\rof the newborn.\radministration of naturally occurring steroids\r(estriol, pregnanediol, cortisone)\rbetween the 7th and the 11th day of life increases\rthe bilirubin level of these newborns.\radministration of the same steroids\ror of progesterone to nursing mothers\rresults in hyperbilirubinemia of their infants.\rthese facts explain the pathogenesis\rof neonatal jaundice.  interpretation of the\rexperimental and clinical findings leads\rto the conclusion that the high amount of\rsteroid hormones which must be excreted\rduring the neonatal period in conjunction\rwith the relative insufficiency of the neonatal\rliver is responsible for the inability\rto conjugate bilirubin with glucuronic acid.\rthe steroid hormones probably compete\rwith bilirubin for the enzyme and substrate\rnecessary for conjugation.  the functional\rcapacity of the neonatal liver is\rnot high enough to conjugate both bilirubin\rand steroids.  only after excretion of the\rplacental steroids does sufficient conjugation\rof bilirubin become possible.  furthermore,\rpregnanediol appears to inhibit the\renzyme glucuronyl transferase.  these\rmechanisms show the importance of steroid\rhormones in the pathogenesis of neonatal\rjaundice and their importance as an\raggravating factor in the development of\rjaundice due to erythroblastosis.  these newly\rdeveloped concepts may have therapeutic\rimplications on which the author will\rreport at a later date.\r'),
 (1007,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'problems in neonatal obstructive jaundice.\ra critical analysis of 57 cases of neonatal\robstructive jaundice led to the conclusion\rthat proper diagnosis can be determined\rby study of liver biopsy.  the very\rlow percentage of surgically correctable lesions\ramong patients with neonatal obstructive\rjaundice and the seriousness and\rhigh mortality of the cases of hepatitis\rtreated with a hazardous operation are stressed.\rconservative management is recommended\runtil 3 mth. of age and even later\rif a serial fall in bilirubin is noted.\r'),
 (1008,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'clinical study and histological study of the liver in hepatitis in\rinfants.  i.  classification and findings of clinical study and\rhistological study of the liver in hepatitis in infants (japanese).\rclinical observations and histological studies\rby liver biopsy on hepatitis in infancy,\ri. e. obstructive jaundice of unknown cause in\rinfants, were made.  histologically,\rhepatitis in infancy was divisible into 3 types:\r(1) no giant cell formation was observed.\rin general, slight degeneration of liver\rcells, necrosis and inflammatory\rchanges with stasis of bile were characteristic.\r(2) the so-called giant cell hepatitis\rwas characteristic.  (3) specific type, presenting\rthe picture of cholangiolitis.\rhistological changes in the liver other than biliary\rstasis were scanty.  no specific\rchanges which could clinically differentiate the\r3 types were found.  in each type,\rserum bilirubin, sgot and sgpt activities had\rslight characteristic points in clinical\rand laboratory studies.  in type 1, the values\rwere relatively low, while in type\r2 they were markedly high.  in type 3, sgot activity\rwas within normal range.  histological\rcharacteristics of the liver of type 1\rwere necrosis of liver cells, formation\rof acidophilic granules and balloon cells,\rcellular infiltration in glisson\'s capsule,\rand biliary stasis in the liver cells and\rfine bile ducts.  morphologically, findings\rof viral hepatitis were observed.  in type\r2 liver tissue was replaced by many\rmultinuclear giant cells.  extreme distortion\rof cords of liver cells and cellular infiltration\rin glisson\'s capsule and lobules were\rnoted.  there was marked biliary\rstasis in the capillary bile ducts and liver cells.\rit was characteristic that proliferation\rof bile ducts and bile plugs were not found,\rwhich was consistent with giant\rcell hepatitis of craing-landing.  in type 3, degeneration\rof liver cells, necrosis\rand inflammatory changes were slight.  biliary\rstasis in the hepatic lobules was conspicuous.\rhistological findings similar to cholangiolitic\rhepatitis due to drug poisoning\rwere observed.\r'),
 (1009,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the pathology of \'giant cell hepatitis\' in early infancy.\ra 1-month-old male infant was admitted to\rhospital because of acute cardiac and\rcirculatory failure.  autopsy revealed macronodular\rliver cirrhosis with splenomegaly,\rleft ventricular dilatation of the heart,\rhydrothorax, and ascites.  histology\rof the liver showed a giant cell hepatitis.  the\rportal areas were widened, with foci\rof erythropoiesis and histiocytic infiltrations.\rthe liver cells showed vacuolar and\rdegenerative changes.  the giant cells, present\rin the margin of the regeneration\rareas, as well as in the degenerated lobules\rhas irregular borders and varied in\rsize from 45-60 ft.  their nuclei were large,\rsometimes bizarre.  their basophile\rcytoplasm showed granules of iron pigment\rwhich was also found in some normal\rhepatic cells, in the prominent kupffer cells\rand in the connective tissue.  in the\rspleen there were proliferation of connective\rtissue and scattered areas of erythropoiesis,\ras well as pigment deposits in the pulpa.\riron pigment was also found in the\rpancreas and salivary glands.  the islets of\rlangerhans were hyperplastic.  the etiology\rof giant cell hepatitis is still unknown.\rits pathogenesis may be due to a malformation,\rimmunologic response to some type\rof antibody, inborn errors of iron\rmetabolism and viral infection.  it is suggested\rthat the giant cell transformation is\ra response of the immature liver cell to a variety\rof stimuli.  this case is of interest\rfor the predominance of giant cells with 1 or\r2 nuclei, presumably it is an intermediate\rstage or a variant of hepatitis.\r'),
 (1010,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the surgery of infantile obstructive jaundice.\rthe results of suruga-yamazaki\'s procedure\rin 14 cases of congenital biliary duct\ratresia are reported.  postoperative anorexia,\rdiarrhea, or edema due to circulatory\rdisturbance in the upper extremity have\rnot been found after this operation.  the operation\ris technically difficult.  postoperative\rfat, protein, and electrolyte metabolism\ris a problem.  in order to obtain better\rresults this disease should be differentiated\rat an early period.  a long-term follow-up\rand continued study of this problem\ris required.\r'),
 (1011,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'transient familial neonatal hyperbilirubinemia.\ra syndrome of transient familial neonatal\runconjugated hyperbilirubinemia not due\rto known causes has been described in 24\rinfants of 8 unrelated, healthy caucasian\rmothers.  four of the infants developed\rkernicterus.  beginning in the 2nd trimester\rof pregnancy, sera from the 8 mothers\rand their newborn infants inhibited direct-reacting\rbilirubin and o-aminophenol glucuronide\rformation by rat liver slices and\rhomogenates, respectively, 4 to 10 times\rmore than was observed with sera from\ra control group of pregnant women and\rtheir infants.  the serum inhibitory factor\rin these women is unidentified.  the fact\rthat the inhibitor occurs in pregnancy\rserum suggests that it is probably a progestational\rsteroid that inhibits glucuronyl\rtransferase activity in the liver of neonates.\rthe mechanism responsible for increased\rserum inhibitor factor activity\rin these women is unknown and requires\rfurther study.\r'),
 (1012,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hepatitis virus in neonatal liver disease.\rliver-biopsy specimens from 3 babies with\rneonatal hepatitis, and 3 with extrahepatic\rbiliary atresia, were studied for the presence\rof hepatitis virus.  culture yielded\rpositive results in all 3 babies with neonatal\rhepatitis and in 1 of the infants with\rbiliary atresia.\r'),
 (1013,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neonatal hepatitis: liver biopsy findings and clinical features.\ron 22 infants with a clinical diagnosis of neonatal\rhepatitis, histologic examination\rof the liver was made by needle biopsy and\rits relation to the clinical course was\rinvestigated.  histologic findings were classified\rprovisionally into 3 types: type i\rshowed no giant cells but only slight damage\rto hepatic cells with prominent intracellular\rcholestasis; type ii was characterized\rby occurrence of numerous giant\rcells; the specific type was characterized by\rcentrolobular cholestasis without inflammatory\rreaction.  laboratory examinations\rrevealed that increases in serum\rtransaminases and bilirubin were greater in\rtype ii than in type i, and in the specific\rtype there was no increase in serum transaminase\rbut there was a direct hyperbilirubinemia.\ras to histologic sequelae,\rthe results of serial biopsy revealed that\rin type i hepatic damage healed almost completely,\rand that in type ii giant cells\rdisappeared within 1 yr and, in some cases,\rhepatic cirrhosis resulted.  the prognosis\rof neonatal hepatitis may be said to\rbe good in type i, poor in type ii, and\rundetermined in the specific type.\r'),
 (1014,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'spherocytic anemia with early deglobulisation crisis and avitaminosis a.\rfrom birth, 2 homozygous male twins had\rhad a series of hemolytic crises.  these\rcaused a low crythrocyte count and jaundice\ron the one hand, and xerophthalmia,\rprobably owing to the existence, proven by\rliver biopsy, of a complicating obstructive\rbiliary syndrome, on the other.\r'),
 (1015,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neonatal hepatitis or familial neonatal obstructive jaundice?.\rfour siblings all of whom were boys with\rchronic obstructive jaundice are described.\rthe onset of the jaundice varied from 1 day\rto 4 weeks after birth.  two other boys\rand 2 girls in the same family are healthy.\ralthough in one of the 4 cases pathological\rfindings were the same as in neonatal hepatitis\r(\'giant cell hepatitis\'), other possibilities\rcould not be excluded.  what has been\rdescribed hitherto as giant cell hepatitis\rappears to be only a morphological picture,\rfor which there must be several causes.\rit is concluded from the findings in the 4 patients\rthat one of the possible causes of\rso-called giant cell hepatitis is an inborn\rerror of metabolism.\r'),
 (1016,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hypoplasia of the intrahepatic bile ducts.\ra description of 2 cases: (1) a boy of 13 days\rold had atresia of the small intestine\rand pneumonia, and a slightly enlarged liver\rwith faint green coloration.  histological\rexamination revealed numerous collapsed\rbile ducts which had solid ductular\rcell sprouts reaching the liver cells;\rthe minor and smallest bile ducts were\rempty.  (2) a girl of 1 yr and 4 mth had increasing\rjaundice since birth.  autopsy\rrevealed a hypoplastic common bile duct,\rwhich was, however, open to probing,\rand marked green coloration of the liver.\ralso in this case, the bile ducts were\rvery narrow and had solid ductular cell sprouts\rreaching the liver cells.  this\rtype of bile duct corresponds to a stage in\rontogenesis and does not show signs\rof proliferation.  it may be considered a form\rof hypoplasia, as the size and number\rof the primordial bile ducts is reduced.  when\rpresent the anlage shows a regular\rconnection with the liver cells.  this hypoplasia\ris to be distinguished from an\ratresia.  the long survival of the second case\rcan be explained by the great\rcompensatory capacity of the liver.\r'),
 (1017,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fetal and neonatal hepatitis and its consequences.\rthe author reports on 18 fatal cases observed\rin infants from 3 weeks to 1 year old.\rin all cases, jaundice appeared just after birth\ror during the first days of life, and\rwas persistent.  the stools were sometimes\rdiscolored.  there was no blood incompatibility.\rthe picture was similar to that\rof congenital biliary atresia.  pathological\rstudy revealed 2 groups: (1) with pathological\rchanges of hepatitis (11 cases).\rthe liver is enlarged, flabby and icteric.  microscopy\rshows dissociation of the cell\rcords and polymorphism of the hepatic cells\r(necrotic cells, balloon cells, giant cell\rtransformation).  some of the giant cells show\rvacuoles, erythrocytes, lipids and\racidophilic material in their cytoplasm.  there\rare signs of regeneration, collapse\rof the stromal framework, proliferation of the\rmesenchymal cells and bile retention.\rcells of the erythrocytic series are scattered\rin the periportal spaces with eosinophilic\rleucocytes, lymphocytes and histiocytes.\r(2) with fibrosis and cirrhosis (7\rcases).  the liver is green, firm, with a nodular\ror granular surface.  the extra-hepatic\rbiliary tree is normal.  the spleen is\renlarged.  microscopy shows bile stasis,\rpericholangiolitic fibrosis, and proliferation\rof bile ductules.  the periportal, interlobular\rand intralobular fibrous tissue is increased,\rand shows cellular infiltrations.\rthe architecture of the liver is disturbed by\rthe presence of pseudolobuli in the regeneration\rareas.  it is suggested that these cases\rare due to a congenital viral hepatitis,\rwhich is not only the result of an intrauterine\rinfection, but also a feature of\rfetal hepatitis, with secondary pericholangiolitic\ror post-necrotic liver cirrhosis.\rthe neonatal giant cell hepatitis is to be considered\ras the result of a cytotoxic action\rof the virus.  the author considers also\rthe possibility of a viral etiology in\rcases of biliary atresia on the basis of their\rmorphological similarity with congenital\rviral hepatitis.\r'),
 (1018,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'metabolism and excretion of bilirubin c in experimental obstructive\rjaundice.\r   bile duct ligation was carried out in a series of\rrhesus monkeys.  the time required for the serum bilirubin\rto stop rising and achieve a relatively stable level,\rand the average serum bilirubin reached, paralleled closely\rthat seen clinically.  after the serum bilirubin levels\rhad stopped rising and a \'steady state\' had been reached,\rradioactive bilirubin was injected i.v.  the radioisotope was\rdistributed principally extravascularly and not in the same\rratio as albumin, as in other forms of jaundice.  daily turnover\rof bilirubin was found to be double that anticipated\rfrom normal hb breakdown, suggesting increased bilirubin\rproduction in obstructive jaundice.  in animals followed for\r2 wk nearly 80% of injected radioactivity was excreted in the\rurine, indicating that in obstructive jaundice the kidney\rtakes over entirely from the liver the function of bilirubin\rexcretion.\r'),
 (1019,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'major surgery on the severe hemophiliac, lessons in management.\rthree cases of pseudotumor of the thigh which\rrequired surgical amputation and one\rcase of open pericardial drainage for cardiac\rtamponade are briefly reported in severe\rhemophiliacs.  in the first case hemostasis, following\ramputation, was produced, but the\rpatient died of septicemia secondary to proximally\rinfected tissues; the level of amputation\rshould, therefore, be proximal to all grossly\rinfected tissues.  in the second case, with\rinfected massive pseudotumor of the left thigh,\r5 separate operative procedures were\rperformed.  the last procedure was elective revision\rof skin flaps at the hip disarticulation\rsite.  here application of the knowledge gained\rfrom previous experience resulted in a completely\runcomplicated postoperative course by\rdint of timing of the surgical procedure\rin relation to control of infection, loss of plasma\rfastness, and the judicious use of antibiotic\rand direct-current electrocoagulation therapy.\ra plea is made to avoid the use\rof plasma and ahg therapy in hemophilias\rfor trivial reasons and to consider patients\rfor surgical procedures early in the course of their\rcomplications, which demand surgery,\rat a time when the patient is still responsive\rto hematologic therapy and prior to the\ronset of infection in areas of hematoma.  it is\rfelt that a second significant hemorrhage\rin any particular site constitutes a bona fide\rindication for surgical intervention, long\rbefore the time when surgery is considered as\rthe last resort by the physician, patient and\rfamily.  although the authors believe that surgery\rin the hemophiliac is not to be taken\rlightly, they do not endorse the prevailing nihilistic\rattitude that has resulted in temporizing\rdelays which can only guarantee a fatal outcome.\r'),
 (1020,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'immunological demonstration of factor viii protein in the plasma of\rhemophiliacs and its value for an insight into hemophilia a.\rby immunization of rabbits one obtains antisera\ragainst human factor viii, the action\rof the immunsera has been determined using\ra modification of the thromboplastingenerations\rtest (the factor viii neutralization\rtest).  the antibodies against factor viii\rare equally absorbed by either normal or hemophilia\ra plasma.  this observation shows\rthat hemophilia a plasma contains as much factor\rviii protein as normal plasma does.\rin normal and hemophilia a serum one finds\rat a lower level similar concentrations of\rfactor viii.  in analogy with cross-reacting substances\r(crm) in bacteria mutants an\rhypothesis has been made according to which\rthe authors are dealing with the product\rof a genetically altered synthesis of factor viii.\rthis product is functionally less active\rbut possesses the same antigenic determinants\ras the normal factor viii.  some inhibitor\rproperties of the hemophilia plasma can be\rexplained by competitive inhibition made\rpossible by the similarity of structure.  the fact\rthat the inhibitor discovered by mammen\rand factor viii have similar properties support\rthe hypothesis.  the theory of some\rauthors according to which the plasma of an\rhemophiliac a contains normal amounts\rof a normal factor viii blocked by a specific\rinhibitor, the pathogenetic agent of hemophilia a\ris rejected because of genetic considerations\rand because the accelerator appearing\rafter ether treatment of hemophilia a plasma is\rnot identical with factor viii.\r');
INSERT INTO `Vectorial-Space-Search_development`.`docs` VALUES  (1021,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haemophilic pseudotumours (3 cases).\rthe 2 first cases of haemophilic pseudo-tumours\rin 2 adults affected with haemophilia\ra reported are remarkable on account of their\rclinical latency and their intertrochanteric\rlocalization.  the third, in a haemophiliac b, is\rvery extensive and is accompanied by very\rmarked clinical symptoms of tumour.  there is\ran extensive femoral gap with a subjacent\rimage of osseous infarction and a progressive\rturgid tumour of the iliac wing of the\rsame side.  the literature data stress the discrepancy\rbetween the progressive character\rof this veritable tumour and the absence of\rany sign of histological malignancy.\r'),
 (1022,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'protein-losing enteropathy complicating prolonged bleeding in\rhemophilia.\rgastrointestinal bleeding in a severe hemophiliac\rcontinued for 110 days, and 263\rpints of fresh blood were replaced.  treatment\rwith eaca, steroids, and factor\rviii, rich fibrinogen did not control bleeding.\rmarked hypoproteinemia developed\rby the 94th day of bleeding.  a protein-losing\renteropathy was suspected on the basis\rof x-ray findings of mucosal thickening and\raltered motility.  discontinuance of\rsteroids and protein replacement resulted\rin the appearance of a more normal\rsmall bowel mucosal pattern and coincided\rwith the cessation of bleeding.\r'),
 (1023,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bilateral hemophilic pseudotumors of the calcaneus and cuboid treated\rby irradiation.  case report.\ra case is presented in which bilateral pseudotumors\rof the calcaneus and cuboid in\ran 11-year-old boy with apparent classic\rhemophilia responded promptly to deep x-ray\rtherapy with relief of pain and subsequent\rdisappearance of the tumors without\rrecurrence for 2 yr. and 8 mth. after treatment.\ralthough previous reports on the\reffects of radiotherapy for pseudotumors\rhave been conflicting, the results in this\rcase were dramatic.\r'),
 (1024,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'some bone lesions in the course of blood diseases with special reference\rto the formation of bony callus and to the treatment of fractures in\rpatients suffering from blood diseases.\rafter some preliminary remarks on the embryology\rand physiology of the bone\rmarrow and on the mechanism of coagulation\rof the blood, the authors pass on to\ra consideration of the genesis of bony callus,\rand the treatment of fractures in\rpatients suffering from blood diseases.  an\raccount is given on the basis of some examples\rof pathological fractures, and also\rof some traumatic fractures in subjects\raffected by various kinds of blood diseases\rsuch as solitary myeloma, polyosteotic\rplasmocytoma, waldenstroem\'s syndrome,\rthe coagulopathic syndrome\rfrom a structural defect of the fibrin coagulum,\rand hemophilia.  fractures in patients\rwith blood diseases are characterized\rby an abnormal course, and, for an\reffecient cure, it is necessary to make an\raccurate diagnosis with regard to the\rpre-existing blood diseases and to re-establish\rhemostasis when this has been\rchanged, to prevent hemorrhages, and to correct\rany plasma defect that may be\rpresent and which are reflected in the formation\rof the bony callus.\r'),
 (1025,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studies of the antihemophilic factor (ahf, factor viii) produced in von\rwillebrand\'s disease.\rit has been confirmed that persons with autosomal\rahf deficiency (von willebrand\'s\rdisease) produce large quantities of\rahf when transfused with ahf-deficient\rplasma from persons with hemophilia a.\rthis occurs despite the fact that\r\'complementation\' does not occur in vitro.  one\rprediction from a model suggesting\rthat the x-locus for ahf is structural while\rthe autosomal locus is regulatory is\rthat the ahf which appears in von willebrand\'s\rdisease after transfusion will be\rstructurally normal.  the ahf obtained under\rthese conditions has been tested by\rmethods and the results fulfil the prediction.\rthis may imply that the model is\rcorrect.  on the other hand, the prediction may\rhave been fulfilled for other\rreasons.  perhaps the wrong parameters were\rexamined, or the large standard\rerrors of the tests masked a real difference.\rfurther tests are obviously needed\rbefore one can feel reasonably certain that\rmutation of a regulatory gene is the\rbasis of von willebrand\'s disease.  an examination\rof persons with sex-linked and\rautosomal ahf deficiency using an antibody\rprepared against wild type ahf might\rbe very illuminating.  also, transfusion studies\rshould be carried out on persons\rhomozygous for von willebrand\'s disease if\rsuch persons can be found.  failure\rto obtain \'new synthesis\' in a homozygote would\rthrow great doubt on a model which\rimplies that the reduced ahf levels in von\rwillebrand\'s disease heterozygotes is\rdue entirely to reduction in an effector substance\rwhich neutralizes the repressor\rof an x-chromosome operon directly coding\rthe ahf molecule.\r'),
 (1026,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'tumor-like bone lesions in hemophilia.\rthis report deals with the clinical and radiologic\rfindings in a hemophilic pseudotumor\rof the femur observed over a period\rof 10 yr.  the pathogenesis, treatment\rand radiologic differential diagnosis are\rdiscussed.\r'),
 (1027,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'concurrent hemophilia and christmas\' disease in one family.\ra study is presented of a number of generations\rof a family in whom two members had\rchristmas\' disease and three hemophilia a.\rit is suspected that the preceding generations\rmust have been afflicted with hemophilia\rab, or a mutation in x-chromosome genes\rwhich are responsible for both types of hemophilia\rmust have occurred in the grandmother\'s\rfamily.  in her daughters the genes\rresponsible for hemophilia ab segregated\rso that their children and grandchildren inherited\ronly one type of hemophilia i.e. hemophilia\ra or christmas\' disease.  relevant genetic\rconsiderations are briefly reviewed.\r'),
 (1028,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'albinism associated with angiohemophilia.  report of a case.\r   a case is presented of a rare association of albinism\rand angiohemophilia, occurring in a man of 25.\rthe bone marrow contained cells resembling proper\rreticulum cells and containing large basophilic granules.\r'),
 (1029,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'major surgery in classic hemophilia using fraction i.  experience in\rtwelve operations and review of the literature.\r   a therapeutic regimen that provides hemostasis in\rhemophiliacs during and after major surgery without requiring\rlaboratory control has been established with a\rfactor viii concentrate.  the effectiveness of this regimen\rof fraction i therapy was evaluated in major surgery\rof 6 severely deficient and 4 moderately deficient hemophiliacs.\ran analysis of clinical results was made, combining\rthe 12 operations of the series with the 116 major\roperative procedures on hemophiliacs recorded in the\renglish literature, in which fraction i was the sole or\rmajor source of factor viii therapy.  dental and nondental\rsurgery were analyzed separately, as was the\rspecial problem of blood cysts.  although the over-all\rmortality rate following major surgery in hemophiliacs\ris presently only 5 to 10% using factor viii concentrates,\rproblems still remain.  these include the continued high\rincidence of abnormal postoperative hemorrhage, the\rvariation in factor viii potency of different lots of fraction\ri, the late development of serum hepatitis, hemolytic\ranemia due to contaminating isoantibodies and the\rhigh cost of adequate amounts of the product.  more efficient\rmethods of preparing purer and more potent factor\rviii concentrates could eliminate most of these difficulties.\r'),
 (1030,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lengthening of the thrombin time by an anti-equine antithrombin in a\rhyperthrombocyte myelosis.\r   a report is given on a patient treated with numerous\ri.m. injections of thrombase (equine thrombin) for\rchronic gingivorrhagia caused by a hyperthrombocytic\rmyelosis.  these were ineffective and an antithrombin\rspecific against equine thrombin had developed.  this\rdid not cause any specific disturbance of the intrinsic\rcoagulation.  the observation can be compared with two\rcases of haemophilia where such an antithrombin had\ralso developed after repeated injections of equine thrombin.\r'),
 (1031,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'epsilon-aminocaproic acid (e-aca) as a therapeutic agent based on 5\ryears clinical experience.\r   experience in the treatment of 744 patients with\re-aca suggested that the use of the preparation is indicated\rin the following situations: (1) fibrinolytic haemorrhage\rin association with delivery.  (2) acute systemic\rfibrinolysis in association with surgery.  it is\rmainly major operations on the thorax, pancreas, prostate,\rliver and genital organs that are complicated by\rfibrinolysis, but fibrinolytic bleedings can occur after\rany operation.  (3) acute systemic fibrinolysis in patients\rwith cancer, particularly cancer of the prostate\rand pancreas.  (4) systemic fibrinolytic states complicating\rvarious disorders, especially leukaemia, liver\rcirrhosis and boeck\'s sarcoid.  (5) as an antidote in\rthrombolytic therapy.  (6) local fibrinolytic activity\rin the urinary tract in the following situations: (a)\rafter prostatectomy.  e-aca will substantially reduce\rblood losses following prostatectomy, especially if the\rtreatment is continued until the urine has become macroscopically\rclear.  (b) haematuria in prostatic cancer,\rprostatic hyperplasia, prolonged haematuria after traumatic\rinjury of the kidney, haematuria in haemophilia and\rother coagulation defects, and so-called essential haematuria.\r(7) ulcerative colitis.  the drug is equally effective\rwhether given orally or intravenously.  in states\rwith increased systemic fibrinolytic activity a dose of\r0.1 g per kg body weight every 4-5 hours is recommended.\rfor inhibition of local fibrinolytic activity in\rthe urinary tract, a dose of 3 g three times a day has\rproved sufficient.  the side-effects consisted of dizziness,\rnausea and diarrhoea.  no toxic effects of the drug on\re.c.g., blood picture, n.p.n. and liver function tests\rwere observed, not even in cases receiving more than\r1000 g of e-aca.  nor did postmortem examination in\r46 cases reveal any signs of a toxic effect.  no signs of\rintravascular coagulation in connection with e-aca\rtherapy were observed.  the incidence of thromboembolic\rcomplications after prostatectomy in patients\rtreated with e-aca and a series of controls was identical.\rjudging from the authors\' experience in this material\re-aca did not act as an agent inducing thrombosis.\r'),
 (1032,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'femoral neuropathy in hemophilia.\r   six new cases of femoral neuropathy in hemophilic\rpatients are described.  the syndrome begins with severe\rpain in the groin, in the inferior aspect of the thigh,\rand deep in the hip region.  this is followed by a pronounced\rcontracture of the hip in flexion and external\rrotation.  a tender swelling appears in the iliac fossa and\rgroin with a depression in the center corresponding to\rthe inguinal ligament.  finally, a flaccid paralysis of\rthe quadriceps femoris and diminution or absence of sensation\rin the anteromedial aspect of the thigh and proximal\rportion of the leg, with a depressed or absent\rpatellar reflex, is discovered.  the authors propose that\rthis syndrome is the result of hemorrhage in the iliopsoas\rmuscle at the musculotendinous junction beneath\rthe iliacus fascia and that the femoral nerve becomes\rcompressed beneath the unyielding inguinal ligament\rsuperiorly and the iliopectineal ligament medially.\rtreatment consists in bed rest, analgesics, and freshfrozen\rplasma during the acute phase.  during the convalescent\rphase, a hessing long brace is used to protect\rthe knee from hemarthrosis until functional return\rof the quadriceps femoris has occurred.  to date, the\rvalidity of the theory that the femoral-nerve palsy is\rthe result of iliopsoas hemorrhage at the musculotendinous\rjunction and compression of the femoral nerve beneath\rthe inguinal ligament has not been verified.  the\rauthors anticipate some day seeing a non-hemophilic patient\rwith a traumatic iliacus hemorrhage and femoral\rneuropathy.  should such an opportunity present itself,\rexploration beneath poupart\'s ligament may show the\rfemoral nerve to be compressed and thus confirm the\rproposed cause of the clinical picture.\r'),
 (1033,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'hemorrhagic episodes in hemophilia: a 5-year prospective study.\r   medicosocial studies of hemophilia are of\rparticular clinical importance in allowing an assessment\rof the likely course of the disease at different\rages and for differing grades of severity, and in\rproviding knowledge of which complications cause\rthe most disability, loss of education, and earning\rcapacity.  they also overcome the distorted clinical\rimpression of the disease which arises from the\rrecurrent admission of the same few severely affected\rhemophiliacs.  owing to the considerable individual\rvariation in the number and severity of complications\rin different hemophiliacs an accurate individual\rprognosis can never be given.  in general,\rhowever, the number of spontaneous episodes per\ryear decreases with age, while the severity of individual\repisodes tends to increase, at least until\rthe age of 21 yr.  there is general agreement that\rthe bulk of hospital hemophilic admissions are due\rto hemarthroses and that hemophilic arthropathy\rinvolves the knee more than it does any other joint.\rthe increased time spent in hospital per episode in\rlater life is in part at least due to the development\rof relatively unstable weight-bearing joints due to\rhemophilic arthropathy and associated muscle atrophy.\rthus the correct management of individual\rhemarthroses in childhood is of considerable importance,\rand at the present time too little is known\rof the best possible treatment for these episodes.\rlittle is known of the pathological mechanisms of\rhemophilic arthropathy and whether it is the presence\rof blood or its presence under tension which\rleads to joint destruction.  thus opinions differ concerning\rthe routine admission of all hemarthroses\rto hospital regardless of severity and also about the\radvisability of joint aspiration in an attempt to avoid\rthe development of destructive arthropathy.  because\rof the individual variation between patients, the\rchanges in the pattern of the disease with age, and\rthe difficulty of obtaining suitable control patients\rthese questions can be answered only by further\rlongterm prospective medicosocial studies.\r');
